<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The incredible shrinking Florida Legislature
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Does Florida have too many legislators?
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Feeney suspects so and since he is likely to be speaker
of the House in two years, he might do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Feeney believes a smaller Legislature would be more efficient,
more manageable, more Republican ... an altogether better place.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker designate won't venture a specific optimal size.
Perhaps the House, which now has 120 members, could be slimmed by
just a few seats or cut more dramatically to 100. Feeney also would
like to see the Senate reduced from 40 to about 30 senators.
Coincidentally about the average size of an elementary school
class.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many people distrust government, the idea of fewer
politicians in Tallahassee is an easy sell. Pushed out of
lawmaking, former officeholders would be forced to take up
productive work, get real jobs and pay for their own lunches. In
philosophy, this is not too different from welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to assume, too, that fewer dumb ideas would come out
of the Legislature if fewer people were around to hatch them and
nurture them.
</P>
<P>
   This hope, however, is based on the assumption that politicians
carry more or less the same number of dumb ideas per capita. And
that nobody would pick up the slack if there were a lull in the
production of dumb ideas.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure. In fact, I suspect the opposite is true. We would
get more dumb ideas in a smaller Legislature because there would be
fewer folks who might pause and say, ``Hey, that's a dumb idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving lots of people the chance to wonder aloud about dumb
ideas is what makes democracy work.
</P>
<P>
   That's my theory, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This is, I admit, a theory tainted with bias. Perhaps as a
columnist I have a vested interest in maintaining the number of
politicians roaming the state. Maybe I enjoy the spectacle of a
troublesome and inefficient Legislature. Could it be I just want
more trouble in Tallahassee? Possibly.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I stand adamantly opposed to efficiency in
legislating. I want wasteful debate and second-guessing by people
who aren't with the program. I want passage of bills slowed. I want
marching orders to be disregarded, misinterpreted and willfully
opposed for no good reason. I'm for the uncertainty and
unmanageability of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Florida already has a small House for its size. We have only one
person representing every 124,000 Floridians. Up from one for every
53,000 in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Florida has a hugely mixed population _ retirees who
think of themselves as New Yorkers, dogs-in-the-pickup truck
Panhandle types, Bikers for Christ, Santeria priests, beach dudes,
old guys in guayaberas ... very often people who check ``other'' on
every form shoved their way _ and 120 legislators are supposed to
reflect and speak for the wishes of this big slice of humanity? It
isn't happening.
</P>
<P>
   Compare this to the state that is in many ways our opposite
among low-tax havens, New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire voters seem a lot alike by Florida standards,
especially in winter when they must all wear goofy hats, yet they
have one representative for every 3,000 parka wearers. Their House
of Representatives has 400 members. Party leaders must take to the
streets to grab enough people to keep the seats full.
</P>
<P>
   This arrangement might be chalked up to the long winters. New
Hampshire is a state full of people who are starved for
entertainment and they designed their state government and a
national presidential primary accordingly. But I envy them.
</P>
<P>
   Every hamlet has some voice in Concord. Every state road,
bridge, park and high school has an impassioned advocate.
</P>
<P>
   These are matters that get lost in Florida-style mega-districts.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger the district, the more television-oriented the
campaign. The more television-oriented the campaigning, the more
important it is to raise money. The more important it is to raise
money, the bigger the influence of big-money donors.
</P>
<P>
   The cure for mega-districting? A bigger Legislature, not a
smaller one.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I'm going to say it: Florida needs more politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
