<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'm putty in my kitty's paws
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Picture this. Sharon (we're sisters-in-law
twice removed _ divorced from brothers) wanders in the back door
and hollers, ``Hallooo!'' as she climbs the stairs to my
second-floor office. She rounds the corner and stops. ``Why are you
doing that?'' she asks. I ask her ``Doing what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you sitting on the floor writing?'' I tell her to take
a look in my
</P>
<P>
   desk chair. She does and discovers Biddy the Siamese cat curled
up on the
</P>
<P>
   cushion. ``You could move the cat,'' she says like I should
already have known
</P>
<P>
   that. I try to explain that if I disturb her sunny nap she'll
ruin my afternoon. She'll begin by wiping out my desk, bumping file
baskets onto the floor and knocking over the picture of Amy and
Kristofor in their wedding finery. And if that doesn't work, she'll
rip leaves off the hibiscus plant.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon shakes her head. She doesn't understand. Her cat is an
owner-friendly
</P>
<P>
   calico whose only demand is for someone to be there to open the
door when she
</P>
<P>
   wants to sniff out the neighbor's mint bed. So I can't blame her
for not getting it.
</P>
<P>
   With Biddy and me it's different. We have an understanding; when
she talks, I
</P>
<P>
   listen. Like last night when she jumped on my chest, looked me
square in the
</P>
<P>
   eyeballs and let out a howl Steven Spielberg would kill for. I
know it's
</P>
<P>
   pointless to argue because she always outlasts me, so I roll out
of bed grumbling, shrug into my robe, and follow her down the
stairs.
</P>
<P>
   First, I check on Stella, our mild-mannered, milk-white lady
cat. She's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Fast asleep in her basket under the window seat _ next to the
radiator.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Biddy has split for the kitchen and is howling like
she's down to her last bite of tuna. The problem is easy to spot.
The red catnip mouse (her favorite) is belly-up in the water dish.
This is what couldn't wait until morning and how I came to be
sitting on the kitchen floor at
</P>
<P>
   2 a.m. squeezing a wet mouse in paper towels. I put it on the
radiator under the kitchen sink to dry.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy enjoys summer when the doors to the screened porches are
open. She loves to sit on the rail ``yikking'' at the birds. Often,
a squirrel who has long since learned that Biddy's on the inside
and he's not, will perch on the other half of the rail, just
outside the screen, and go nose-to-nose with her. They ``cluck''
and ``yikk'' until one or the other loses interest and leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Biddy's nocturnal buddy, the ring-eyed raccoon who
uses our porch
</P>
<P>
   roof for his outhouse, will thump down from a nearby tree limb
for a peek
</P>
<P>
   through my office window to catch Biddy napping on the sill.
When he does, she
</P>
<P>
   shrieks for back-up. ``Sissy kitty,'' I say, reminding her she's
supposed to be fearless considering she's descended from a long and
distinguished line of cats that guarded the ancient temples.
</P>
<P>
   And when I sometimes doubt her intelligence, she brings me up
short. Like
</P>
<P>
   last night. It was rather late and I was reading in the easy
chair at the foot of my son's old bunk beds in the back bedroom.
Biddy had been napping contentedly in the bottom bunk but after a
while she wandered over, draped herself across the footboard, and
gazed longingly at the top bunk. ``Ye-oww,'' she demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get jump from the bottom bunk to the top one,'' I
explained without
</P>
<P>
   moving, ``you have to jump over here and launch from the back of
the chair like
</P>
<P>
   you always do.'' Biddy shook her head and yelled again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ye-owwww!'' Automatically I put down my book, got up, lifted
her from the bed
</P>
<P>
   and boosted her into the top bunk. She thanked me with a
``Mmm-row.'' Trust me, the only dummy in this house is a two-legged
one.
</P>
<P>
   But right now as I write, all's well in Biddy's kitty kingdom.
She's sprawled in a patch of sunshine, grinning and talking in her
sleep. I'm pretty sure I know what she's saying: ``This human is
putty in my paws.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
