<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Check review before going to movies
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nowadays, regular moviegoers spend enough money in a
month to make payments on a used car. It's not the tickets that get
you, it's the popcorn and Cokes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there isn't much _ beyond bargain matinees _ that you can
do about the prices. But there are ways to make sure your
movie-going money is spent wisely. The Web has literally hundreds
of sites where you can find informed and literate movie reviews.
Many of these sites also help you find the names of the theaters in
your area where the movie is playing. But, for today's column, the
review is the thing.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with a site called Filmcritic.com located, logically
enough, at www.filmcritic.com. One of the pluses of this site is
that it delivers a long and meaty review. Inside a one-paragraph
capsule, you'll get a review similar to the kind you'd find in the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in a hurry, you can just glance at the number of stars
awarded the movie, but if you want an informed opinion, the review
is just a click away. Most reviews are done by Christopher Null, a
magazine journalist and the author of a screenplay called
``Fringe.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, now that many folks like to watch movies at home on
videotape or DVD, you'll also be able to search for older movies
that have been released that way.
</P>
<P>
   The next site, Film Nation(at)Planet Lunch is located at
/homearts.com/depts/pl
</P>
<P>
   /movie/00filc1a.htm (or if that's too much typing for your
fingers, just follow the links from homearts.com). As you'd expect,
you can find reviews of most popular films here. But there are also
some special-purpose reviews.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there's an entire category of reviews called
``Date Movies.'' These are specially selected for hand-holding and
earnest glances. Predictably, some of the movies reviewed in that
section include ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``At First Sight'' and
``You've Got Mail.'' Perhaps you can see the trouble without me
saying, but most of those movies are now only showing at second-run
houses and at your corner video store. But the reviews themselves
seem well done. Another feature of this site is a series of
interviews with filmmakers and actors.
</P>
<P>
   Another excellent site is part of the service offered by
AccessAtlanta at www.accessatlanta
</P>
<P>
   .com/FEATURES/movies/. Most of the reviews are taken from the
ones printed in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution (and that makes
sense, since both AccessAtlanta and The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution are owned by Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises).
One handy feature of the site is the fact that it's linked to other
movie review sites and to other movie news on the Web. So, a second
opinion for the movie is usually just a click away.
</P>
<P>
   Film Land at www.filmland.com is a really fine movie site for
those who want an insider's view of the movies. For instance,
you'll find sections that show you how much money the movie has
made and how that ranks against other new films.
</P>
<P>
   Then, from that section, simply click on the name of the movie,
and you'll be taken to the movie's official Web site (almost every
film released these days, especially the big-budget ones, has its
own Web site). Obviously, these sites aren't exactly unbiased, but
they are usually rich in still photography and information about
the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, since many moviegoers are teen-agers, someone in your
family may want to bookmark the Teen Age Movie Review Page at
www.theteenage.com
</P>
<P>
   /MovieReviews/movie
</P>
<P>
   reviews.htm. (Again, you can simply type in www
</P>
<P>
   .theteenage.com and follow the links if you want to save some
typing).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
