<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New book profiles barons of cable TV
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So much has changed in cable TV during the past
several years that even longtime participants have trouble keeping
up. But a new book by Stephen Keating, a reporter for The Denver
Post, tries to make sense of the rapid change rocking the industry.
Published by Johnson Books, ``Cut Throat'' profiles major figures
of the industry, among them Rupert Murdoch, John Malone and Charlie
Ergen. Keating also follows the rise of direct satellite television
and the entry of telephone companies into the cable business. The
book retails for $18.
</P>
<P>
   In its December issue, PC World calls the computer ``one of the
greatest inventions of the 20th century and one of the most
exasperating.'' The comment is part of a special section called
``Digital Century,'' which looks at the history of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   You can refight World War II in Microprose's new strategy game
called ``Iron Blitz.'' The game lets you fight the war from the
level of supreme commander, directing both the European and Pacific
theaters. The game, available only for PCs with Windows 95 or
higher, contains mild animated violence. It is recommended for ages
12 and up.
</P>
<P>
   The latest entry in the horror game category is Terminal
Reality's ``Nocturne.'' It features gory 3-D action in which you
battle monsters, spirits and devils. The game is recommended for
mature audiences only. ``Nocturne'' does include a command that
lets you turn off the adult language, nudity and blood. But even
so, the game is not for young players.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   This may be the holiday season you at last try buying something
online. If so, there are plenty of new sites to check out. Among
the more popular is eToys, which carries more than 100,000 things
for kids. Prices aren't necessarily lower, when you add in the cost
of shipping. But you can't beat the convenience. You can check out
eToys at www.etoys.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
