<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball's case vs. Pete Rose on Web
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pete Rose has always been guilty of having bad
haircuts. But when it comes to whether he is guilty of anything
else _ like betting on major-league baseball while managing a team
_ people are less certain.
</P>
<P>
   Fan reaction to Jim Gray's recent interview on NBC of baseball's
all-time hit leader is proof of one of two things: Either the news
media, as with the President Clinton/Monica Lewinsky affair,
misjudged public outrage, or people actually believe Rose when he
says he did not bet on baseball while managing the Cincinnati Reds
in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can judge for yourself. The Dowd Report, the findings of
the baseball commissioner's former special counsel, John W. Dowd,
is available at www
</P>
<P>
   .dowdreport.com.
</P>
<P>
   On the site, Dowd said he made the report available because of
the renewed interest in the topic.
</P>
<P>
   The one-page site includes images of the five-page agreement
signed 10 years ago last August by Rose and then-commissioner Bart
Giamatti. The documents are available in Adobe Acrobat Reader
format. If you don't have the software on your hard drive, it can
be downloaded free from the site.
</P>
<P>
   RATING THE STARS' WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   Cindy's done it, and so have Daisy and Francis Ford. But is
there anything of substance to Web sites that bear the name of
someone famous?
</P>
<P>
   The premiere issue of eshopper, a magazine from the editors of
Yahoo Internet Life, takes a look at celebrity Web sites. The chart
ranks the sites of such luminaries as Cindy Crawford, Daisy Fuentes
and Francis Ford Coppola by what they sell, whether it's useful and
how much it seems to stroke the star's ego.
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes, a television personality, sells purses, tote bags,
clothing and jewelry from her well-reviewed site. The magazine says
the site is ``refreshingly low-key'' and the stuff for sale is
``tasteful, inexpensive and solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's site sells books, photos and the model's workout
videos. The magazine ranks Cindy.com fairly high on the ego meter:
``Cindy's lovely mug stares at you from every page. This site is
all about controlling the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola, the movie director and budding winemaker, sells his
wine, his movies, pasta bowls and a fancy corkscrew. The products
are considered useful: ``Who can't use a night of wine, pasta and
`The Godfather'?''
</P>
<P>
   The December issue also tries to help you steer clear of
Internet scams, and it ranks the 300 best shopping sites.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS STUFF GALORE
</P>
<P>
   Spend an hour on your drive home listening to a call-in sports
talk show on the radio. Then spend some time at ESPN.com or
SportsLine.com or any team's Web site and see the amount of
information devoted to sports, both college and professional.
</P>
<P>
   Sports information sources have expanded almost as fast as some
of the leagues. And some might say the growth is diluting the
quality of information on these sites as much as it has the quality
of play (see also: Florida Marlins and Cleveland Browns).
</P>
<P>
   One site, www.rivals.com, is hoping to become the site people
turn to for sports information on the Internet. Rivals.com has
attracted $30 million in venture capital to finance the effort. The
site contains links to more than 350 Web sites devoted to teams and
sports and related topics such as recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Features include team and player statistics, on-demand digital
video of games and player interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based company was formed in 1998. Investors include
Hummer Winblad Venture Partners and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU CAN'T BEAT 'EM ...
</P>
<P>
   Radio Shack has decided to join them. Since more people are
online during work hours and the holidays are near, the company has
decided to make it easier for its employees to shop online.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas-based company said last week it will start letting its
3,000 employees shop at Web sites on company computers during
breaks and before or after work. The company will even allow
employees to have packages sent to their work addresses to avoid
the risk of friends, loved ones and burglars spotting incoming
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
