<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New genealogy programs have different strengths
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Step right up, family researchers, it's genealogy time
again.
</P>
<P>
   We have two new genealogy programs, Generations V.6 from Sierra
and Family Origins V.8 from Parsons. Without further ado I'll turn
the podium over to my wife, the genealogist.
</P>
<P>
   She says:
</P>
<P>
   If I could combine the depth and breadth of the reports that
Family Origins generates and the ease of entry and screen of
Generations, I would have a contender. As it is, I'll probably stay
with Family Tree Maker.
</P>
<P>
   Entering information in Family Origins feels dated _ there seem
to be more keystrokes than necessary. The family view screen
includes children and parents of both mother and father, but birth,
death and marriage information on just one of the spouses. I would
prefer smaller type and information on both on the same screen.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, however, are the best of any program I've seen. In
addition to the usual charts and reports _ family group sheets,
pedigree charts, hourglass charts, etc. _ Family Origins gives you
lists that range from addresses for mailing labels to unlinked
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   I found the Place list particularly useful. It tells me what
event I have recorded where _ if I ever make it to a library in
Lancaster County, Pa., I know to look for Andreas Kauffman, who
died there in 1743, Jacob Ringer, who was born there in 1757, and
Ulrich Longenecker, who died there in 1759. This would be
particularly helpful to anyone who takes the scatter-gun approach
to genealogy, looking for everyone at once. If you are dealing with
enough generations, it can be difficult to remember who lived in
what county when.
</P>
<P>
   The Problem list is also helpful, pointing out that Derick Op
den Graeff probably didn't live to be 332 and that Mary Lind
probably didn't marry at age 6. Programs such as Family Tree Maker
point out the problems when you enter the material, but mistakes
can slip in.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics were interesting, although the average age at
death for males (65) may have been somewhat skewed by Derick Op den
Graeff.
</P>
<P>
   Family Origins has no manual, but is so intuitive that it
doesn't need one. The beauty of Generations is that the material is
available on a single screen. It profiles both mother and father,
with date and place of birth, death and marriage, as well as names
and dates of parents and children, and divorce, if any. The screen
also shows occupation, religion, education and notes. Entry is
easy, although somewhat more complicated than Family Tree Maker.
</P>
<P>
   Generations comes with 15 CDs. They include the Social Security
Death Index, Civil War muster rolls for both Union and Confederacy,
1870 census digital microfilm for counties in Ohio, Illinois and
Georgia and the World Name Index. I found Daniel Reitz in the 16th
Ohio Infantry but couldn't find Robert McDonald, who died within
months of joining the Georgia infantry.
</P>
<P>
   Generations transfers reports into your word processor. They are
fine as far as they go, but don't go as far as Family Origins.
</P>
<P>
   Generations has an excellent manual and also comes with an
informative book, ``Netting Your Ancestors _ Genealogical Research
on the Internet,'' by Cyndi Howells. Howells owns Cyndi's List
(www.CyndisList
</P>
<P>
   .com/), the starting place for genealogy on the Internet. She
has also served as an adviser to Generations.
</P>
<P>
   Further information and ordering data on Generations may be
obtained from www.sierra.com/sierrahome
</P>
<P>
   /familytree/. If you go to www
</P>
<P>
   .learningco.com/brands/default
</P>
<P>
   .htm, you can branch off to information on both Family Origins
and Family Tree Maker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
