<SLUG> BC-GIRL-TECH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hi-tech toys designed with girls in mind
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At least in the world of toys, there are times
when boys will be boys, and girls will be girls.
</P>
<P>
   Radica Games Limited, a Dallas-based company best-known for its
hand-held games, has a line of products sold under the name Girl
Tech designed to meet the unique desires of preteen girls. The
products add technology to such pursuits as keeping a diary,
hosting pajama parties and paying tribute to whoever is this week's
``best friend forever.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the products is the Password Journal, a plastic box that
opens only for its owner thanks to a voice recognition module.
Password Journal has compartments for trinkets and slots for pens
and paper. It's small enough to carry around and sells for $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   Another Girl Tech gadget that uses voice recognition technology
is the Door Pass. Attach it to a door and it will ask for a
password any time the door is opened. Unless the owner speaks her
password, the Door Pass, which costs $19.99, sounds an alarm. The
Keepsake Box comes with a remote control, and the box will only
open when the owner punches in a secret code. The Keepsake Box is
supposed to show up in stores later this month and will sell for
$19.99.
</P>
<P>
   Also do out this month is Bug 'Em, a listening device. The user
places a ladybug-shaped microphone in the room she wants to monitor
and listens on a receiver from a nearby room. It is to sell for
$19.99.
</P>
<P>
   Girl Tech devices are sold through major retailers, and online
through EToys.com and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0053 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-GAMER16-COX     11-15 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER16-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Homeworld's the place to beFOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Every year, a game comes out and kicks the incumbents in the
teeth. Last year it was Sierra's Half-Life, and now Sierra has done
it again with the release of Homeworld. Ever since Sierra released
a demo on the Web, buzz for this game has been building. It is
deserved. After a five-hour gaming session that lasted until 3
a.m., Homeworld sent this reviewer out into the world raving to all
who'd listen about how this game is gonna revolutionize real-time
strategy. Because, folks, it will. Forget StarCraft. Chuck Command
&AMP; Conquer. Throw out Total Annihilation. Homeworld changes
everything. It's all 3-D, on a beautifully rendered six-axis
universe. The ships are silky smooth; the game gives you full
control of the camera, zooming in and out, panning around. And you
think you've seen cool explosions? Zoom in on an attack formation,
and you'll feel like you're right in the middle of a ``Star Wars''
battle. Add to this an ongoing storyline revealed within the game
and beautiful hand-drawn animation interspersed between missions,
and you've got a legend in the making. There are a few 3-D
real-time strategy games on the horizon, including Digital Anvil's
``Conquest,'' due out next year. It will take a lot to usurp
Homeworld's status as the best of the breed. Sometimes games suffer
from being released too quickly, but Homeworld shows you can get
there first and still show off a fantastic game. FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Fishing. It's boring. You sit in a boat, pop open a beer, throw
your bait in the water and wait. And wait some more. That's why I
was ecstatic to see Agetec's Bass Landing ($60, for the
Playstation) packaged with a rod-and-reel-like peripheral (one of
the coolest peripherals I've ever seen). How could fishing from the
comfort of your own couch be boring? Especially with a virtual rod
vibrating in your hand every time a fish hits. However hard it was
to make it boring, they did it. This can be seen as a good thing or
a bad thing. It's ``bad'' because who wants to to play a fishing
game that's boring? But, on the ``good'' side, it's very realistic.
It took me 20 minutes just to catch a fish. And, when I caught the
fish, it was so small it wasn't worth the effort. The game also
comes equipped with a tutorial that's really hard for the angling
impaired to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Bass Landing offers five lakes, seven tournaments, 20 lures, two
reels, eight fishing lines and a virtual depth finder so that you
can have the real feeling of catching 14 different kinds of fish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
