<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Checking the weather on the Web
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ We still can't do
<TEXT>
anything about it, but at least we can venture to the following
weather-related Web sites:
<P>
   www.weather.com _ The Weather Channel's official site is
pinpoint accurate (well, as accurate as weather forecasting can
be). On weather.com, enter your ZIP code (or any ZIP code you want
information about) and you'll get a five-day forecast, current
conditions and the all-important Doppler radar. The best way to
avoid turning on the TV for your weather.
</P>
<P>
   www.redcross.org/
</P>
<P>
   disaster/safety/floods.html _ After a long, dry summer, we can
start preparing for winter and spring rain with this guide on
getting ready for floods. The Red Cross site includes information
on reducing the impact of flooding, assembling a disaster supply
kit, setting up a family disaster plan and what to do during a
flash flood.
</P>
<P>
   www.elnino.com _ Remember when every little weather aberration
was blamed on the El Nino, the mysterious phenomenon that wreaked
havoc on world climates? According to this San Diego site, El Nino
is actually ``a season that comes at irregular intervals and stays
for an unspecified period of time.'' We're still confused, but at
least someone out there is keeping the spirit of El Nino and La
Nina alive.
</P>
<P>
   www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   wwcgi.dll?wwEvent(tilde)
</P>
<P>
   Storms _ Now, was it the tornado of 1955 or the great hail storm
of 1957 that tore down Uncle Floyd's shed? When memory fails,
history is there to correct; this site is a searchable database of
historical weather diasters. Search by county and by type of event
for a list of historical damage done by Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
