<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online magazines cover lots of turf
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Read any good Web sites lately?
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't, you should. You can sit in front of your
computer and peruse a wide variety of outstanding articles, essays
and opinions. Don't believe the folks who tell you people don't
want to sit at computers reading things. That's baloney. If you
have the attention span to sit and read the stupid e-mail jokes
your relatives and co-workers send, you certainly have the stamina
to take on headier stuff.
</P>
<P>
   When you mention online magazines, most people just assume you
mean Salon (www.salon.com). Salon is a great online magazine with
great writers tackling topics ranging from racism to sex, politics
and raising kids. But you already know that, so let's move on to
some other online reading material.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a bad week for Microsoft, but its online magazine
Slate (www.slate.com) has never been in finer form. After many
sputters and misfires, including wordy articles, silly theme music
and even an online subscription plan, it's nice to see Slate settle
down and learn to love the online medium.
</P>
<P>
   Slate found its voice in political coverage that ranges from
presidential politics to foreign policy to parent company
Microsoft. Last week, the magazine ran a provocative story about
Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush titled ``Do Dim
Bulbs Make Better Presidents?''
</P>
<P>
   The article cited an article from The New Yorker offline
magazine, which touted Bush's less-than-stellar academic record at
Yale in the mid-1960s. The thoughtful essay wondered if one really
needs to be able to finish The New York Times' Sunday crossword
puzzle or name each and every Third World leader to be a good
president, and the answer was ``not necessarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, you could run out and get The New Yorker magazine to read
the original article and see a reprint of the younger Bush's
college report card, but why bother when you can read Slate's
analysis and opinion at your computer? (Wake-up call to The New
Yorker: Get some essays and a few original Roz Chast cartoons
online and people will be reading your articles online instead of
reading better articles about them online.)
</P>
<P>
   This past week brought another bit of controversy in a
discussion of Michael Lind's ``Vietnam: The Necessary War.''
There's also a refresher course for presidential contenders and
others who skipped geography class, called ``How to Tell Armenia
From Azerbaijan,'' which is as easy to read and understand as the
maps and glossaries ABCNews.com has built its reputation on.
</P>
<P>
   Feed magazine's founders, Steven Johnson and Stefanie Syman,
have yet to get rich with their online magazine (www
</P>
<P>
   .feedmag.com), but it's certainly not for lack of intelligence
or trying. Feed may be short on money, but it's never short on
ideas. Last week's commentary on the end of the Microsoft era was
as good as anything published about the software maker.
</P>
<P>
   The only real criticism of Feed is that it can sometimes be too
self-consciously hip and intellectual. But then they make up for it
with a series of offbeat interviews with people you'd never think
to interview, like a boy-crazy editor at Seventeen magazine.
</P>
<P>
   We also refuse to give up on fledgling publication Way South
(www.waysouth.com). This journal of Southern literature from mostly
unknown writers is worth reading whether or not you live in the
South. Publisher Grayson Hurst Daughters recently sold a story to
the folks at Salon, which hopefully will drive some traffic back to
Way South and give the magazine the boost it needs.
</P>
<P>
   According to New York magazine, Feed is trying to partner with
online magazines of similar size and financial predicament to form
a portal site for small, hip Web publications.
</P>
<P>
   This, they believe, will be the key to success and the
inevitable initial public offering. But before anybody gets rich,
they need readers. So take the next logical step up from e-mail and
read something interesting online today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
