<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Principal makes housecalls
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How would you like it if your principal showed up at
your house to read you a bedtime story?
</P>
<P>
   Younger kids in Boca Raton, Fla., like it very much and are
reading 20 books a month to earn the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Whispering Pines Elementary School Principal Alan Goldstein
wanted to improve his school's reading test scores. So he created
the ``Sandman.'' The Sandman makes 10 housecalls a month to
preschoolers, kindergartners and first-graders who read or had read
to them at least 20 books that month. The kids' names are drawn
from a hat to decide who gets the visits.
</P>
<P>
   For the older students at his school, Goldstein promises to dye
his hair purple and wear it around town for a week _ if they can
read 10,000 books as a group.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
