<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Better products are created in marketplace, not courts
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I was glad that I wasn't a parent the night the
preliminary Microsoft antitrust findings came down.
</P>
<P>
   I knew, if I were a parent, I'd have to try to explain the
revised American dream. I'd have to tell my kids that it is OK to
succeed but that it is against the rules to succeed wildly and
completely.
</P>
<P>
   I'd explain that Microsoft is a company that dominates the
software market. I'd explain that _ like the Rockefellers, the
Carnegies and Henry Ford _ Bill Gates built a company that got a
lion's share of the market. And that, largely on the shoulders of
Microsoft, America became the dominant player in the software
business. While we no longer are the undisputed world leaders when
it comes to automobiles, steel or oil, America leads the world when
it comes to creating software. Now the government is worried that
Microsoft has done too well, succeeded too completely.
</P>
<P>
   That's where explaining the opinion gets more complicated,
because no one is completely pure in this case _ not the
government, not Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   I'd have to explain that Microsoft has competed hard in a tough
business and done well. And that a judge believes that it has
become a monopoly. While there have been charges of tough and even
mean-spirited actions, Microsoft has not been charged by the court
with any illegal acts, not yet at least. But there is evidence that
_ as it became a giant _ it also became a bully, using its market
power to squash competition.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to teach a kid that it's OK to succeed at any
price. But the world isn't black and white, it's gray. And then I'd
have to tell the kids that America wasn't built by wimps. That
without tough and driven business leaders and businesses America
would have never emerged as a world power, a leader.
</P>
<P>
   The people who built America played tough. But ultimately, to
dominate their business niche, tough isn't enough _ the Fords, the
Rockefellers and Bill Gates sold something that people wanted to
buy and was in more demand than the products that competed against
it. In what may be the best demonstration of democracy I know,
people and businesses voted with their money.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft grew from a tiny company with a single product called
MS-DOS, an operating system for PCs. Microsoft didn't invent DOS.
Gates bought it for a song. But Microsoft did _ through a deal with
IBM _ nourish and promote DOS until it defeated the established
operating systems of its day. If you think that Microsoft and DOS
were dominant players in those days, go back and reread the books
that chronicle those times. Neither the company nor the products
were dominating.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Windows. The first versions of Windows were so
bad they were jokes.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, there was strong competition from Macintosh,
which had a much superior operating system, and from IBM, which
also offered a better operating system, OS/2. Microsoft was a
powerhouse by then but not yet so big and powerful that it could
roll over an IBM or an Apple. Instead, it did a better job of
selling. That's allowed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it did such a good job that Windows became the main way
people used personal computers. That's true today. And, over time,
what had been a mediocre product became one that is _ arguably at
least _ better. Macintosh enthusiasts will say that Apple still
leads the way. Linux backers will say that operating system is the
best _ much more stable, much less demanding of system resources.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that the Mac folks or the Linux folks are right.
But the marketplace has voted for Windows so far. It has that
right.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where being a country boy from Arkadelphia, Ark., may
handicap me. I honestly believe that if these products are better,
and sold smarter, that the marketplace will respond, long term.
There are early signs of that. Linux is growing fast (with no help
from the courts). And look at what's been happening with Apple.
People gave it up for dead, but Apple didn't roll over. It created
products that the marketplace wanted. The iMac is probably the
trendiest computer around today.
</P>
<P>
   None of this was done by court order. In fact, had there been a
court order that reduced the clout of Microsoft, the need to
innovate and make a better product wouldn't have been so desperate,
so important. Apple would have rolled along without innovation. The
marketplace, not the courts, creates better products.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's not popular _ and it sounds naive in the dwindling
days of the century _ but I believe the world works best when the
government stays out of the marketplace and lets the strongest
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
