<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: Can you send me the phone number for UT Tower
tours? _ Kerry Watson
</P>
<P>
   A: I hope you want the $3 per person tickets for next year
because tickets for the weekend tours (10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Saturday
and Sunday) are all reserved for this year (ending Dec. 12). That
is the word from the Tower tour staff, who are taking reservations
for next year now. Call 475-6633 or toll-free at (877) 475-6633.
However, reserved tickets that are unclaimed 20 minutes before each
tour will be released to lucky walk-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My son and his fiancee are getting married soon. This is not
the first marriage for either one. Instead of gifts, they would
rather receive money. What is the proper way to indicate this on
the invitations? _ R.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: There is no proper way to include that wish on the
invitation. Carley Roney in ``The Knot's Complete Guide to Weddings
in the Real World'' advises couples to let friends and relatives
know this gift preference and encourage them to spread the word
among guests. The couple may be surprised by the interesting and
useful noncash gifts received, which can always be exchanged for
store credit (or cash) or liquidated (sold at a garage sale). Put
the givers of cash gifts at the top of the thank-you note list. It
is easier to lose a check than a chafing dish in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a third-generation Purdue Boilermaker. Purdue's marching
band takes pride in having ``The World's Largest Drum.'' When I
came to Austin and attended a few Longhorn games, I noticed UT's
band also takes pride in having ``The World's Largest Drum.'' Which
one is actually larger, or are they the same size? _ Bryan Parker
</P>
<P>
   A: Let's start with the University of Texas' drum, Big Bertha.
At 8 feet in diameter, 54 inches (4 1/2 feet) wide, Bertha stands
10 feet tall on her cart. Created by C.G. Conn Ltd., for the
University of Chicago in 1922, it came to UT courtesy of longtime
band benefactor Col. Harold Byrd in 1955. The Boilermakers' drum
was purchased in 1921 from the Leedy Corp. for the band, then
directed by Paul ``Spotts'' Emrick. This drum is ``about 8 feet in
diameter, 48 inches (4 feet wide) and stands (yep) 10 feet tall on
its perch,'' says Purdue's spokeswoman Kathy Matter. So it looks
like Purdue's ``World's Largest Drum'' is not quite as big as UT's
Bertha.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have an address for Milton Friedman? _ Bill P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Address your missives to Nobel Prize winner (for economics,
1976) Friedman in care of the Hoover Institution, Stanford
University, Stanford, CA 94305-6010.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am changing physicians and was informed that charts can
only be transferred from one office to another. Don't I have a
legal right to obtain my personal medical records? _ L.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: You bet you do. I checked with the Texas State Board of
Medical Examiners. Texas law requires a physician to release copies
of records to the patient or a new doctor, says spokeswoman Jill
Wiggins. The request must be in writing and include a description
of the records, the reasons for the release, and the person to whom
the information is to be released.
</P>
<P>
   Exception? If the physician feels releasing the information
would be harmful to the patient's physical or emotional health. The
physician is required to provide the information within 30 days of
receiving the request and may charge reasonable fees ($25 for the
first 20 pages and 15 cents for every page thereafter). Note the
records cannot be withheld based on a past-due account status.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   OK, readers, the requests for the colorful burning pine-cone
recipe have started to cross my desk. Dip pine cones in liquid
floor wax (yes, floor wax) and shake off the excess. Place the
dipped pine cones on newspapers. While they still are damp,
sprinkle with Rainbow Flame Crystals. Let dry. Toss one of your new
and improved pine cones into the fire and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
