A0066 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-TONYSGANG     11-15 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-TONYSGANG16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tony's Gang helps sick children with stories and love
 &HT;    By Cathy Hulbert
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Seven-year-old Craig Little of Kennesaw, Ga.,
practiced reading Dr. Seuss' ``Green Eggs and Ham'' until he almost
knew it by heart.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to read the story perfectly because a recording of his
reading would be sent to a seriously ill child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good doing this, and it'll probably make kids
who are sick feel good, too,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of dozens of children who showed up at an Atlanta
Chapter 11 bookstore to help Tony's Gang with its Tell Me a Story
Project.
</P>
<P>
   Tony's Gang was created to brighten the lives of seriously ill
children and to provide support for their families. It is named for
Tony Lizza, who died of leukemia in 1996 after fighting the disease
for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Leukemia is a type of cancer that affects the blood. The
treatment can make kids feel weak, sometimes too weak to go to
school or play.
</P>
<P>
   Tony's Gang has chapters in Georgia, Pennsylvania and New
Jersey. Others are forming.
</P>
<P>
   For the Tell Me a Story Project, kids take turns reading their
favorite books into a tape recorder. Their stories _ as well as
donated books _ will be sent around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Kids who missed the recent recording session can still help by
writing stories and drawing pictures for the colorful Tony's Gang
Web site at www.tonysgang.com. The Web site features a raccoon and
a chameleon who want to build a treehouse _ the type of treehouse a
sick child can visit from his or her computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sick kids get very lonely sometimes, and this lets them know
that they're still cared about,'' said Ali Lizza, 12, of Marietta.
Ali speaks from experience because she is Tony's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Gretchen Lizza, said, ``Our most enthusiastic
support is coming from kids. They seem to understand what their
peers are going through.'' All stories and drawings submitted by
kids will be published on the Tony's Gang Web site, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Cooper, 9, of Marietta said her reading will make a
difference for sick children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing this because I'd like to help save children's
lives,'' she said. ``If sick kids know they're special, it has to
make them feel better. Being sad can't be good for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig's sister, Casey Little, 8, also showed up to help. She
said sick children ``don't get to hear other kids reading to them
like we do. So this might help.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tony's Gang seeks fund-raising and volunteer support
from adults, ``it's the kids who really get it,'' said Gretchen
Lizza.
</P>
<P>
   The group's other projects include the Pen Pal program, which
gears up in the spring, as well as a year-round collection to round
up new books and tapes for sick kids. Tony's Gang works with
hospital social workers and medical staffers to find kids who could
benefit from the projects.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU WANT TO HELP
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Tony's Gang, call 770-321-1320. Or you
can e-mail Tony's Gang at tonysgang(at)earthlink.net or check out
the Web site at www.tonysgang.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
