<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0068 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN16-C     11-15 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ambush tactics not what the public had in mind
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ What do Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Pete Rose
have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Besides their love of baseball, both were recently ``ambushed''
on national television, once again arousing public indignation over
mean-spirted, unfair reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But what exactly is an ambush? Unless reporters submit all
questions in advance, any TV grilling could constitute an ambush.
An ambush has nothing to do with how tough the questions are. It
has to do with why they're asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of motivation,'' says Stephen Reese, head of
the journalism department at the University of Texas. ``Is the
journalist really trying to get the candidate's views and explain
them to the public? Or is he trying to put another notch in the
microphone?''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, enlightenment, not embarrassment, should be the
motivation. When the motivation is embarrassment, the result is
``gotcha journalism.'' Television is more prone to the charge
because the person's flustered reaction is part of the ``gotcha.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's response to Boston reporter Andy Hiller's pop quiz two
weeks ago is still making news. Bush failed to identify three of
four world leaders, and he said a military coup in Pakistan
appeared to ``bring stability to the country.'' Then he tried to
turn the tables on the questioner, looking angry and defensive.
</P>
<P>
   During the World Series, Pete Rose was cornered by feisty NBC
reporter Jim Gray, who grilled him on whether he'd ever gambled on
baseball. Rose has been asked that question repeatedly and shows no
signs of changing his answer. The questions were legitimate, but it
angered viewers that they were asked when Rose, who was banned from
baseball for gambling, was at an event honoring the century's
greatest ball players. If Gray's motive wasn't bad, irate public
thinking goes, at least his manners were.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, however, Gray's questions to Rose, moments after he
had received a sustained ovation, didn't come out of the blue. At a
nontelevised news conference a short time before, the same
questions had been asked by Gray and others (and not answered). To
home viewers, Gray's combative interview on NBC came out of left
field at a time when Rose was basking in fan adoration.
</P>
<P>
   The public and the broadcast media have been wrestling with
ambush journalism ever since the earliest days of ``60 Minutes,''
when Mike Wallace leapt from behind a potted palm tree and thrust a
microphone into the face of a corporate executive who had been
avoiding him. Sometimes the ambush gets results, but more often
than not it just produces an embarrassed or guilty-looking subject.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldo Rivera has a long history of ambushing people, and any
time Sam Donaldson opens his mouth, he's accused of hostile
behavior. Even the mild-mannered Stone Phillips of ``Dateline NBC''
was accused of ambushing former President Bush with a question
about marital fidelity during the '92 election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambushing a presidential candidate is not necessarily unfair,
if the questions themselves are meaningful and the answers tell us
something,'' Tom Rosenstiel, director of Columbia University's
Project for Excellence in Journalism, said in a report for the
Washington, D.C.-based Freedom Forum.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear the public agrees. According to a recent poll by
the Pew Research Center for People &AMP; the Press, there's been an
erosion of support for the press' role as watchdog. Only 53 percent
of the respondents in a September survey said they value close
media scrutiny of candidates. A growing number believe such
scrutiny is a bad idea because it discourages good candidates from
running. And while the public is critical of the press, 30 percent
said the press is too easy on the front-runners. But campaigns are
so tightly controlled and choreographed that they seem to invite
ambush journalism. Popping off questions unexpectedly may be the
only way reporters can catch a candidate in an unguarded,
unpackaged moment.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters are stuck in a no-win situation. Either they ambush
people and get criticized for unfairness, or they lob softball
questions _ like the ``Do-you-really-have-a-bad-temper?'' fluff
posed to Sen. John McCain by Charlie Gibson on ``Good Morning
America'' recently _ and get accused of sucking up to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's room in the middle for some real discussion of
what the political views are,'' Reese says. ``In the case of Bush,
it's quite important that he be questioned in a lot more detail
than he has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Detail, unfortunately, is a luxury TV reporters usually can't
afford. So many problems and so little time, with important
political stories reduced to sound bites and 30-second hits .
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brevity is) one of the weaknesses people point to, but in a
brief moment, Bush revealed that he thought the Pakistan coup
encouraged stability,'' Reese says. ``It's not necessarily the case
that you can't ask important questions if you have less time.''
</P>
<P>
   So, it's OK to pounce as long as some thought and preparation
goes into the questions. Reporters should ask themselves:
</P>
<P>
   1. Do people need to know the answer?
</P>
<P>
   2. Am I asking this really stupid question because I know he/she
won't know the answer and therefore he/she will look really stupid?
</P>
<P>
   3. Am I hoping that every TV news outlet in the country will
slap my earnest-looking face on the evening news?
</P>
<P>
   If the answer to the first question is yes, the reporter should
fire away. If the answer to either of the other two questions is
yes, the reporter should chant ``Geraldo!'' several times and
abandon the ambush.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
