   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Piedmont, Calif.) _ A small group of prominent
Chinese Americans last year launched an ambitious national
political movement called the ``80-20 Initiative.'' Its specific
goal is to convince Asian Americans to swing 80 percent of their
vote and financial support to the major party presidential
candidate who pledges to support the group's mission. By WILLIAM
WONG.
</P>
<P>
   MAN-OF-THE-CENTURY (San Francisco) _ The world waits for Time
magazine to anoint the ``Man of the Century.'' Realists might
suggest Hitler, Stalin or Mao, the three monsters who together made
the 20th century the bloodiest era of human history. Others might
suggest a real hero like Franklin D. Roosevelt, the man who
(according to his supporters) saved American capitalism during the
1930s and then saved Western civilization during the 1940s. By
WILLIAM M. BURKE.
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMES (Redwood City, Calif.) _ More than a half-century
after the Korean War, the Defense Department is investigating the
massacre of 400 Korean civilians at the No Gun Ri bridge. The
Associated Press reported that U.S. soldiers gunned down the
refugees because of a general's suspicion that North Korean
infiltrators were among the refugees fleeing a Communist onslaught.
Yet there is no apparent willingness to do the same thing with the
Vietnam War. By ELIAS CASTILLIO and JIM BARKER.
</P>
