<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JALEEL-WHITE-IN-GROWN-UPS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JALEEL WHITE BATTLES THE GHOST OF WHAT'S-HIS-NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jaleel White in a scene from
``Grown-Ups.'') 
 By CHRISTOPHER NOXON  
 c.1999 The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jaleel White doesn't like to talk about the character he played
for nearly 10 years on network television.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he'd rather not think at all about that little,
polka-loving dweeb, Urkel. The character's name alone _ goofy and
guttural, an instant buzzword for all things nerdy _ makes him
wince visibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let him die,'' the 22-year-old White says, relaxing on the
patio of Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel. ``I've got a mental
tombstone for that character. I've got lots of flowers around it,
but that boy is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be that easy to erase the memory of the character,
who surely ranks as one of television's most vivid sitcom
creations.
</P>
<P>
   White had made appearances on ``The Jeffersons'' and the pilot
of ``Saved by the Bell'' before auditioning at age 12 for a guest
spot on the ABC series ``Family Matters,'' appearing before
producers in tight suspenders, trousers cut off at mid-shin and an
enormous pair of plastic eyeglasses that framed his darting, googly
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He moved around the sound stage in jerks and jolts, and spoke in
a voice so high-pitched and nasal that it hovered several registers
above that of anyone else who dared inhabit the same scene.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Urkel was born.
</P>
<P>
   That guest spot grew into a starring role, and led the
Friday-night sitcom to an astonishing nine seasons on ABC and CBS,
ranking alongside ``Seinfeld'' for longevity. At the peak of the
show's popularity, the schoolyard set's version of Cosmo Kramer had
a breakfast cereal, an ABC special and legions of fans.
</P>
<P>
   When the end finally came in 1997, long after White had grown
out of the twiggy, 5-foot frame in which he began, ``Family
Matters'' vanished with hardly a peep, its final episodes broadcast
in the Nielsen dead zone of July.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later White has returned to prime-time television in a
most unlikely package. Few recognized him in the opening scene of
his new UPN sitcom, the cannily titled ``Grown-Ups,'' which
premiered in August and is now running Mondays at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Urkel's getup is gone. So is his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Instead we met a bulked-up fellow in a tank top and Air Jordans
who shoots hoops and makes quirky asides to a pudgy sidekick. As J.
Calvin Frazier, a frustrated junior manager at a corrugated-box
company, White is playing the sort of young man who, faced with the
uber-nerd Urkel, would be likely to administer a quick and expert
wedgie.
</P>
<P>
   But even with his gym-enhanced physique, White knows he will
have to work hard to make audiences forget the role that made him
famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you break your Vinnie Barbarino/Mork mode, that's what
you are,'' he says, citing the television roles that sparked the
careers of John Travolta and Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the studio machine had a lot invested
in Urkel,'' he says. ``They sold that character for a decade. You
think you can go out and break that in a year? No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Studio executives at UPN don't mind a bit if the scent of Urkel
clings to the buffed-up White. According to Tom Nunan, the
network's president of entertainment, while the association may not
do much for the struggling network's ``cool factor,'' White has
nothing to be embarrassed about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching him play that part over the years was like watching
Jerry Lewis or Groucho Marx or, dare I say, Charlie Chaplin at
times,'' Nunan says. ``It was perfectly realized. Urkel was a very
successfully rendered character, and a lot of people have a lot of
affection for him.''
</P>
<P>
   White is not one of those people. Shortly after ``Family
Matters'' was canceled, he told a reporter, ``If you ever see me do
that character again, take me out and put a bullet in my head and
put me out of my misery.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor attributes that bitterness to his feeling, long before
the show ended, that he had wholly outgrown his inner Urkel.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in his senior year at the University of California at Los
Angeles, White is a film student and avid jock, closely following
pro and college basketball and hanging out with Anfernee Hardaway,
the star guard for the Phoenix Suns. His speech is fast and
colorful _ ``Some mango would be the bomb,'' he tells a waitress _
and his abilities as a performer, he says, extend far beyond
geekdom.
</P>
<P>
   And while he enjoyed the perks of starring in a long-running
network show, White says he was more than happy to leave behind the
life of a child star.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get credit for what you do _ you get chalked up to
being cute or cuddly,'' he says. ``And you're never treated like
your adult counterparts. They come along and get production deals
and do other shows. With a child, it's like, `Send him a bike.'''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any surprise that the man behind Urkel just wants a little
respect?
</P>
<P>
   To make sure he gets it, White told UPN that he would appear in
``Grown-Ups'' only if he could also produce, working alongside
series creator Matthew Miller.
</P>
<P>
   At first the former child star was not exactly welcomed by
Miller, a 27-year-old screenwriter who had sold ``Grown-Ups'' as an
hour-long dramedy, a sort of ``Ally McBeal'' for guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a phone call telling me that `Grown-Ups' was getting
picked up, but as a half-hour, multi-camera show starring Urkel,''
Miller says in a separate interview. ``I immediately hung up the
phone. That was my big artistic stance _ it lasted about 15
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   His doubts eased, Miller says, when White came in for a reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's totally charming,'' the writer says. ``His timing makes
it so easy to write for him. You just give him the suggestion of a
joke, and he nails it.''
</P>
<P>
   White hopes that audiences will feel the same way once they see
him performing a regular-guy role, wearing pants that fit. In fact,
he's counting on many viewers not making the Urkel association at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times parents will see me on the street, grab their
kids, pull them over and say: `Look, look! Urkel!''' he says. ``And
the kids just look at me, like, `Huh?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how happy that makes me _ at this point, it's
very rewarding not to be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Noxon is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Grown-Ups,'' consult the UPN
Website at www.upn.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0095 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-SINGER-PAUL-MCCARTNEY     11-15 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-PAUL-MCCARTNEY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BACK TO BASICS: PAUL McCARTNEY SINGS THAT OLD-TIME ROCK 'N' ROLL  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Paul McCartney.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Actor Woody Harrelson sits in the VIP room on the mezzanine of
New York's Hammerstein Ballroom, chatting with rocker Sheryl Crow
and awaiting, with several thousand others, a preview playback of
Paul McCartney's new album, ``Run Devil Run.''
 &HT;    ``I guess I've been an enormous fan of his since I was 6,''
Harrelson says. ``It was the first music I listened to. I still
listen to his music every day, every single day.
 &HT;    ``And what I've heard about this album, it's more rockabilly and
rock 'n' roll. I like that.''
 &HT;    So does the rest of the crowd, a mix of contest winners,
celebrities and music-industry folks who sway and dance as ``Run
Devil Run's'' 15 songs _ 12 covers of old, mostly obscure rock 'n'
roll songs and three McCartney originals _ blast over the speaker
system.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, looking tanned and trim in a black suit, McCartney
sits in a quiet office nine stories above, talking about the album
which takes him back to where his legendary career began.
 &HT;    ``Run Devil Run,'' which arrives in stores Tuesday, was in the
works before McCartney's wife, Linda, died of breast cancer 17
months ago. He's released it, he says, as a tribute to her and as a
kind of comfort for himself in its return to his rock 'n' roll
roots.
 &HT;    ``It was next in line, the next project,'' explains the
57-year-old McCartney, who also has his third classical album,
``Working Classical,'' coming out on Oct. 19. ``I wanted to make a
rock 'n' roll record before the 20th century ended. It's also
something Linda was very keen on me doing, and she was egging me
on, really bugging me about it, because she was a big rock 'n' roll
fan.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, I regret she isn't here to hear it,'' he says.
``That's a major regret, but never mind _ we did it for her.''
 &HT;    With a smile, McCartney juts his thumb over his right shoulder.
 &HT;    ``She's still here,'' he says, ``bugging me _ `Come on, man, get
it right!'''
 &HT;    She would most likely be proud, as ``Run Devil Run'' presents
McCartney in his most rocking form in years, possibly since his
1988 collection of oldies for the former Soviet Union, ``CHOBA B
C.C.C.P.'' (``Back in the U.S.S.R.'').
 &HT;    His new songs _ the title track, ``Try Not to Cry'' and ``What
It Is'' _ display the same rollicking, resounding quality as the
covers, and the selections from the catalogs of Elvis Presley,
Chuck Berry, Gene Vincent, Fats Domino and others reveal a personal
and passionate connection to 1950s and early-1960s rock that goes
beyond simple sentimentality and nostalgia.
 &HT;    ``It's pure memories from childhood,'' McCartney says. ``There's
a fairground in Sexton Park where me and my friend Ian James walked
around in our flak jackets with the little flap on the top and
thought we were really cool, and we thought we'd attract women _
and we didn't.
 &HT;    ``To remember it was very exciting,'' he says, ``but also to be
a teen-ager at that time was a very exciting, interesting time. It
was America reawakening the world, because we were into sort of
other stuff. Suddenly Elvis and Little Richard came screaming out
across the Atlantic, and it was just so exciting for us all.''
 &HT;    If the song selection came from his youth, the actual making of
the album harkened back to McCartney's days with the Beatles. The
band which he and co-producer Chris Thomas assembled included his
old friend David Gilmour, the former guitarist from Pink Floyd, as
well as Deep Purple drummer Ian Paice, whom McCartney had never met
_ former Beatle Ringo Starr was his first choice, he says, but
Starr wasn't available.
 &HT;    They then set aside no more than a week in which to make ``Run
Devil Run.''
 &HT;    ``With the Beatles,'' McCartney recalls, ``what we used to do in
the very early days was we were expected to show up at the studio
at 10:00 on a Monday morning and be ready to record at 10:30.
Between 10:30 and 1:30 we were expected to have done two songs _
then we got 1:30 to 2:30 for lunch, then 2:30 to 5:30 for two more
songs. That was the way we did it.''
 &HT;    In that spirit, McCartney didn't even confer with the musicians
ahead of time.
 &HT;    ``So Monday morning it was, `Hey, how you doing? We're going to
make an album together,''' he recalls. ``So it was very
spontaneous, but that was the way I wanted to do it. It was
actually cool working that way _ I got some professional nostalgia
for it.''
 &HT;    The sessions netted 19 songs, 15 of which appear on the album.
The others will be used as B-sides, starting with his version of
Charlie Gracie's ``Fabulous,'' a Top 20 hit in 1957 which was the
first track the ad-hoc band recorded.
 &HT;    ``I met Eric Clapton in a restaurant in L.A. the other night,''
McCartney says. ``He said, `Man, I heard you found some stuff I
don't even know.'
 &HT;    ``These were just pure memories,'' he adds, ``all stuff that
really affected me as a kid.''
 &HT;    His current projects have also brought McCartney back into the
public eye after more than a year devoted primarily to private
mourning. He's held listening parties for ``Run Devil Run'' in Los
Angeles, New York and London, and he recently performed at the
annual awards ceremony for People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals, a cause long dear to Linda McCartney.
 &HT;    But the singer, who hasn't toured since 1993, says he has no
current plans to tour to promote ``Run Devil Run,'' though he
admits that he had ``a real great time'' performing live at the
PETA gig and that tour plans may eventually come together.
 &HT;    ``I think we're going to want to do it,'' McCartney says.
``Normally it's the promoters or your record company wants you to
do it, and there's something that forces you to do a tour. I
thought, `Wouldn't it be really cool if it's the band that's really
itching to get on tour?'
 &HT;    ``It may happen _ not at the moment, but it may well be soon.''
 &HT;    It will be difficult to tour without Linda, he adds. During
their 29-year marriage, they were apart only during the time he
spent in a Japanese jail after a January 1980 arrest for marijuana
possession.
 &HT;    His grieving, McCartney says, is not over, but ``Run Devil Run''
provides an appropriate point of re-entry.
 &HT;    ``It feels good, and it feels like Linda would be very behind
it,'' he says. ``One of the pieces of advice people will give you
if you have a major grief is get busy, keep busy, keep your mind
off it. And I didn't want to do that. I made a point of, for a
year, not doing that.
 &HT;    ``I said `No, I'm going to experience the feelings for a year,
try and find where that all takes me,'' he says. ``So now, after
all that time, I'm feeling more comfortable with just easing back
into things.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Run Devil Run,'' consult the
