<HEADER>
A0096 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-TIM-BURTON-DIRECTS-SL     11-15 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIM-BURTON-DIRECTS-SLEEPY-HOLLOW-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT, ME DARK? TIM BURTON TAKES A RIDE THROUGH `SLEEPY HOLLOW' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Tim Burton directing Johnny Depp in a
scene from ``Sleepy Hollow.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Tim Burton does not live in a black house, with black furniture,
black carpeting and black roses in every room.
 &HT;    There are no coffins in his basement, tombstones in his backyard
or, for that matter, skeletons in his closet.
 &HT;    ``People who know me know I'm not like that,'' Burton says,
flashing a grin. ``I don't even consider my films dark.''
 &HT;    Well, that may be a bit hard to believe. After all, while the
39-year-old director did start off with the sun-dappled ``Pee-wee's
Big Adventure'' (1985), he's since made his name with such sinister
fare as ``Beetlejuice'' (1988), ``Batman'' (1989), ``Edward
Scissorhands'' (1990), ``Batman Returns'' (1992), ``Tim Burton's
The Nightmare Before Christmas'' (1993, which he produced), ``Ed
Wood'' (1996) and ``Mars Attacks'' (1998).
 &HT;    Burton lives up to his reputation by sporting an all-black
ensemble and black shades during a conversation at New York's
Regency Hotel. He's a speed-talker, prone to changing subjects in
midsentence.
 &HT;    ``I've seen dark films,'' he insists. ``I guess it stems from
the puritanical roots of this country, in a way. In Mexico, they
celebrate the Day of the Dead. There's humor involved with it. It's
not treated with such ... `Eeeew.'''
 &HT;    Throughout his career, Burton has proved adept at fusing
``Eeeew'' with humor. And his latest film, ``Sleepy Hollow,'' based
on Washington Irving's ``The Legend of Sleepy Hollow'' and set to
open nationwide on Nov. 19 ... well, let's just say that it won't
help him convince people that he's not a guy who makes dark films.
 &HT;    Set in 1799, the movie stars frequent Burton collaborator Johnny
Depp as Ichabod Crane, an offbeat, queasy constable assigned to
solve a slew of beheadings in Sleepy Hollow, a community as
littered with secrets as it is with corpses. Crane's investigation
brings him into contact with Katrina Van Tassel (Christina Ricci),
daughter of Sleepy Hollow's most affluent couple (Michael Gambon
and Miranda Richardson), and with the notorious Headless Horseman
himself.
 &HT;    ``When I read the script I really liked it, and thought I could
actually do a movie like the ones I loved as a kid,'' Burton says,
``like the Hammer films of the 1950s and 1960s.
 &HT;    ``I knew the `Sleepy Hollow' story from school and the Disney
cartoon,'' he recalls. ``Actually, the cartoon had a fair amount of
inspiration on me because of the chase scene _ I remember, as a
kid, being really affected by that scene.
 &HT;    ``It set the tone I like, which is funny, scary and
action-oriented all at once.''
 &HT;    In his effort to make the best Hammer film Hammer never
produced, Burton erected the Sleepy Hollow village on sound stages
and on location in London. He also tapped the talents of genre
veterans such as Christopher Lee, Richard Griffiths and Michael
Gough.
 &HT;    ``We were so lucky to get Christopher Lee,'' Burton says, giddy
as a vampire at a blood bank. ``When he was sitting there, it was
like looking at Dracula. He's hypnotic.
 &HT;    ``The scene in the movie with Johnny, Michael Gough, Michael
Gambon, Richard Griffiths, Jeffrey Jones and Ian McDiarmid was done
on our first day,'' he recalls. ``I was looking forward to that
day, and I couldn't wait to see all these people in one room at the
same time.
 &HT;    ``I was so scared,'' Burton admits, ``but it was amazing. I was
just looking at all of these guys who've done so many things. I was
like, `There's the Singing Detective,' or `There's Michael Gough,
who was in ``Konga,'' which is one of my favorites,' or `There's
Richard Griffiths and Jeffrey Jones.'
 &HT;    ``It was great, fantastic. I loved it.''
 &HT;    As for Depp, Burton knew from square one that his former Edward
Scissorhands and Ed Wood would make an ideal Ichabod Crane.
 &HT;    ``He does something different each time, and that's fun,''
Burton says. ``I like chameleons _ I like people who are different
from one film to the next.
 &HT;    ``Johnny's never really done action before, and we were going
for action with a bit of elegance,'' the director adds. ``I know
he's a good actor and I knew from `Scissorhands' that he's a good
physical actor, but I was surprised by how well he did the
action.''
 &HT;    Burton's earlier films often hinted at acts of terrible violence
or cruelty, but depicted them discreetly. Heads really do roll,
however, in the R-rated ``Sleepy Hollow'' _ and the director makes
no apologies.
 &HT;    ``It's part of the storytelling,'' he says. ``What I tried to do
was keep it in the fantasy realm, especially given the climate in
the country.''
 &HT;    The recent uproar over violence in movies is misdirected, Burton
believes.
 &HT;    ``There's a lot of talk about violence, obviously,'' he says.
``But I feel that it's the wrong kind of talk. It's easy targets,
and the real root of it is not addressed at all.''
 &HT;    There was plenty of violence in the old Hammer films, he adds,
but he doesn't think it hurt him growing up.
 &HT;    ``If I didn't have the opportunity to see these kinds of movies
when I was a child, I don't know what I'd be like,'' the director
says. ``It was a catharsis for me.
 &HT;    ``Kids need parameters,'' he adds, ``but I think they're pretty
good at finding their own level of what they can and can't take. I
consider `Sleepy Hollow' a fairy tale, and most fairy tales deal
with even more horrific imagery.''
 &HT;    Passionate as he now is about ``Sleepy Hollow,'' Burton didn't
originally plan to make the film. He received the script only after
the long-gestating ``Superman Lives,'' which would have cast
Nicolas Cage as the Man of Steel, hit a wall of Kryptonite.
 &HT;    ``I worked for a year on `Superman,''' Burton says, clearly
still seething more than a year after Warner Bros. pulled the plug
on the project. ``It was a year of my life. We were making the
movie.
 &HT;    ``It was probably one of the most damaging things for my psyche
that I've ever had happen,'' he says. ``I like to be positive, but
I actually feel that I wasted a year of my life. That's a terrible
feeling, and you never want to feel that in anything you do.''
 &HT;    Burton considers himself a Hollywood outsider, though he grew up
in Los Angeles and lives there _ and in New York _ with his
longtime girlfriend, actress Lisa Marie.
 &HT;    ``L.A. is a nice place to visit, but you wouldn't want to live
there,'' Burton says, smiling.
 &HT;    ``Listen, I like weather. I like walking. And those are two
things you can't do in L.A.,'' he says. ``They don't have them _
there's not much weather and you can't walk. If you walk in L.A.,
the cops will stop you and ask what you're doing.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Burton is a rare example of a vanishing breed: a
director who, working within the Hollywood system, is still able to
make highly individualistic films.
 &HT;    ``I've been lucky enough to do what I've wanted to do, even
early on, even within the system,'' Burton admits. ``That's very
lucky, and my luck has held out.
 &HT;    ``I like doing my films,'' the director adds. ``I can't imagine
doing a Western. It would probably be the worst thing.
 &HT;    ``People say, `When are you going to make a real movie?'''
 &HT;    He shrugs.
 &HT;    ``I treat my films as real,'' Burton says. ``I'm sorry, but
they're real movies to me.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Sleepy Hollow,'' consult the
official Website at www2.sleepyhollowmovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
