<SLUG> BC-JEWEL-IN-RIDE-WITH-THE-DEVIL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RIDING' HIGH: JEWEL TAKES HER SHOT AT THE BIG SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jewel with Tobey Maguire in a scene from
``Ride With the Devil.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The name is Jewel _ Jewel Kilcher, technically, but she prefers
to be singular _ and it's hard to discourage her.
 &HT;    Always has been, since her earliest days on stage.
 &HT;    ``When I first started singing, there was one night in a rundown
bar. I was crying because all these drunks were screaming things at
me,'' the 25-year-old singer recalls during an interview at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons hotel. ``But my father said, `Stop thinking
about yourself. A lot of people have it worse than you _ sing for
them.'
 &HT;    ``That was the first moment when I realized that I was put here
on this earth to please an audience.''
 &HT;    That never-quit attitude came in handy when she finally found
the role she wanted to play in her screen debut _ a young frontier
woman who, in Ang Lee's Civil War drama ``Ride With the Devil,'' is
wooed by two young men whose lives are changed forever by a year of
combat.
 &HT;    Before she could even try to convince audiences that she had the
acting chops for the role in the movie, which will open Dec. 10,
Jewel had to persuade an even-more-skeptical audience of one,
director Lee.
 &HT;    ``I told her that I would work with her for six months and then
we would see if she could earn the part,'' Lee recalls in a
separate interview. ``Honestly, we didn't think a big music star
like Jewel would stick with the program where she would learn
acting with no promise of a role.''
 &HT;    But the singer surprised him, persevering and ultimately winning
the role.
 &HT;    ``I've had many movie offers in the past,'' Jewel says. ``But I
chose the Ang Lee movie because it's not so much about war _ to me,
the film's message is that extreme circumstances force you to get
to know yourself.
 &HT;    ``In peaceful times a person can go, `What the hell am I going
to do with myself?''' she says. ``You socialize. You flirt. You get
married _ your entire life is on this course. And I think this
movie shows what happens when something big knocks a human being
off their course.
 &HT;    ``Some of the strongest people I know have had to go to depths
within themselves to fight for their lives,'' she adds. ``They're
currently fighting a war called poverty.
 &HT;    ``But the best part of fighting a war is that you emerge even
stronger,'' she says. ``My friends who survived the most bleak
circumstances have more peace of mind than people who were handed
everything on a platter.''
 &HT;    Even a topless scene didn't dissuade her.
 &HT;    ``There's a scene where I breastfeed someone,'' Jewel says. ``I
felt comfortable doing this on screen, because I knew Ang didn't
put breast-feeding in the movie because he wanted a glimpse of my
boob. He just wanted to add softness and warmth to his movie.
 &HT;    ``For another director, hell no, I wouldn't have done it,'' she
adds. ``For Ang, nothing was impossible for me to muster up.''
 &HT;    ``Nothing is impossible'' is the novice actress's motto,
actually. Jewel Kilcher grew up in rural Homer, Alaska, living with
her bohemian parents and two brothers on 800 acres of land. There
was no television nor running water, and the bathroom was an
outhouse in the field.
 &HT;    ``People ask, `Did you know you were this poor as a child?'''
Jewel says. ``Of course I did _ I grew up in the '80s. All I wanted
in my life back then was a pair of new acid-washed jeans, and I
felt denied because we couldn't afford them.
 &HT;    ``On the other hand,'' she says, ``I also felt very proud of my
heritage as a kid. I felt lucky that I came from a family who could
make things _ we were a really talented family, so for Christmas we
would get beautiful baskets and hand-knit sweaters. These were
gifts that had some meaning behind them.''
 &HT;    Her parents moonlighted as a singing/songwriting duo, and in
their spare time taught their daughter to yodel.
 &HT;    ``It was my show-biz break,'' she says, laughing. ``I was so
good at yodeling that my parents made me part of the show.''
 &HT;    But the show ended a few years later when her parents divorced.
During her father's visits, Jewel would sing with him in different
bars. Her mother devoted her time to home-schooling her daughter
and focusing on music, art and poetry.
 &HT;    Eventually, Jewel earned a voice scholarship to Michigan's famed
Interlochen Arts Academy, where she studied opera, sculpture, dance
and drama.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, her mother moved to San Diego, where times got even
tougher. After Jewel graduated from high school she returned home,
where she and her mother waitressed, punched cash registers and
struggled to make ends meet.
 &HT;    ``When you're poor in the city, that's a different ball of
wax,'' Jewel says. ``It was just about getting by from meal to
meal. And it was about witnessing heartbreak _ I would see people
collapsing in the streets from drug overdoses.''
 &HT;    The worst moment came when she was felled by a kidney infection.
 &HT;    ``I could barely walk,'' she says quietly, ``but I had no
insurance, so hospital after hospital refused to treat me. It was a
brutal wake-up call about life.''
 &HT;    Finally, Jewel decided that she wanted to become a singer and
songwriter.
 &HT;    ``My mother said we needed to give this dream 100 percent
effort,'' she recalls. ``To do that, we couldn't worry about paying
the rent. So we moved into the family van. We would only eat
carrots and peanut butter. At night, I would sing in the local
coffee shops.''
 &HT;    A regular gig at the Innerchange Coffeehouse in Pacific Beach
got her career moving. In 1994 she was signed by Atlantic Records
and sent out on a nationwide coffeehouse tour. The next year, her
debut album, ``Piece of You,'' was released.
 &HT;    It took 14 months, but ``Piece of You'' finally made its way
into the Billboard Top 200. The singles ``Who Will Save Your Soul''
and ``You Were Meant for Me'' eventually climbed the charts, with
the first song peaking at No. 11 and the second hitting No. 2.
 &HT;    The album went triple platinum, and Jewel became a star and an
inspiration to millions.
 &HT;    ``I hate, hate, hate the word idol,'' Jewel says intensely. ``I
would rather be an inspiration.''
 &HT;    Her fans helped make Jewel's second album, ``Spirit'' (1998),
into another hit _ and likewise ``A Night Without Armor: Poems''
(Harper-Collins, 1998), her book of poetry. But she admits to
feeling uncomfortable with their level of devotion.
 &HT;    ``Finally,'' she says, ``I wrote to my fan group on the Internet
and said, `I don't want to cripple people. If I'm here to make you
people worship someone, I will quit right now _ I can't be
responsible for that thinking. I'd much rather you people use the
inspiration I give you to do something with your own lives.''
 &HT;    And Jewel got her wish.
 &HT;    ``For my last birthday,'' she recalls, ``the fans wanted to send
me a present. I'm like, `Hi, I'm rich. Don't need presents. Give
them to people who need them.'
 &HT;    ``Now they send me a book of everyone who does community service
in their areas,'' Jewel says. ``I get thousands of hours of
community service done in my name. That's so cool.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Ride With the Devil,'' consult
the Universal Pictures Website at
www.universalpictures.com/ridewiththedevil. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
