<HEADER>
A0098 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JALEEL-WHITE-IN-GROWN     11-15 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JALEEL-WHITE-IN-GROWN-UPS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JALEEL WHITE BATTLES THE GHOST OF WHAT'S-HIS-NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jaleel White in a scene from
``Grown-Ups.'') 
 By CHRISTOPHER NOXON  
 c.1999 The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jaleel White doesn't like to talk about the character he played
for nearly 10 years on network television.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he'd rather not think at all about that little,
polka-loving dweeb, Urkel. The character's name alone _ goofy and
guttural, an instant buzzword for all things nerdy _ makes him
wince visibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let him die,'' the 22-year-old White says, relaxing on the
patio of Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel. ``I've got a mental
tombstone for that character. I've got lots of flowers around it,
but that boy is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be that easy to erase the memory of the character,
who surely ranks as one of television's most vivid sitcom
creations.
</P>
<P>
   White had made appearances on ``The Jeffersons'' and the pilot
of ``Saved by the Bell'' before auditioning at age 12 for a guest
spot on the ABC series ``Family Matters,'' appearing before
producers in tight suspenders, trousers cut off at mid-shin and an
enormous pair of plastic eyeglasses that framed his darting, googly
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He moved around the sound stage in jerks and jolts, and spoke in
a voice so high-pitched and nasal that it hovered several registers
above that of anyone else who dared inhabit the same scene.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Urkel was born.
</P>
<P>
   That guest spot grew into a starring role, and led the
Friday-night sitcom to an astonishing nine seasons on ABC and CBS,
ranking alongside ``Seinfeld'' for longevity. At the peak of the
show's popularity, the schoolyard set's version of Cosmo Kramer had
a breakfast cereal, an ABC special and legions of fans.
</P>
<P>
   When the end finally came in 1997, long after White had grown
out of the twiggy, 5-foot frame in which he began, ``Family
Matters'' vanished with hardly a peep, its final episodes broadcast
in the Nielsen dead zone of July.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later White has returned to prime-time television in a
most unlikely package. Few recognized him in the opening scene of
his new UPN sitcom, the cannily titled ``Grown-Ups,'' which
premiered in August and is now running Mondays at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Urkel's getup is gone. So is his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Instead we met a bulked-up fellow in a tank top and Air Jordans
who shoots hoops and makes quirky asides to a pudgy sidekick. As J.
Calvin Frazier, a frustrated junior manager at a corrugated-box
company, White is playing the sort of young man who, faced with the
uber-nerd Urkel, would be likely to administer a quick and expert
wedgie.
</P>
<P>
   But even with his gym-enhanced physique, White knows he will
have to work hard to make audiences forget the role that made him
famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you break your Vinnie Barbarino/Mork mode, that's what
you are,'' he says, citing the television roles that sparked the
careers of John Travolta and Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the studio machine had a lot invested
in Urkel,'' he says. ``They sold that character for a decade. You
think you can go out and break that in a year? No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Studio executives at UPN don't mind a bit if the scent of Urkel
clings to the buffed-up White. According to Tom Nunan, the
network's president of entertainment, while the association may not
do much for the struggling network's ``cool factor,'' White has
nothing to be embarrassed about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching him play that part over the years was like watching
Jerry Lewis or Groucho Marx or, dare I say, Charlie Chaplin at
times,'' Nunan says. ``It was perfectly realized. Urkel was a very
successfully rendered character, and a lot of people have a lot of
affection for him.''
</P>
<P>
   White is not one of those people. Shortly after ``Family
Matters'' was canceled, he told a reporter, ``If you ever see me do
that character again, take me out and put a bullet in my head and
put me out of my misery.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor attributes that bitterness to his feeling, long before
the show ended, that he had wholly outgrown his inner Urkel.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in his senior year at the University of California at Los
Angeles, White is a film student and avid jock, closely following
pro and college basketball and hanging out with Anfernee Hardaway,
the star guard for the Phoenix Suns. His speech is fast and
colorful _ ``Some mango would be the bomb,'' he tells a waitress _
and his abilities as a performer, he says, extend far beyond
geekdom.
</P>
<P>
   And while he enjoyed the perks of starring in a long-running
network show, White says he was more than happy to leave behind the
life of a child star.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get credit for what you do _ you get chalked up to
being cute or cuddly,'' he says. ``And you're never treated like
your adult counterparts. They come along and get production deals
and do other shows. With a child, it's like, `Send him a bike.'''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any surprise that the man behind Urkel just wants a little
respect?
</P>
<P>
   To make sure he gets it, White told UPN that he would appear in
``Grown-Ups'' only if he could also produce, working alongside
series creator Matthew Miller.
</P>
<P>
   At first the former child star was not exactly welcomed by
Miller, a 27-year-old screenwriter who had sold ``Grown-Ups'' as an
hour-long dramedy, a sort of ``Ally McBeal'' for guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a phone call telling me that `Grown-Ups' was getting
picked up, but as a half-hour, multi-camera show starring Urkel,''
Miller says in a separate interview. ``I immediately hung up the
phone. That was my big artistic stance _ it lasted about 15
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   His doubts eased, Miller says, when White came in for a reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's totally charming,'' the writer says. ``His timing makes
it so easy to write for him. You just give him the suggestion of a
joke, and he nails it.''
</P>
<P>
   White hopes that audiences will feel the same way once they see
him performing a regular-guy role, wearing pants that fit. In fact,
he's counting on many viewers not making the Urkel association at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times parents will see me on the street, grab their
kids, pull them over and say: `Look, look! Urkel!''' he says. ``And
the kids just look at me, like, `Huh?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how happy that makes me _ at this point, it's
very rewarding not to be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Noxon is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Grown-Ups,'' consult the UPN
Website at www.upn.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
