<HEADER>
A0111 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-ROCK-OLDSTERS-KANSAS-     11-15 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-OLDSTERS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW' ALBUMS BY CSNY AND OTHER AGNIG ROCKERS JUST AREN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TIMOTHY FINN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title of the brand-new Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young CD is
``Looking Forward,'' and on the wispy title track, Neil Young
sings: ``Writing a song, won't take very long//Trying not to use
the word `old' ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Age and maturity, though, are the implicit themes on this
record. Nearly 30 years after they released ``Deja Vu,'' one of the
more acclaimed epilogues to the 1960s, CSN&AMP;Y are together again,
older and richer and willing to share the bounty of their years.
(Young turned 54 on Friday; the others are between 55 and 60.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking Forward'' is one of several major-label records
released recently by seminal//mythical rock stars trying to deal
with their maturity without speaking the word ``old,'' and like
most of those records, ``Forward'' suffers from that inherent
denial. As a writer for salon.com wrote in a bit about the CSN&AMP;Y
album and world tour: ``I almost cut my hair ... then I remembered
I didn't have any.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletes and actors have peaks, primes and declines _ natural,
physical paths to retirement. But rock stars? They just keep
writing songs, keep hoping that the generation that grew up with
them will grow old with them, will negotiate their shifts in focus:
from sex, drugs and rebellion to regrets, love, melancholy,
divorce, rebirth, death ...
</P>
<P>
   It was in the winter of my 50th year when it hit me//I was
really alone//And there wasn't a hell of a lot of time left ...
</P>
<P>
   That's Iggy Pop, 52, reciting the poem that opens ``Avenue B,''
his fierce, lugubrious new disc inspired by a recent divorce.
</P>
<P>
   His intent, Pop told Mojo magazine, was to write specific lyrics
and good melodies that would ``provoke emotion without depending on
noise ... It's not a divorce record. It's a post-marriage record
about a guy figuring out what he's going to do with what is left of
his life.''
</P>
<P>
   That precise objective served him well. ``Avenue B'' gets
uncomfortably raw and emotional, proving that, like visual artists
and photographers, rock musicians can remain fresh and provocative
as they get older _ or because they've grown older.
</P>
<P>
   On ``She Calls Me Daddy,'' Pop sits alone in the dead quiet of
his apartment, reliving his mistreatment of a woman he slowly froze
out of his life: ``I was always ashamed she read Cosmopolitan//I
should have been proud of her ...//She just wanted to believe
someone would love her ...''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Avenue B'' is the only recent exception to the rule. Like
Dylan's highly acclaimed, Grammy-winning ``Time Out of Mind,''
Pop's new record succeeds because Iggy is up front about his
position in life _ he's growing older and more alone _ something
Sting, 49, isn't ready to admit, at least not on record.
</P>
<P>
   On the title track to ``Brand New Day,'' a feeble flight of
adult-contemporary tunes, Sting, who was once inspired to sing
about the tyranny of South American dictators, sings wistfully
about the future: ``Turn the clock to zero, honey//I'll sell the
stock, we'll spend all the money//We're starting a brand new day.''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to a rock superstar to figure his portfolio will buy
him time, or at least a fresh start. The rest of the album is a
sunshower of platitudes and cliches dressed in slick, predictable
pop arrangements _ the sounds of a guy who will charter a flight to
the Bahamas when winter sets into his 50th year.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately CSN&AMP;Y's ``Looking Forward'' suffers some of the
same afflictions: vacuous anthems about hope and paradise; lyrics
weakened by cliches, sentimentality or rank pretension.
</P>
<P>
   Young's contributions are the most respectable, though they
sound a lot like the better country-folk moments on ``Harvest
Moon.'' Beyond those tunes, there are plenty of sweet, perfect
vocal harmonies but little flavor or heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seen Enough'' is Stills' cranky sermon against all that
cyber-stuff the yung'uns are into these days; ``Heartland,'' one of
Nash's two contributions, is an outsider's mushy conception of life
here in slow, lazy middle America, where people ``try to share
their hopes and dreams'' and where ``on any given day you can find
your way back home ...'' (But you might want to avoid the Grandview
Triangle.)
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, who has suffered two lives' worth of personal turmoil
and torment, nonetheless commits the most severe acts of banality.
On ``Stand and Be Counted,'' he sings: I want to stand alone in
front of the world and that oncoming tank//Like that Chinese boy
that we all have to thank ...
</P>
<P>
   Later, on ``Dream for Him,'' he festers over what to tell his
young son and other innocents about all the bad things out there in
the world today _ like two-faced politicians. Whatever happened to
teaching your children well?
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between Sting's tedium, CSN&AMP;Y's pretensions and Iggy
Pop's naked testimony lies the intent of David Bowie, 52, on his
album ``Hours ... ,'' released in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a complicated album, by any means,'' he blithely told
Rolling Stone recently. ``It's just a guy reflecting on his
youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Musically, the record showcases Bowie's voice and his strengths
as a songwriter, at times invoking the flavors of records like
``Heroes'' and ``Low.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically, though, ``Hours ...'' could use a little more
complication. Unfortunately, things don't get more introspective
than wan lines like, ``All of my life I've tried so hard//Doing my
best with what I had//Nothing much happened all the same ...''
Ultimately, Bowie sounds detached from the project, like he's
making a cameo appearance on his own album.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone deserves extra slack, though, it's Bowie, who has
proved that he's capable of remaking himself or of concocting his
own provocative take on whatever fresh fad catches his fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Other rockers emeritus look back for an excuse to cut an album,
such as Bryan Ferry, 54, one of Bowie's contemporaries. ``As Time
Goes By,'' Ferry's first record in five years or so, is his version
of several 1930s standards.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Run Devil Run,'' the new record of old-time rock songs by
Paul McCartney, 57, Ferry's ``Time'' is essentially a vanity
project: a few of his favorite songs. Lacking a similar emotional
attachment, though, the listener ultimately feels uninterested,
like he's watching slides of someone else's vacation to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Devil,'' McCartney called in famous friends like David
Gilmour of Pink Floyd and Ian Paice of Deep Purple to help him
re-create the music that made him want to be a rock star way back
in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the record is crisp and brilliant. Emotionally,
though, it is 15 shades of neutral. `` `Run Devil Run' is the sound
of the past and the promise of the future,'' the liner notes say.
``It is Paul McCartney looking forward by stepping back.'' And
slogans like that are the rationale of an artist out of fresh
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Ferry, bless his heart, curtly explains his dearth of fresh
material: He refuses to put out inferior music, a trait some have
confused for writer's block or an addiction to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   In Mojo recently, he told a writer: ``I felt pressure to get
something out because I hadn't had anything for a long time ...
From `Boys and Girls' (1985) onwards, it's been dead slow, I must
confess, but I think your life gets more complicated as you get
older.''
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, on the other hand, contrives a supernal explanation for
what inspired ``Looking Forward.'' In promotional literature
provided by Reprise Records, he starts with a truth: ``One of the
things they used to say about us was that we were speaking for our
generation ...''
</P>
<P>
   But he parlays that into a wobbly assumption: ``And I think in a
sense that's still true. You hear a lot of music these days about
rage and frustration and anger but not much about hope and love and
forward motion. That's what we continue to stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   That hardly explains the end of ``Looking Forward,'' a song
written by Denny Sarokin called ``Sanibel.'' The song includes
images of a girl in white, a ship, an island and ``starlit nights
in paradise,'' which is where the singer ultimately wants to spend
his life.
</P>
<P>
   CSN&AMP;Y will tour the world (they come to Kemper Arena on Jan. 26)
and they will no doubt rock the place by reliving so many of their
fine songs.
</P>
<P>
   But records like ``Looking Forward'' and ``Brand New Day'' make
it clear that, like jocks and actors, rock stars have their primes,
too: Eventually the spotlight leaves them and their muse loses
context and fresh ideas, no matter what they continue to stand for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
