<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0117 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BIOGRAPHY-EMBELLISHME     11-15 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOGRAPHY-EMBELLISHMENT-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAGAN BIO IS LATEST IN NONFICTION EMBELLISMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 GEORGE GURLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many readers have turned to biographies in recent years,
complaining of a dearth of good stories and characters in
contemporary novels. Perhaps as a way of addressing this
deficiency, it has become commonplace for novelists to introduce
historical characters in their fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes this has been effective _ J. Edgar Hoover, Frank
Sinatra and others in Don Delillo's Underworld, Bobby Kennedy, JFK
and Howard Hughes in James Ellroy's American Tabloid. Often,
however, the device comes across as a lazy man's way to create
verisimilitude.
</P>
<P>
   But fiction is one thing, nonfiction another. What are we to
make of a biography _ a literary form that's supposed to be factual
_ in which fictional characters appear?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Edmund Morris did in his biography of Ronald Reagan,
Dutch, which has been the recipient of a nearly unanimous barrage
of rotten tomatoes. Morris, who won a Pulitzer Prize for his
biography of Teddy Roosevelt, says that he turned to fiction
because _ after 14 years of work and extraordinary access to Reagan
and his personal papers _ he was still unable to explain the man.
Morris thought fiction would help him get inside Reagan so he could
reveal what makes him tick.
</P>
<P>
   Most complaints about Dutch are that _ fact or fiction _ it's
not a very good book. Michiko Kakutani in The New York Times called
it a ``bizarre, irresponsible and monstrously self-absorbed book''
with ``a looney hodgepodge of fact and fiction.'' Peggy Noonan in
The Wall Street Journal said it was a ``high dive, belly flop into
the pools of Narcissus.'' Joan Didion in The New York Review of
Books chastised Morris for factual errors as well as sophomoric
fictional devices. The consensus seems to be that the fictional
characters and scenes in Dutch are not just extraneous to Reagan
but don't work on any level.
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, see Dutch not just as a hatchet job but as a
violation of the nonfiction writer's obligation to tell the truth.
Kakutani, for one, deplored the tendency of today's writers to
project themselves and their prejudices into matters of fact.
</P>
<P>
   But is this altogether bad? If biography were just about facts,
people wouldn't keep writing new books about the same person.
There's always room for reinterpretation. There never will be an
end to biographies of Napoleon or Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Biographer Judith Thurman _ author of Secrets of the Flesh: A
Life of Colette _ boldly affirmed the point in a recent article.
``There is no objective biography,'' she said. ``You are judging in
what you choose to describe and the way you choose to structure the
story. The question is how conscious you are of your own
subjectivity and how much latitude you can allow your subject.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of autobiography, another supposedly nonfiction form
where the author ought to know the facts, the last thing we expect
is truth. On the contrary, we expect the author to put himself in
the best light and his enemies in the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Embellish or not?
</P>
<P>
   In his recently released memoir, River-Horse: The Log Book of a
Boat Across America, William Least Heat-Moon created Pilotis, a
``sequential composite'' character based on the seven people who
accompanied him on parts of the trip. The first thing you notice
about Pilotis it that ``he'' is remarkably eloquent and witty. Did
Heat-Moon prune, embellish and burnish his utterances?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first place, the people I asked to go with me are
well-read and articulate,'' he said in a recent conversation.
``When they said something memorable I told them to write it down.
I burnished to the extent that I cut out the stupid things they
said and things that would take away from the unity of the
character, Pilotis.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat-Moon said he wouldn't feel comfortable with making
something up and putting it in someone else's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the reader to have confidence that I'm reporting
accurately,'' he said. ``But I'd argue for the right of anyone else
to embellish. My rule of thumb is that as long as the reader knows
what you're doing, it's fair. When you come to the end of Midnight
in the Garden of Good and Evil, John Berendt tells you that he's
made some of this up. Why didn't he tell you at the beginning?''
</P>
<P>
   Heat-Moon said he was afraid of getting some flak for Pilotis
due to the controversy surrounding Dutch. But he informs the reader
of Pilotis' composite nature at the outset. Furthermore, was he
under the same obligation as Morris? The seven characters who make
up Pilotis aren't players on the public stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of the democracy didn't depend on anything any of
us said,'' Heat-Moon said. Nor does he present himself as a
journalist, reporting on someone else's trip. In the case of
River-Horse, which would you rather have, aesthetic truth or
journalistic truth?
</P>
<P>
   Robert Unger, associate professor and head of the Urban
Journalism program at the University of Missouri-Kansas City,
agreed with Heat-Moon's rule for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it `truth in advertising,' '' Unger said. ``If you make
it clear what you're doing, it's usually OK. In the case of Dutch,
Morris did some things to conceal what he was going, such as making
up footnotes ... You have to ask what's your contract with the
readers. If it's simply to entertain them, you can do pretty much
what you want to. If your contract is to tell them what really
happened, you have to do just that. It may be open to the writer's
interpretations, but it's not open to manufacturing quotes,
characters and events ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Trust or not?
</P>
<P>
   ``A truth is not hard to kill,'' wrote Mark Twain. ``A lie told
well is immortal.'' William Faulkner made up many unforgettable
characters in his novels _ fair enough. But he also told tall tales
about his exploits in the Royal Air Force. Whom can we trust? Can
we put our hands on anything that's absolutely true? Alas, for the
real skinny, we may have to wait until Judgment Day. Even in the
sciences, which aspire to the highest standards of truth, there
have been cases of falsification.
</P>
<P>
   Freud has been accused of having suppressed facts that would
have contradicted his theories. Margaret Mead distorted the truth
in her famous anthropological study Coming of Age in Samoa,
according to anthropologist Derrick Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   Mead argued that young girls go through puberty without sexual
hang-ups in Samoa because of its liberated culture. Freeman has
charged that Mead heard what she wanted to hear and that her thesis
is the virtual opposite of the truth. Samoans are in fact very
uptight and repressive about sexual matters, according to him.
</P>
<P>
   The most venerated historical traditions, in fact, may partake
of fiction. A big issue in anthropology today is the ``invention of
traditions,'' said Allan Hansen, University of Kansas professor of
anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that a lot of oral histories of cultures are
highly embellished and made up to suit political agendas of the
present rather than representing accurate accounts of the past,''
he said. ``It's not so much that the people are lying. It's that
tradition is, in fact, an embellishment of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen himself has written about the ``invention of tradition''
in the case of the Maori culture in New Zealand. And he's run into
some opposition from New Zealanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't like to be told that their `traditions' aren't
historically accurate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, Hansen grew up in Ronald Reagan's hometown,
Dixon, Ill. Before he was born his family actually lived in one of
the houses Reagan lived in.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to Dixon, Hansen noticed a mural in his motel
of the young Reagan in a swimsuit along with a tribute to the
legend that he saved the lives of some 70 people when he was a
lifeguard. (The main fictional character in Dutch is one of those
Reagan ``saved.'')
</P>
<P>
   `` `Gee,' I thought,'' said Hansen. `` `That's a lot of people.
There must have been a terrible rash of drownings in Dixon after he
retired.' '' Hansen thought it over and concluded that Reagan
probably counted it as a rescue every time he blew his whistle.
``Talk about invented tradition,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
