<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
Nov. 16. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   HMO: Beginning next year, Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs will
face the biggest cut in benefits in this decade. Premiums also are
going up in most HMOs. The is happening nationwide because of
federal cutbacks in Medicare payments, healthcare inflation and the
rising cost of prescription drugs. About 50,000 area seniors are
enrolled in Medicare HMOs. This doesn't affect the 200,000 local
folks who just get regular Medicare, which provides fewer benefits.
Alan Bavley. 35. Photo possible. Graphic
</P>
<P>
   ECOM. Worries grow that the move to Internet commerce, now
estimated at $14.9 billion a year, will cut into local sales tax
revenue; state, city and county governments are lobbying the fed to
tax the Internet and the idea is under study. Brad Cooper. Graphic
possible.
</P>
