</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFT-IDEAS-HEALTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    HOLIDAY GIFT IDEAS THAT ARE BOOD FOR BODY AND SOUL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;    (Eds: Not for use before Monday, Nov. 15) 
 &HT;     
 &HT;    By PHIL DAVIS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Natural medicines and herbal remedies are hot. But it can be
tough for a novice to figure out what's good for what. And it's
possible to go broke buying the plethora of books touting the
healing powers of everything from cayenne pepper for arthritis to
St. John's wort for depression.
</P>
<P>
   Enter ``The PDR Family Guide to Natural Medicines and Healing
Therapies,'' (Crown Publishing; $23), which promises to ``sort the
help from the hype'' in the growing field of natural medicines.
</P>
<P>
   This objective guide, published by the editors of the respected
Physician's Desk Reference, offers a serious evaluation of hundreds
of herbal remedies and therapies, including evaluations of which
work and which remain unproven. The guide, available at most
bookstores and Internet booksellers, also offers advice on how to
choose a qualified herbal practitioner and ways to protect against
quacks and frauds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a door, it's a beginning,'' says a sign at the
front of Teddy G's Boxing Gym in Reseda, where $79 a month gets you
24 workouts with former amateur boxer Teddy Groat. It's the perfect
gift for a stressed-out loved one _ or anyone looking for a good,
aggressive aerobic workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, they're not in good shape when they come in, but you
can bet they are in great shape when they leave,'' Groat said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his clients are men and women looking to get in shape,
not take on Mike Tyson. But, Groat said, after a few months most
people should know how to survive in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (818) 345-8200. The Hollywood Gym on
La Brea Los Angeles also offers boxing lessons at $89 a month. Call
(323) 845-1420.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, long hair and baseball didn't mix. Small holes
were cut in the back of batting helmets to accommodate ponytails,
but extricating the hair from the hole can be a hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Fret no more, long-locked athletes. The Female Athlete offers a
``ponytail-friendly batting helmet,'' which features a raised
ponytail port on the back. No threading required. Just slip it on
and step up to the plate. The helmet costs $27. Call (888) 316-5882
to order.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Frisbees? These flying disks never really went out of
fashion, but they often are overlooked as an inexpensive gift or
stocking stuffer. It's tough to beat the simple fun of tossing a
saucer around a park or beach _ and it's not bad exercise either.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Frisbee is tough to find on cluttered toy store
shelves, but there are some intriguing alternatives. Our favorite
comes from Van Nuys-based WPF Inc. _ ``The Brain Freaky Flying
Disc.'' The squishy foam saucer looks _ as advertised _ like a
brain. You can also get a shark, mouth, Earth, eyeball or pizza.
Freaky Flying Discs cost $7.99 at Toys `R' Us.
</P>
<P>
   Too many hoop dreams are dashed by strict neighborhood codes
that prohibit basketball backboards in driveways. But there are
many fine portable goal systems that can be wheeled out for fun and
stored away when the game's over. The goals, available at many
local mass-merchandise and sporting-goods retailers, range in price
from $100 to $250. The more expensive goals offer more options:
adjustable height _ from 7 to 10 feet _ and backboards that can
withstand slam dunks.
</P>
<P>
   For those who like to hike, authors Jerry Schad and John
McKinney have written two books that are literal hiking catalogs
for Angelenos. McKinney's ``Day Hiker's Guide to Southern
California'' (Olympus Press; $14.95) and Schad's ``101 Hikes in
Southern California: Exploring Mountains, Seashore and Desert''
(Wilderness Press; $15.95) rank everything from the difficulty of a
hike to the scenery. Both books are available in stores or on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Fitness nuts who prefer function over fashion will love the
Timex 100-lap Ironman Triathlon watch. The watch features an
Indiglo night light that activates at the flick of a wrist, a dated
training log diary and enough memory to store 100 lap times. The
Ironman costs $59.95 and is available at most sporting-goods stores
or major retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say a glass of red wine a day can help the body fight
heart disease. It tastes great, too. Bryan Thomas, manager of
Woodland Hills Wine Co., recommends three red wines you can give as
a toast to a loved one's good health: A 1996 Spelletich Cellars
cabernet sauvignon, $29.99; a 1997 Stags Leap Wine Cellars cabernet
sauvignon, $29.99; or a 1996 Lewis Cellars merlot, $31.99. Cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Biking anytime can be hard on the posterior. And biking at night
in Los Angeles can be lethal. The Velo Flash Gelite Safety Flash
bike seat tackles both these problems with a squishy,
posterior-friendly gel filling and red LED lights on the back to
catch the attention of clueless motorists. The seat cost $19.99 at
Target. Batteries included.
</P>
<P>
   For those gift-givers looking for a ridiculously expensive gift,
the folks at Sunbeam have come up with the Body Comp Scale. The
scale uses a low-frequency current to determine weight, percentage
of body fat, lean muscle mass and body mass index. The information
is printed out on a color printer. With a price tag of $3,595, the
folks at Sunbeam aren't kidding when they say the scale is for
serious or affluent users only. Call (800) 815-6615 to order it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
