<HEADLINE>
&HT;    HIGH-TECH TOYS MAKE GREAT HOLIDAY GIFTS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;    (Eds: Not for use before Sunday, Nov. 14) 
 &HT;     
 &HT;    By DAVID BLOOM 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Digital video
</P>
<P>
   Digital video is one of this season's hottest trends. Shoot your
stuff on a digital video camera, edit it on a computer, then master
it to DVD or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sony and Apple are making the most DV friendly computers, with
the high-speed IEEE 1394 connectors for transferring video and
great editing software.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's newest iMacs include two with DVD drives, and their G4s
are the most powerful desktop computers ever. Both lines combine
the delightful Mac operating system, tremendous power and easy
iMovie editing software, for as little as $1,299.
</P>
<P>
   For Windows-compatible machines, Sony's Digital Studio line is
the way to go. The top-end model comes loaded, with a DVD-ROM
drive, a rewritable CD-ROM drive and tons of software, including a
limited-edition version of Adobe's Premiere video-editing software
for less than $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Computer software
</P>
<P>
   For children's titles, try Midnight Play, based on a notable
Czech illustrator's work; and Trans-Con!, an engrossing simulation
of building the transcontinental railroad last century.
</P>
<P>
   For golfers, Links LS 2000 is the choice, while the abiding
beauty of the newly gussied-up Myst Masterpiece Edition remains a
good choice for many.
</P>
<P>
   For offbeat reference, try National Geographic Maps, all 8
CD-ROMS of it, and Mad, with more than 500 Mad magazines and
special issues and lots of wacky extras.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzle fans will adore Pandora's Box, the latest creation of the
Russian wizard who made Tetris. And strategy gamers will love
Panzer General Assault 3D and Command &AMP; Conquer Tiberian Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Folks who like a little gore will go for the beautifully wrought
Nocturne and, assuming it ships in a couple of weeks, Quake III
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Consoles
</P>
<P>
   For Sega Dreamcast, start with Sonic Adventure, Soul Calibur and
Ready2Rumble, the best of the launch titles. Then add NBA Showtime:
the NBA on NBC; Virtua Fighter 3tb; Sega Bass Fishing; and Air
Force Delta.
</P>
<P>
   For Sony PlayStation, great new titles include: the
free-wheeling Omega Boost; role-playing wonder Final Fantasy VIII;
music game Um Jammer Lammy; extreme sports Tony Hawk's Pro Skater
and Cool Boarders 4; and wrestling title WCW Mayhem. For real
mayhem, try Dino Crisis and Resident Evil 3 Nemesis. For great
driving fun, try Hot Wheels Turbo Racing and Crash Team Racing.
</P>
<P>
   For Nintendo N64, younger gamers will beg for Pokemon Snap! Also
try Mario Party and Super Smash Brothers for multiplayer fun. Older
players will enjoy Quake II and another PC import, the real-time
strategy game, Command &AMP; Conquer. &UR; !end! &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
