<HEADLINE>
&HT;    TOP MUSICAL GIFTS FOR THE HOLIDAYS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;    (Not for use before Tuesday, Nov. 16) 
 &HT;     
 &HT;    By FRED SHUSTER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to remember what the dressing room of Hollywood's
now-defunct Club Lingerie looked like to be enthralled by author
Lewis Shiner's realistic account of the fictional rise and fall of
a Next Big Thing named Laurie Moss. With unusual insight, ``Say
Goodbye'' ($23.95) tells you what that dressing room looked like _
plus a lot more about the machinations of the music biz as it
devours promising new talent. We follow Moss from her Texas roots
to her first recording contract, from her struggling early days in
Los Angeles to her final tour _ and beyond. A rock fan won't find a
better read this year.
</P>
<P>
   Soul music didn't disappear with the popularity of hip-hop, it
just packed up and moved to Jackson, Miss., where the mighty Malaco
label is based. ``The Last Soul Company: Malaco _ A 30 Year
Retrospective'' ($70.97) is a delightful six-disc box featuring
various artists that proves the patient is still robust. Included
among these 112 examples of gritty Southern r&AMP;b magic are obvious
'70s gems like King Floyd's ``Groove Me,'' Jean Knight's ``Mr. Big
Stuff,'' Dorothy Moore's elegant ``Misty Blue'' and raw, earthy
sides from Little Milton, Bobby ``Blue'' Bland, Johnny Taylor and
the great Bobby Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, ``At the Close of a Century'' ($59.97, in stores
Nov. 23) is the first comprehensive retrospective of Stevie
Wonder's incredible career, and they really got it right. These 70
beautifully remastered selections span the '60s through the '90s on
four discs, collecting all of Wonder's 27 Top 10 hits, key album
tracks, soundtrack contributions and a first-time rarity: Wonder's
original 1967 version of ``Until You Come Back to Me (That's What
I'm Gonna Do),'' a Top 10 hit for Aretha Franklin in '74.
</P>
<P>
   Considered one of the greatest rock concert films ever, ``Stop
Making Sense'' was first shown in 1984. Using no voice-overs, no
cut-aways to the audience or backstage and no between-song patter,
director Jonathan Demme focused on the music of Talking Heads and
had 'em dancing in the aisles. The remixed and remastered DVD
version of ``Stop Making Sense'' ($29.95) includes three audio
mixes, several bonus tracks that didn't make it on the original
soundtrack, commentary by all four band members and Demme, original
promotional trailer, and more.
</P>
<P>
   CDs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Midnite Vultures,'' Beck ($17.97, in stores Nov. 23).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Battle of Los Angeles,'' Rage Against the Machine
($17.97).
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural,'' Santana ($17.97).
</P>
