<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i PM-CHINA-U.S.TRADE-575&AMP;A     11-15 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., CHINA REACH ACCORD ON BILATERAL TRADE, MEMBERSHIP IN WORLD
TRADE BODY 
</HEADLINE>
 PM-CHINA-U.S.TRADE-575&AMP;ADD-NYT  (gm) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM with DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ American and Chinese trade negotiators announced one
of the largest trade deals in American history Monday, a
comprehensive agreement to open China's economy to foreign
competitors in return for Beijing's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The United States trade representative, Charlene Barshefsky, and
China's trade minister, Shi Guangsheng, signed the agreement here
at 3:50 p.m. Monday, shook hands and raised a champagne toast to
the conclusion of 13 years of on-and-off negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just say that this is a profound and historic moment in
U.S.-China relations,'' said a clearly exultant Ms. Barshefsky,
adding that the agreement would not only aid the economies of both
countries but also serve as an anchor in their tumultuous political
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The last six days of arduous negotiations were conducted in a
``win-win spirit,'' Shi said at the ceremony, ``and finally we
reached an agreement that serves the interests of both China and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After the signing, Ms. Barshefsky and Gene Sperling, the White
House chief of economic policy, were driven to the secluded
leadership compound for a brief meeting and photo opportunity with
the Chinese president, Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   The accord goes to the heart of China's transition to an open,
market economy and for the first time it puts Beijing under the
jurisdiction of the rules of international trade set by the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   It also provides a badly needed centerpiece for President
Clinton's fraying policy of engagement with China _ holding the
promise of tangible benefits for many American companies and
consumers, as well as a positive influence on China's future
development.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Turkey on Mondday, Clinton said: ``I think this is a
good agreement for China, for America and for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has spoken often of ``integrating China into the world
economy'' and gradually getting the country to embrace ``the rule
of law,'' starting with commercial law. But without a WTO
agreement, his aides said, he would have little progress to point
to.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement may also help to repair the damage done from
charges of Chinese spying in the United States, the accidental
American bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade last May and
China's continuing suspicion that the United States is attempting
to ``contain'' its military and economic power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Successful completion of WTO will go a long way to smooth out
some of the extreme oscillation that we have seen in Sino-American
relations in recent years,'' said Joseph Fewsmith, a China expert
at Boston University. ``I think it gives us a chance to build some
substance into a relationship that has been badly damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   The WTO sets rules for global commerce, adjudicates disputes and
is generally intended to press for freer markets. Monday's
agreement is a huge step toward membership for China. It still must
complete side agreements with the European Union, Canada and some
developing countries before its application can be taken up by the
body's 134 member states, but Shi on Monday expressed the hope that
China could be in by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably already too late, experts said, for China to be
fully admitted before Nov. 30, when a new round of global trade
negotiations will begin in Seattle, but these talks are expected to
last for years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   From the beginning, the American goal was to press China not
only for large reductions in tariffs on imported farm products and
industrial goods such as automobiles, but to persuade China to
commit itself to allowing foreign companies to take majority
investments in many industrial and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement involves a general reduction in China's import
tariffs from the current average of 22.1 percent down to 17
percent, with tariffs on major American farm products cut sharply
to 15 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   Tariffs on automobile imports, which now range up to 100 percent
to protect China's inefficient producers, will be reduced over a
six-year period to 25 percent, with the fastest reduction in the
initial years. Equally important, foreign auto companies and banks
will for the first time be able to offer consumer loans for car
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Chinese consumers may soon be purchasing General Motors
cars, for example, with the ``GMAC'' loans so familiar to
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most contentious issues in recent days, Ms.
Barshefsky said, involved the American demands for ways to respond
to ``import surges'' and for use of a methodology to identify
illegal ``dumping.'' China wanted such measures to phase out
quickly, but in the end agreed to surge protections for a 12-year
period, and the anti-dumping regime for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the textile area, politically sensitive in the United States,
it was the Americans who called for restrictions on free trade. The
Chinese wanted to scale back the American demand to continue its
existing textile import quotas for another 10 years. In the end,
the United States agreed to end quotas after five years, but with
special ``anti-surge'' safeguards for another four years after
that.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-dumping and textile provisions are charged issues for
Vice President Al Gore, who hopes to keep the support of organized
labor in his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment in China's telecommunications sector had
become a sore point inside China, where some saw it as an issue of
national security. The Americans fought for ownership rights but
finally agreed that foreign firms could take 50 percent ownership
of companies in this booming sector, beginning two years after
China enters the trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   Important provisions will open Chinese retail banking to foreign
firms over several years, and also improve market access for
insurance companies, and legal and accounting firms. In the infant
financial securities field here, foreign companies are held to
minority stakes in such activities as underwriting stock issues.
</P>
<P>
   For China _ which is still unraveling the legacy of Mao Zedong's
cloistered, command economy _ entry into the world trade body
symbolizes acceptance into the ``club'' of the world's major
economic players.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists here compare WTO entry to Deng Xiaoping's
landmark opening of the economy to market forces and foreign
influence in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opening of China to the outside world began with Mao
Zedong's meeting with Richard Nixon in 1972,'' said Hu Angang, a
leading economist here at the Chinese Academy of Sciences. ``The
second major stage was marked by Deng Xiaoping's visit to the
United States in 1979.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Joining WTO will represent a whole new stage in China's
opening to the world,'' Hu said. ``It will signify a shift from
partial to comprehensive opening and reform,'' he said, ``and a
shift from an opening based on domestic rules to an opening based
on internationally defined rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
