u s BC-BKC-GUARDS-BOS &LR;      11-15 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GUARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENTED POINT GUARDS SHOW THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Khalid El-Amin knew things had changed when he took a brief
vacation with his family to the Bahamas this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Even there, hundreds of miles and several months removed from
the highlight of his career, El-Amin, the point guard for the
national champion Connecticut Huskies, was the center of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangers would come and talk about the game, about the
season,'' El-Amin said, adding that feedback was preferable to the
derision and taunts he received during last season. ``That was OK.
That kind of attention is fine. Now I want to show people that we
can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn may be able to do that, or at least make the Final Four,
because El-Amin is back and now is The Man in Jim Calhoun's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, point guards are taking lead roles in many of the top
programs around the country, and history shows if you want to
compete for a championship, you'd better have a quality point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the NCAA champs of the recent past. El-Amin last season,
Kentucky with Wayne Turner in 1998, Mike Bibby for Arizona in 1997,
Tyus Edney at UCLA in 1995. When Duke won back-to-back titles in
1991 and '92, Bobby Hurley was the catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there have been other stars, ranging from Duke's Christian
Laettner and Grant Hill to UConn's Richard Hamilton last season,
but the linchpin for success most often has been found in the
backcourt, primarily at the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, the guards are the guys, more often than
not, to help you win games when it comes down to the end,'' said
Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien, who saw his team go from last in the
Big Ten to the Final Four after point guard Scoonie Penn became
eligible following his tranfer from Boston College. ``You may have
a play called and are as organized as you can be, but most of the
time it comes down to who is going to be able to create and have
hands on the ball at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches such as O'Brien like to control the flow and tempo of
the game. ``Coaches try to have their fingerprints on everything,''
he said with a laugh. ``But a lot of situations at the end, you
can't dictate what's going to happen. Having a real good point
guard gives you a sense of confidence that at the very least the
right decision will be made, the right thing attempted.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien does not dismiss the advantage of having good big men.
``But you can have the best guy in the world, at the end of the
game, it's really hard to get the ball to him, unless you have
someone who can do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten, like most conferences, is loaded with quality point
guards. And those teams that don't have one, are making getting one
a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to talent, experience is a key ingredient at the
point. When you can find a senior point guard such as Penn or
Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves, you have an even bigger edge.
</P>
<P>
   Because William Avery opted for the NBA after two seasons at
Duke, coach Mike Krzyzewski is at the disadvantage of working in a
freshman, highly touted Jason Williams. Williams already has
acknowledged the difference between high school and college.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find out all those moves you used in high school don't
work here,'' said Williams. ``They don't work at all. It made me
realize I have to stop doing all those fancy moves and keep it
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say a freshman can't do the job. Arizona has Jason
Gardner moving into the role as a team leader, and Florida is
turning to highly recruited Brett Nelson, who has been called the
best player out of West Virginia since Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young guys are much more aware now than they were five
years ago of how critical strength is in their adjustment to
college,'' said Arizona coach Lute Olson, who hopes to have Gardner
make a smooth transition from last year's star, Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner hopes to make the adjustment quickly. ``We have a great
team,'' he said, ``and I think the guys will help me out in
practice and let me know what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, you need more than a point guard to win consistently.
``It's just like baseball,'' said O'Brien. ``If you're strong up
the middle, you've got a chance to be pretty good. Point guard,
center. You fill those two spots and you can plug in the gaps and
get by.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at the mid-major level, point guards are essential. And
often they are asked to do more than at bigger programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any good team is going to have good guard play in general,''
said Boston University coach Dennis Wolff, who must try to rebound
from last season's 9-18 disappointment with a mixture of veterans
and newcomers led by sophomore point guard Dereck Franklin. ``At
our level you end up compromising a little; you need the point
guard to score a little more than a point guard might have to at
other places. But the main thing is that the point guard must have
a connection with the coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   At UConn, El-Amin has that connection with Calhoun, who has
given his point guard more leeway than almost any player he has
coached. ``Khalid is just a special, special person,'' said
Calhoun. ``He just has an ability to make everyone around him a
better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you look you see point guards who are stars or are
ready to reach that level. From Cleaves, who is the consensus pick
as player of the year, to Penn, El-Amin, and Pepe Sanchez, a
four-year player for John Chaney at Temple. Then there's the group
of freshmen who are stepping from high school into key roles in
college.
</P>
<P>
   The point seems to be well taken. If you want to win, you need
someone to lead the way, and who better to lead than the point
guard?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of always been that way,'' said O'Brien. ``But it
just seems to me that's there more quality at that position than
ever before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
