<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-SHOOTERS-BOS &LR;      11-15 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SHOOTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKSMEN ARE A SHOT IN THE DARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, there was a perennial Eastern Basketball
League All-Star guard named Swish McKinney, so nicknamed because,
well, c'mon, duh. The man made exceedingly sweet music when he shot
the basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, many people maintain that a more likely nickname for
the average basketball player coming out of college would be Clang.
</P>
<P>
   The overall team shooting percentage for the 310 Division 1 NCAA
basketball teams last year was .436, which happens to be the lowest
figure in 34 years. Figures can be exquisite prevaricators, as we
all know, but the unmistakable fact is that shooting figures have
been drifting downward for the past 15 years, or ever since teams
established the high mark of .481 in 1983-84.
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches are alarmed; some are not. Some coaches are
resigned to a changing cultural world; some are determined to turn
things around. But the one thing everyone can agree on is that the
pure act of shooting the basketball ought to be the lifeblood of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting is at its all-time worst,'' maintains George
Washington coach Tom Penders, who claims that his early '70s Tufts
squads, featuring the likes of Leroy Charles, Eddie Tapscott, and
Dennis Mink, could shoot better than anything that's out there
today. ``Skills and fundamentals are eroding, even as we speak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not getting any better,'' agrees Duke coach Mike
Krzyzewski. ``A lot of it has to do with the fact that to be a good
pure shooter requires time, and most kids today don't put the
overall time in at the gym that people did in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that shooting has gone down,'' says Princeton's Bill
Carmody. ``Our own shooting has gone downhill; I can tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always struggling to find kids who can shoot,'' says
Boston University's Dennis Wolff. ``And good shooting can cure a
lot of ills.''
</P>
<P>
   But optimists do exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting a little better,'' says Syracuse coach Jim
Boeheim, himself a solid shooter three decades ago. ``I see kids
working on shooting a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cremins of Georgia Tech and Roy Williams of Kansas go much
further. ``It may not be what it was overall in years past,'' says
Cremins, ``but there are still great shooters out there. We just
signed a kid named Marvin Lewis, who is one of the best shooters in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got shooters on my team who are as good as anything I saw
10 years ago here or 20 years ago when I was at North Carolina,''
declares Williams. ``We've got as good a shooting team as we've
ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people who agree that shooting isn't what it used to be are
reluctant to excoriate the shooters themselves. They prefer to laud
the modern defenses and, therefore, the defenders. ``I think a lot
of it has to do with the defense,'' says Massachusetts coach
Bruiser Flint. ``Everybody plays up so tight to defend the 3. We
want opponents to be shooting with a hand in their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense is much better today,'' echoes Boston College's Al
Skinner. ``You can no longer be a stand-still jump shooter and
expect to get shots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is finally getting its due,'' submits Arkansas coach
Nolan Richardson. ``Before, you'd go to clinics and all you'd hear
was offense. Now people want to hear about how to stop someone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're guarded now,'' says Utah's Rick Majerus. ``Everyone
videotapes everything. Preparation is better. If you're just a
shooter, you're up against people who are much more athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   But are they stopping guys who can really shoot it in the first
place? Are there any more kids around like Richardson's own Al
Dillard, who once drilled a surreal 12 3-pointers in a single game?
``Now he could flat-out stick it,'' rhapsodizes Richardson.
``That's all he did. He'd be out there two hours after practice,
still shooting. He was dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach K had a serious shooter of his own these last four years
in Trajan Langdon. ``It didn't happen by accident,'' Krzyzewski
explains. ``He really worked at it. On days off, he'd be in the
gym, shooting. Shooting is an art, and good art takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Most kids today are not interested in devoting that sort of time
to becoming a great shooter. Shooting has lost its cache. Rather
than turning themselves on by the sight and sound of sinking shot
after shot after shot from the outside (or dreaming of acquiring a
nickname like ``Swish''), they want to take it to the hoop and
throw one down.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kid might make three or four in a row during practice,''
points out Flint. ``He goes back to the locker room. And what does
he hear? `Hey man, so-and-so dunked on you!' ''
</P>
<P>
   An entire generation has grown up equating dunking and
dipsy-doodle moves with basketball. Shooting is an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dunks,'' sighs Flint, ``get you on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   A young player today considers it a rite of passage to have Dick
Vitale screaming ``OHHH, WHAM-BAM, WHAT A SLAM! OH, BAYBEEE!'' in
his honor. Sticking the J won't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time you ever see a jump shot on the highlights,''
says Coach K, ``is if it's a last-second game-winning shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just the dunks. ``What do kids replicate?''
inquires Utah's Rick Majerus. ``It's (Latrell) Sprewell's spin
move, or (Allen) Iverson's crossover move, never a jump shot. I
haven't had a kid come to me in years with what I'd call shot
preparation or shot readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Penders can relate to that. ``You talk to a kid about something
like stepping into a shot or holding your release, and they look at
you as if they're speaking a foreign language,'' he says.
``Shooting is nowhere near what it once was. Why is a guy like Dale
Ellis still around after all these years? Because he can shoot. You
look at Classic TV and see something like the 1972 All-Star Game.
You go, `Jack Marin just missed a jump shot?' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are 3-point shooters, yes. What's missing from the game
today are the scoring machines from the 10- to 20-foot range. You
hear it over and over. The ``intermediate'' game is on the
endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no intermediate game,'' laments Michigan State coach
Tom Izzo. ``Where are the kids who can take one or two dribbles,
pull up, and shoot? That's what separates the colleges from the
pros now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids do not practice in that area as much as they used to,''
says Skinner. ``If they do penetrate, they either take it to the
hoop or kick it out for the 3.''
</P>
<P>
   The classic theory of man-to-man offense was to set screens,
then have someone use them to get open for a jumper. That's almost
extinct now. ``The art of coming off a screen is lost,'' says
Richardson. Of course, there would have to be some screens in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only ones who still run those types of offenses,'' points
out Williams, ``are Bob Knight and his disciples.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmody listens to all this and sometimes wonders if he's
participating in the same sport. ``The intermediate game?'' he
inquires. ``Was it ever there? You have to be good to do that. It's
a lot easier to drive and it's a lot easier to make the long shot
than do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmody has thought a lot about shooting. Without it, Princeton
can't win. Forget about the celebrated back door stuff. Princeton
is only good when Princeton can make open shots. By the way,
Carmody isn't buying the defense argument. ``I don't care what type
of offense you run,'' he says, ``when it's all said and done, 65
percent of the time you're going to get an open shot. You've got to
have guys who can make those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad Brian Hammel, Eddie Murphy, and Dana Skinner aren't
around today. They all flourished in the '70s, the Golden Age of
Division 2 basketball in New England. These guys were shooters. Al
Shields coached Hammel and coached against the other two, who
composed an astonishing Merrimack backcourt. ``There is absolutely
no doubt in my mind,'' says Shields, the long-time Bentley coach
and athletic director, ``that those two were the best shooters on
one team I ever saw in New England _ in any division.'' Take this
to the bank: No team in today's Top 25 has shooters to compare.
</P>
<P>
   What all the above-mentioned heavy hitters are doing is trying
to remake their new, improved athletes into Hammels, Murphys, and
Skinners. From Coach K, who has got an entire separate practice
facility where his players can practice shooting during their free
time, to Flint, who has added an additional 20 minutes of shooting
practice each day, the search is on for someone who can simply put
the ball in the basket in a non-dunk manner.
</P>
<P>
   Cremins wonders if any of it helps. ``I'm not so sure great
shooters aren't born,'' he theorizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a great shooter out there,'' says Penders,
``everybody tries to recruit him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one scholarship left,'' explains Izzo, ``and it's
reserved for a shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Born or manufactured, pure shooters are precious. Every coach
wants to find his own Swish McKinney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
