<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY JUMPERS KEEP TALENT POOL SHALLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billy Packer has long criticized the NBA for allowing
underclassmen to declare themselves eligible for the draft. The CBS
analyst doesn't have a problem with the kids earning big money. He
does have a problem, however, with the draining of talent and other
impacts the departures have had on the college game.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Packer argues, coaches are forced to change their
recruiting and team development from a four-year plan to a two-year
plan. No telling when a high-scoring freshman or sophomore will
bolt for the NBA, leaving his team without experienced players to
compete in the NCAA tourney.
</P>
<P>
   College basketball fans will be hearing Packer's opinions a lot
this winter, as CBS will televise 40 games, mostly on Saturdays,
including the NCAA tournament. Also chronicling this year's Road to
the Final Four will be ESPN and ESPN2, which with a crew of
announcers headed by Dick Vitale will cover 273 men's games and 56
women's games. Other outlets will be Fox Sports New England and New
England Sports Network.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of underclassmen ``has changed the history of the
college game,'' Packer said. ``You will no longer have players of
that magnitude sticking around for their senior years. You'll never
see that again.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Packer has a new target: the Continental Basketball
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Packer predicts that in the next five years the CBA, under the
ownership of Isiah Thomas, will attract many All-American high
school players, leaving the college game without young talent. The
loss of younger players won't mean the death of college basketball,
though. The game will be just as competitive, but not as dominated
by potential pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those fans who can accept the way the game will be,
college basketball will still be a lot of fun,'' Packer said. ``But
the game will undergo another dramatic shift in five years. No
longer will the college game have the 100 top high school
prospects. I have great respect for Isiah, and he will be able to
offer a 17- or 18-year-old kid the chance to make $75,000 a year to
play basketball and have a shot at the NBA without going to a
single class.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell if Packer is right. Thomas is still busy
reorganizing the CBA, and of more pressing concern to college
commentators is the impact the NCAA tournament has had on coaching
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge, but unfortunate in a sense, because a team's and
coach's success is completely defined by what happens in March,''
said CNN/SI's Seth Davis. ``A team could have a great year but lose
in the second round or the Sweet Sixteen and then be perceived as
not having a good year. The tournament is a bit hyperbolized.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside of the college game's focus on the NCAA tournament is
the advent of what are called ``good losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years ago, a team worried about its national
ranking and tournament seeding loaded up its early-season schedule
with weak opponents to build up its record. But the days of playing
teams that former St. John's coach Lou Carnesecca described as the
``Little Sisters of the Poor'' are over.
</P>
<P>
   Because the NCAA tournament selection committee considers
strength of schedule as an important factor, coaches don't have to
be afraid of losing to competitive teams. ``It allows them to get
better through losing,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lousiville's Denny Crum was probably the first coach to use
early-season games to improve weaknesses, an unusual plan
considering Crum was a disciple of UCLA coach John Wooden, who
rarely scheduled tough opponents early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibility of a coach has changed dramatically in the
last 15 years so much so that a head coach doesn't relate to a
Wooden these days,'' Packer said. ``Any coach of a major program
has to use the early games to test his team and shore up their
weaknesses. The coach has to get his players ready to not only
execute during tournament time but also display mental toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside of tournament play is the pressure on coaches to
win. Packer said he has never seen so much angst among coaches.
``They are really afraid if they don't win the big one, they will
be considered a loser,'' Packer said.
</P>
<P>
   Packer believes Richmond coach Dick Tarrant has the right idea.
Richmond has never won a national championship but has been able to
score major upsets in tournament play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarrant knew that he didn't have enough talent to win a
championship,'' Packer said. ``He knew his team was not capable of
winning three games in the tournament. He might win two games and,
as a result, he used to say, `My Final Four is making it to the
Sweet Sixteen.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a coach out there today that really has that
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
