<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOM-UCONN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 UCONN WELCOMES THE GANTLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   University of Connecticut coach Geno Auriemma is having a hectic
week, and the season hasn't even begun.
</P>
<P>
   It began when his team rolled over the Australian Institute
team, 96-64, in last Sunday's exhibition game. On Wednesday, he
fielded questions from Husky fans in an on-line chat. On Thursday,
he and his team were the guests of honor at a reception at a local
TV station held after practice. And, all week he was waiting to get
letters of intent from five high school players to whom he has
offered scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's grueling at times, but it's part of the grind that
comes from being the No. 1 team in the country in the AP preseason
poll.
</P>
<P>
   And while the spotlight puts added pressure on the team,
Auriemma seems to be relishing the spotlight. Especially after last
season, which ended with a thud when the team didn't get beyond the
Sweet 16 in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to this season,'' he said via e-mail.
``It's a tremendous honor for us to be ranked No. 1. We're just
going to enjoy it and keep it in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   The perspective, he acknowledged, will be quickly challenged
when the team embarks on its season next Sunday against Iowa. Over
the next five months, the Huskies will face second-ranked Tennessee
twice and Rutgers (No. 4) twice. Add to that UCLA (No. 5),
Louisiana Tech (6th), Notre Dame (8th), Penn. St. (10th), Illinois
(12th), and Boston College (19th), and the Huskies will have plenty
of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, said Auriemma, who is not known for ever giving his
players an easy route to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our schedule, we'll have the chance to prove if we're No.
1 or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma's top player is also one of the country's top players.
Junior Svetlana Abrosimova, a 6-foot-2-inch forward from St.
Petersburg, Russia, averaged 16.6 points per game, 6.6 rebounds,
and 3.7. assists.
</P>
<P>
   She was named preseason All-America for the second consecutive
year and also the Big East's preseason player of the year. Last
season, she was voted Big East player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma said the accolades are definitely deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever coached anybody who can do as many
things as she can on a basketball court,'' he said. ``She is an
important player for us because she is going to touch the ball the
most.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn, which went 29-5 in the regular season last year and
shared the Big East title _ its eighth _ with Rutgers, and won the
Big East Championship, returns most of its lineup, and returns them
in playing form.
</P>
<P>
   Shea Ralph, who sat out the year before with an anterior
cruciate ligament tear, was back last year, although she missed
four games with a knee injury. The 6-foot shooting guard came back
to be the team leader as she averaged 16.8 points and pulled down
an average of 3.8 rebounds. (She scored a career-high 36 against
BC.)
</P>
<P>
   Another player plagued by injury was Sue Bird, who was sidelined
after only eight games with an ACL, but is back to take over the
point guard spot.
</P>
<P>
   Kiersten Walters, who had filled in for Bird, was felled with a
knee injury at the end of last season and is still a question mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors are going to have another look at the knee,''
Auriemma said. ``We're going to try as much as we can to get her
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Also suffering on the sidelines was 6-foot-2 forward Swin Cash,
who averaged 9.5 points but missed 12 games with a stress fracture.
</P>
<P>
   The freshman ``fab five'' have moved up a grade, but are still
known by that moniker, according to Auriemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting more and more confident in their own games and
in each other as a group,'' he said, acknowedgling that sometimes
they still act like the new kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still kind of a young team at times,'' said Auriemma.
``They still have some growing up to do, and they will throughout
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is Tamika Williams, last year's Big East
rookie of the year who led UConn in rebounds (6.8) and was No. 3 in
the nation and the Big East in field-goal percentage (.658) as she
averaged 13.5 points per game. Rounding out the stellar recruiting
class was 6-foot-2 forward Asiha Jones (9.8 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   This year, there is only one freshman _ Kennitra Johnson, from
New Albany, Ind. The 5-7 guard who averaged 21 points, 5 steals,
and 4 rebounds her senior year was named a Parade first team
All-America and Gatorade Indiana player of the year last year.
Johnson also was named Big East preseason rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The other new face is 6-6 center Christine Rigby, who was seen
on the sidelines but not on the court last year. She sat out the
season after transferring from Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   The only two seniors in UConn's lineup are 6-foot-1 forward
Stacy Hansmeyer, and 6-5 center Paige Sauer.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma, who is entering his 15th season as head coach, has
been with UConn to the NCAA tournament 11 times, to the Final Four
three times, and took his team to the national title in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   While he's not going to make any guarantees, Auriemma will come
as close as he can to a making a prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good group,'' said Auriemma. ``It's as good a group
as I've had here in a long time. I really feel confident about
these players.''
</P>
<P>
   For the coach of a No. 1 ranked team, he should.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
