A0231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      11-15 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CLEARER SAILING FOR VIRGINIA TECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you thought the Bowl Championship Series rankings were
hopeless, things cleared up. That's the beauty of November games.
Sure, there's no playoff system, but consider the significance of
Saturday's games.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee lost to Arkansas. So long, Vols.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State lost to Alabama. See you, Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State lost to Michigan. The Lions' roar was completely
silenced.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State lost to Nebraska. The Wildcats again were the
Mildcats.
</P>
<P>
   What is apparent is Virginia Tech's position of strength.
Barring another abnormality in the computer rankings, Virginia Tech
looks like a lock to make the BCS championship Sugar Bowl game in
New Orleans Jan. 4 _ if the Hokies get past 2-7 Temple next week
and 7-2 Boston College the day after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The other slot looks like it will go to the winner of the
Florida State-Florida game next week, although if Florida wins it
must still beat Alabama in a rematch in the SEC title game in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The most shocking loss was Tennessee's. Just when the Vols
seemed poised to make a serious run at defending their national
championship, they got beaten by Arkansas, 28-24. That was the same
score as last year, when the Razorbacks fumbled away the lead in
the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Race still on
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Heisman Trophy race may not be quite over. Although Ron
Dayne broke Ricky Williams's NCAA career rushing record with 216
yards in Wisconsin's 41-3 win over Iowa, other contenders remain.
Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton threw five touchdown passes
in Tech's 45-42 win over Clemson. ``It's not over yet,'' said
Hamilton, who argues that with two games remaining, against Wake
Forest and Georgia, he has a chance to convince some voters. He may
be right. Dayne's done for the regular season and Heisman voters'
memories tend to be short . . . With Wisconsin's victory and Penn
State's loss to Michigan, the Badgers are making back-to-back Rose
Bowl visits for the first time in their history . . . What's going
on at Florida? Coach Steve Spurrier's Fun and Gun offense has
become Run and Gun. The Gators' passing game has been nonexistent.
In Saturday's 20-3 win over South Carolina, the Gators had only 161
yards in the air. ``We're not as mighty as some people think we
are,'' said Spurrier. ``But we keep winning.'' . . . What a year
for South Carolina coach Lou Holtz. The Gamecocks have lost 20
games in a row, the most in Division 1-A, and are 0-10 this season.
Holtz's wife, Beth, is battling cancer and on Friday his mother,
Ann Marie, died . . . Miami freshman running back Jarrett Payton
wore No. 34 in the Hurricanes' loss to Virginia Tech. It was, of
course, the number his father, Walter, wore with the Chicago Bears.
Payton died two weeks ago and his son wanted to do something to
honor his father. ``It was something I never thought I'd do,'' said
Payton, who wore No. 32 when he arrived at Miami. ``But it felt
like the timing was right.'' . . . What a wild two weeks for Duke.
Last week, the Blue Devils were blown away by Clemson, 58-7.
Saturday they rolled to a 48-35 win over Wake Forest . . . It's a
good thing Ohio State coach John Cooper signed his contract
extension earlier in the year. Folks in Columbus are not real happy
with Cooper after the Buckeyes' 46-20 loss to Illinois. With a 6-5
record, Ohio State needs to beat Michigan next week to even qualify
for a bowl. Illinois, on the other hand, has its six wins and is
bowl eligible, with road triumphs over Ohio State and Michigan to
boot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Red-letter day
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was some good news for Rutgers. By beating
Syracuse in overtime, 24-21, the Scarlet Knights avoided a winless
season, and beat the Orangemen for the first time in 12 years. It
was also revenge for the Knights, who were four-touchdown
underdogs. In the last three years, Syracuse had outscored them,
152-17 . . . If Pittsburgh can beat West Virginia next week and
Miami can beat either Syracuse or Temple in the next two weeks, the
Big East could have five of its eight teams bowl eligible, a
delightful set of circumstances. The league must start to work on
finding a spot for Syracuse if the Panthers become bowl eligible .
. . Boston College's win over West Virginia guarantees the Eagles a
bowl slot. Their best bet is Nashville and the Music City Bowl
against a Southeastern Conference team, but a win over Notre Dame
Saturday probably would send the Eagles to the Insight.com Bowl in
Tucson. If one makes the assumption that Virginia Tech was expected
to be as good as it is, can there be any other choice for Big East
Coach of The Year than BC's Tom O'Brien? Had the Eagles not blown
that lead against Miami, they would be very much in the hunt for a
BCS bowl slot, a remarkable turnaround after a pair of 4-7 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spoiling for a fight
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's loss to Penn casts the Crimson into the role of Ivy
League spoilers. And whose season better to spoil than Yale's. The
Bulldogs need a win over the Crimson to clinch at least a tie for
the Ivy title. With back-to-back losses, coach Tim Murphy's Crimson
now need a win at Yale to guarantee a winning season . . . If the
season were to end today, here's how the BCS bowls probably would
look: Sugar Bowl _ Florida State vs. Virginia Tech; Orange Bowl _
Florida vs. Michigan; Fiesta Bowl _ Nebraska vs. Tennessee; Rose
Bowl _ Wisconsin vs. Stanford . . . Wisconsin locked up a Rose Bowl
berth with its win over Iowa, but the Pac-10, as usual, is muddled.
A Stanford win over California Saturday would clinch the berth for
the Cardinal. A Stanford loss to Cal and a Washington win over
Washington State would send the Huskies to the Rose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
