<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0224 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-HIGH-TECH-VETS-LIFEBE     11-15 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TECH-VETS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHERISHED PETS RECEIVE PRICEY HIGH-TECH TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photo of a vet with an ultra-sound and a photo of
Sterling (cat) with his owner) 
 By CHRIS BRENNAN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sterling is a medical success story, once near death but now
thriving, thanks to the donated kidney that saved his life.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling, by the way, is a cat. A cat who has had an organ
transplant, a surgery once reserved only for humans. As the 1900s
come to a close, it's not unusual for our four-legged friends to
benefit from some of the same medical advances humans have access
to.
</P>
<P>
   Only fair, animal activists might argue, since much of the
research used to develop the techniques is conducted on animals.
</P>
<P>
   But extending the new technology to veterinary care comes at a
price tag not everyone can or is willing to pay. In the extremes _
Sterling's case, for example _ the cost of saving a pet can equal
that of a new car or a week in Europe for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling's tab, because his condition was so advanced, ended up
somewhere between $12,000 and $15,000. But the expense was worth it
to owner Diana Markovich, even though the cat was a stray she had
rescued as a kitten.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a blessing and a miracle,'' said the Lakeland, Fla.,
woman. ''He's like a million dollar kitty.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, the only option for an animal in Sterling's
condition would have been euthanasia. But a booming economy has
given rise to the demand for more options in pet care and for
advances in treatment and diagnostic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I started in 1970, a lot of the stuff we did was by
hand,'' said Tom Houghton, a veterinarian at Cleveland Heights
Animal Hospital, where Sterling receives care. ''If we really
wanted to get sophisticated, we used an X-ray.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the medical setting Sterling had the good fortune
to encounter was a high-tech environment of highly trained
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   When the cat's kidneys began to fail, he was taken to the
University of Florida's Veterinary Medical Teaching Hospital in
Gainesville. He was so weak that the veterinarians were unable to
operate, and twice they recommended ending the cat's life.
Markovich would not give permission.
</P>
<P>
   As a last resort, Sterling received a kidney from an
18-month-old cat named Charlie, who had been used in experiments to
study feline leukemia. (Charlie was later adopted by a student).
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a pretty big ordeal we went through,'' said Markovich.
''He was on life support in severely critical condition for three
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she said, the cat is stronger than ever. Like humans who
receive transplanted organs, he must take drugs to keep his body
from rejecting the kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Hi-tech developments extend beyond the veterinary teaching
hospitals and are making a difference in treatment options at the
local clinics.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cleveland Heights Animal Hospital, a new $27,000 laser
enables veterinarians to remove tumors in areas that once made for
difficult surgery _ under a tongue, near a tonsil, above an eye.
</P>
<P>
   For a 1-year-old black Labrador retriever named Sheriff, the
laser meant quicker healing and less pain following a procedure
veterinarians often perform _ neutering.
</P>
<P>
   The laser beam, invisible to the eye except for the small puff
of smoke it creates, slices through skin quickly and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely a tool of the future for surgery,'' said Dr.
Houghton.
</P>
<P>
   Other advances in use at the hospital include a $20,000
ultrasound machine that enables veterinarians to examine internal
organs without the need for invasive surgery and a $7,000 hand-held
blood testing machine that can help with diagnosis of diabetes and
other problems.
</P>
<P>
   And coming soon to the clinic: Electromyograms that show the
electrical activity in muscle contractions. The test, known as an
EMG, can help a veterinarian diagnose vision or hearing problems
and evaluate strength in limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is also making it much easier to bring specialists
into the diagnosis and treatment process, regardless of their
physical location. The Internet makes it possible for X-rays and
medical charts to be reviewed by the right specialist, no matter
where he is.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't possibly be experts about everything,'' Houghton said
of the local veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is enhancing the life of pets in other ways, as
well. A proliferation of sites catering to animal needs reflects
the growing demand for all kinds of pet products and services.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Heights Animal Hospital's Web site
(www.pethospital.com) offers a link to suppliers of 14,000 items
that can be purchased online. Pet owners can also e-mail questions
about their pets for the veterinarians to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I answered several people's questions this morning in much
less time than it would take for me to call them,'' Houghton said.
</P>
<P>
   The answers, themselves, speak to the new age of veterinary
medicine. A misbehaving dog may be prescribed the pet version of
Prozac to control his mood. A continuous barker may require a
lasering procedure on the vocal chords, known as ''de-barking.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as human health care has given rise to alternative
treatments _ many of which embrace ancient techniques _ so, too,
has veterinary medicine. Dr. John Haromy, a Lake Wales, Fla.,
veterinarian, uses acupuncture and homeopathic remedies on some of
the animals he treats.
</P>
<P>
   It's not very futuristic, he concedes, but it is an alternative
to the high-priced animal care some pet owners are encountering.
</P>
<P>
   A hip replacement surgery for a dog can cost more than $1,000,
said Haromy. He treats hip trouble using acupuncture needles to
push gold pellets under the skin of the animal, a procedure that
costs less than $100.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a manner of speaking, I'm in the past, like 5,000 years
ago,'' he says of the ancient healing arts.
</P>
<P>
   But the future will see more alternative medicine for pets,
Haromy says.
</P>
<P>
   The International Veterinarian Acupuncture Society once
attracted just Haromy and one other doctor to an alternative
medicine class. Now the society limits their enrollment each year
to 100 vets.
</P>
<P>
   When animals begin to have surgeries that cost thousands of
dollars, can health insurance be far behind? The numbers are still
small, but some pet owners want to cushion the blow of a major
health problem.
</P>
<P>
   National Casualty Co. in Anaheim, Calif., reports the sale of
more than 850,000 pet health insurance policies since 1980.
Premiums range from $92 to $227 a year for cats and dogs, depending
on the pet's age and the amount of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   And Houghton expects to see more pet insurance policies in the
years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is a coming thing,'' he said. ''This equipment
isn't any less expensive for animal use than for human use.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Chris Brennan writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
