<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0230 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-COPY-THANKSGIVING-CLO     11-15 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPY-THANKSGIVING-CLOSENESS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODEL EVERYDAY DINNERS ON THANKSGIVING CLOSENESS
</HEADLINE>
  By LAURA TAXEL 
 c.1999 magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanksgiving is the quintessential family meal. Traditionally
it's a day set aside for the generations and relations to gather
around the table and eat together.
</P>
<P>
   We plan our lives so we can be there. We expect a leisurely meal
of good food and conversation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a special time, but one that many believe should not be
reserved for holidays. Shared mealtimes give parents the
opportunity to oversee what their children are eating, to model
healthy eating habits and at the same time offer emotional
nourishment too.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eating is related to the emotional life of the family, or
should be,'' said Dr. Derrick Lonsdale of the Preventive Medicine
Group, an Ohio practice that specializes in nutritional related
problems. ''Shared meals are an essential part of raising healthy
children and a time for the social intercourse of family life,
providing an opportunity to reinforce relationships. I'm convinced
that the fact that most families don't do this on a daily basis is
impacting the well-being of children.''
</P>
<P>
   I've always thought family meals should be a daily event. So,
with the occasional exception, my husband, our sons, and I sit down
and eat together every night, working around a complex schedule of
jobs, classes, meetings, and activities.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy. I'm no June Cleaver. I don't live to make the
guys pot roast and lasagna, day after day, week after week. I work,
I chauffeur, and I know what it's like out there on the front lines
of the fast track. If I don't have time to cook, we may turn to
take-out, but we will still gather round the table to socialize as
we chow down.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever eats alone or in front of the TV; it's simply not
allowed. Some nights we have to make a special effort to wait for
each other. But we do these things because, although it is
difficult to maintain the ritual of the family meal, I'm convinced
that we benefit in many ways. Pediatricians and nutritional experts
agree.
</P>
<P>
   Children's nutritional health depends both on what they eat and
how they eat it. Obviously, their growing bodies need
good-for-you-food. But they also need to have that food in the
company of others.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritionist Laurel Mellin, former director of the Center for
Child and Adolescent Obesity at the University of California-San
Francisco School of Medicine, believes that lacking scheduled,
structured mealtimes with the family, children may turn to the
refrigerator for their nurturing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eating together is a sign of family order and closeness,'' she
says. ''When families don't eat together, it often means that
they're not as organized or connected as children need them to
be.'' Writing in The Journal of Pediatric Health Care, Mellin cited
emotional overeating triggered by boredom, loneliness, sadness, and
anger; meal irregularity, and high-fat, fast food diets as factors
related to the dramatic rise in childhood obesity.
</P>
<P>
   With both parents working, there's often no one home to prepare
a meal and anchor the family to a regular meal time. Children who
are home alone after school may snack so much that they have no
appetite for dinner. Older children are on the run from one
activity to another. Tired parents may find it easier if everyone
watches TV during the meal. Fast food has come to describe not only
what most people eat, but also how they eat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's rare that families sit down to eat dinner
together nowadays,'' said Joanne Lane, a registered dietitian in
private practice. ''It's a lost tradition that's creating bad
eating habits. Many convenience foods are high in fat, salt, and
sugar. Because they're quick, they encourage eating fast and in
isolation. Family members routinely skip meals, or grab food on the
run.
</P>
<P>
   ''And of course when family members aren't eating together every
day, it can't help but lead to diminished communication between
parents and children.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a working parent,'' she adds. ''The hardest thing was
figuring out what to make so I pre-planned menus, prepared food
days in advance, cooked two dinners at once and froze one, and used
the crock pot often. I'd balance takeout food like pizza with green
salads, fresh fruits and vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   Eating meals as a family is no guarantee that children won't
suffer from obesity or experience other diet-related problems. A
dinner hour for the family does not necessarily mean that everyone
will stay in touch. But the practice goes a long way towards
helping.
</P>
<P>
   Because the dinner table may be the first and only time in the
day that the whole family gets together, it's important that it be
an occasion for socializing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't let it be a time to discipline, argue, issue ultimatums,
nag about table manners, or for kids to tattle on one another,''
says Dr. Robert Mendelson, an Oregon pediatrician with more than 30
years experience and one-time spokesperson for The American Academy
of Pediatrics. ''Make it a what-did-you-do-today time. Give
everyone a chance to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Eating dinner together, once so typical an event it didn't even
warrant discussion, is increasingly uncommon. The changes in how
families function are here to stay. We can't go back to the world
of the '50s, so we need some new, creative solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell busy parents that if it can't be every day, than at
least they should pick some days of the week when the family will
convene around the dinner table,'' said Ellen Caspaer, Ph.D., a
psychologist in family practice. ''If it can't be dinner, try
breakfasts. But make the commitment because shared meals in a
family are about much more than just eating.''
</P>
<P>
   So when your family sits down to Thanksgiving dinner this year,
think about how you can make that celebration a part of your
children's life, each and every day.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ideas to help you:
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)Make dinner a scheduled family gathering. Parents must
plan their time around this event. If they make it a priority in
their lives, children will too. If it can't be every night, then
designate certain days as family meal days and protect that time
from any distractions.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)Make the meal hassle-free, an occasion for relaxed,
positive contact between family members. Offer healthy, balanced
choices, but don't focus on who eats how much of what. If you set a
good example, the kids will eventually follow your lead.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If younger children need to eat earlier, or older
children need to eat separately because of unavoidable commitments
that conflict with the dinner hour, their mealtimes need to be a
social time too. They shouldn't eat alone. Someone should sit down
with each family member when they eat.
</P>
<P>
   Younger children can still come to the table and join in the
family time too, having a before bedtime snack or something to
drink.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Laura Taxel is an Ohio-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
