<HEADER>
A0232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-BOS &LR;      11-15 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL CLINTON'S LONG GOODBYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now begins the end.
</P>
<P>
   With the next presidential election now officially less than a
year away, Bill Clinton is embarking on a long farewell. He may
have goals for his last year in office, but he has little real hope
of achieving them. He may send proposals to Capitol Hill, but he
has little real hope of signing them into law. He may have dreams
of putting final touches on his legacy, but he has little real hope
of giving new shape to how historians will view his eight years in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eighth year is not a productive time,'' says George C.
Edwards, director of the Center for Presidential Studies at Texas A
&AMP; M University. ``Everybody does not put politics aside and come
together for the common good in the eighth year. Believing in that
is like believing in the tooth fairy.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, Bill Clinton _ dreamer, policy wonk, master of the
10-part program _ can set a foundation for a future in which he
will not play a part. But this final year of his presidency will
pose special challenges and present special impediments to success.
</P>
<P>
   Eight full years in the White House is a rare phenomenon: Since
mid-century, only three men, Eisenhower (1953-1961), Reagan
(1981-1989), and Clinton will have done it.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his two GOP predecessors, Clinton doesn't enter his last
year mired in fatigue. Clinton is a young man at 53, compared with
Eisenhower, 69, and Reagan, 76, when they began their eighth years.
Clinton still has fresh ideas, fresh approaches, fresh interests.
Many of his priorities, especially expanded health insurance,
remain unrealized.
</P>
<P>
   But he faces formidable obstacles. Many presidents are eased off
the stage, often by their vice presidents. ``I'm in the seventh
year of my vice presidency,'' Al Gore told a New Hampshire teenager
the other day, ``and I'm ready to graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Eisenhower watched Richard Nixon win the 1960 Republican
nomination and then lose the White House to US Senator John F.
Kennedy of Massachusetts; Reagan watched his vice president, George
Bush, become the 1988 GOP nominee and defeat Governor Michael S.
Dukakis of Massachusetts for the presidency. Clinton is being
overshadowed not only by Al Gore, who is in an unexpectedly heated
race with Bill Bradley, the former US senator from New Jersey, for
the Democratic nomination, but he is also being challenged in the
spotlight by his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who almost certainly
will be campaigning for the Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know as I've ever seen anyone who looks as
marginalized as Clinton does,'' says Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a
political scientist at the Claremont Graduate University in
California. ``He's a political hologram: He's there but he's not
really there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Clinton's prospects are weakened by a daunting
combination of factors that shape his time and circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   He presides over a government divided by party, with the
Democrats holding the White House and the Republicans controlling
Capitol Hill. He's the first impeached president in 131 years,
eroding his moral authority and making the ``bully pulpit'' harder
to ascend in his final months than it otherwise might be. And the
absence of the kind of tensions spawned by the Cold War make it
unlikely that the nation will rally around the president as it did
so many times when the United States and the old Soviet Union stood
face to face with their antagonisms _ and their nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When historians look back at the Clinton presidency, they will
see that he tried to do a host of things and argued on their behalf
_ but in most cases was unsuccessful,'' says Robert Schmuhl,
chairman of the American studies department at the University of
Notre Dame. ``His last year would probably be little different.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that these low expectations might provide him with
an opening for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still lots of balls in the air over there _ deals
Congress may want to cut to have a record to run on, peace treaties
in the Middle East and Ireland,'' said Mike McCurry, who served as
press secretary in the Clinton White House. ``A few little things
and he'll look great by comparison with the other eight-year
presidents. One of the reasons may be that Clinton never had a
second term. He's been dragging a ball and chain around for most of
the second term, so in some ways he's just beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the precedents are exceedingly discouraging. Eisenhower
entered his last year in the wake of a recession and a disastrous
set of midterm congressional elections in which the Democratic
margins grew to 63-35 in the Senate and 280-153 in the House. The
Congressional Quarterly annual assessment for 1960 called the year
a time of ``indifferent accomplishment and spirited partisanship.''
So little was at stake that the Congress adjourned nine minutes
before midnight Sept. 1. ``Weighed against the slim fruits of the
1960 session were acres of unharvested production, blighted by the
rust of political schism,'' concluded the editors of the quarterly,
which is respected for being rigorously nonpartisan.
</P>
<P>
   The only important achievement of the year was the 1960 civil
rights bill, which passed after two months of petty debate and is
remembered chiefly for the role played by Lyndon B. Johnson, which
adumbrated Johnson's later role as a presidential advocate for
aggressive civil rights legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower tried but failed to win authority to raise interest
rates on government bonds. He tried but failed to win a boost in
the federal gas tax. Major school-aid programs stalled on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan did little better in 1988, when the nation was still
reeling from a stock market crash and when the Republicans, who had
controlled the Senate for the first six years of his presidency,
were still settling uneasily into their role as the minority in the
chamber. The administration, moreover, was still suffering from
repercussions from the Iran-Contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In Reagan's last year, Washington took a tentative step on
overhauling welfare, approved an expansion of Medicare, and
ratified an arms accord with the Soviet Union, but overall left few
footprints in the capital or the country.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there wasn't a lot to do _ then or now.
</P>
<P>
   The president flew to Norway early this month in the hope of
pushing Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, toward new steps in the peace process. His
special envoy, former Democratic senator George Mitchell of Maine,
still toils to establish peace in Ireland. Major economic questions
remain unresolved in Washington, including how to use the budget
surplus, whether taxes need to be lower (or flatter), how to shore
up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In his last year, the president must decide whether to reappoint
Alan Greenspan chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank. Greenspan's
term expires in June and he can stay until the Senate confirms his
successor. Already Democrats are pressing Clinton to appoint Robert
Rubin, but Republicans believe that the former treasury secretary
is ``too political'' and are prepared to argue that the question
should wait until the next president is elected.
</P>
<P>
   The country still hasn't decided how it's going to improve the
schools, preserve the environment, care for the sick, and cure its
manifold social ills. That's probably what elections are for. It's
probably not what ends-of-presidencies are for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Administrations run out of steam and they run out of political
capital by the time they get to the eighth year,'' says Edwards,
the Texas A &AMP; M political scientist. ``It's wonderful to talk about
a `legacy year,' but there is very little chance that there will be
much legacy from the last year. The conditions for a legacy item,
like major reform of Social Security, just are not there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is chief of the Globe's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
