<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0234 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-SALVADOR-ANNIVERSARY-     11-15 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-ANNIVERSARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALVADOR ON A BRUTAL ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY MEIER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``The Spirit breathes in many ways, and supreme among
them is the disposition to give one's life for others, whether by
tireless daily commitment or by the sacrifice of a violent
death.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   --Reverend IGNACIO ELLACURIA, S.J. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rector, University of Central America &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celina Ramos would be 25. A raven-haired university student
perhaps. Or a social worker. Or a mother.
</P>
<P>
   But Celina Ramos was shot to death, along with her mother, Elba,
10 years ago (Nov. 15), on the same night and on the same campus
where six Jesuit priests were murdered by right-wing Salvadoran
terrorists, at the University of Central America in San Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary of the brutal killing, which ultimately shocked
the US Congress into shutting off military aid to El Salvador's
ruling oligarchy, will be remembered with a candlelight procession
and all-night vigil near the university garden where the six
elderly priests were shot, each in the head. After the killings,
Celina Ramos's stepfather, Obdulio, who still works as a gardener
for the university, planted commemorative rose bushes in the
blood-drenched soil. His wife had been a housekeeper on the campus.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary will also be marked by forums on liberation
theology, with a special look at the writings of the six priests,
rector Ignacio Ellacuria, Ignacio Martin-Baro, Juan Ramon Moreno,
Amando Lopez, Segundo Montes, and Joaquin Lopez y Lopez. All were
university faculty. An anthology of their writings has been
published, titled ``Companions of Jesus: the Jesuit Martyrs of El
Salvador.''
</P>
<P>
   What was gained by their martyrdom?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is cloudy, although the peace agreement three years
later, in 1992, between warring factions in the 12-year civil war
continues to hold. Presidential elections in March _ which retained
the right-wing Arena Party in power, but gave the now fragmented
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN, one-third of
the National Assembly seats and many local mayoralties _ were
relatively free of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Memories of bloodshed are still strong on both sides. And the
Arena Party is cognizant that economic growth cannot occur in a
nation paralyzed by militias.
</P>
<P>
   El Salvador's current business boom (the country has one of the
highest credit ratings in the Western Hemisphere) is largely fueled
by the $1.2 billion sent back home each year by the 1 million
Salvadorans who have emigrated to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But along with money orders, the United States has introduced
Salvadorans to another huge export: crime.
</P>
<P>
   From the slums of East Los Angeles, Salvadoran youths have
mastered gang violence. They are called ``Las Maras.'' Transported
back to Central America, the gangs' crime has grown amid the
plethora of weapons shipped there by the United States during the
civil war. Maras graffiti _ the letters MS _ is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the annual murder rate is 150 per 100,000 people,
among the highest in Latin America, and 12 times the rate of New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled with one of the densest populations in Latin America
(708 people per square mile), El Salvador is struggling to set firm
feet on a slope of prosperity. There are always coffee exports, and
there is some industrialization, although many factory jobs have
been lost to Mexico under the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there any pattern of self-sustaining growth?'' says Robert
White, former US ambassador to El Salvador who was recalled in 1981
by President Reagan for decrying US support for the right-wing
militia. White, now president of the Center for International
Policy in Washington, does not have an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Class divisions are still sharp. True to its history, the rich
grow richer and the poor remain poor. Some 60 percent of
Salvadorans have little access to health care. More than 30 percent
do not have safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, the class truce continues. There is none of
the violence of a decade ago, no attacks on San Salvador's wealthy
quarter of San Miguel.
</P>
<P>
   White says, ``The rich in El Salvador could tolerate violence in
the barrios of the poor, but not seeing their Mercedes used for
target practice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mary Meier is a Globe staff member.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
