<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-CENTURY-ARTS-BOS &LR;      11-15 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-ARTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTURY IN THE ARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has the 20th century been worth it? Has the pursuit of harsh
reality instead of Platonic beauty, an acceptance of disorder
instead of a search for order, been an invigorating trip or a road
to nowhere? Whatever you make of it, the 20th century is our time,
and unless you have sealed yourself off in a monastery (in which
case you're not reading this), it is the time we have to come to
grips with as millennium madness says goodbye to Modernism and
hello to who-knows-whatism.
</P>
<P>
   The history of art in the 20th century can be broadly described
as the movement from Romanticism to Modernism, from thinking of
humanity as being on a quest for spiritual meaning to a species at
the nihilistic mercy of a Godot (or God) who is either silent or
nonexistent. What unites the modernists of the late 19th and the
20th centuries _ from Fyodor Dostoevsky, Karl Marx, and Charles
Baudelaire to city-builder Robert Moses _ is, says author Marshall
Berman, that ``They are moved at once by a will to change _ to
transform both themselves and their world _ and by a terror of
disorientation and disintegration, of life falling apart. They all
know the thrill and the dread of a world in which `All that is
solid melts into air' '' (the title of Berman's 1982 book).
</P>
<P>
   That ``disorientation'' is felt by the audience as well, trying
to keep up with the growing non-narrative abstraction of artists in
the shadow of Freud, Darwin, and Nietzsche; the streams of
consciousness of James Joyce and Virginia Woolf; the Surrealism of
Eugene Ionesco and Samuel Beckett; the serialism of Arnold
Schoenberg and Alban Berg; the Abstract Expressionism of Jackson
Pollock and Willem de Kooning.
</P>
<P>
   These were, of course, only the most radical exponents of their
idioms, and one could assemble a less severe list of Iris Murdoch,
August Wilson, Igor Stravinsky, and Pablo Picasso. Nevertheless,
all these artists embody that same sense of disorientation with the
world. And as musicians and painters, in particular, retreated into
the academies, the door was left open for a more democratic,
electronic, accessible, and _ let's be honest _ more exciting
avenue of expression: popular art.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plugging in
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marshall McLuhan predicted the growing supremacy of the
plugged-in artists of music and movies. As the 1960s took form,
with help from McLuhan, poetry on the page seemed sleepy next to
Bob Dylan's folk-rock lyricism; theater was decidedly low-tech and
nonvisceral next to a Martin Scorsese film; and even television
series like England's ``The Prisoner'' seemed to capture the times
as well as any novel.
</P>
<P>
   Whether their latter-day counterparts _ Prince or Ani DiFranco,
David Lynch or ``The X-Files'' _ have advanced the form or not,
there is a growing sense of the limitations of pop culture today.
As playwright Craig Lucas said in a letter to the New York Times
Arts section Sunday, ``As for our supposed competition, can
somebody tell me what is the burning passion behind David E.
Kelley's `vision,' or the deeper messages in Quentin Tarantino's
pop-culture slaughterfests? So many movies praised for their
supposed engagement with serious issues strike at least one viewer
as being thoroughly predigested and uninspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lucas's letter goes beyond theatrical or generational whining
and strikes a chord about the shallowness of popular art, there is
an even greater lament about the legacy of abstract art. Getting
beyond the polemics about the recent Brooklyn Museum of Art's
recent exhibit, ``Sensation'' stands as a touchstone for the debate
about abstract and conceptual art. Glenn D. Lowry, director of New
York's Museum of Modern Art, came to the defense of contemporary
art with an op-ed piece in the Times: ``Art is a language, a means
of communicating deeply held ideas and beliefs, and to dismiss that
which we do not like because we do not understand it makes no more
sense than ignoring German or Chinese literature because we cannot
read German or Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that what appreciating art has come to? That it is as
difficult to comprehend as a foreign language? True, it takes some
time and intelligence to deal with the language of Shakespeare or
Melville; it helps to know the origins of Impressionism to
appreciate van Gogh or Monet; and everyone knows that Stravinsky's
``The Rite of Spring'' caused a riot in 1913. Still, one does not
need to learn a new language, verbal or tonal, to sense what the
artist is trying to convey. It may be that pop culture has devalued
art to the point where we want everything instantly accessible; but
perhaps the elite cult of inacessibility has been even more
damaging _ and may have even paved the way for the supremacy of pop
culture.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction to the 10-CD retrospective of composer John
Adams, the president of Nonesuch, Robert Hurwitz, recounts a story
that's emblematic of the way many have come to think about art in
the 20th century. He had been hired in the 1970s to write the liner
notes for ultracerebral composer Elliott Carter's Pulitzer
Prize-winning String Quartet No. 3. He took great pride in making
all the intellectual and structural connections, and greatly
admired the music, but has not had any interest in listening to the
piece since:
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge gap between what the music was supposed to be
saying, and my gut response to it. Should you have to convince
yourself to like a piece of music _ music to be admired but not
listened to? (In 1999 it is possible to talk about this, but in
1974, if you were a composer, musician, or critic . . . you
couldn't even think this way.'')
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Nonesuch points a way to how we, at the end of the
century, can look at art in all its incarnations. For want of a
better term, call it Eclecticism. Not a nonjudgmental,
Madonna-is-equal-to-Faulkner Eclecticism, but perhaps less of a
polarized art world: one where one can render unto Carter what is
Carter's and unto Adams what is Adams's, along with a healthy
respect for jazz, world music, Mozart, Broadway . . .
</P>
<P>
   Is it not possible to lose oneself in the surrealism of Salvador
Dali one week and the rejection of that world in Winslow Homer the
next? Don't a nonrepresentational novel like Salman Rushdie's ``The
Ground Beneath Her Feet'' and Michael Frayn's more realistic
``Headlong'' both tell us important things about the unbearable
lightness of being? And one probably could make as much of a case
for a David E. Kelley vision as a Craig Lucas world view.
</P>
<P>
   The Modernism of the 20th century is exhausted; what will take
its place in the 21st is impossible to see. This doesn't seem like
the time for manifestos _ this transition calls for synthesis more
than a new thesis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
