<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-DISGRACE-BOS &LR;      11-15 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DISGRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LITERARY NICETIES ON THE RAW EDGE OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DISGRACE 
By J.M. Coetzee. Viking. 
220 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Great subjects do not necessarily lend themselves to great
literature. When history eclipses the imagination, the writer must
overcome the force of the external rather than embrace it;
otherwise, what you have is a tract instead of a novel. Tolstoy got
around this problem _ one where the world is too much with us _ by
expanding the parameters of realism; Faulkner, by concentrating on
his postage stamp of invention called Yoknapatawpha. Writers of
modern South Africa have been faced with a peculiar kind of
challenge. The state-sanctioned iniquities of apartheid made
literature itself seem suspect, a weapon in the language of the
oppressor that, even in the right hands, couldn't promise to build
a house, feed a family, or save an innocent life.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the finest novelists of contemporary South Africa, J.
M. Coetzee has both confronted and evaded this tyrannical reality
of his homeland. In ``Waiting for the Barbarians'' and ``The Life
and Times of Michael K,'' he dealt allegorically with the moral
consequences of racial inhumanity; in ``Foe'' and ``The Master of
Petersburg,'' he turned to the creative process _ to the world of
Daniel Defoe and Dostoyevsky _ for his inspiration. Now faced with
the chaos and overt suffering of a post-apartheid state, he has
written a small but bracing novel in ``Disgrace'' _ the story of a
self-centered, middle-aged white man, a former professor whose
downfall is of his own making as well as his only possible
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   In October ``Disgrace'' was awarded England's coveted Booker
Prize (the second for Coetzee, after ``The Life and Times of
Michael K''), and it's tempting to speculate why: The novel is
tightly, forcefully realized, and about as morally and politically
germane as it's possible to be these days. But it isn't Coetzee's
best work. Next to the piercing beauty of the prose in ``Waiting
for the Barbarians,'' this is a slightly drab story; next to the
wrenching suffering of ``Michael K,'' the troubles of ``Disgrace''
feel desultory and sometimes bitter. What the novel does accomplish
is the evocation of a suffocating milieu where any action is
compromised _ where history's mark, when cruel enough, cannot be
undone by the mere gestures of love or mercy.
</P>
<P>
   David Lurie is a familiar anti-hero of contemporary Western
fiction; his solipsism even feels slightly American, though he
lives in Cape Town. Twice-divorced, 52, the father of a grown
daughter, he's languishing at Cape Technical University teaching
communications skills; his old department, classics and modern
languages, has been disbanded in the post-apartheid order. Though
his heart belongs to Wordsworth and Byron, he now spends his time
teaching indifferent students about punctuation and inductive
reasoning. For his own untended fires, he visits women from
Discreet Escorts, until a chance encounter with a female student 30
years his junior charts the beginning of his undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Exposed almost immediately for their brief and disastrous
affair, Lurie is hardly repentant; he provokes the academic
committee investigating his impropriety, and eventually resigns his
position in the midst of scandal. Clutching what's left of his
pension and his reputation, he sets out for the Eastern Cape, where
his daughter, Lucy, works a small farm. A gentle, plain woman in
her mid-20s, Lucy has chosen a vastly different life from that of
her father; she loves women, keeps a boarding kennel of dogs;
shares the upkeep of the land with an older, black African named
Petrus. It's symptomatic of Lurie's lack of power over his daughter
that she refers to him only as ``David''; though she treats him
with respect and affection, it's also clear from the moment of his
arrival that Lurie's intellectual tools _ his scholarly pursuits,
his interminable irony _ are worse than useless here.
</P>
<P>
   Then one morning, everything changes. Three young black men
approach from nowhere, asking to use the phone. Cautious but afraid
of her own suspicion, Lucy kennels the Dobermans who might have
protected her. And the next few hours are what Lurie thinks of as
``not human evil, just a vast circulatory system, to whose workings
pity and terror are irrelevant.'' Lurie and his daughter get away
with their lives, but not much else; undone by violation, they have
also lost the link between them of mutual understanding. He carries
the burden of having failed to protect his daughter; she, the
larger and less personal weight of history _ of being a white woman
alone in a land of vengeful reclamation. The refuge afforded each
of them in the past abandons them now: Her dogs are gone, her good
will is but a naive intangible, and Lurie's beloved Byron _
scalawag that he was _ goes the way of the dustheap of history.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuilding that takes place from this pivotal moment in
``Disgrace'' is the agonizing point of the story, one with more
endurance than hope. Petrus, who had disappeared the day of the
attack, understands what has happened to Lurie and Lucy; neither
friend nor enemy, he is instead an impenetrable witness to history.
Like the magistrate of ``Waiting for the Barbarians'' and the title
character of ``Michael K,'' Lurie must undergo a transformation of
self _ the old bundle of defenses and demands he once thought of as
character has managed to rob him of humility and blind him to
decency. Crawling rather than ascending from the ashes, he emerges
clinging to his love for Lucy _ larger than any of his life's
possessions, and certainly the only one that will last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disgrace'' is a relentlessly bleak novel; some of it is also
predictable. Faced with the heartless byproducts of a brutal piece
of history, Coetzee has delivered this story with a familiar
mastery, but the voice here is austere _ as Lurie conceives of it,
English itself has become ``an unfit medium'': ``Like a dinosaur
expiring and settling in the mud, the language has stiffened.''
However apt or powerful this observation, its application does not
lift ``Disgrace'' into the splendid stylistic realm that ``Waiting
for the Barbarians'' inhabited. David Lurie, teacher of the
Romantics, turns away from the old pathways of aesthetic retreat;
as if imposing similar penance on himself, Coetzee has relinquished
beauty for something with the cold weight of steel.
</P>
<P>
   At moments, the moral conceit of ``Disgrace'' seems reminiscent
of the world invoked by William Trevor _ a lightless place where
grace is never promised but not forgotten, either. And yet there's
something too simplistically harsh about this novel, as though the
form itself must suffer under the scourge of South Africa.
Dis-graced and dismantled, Lurie will find his only chance at
redemption through the sacrificial act of honoring the dead. His
work is to grasp that the fires of passion, so seductive and
elusive to him in theory, still go on burning, burning, in the
light of day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
