<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-WOM-BIGEAST-BOS &LR;      11-15 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOM-BIGEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG EAST BECOMING BIG NATIONALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the time Louisiana Tech carried off the first trophy until
just over a dozen years later, the roll call of NCAA women's
basketball champions was a virtual geographical cornucopia of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   From Southern Cal to Old Dominion to Texas to Stanford to Texas
Tech to North Carolina, every region in the country was represented
_ except one.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Northeast gained its first national title when the
University of Connecticut broke through in 1995, the Huskies'
success still was considered a curiosity. After all, order was
restored the next three years when Tennessee of the mighty
Southeastern Conference won three straight times before ceding last
season to Purdue of the equally intimidating Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   Even after UConn became one of the sport's glamour teams, the
Big East often was viewed as a one-team league. Show us more, the
world of women's basketball seemed to be saying.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, when Notre Dame went to the Final Four, and 1998,
when four Big East teams went to the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And until last season, when the conference kept its Four on the
Floor until the third round. And this year, when the same Gang of
Four are consensus Top 20 preseason selections.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East is no longer the Big Easy.
</P>
<P>
   It has been far from an overnight process, the establishment of
the Big East as a force in collegiate women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the conference didn't get the respect it deserved,''
said Doris Burke, who starred at Providence in the mid 1980s.
``There was parity among the teams, beating each other up among the
round-robin format of the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but that didn't translate into NCAA success. For the
tourney's first eight years, the Big East was known as a ``one and
done'' league. Only three times had a conference team won so much
as a first-round game.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1991, an aggressive former Virginia assistant took UConn
to its first Final Four. The women's basketball establishment was
shocked when Geno Auriemma and the Huskies nearly upset Virginia in
the national semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``UConn caught lightning in a bottle in 1991,'' said longtime
Philadelphia Inquirer sportswriter Mel Greenberg and the originator
of the national women's poll in 1976. ``They got some breaks, such
as when a higher-seeded team lost, but they certainly enhanced the
coverage of the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something of a surprise when UConn made it,'' said Doug
Herakovich, publisher of the North Carolina-based Women's
Basketball Journal, which has circulation nationwide. ``They raised
the bar in the Big East. Geno Auriemma came on the scene and proved
you can build a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' first taste of national publicity coincided with
Rebecca Lobo's senior year of high school in nearby Southwick,
Mass. UConn's success made it easy for the highly touted scholastic
star not to stray too far from home to attend college. Thus,
Auriemma had his first blue-chip recruit and four years later, Lobo
and UConn were national champions.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Huskies' popularity captivated the national
media, UConn still had little company at the top of its conference.
Essentially, UConn was the Big East, and from its bully pulpit
swatted away any league competition, losing only twice from
1995-98. The Huskies' success didn't help the Big East as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``UConn carried the baton, so to speak, for the entire Big
East,'' said Burke.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, the Huskies had company. A year after losing in
overtime in the national semifinals to eventual champion Tennessee,
UConn watched the Final Four on television. Notre Dame, in only its
second year in the conference, became the latest Big East team to
fall to the Lady Vols.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two significant coaching hires before the Irish's
success laid the foundation for last season. Rutgers, also a
conference add-on in 1995, hired C. Vivian Stringer (12 years at
Big Ten Iowa, a Final Four in 1993). Two seasons earlier, a
somnambulant Boston College gave Cathy Inglese (back-to-back
perfect records at Vermont) a chance to awaken its program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having grown up in New England and coached here, I knew it was
a premier conference,'' said Inglese. ``I wanted to get it to
become a bigger and better conference, more than just one team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Generally, coaching has been the most important factor in the
rise of the Big East. If the conference is to continue to be
regarded as a major national factor, the coaches will have to
continue to play a significant role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes back to UConn, a team like that can only help
you,'' said Bill Gibbons, whose Holy Cross team often scheduled Big
East teams in nonconference games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notre Dame has their own ambitions,'' said Greenberg.
``Rutgers hired Vivian, who just was not going to take not being
competitive. Cathy was a great hire for BC.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is their quality of coaches,'' said Herakovich. ``The
competition is getting tougher and tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with game strategy and preparation, coaches must also
recruit and serve another, equally important though often
overlooked function, according to Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches in the SEC are constantly touting their conference
to the media,'' said Burke, who is a commentator for college games
and also for the WNBA's New York Liberty. ``The rest of the coaches
at other conferences like the Big East should do that as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinions as to the Big East's rank among the nation's
conferences vary anywhere from Herakovich's No. 3 (1 and 2 being
the SEC and Big 12) to top four to top half-dozen.
</P>
<P>
   The Ratings Percentage Index, used by the NCAA to select and
seed teams for the NCAA tournament, is perhaps the most accurate
measure. Last season, the Collegiate Basketball News's RPI rated
the Big East seventh; in its four years ranking teams, the
publication placed the Big East anywhere from sixth to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while it appears the upper third of the league is in
terrific shape, work remains to make the Big East one of the
nation's elite conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big East used to have a terrible bottom portion,'' said
Greenberg. ``Not anymore. They play other conferences and hold
their own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of how the schools (under the top echelon)
will turn it around,'' said Burke. ``It'll be a key for schools
like Villanova and Providence to break through. How they'll do it,
I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All this stuff builds on itself,'' said Herakovich. ``BC can
sell that you can play UConn and be on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC and its yearly quota of six or seven NCAA tournament
teams might laugh at such a seemingly picayune recruiting tool, but
the Big East doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all four teams winning a game, that attracts attention
and notoriety,'' said Inglese. ``Name recognition is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Greenberg said: ``People know who the Big East is now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
