<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOM-BOSCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC EAGLES GETTING RESPECT EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Cathy Inglese can't get far without passing by the
photo, which at 28x40 inches not including frame looms almost as
large on the wall outside her Boston College office as it does in
the history of the women's basketball program. In it, the
scoreboard (5:52 left in the first half, Eagles 31, Huskies 19);
the Conte Forum crowd (8,606, a full house); the ball arcing toward
guard Alissa Murphy (32 points, a career high). All combining to
hint at the triumphs and turning points to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just demonstrates what last season was all about,'' said
Inglese last week. ``It was a special year.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, BC's magical 78-66 upset of the second-ranked
University of Connecticut was the cornerstone for the most
successful season in school history, in which the Eagles would
crack the Top 25 for the first time, finish 22-8 and make their
first trip to the NCAA tournament. But it was the second-round
tournament game against powerhouse Tennessee, in which BC came out
aggressively and led for most of the first half before losing,
89-62, that laid the foundation for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed us we belonged,'' said returning guard Cal Bouchard.
</P>
<P>
   No one is arguing. As the 1999-2000 season begins Monday night
(Nov. 15) with a tough matchup against Maine (24-7 last season),
Boston College is ranked as high as 15th in one preseason poll, and
comes in at 19 _ ahead of recent Final Four teams Duke, Purdue, and
North Carolina State _ in the benchmark Associated Press poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never started the season that way,'' said Inglese.
``Last year, I thought we were a good team entering the season, but
people didn't know about us.'' After three successive campaigns of
18-10, 17-11, and 22-8, said the coach, ``This year would be a good
year to show people we're here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles certainly won't be sneaking up on anybody. Although
they've lost center Whitney Steele, who was second high-scorer a
year ago with 11.3 points a game, BC returns four starters and
senior captain Bouchard, the feisty guard who was sidelined for the
second half of last season when she went down Jan. 10 with a torn
anterior cruciate ligament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want so badly to make it (back to the NCAAs) for her,'' said
Inglese, still pained that the soul of her squad missed out on much
of last season's excitement. ``She was one of the kids who turned
the program around.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bouchard in the backcourt will be senior Murphy, who led
the team last year with 16 points a game to earn the Big East Most
Improved Player Award, and sophomore Brianne Stepherson of
Masconomet High School, who by year's end had taken charge at point
guard. Sophomore Nicole Conway, who started 17 games last year,
will be first off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any benefit to Bouchard's injury, it was the
emergence of Murphy, who quickly stepped into a leadership role
while averaging 37.7 minutes a game. Now, said Inglese, ``We've got
two great go-to players. Whoever takes the last shot, I feel
totally confident.''
</P>
<P>
   In the frontcourt, Jamie Cournoyer is the leading candidate to
replace Steele at center. The 6-foot, 3-inch junior out of North
Attleboro High School started six of the final seven games of the
season, and scored a career-high 16 points in the tournament loss
to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jamie is ready to do some damage,'' said Inglese.
</P>
<P>
   Joining her will be hard-nosed sophomore Becky Gottstein, who
led the team in rebounding with 7.1 a game and was third in scoring
with 10.4 points as a freshman surprise who earned Big East rookie
of the week honors six times. Freshman Maureen Magarity, a 6-2
forward out of Wappingers Falls, N.Y., who is good in the low post,
should see some action.
</P>
<P>
   Also making its debut in the lineup: pressure. Last year, 20
wins was a milestone; the NCAA bid, historic. This year, the bar
has been raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first year we're going to have to deal with
(outside) expectations,'' said Inglese. ``Before, they were just
ours. We've gotten the attention now, you don't want to let anybody
down. But you have to put it in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   In that, she brings experience. When Inglese came to BC in 1993,
it was following back-to-back seasons at the University of Vermont
in which the Catamounts took records of 29-0 and 28-0 into the NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way to handle that is the same way I handled it in
Vermont after the first undefeated season, in that you really try
to keep it focused internally,'' said Inglese. ``You play to reach
your own goals. If you do that, everything externally will take
care of itself. That's going to be important for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Her players seem to be taking in it stride. ``I'm actually not
nervous about it,'' said Bouchard. `Yeah, there are expectations.
But we always had them of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' schedule is neither easy nor ideal. Starting with
the trip to Maine, which beat Stanford to advance to the second
round of the NCAAs last spring and is led by the nation's
fourth-leading scorer (24.2 points) in Jamie Cassidy, BC doesn't
seem to get a break. Its games against Big East rivals UConn (Jan.
26), Notre Dame (Feb. 5), and Rutgers (Feb. 23) are all on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   But while there will be no repeat of the picture-perfect rapture
in Conte Forum that erupted after BC vanquished UConn last season,
the confidence it spawned lives on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be something I tell my grandkids,'' said Murphy last
week, reminiscing about the stunning victory. ``I don't think
anything will be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard corrected her. ``Unless,'' she said, ``we go to the
Final Four.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
