u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-15 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHING OUR HANDS OF THE PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you wash your hands?
</P>
<P>
   How many times did your mother ask you that question when you
were growing up? Maybe she still asks you. My mother asks,
occasionally. Force of habit. At least I think it's force of habit.
Maybe she thinks I still need to be reminded.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers may be wrong about some things, but they're right about
the importance of washing your hands. So get in there and scrub.
That means you, kid. And don't forget to wash the backs of your
hands, because germs are lurking everywhere, poised to do their
worst, and their worst is very bad indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Germs. The word alone used to scare us. We've lost our fear.
We've put our faith in antibiotics. But antibiotics aren't a sure
cure anymore. More and more contagious diseases are fighting back,
changing, adapting, learning to coexist with modern medicines,
rendering them useless.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times last week reported that, according to the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, hospitals are teeming
with potentially lethal infection. Each year 1.8 million people
pick up infections while hospitalized for something else, according
to the Centers, and 20,000 of them die as a result.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times story, studies have shown that medical
personnel aren't washing their hands as thoroughly or as often as
they should. Dirty hands spread infection, sometimes fatal
infection.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine. You check in for, say, a tonsillectomy and you check
out, permanently, because somebody neglected to wash his or her
hands.
</P>
<P>
   So if doctors and nurses, of all people, aren't washing their
hands, who is?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the rest of the population isn't doing a great job of it
either. You might even call us the great unwashed.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1997 hand-washing survey of 7,000 people
conducted for the American Society of Microbiology, 98 percent of
Americans said they always wash their hands after they visit the
bathroom. That's what they said, but researchers stationed in
public bathrooms found that only 68 percent of those observed
washed up afterward. Women were somewhat more likely to wash than
men, 74 percent to 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study asked about hand-washing in other, non-bathroom
situations. Only 48 percent of those interviewed said they washed
after handling an animal. And a mere 33 percent said they washed up
after coughing or sneezing into their hands. (So Donald Trump is
right about at least one thing; he refuses to shake hands because
he believes it spreads disease.) On a more encouraging note, 81
percent of those surveyed said they washed before handling food,
and 78 percent said they did after changing a diaper. That's what
they said, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times story, medical personnel surveyed cited
lack of time as a major reason for failing to wash their hands as
often as they should, i.e dozens, even hundreds of times a day.
Hospital hand-washing is time-consuming. One study found that some
of the busiest doctors, those in an intensive care unit, were the
least likely to wash their hands. Since doctors and nurses are only
going to get busier, one researcher suggests hospital patients take
responsibility for hygiene and ask every health care worker who
approaches: Did you wash your hands?
</P>
<P>
   Most non-medical people need to wash their hands only a few
times a day. It takes seconds. Why do so many people neglect to do
it? Maybe they think it's unnecessary. Or maybe it's a kind of
germ-related narcissism. They can't imagine their germs could harm
anyone. And other people's germs? Mother was right; they can make
you sick. So wash your hands, for her sake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1351EST &QL; 
