u i BC-RUSSIA-COMMUNISTS-BOS     11-15 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-COMMUNISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODDS DWINDLE COMMUNISTS WILL REGAIN DOMINANCE IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIPETSK, Russia _ Generation X glanced up. Generation Red glared
down.
</P>
<P>
   In a run-down movie theater in the dreary southern Russian city
of Lipetsk, the Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, known as the
candidate of the angry, the elderly and the dispossessed, was
trying to connect with the Nintendo crowd: young people playing
video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiya, kids, hey, wait, don't run away, let's take a look at
that,'' Zyuganov began in his sonorous baritone. ``Hmm, those are
pretty good graphics. What's that with the sword, a samurai? Hey,
if you win, do you get a prize?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh? Uh, no,'' said Ivan Bazarov, 18, who will vote for the
first time in December's parliamentary elections, but not for the
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Zyuganov was back in his element, surrounded by red
flags, beaming through a cold drizzle at a crowd of retirees as the
old Soviet national anthem played. These were the people he had won
over long ago, people who miss the certainties of living in the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks before the Dec. 19 vote, the Communists are leading a
pack of 28 parties, with about 20 percent of the vote, according to
most polls. There was a time when such numbers made people all over
the world wonder about a red revanche in Russia. But no longer. In
the view of most observers here, the Communists are out of touch,
and already out of the race for the big prize that will be
contested next summer, the Russian presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, the Communists
have maintained the core of voters that has made them Russia's most
powerful opposition party. But as each subsequent year brings new
hardships and Russia's ranks of angry, impoverished, and
dispossessed increase, the Communists' support has remained about
the same. The appearance of powerful competitors means that their
share of seats in the lower house of parliament, the State Duma,
will probably shrink from the current 140, nearly a third of the
Duma's 450 seats.
</P>
<P>
   This says as much about the way Russia has changed as it does
about the way the Communists have not. No longer can anyone portray
Russia as a battlefield of an entrenched Soviet system versus
liberal, Westernizing reformers, as President Boris N. Yeltsin
successfully did in defeating Zyuganov in 1996 presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a `Communist comeback' has disappeared,'' said
Dmitri Kamyshev, political analyst for the weekly Kommersant Vlast.
</P>
<P>
   The battles being fought now are murky conflicts among feuding
power elites and oligarchs, motivated as much by their narrow
self-interest as by the future of Russia. Fittingly, all party
leaders sound the same: Stop the crime, corruption, and bandit
capitalism that has dominated Yeltsin's Russia; return dignity to
ordinary people after years of crisis and hardship.
</P>
<P>
   So what if Zyuganov has been saying that for years, long before
it became fashionable? After four years as the main party in
parliament, the Communists have become just another party. They
scare no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Communists have become an opposition party that is part of
the system,'' said Sergei Mulin, a political commentator for the
newspaper Segodnya.
</P>
<P>
   When the Communist faction in the State Duma gave preliminary
approval to the government's fiscal 2000 budget two weeks ago, some
opposition figures speculated that the Communists had supported the
Kremlin in exchange for government backing in the parliamentary
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Commmunists denied any deals. But that the theory exists is
confirmation of a larger truth in these elections: Far more than
the Communists, the Kremlin fears the Fatherland/All Russia bloc,
led by Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov, as well as Yevgeny Primakov, a
former prime minister and a leading presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists' platform calls for prosecuting and jailing
well-connected businessmen whom they accuse of plundering the
economy. But so does Fatherland's Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists talk about recovering state assets sold off under
the efforts to build a market economy. Such talk used to strike
fear in the hearts of investors. But lately Yeltsin's government
has been accused of taking control of lucrative companies, and of
running roughshod over shareholders' rights, to help finance the
upcoming election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists appeal to Russia's erstwhile great power status.
But so does Primakov, who, polls say, would easily defeat Zyuganov
in a head-to-head presidential vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists hit a low point late last year when they failed
to denounce or distance themselves from anti-Semitic remarks by two
prominent party members (who eventually left to form their own
movement).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Luzhkov enforced oppressive residence rules for
people with dark skin who live in Moscow, and the Kremlin began
prosecuting its latest brutal campaign in the Caucasus. Anytime
someone reminds Zyuganov that Communists in Russia once killed
millions during the Great Terror of the 1930s, he smiles and says,
``But who's doing the killing now?''
</P>
<P>
   But being no worse than anyone else has not brought Zyuganov
more support. Instead, his party's supporters are Russia's oldest
and least educated, according to a report by the think tank
Carnegie Moscow Center. Far from revolution, they want something
that is getting less likely each year: a return to the life they
knew 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had everything we need, food, clothing, work, education,
medicine,'' said Lipetsk pensioner Tamara Sokova, 62, as she
listened to Zyuganov in Lipetsk. Sokova cannot make ends meet on
her $15 monthly pension, so she started collecting bottles to sell
to recycling firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except now the empty bottles have started to disappear,''
Sokova said. ``Because too many people are collecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Communists chide their leader for not doing more to attract new
voters, for failing to build a larger coalition uniting leftists
and nostalgic nationalists, for not turning his old message of
opposition to the Yeltsin regime into something positive for
Russians to rally around, and for being so wooden that he makes Al
Gore look fiery by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of Yeltsin and his proteges is treason of
Russia's interests,'' Zyuganov intoned at a rally about 1,000
people in Yelets, a decrepit industrial town that lies 250 miles
south of Moscow, where buildings ruined during World War II have
not been restored. ``Over $150 billion has left Russia, and today
the budget is smaller than that of Finland. Where did it all go?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot him! Shoot Yeltsin!'' cried one very small, elderly
woman carrying an anti-Semitic poster. Her cry raised a smattering
of applause from those close enough to hear her tiny voice.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov smiled down at her benignly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are at least 7,000 of you,'' he beamed at the crowd as
his aides snickered at the exaggeration. ``It is good to see you
all here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Olya and Sveta, two 18-year-olds hurrying past the rally,
had no intention of voting for Zyuganov. Nor did they know anyone
who would.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard all about the Communist era,'' said Olya, who is too
young to remember much about it. ``They'd make us have ration cards
and tell us what to think. They'd make it illegal to have fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
