<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S BEST MAKEUP FOR FIXED-INCOME PORTFOLIO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Often in your articles you say that people now retired or
near retirement should be able to safely earn a 6.5 percent yield
from an established fixed-income portfolio. You also mention that
they should keep a portion of their portfolio in stock funds or
individual stocks to protect against inflation. However, I don't
recall seeing where you discussed the makeup of the fixed-income
portfolio, and the percentage of the total portfolio that should be
in stocks. Could you provide specifics and the names of the funds
you would select?
</P>
<P>
   M.C., Arlington, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Part of this _ how I would suggest you build a fixed-income
portfolio _ is pretty easy. But the percentage of your total
savings that should be in stocks is pretty hard to pin down, since
it relates largely to the overall resources and needs of the
individuals in question.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a person needs an $80,000 annual income stream
and has resources of $4 million, he could probably leave all of his
money in stocks, where the long-term returns are likely to be
highest, and where he could expect to get enough money for his
needs from the dividend yields.
</P>
<P>
   But most of us don't live like that. Generally, I consider that
a person is in a pretty comfortable situation if they have a
fixed-income portfolio that supplies their income needs, and in
addition a stock portfolio that represents 50 percent of the value
of the fixed-income portfolio, with the latter designed to protect
them against inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no need to panic if you can't fit your specifics
into that profile. That is a target for a very comfortable
retirement. If a person has enough money to keep a third of his
savings in stocks, the chances are good that he can move through
retirement with little or no erosion of principal.
</P>
<P>
   That's a comfortable situation, but not necessary; what is
necessary is to have enough money to provide you with the funds you
need in retirement, including the raises you will have to give
yourself to keep in step with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, it is quite satisfactory that their principal
decline steadily as they age _ just so long as they don't get into
a situation in which they will outlive their income stream.
</P>
<P>
   So it all comes down to the fact that there is no such thing as
a one-size-fits-all financial plan.
</P>
<P>
   To a much lesser degree, that's also true of building a
fixed-income portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   What I usually suggest to people who are comfortable with the
vagaries of the bond markets is a three-tiered fixed-income
portfolio, with a GNMA or government securities account at the
center and representing about half of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the opposite ends of the spectrum, I suggest equal
investments in a high-yield (or junk bond) fund, balanced either by
a short-term corporate bond fund, CDs, or a money market fund at
the conservative end.
</P>
<P>
   If a person is uncomfortable with the risks of a junk bond fund,
he or she could reorganize the plan with about two-thirds of the
money in intermediate-term government-backed securities such as the
GNMA fund, and the balance in conservative holdings such as I
outline above.
</P>
<P>
   The returns in that case, of course, would dip a bit lower, but
for many people, the additional peace of mind is worth the lower
return.
</P>
<P>
   (And of course, investors should be aware that all of these
investments except the CDs and money market investments entail
risk, and that such holdings must be viewed as long-term
investments, with as much focus on the yield as fluctuations in net
asset value.)
</P>
<P>
   As for specific funds, I tend to favor those of Vanguard, based
on its plain-vanilla, low-cost approach to running its business.
Vanguard Short-Term Corporate Bond fund, Vanguard GNMA, and
Vanguard High-Yield Corporate Bond funds would be my choices. (And
for the record, they are, since I hold positions in the latter two
offer-ings.)
</P>
<P>
   Most fund families offer similar funds, and you are not likely
to hurt yourself if you go elsewhere. But I do suggest that on the
fixed-income side of your portfolio you confine your research to
no-load funds. Good research and talented portfolio managers can
often make a stock fund with a sales charge a wise investment, but
in general the added cost of a sales load is simply too much for a
fixed-income portfolio manager to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I enjoy your column, but I was saddened by your seeming lack
of understanding of charitable giving; you seem to say get and keep
all you can and maybe your heirs will be able to give some away. I
believe that giving is a test of our humanity.
</P>
<P>
   R.B., Santa Clarita, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Gee, I think you may have misread a column a couple of weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   That involved a couple who had a pool of money invested in
stocks, and their plan was to take a percentage of that money each
year and distribute it to charities. This, of course, was an
admirable approach to handling their money.
</P>
<P>
   But from other factors in their financial situation it seemed
that they would be a bit hard-pressed to meet their retirement
goals with any significant margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   So I suggested that they allow this money to accumulate during
their remaining years, and to designate through their wills that
this money eventually go to charity. I didn't say they shouldn't
give at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
