<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-YAMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING ECHOES OF `THE DEATH OF ZIONISM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been more than 17 years, but I can still hear the wiry,
young bearded settler shout, ``This is the death of Zionism,'' as
he struggled in vain against the clutches of four Israeli soldiers
_ one to a limb _ who carried him out of his apartment in the
northern Sinai town of Yamit.
</P>
<P>
   I held his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the young man's wife and daughter screamed and sobbed as
they saw him carried off, resisting the first efforts of women
soldiers assigned to calm them down and get them to focus on
packing their belongings in military-issue cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Yamit, similar scenes played out that Friday morning
as the Israeli army, bringing Israel into compliance with the terms
of its peace treaty with Egypt, removed the last pockets of settler
resistance to the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   For the Jewish army, it was the first such wrenching assignment
and the largest of its kind so far, dwarfing the pre-dawn
evacuation this past Thursday of Havat Maon, an illegal hilltop
outpost in the southern West Bank that religious nationalist
settlers had set up to create political ``facts on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak's order to evict the Havat Maon
settlers removed an obstacle to the latest round of Mideast
peacemaking, this time between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But the brief clash last week between hundreds of Israeli troops
and dozens of protesters at the hastily built hilltop outpost paled
in comparison to the four-day showdown over the idyllic coastal
community of Yamit, when 20,000 troops were involved.
</P>
<P>
   That late-April Friday in 1982, evacuation day, had been
preceded by ultimatums, 11th-hour negotiations, and a steady
emotional buildup as Israelis braced for the spectacle of their
army doing the unthinkable: removing fellow Israelis from homes
they had built in good faith to help realize the Zionist dream of a
secure homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Havat Maon, Yamit was populated primarily by secular
middle-class Israelis trying to find a better quality of life in a
new community. The northern Sinai, unlike the West Bank, was not
part of the holy land. No settler could claim God promised this
land to the Jews. It was just a sliver of territory on the edge of
a giant strategic buffer zone between Israel proper and Egypt, then
the Jewish state's most powerful adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Yamit, its name in Hebrew evokes the sea, literally sprang up
from the sand dunes a few hundred yards from the Mediterranean, a
growing cluster of red-roofed stucco homes divided by pedestrian
walkways and tropical gardens. Residents boasted that they didn't
lock their doors, that the community was a throw-back to simpler
times.
</P>
<P>
   But you won'f find Yamit today on a map. The Israeli army,
operating under the orders of the hawkish then-defense minister,
Ariel Sharon, saw to it.
</P>
<P>
   The army had assembled a select group to handle the delicate
task of evicting Jews, calling in soldiers training to be
commanders and amassing a disproportionate number of senior
officers.
</P>
<P>
   For some soldiers, the evacuation of Yamit, while painful,
symbolized the triumph of democracy and of the peace process. For
others it was a national tragedy. An American Jew on my own
ideological journey (and a trainee in a noncommissioned officers
course), I espoused the former view.
</P>
<P>
   My team's first assignment, the previous day, was to help a
family pack its belongings. The family, a man in his 50s and his
daughter, who said she was a soldier on leave, had lived in Yamit
for years. They were not resisting the order to leave, but they
were emotionally exhausted from confronting the inevitability of
losing their home. The father shuffled around in apparent shock.
From outside came the sounds of a bulldozer knocking down his
neighbor's house.
</P>
<P>
   In one cardboard box we put his collection of imported liquor, a
prized possession for Israelis in those days, and carried it
outside. His daughter, spotting the box, came over. Without a word,
with a contemptuous half-smile on her lips and her eyes wide and
defiant, she bent down, grabbed a bottle, and flung it against a
garden wall. The exploding glass made everyone jump. Her smile
widened and she threw another before she whirled and stalked off.
</P>
<P>
   That evening my team was invited to a surreal farewell cookout
as another family, one of Yamit's first, they said, emptied their
freezer and lobbied the officers to leave their evacuation to the
end. ``Please,'' they pleaded with a colonel, ``just guarantee us
we'll be the last to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   One soldier, seeing the panic in the eyes of the family members
and sensing that their request would not be met, refused the
family's hospitality and scolded his comrades. ``How can you eat
their food? Tomorrow you'll pull them out by force.''
</P>
<P>
   Late that night the army sent its troops onto the roofs of
apartment buildings, seizing the ``high ground'' in anticipation of
the confrontations at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as it was to wrestle a man away from his hysterical
family, other troops had even more arduous tasks.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Shekhunat Ha'Ixim,'' the ``X Neighborhood'' in which rows
of previously evacuated apartments had been marked with large black
painted X's, literally crossed off the army's list, settler
activists with megaphones mounted a counterstrike, taking to the
roofs, where they held out for hours and scuffled with soldiers
before succumbing to the inevitable. Notably, most of these
activists had come to Yamit from settlements in the West Bank in
the days and weeks before the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a group of right-wing university students led by
Tzachi Hanegbi, who years later joined the Likud Party and
eventually served as justice minister under former prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, shouted their defiance of the army from atop a
70-foot-high monument to fallen Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But away from the isolated clusters of holdouts, the demolition
proceeded in earnest. Bulldozers knocked down the one-story villas;
excavation machines, looking like giant birds of prey, brought
their pneumatic hammers down on the reinforced concrete tops of
bomb shelters; and teams led by the army's engineering corps rigged
the larger apartment buildings with sacks of TNT and other
explosive ordnance, linking each neighborhood in a giant white web
of twined explosive fuse.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the order was given for all military personnel to clear
the town, and we retreated the prescribed safe distance. The blast
came promptly at the appointed hour, and a giant mushroom dust
cloud rose over what had been Yamit.
</P>
<P>
   The drama of that day was quickly forgotten by the rest of the
world when Israel invaded Lebanon 6 1/2 weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   But for Israelis an important lesson had been well learned. Many
suspected it was a lesson deliberately taught by the Likud
government of Prime Minister Menachem Begin and Defense Minister
Sharon. And it was a lesson apparently not lost on Ehud Barak: If
it were this difficult to abandon the sands of the northern Sinai,
how could settlers ever be uprooted from the West Bank?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Kaplan is a Globe assistant foreign editor.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
