<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-EISENHOWER-BOS &LR;      11-15 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-EISENHOWER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN CLASSIC IN WAR AND PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
EISENHOWER 
By Geoffrey Perret. Random House. 
685 pp. Illustrated. $35. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We knew him as the irresistible hero of World War II, the
architect of the North Africa offensive and D-Day. As the commander
of NATO when Berlin was a flashpoint in the early days of the Cold
War. As the genial president whose easygoing ways _ the shopworn
aphorisms, the graceful golf stroke _ symbolized America in the
1950s. We knew him, mostly, as Ike.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at century's end, comes a new biography of Dwight D.
Eisenhower, written by Geoffrey Perret, befitting the New Look that
Ike pushed at the Pentagon and the new look that historians,
commentators, and political professionals are taking at the
president who, until recently, was known primarily as the
placeholder between Truman and Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   No more. The new, refurbished Ike is a visionary, a strong and
decisive president in his own right, just as cagey as Truman, just
as charismatic as Kennedy, and maybe more nearly indispensable than
either of them. This Ike is a man for whom it can be said _ unlike
the current incumbent _ that the presidency was the culmination of
a lifetime of experiences, not a formative experience in its own
right.
</P>
<P>
   This new life of Eisenhower, appearing just two decades after
the monumental two-volume biography by Stephen Ambrose, is a
breezier, more compact version, lacking in the details and, on
occasion, the bite that gave the Ambrose books their distinction.
No matter. Perret has examined documents and source material
unavailable to Ambrose and, of course, writes with two decades'
more perspective. Inevitably the experience of the Clinton
presidency, animated by chaos theory, has shaped Perret's (and our
own) view of Eisenhower, who was nothing if not steady and sure,
and who was not much for either chaos or theory.
</P>
<P>
   In myth and memory, Eisenhower was not a complicated man, but
Perret reminds us that he was the son of a mother whose impulse ran
to pacifism, a man whose autobiography oddly begins not in Abilene
but at West Point, and one whose early life, like so many great
generals', was a portrait in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower's frustration came not from drink nor from defeat,
but from dreariness. He ached for the front in World War I and
never saw it, and though he trained hundreds of soldiers and
readied tank battlions for combat overseas, he didn't receive
orders to depart for France until November 1918. That was the month
the war ended. But he was dashing and he was dedicated, and he
learned to wait his turn. It came in command, not in combat.
</P>
<P>
   His great role came not in Washington but in London. Here is
Perret's description of Eisenhower's arrival in England, when he
and the Allies were haunted by tragedy even as they were preparing
for triumph: ``an avatar in khaki, brass buttons and a rainbow
smear of medal ribbons, the manifest form of the assurance of
victory, with all the power of America at his back.''
</P>
<P>
   In England he struggled with Winston Churchill, struggled with
his own doubts as he pressed ahead with the strategic plan for
Allied forces in the battle of North Africa, and struggled with
Charles de Gaulle and French sensibilities, a political problem
that, up to the very night of the invasion, preoccupied Eisenhower
_ and was precursor to graver, more consequential political
challenges he would face two years later in the invasion of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For Eisenhower was a military man with a political job. Indeed,
his political skills were a match for his military skills, and they
were brought to bear with de Gaulle, Churchill, Franklin Delano
Roosevelt, George Marshall, Omar Bradley, and Bernard Montgomery.
(Three months after D-Day, with the Allies deep into Europe, Ike
touched the field marshal's knee and said: ``Steady, Monty. You
can't speak to me like that. I'm your boss.'')
</P>
<P>
   He suppressed (though never conquered) tensions by creating a
chain of command where each American would have a British officer
above him and another one below him; as a consequence, each British
officer had an American above him and an American below. The result
was, as Perret explains, ``to take combined arms to a level that no
one had ever imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   The big challenge, of course, was Overlord, the hugely
complicated, hugely costly, hugely heroic invasion of Europe: more
than 4,000 warships, 3,500 heavy bombers, 1,500 medium bombers,
5,000 fighters, plus the hopes of millions. It remains the greatest
military operation in history, and, revisionism be damned, it
remains the greatest moment of Eisenhower's career.
</P>
<P>
   Through all this Ike developed his own leadership style but,
more important, his own decision style. ``It was when Eisenhower's
mind seemed made up that he was probably still open to new ideas,
and when he sounded undecided, there was a good chance he had
already made a decision,'' Perret writes, explaining that the
peculiar Ike style ``reserved him his freedom of action while he
went about picking other people's brains with the cold-blooded
detachment of a professional burglar.''
</P>
<P>
   As president, too, the open questions were closed, the closed
questions opened. He was a Republican who shored up the New Deal
(his goals included expansion of Social Security and the
establishment of a Department of Health, Education and Welfare). He
was a warrior who abhorred war and looked skeptically on the Cold
War the United States and the Soviet Union were prosecuting. Listen
to Eisenhower: ``This world in arms is not spending money alone. It
is spending the sweat of its laborers, the genius of its
scientists, the hopes of its children. The cost of one modern heavy
bomber is this _ a modern brick school in more than 30 cities.''
</P>
<P>
   His mind was supple enough to argue for reduced levels of
military spending but insufficiently supple to see the difference
between the threats the West faced at Munich in 1938 and at Dien
Bien Phu in 1954 (or in Iran and Guatemala). And yet he left the
nation with a priceless gift, a farewell address quoted,
astonishingly, as often as Washington's, with his warnings about
``the conjunction of an immense military establishment and a large
arms industry'' (his shorthand: ``the military-industrial
complex''), cited for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower was an American original and, in Europe as in the
White House, an American symbol. He was the emblem of a native
patriotism and a native savvy. Like the country, he was naive,
optimistic, pragmatic, shrewd, inventive, slow to anger but
fearsome when roused. With an American face, he was, for two
decades, in war and in peace, in uniform and out, the face of
America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is the Globe's Washington bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
