<HEADER>
A0266 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-LAST-NIGHT-BOS &LR;      11-15 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LAST-NIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON MCKELLAR: PLAYING THE ENDGAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Don McKellar was writing ``Last Night,'' a movie set during
the putative last six hours on earth, he was thinking of calling it
``Whimper'' _ as in, the world ends not with a bang, but with a
whimper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very unpopular title,'' McKellar says, dryly, over a
steak at a recent interview in the Back Bay. ``My distributor was
not very happy with that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   So ``Last Night'' it became. But ``Last Night,'' which opens
Friday, is not exactly an ``Armageddon,'' ``Deep Impact,'' or
``Independence Day'' kind of movie. No bigtime smash-it-up special
effects. No Harrison Ford, Will Smith, or Bruce Willis playing a
Mighty Mouse kind of hero, rushing in to save the day. Frankly, for
an end-of-the-world movie, ``Last Night'' is rather low on
explosions and mayhem. For budget reasons, yes (it cost just under
$2 million to make), but also by design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really thought I would love to do that (even) if I had
the budget,'' says McKellar, who directed and stars in the film.
``The idea was to make a more intimate film by making it not about
what is happening, but about the people.''
</P>
<P>
   McKellar, 36, plays the lead character, Patrick, who is trying
to decide how to spend his Last Night, as is everyone else in the
movie. Patrick's first choice is solitude, but it's not a goal he
will be able to achieve. Some of his friends, acquaintances, and
strangers make choices such as these: Craig (Callum Keith Rennie)
wants to enjoy as many choice permutations of sexual intercourse as
he can, including a go-round with his former French teacher
(Genevieve Bujold); Duncan, a gas-company employee (played by
director David Cronenberg) calls customers assuring them they can
count on uninterrupted service right until the end; Jennifer (Sarah
Polley) wants to party; Patrick's parents and relatives want to
re-create Christmas festivities; Sandra (Sandra Oh) wants
desperately to get across town to spend the evening with her
husband. And, yes, some of the folks in the background, out on the
street, opt for that perennial apocalyptic favorite, looting and
pillaging.
</P>
<P>
   One curious bit about the film is that the reason the world is
ending is never defined. ``It was not the point,'' says McKellar,
``and I thought it would have been a distraction for the audience
to be wondering what was going on _ `Can this happen? What is Bruce
Willis doing?' I did not want the audience thinking about that. And
also, I didn't want the characters to be discussing that on the
last day.''
</P>
<P>
   He also avoided the usual disaster-movie cliche of having, as
McKellar puts it, ``some lame exposition with some news broadcaster
explaining the science.'' What he aimed for when the camera
ventures outside was ``that stark, empty, sort of paranoid look.''
</P>
<P>
   But McKellar's people are not behaving as if they were in an
updated ``Road Warrior.'' ``It is Canada,'' he says, with a laugh.
``Americans always ask: `Where is the violence? Where is the
violence?' ''
</P>
<P>
   McKellar's working premise was that his characters had known
about the end of the world for three or four months and had dealt
with the ``disbelief and denial and the panic. They are at a point
now where they have come to terms with it. I'm not suggesting
that's true of society, but of the people I'm focusing on.'' All of
McKellar's characters, he says, ``eventually deviate from their
plan, and all of them benefit from it, to some degree. It is the
end of the world, and being open to it, to other humans in
difficult situations.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, says McKellar, ``some comic effects and absurd
angles'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   McKellar, who says he was a class clown in school, is himself a
witty, self-deprecating chap, negotiating the baby steps of stardom
with some hesitancy. ``I am fairly privileged to be making
movies,'' he says: He enjoys the travel that comes with the
business, the fancy hotel suites studios put him in. Home life?
``The apartment is a little messy,'' he says. He lives with a
2-year-old black-and-white female cat named Stinky he found at a
bar. He has just broken up with a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to ``Last Night,'' McKellar earned kudos for his work as a
screenwriter for ``The Red Violin'' and ``Thirty Two Short Films
About Glenn Gould.'' Heady stuff. The first film he ever appared in
was a cheapie called ``Road Kill,'' which also featured former
Ramones singer Joey Ramone. Cool stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Night'' takes place on McKellar's native turf, Toronto,
which has frequently been used as Anycity for Hollywood
productions. He says some Canadians watching the film laughed
happily, in suprise, when actual Toronto streets and locations were
noted _ imagine, Toronto playing Toronto!
</P>
<P>
   McKellar, who was born in the city and attended the University
of Toronto, says the natives have gotten over the buzz of having
their city featured in movies. He admits he was probably not the
most popular guy in town when he shot a demolished-streetcar scene
that closed down streets and brought a fire engine to the site
three times in one day.
</P>
<P>
   McKeller _ whose most recent acting credit was playing a creepy
high-tech game-maker in Cronenberg's ``eXistenZ'' _ did not
initially envision himself as the lead actor in ``Last Night.'' He
says he thought he'd play the part of the sex-obsessed Craig _
``He's more like me in real life. But my French producer suggested
the other part was better. I thought it was a way of throwing
myself right in the middle of the film with no one else to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous, pretty scared,'' McKellar says, about
shouldering the writing/directing/acting yoke. ``I was most scared
about the acting thing, because I thought it would be difficult for
the other actors because actors are afraid to comment on their
peers' performances. I think overcoming my fear of megalomania was
part of it. But I made sure I had actors that I trusted both in
their skill and in their person. I did not want to have any big
strange egos, and I had worked with a number of them before.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronenberg, whom McKellar calls ``the godfather of the Canadian
scene,'' was cast as the soft-spoken gas company worker. ``He's
very articulate, very controlled,'' says McKellar, ``and yet he
makes these (weird) movies, and you can see that going on'' within
him.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a character to Canadian films in general, McKellar
says, it would be ``our most successful films have been fairly
unnusual films. They're indie films by definition, they come out of
a more renegade (mindset), closer to regional film-makers like
David Lynch or George Romero. Outsider cinema. On the other hand, I
think there is something of a historical affinity for European
cinema and a closer emotional connection there than a lot of
American indie guys have. I think we are not generally as tempted
by genre pieces. `Last Night' is, theoretically, a genre. I won
this award at a sci-fi festival in Portugal and I thought, `I guess
it's science-fiction, I never really thought about it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McKellar has been living with ``Last Night'' for a couple of
years, and has discovered ``directing is sort of the first thing I
want to do. I have got to get that going because it is such a
long-term process; once I get that going I will relax and be able
to work.'' He says he is writing a script now, but elects not to
discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   A question McKellar is always asked in connection to ``Last
Night'': What would he really do if the world were ending in six
hours?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for me to say, in a way,'' McKellar answers. ``I
feel closer to Patrick now, but they all come from me and I
sympathize with all of them. I don't think there's anyone in the
movie I find completely alien. So, I guess the answer is I would do
a mixture of all those things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
