<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      11-15 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! ``Anywhere But Here'' Old-fashioned mother-daughter soap
opera, done as well as it can be, thanks to Susan Sarandon's
performance as the restless single mom who grows from being
perceived as an airhead by her daughter to being perceived as the
earth mother she is. Natalie Portman's offspring, often finding
herself trapped in adult-child role reversals, is in all respects a
match for her mom in heart, intelligence, and big-screen-filling
personality. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   !!! ``Dogma'' Sweet, clunky, earnest, and often very funny mix
of heaven and earthiness as demons and angels duke it out en route
from Wisconsin to New Jersey. Kevin Smith's often profane but
always sincere satire stars Linda Fiorentino as Christ's
descendant, Chris Rock as the 13th Apostle, Alanis Morissette as
God _ and Ben Affleck and Matt Damon as bad-news angelic exiles
trying to blast their way back into heaven. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !! ``Finding North'' He's gay and suicidal, since his lover has
just died of AIDS. She's straight and tired of her dead-end life as
a bank teller and the daughter of disappointed parents _ but she's
not despondent. They bond. They take a trip to rural Texas, on a
sort of scavenger hunt/sentimental journey guided posthumously by
his dead lover. They bond some more. You stop caring somewhere in
there. (Unrated) (Jim Sullivan)
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Light It Up'' The warmth and energies of a strong
ensemble cast (led by Usher Raymond and Rosario Dawson) carry this
well-intended film about six kids who inadvertently find their
reasonable demands on a run-down high school escalate into a siege
situation. The rigging is transparent, which is another way of
saying the film plays like a connect-the-dots TV movie. But at
least it's about something and deals in positive values, as opposed
to the usual exploitation. (R)
</P>
<P>
   ! 1/2 ``The Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc'' Lots of epic
sweep and energetic battle scenes can't conceal the deficiency at
the center of this homemade take on France's legendary hero. Milla
Jovovich looks good _ too good, if you count her hairstyles _ but
she simply hasn't the acting range or depth to give us the barest
hint of Joan's spirituality or the kind of passion it ignited.
There have been worthwhile films about Joan of Arc, but this one,
directed by Luc Besson, isn't among them. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``Train of Life'' It's 1941, and Jewish villagers in an
Eastern European town respond to rumors about deportation by
pretending to be deported. They load up on a train, some of them
impersonate Nazis, and they take off for Palestine by way of
Russia. Plausible? No, but writer/director Radu Mihaileanu (a
Romanian refugee) successfully shuffles humor and harsh reality _
and a resonant ending _ to make a Holocaust-tinged comedy that's
much better than ``Life Is Beautiful.'' (R) (Jim Sullivan)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
