<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-BACALL-BOS &LR;      11-15 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-BACALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACALL GETS READY FOR BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the first floor of the building that houses the
Manhattan Theater Club, construction workers are busily creating
this city's latest theme restaurant. It's the World Wrestling
Federation night spot where fans will eventually arm wrestle their
waiters and waitresses for the check. Just down the block, teen
sensation Britney Spears is putting in an appearance at the
headquarters of VH1.
</P>
<P>
   But upstairs at the MTC, a company of actors whose cumulative
ages add up to more than half a millennium are reinvigorating
``Waiting in the Wings,'' a Noel Coward play that had a brief run
nearly 50 years ago in London, and has began a two-week,
pre-Broadway run in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Bacall, Rosemary Harris, Rosemary Murphy, Fionnula
Flanagan, Dana Ivey, Barnard Hughes, and several other stars are
listening to director Michael Langham, whose previous credits
include ``The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie,'' ``St. Joan,'' and
``Timon of Athens,'' all of which received Tony nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Cohen, the legendary producer of dozens of Broadway
hits, ranging from Richard Burton's ``Hamlet'' to ``Beyond the
Fringe,'' sits with colleague Chase Mishkin outside the door
waiting for Bacall.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old play with an elderly cast, but when the question of
age comes up, Cohen is quick to counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not running a geriatric ward,'' says the erudite Cohen.
``We're getting a play together for Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting in the Wings'' is a chestnut that's making its
American debut some 25 years after the author's death. It's set in
a rest home for retired actresses unaccustomed to waiting. Bacall
and Harris portray performers who, thanks to a long-simmering feud,
haven't spoken in decades. In this new edition, the play is being
polished up by playwright Jeremy Sams and brought to life by this
stellar cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know when they're going to break?'' asks Cohen, of a
production assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any moment, sir,'' comes the reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing this the old-fashioned way,'' says Cohen. ``We're
bringing it to Boston as a preview. The Boston audience closely
parallels the New York audience.'' Cohen then slips into evocative
recollections of late-night reworkings over sandwiches at Jacob
Wirth's and rewritings in suites at the Ritz. ``I brought about 25
plays to Boston over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the door sweeps open and a pride of lionized actresses
emerges. It's theater's equivalent of baseball's team of the
century. The sharp and sprightly Rosemary Harris emerges followed
by a pensive Rosemary Murphy and a smiling Fionnula Flanagan.
There's Patricia Conolly and Elizabeth Wilson. And Dana Ivey.
</P>
<P>
   Bacall, dressed in black from head to toe, as if she were still
doing those fabulous ads for what becomes a legend most, makes her
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only have 10 minutes,'' says the star who was born Betty
Joan Perske, ``and then it's back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacall is back on Broadway, a place she dominated nearly 30
years ago with her Tony Award-winning performance in ``Applause.''
Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just crazed,'' she laughs. It's that deep, throaty,
intelligent, sincere laugh we've heard so many times in films,
beginning with her startling screen debut at 20 opposite Humphrey
Bogart in ``To Have and Have Not'' (1944). ``It's damned hard work.
But that's what I've done all my life is work. What else is there?
Retire? What's that? I'm not going to enjoy going to lunch and
cocktail parties. Retire? What the hell's that about? Christ
Almighty, why should I spend my whole life trying to reach a goal
and as soon as I reach it quit? The idea isn't to stop as soon as
you can but to keep on going.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a hint of lipstick, Bacall doesn't appear to wear any
makeup and, while she has a deserved reputation as a fashion plate,
she seems comfortable wearing black slacks and a matching sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy ensemble work,'' she says, without a hint of
facetiousness. ``I don't want to be the whole cheese. It really is
fun, and if I'm ever going to do it again the time is now. I'm no
spring chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a personal reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noel Coward was a friend . . . a wonderful friend,'' she says,
between swigs of bottled water. ``Last week, they did a revival of
a TV version of his `Blithe Spirit' at the Museum of Radio and
Television History. I was in it and they asked me to talk about it.
I did. It was fun. Noel has such a gift. When Noel was writing this
one he got slightly depressed about all these women retiring to a
rest home. But there's such a wonderful rhythm to the lines and
language. And then you have us seven nuts running around. It's very
funny. And we're not interchangeable, which is one of the terrific
things about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacall pauses. ``I guess sometimes I wish I spent more time with
the children, but what can you do? Mothers are impossible. Children
are impossible. It's an impossible relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Her two children with Humphrey Bogart are doing well. Her son,
Steven, is a producer at NBC News, and daughter Leslie is a yoga
therapist in California. Sam Robards, her other son, whose father
is Jason Robards, is a respected actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't let me help him,'' says Bacall. ``Not even a phone
call. Leslie's always doing things to help people. She didn't get
all her generosity from me. Bogie's father was a doctor _ maybe
that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   She pauses. Each time the name of her first husband is mentioned
it's as if she switches emotional channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of how young I was when all this started,'' says
the star who just celebrated her 75th birthday. ``I'd go into
Howard Hawks's office and there'd be William Faulkner one day and
Raymond Chandler the next. And there was Bogie and all his friends.
Sometimes I feel like I must be 500 years old. Suddenly I feel as
if I've lived so many different lives. Now, especially in
television, the important thing is to get a name on a parking
space. Everything's sound bites. That's what's good about being
back on stage. Solid writing. There's an intelligence in the
theater. I get letters from young children who have seen the old
movies and write and want to know why they don't have movies like
them anymore. It's very rewarding to get the letters.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you say when you write them back?
</P>
<P>
   ``Write them back?'' she asks with a huffy laugh. ``I've got
better things to do with my time than write to teenage girls. But
that doesn't mean I don't like getting them.''
</P>
<P>
   The assistant returns with a cardboard bowl of chicken soup and
a red Delicious apple. The designated 10 minutes has drifted into
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bacall stares at the container.
</P>
<P>
   She carefully picks up the plastic spoon with long fingers that
are decorated with several ornate gold rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no noodles,'' she barks, while stirring
disdainfully. ``A cardboard bowl of soup with no noodles . . . even
though I asked for chicken noodle soup. . . . I guess that's what
it means to be a stahr.''
</P>
<P>
   In that one moment, the dichotomy of Bacall crystalizes. She is
certainly proud of being who she has become and yet she also sees
the other side of herself. The Betty Joan Perske side that sees the
ironic, silly, and funny angle of Lauren Bacall's stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there are a few noodles,'' she says, as the assistant
reminds her that she's got five minutes before the rehearsal
resumes.
</P>
<P>
   A few nights earlier, Bacall appeared at a star-studded New York
political gala. The longtime Democratic Party activist, who fought
against the Hollywood blacklist and supported everyone from Harry
Truman and Adlai Stevenson to Bill Clinton and Ted Kennedy, is a
diehard liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Teddy,'' she says, referring to Massachusetts's senior
senator. ``Let's not denigrate liberalism. Liberals have done more
for this country than the Republicans any day. What did Trent Lott
ever do? I love Teddy because he fought the good fight against
these people. He's the only one up there who isn't afraid of being
a liberal. Since Roosevelt, the liberals have done everything to
help people in this country. And I hear Patrick (Kennedy's son) is
doing great things in Rhode Island.''
</P>
<P>
   The assistant beckons Bacall.
</P>
<P>
   Bacall makes a gift of the apple and grabs a bottle of water.
</P>
<P>
   When the cast heads back into Studio 2, there's only one lady
doing the leading. And she knows who she is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1411EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SWAMP-BOS &LR;      11-15 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SWAMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELUSION, DESTITUTION COLLIDE IN `DISMAL SWAMP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE FABULOUS HISTORY OF THE DISMAL SWAMP COMPANY 
A Story of George Washington's Times 
By Charles Royster 
Knopf, 622 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Great Dismal Swamp, some 106,000 acres of cypress swamps on
the Virginia-North Carolina border populated by deer and otters,
bobcats and bears, and hordes of mosquitoes is today a national
wildlife refuge. But in the late 1700s it was a land speculator's
dream, where a scheme to drain the swamp for farmland promised
investors a 900 percent profit in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Very few of the colonial gentry who were lured into this ``land
of promise'' got rich _ and more than a few went bankrupt _ but the
story of the company formed to develop the swamp has provided
Charles Royster, a professor of history at Louisiana State
University, with a marvelously realized opportunity to explore a
society based on a culture of conspiculous consumption.
</P>
<P>
   The initial scheme involved transporting hundreds of slaves into
camps in the swamp where they would clear the land and cut drainage
ditches _ even though it was acknowledged that the swamp's
``malignant vapours'' would kill many of them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1764, George Washington, acting for the company, had the task
of ``collecting slaves from members'' of the company. But
suggesting the skepticism of even its investors, many sent slaves
who one observer called ``the worst collection that was ever made _
they seemed to be the refuse of every one of the estates from
whence they were sent.'' Work moved slowly with the only income
coming from the felling of ancient white cedars for shingles, a
forerunner of the logging that was the final commercial enterprise
in the swamp.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was only one of a number of men, including Patrick
Henry and Thomas Jefferson, whose reputations survived their
involvement with the Dismal Swamp Company. The most intriguing
figure who emerges from the story is one whose primary interest was
not getting rich quick. Dr. Thomas Walker had studied in
Williamsburg and married into wealth, but was a man, writes
Royster, ``whose blue eyes looked across many western vistas'' as
surveyor for various land companies.
</P>
<P>
   He strides in and out of the story, a true frontiersman dwarfing
the planters and politicians for whom he worked. He celebrated his
65th birthday, Royster writes, on an extended surveying mission
during the winter of 1780. It was the coldest winter in 40 years
and Walker's party was snowbound for weeks, burning fires night and
day. ``Dr. Walker, lover of tall stories and practical jokes,
allowed no gloom'' even if the weather prevented him from pulling
``one of his favorite stunts: boiling a rattlesnake in a coffeepot,
serving coffee, then pulling out the dead snake.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real action was miles away from the ``malignant
vapours'' and ``noisome exhalations'' of the swamp, in London
trading houses and on the Tidewater plantations where a
status-yearning gentry were transplanting the excesses of English
aristocracy _ and losing fortunes in the process. And this, the
story behind the story, is fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   There was William Byrd, the originator of the 900 percent profit
scheme. His estate, Westover, boasted a naked Venus that the family
claimed to be the work of Titian. When his son's widow died in
1813, an observer noted that while Byrd was ``a magnificent prince
himself, his children and grandchildren (had become) beggars.''
Mann Page's Rosewell boasted a checkerboard floor with ``tiles of
English Purbeck white stone and black Belgian marble.'' But he died
in debt, and when his grandson and heir died some 80 years later,
his widow wrote that ``to clear the estate from debt is my first
object.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Enterprising men with capital,'' writes Royster, got rich
through speculation in slaves, buying dozens at a time at a
discount, then selling them one by one at 25 to 50 percent profit.
Planters, already in debt, would have sold their tobacco crop and
used the cash not to pay off those debts but to buy slaves _ who
might end up being mortgaged, along with the land they worked, in
order to pay off those debts.
</P>
<P>
   The vast expanses of land that fueled this social economy are
beyond comprehension today. Before the Revolution, land companies
and individual speculators were obtaining royal charters granting
them land that was measured in the tens of thousands of acres in
Virginia and the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was to be a Land of Eden _ as early investors
believed the Dismal Swamp would be _ it lay to the west. And that
is where many of the company's investors and their heirs headed in
the years after the Revolution, leaving disappointment and debt
behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1412EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0278 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ARTS-CENTURY-COMPOSE-     11-15 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-CENTURY-COMPOSE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRADITION REMAINS VITAL AND UNPREDICTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is sometimes said that 20th-century music began at the
riotous premiere of Igor Stravinsky's ``Le Sacre de Printemps'' in
1913. But you could also claim that it began with Strauss's
``Salome'' in 1905, or Charles Ives's ``Variations on `America' ''
for organ, which was written in 1891 _ or for that matter, if we
are talking about ``modernity'' of sound, one could cite some of
the madrigals of Gesualdo, collected in 1611.
</P>
<P>
   Puccini's ``Tosca'' was probably the earliest masterpiece to
appear in this century, though not everyone thought so at the time.
The premiere came Jan. 14, 1900 in Rome, and when the opera was
played in London a year later, one critic wrote it was ``brutal . .
. demoralizing . . . induced a feeling of nausea. . . . What has
music to do with a lustful man chasing a defenseless woman or the
dying kicks of a murdered scoundrel?'' This doesn't sound all that
different from the fulminations of critics of popular culture today
_ or some of the complaints following the Boston Symphony
Orchestra's performances of Oliver Knussen's ``Where the Wild
Things Are'' a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   History (and within it, the history of music) doesn't fall
conveniently into centuries, though centuries do seem to reflect
biorhythms, the way people do. Music that bade poignant farewell to
the 19th century _ like Mahler's Ninth Symphony, first performed
posthumously in 1912, and sounded unimaginably difficult at the
time _ now speaks with particular directness to music lovers at the
close of the 20th.
</P>
<P>
   The music of the first half of our century has been seen as some
kind of battleground between Stravinsky and Arnold Schoenberg, or
between their supporters. Schoenberg carried the implications of
Wagner's ``Tristan'' chord to its logical conclusion in atonality,
and the organization of atonality into system. He felt it was a
historical necessity to do so, and it was not a burden he carried
lightly. If there was a battle, there wasn't a winner; Stravinsky
wrote 12-tone masterpieces late in his life, and Schoenberg
``returned'' to tonality in certain of his late works _ and both
composers always sounded like themselves in whatever they wrote. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Villains of the century &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Simple-minded commentary has cast Schoenberg, or his followers,
as the villains of the century. The myth goes that only the
free-spirited composers of the very recent past have escaped the
``stranglehold'' of '50s academicism by responding to the basic
elements of music (as in the school of ``minimalism'') or by
assimilating the musical achievements of popular culture (which has
been going on since medieval and Renaissance composers put ``pop''
material like dances into counterpoint with Gregorian chant; Bach's
``Goldberg'' Variations end with two folksongs in counterpoint). A
lot of the controversy came from outside the musical world;
composers themselves tend to be curious about everything that's
going on around them _ Puccini attended the Italian premiere of
Schoenberg's ``Pierrot lunaire.'' Schoenberg himslf famously
remarked that there was a lot of good music still to be written in
the key of C major; the unspoken corollary was that there is still
a lot of good music still to be written in other tonal and
non-tonal systems. A lot of argument could have been circumvented
by making the concession that technique and style are elements of
musical value, but not the only ones; talent and urgency count,
too. Twelve-tone masterpieces like Berg's ``Wozzeck'' and Violin
Concerto have entered the standard repertory, and their descendents
and successors will too, if they continue to compel the attention
of performers and of audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Most generalizations about historical periods don't hold up. It
is a commonplace to observe, for example, that the 19th century was
the golden age of the symphony, which has come under threat in our
own _ but Shostakovich and Prokofiev wrote all of their symphonies
in this century, Sibelius all but one of his. For years, it was
claimed that Puccini's ``Turandot'' (1926) was the last opera to
enter the international standard repertory. But then ``Wozzeck,''
``Peter Grimes,'' ``Les Dialogues des Carmelites,'' and
``Mahagonny'' became more familiar in the international repertory,
and part of the cherished experience of most operagoers, and each
country also produced its own national repertory of favorites
(``Porgy and Bess,'' ``The Ballad of Baby Doe,'' and ``Susannah''
are American examples). As in previous centuries, it takes time,
often decades, for the public to catch up to the musical thinking
of the most original and challenging composers. Janacek and Ives,
for example, wrote their music in the first half of this century,
but became national and international figures only in the second
half, and there's little question that some composers the 21st
century will come to value highly are little-known today. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Effects of war &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The central historical events of the 20th century, the two world
wars, profoundly affected musical development. In the most basic
sense, the wars interrupted _ or, in many tragic cases, ended _ the
creativity of gifted musicians who might have contributed more to
musical history, or changed it. Only now is some of the most
important music written during and before World War II coming to
attention. That war in particular altered American musical life for
several generations because of the arrival in this country of
composers (Schoenberg, Stravinsky, Bartok, Hindemith, Weill),
conductors, instrumentalists, and a whole support system of
managers, critics, and other members of a discerning,
public-spirited audience. This infusion of talent revived a musical
culture that had been severely threatened in the period of the
Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Some things did not change during this century. Throughout most
of it, most music remained specifically national in character and
culture even as it sought to transcend national boundaries; the
universal lies in the particular. It takes only a few bars to
recognize Bartok as Hungarian, Shostakovich as Russian; Ravel,
Poulenc, Dutilleux, or Boulez as French. The 12-tone composer Luigi
Dallapiccola sounds as Italian as Puccini. Some composers, like
Aaron Copland, Virgil Thomson, George Gershwin, and Leonard
Bernstein set out quite self-consciously to create an ``American''
music; other American composers, like Roger Sessions, resisted such
impulses and tried to compose in an ``international'' vein _
although, with distance, it is hardly possible to hear Sessions as
any less ``American'' than Copland.
</P>
<P>
   Also, composers continued to choose the audience they wrote for.
Some tried to write for a large public and sought popular appeal;
others pursued advanced musical thought wherever it led them, and
wrote for a small and musically sophisticated audience. What was
important was to compose from inner imperative. Problems arose only
when composers didn't want to live with the consequences of their
decisions _ when advanced composers hankered after larger
audiences, or popular composers complained about lack of respect.
</P>
<P>
   Popularity and immediate appeal are dangerous criteria for
musical quality. Some very great music has held such appeal; Verdi
is a prime example, as Shakespeare and Dickens were in literature.
It is equally certain that some very great music never did.
Beethoven's ``Wellington's Victory'' was one of the great success
of his lifetime. Today the piece is a minor curiosity _ and
audiences and dedicated performers are still grappling with the
meaning of his late string quartets. Popularity doesn't always
last, and the winds of fashion blow reputations around. Victor
Herbert, for example, would have appeared on any list of the most
successful and popular American composers between 1900 and 1920;
his music, and his brand of sentiment, now appeal only to nostalgia
buffs. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
