<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0283 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-STARS-ON-THE-WEB-ART-     11-15 1706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARS-ON-THE-WEB-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOOPI AND THE WEB: STAR SEARCH IN CYBERSPACE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE B&AMP;W SLIDE showing Cindy Crawford and husband Rande Gerber is
available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this article. The art can
be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that you want the
art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANNE D'INNOCENZIO 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I missed out on the early days of television. I
missed out on Chrysler and Ford. This is a possibility of making
money for life,'' said Whoopi Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, calling from Los Angeles, was referring to her first
foray into the Internet: her role as an equity partner and
spokeswoman for Flooz.com, an online gift-currency program that was
launched in February.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Goldberg isn't financially comfortable. She says she
does ``OK.'' But her venture into cyberspace could catapult her
into the leagues of the Internet rich. She is exchanging her
celebrity status for an undisclosed amount of stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg is in the vanguard of personalities who are being
sought by Internet companies not only for their celebrity value,
but for their ``fit'' with a particular site's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   In Goldberg, for example, Flooz.com sees someone whose
irreverence and sense of fun are compatible with the Web site's
persona. So far, few celebs have actually been signed, and there
are still many Web sites that are waiting and watching before
moving, but word around the Internet companies is that the momentum
is beginning to build.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, while Flooz was breaking its $8 million national
outdoor and TV ad campaign promoting Goldberg, another Web company
called Estyle Inc. was trumpeting its own celebrity catch: Cindy
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   The startup company, which launched a maternity and baby
products site at address babystyle.com in May, toasted the model
and new mother as its latest board member and strategic consultant
at a party at the W Hotel's Whisky Blue here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to get into it,'' said Crawford, adding that
she had studied other Web opportunities before signing on with the
privately held Estyle for a piece of the company. How big a piece
no one would say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upside could be huge ... but I'm not looking to buy a Gulf
Stream or anything. This gives me a new dimension to my life.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have started more than a year ago with ``Star Trek''
star William Shatner's radio commercials for Priceline, a Web site
that allows people to bid for airline tickets. And TV ads for
Internet companies have popped up featuring the likes of Geena
Davis and Donald Trump.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet sources expect Goldberg and Crawford, both of whom
see themselves as active business partners in their respective
ventures, could be the real trailblazers in a trend toward a deeper
partnership between celebrity and startup Web firms.
</P>
<P>
   Other startups, including many fashion sites, are now on the
hunt for a household name to act as a spokesman, spokeswoman or
consultant. The goal: to increase market share in an increasingly
competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   They include Beautyjungle.com, a beauty site that wants to hire
an actress or supermodel to star in its February ad campaign, and
Fashion 500, which will be launched early next year and will
include major designer brands.
</P>
<P>
   Others such as Ibeauty.com, Eve.com and Beautyscene.com all say
they are mulling the idea of teaming with a celebrity as an equity
partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is very exciting, and the Internet industry has
matured,'' said Lisa Freedman, vice president of marketing at
Styleclick.com, a network of fashion sites. It just signed a deal
to be the e-commerce enabler of Daisy Fuentes.com and other
celebrity sites, and Freedman said she is studying other
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at all kinds of options in terms of how to
bring our celebrity contacts under our umbrella, including having
them participate as spokespeople,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrities can take a company in its early stages and
catapult it into large exposure in a short time,'' said Tim Draper,
who runs his own venture capital firm called Draper, Fisher &AMP;
Jurvetson in San Francisco. It is an investor in Estyle.
</P>
<P>
   Already, executives at Flooz and Estyle said they are seeing an
increase in traffic to their site.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at us very differently today than before we had
Whoopi,'' said Robert Levitan, co-founder of Flooz, citing a
traffic increase of 35 percent since the launch of the ad campaign
and what it calls its ``Whoopi gizmo'' on its site. The site
features an animated cartoon of Goldberg, promoting certain items.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan, who was a co-founder of IVillage network for women,
added, ``Investors are pleased that Whoopi has given us a vote of
confidence. Consumers look at us with more legitimacy, and they
better understand our brand. This will be our first holiday season
that we are online, and we expect there will be a lot of noise out
there. Whoopi enables us to get above the noise this holiday
season. It helps us to scale faster, and we need to do it this
holiday. We have no time to wait on the Internet. Everything is
urgent.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Estyle founder and chief executive officer Laurie
McCartney, nabbing Crawford has helped ``increase momentum'' in
only a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen an increase in our traffic,'' McCartney said. ``And
while it is partly due to our increasing our styles on the site,
Crawford has attracted a lot of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The site features Cindy's Corner, where the model dispenses
style advice on maternity and baby clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is under intense pressure,'' said Lars Kry, vice
president of marketing at Beautyjungle.com, which officially
launches next month. ``It is so important to establish yourself
with an upscale image.''
</P>
<P>
   Kry added that Beautyjungle is working with advertising firm
Badger Worldwide to develop a short list of candidates and expects
to find someone within the next two or three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like a woman who embraces the values of our customer
... a modern woman who is intelligent and who has a good sense of
humor,'' he said. ``Some celebrities really embrace the idea;
others are apprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are we interested in celebrities, but celebrities
have been interested in us,'' said Patty Isen, fashion director at
Fashion 500, which has had several meetings with celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to give names, but said that she is focusing on
models turned actresses. She added that she is not sure what kind
of role that person will play, but options include having them
serve on the advisory board or making them part of the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But hiring a big name won't necessarily mean instant success.
Industry sources say that there has to be a strong connection
between a star and the startup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the celebrity status will only work if it is
authentic. They have to use celebrities appropriately, and not
overuse them,'' said Judy Newman, a director at Maveron, a venture
capital fund that is an investor in Flooz.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, a celebrity will only work if he or she is an
active participant in building a brand presence,'' said venture
capitalist Draper.
</P>
<P>
   Estyle's McCartney, who said she was besieged by Hollywood
agents, believes that Crawford, who gave birth 3 1/2 months ago, is
a perfect fit, who ``really resonates with our consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Flooz had reportedly been in talks with Lisa Kudrow and Sarah
Jessica Parker, but company officials wanted Goldberg because she
better matched the Flooz attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something magical about her,'' Levitan said. ``Whoopi
is the essence of Flooz. She is funny but smart. She's got attitude
but is dignified. She's on the edge but trustworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Crawford, said McCartney, ``brings great insight into
fashion and style'' as well as ``great access to vendors.''
</P>
<P>
   McCartney added that she was also able to get access to
Crawford's personal stylist, Vivienne Turner, who suggested
featuring certain fashion styles for the pregnant woman: pashmina
shawls, a certain kind of bodyslimmer pantyhose that offers one
clean line, and V-neck cashmere cardigans, with a sexy piece of
lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cindy also told me about these great baby massage oils and a
baby monitor that we now feature on the Web,'' McCartney said. She
added that she plans to use Crawford in Estyle's other fashion
channels as they roll out, but declined to be specific.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford was also helpful in critiquing Estyle's advertising
mockups for its radio campaign, which broke a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told us how to make the message clearer,'' McCartney said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said that her venture into Estyle is ``like going to
business school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning a lot about how a company goes public, about the
different issues of stock,'' she said, adding that her role as
spokeswoman for Revlon did not allow her to get into the inner
workings of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, who said she calls the Flooz office every couple of
days, said she wants to get ``incredibly involved'' with the
company and would like to get a seat on the board. Currently, she
is on the advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Goldberg, whose only other endorsement is for MCI, has
put her own stamp on the Flooz ad campaign, changing copy and
adding funny lines to most of the TV spots. The campaign broke on
11 cable networks recently, according to Jack Feuer, marketing
director at Flooz.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Anne D'Innocenzio is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
