<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TEST2-HNS &LR;      11-15 0211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST </SLUG>
 2-HNS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a testplease ignore. (test 2)
</P>
<P>
   This is ``a banner year'' for enrolling first-year black
students at Texas's public law schools, but 90 percent of them are
attending one school -- historically black Texas Southern
University, state higher education officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Educators say the scant enrollment of blacks at predominantly
white law schools shows how the end of affirmative action in
college admissions still hampers minority enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 212 blacks are first-year law students among the four
state-supported schools. In 1997, only 159 blacks began law
studies. That was a year after Texas colleges dropped race as an
admissions factor because of a reverse-discrimination court ruling
against the University of Texas law school. The case is being
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 6 percent of first-year black law students in Texas
are attending the University of Houston law school. Elsewhere, 3
percent enrolled at UT law school, and 1 percent enrolled at Texas
Tech University's law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that these schools are still struggling with
minority recruitment,'' said Lynn Rodriguez, general counsel for
the Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board, which oversees
public colleges.
</P>
<P>
   2
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1421EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HOLOCAUST-INSURERS-HN     11-15 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-INSURERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA THREATENS INSURERS OVER HOLOCAUST CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's insurance commission is expected on
Tuesday to subpoena as many as 15 European insurance companies
concerning policies written for the victims of the Holocaust and
their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings are scheduled Dec. 1 and 2 in Los Angeles and San
Francisco, where Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush wants
executives of the companies _ all of which do business in the state
either directly or through U.S. subsidiaries _ to report their
progress in complying with disclosures required by the new
California Holocaust Registry law.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to comply with the requirement, which takes effect on
April 6, 2000, could lead to the revocation of a license to do
business in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (who) believe they are not compelled to turn over their
lists should understand now that they will not long be doing
business in California should they maintain such a defiant
position,'' Quackenbush said last week. ``If there is no compliance
by April 6, we will be throwing these companies out of
California.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Holocaust Registry Law was approved unanimously
by both the Assembly and Senate in September and signed into law by
Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, on Oct. 8. It compels insurance
companies doing business in the state to disclose information about
policies sold in Europe from 1929 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
   With the data, the Department of Insurance will create a
Holocaust Insurance Registry for the information and correlate the
names of policyholders with an international registry of Holocaust
victims, seeking matches.
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires insurers to certify they have searched for
heirs of Holocaust policyholders and paid claims, or, where heirs
could not be found, paid a comparable amount to a charitable
nonprofit organization assisting Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The same bill was approved unanimously in 1998 and vetoed by
then-Gov. Pete Wilson, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, also a Republican, is frustrated by what he
considers the languid pace of the work of an international
commission _ of which he is a member and helped create _ as it
attempts to settle claims from the era. He believes the commission,
which is headed by former Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger
and which includes major European insurers and the World Jewish
Congress, has been compromised by the insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our position that the insurance companies on the vast
majority of issues have been obstructionists in the process,'' said
Richard Mahan, a Los Angeles-based consultant hired by the state to
help settle the claims that date to 60 or more years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner does not have a whole lot of confidence in
the international commission and what has been set up for
processing claims,'' Mahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush has not provided the commission the claims being
developed in California, preferring to try to settle them
separately. Insurers say this is frustrating the process.
</P>
<P>
   The potential effects of a confrontation between California and
the major insurers are enormous. Quackenbush has particular
interest in several companies with global alliances, such as
Allianz AG, a major German corporation now as well during World War
II, which operates the Fireman's Fund Insurance Companies and
employs 4,000 people in California.
</P>
<P>
   During a telephone interview from Munich on Friday, Allianz
spokesman Nick Tewes said: ``It's too early for us to say
something.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Peter Lefkin, director of government affairs for
Fireman's Fund in Washington, said the company was ``extremely
sensitive to the implications of the California law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The authors of the law and Mr. Quackenbush are aware of the
fact that Fireman's Fund has been in this state since 1863. The
company has enjoyed a reputation as one of the state's premier
insurance carriers, but also has enjoyed an excellent working
relationship with Mr. Quackenbush.''
</P>
<P>
   Eagleburger, chairman of the International Commission on
Holocaust Era Insurance Claims, wrote to Quackenbush on Friday to
say he believes Allianz and the Italian insurance company
Assicurazioni Generali ``deserve to be exempted from subpoenas at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter says that the two companies ``have shown a
willingness to fully cooperate with the processes and funding of
the (commission). Accordingly, they deserve safe haven from the
requirements of California's legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislator who wrote the California Holocaust Registry Law,
Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles, expressed less confidence in
the willingness of the European insurers to cooperate in efforts to
compensate Holocaust victims or their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurers' game plan is obvious _ delay until the
claimants, many of whom are elderly already, die or give up,'' Knox
said. ``In the meantime, for appearances' sake, they make a
pretense of cooperating with the international commission without
making any real concessions. The antidote to this strategy is to
exert the unparalleled economic leverage of California state
government over the recalcitrant insurers desiring to do business
in our lucrative market.''
</P>
<P>
   Assicurazioni Generali and other insurance companies contend
that the international commission is the proper venue for resolving
the Holocaust assets issue.
</P>
<P>
   Other insurance companies potentially affected by the California
law are AXA of Paris, which earns half of its foreign income from
U.S.-based The Equitable Companies; Baloise Insurance Group of
Switzerland; Winterthur Swiss Insurance, which has nine
subsidiaries in the United States; and Zurich Financial Services,
which operates Farmers Group Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Holocaust survivors and their relatives have
testified before Quackenbush and other state insurance
commissioners about the refusal of insurance companies to honor
claims. Lack of a death certificate is one reason given even though
they were not issued at concentration camps, Quackenbush said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
