<P>
   LOBBY (Washington) _ When lobbying first became a profession a
few decades ago, the ground rules were pretty basic. About two
dozen members of Congress got most issues decided, and an effective
lobbyist had to have an in with at least one of them. But Congress
and the rest of the government have changed. And government affairs
and public relations businesses are changing, too. They are acting
more like a global business and are now even undergoing a wave of
consolidation. A handful of mega-firms are being born, offering
clients a full buffet of services: everything from public
relations, direct lobbying, research, polling, and direct-mail
canvassing to specialists who deal in drumming up ``grass roots''
support for issues. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   VODAPHONE-MANNESMANN (London) _ Development on the effort by
Vodafone to acquire Mannesmann. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
