<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-RANCHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD CHICKEN COOPS OFFER NESTS FOR ARTISTS, ENTREPRENEURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICKI HADDOCK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETALUMA, Calif. _ In years past, when Petaluma's chicken
ranches gave it the nickname ``Egg Basket of the World,'' millions
of chickens sprang from acres of cavernous coops.
</P>
<P>
   The poultry industry has long since flown those coops in
Northern California, leaving them weathered, dilapidated, rotting
from sun and rain. But an underground revolution is taking place on
the old chicken ranches, a quiet effort to reclaim scores of
abandoned coops and barns for a host of feather-free uses.
</P>
<P>
   Artists, artisans and fledgling entrepreneurs are renting them,
scraping off layers of excrement and using them as prized studio
space for pottery schools, yoga centers, recording studios and
other uses. Some of Sonoma County's most successful small
businesses incubated in coops.
</P>
<P>
   In short, chicken coops have become the trendy rural equivalent
of the urban warehouse studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the wind is blowing through the cracks and there's no
heat and the smell is overwhelming, let me tell you, you really
start to feel the inspiration of the starving artist,'' said
Jennifer Laporte, a painter who rented a coop for $75 a month _
mere chicken feed in the art world. ``There's nothing like working
in a coop to really conjure up that Van Gogh experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, some of these cool coups run afoul of zoning laws in
Sonoma County. Officials are cracking down and forcing the eviction
of some artists, entrepreneurs or their landlords who try to flaunt
regulations that limited commercial uses in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shell game,'' said Ben Neuman, head of code enforcement
for the Sonoma County Permit and Resource Management Department.
``Some of these places are very bold. I went to one where I stood
in the driveway and watched the UPS trucks coming in and out of
there every 15 minutes. We don't go out searching for violations,
but when we get a complaint we don't look the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows for certain what portion of southern Sonoma
County's artists and artisans work out of coops and barns, but it
is estimated about half of the coops are in use. Neuman said coop
and barn use makes up a ``significant amount of our workload.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenants often calculate that the benefits outweigh the inherent
risks of trying to skirt the zoning laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we did the chicken coop dance,'' said Tinalyn Marston,
founder of Pipsqueaks, a company that makes decorative children's
furniture seen in several prestigious catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Eric, started the operation out of their
garage in San Francisco, then moved to Petaluma to get less
expensive work space. And they found it in chicken coops, where
rents were about half the cost of industrial space. Still Marston
admitted there were challenged working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's it like inside? The coops are really raw. You can see
sunlight through the walls. The sheep were right next door _ they'd
come into our shop and you'd hear `baa baa baa.' As for plumbing,
there was only a porta-potty and it was really disgusting. Did I
mention the flies? They were so bad they'd drop into the paint cans
and just die. We were always having to pick them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have electricity, but the water was stinky and
copper-colored so we'd always remember to bring in bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Cats would come in at night and leave paw prints all over our
chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, we loved it,'' she said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the county ordered the coops closed, Pipsqueaks had
grown enough to move into a large industrial space along Petaluma's
riverfront. But the Marstons emphasized that the low overhead
during their ``coop years'' enabled them to make a profit and
expand.
</P>
<P>
   The county is investigating complaints on 65 properties where
farm buildings allegedly are being used illegally as studios,
workshops or dwellings. The officials say they have against twice
that many outfits that were operating illegally in farm buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The officials say they deal most severely with the few landlords
they have found who rent abysmally substandard coop housing to
farmworkers or poor families.
</P>
<P>
   Another high enforcement priority are coops that house sweatshop
manufacturing setups using illegal immigrant labor.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors report recently uncovering one ``extremely
hazardous'' wood manufacturing business where ventilation was so
poor that toilet paper rolls hung from the ceiling: workers were
instructed to pull off some sheets to cover their noses lest they
choke on the thick sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   But many coop landlords and tenants counter that most coops are
used only for artists' work space, and what dangers exist are
exacerbated by the county's refusal to relax its zoning on coops _
a recalcitrance that drives the current economy underground.
</P>
<P>
   Landlords are less likely to be able to hire reputable
contractors to fix a coop being used illegally, making it more
likely that electrical wiring, heating and sanitation are
potentially hazardous, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Petaluma's chicken heyday, of course, has come and gone. In
1930, more than 4 million chickens populated the Petaluma area and
produced many millions of eggs that were shipped around the world.
But the rise of corporate farming put most family farming
operations out of business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
