<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for TUESDAY, November 16,
1999
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WTO _ ANKARA, Turkey _ The United States and China
struck a landmark trade agreement Monday, opening the way for
Chinese membership in the World Trade Organization, which oversees
the rules of the road in the global marketplace. President Clinton,
here on a state visit, said the accord, which caps 13 years of
U.S.-China negotiations, would lead to economic growth and new jobs
for American farmers, computer makers and providers of a wide range
of services from telecommunications and entertainment to banking.
It has also gone a long way toward righting badly strained
relations between the United States and the world's most populous
country, said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. (Deans, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TURKEY _ ANKARA, Turkey _ President Clinton paid tribute
Monday to Turkey's growing strategic value at the crossroads
between Europe and Central Asia. He took aim, however, at Turkey's
poor human rights record, saying ``sovereignty should not be built
on fear,'' in the first speech ever given by a U.S. president to
Turkey's elected Parliament. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CYPRUS _ ANKARA, Turkey _ It was ``ping-pong'' diplomacy
that brought the United States and China together three decades
ago. The quest for Mideast peace gave rise to ``shuttle
diplomacy.'' And ``baseball diplomacy'' has provided a tenuous link
between the United States and Cuba. Now, said President Clinton,
``earthquake diplomacy'' has opened a window for Greece and Turkey
to settle longstanding disputes that have been a thorn in the side
of NATO for decades. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-MOVIE _ WASHINGTON _ Congressional and Clinton
administration staffers working on the Y2K computer issue view the
upcoming NBC production, ``Y2K: The Movie,'' at the Cox Newspapers
Washington Bureau and react to its disaster scenario. (Geewax, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 5 p.m. EST in (w) Washington and (e)
entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The movie airs Sunday, Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-GRADES _ WASHINGTON _ Your state's efforts to improve
teacher quality are graded in a report card to be issued Monday by
the conservative education reformers in the Washington office of
the Dayton-based Thomas B. Fordham Foundation. Ohio gets a D-plus,
but other Cox states rank very high: Texas (A) ranks first; Florida
(A-) second; North Carolina (B-) and Colorado (B-) tied for fifth,
and Georgia (C-) tied for 10th in the think tank's national
rankings. (Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   HOMESTEAD _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate has approved a limit of
$100,000 in a home that can be shielded from creditors in a
bankruptcy suit. The limit, far stricter than a House-passed
version, would particularly affect states such as Florida and Texas
that currently protect a home's entire value. (Malone, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX _ LAS VEGAS _ Back in the nation's capital, a judicial
ruling has tarnished Microsoft as an abusive monopolist. But in
this gambling capital, hosting the world's largest computer trade
show, Microsoft's new Internet technology far outweighs its legal
woes. But a banner lofted by arch-foe Sun Microsystems, the size of
a football field, suggests that the battle for the desktop
continues. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (a) national and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   GA-FIRE _ ATLANTA _ The U.S. Forest Service brought in fire
crews from California late Sunday and was expecting more
reinforcements today to help battle two forest fires that have
charred more than 450 acres in the Blood Mountain Wilderness Area
of northeast Georgia. Two crews were enroute from Puerto Rico, and
the rest would come from ``wherever they can be found,'' an
official said. The fires are near the popular Appalachian Trail,
but hikers should not be in any danger. Some houses are near one of
the fires, but were not threatened. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH LOCATOR MAP.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-BROWN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He's one of a select club in Texas,
a state senator whose imprint is on most of the environmental
legislation passed in the last two decades. He's talked about as a
candidate for lieutenant governor. But Sen. Buster Brown's had a
tough year, defending against charges of sexual harassment in the
workplace. Last week, the Republican Party in his Southeast Texas
district, which has been sending him to Austin since 1981, turned
against him. The Lake Jackson Republican Party said he should
resign because his sexual escapades make the party look bad.
(Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-SPACE _ MELBOURNE, Fla. _ Within a decade, rockets might use
a spaceport the way an airplane uses Hartsfield. ``We could be
competing with any number of states. It could launch and land in
Texas or anywhere in the U.S. . . . This is a major, major issue
for the state,'' said Catherine Deans, spokeswoman for Enterprise
Florida, a group formed to keep business coming to the Sunshine
State. During the heady days of Apollo, Cape Canaveral was the
undisputed launch capital of the world. Not so today. With wireless
communication demanding more satellite launches every day,
companies are contracting for blast-offs from spots around the
world, including an oil platform in the Pacific. On Tuesday, U.S.
space policymakers will assemble for a conference, largely
discussing the state of the space race in Florida. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LOWES-ARREST _ GREENSBORO, N.C. _ A suspect has been arrested in
the bombings of two Lowe's Home Improvement stores and in a third,
attempted Lowe's bombing. Authorities planned to announce the
arrest at a 1 p.m. news conference. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-BOOK _ DAYTON, Ohio _ An interview with former astronaut
John Glenn about his new book. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   KILLER-LAWYER _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Convicted cop killer Derek
Anthony Farmer is now a lawyer in Cincinnati, sworn in with the
backing of U.S. Judge Walter Rice and another local judge. Farmer
was convicted in one of the most infamous crimes ever in Dayton _
the slaying of Sumter McIntosh, a prominent civil rights advocate,
and highly respected Dayton Police Sgt. William Mortimer.
(Hills/Wagner, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
