<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0343 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-OBIT-STEGER-SFCHRON &LR;      11-15 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STEGER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAT STEGER, CHRONICLER OF SAN FRANCISCO SOCIETY, DIES AT 67 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL NOLTE  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pat Steger, the Chronicle's society editor and a
columnist who specialized in the life and times of the famous and
the famously rich, died Sunday of complications after cancer
surgery. She was 67.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Robb Steger was one of a vanishing breed _ a reporter
who covered people active in what used to be called Society with a
capital ``S,'' patrons of the arts and the opera, diners at the
best restaurants, members of the best clubs, graduates of the best
schools and of the cotillion, ladies and gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   The inhabitants of Steger's world _ a kind of Four Hundred whose
names regularly appeared in her column _ were part of what made San
Francisco a city. They were descendants of old money and possessors
of new, and in her columns they had style and class, feuds and
adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Steger was also a consummate journalist, much admired by her
colleagues for her reporting abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an institution,'' said William German, editor of the
Chronicle. ``She was also an excellent reporter and took enormous
pride in her own work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She always had the inside scoop,'' said Liz Lufkin, assistant
managing editor for features. ``It seemed like she knew everyone
and everything, and she was very generous about sharing it. We will
miss her terribly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown said Steger's death was ``terrible news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a wonderful person with an incredible sense of
humor,'' he said. He compared her to Chronicle columnist Herb Caen,
who died in 1997. ``We are all going to miss her,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Steger moved in San Francisco's best society, she also
took a wry view of the people she wrote about.
</P>
<P>
   One of the characters in her column was a woman named
``Muffie,'' an imaginary young matron, ``attractive, young,
thirtysomething more or less,'' a divorcee who dabbled in real
estate and social work. ``Muffie's Diary'' was used to make fun of
those who took themselves too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   However, Steger also believed that there was a San Francisco
society and that it was important. ``If there is any one event in
San Francisco where there is really a there there, it is at the
opening night of the opera,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Society was her beat the way some journalists cover football,
others politics and still others the courts. She was one of the
best, a reporter who took her work so seriously that her last few
columns were written in advance to run after she had been admitted
to the hospital with a grave illness.
</P>
<P>
   Her final column appeared November 8 and was as usual breezy,
newsy and graceful. There was not a hint she was ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``She took her column very seriously,'' said the Chronicle's
Catherine Bigelow. ``She always made sure items matched or she
would tie them together. She often would write the column and then
toss the whole thing if a more interesting item came in. Being
timely and current was very crucial to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Steger's column was less about high society than it was about
the city. ``Everyone from the guy at the gas pump to a top CEO read
the column,'' said Stanlee Gatti, president of the city Art
Commission and San Francisco's premier events planner.
</P>
<P>
   ``She chronicled the important events in our life,'' said Jo
Schuman Silver, producer of ``Beach Blanket Babylon,'' another San
Francisco institution. ``She was like our own diary, but everyone
could enjoy it. She was always loving and giving, never
mean-spirited. I'm afraid that every benefit, every type of
fund-raiser and the AIDS community will suffer now without the
mentions she always put in her column.''
</P>
<P>
   She was good for business. Allison Speer, who does public
relations for Giorgio Armani and the Emporio Armani boutiques, said
the firm ``always fought to get the ad space next to Pat's column
because we knew so many of our clients read it faithfully.''
</P>
<P>
   She also had the common touch. When unions went on strike
against the Chronicle and the San Francisco Examiner in 1994,
Steger took her column to the union-sponsored Free Press, which
became probably the only strike newspaper in the world to feature a
society column.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Robb was born in San Francisco in 1932 into a family
wealthy enough to send her to the Sarah Dix Hamlin School for Girls
and poor enough so that it took vacations in Palm Springs during
the summer, when it was hot and the auto court rates were low.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hamlin School she wrote a column in the school paper
called ``Out and About.'' ``It was very popular,'' she wrote later.
``There were even blind items, like who was overeating at Blum's.''
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in a world on the edge of change, but still in a
time when young women invited to a black-tie dance at a local
college went to I. Magnin to buy an evening gown.
</P>
<P>
   Steger remembered that day, in a story that was an obituary for
both the I. Magnin store and a way of life. It was 50 years ago,
and she could remember the look on the saleswoman's face and the
tone of her voice. She never forgot the woman's name: Miss Irene.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, the story won her an Atrium Award from the
University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Robb went to college, of course _ to Stanford, of course.
Later she transferred to USC. Ladies of her era did not transfer
from Stanford to Southern California; it was not done.
</P>
<P>
   But Robb did it. She received a degree in telecommunications,
but women did not work in this field then. ``Breaking into creative
jobs was almost impossible,'' she said. ``There was no way. The men
always got them.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``impossible'' was not a word for Pat Robb. One day, she got
into an elevator with a man carrying a couch. ``Are you a
psychiatrist making a house call?'' she said. Someone sent the
crack to Herb Caen, the dominant columnist in Northern California.
He ran it.
</P>
<P>
   This gave her an idea. She sent items to columnists _ not Caen,
but to Paul Speegle, who wrote a similar column in the old San
Francisco Call-Bulletin. Speegle eventually hired her as his
assistant _ his legman, as they used to call such functionaries.
</P>
<P>
   She also worked as a critic, entertainment reporter, and when
the great man was not up to the task, she wrote the Paul Speegle
column. ``In those days,'' she said, ``you were grateful for the
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the day of the Call-Bulletin was rapidly fading. One
afternoon, she got a telegram announcing staff cutbacks; she had
been laid off. She ignored it, and reported to work as usual on the
theory that no one would have enough nerve to fire her in person.
She was right, but the time was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Call died, but Robb had a life. She married Wilfred Steger,
moved abroad and had two sons. By the '70s, she was back in San
Francisco, again sending items to columnists, this time to Caen,
the king of the hill here.
</P>
<P>
   People noticed, and in 1974, she was hired by the Chronicle and
asked to write a society column. ``I never read them before I wrote
them,'' she said. ``But I figured, `Why not?' I loved working at
newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Steger was a natural. Every weekday for years, later three times
a week, she wrote a column, 25 years of them _ about people and
places, British royalty, celebrities, society figures, the Napa
Valley and Lake Tahoe, Trader Vic's and Moose's, black tie and
white tie, the life of a city and the death of I. Magnin.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, a part of the city died with Pat Steger. In her
farewell to the Magnin store, she wrote how in the new stores,
``the minute you walk in the door ... someone bounces up and asks,
`Finding everything you need?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I may find what I need,'' she wrote, ``but I don't always find
what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a tremendous resource and wonderful to work with, ''
said Trish Donnally, the Chronicle's fashion editor. ``She was a
lady in the best sense of the word.''
</P>
<P>
   Steger is survived by her husband; their two sons, Robert of
Half Moon Bay, Calif., and William of Los Angeles; and her brother,
Joseph Robb of Tiburon, Calif. Services are pending.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
