u v AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      11-15 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Nov.
16.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Editors, adds HUBBLE story, updates with photos and graphics
notations.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUBBLE-BREAKDOWN (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ NASA's Hubble
Space Telescope suffered a system failure over the weekend that
will leave it unable to transmit any pictures to Earth until the
next, much-delayed, space shuttle mission, the space agency said
Monday. By Warren E. Leary. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-PLANET (Undated) _ Astronomers report the most direct
evidence yet for the existence of a planet around another star, a
dimming of the star's light when the planet passed between us and
the star. The data allows them to calculate the mass, density, and
other characteristics of the planet. By John Noble Wilford. (900
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRAVITY-WAVES (Livingston, La.) _ Scientists hope a new,
gigantic gravity wave detector inaugurated on Friday will open a
new window on the universe. The L-shaped detector and a recently
completed twin in Washington are called LIGO for Laser
Interferometer Gravitational-wave Observatory. The signals of
gravity waves reaching the earth from the merger of black holes and
other cosmic catastrophes hold the possibility of deciphering
gravitational radiation as a means of penetrating secrets of the
birth of the universe and the evolution of black holes, galaxies
and other mysteries. By Malcolm W. Browne. (2180 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GARWIN-TESTBAN (Undated) _ Scientist at Work: Dr. Richard L.
Garwin, 71, one of the federal government's most widely respected
science advisers, remains optimistic despite one of the worst
defeats of his career, the Senate rejection of the nuclear test
treaty. An adviser to six presidents, including Clinton, Garwin
says he is now taking on the treaty's most vociferous public foes
one by one, writing letters, challenging their claims, suggesting
that they debate him publicly and generally trying to undo what he
regards as the trashing of the factual record. By William J. Broad.
(1990 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORPHAN-DISEASES (Undated) _ About 5,000 rare disorders are
classified as ``orphan diseases,'' and at one point stood little
chance to be cured, as drug researchers ignored them, assuming
there would be too few customers to make it pay to develop
treatments. Many of the disorders are severe or fatal, and in 1983,
hoping to encourage research, the government began offering tax
credits, research grants and other incentives to companies working
on rare diseases. Now the orphans drugs prove a boon to some
pharmaceutical companies, and some have made more than $1 billion a
year as a result. By Denise Grady. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BUFFALO-DECLINE (Undated) _ As portrayed in a number of new
books, the real story of the decline of the buffalo involves a
dramatic change in climate, competition for forage and cattle-borne
disease. Another key factor, the authors say, were Indian tribes,
empowered by the horse and gun and driven to hunt buffalo for the
profits that came from hides and meat. By Jim Robbins. (1540 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: items on a
substance that works like a birth control pill on copepods, the
complexities of dirt and the composition of an asteroid. By Henry
Fountain. (690 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AUDIO-RECORDING (Undated) _ A Michigan State physicist has
devised a recording technique so lifelike that listeners almost
believe musicians are right in the room with them. (1525 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LEONID-METEORS (Undated) _ Experts forecast that the Leonid
meteor shower, which occurs when Earth travels through a plume of
dust particles from the comet Tempel-Tuttle, may provide quite a
show in some parts of the world, with 1,000 to 1,500 meteors per
hour arcing through the sky late Wednesday and early Thursday. By
Henry Fountain. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GIRLS (Undated) _ Girls today need not go it alone, naive or
humorless. There are sources where they can learn about their
bodies, minus the medicalese and pious homilies. At the forefront
of this female informist movement is a new book, ``Deal With It! A
Whole New Approach to Your Body, Brain and Life as a Gurl.'' Based
on a Web site, gURL.com, that three women started in 1996, the book
offers a frank, detailed and zealously nonjudgmental take on all
aspects of girlhood. By Natalie Angier. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRESCRIPTIONS (Undated) _ When it comes to regulating
tobacco use, saving people from themselves is a tricky business,
especially when prescriptions are the means to the end. This is a
lesson that sinks in only slowly after medical school. Young
doctors think their prescriptions are sacrosanct, little pieces of
delivered wisdom. Eventually they discover their prescriptions are
just little pieces of paper. Just because you write someone a
prescription doesn't mean they will take the medication. Just
because you withhold a prescription doesn't mean they won't. The
hoary and jaded among us know that a prescription is really only a
suggestion, a word of friendly advice, nothing more. By Abigail
Zuger, M.D. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Second of two columns on what can
be done safely in pregnancy. Not so long ago, pregnant women were
almost universally warned to avoid strenuous activity. But faced
with women's growing interest in exercise and sports and their
desire to stay in shape while a new life takes shape within them,
doctors gave exercise during pregnancy a second look. And to the
surprise of many, medical research has shown that most women can
safely continue to exercise throughout pregnancy, as long as they
make some sensible adjustments to their routines. By Jane E. Brody.
(1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-MONITORS (Undated) _ Heart monitors may be useful for
exercise, especially for beginners, some fitness experts contend.
By Liz Neporent. (800 words)
</P>
