<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0394 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-WAR-CRIMES-HNS &LR;      11-15 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON NEEDS TO PROBE VIETNAM ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIAS CASTILLIO and JIM BARKER   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ More than a half-century after the Korean
War, the Defense Department is investigating the massacre of 400
Korean civilians at the No Gun Ri bridge. The Associated Press
reported that U.S. soldiers gunned down the refugees because of a
general's suspicion that North Korean infiltrators were among the
refugees fleeing a Communist onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the passage of 50 years, the will to investigate such a
horrendous event and determine the responsibility, no matter where
it may lie, is seemingly undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no apparent willingness to do the same thing with
the Vietnam War. Other than the My Lai massacre, the Pentagon has
never sought to probe reports of why seemingly normal American
soldiers began committing savage and barbarous atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, the Veterans Administration and counselors who
work with Vietnam veterans have listened to traumatized veterans
recounting tales of participating, or watching helplessly, as some
U.S. soldiers committed butchery against Vietnam civilians and
captured soldiers of the Viet Cong. Those incidents range from
decapitation, massacre of prisoners, murders of fellow Americans,
needless slaughter of Vietnamese civilians and mutilation of their
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Sara A. Haley, a counselor at Boston Veterans
Administration Outpatient Clinic, wrote in a psychiatric journal:
``Killings of POWs, civilians or fellow soldiers . . . have now
been documented by the hundreds in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Those incidents, she said, were unlike the ``isolated reported
episodes'' of previous wars in which American soldiers had
participated.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Chaim F. Shatan, also a counselor for veterans, likens the
use of terror and ``dehumanization of Orientals'' during the
traumatic stress disorder resulting from either participating in or
witnessing an atrocity. The stories of these veterans are anguished
and guilt-ridden because of what they did or failed to Vietnamese
War ``as so pervasive that mass slaughter became almost as
automatic as it was in Nazi death camps.''
</P>
<P>
   His comment is included in ``Stress Disorders Among Vietnam
Veterans, Theory, Research and Treatment,'' a book edited by
Charles R. Figley of Purdue University.
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, Veterans Administration counselors share
reports of treating Vietnam veterans suffering from the effects of
atrocity-induced post stop.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these veterans describe themselves as ``wanderers,''
haunted by what happened to them, unable to maintain relationships
or jobs, highly irritable, suffering from nightmares so intense
that many wake up screaming night after night, bathed in sweat and
plagued during the daytime by intense flashbacks that can occur at
any moment no matter what the activity. Some seek solace in drugs
and alcohol; a few consider suicide to end their suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the debilitating symptoms of post-traumatic stress
syndrome, which can also be induced by combat stress.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors, in treating the atrocity-induced syndrome, have
found that therapy, if it is to be effective, involves lengthy
sessions in which a close bond develops between the patient and
counselor.
</P>
<P>
   This allows veterans finally to confess their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that the primary symptoms of post-traumatic
stress disorder do not fade with time but may instead intensify.
</P>
<P>
   The question that remains to be answered is: What possessed some
otherwise normal American youths to commit unspeakable acts of
barbarism? These soldiers were not reared by their families, or
trained by the military, to kill unarmed civilians without
provocation _ or to slice off noses, fingers and scalps of Viet
Cong enemies and wear them proudly as necklaces or hang them from
staffs. (While the Viet Cong upper command deliberately
countenanced terror and mutilation as part of a modus operandi to
win the war, those acts were never part of Pentagon policy.)
</P>
<P>
   Was it the fact that Vietnam was a guerrilla war in which stress
turned too many U.S. soldiers into sociopathological killing
machines who could not differentiate between the enemy and unarmed
Vietnamese civilians?
</P>
<P>
   Was it Army and Marine officers who encouraged mutilation, such
as George S. Patton III, then a colonel and later a general, who
sent to his troops full-color Christmas cards of dismembered Viet
Cong?
</P>
<P>
   Can their behavior be blamed on the basic training they received
in which command officers stood by and ignored the racial slurs of
drill sergeants that dehumanized all Vietnamese?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the answers, we need it to help heal the torn lives of
too many Vietnam veterans who were sacrificed for this nation's
worst war blunder, then whisked out of that terrible environment
and dropped back into their homes without the slightest concern by
the Pentagon as to what the war had done to their minds.
</P>
<P>
   No one counseled young, traumatized soldiers, as they left
Vietnam, to seek help if they suffered from post-traumatic stress
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   We need a Congressional investigation into U.S. atrocities
committed in Vietnam to determine what possessed so many U.S.
soldiers to go berserk and why, at the first sign of such behavior,
it was not stopped by their commanding officers.
</P>
<P>
   My Lai was not an isolated event. It was a symptom that
something vital had snapped in the minds of too many young American
soldiers and was then ignored by the generals who directed that
war.
</P>
<P>
   The massacres and mutilations cannot just be swept under the
carpet or shrugged off with the comment, ``his happens in every
war.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elias Castillo is a free-lance writer, journalism teacher and
consultant in Redwood City. Jim Barker, a former soldier and a
student of Vietnamese culture, has counseled veterans for nearly 20
years. They are writing a book on atrocities in the Vietnam War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
