<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0405 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-BOOK16-COX     11-15 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newest Bush book gives governor's perspective
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (e) Entertainment and (p) Political categories.)
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A reporter and an ex-con have had their turns.
Now it's Gov. George W. Bush's turn to put his life between hard
covers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's version, ``A Charge to Keep,'' published by William
Morrow and written with Bush aide Karen Hughes, hits bookstore
shelves Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's the third Bush book spawned by his presidential campaign.
One, written by Dallas Morning News reporter Bill Minutaglio, is
still available. The other, written by ex-convict J.B. Hatfield and
including unsubstantiated allegations that Bush, many years ago,
was arrested for cocaine use, was yanked from shelves when the
publisher learned of the author's criminal past.
</P>
<P>
   For $23, Bush's book promises a ``warm, insightful, honest look
at the personal and political experiences'' that helped shape the
GOP presidential front-runner. For Texans familiar with the
governor's career and philosophy, the book is a 243-page version of
what has become Bush's stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   The book reads like what it is, part and parcel of a political
campaign. In the foreword, as he has told biographers with whom he
chose not to cooperate, Bush writes that he was disinclined to
produce a book about his life because ``I feel that many chapters
of my life story are yet to be written.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not promise a ``comprehensive look at every event of
my life,'' but he does offer accounts of ``some of the events that
have shaped my life and some of my major decisions and actions as
governor of Texas.'' Predictably, and appropriately for a book
timed to a presidential campaign, Bush offers a one-sided view _
his side _ of his performance in government and business.
</P>
<P>
   The governor offers familiar accounts _ and no new information _
of how he wound up as a congressman's kid in the Texas Air National
Guard during the Vietnam War and how he quit drinking and left
behind his ``young and irresponsible'' years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would serve,'' he writes about his role during the
Vietnam War. ``My inclination was to support the government and the
war until proven wrong, and that only came later as I realized we
could not explain the mission, had no exit strategy and did not
seem to be fighting to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has said he knew nothing about any preferential
treatment, makes no mention of the back-channel efforts made by a
family friend through then-Texas House Speaker Ben Barnes to get
Bush a slot as a pilot in the Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard from contemporaries that there were openings for
pilots in the Texas Air National Guard, and I called to ask about
them,'' he writes. ``There were several openings, I was told,
because many people who wanted to go into the Guard were unwilling
to spend the almost two years of full-time duty required for pilot
training.'' He writes that he learned ``the lesson of Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation should be slow to engage troops. But when we do, we
must do so with ferocity. We must not go into a conflict unless we
go in committed to win. We can never again ask the military to
fight a political war,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also recounts the oft-told story about how he swore off
alcohol after having a few too many, again, at his 40th birthday
party in Colorado. ``Quitting drinking made me more focused and
more disciplined,'' he tells readers.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the book, as he does on the campaign trail, Bush
offers credit to his family and his faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw, first-hand, that you could enter the arena, give it
your best and leave with your integrity intact,'' he writes of his
father's 1992 presidential election loss.
</P>
<P>
   It was in a moment when faith intersected with government that
Bush says his desire to run for president gained strength. At a
church service before this year's gubernatorial inauguration, Bush
listened to pastor Mark Craig talk about how America ``needs
leaders who have the moral courage to do what is right for the
right reason.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking to you,'' Bush says his mother told him later.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no magic moment of decision. After talking with my
family during the Christmas holidays, then hearing the rousing
sermon to make the most of every moment during my inaugural church
service, I gradually felt more comfortable with the prospect of a
presidential campaign,'' Bush writes.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor also tells about the death of former
Texas Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, a Democrat who may have done as much as
anyone to make Bush a credible presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we wept together,'' Bush writes of his final
meeting with Bullock before his death this year. ``He was so proud,
so eager, so convinced that I had a great chance to be the next
president. He had told friends that he looked forward to watching
me take the oath of office. Bullock, a man who had lived for years
on his sheer strength of will, realized that if it happened he
would not be there to see it. If it happens, he will have been a
huge part of making it so.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
