<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0407 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      11-15 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: SIMPLE ADJUSTMENTS FOR A FIT PREGNANCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Second of two articles on health in pregnancy) 
(The Science Times) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not so long ago, pregnant women were almost universally warned
to avoid strenuous activity. Running, cycling, skiing, horseback
riding, singles tennis _ all were off limits. Only walking had
widespread approval, and even that was to be limited to about a
mile a day, preferably broken up into several short sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But faced with women's growing interest in exercise and sports
and their desire to stay in shape while a new life takes shape
within them, doctors gave exercise during pregnancy a second look.
And to the surprise of many, medical research has shown that most
women can safely continue to exercise throughout pregnancy, as long
as they make some sensible adjustments to their routines. And for
those women who were relatively inactive before conceiving and now
wish to get in better shape before baby comes, it is even safe to
begin exercise programs during pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   There are now only a few prohibitions. Very strenuous
competitive activities are still ill-advised, as are contact
sports, scuba diving and vigorous exercise at high altitudes by
women who are not acclimated to thin air. Nowadays I regularly see
women at various stages of pregnancy jogging, walking, cycling, ice
skating, playing tennis and especially swimming. Swimming was my
own salvation during the last two hot months of a twin pregnancy
that ended at term on Aug. 28, 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is still more work to be done to address some
residual concerns about what can happen to an unborn child when the
mother engages in vigorous activities, the benefits of remaining
active or becoming active during a normal, uncomplicated pregnancy
seem clear. Active pregnant women typically report fewer
discomforts like nausea, fatigue, backaches, swelling and shortness
of breath, as well as more energy, better weight control, improved
mood and self-esteem and an easier labor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the American College of Obstetrics and Gynecology
lifted its previous limits on exercise during pregnancy and, based
on research, concluded that women with uncomplicated pregnancies
could exercise safely by taking pretty much the same precautions
recommended for women who are not pregnant. It's just that during
pregnancy it is all the more important to pay attention to
exercise-related advice.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Raul Artal, chairman of obstetrics and gynecology at the St.
Louis University School of Medicine and a fellow of the American
College of Sports Medicine, noted recently in The Physician and
Sportsmedicine, a medical magazine, that bodily changes during
pregnancy call for a certain amount of prudence. Breast growth and
abdominal expansion shift a woman's center of gravity forward,
putting an added strain on her back, and the hormonal changes of
pregnancy result in greater laxity and mobility of joints, which
can increase the risk of hip, knee or ankle injury. Those women who
experience a notable increase in joint laxity would be wise to
limit their weight-bearing activities, Artal advised.
</P>
<P>
   Two major concerns during pregnancy are getting overheated and
dehydrated. Avoid intense exertion in hot, humid weather; wear
light clothing that ``breathes''; use a small fan, if needed, to
cool down while using exercise equipment; drink plenty of plain
fluids (water, decaffeinated beverages, diluted fruit juice or
diluted sports drinks) before, during and after exercise, stay out
of saunas and steam rooms and use hot tubs and whirlpools for only
a few minutes at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Stick to moderately intense activities; you should be able to
converse while exercising. Limit workouts to 45 minutes, and stop
before you're exhausted. If exercise makes you excessively tired,
dizzy or short of breath, or causes pain (especially in the back or
pelvic area), palpitations, persistent uterine contractions,
decreased fetal movement or vaginal bleeding, stop exercising and
get medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Women with heart or lung disease should consult their physicians
before exercising during pregnancy, and according to the guidelines
established by the American College of Obstetrics and Gynecology,
some women should not exercise at all. Among them are women with
gestational hypertension, vaginal bleeding during the second and
third trimesters, premature labor during the current or a previous
pregnancy, intrauterine growth retardation, incompetent cervix,
placenta previa or premature rupture of membranes.
</P>
<P>
   For some women, an exercise program should be individually
designed and carried out with extreme caution under medical
supervision. These include women carrying two or more fetuses,
those who are excessively obese or seriously underweight and women
who have insulin-dependent diabetes, seizure disorder or anemia.
But for women with gestational diabetes _ diabetes touched off by
pregnancy _ exercise can help control the problem and is
recommended by the American Diabetes Association.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes pregnancy becomes a motivating factor for women to
start an exercise program. But women who were previously sedentary
should stick to moderate activities like walking at a comfortable
pace or activities like swimming or cycling on a stationary bike
that do not involve weight-bearing movements. For someone who is
not in shape to begin with, pregnancy is no time to start jogging
or training intensively in a new sport.
</P>
<P>
   Strength training can be done during pregnancy using light
weights with multiple repetitions. Avoid lifting or pushing against
heavy weights, which may compromise blood flow to the womb.
</P>
<P>
   Yoga, too, can be done during pregnancy, with certain
adaptations. According to Nancy Crum Stechert, a certified yoga
instructor in New Jersey, legs should always be apart and the
abdomen lifted in the various yoga positions.
</P>
<P>
   But the ideal mode of exercise, especially during the second
half of pregnancy, is in the water. Jane Katz, a champion swimmer
and swimming instructor at City University of New York and author
of ``Water Fitness During Your Pregnancy,'' (just published as a
$17.95 paperback by Human Kinetics,800-747-4457), points out that
water offers a big plus to a pregnant woman: buoyancy, which
provides support for body weight (if you weigh 120 on land, you'll
feel like only 12 pounds in the water) and ``reduces the amount of
perceived exertion for a given activity.'' In other words, you can
work harder and longer without feeling the strain, and in water you
can continue to exercise until the day your water breaks and you're
ready to give birth.
</P>
<P>
   Water workouts are also less risky to your joints and less
likely to cause overheating in warm weather. And water is relaxing
and soothing. With words and drawings, Dr. Katz's book describes
numerous water exercises and strokes suitable for pregnant women,
44 workouts in all, with modifications appropriate to the stage of
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Choose pools that are well maintained. Ideal water temperatures
are 80 to 85 degrees. Avoid water skiing and surfing. Do not dive,
jump or do strenuous wall push-offs during pregnancy. Never swim
alone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
