<HEADER>
A0409 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-SKIING-PACKAGE     11-15 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKIING-PACKAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;    Planning makes the whole ski trip perfect 
 &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)   &HT;    By Richard Irwin 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skiing is a very expensive sport. By the time you buy the fancy
new skis with microchips built in, the brilliant bindings and the
colorful, high-tech clothing, there's little money left over.
</P>
<P>
   But the beauty and freedom found in skiing is addictive, and
with a little planning you can still take that ski vacation. The
trick is to go during the shoulder seasons and to ski the
lesser-known areas.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ski packages that will get a couple out on the
slopes for $1,000 a week. While that may sound expensive, these are
legitimate values when you consider that air fare is included and
these ski resorts are some of the best in the world. In most of the
packages, you also get ski-lift tickets, which often cost $50 a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Canada continues to be a real bargain because of the excellent
exchange rate (currently just under $1.40 Canadian for $1 U.S.).
While winter might be prime time for American ski resorts, they're
off-season for places such as Banff and Lake Louise in Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these two areas are home to some of Canada's finest skiing,
with three ski mountains _ including Lake Louise, the largest ski
resort in the country. Together, the ski areas offer 218 runs on
more than 5,000 acres of terrain, serving every kind of skier from
beginner to expert.
</P>
<P>
   Horizon Air is offering a bargain package, which includes air
fare to Calgary, five nights' lodging and a three-day
interchangeable lift ticket. The cost is only $520 per person,
based on double occupancy, from Monday to Dec. 23, Jan. 3-31 and
April 24-30. (All prices are quoted in U.S. dollars.)
</P>
<P>
   Lodging is at the new Banff Caribou Lodge or the recently
renovated Banff Ptarmigan Inn. Both hotels are located in downtown
Banff, an easy walk from the town's many excellent restaurants and
shops.
</P>
<P>
   For only $100 more per person, skiers can opt to stay at
Canadian Pacific's elegant Banff Springs Hotel. This classic hotel
looks like a baron's castle nestled in the Canadian Rockies and has
been serving guests for more than a century. The grand dame has
recently been remodeled, including a marvelous new
35,000-square-foot spa called Solace.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about forking over a grand and not having any snow?
Horizon Air is guaranteeing the snow. Between Nov. 25 and Dec. 18,
the airline promises that there will be downhill skiing at the
resorts. Between Dec. 19 and April 1, it guarantees that at least
50 percent of the ski terrain will be open.
</P>
<P>
   If not, the airline will reschedule or refund the ski package.
All a skier has to do is call the snow-information line 48 hours
before departure to check the weather. For more information, call
Horizon Air Holidays at (800) 547-9308 or check its Web site at
www.horizonair.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking to ski closer to home, Daman-Nelson Travel
Inc. is offering a great package to Sun Valley, Idaho. For $445 per
person, double occupancy, the package includes round trip charter
air on Alaska Airlines to Twin Falls, charter bus to Sun Valley and
seven nights lodging at the Elkhorn Resort.
</P>
<P>
   The Elkhorn is located next to Dollar Mountain and recently
completed a thorough remodeling. Lift tickets are additional, but a
multiday ticket discount is available.
</P>
<P>
   The package is offered Jan. 15-22, Jan. 29-Feb. 5 and Feb.
19-26. For more information, call Daman-Nelson Travel at (800)
343-2626.
</P>
<P>
   If you're worried about Y2K problems, Horizon Air has come up
with some Y2K Relief ski packages to mark the new year. For $471
per person, double occupancy, the airline is offering a trip to
Montana's Big Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes round-trip air fare to Kalispell, four
nights at Grouse Mountain Lodge and a three-day lift ticket. It is
available from Jan. 6 to Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Not familiar with Big Mountain? It's one of the country's
largest ski resorts, with 67 runs and 3,000 skiable acres. Skiers
can take the gondola to the summit for fantastic views of Glacier
National Park and the Flathead Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Grouse Mountain Lodge captures the Montana spirit with
etched-glass walls in the lobby and rough ceiling timbers. The
144-room lodge sits on a golf course, which offers miles of
cross-country skiing in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   For only $70 more per person, skiers can stay at the beautiful
Kandahar Lodge, located right at the base of Big Mountain. If you
like to ski in and ski out of your lodging, this is a great place
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Canadian Rockies resorts, Horizon Air will guarantee
the snow conditions before your arrival or you will get a full
refund.
</P>
<P>
   Though it costs slightly more than our target of $1,000 per
couple, British Columbia's Whistler-Blackcomb should also be
considered. The skiing is world-class, as is the village at the
base of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   For approximately $550 per person, double occupancy, skiers can
enjoy a five-night stay with a three-day lift ticket. Visitors have
several fine hotels to choose from, with the prices varying only
$10-$20 per night.
</P>
<P>
   These bargain prices are only offered from Nov. 25 to Dec. 23.
In January, the rate rises $100 per person at this popular resort.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes nonstop air from Los Angeles to Vancouver.
Until Dec. 17, the package also includes a mountaintop breakfast
buffet with early uploading on the chair lifts.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a place closer to home, Heavenly ski resort in South
Lake Tahoe is enticing early skiers with a special package. From
Monday to Dec. 16, the package offers round-trip air, a three-day
lift ticket and three nights' lodging. The cost is $285 per person,
double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Another package covers the entire season and includes four
nights' lodging, three-day lift ticket and round-trip air. That
cost climbs to $437 per person, double occupancy. For more
information, call Heavenly at (800) 243-2836.
</P>
<P>
   Grab those skies and make your plans early. You'll be glad you
did when you're flying down the slopes with the cool, crisp air in
your face _ knowing that you didn't have to spend your last dime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
