<HEADER>
A0412 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-BEST-SPI &LR;      11-15 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO MUCH GOOD TV, THERE`S NO TIME TO GET A LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just to stay on top of the game, conscientious TV critics _ and
they all know who they are _ watch a lot of stuff they don't
necessarily like. This helps explain the times they've had to tell
loved ones they couldn't go out to Chez Chimichanga for the
free-range chicken burrito on a Friday night because they had to
stay home and watch ABC's TGIF lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this sort of diligence allows for easy differentiation
between Hilda and Zelda on ``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch.'' (I'm
still wondering why witches dress like hookers, Sabrina included.)
But it does provide a working knowledge of what's out there, and
enables us to speak semi-knowledgeably when a TV reporter from
Boston springs a pop quiz. Like George W., we may blank on who's
running Pakistan at the moment, but we sure as heck will know if
he's appearing this week on ``The Hughleys.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, there's some stuff we actually like to watch, rendering
this job easy to take at times. I'm told this makes us just like a
lot of other people, though I've never met any of them personally.
Everyone I run into claims only to watch Discovery, PBS and C-SPAN.
Never mind that they seem to know an awful lot about Joey
Tribbiani's roommate situation on ``Friends.'' (NEWS ALERT: Elle
Macpherson moved in last week.) They would have us believe they
come by this knowledge simply by hanging around their progeny, who
shouldn't be watching ``Friends'' in the first place, but that's
another column.
</P>
<P>
   This one is about the critic's worst fear: too much good stuff
on the air. Each new season usually brings two or three shows that
get added to one's personal viewing schedule. But this season there
are at least six new shows on my don't-miss list, and two or three
others I try to see as often as I can.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the upheaval in the Levesque household! When my wife
says it's time to go out and get a life, I frequently have to
respond, ``Honey, I'm working,'' and then return to the latest
episode of ``Snoops'' so I can figure out how Gina Gershon gets her
lips to do that turny-downy thing. The upside is that I'm
accumulating so much overtime I'll soon be able to upgrade to an
automobile with air bags.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this commitment to quality programming at the networks
has me looking wan these days, which is good in one sense because I
like using the word ``wan.'' It's also bad because if the bags
under my eyes get any bigger the airlines won't let me carry them
on. Then again, if I have to check them at the gate and an airline
loses them and my Mom asks what happened to the bags under my eyes,
I can say with conviction, ``The airline thinks they're in
Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   I digress. A glut of good shows can do that to one's attention
span. Else I wander off again, let's just get to my six new faves,
shall we?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, before we do that, let me first ask the networks to cut back
on the quality just a tad, OK? Otherwise, conscientious critics _
and we all know who we are _ will have no time to watch the bad
stuff, and we'll all lose respect for ourselves and end up cynical
and curmudgeonly in the old critics' rest home, and then we'll
never be able to recognize good stuff like . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesdays on ABC
</P>
<P>
   THE ATTRACTION: Wonderful acting, supremely intelligent writing
from the folks who created ``thirty-something.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HOOK: Each week gets better as Rick Sammler (Billy Campbell)
and Lily Manning (Sela Ward) appear to be less and less perfect,
and their love affair affects their exes, their kids and the other
people in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now and Again''
</P>
<P>
   Fridays on CBS
</P>
<P>
   THE ATTRACTION: A strange premise makes this show an acquired
taste, but if anyone can combine a love story and an
action/adventure show, it's Glenn Gordon Caron, who gave us
``Moonlighting'' a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOOK: An exquisite tale of forbidden love between Michael
Wiseman (Eric Close) and his ``widow,'' Lisa (Margaret Colin).
Caron's choice of John Goodman to play Wiseman in the pilot was a
stroke of genius, too. Goodman's character died, but his brain
lives on in the new Michael Wiseman, a hunky government operative
manufactured to tackle assignments that might endanger the lives of
less well-equipped agents, and ordered to have no contact with his
family. Brilliant tongue-in-cheek escapism on a Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesdays on NBC
</P>
<P>
   THE ATTRACTION: Aaron Sorkin, creator of ``Sports Night,''
imbues this drama with the same crackling dialogue, the same
breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOOK: Some Beltway insiders panned ``West Wing'' because
they say the White House is a place of reverence where staffers
rarely speak above a whisper. Now that would be a boffo show, no? A
drop-dead cast makes Sorkin's busy, buzzy White House the most
interesting workplace of the season. And fuggedabout Warren Beatty
for prez. Martin Sheen is the man!
</P>
<P>
   ``Roswell''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesdays on The WB
</P>
<P>
   THE ATTRACTION: ``Roswell'' is yet another WB show about high
school kids, but Jason Katims, creator of ``Relativity,'' gives it
a more adult slant without losing the teen angst.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOOK: She's a local girl. He's from another state. Of mind.
It's the Next ``X-Files,'' a beautiful take on the
mismatched-lovers story, with a touch of ``The Fugitive'' and just
the right measure of sci-fi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaks and Geeks''
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays on NBC
</P>
<P>
   THE ATTRACTION: A look at high school as most of us probably
lived it.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOOK: A sly willingness to go against the
political-correctness grain; a cast that looks as if it just got
out of homeroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snoops''
</P>
<P>
   Sundays on ABC
</P>
<P>
   THE ATTRACTION: Paula Marshall, who never got a chance to shine
in ``Cupid'' last season.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOOK: I'm as surprised as you. Thought this would be David
E. Kelley's first failure. Not as fluffy as first advertised, it's
a guilty pleasure, but also a compatible lead-in to ``The
Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides these six, I also try to catch ``Third Watch,''
``Angel'' and ``Action'' as often as humanly possible. But,
frankly, I'm exhausted. Memo to networks: This quality thing is
killing me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
