<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LEONID-METEORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORECAST TOMORROW: SHOWERS OF METEORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ala., Calif.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a slugger given a second chance after a disappointing
season, the Leonid meteor shower is back again this week, ready to
take another swat at Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Experts are forecasting that the shower, which occurs when Earth
travels through a plume of dust particles from the comet
Tempel-Tuttle, may provide quite a show in some parts of the world,
with 1,000 to 1,500 meteors per hour arcing through the sky late
Wednesday and early Thursday. That would be better than 1998, when
at the peaks there were only 250 to 300 meteors per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's results were particularly disappointing as many
astronomers had predicted that the event could rival that of 1966,
when by some estimates 15,000 to 50,000 meteors per hour were seen.
Experts are staying away from such extravagant predictions this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the estimates are tempered a little bit,'' said Dr.
Jeffrey Anderson, an engineer at NASA's Marshall Space Flight
Center, in Huntsville, Ala. The center is forecasting a rate of
1,500 meteors an hour, given ideal viewing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting the shower's intensity is an inexact science,
Anderson said. ``We know where the comet is,'' he said. ``But we
don't have any direct observational evidence of where the tail and
the dust streams are until we pass through them.''
</P>
<P>
   The best viewing sites are expected to be in Eastern Europe,
where the peak shower should occur early in the morning. But the
timing is also difficult to predict, as demonstrated last year,
when an additional peak occurred about 12 hours earlier than the
forecast one. So meteor watchers may lose a lot of sleep, staying
up into the early hours of both Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the predicted peak will occur before
midnight Wednesday, when viewing is not at its best. Still, given
good weather, some meteors should be viewable, to the east. And
some experts say there may be a second peak about 4 a.m. Thursday,
Eastern time, when the moon will have set and viewing conditions
should be better.
</P>
<P>
   The Leonids, so named because they appear to originate from the
constellation Leo, occur every year in November. But they put on a
good show only every 33 years or so, when Earth crosses
Tempel-Tuttle's orbit through plumes of particles boiled off the
comet during close approaches to the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Because the comet orbits the Sun in a direction opposite that of
Earth, the meteors are faster-moving than most others, striking
Earth's upper atmosphere at more than 150,000 miles an hour. While
the particles pose no danger to people, burning up long before
reaching the ground, they have the potential to damage satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Amid last year's predictions of a spectacular sky show came dire
warnings that telecommunications and other systems that depend on
satellites could be interrupted. Although the risk of a collision
was considered relatively small, satellite operators took no
chances, shutting down many electrical systems and orienting
spacecraft so that solar panels and other critical components were
edge-on to the storm. No satellites were disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Operators are ``safing'' spacecraft again this year, said Dr.
Glenn D. Anderson of the Aerospace Corp., a company in Los Angeles
that advises the military and private space contractors. But things
are a bit more calm. ``It's not a panic-type situation,'' he said.
``But people are aware of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1633EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
