<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-CYPRUS-1116-C     11-15 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CYPRUS-1116-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QUAKES PROVIDE CRACK FOR GREEK, TURKISH TALKS ON LONG-STANDING
CYPRUS ISSUE
 &HT;    With CLINTON-TURKEY-1116.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey _ It was ``ping-pong'' diplomacy that brought the
United States and China together three decades ago. The quest for
Mideast peace gave rise to ``shuttle diplomacy.'' And ``baseball
diplomacy'' has provided a tenuous link between the United States
and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Now ``earthquake diplomacy'' has opened a window for Greece and
Turkey to try to settle their 35-year-old dispute over the island
republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already seen some manifestation of that,'' said
President Clinton, who goes Tuesday to visit Ezmit, epicenter of an
August quake that killed 17,000 Turks and left another 400,000
homeless. ``I think it's a mood, an atmosphere that needs to be
acted upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey was rocked by another quake Nov. 12. Neighboring Greece
suffered its own serious quake in September.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries responded by dispatching emergency aid crews to
the other. Private citizens on both sides of the Greece-Turkey
divide stepped forward to send money to aid those suffering in the
rival states.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists from both countries write that the outpouring of aid
across the troubled Aegean Sea has shown that politicians in Athens
and Ankara have fallen badly out of step with their people on the
subject of trans-Aegean detente.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence then, said Clinton, that leaders of the
competing Greek and Turkish communities on Cyprus agreed just this
week to sit down in New York on Dec. 3 to try to re-start
long-stalled talks over a dispute that has divided their countries
since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the improved relations between Turkey and Greece over
the so-called 'earthquake diplomacy' and interchange,'' Clinton
told reporters en route here aboard Air Force One on Sunday. ``I
think the people of both countries, and, therefore, the political
leaders of both countries, saw each other with fresh eyes in the
agonies of the earthquakes.''
</P>
<P>
   In brokering disputes among foes, the essence of diplomacy is
often the search for common ground, even, as events in Greece and
Turkey show, shaky ground.
</P>
<P>
   It was a series of U.S.-China table tennis games, after all,
that provided a backdrop for President Richard Nixon's secret talks
with China during the early 1970s, in what became known as
``ping-pong diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The wooing of Cuban baseball stars to American teams has helped
opened a crack in the wall that has separated Havana from
Washington for four decades.
</P>
<P>
   And the hundreds of trips U.S. diplomats have made between the
State Department and the fractious Mideast over the past 20 years
has given rise to the term ``shuttle diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, said Clinton, tragic though the earthquakes have been
for thousands of Greeks and Turks, there may yet be a diplomatic
silver lining to the disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person who lost a loved one or a home to those
earthquakes knows that there was no such thing then as a Turkish or
a Greek tragedy,'' Clinton said Monday in a speech to the Turkish
parliament. ``They were human tragedies, and the world will never
forget the humanity each nation displayed toward the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has provided $14.5 million in humanitarian aid
to Turkey's earthquake victims, in addition to extensive military
assistance. On Monday, Clinton said the United States would also
offer up to $1 billion in private loan guarantees for private
reconstruction efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
