</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TURKEY-1116-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CHIDES TURKEY ON HUMAN RIGHTS, PLEDGES TO HELP IT MOVE
FORWARD
 &HT;    With CLINTON-CYPRUS-1116.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey _ President Clinton assailed Turkey's poor human
rights record Monday as a drag on its integration as a full partner
with the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future we want to build together begins with Turkish
progress in deepening democracy at home,'' Clinton said, in the
first speech ever given by a U.S. president to Turkey's parliament,
the Grand General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sovereignty,'' he said, ``should not be built on fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, however, aware of this country's growing
strategic value at the crossroads of Europe and Central Asia,
leavened his criticism with praise for Turkey's recent progress on
human rights. He was scheduled to go Wednesday to the city of
Ephesus, one time home of the Christian disciple John and the
mother of Jesus, the Virgin Mary, to spotlight the Christian
traditions and religious tolerance in a country that is 98 percent
Moslem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are encouraged,'' Clinton said, ``that the human rights
issue is moving in the right direction in this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's president, though, Suleyman Demirel, bluntly
acknowledged continuing troubles in Turkey. The U.S. State
Department accuses the Turkish government of widespread abuses,
including beatings and killings of detainees as well as
intimidation of journalists, human rights advocates and some
political dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Demirel said the government is taking measures to address those
ills, specifically through new laws aimed at rooting out and
punishing officials who torture detainees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to say that there is no torture in Turkey;
there is torture,'' Demirel told reporters in a joint news
conference with Clinton. ``But torture is not state policy. Torture
is
</P>
<P>
   a crime. And whoever commits this crime, no matter who that
person may be, that person is investigated and is penalized
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rights groups, including the London-based Amnesty International,
counter that Turkey has not only failed to prosecute officials who
torture detainees but that it has tolerated threats against
citizens who speak out against such crimes.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Clinton accented the growing U.S. stakes in
its relationship with Turkey, a NATO ally that has become the
geographical and strategic fulcrum to a host of American priorities
since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, a country of 65.5 million people, has emerged as a key
partner in a broad range of U.S. aims. Those include U.S. efforts
to:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  tap into the oil riches of the nearby Caspian Sea;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  build peace in the Balkans;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  resolve long-standing disputes in the Middle East and on
island of Cyprus;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  contain neighboring Iraq;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  help manage the economic and political transition underway
across the former Soviet Union
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  counter terrorism;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  combat the global drug trade;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and bridge the gulf between the Islamic world and the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these areas and more,'' Clinton said, ``Turkey and the
United States should be partners.''
</P>
<P>
   He thanked Turkey for providing a base for American warplanes
that patrol the no-fly zone of northern Iraq. And he pledged to
lobby for Turkey's stalled membership request in the economically
powerful European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The president also pledged to help Turkey recover from
earthquakes that killed more than 450 people Friday, on the heels
of a quake that claimed more than 17,000 lives in August. On
Tuesday, he will visit an area 60 miles east of Istanbul where U.S.
Marines set up tents to house people made homeless by the first
quake.
</P>
<P>
   He was scheduled to go to Istanbul on Tuesday, where he will
meet with 53 of his counterparts at the annual summit of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
   He is in the region on a 10-day swing that will take him to
Athens, Greece and Florence, Italy later in the week. He continues
on to Bulgaria and Kosovo next week, before returning to Washington
by Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
