<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astigmatism and Art
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is astigmatism and did it affect the work of El Greco?
</P>
<P>
   A. Astigmatism results from a misshapen cornea, the clear front
covering of the eye. A normal cornea has a smooth, round curve. In
astigmatism, the curve is elongated and greater in one direction
than in another, and the shape is often described as bulging, like
a football, rather than circular, like a basketball.
</P>
<P>
   When light rays pass through such a cornea, they are not
refracted, or bent, equally in all directions, and they are focused
on several points on the retina, rather than on one point. Vision
is distorted for both nearby and faraway objects, and what is seen
may be blurred or distorted.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery is one option for correcting astigmatism. In a procedure
called astigmatic keratotomy, incisions are made in a curved
pattern to reshape the cornea. In photorefractive keratectomy, a
laser reshapes the surface.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is probable that neither one would have changed how
El Greco painted. The theory that he was astigmatic was advanced in
1913, but scientists now believe that the elongated shapes in his
paintings were deliberate, rather than the result either of faulty
vision or lenses used to correct it.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays show more realistic drawings under his final paintings,
and there is no evidence that corrective lenses for astigmatism,
which might have produced elongated images in one direction, were
available to him in the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York,
N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
