<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0445 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PRESCRIPTIONS-NYT     11-15 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PRESCRIPTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKE TWO AFTER DINNER AND CALL ME IN THE MORNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I headed into the waiting room at 2:19 the other afternoon,
my 2:20 patient had disappeared. I knew he would be back in a
minute or two, windblown and smelling of cigarette smoke,
sheepishly tossing a crumpled pack into the trash.
</P>
<P>
   Our visits follow a depressing pattern. The only thing ever
bothering him is a cough. He has asthma and recurrent bronchitis,
admits to a pack a day, probably smokes more, and is frank about
his current plans to quit: he has none. He is too stressed to try
any more. As for cutting down: ditto.
</P>
<P>
   I renewed his prescriptions for three inhalers, two blood
pressure drugs and a bottle of cough medicine. He folded them into
his breast pocket, right next to an unopened pack of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The temptation at moments like this is to wish that a higher
authority would just take over the case. And as it happens, a very
high authority is showing a smidgen of interest in my 2:20: among
the cases on the Supreme Court's docket this fall is the question
of whether the Food and Drug Administration has the authority to
regulate tobacco the same way it does other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   I fantasized for a moment about a world where the unimpeachable
logic of the FDA came to prevail on drugstore shelves. Tobacco
products would be treated exactly like the drugs they are, no more
and no less. And, in such an orderly universe I might at that very
moment be facing the decision of whether or not to add a
prescription for menthol 100's to my patient's stack.
</P>
<P>
   Any self-respecting purveyor of health should probably be
champing at the bit for the right to make that decision. With no
more effort than a smile and a shake of the head I could get rid of
my patient's cough. Within a decade or so his risk of other
smoking-related problems would fall as low as if he had never
smoked at all.
</P>
<P>
   Multiply him by the 48 million adult smokers in the United
States, and the result would be one of the biggest health
revolutions in history.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to higher authorities, though, a revolution
by prescription is one I might just as soon sit out.
</P>
<P>
   Saving people from themselves is a tricky business, especially
when prescriptions are the means to the end. This is a lesson that
sinks in only slowly after medical school. Young doctors think
their prescriptions are sacrosanct, little pieces of delivered
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually they discover their prescriptions are just little
pieces of paper. Just because you write people prescriptions
doesn't mean they will take the medications. Just because you
withhold prescriptions doesn't mean they won't. The hoary and jaded
among us know that a prescription is really only a suggestion, a
word of friendly advice, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   My 2:20 patient is a 45-year-old man with no misconceptions
about his situation. He knows he is puffing away little pieces of
his future. He also knows that to survive his present, juggling an
unpleasant job, an iffy marriage and a set of relatives whose
various misbehaviors have him in an unending state of turmoil and
grief, he needs to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Had he more time, more money, or fewer relatives, he might
change his mind. Perhaps in a few years he will. As things stand
now, though, were he and I suddenly catapulted off into a future of
regulated tobacco products, we would both face a cascade of
unappealing choices.
</P>
<P>
   I could choose the clear insanity of treating his bronchitis and
sponsoring his smoking at the same time, with prescriptions for
three inhalers and 60 packs to last the month.
</P>
<P>
   I could choose the medically correct but remarkably cruel
extreme, cutting him off cold turkey with a shrug and a promise
that he will feel much better in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   I could choose the middle ground of slowly tapering his dose of
tobacco despite his enunciated lack of interest in such a plan.
Would he bend to the inevitable and cut down, I wonder, or would he
head for another doctor?
</P>
<P>
   Or would he run out of prescription cigarettes midmonth and head
out to the black market for more? Or would he possibly decide to
stake out a corner of that market for himself, selling out his
wares and begging a new prescription because he left the old one on
the train? Would he sell to adults, or to kids too? Would I ever
catch on?
</P>
<P>
   It's a fantasy for cigarettes, but real enough for the real
prescription drugs. Most unused medication stays in medicine
cabinets, but quite a bit finds its way to the friends and
relatives of the first owners, and quite a bit more to the black
market for prescription drugs that flourishes in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Medications are as tightly regulated here as anywhere in the
world, but even so, with the right friends, almost any pill you
want can be yours.
</P>
<P>
   A prescription pad of mine vanished a few years ago, and I had
the eerie experience, several months later, of looking at a forged
prescription faxed over by an intuitive pharmacist. It was filled
out for an antibiotic: right dose, right quantity, and right
signature in the very wrong handwriting. That was the last I ever
heard of my pad. Maybe some of the other medications it suggested
actually helped someone out.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that even if the Supreme Court upholds the FDA's
right to regulate tobacco, not much is likely to change for adults
like my patient. What the agency really wants is to keep children
and teenagers away from their first cigarettes. It long ago
acknowledged its limits in steering adults away from their
millionth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency recognizes the need for cigarettes and smokeless
tobacco products to remain available to adults,'' Dr. David A.
Kessler, the former FDA commissioner, wrote at the start of this
cycle of regulatory efforts in 1995. ``The potential disruption to
society resulting from the elimination of tobacco products would be
great, and therefore FDA does not intend to remove them from the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   That must be one of the saddest admissions of defeat ever logged
in medical history. But until we accumulate a little more wisdom in
managing the ties between human beings and the substances they
love, perhaps it is the only possible choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
