<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0449 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      11-15 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT RISK: In Heated Heroin, a Dangerous Dragon
</P>
<P>
   Heroin users trying to avoid infected needles have turned in
increasing numbers in recent years to ``chasing the dragon'':
heating the drug and inhaling its fumes. But that method can cause
a rare brain disorder that can in turn cause paralysis and even
death, according to Columbia University neurologists.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors, writing in the journal Neurology, reported the case
of a 21-year-old Manhattan woman who was brought to
Columbia-Presbyterian ``nearly at death's door, unable to talk or
move,'' Dr. Arnold Kriegstein, a neurologist who treated her, said
in an interview. When her sister said the woman had been ``chasing
the dragon'' every day for two weeks, Kriegstein and his colleagues
were reminded of an outbreak of the brain disorder, spongiform
leukoencephalopathy, that had killed 11 heroin users in Amsterdam
years before.
</P>
<P>
   The disease produces a spongelike pattern of fluid-filled holes
in the deep layers of the brain tissue known as white matter.
</P>
<P>
   Because the condition can be caused by a variety of toxins, and
because in the Amsterdam outbreak people who injected or sniffed
heroin from the same batches were unaffected, researchers speculate
that the culprit is a contaminant that adds its vapor to the heroin
plume when heated. After the woman was admitted, her boyfriend came
in for treatment, suffering from severe difficulties speaking and
talking. Another man who had shared a small amount of their
apparently tainted heroin agreed to be examined, and was found to
have subtle movement dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   There is no known treatment for spongiform leukoencephalopathy,
Kriegstein said, and those patients who survive have usually
suffered permanent brain damage. But because her doctors found high
levels of lactic acid in the woman's white matter _ a sign of
metabolic disruption _ they gave her large doses of vitamin E,
vitamin C and coenzyme Q, antioxidants that can help restore
cellular function.
</P>
<P>
   She gradually improved, and left the hospital after two months.
Now, three years later, she is nearly normal, said Kriegstein.
``She walks, runs, rides a bicycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Kriegstein is a long way, however, from calling the treatment a
cure. The boyfriend received similar treatment, but had to be
hospitalized again after he returned to heroin use. He was left
with some permanent motor difficulties. The third man never
returned for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION: Craving Kale? A Study Explains Why
</P>
<P>
   Here's another benefit of getting older: vegetables taste
better.
</P>
<P>
   That's because sensitivity to bitterness declines with age, a
University of Washington study has concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, presented at an Agriculture Department conference
this month, 329 women ages 21 to 84 were tested for their responses
to a bitter medicine and asked what foods they enjoyed and what
they actually ate. The younger the woman, the stronger the reaction
to the medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Older women reported an increasing preference for green
vegetables, whole grain foods, bitter fruits like grapefruits and
lemons and drinks like coffee and tea. ``Age was the best predictor
of healthy diets,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   UPDATE: Cardiologists Share the Latest Wisdom
</P>
<P>
   Cardiologists got together in Atlanta last week for the annual
meeting of the American Heart Association. Here's a sampling of the
studies presented:
</P>
<P>
   _People who take aspirin for the heart's health may be asked to
take Tylenol as well someday. A Baylor medical school study of
rabbits on high-fat diets found that those also given
acetaminophen, the chemical in Tylenol, developed less of the fatty
streaking in their arteries. The streaking can be a precursor to
clogging.
</P>
<P>
   _Orange juice could be good, too. In a study by the University
of Western Ontario, financed in part by Tropicana, 25 men and women
with moderately high cholesterol levels had those levels improved
after they drank three glasses of orange juice a day for a month.
</P>
<P>
   _When a man has a heart attack, his wife should think about
changing her habits. Because couples generally eat the same foods
and often share habits, like smoking or being sedentary, they can
also share the risk factors for cardiac disease. A University of
Nebraska study of 170 men recovering from heart attacks found that
their wives had similar or higher risk factors like high
cholesterol levels and body-mass indexes, but were not getting the
same kind of screening and counseling.
</P>
<P>
   _Impotence does not usually lead men to think about their
hearts, but it should, said a researcher from the Minneapolis Heart
Institute Foundation. Because the blood vessels in the penis are
narrower than in other parts of the body, clogging of the arteries
can lead to impotence before symptoms of heart disease are
apparent. In a study of 50 impotent men, 20 were found to have
asymptomatic blockages of their coronary arteries. So men suffering
from this condition should ask their doctors about more than
impotence treatments, the researcher said.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE LAB: Treadmill Regimen Yields Smarter Mice
</P>
<P>
   Salk Institute researchers have found that, at least in mice,
what the body does can shape the brain's development and enhance
memory and learning.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published this month in Proceedings of the National
Academy of Sciences, Dr. Fred H. Gage and his colleagues at Salk,
in La Jolla, Calif., compared mice allowed to run freely on an
exercise wheel with a genetically identical group of sedentary
mice. After six weeks, the two groups of mice were placed in a
series of mazes. In the easy ones, all the mice performed well. But
when the test was made more difficult, only the runners were able
to perform; the sedentary mice were unable to master the task.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also found that running had increased the number
of cells in only one area of the brain, the hippocampus, a deep
structure that plays an important role in learning and memory.
</P>
<P>
   What was more surprising was that when they looked for the
biochemical changes that indicate memory formation, they found them
only in the area where the new cells had been formed. ``In other
words,'' said Gage, ``the changes were not global, but were highly
specific for one region of the brain. So we're pretty sure that the
new cells are responsible for the improved performance in these
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Gage, who with colleagues turned neural science upside down last
year by reporting that the human brain continues to generate new
cells in adulthood, cautioned against generalizing his results to
humans. ``We know that there are cells that divide in the brain,''
he said. ``Now we know that what the organism does affects the
number of cells, and that these cells in turn influence behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: When Patrons Have a Few Too Many
</P>
<P>
   How can a staggering drunk get a bartender to keep serving him?
Usually he just asks, say researchers looking for ways to limit
alcohol-related injuries and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In two studies at the University of Minnesota, researchers hired
actors to feign severe intoxication and see what happened when they
tried to buy drinks. The findings were presented last week at a
meeting of the American Public Health Association in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In the study's first phase, the actors _ scented with whiskey,
clothes rumpled, weaving slightly _ made 68 visits to 24 bars. They
were turned away 5 times. Once inside, each staggered to a bar
stool, asked confused questions in slurred speech and ordered a
double vodka. They were turned down 20 times and served 43 times.
</P>
<P>
   If given a drink, the actor lurched off to the men's room,
losing the drink along the way, and ordered another double vodka
within five minutes. They were served 23 times and refused 20
times.
</P>
<P>
   The study's second phase extended the trial to 336 bars,
restaurants, liquor stores and grocery stores: 79 percent of the
businesses sold alcohol to the pseudodrunks.
</P>
<P>
   When the bartenders did rebuff requests, they usually did so
without explanation or with comments on the actors' inebriation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
