<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0450 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      11-15 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pill, for Crustaceans
</P>
<P>
   The marine food chain seems so basic. Little things are eaten by
bigger things, which in turn are eaten by bigger things, which are
eaten by still bigger things, until the catch of the day ends up on
a dinner plate.
</P>
<P>
   A nice concept, but like so much in life, not as straightforward
as it might appear. Take the relationship between diatoms,
single-celled algae that are a large component of plankton, and the
tiny crustaceans known as copepods that feed on them.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a simple case of the more the merrier, of copepods
getting fat and happy when they gorge on diatoms. Rather, as
Italian scientists report in the journal Nature, chemicals in the
algae can act like a birth control pill, sharply reducing the
number of copepod eggs that hatch.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, studying copepods in the northern Adriatic Sea,
showed that as few as 12 percent of eggs hatched during blooms of
diatoms that occur over several weeks each winter. During times of
more normal diatom concentration, as many as 90 percent of eggs
hatched.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers point out that copepods reproduce successfully
when they dine on other plankton that contain powerful neurotoxins.
They suggest that the crustaceans have developed a defense system
against these poisons but have been far slower to evolve a means of
coping with a toxin that affects the developing embryo.
</P>
<P>
   The Complexities of Dirt
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the food chain is not so simple, but here is something
that is: dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again. As any gardener knows, soil has structure, due
largely to the presence of decaying organic matter, or humus.
Scientists know that this structure is highly complex, and that the
shape of humic substances (the organic electrolytes resulting from
decay) can affect how well soil retains carbon (which can be used
by plants) and pollutants or pesticides. A denser, coiled shape has
some advantages over a looser, elongated structure.
</P>
<P>
   It had been assumed that coiled structures were formed under
acidic conditions, and elongated structures under alkaline. But a
research team, using an X-ray microscope at Lawrence Berkeley
National Laboratory to perform a kind of high-tech soil analysis,
has shown that things are even more complicated than that.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in the journal Science, show that the
structure of these substances depends on a variety of other
factors, including whether they formed in soil or in river water,
and the chemical and mineral makeup of the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Doomsday Beanbags
</P>
<P>
   When scientists got a look at photos of Mathilde, an asteroid
encountered by the Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous spacecraft in
1997, they were puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   The asteroid, about 30 miles in diameter, had several large
craters, presumably a result of collisions with other objects. But
unlike similar craters on the Moon, Mathilde's have no rims or
debris, signs that material was ejected when it was struck.
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing researcher and colleagues, writing in Nature, suggest
why this is so. Rather than being solid rock, Mathilde is probably
a rubble pile, a porous agglomeration of smaller rocks. When struck
by an object, the asteroid's low density causes material to be
compacted, not ejected. The effect is something like punching a
beanbag chair.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who developed the theory after conducting
simulation experiments in which they fired projectiles at samples
of porous material, say it could explain why material from porous
asteroids seldom reaches Earth in the form of meteorites.
</P>
<P>
   It might also mean bad news for those who are thinking about
ways to save Earth if a large asteroid is ever found to be on a
collision course with the planet. Current thinking is that such a
doomsday rock could be diverted by a huge explosive device,
delivered by a rocket. But the new theory suggests that some
asteroids might be able to absorb the blow and just keep coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
