r e BC-ANCHOR-BATTLES-TEX     11-15 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANCHOR-BATTLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO-COMPETE CONTRACTS CAN PLAY HAVOC WITH TELEVISION NEWS ANCHORS
</HEADLINE>
 (Texas points ATTN) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tracy Rowlett is a talker by trade, a connoisseur of words and
oral prose, of high-minded phrases and playful puns. When he talks
of communication between anchor and viewer, and this he does a lot,
what he really means is connecting, which makes one wonder if he's
feeling a sense of disconnection about now.
</P>
<P>
   It's Day 224 since Rowlett, 56, last delivered the news from
behind the anchor desk of Dallas-Fort Worth's No. 1 television news
operation at WFAA-TV. To better understand his recent frustration,
imagine doing a job you love dearly nearly every day for 25 years.
Now imagine it's gone.
</P>
<P>
   At least now he takes comfort in knowing that the end _ and
beginning _ is near.
</P>
<P>
   Rowlett will make his first appearance at his new on-air home,
KTVT, at the stroke of midnight Jan. 1, anchoring the station's
special Y2K coverage, injecting the local TV news race with a shot
of fresh competition from an old face.
</P>
<P>
   Rowlett will officially end this waiting game, which dates back
to April 6 when he signed off from WFAA, leaving for vacation,
never to return after a bitter contract dispute. His disagreements
with the ABC network affiliate have been well chronicled in the
print media and not necessarily in favor of his former employer,
depicted as The Evil Empire. It hasn't helped balance the public
opinion scales that WFAA executives declined to comment for this
story and others.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Rowlett said, the decision to leave ``wasn't about
money. It was merely about a fair contract. Contracts, you must
remember, are written to the benefit of the company. And they
insisted on contracts, on non-competes, and so forth. And all I was
asking for was just that they wouldn't fire me without cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Which sounds simple enough. But the phrase ``without cause''
turned out to be the unyielding bone of contention on both sides.
WFAA wanted the freedom to fire for any reason, like failing to
attract key age demographics, such as young viewers. Pushing 60,
Rowlett saw it as career suicide.
</P>
<P>
   And economic suicide, too, since his major financial motivation
in what could be the last decade of his career was to sock away
enough money to make certain that his 13-year-old son, Michael, is
taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   Born severely autistic, Michael ``will never ever be able to
earn a dime on his own,'' Rowlett said. ``I need to make enough
money so that I can support him for the rest of his life. So I just
couldn't let them do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Which makes Rowlett's loyalty to WFAA even more astounding. He
was willing to remain at the station with a four-year contract at
no major salary increase _ but without the standard clothing
allowance; in effect, a decrease in salary _ if WFAA had merely
agreed to his wishes about the ``without cause'' clause.
</P>
<P>
   When WFAA General Manager Kathy Clements-Hill returned with what
would be the station's final offer, it was a four-year deal with a
slight bump in salary where the ``without cause'' stipulation was
taken out the first two years, to be reinserted for the final two.
It made Rowlett wonder if they had plans to send him out to
pasture, particularly if his ratings softened.
</P>
<P>
   With NBC-owned KXAS also in the hunt for Rowlett, CBS-owned KTVT
had the quicker draw, going to the network and returning with a
reported $1 million annual salary over seven years. Nowhere is
there a ``without cause'' clause.
</P>
<P>
   Ties severed, this set up the legal fight over the validity of
non-compete clauses. WFAA wanted Rowlett to stay off the air until
July, which would have stretched his wait to 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terribly frustrating and disappointing,'' Rowlett said.
``I didn't expect them to be turning cartwheels about this. I
understand that it's a business. But at the same time, I consider
upper management at Belo (WFAA's parent company) to be friends of
mine. At least they would treat me respectfully and with some
degree of compassion. But I felt they were taking a very punitive
stance. We had no choice but to file the lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a court-appointed arbitrator to rule whether a
non-compete clause, a station-protection device preventing Rowlett
from starting at a competing station until July of next year, was
binding. The compromise struck was that he could appear on-air in
January, which means that until then the Rowlett voice couldn't be
heard on any airwaves in Fort Worth-Dallas; nor could his image be
in any way connected to KTVT. (The ruling is so specific that we
couldn't conduct an interview with Rowlett or take photos of him at
WFAA, and executives there ``went ballistic,'' Rowlett said, when,
during a recent live report from the KTVT Dallas studio, he nearly
walked into the camera shot by accident.)
</P>
<P>
   There was verbal mud-slinging between Rowlett and Clements-Hill
in the print media. There was a purchase of KTVT by CBS followed by
a housecleaning that included the firing of some 60 staffers, three
of them on-air personnel. (Rowlett characterizes this as a ``body
count,'' a way to streamline KTVT to the staff size of CBS stations
in comparable markets.)
</P>
<P>
   Now it's down to business. Rowlett is in the odd position of
fighting the station he helped build to national prominence. Those
who say Rowlett doesn't stand a chance in turning around the
fortunes at KTVT should note that WFAA was ranked a distant third
in the market before he signed on as anchor in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Still, KTVT is not only the fourth horse in a five-horse race,
but its newscast has a reputation for using sensational stories and
animated, giggly anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I`ve been in this business too long to think that any one
person can turn around a news station,'' Rowlett said. ``It takes a
team effort. We have good executive producers, a good news director
and reporters. So it's a matter of everyone getting on the same
page.''
</P>
<P>
   KTVT has talent, such as co-anchor Karen Borta, reporter Steve
Pickett and reporter/anchor Rene Syler. And since August, Rowlett
has been the station's hands-on managing editor, working directly
with reporters on their writing and story development. Knowing that
the station must change from top to bottom, he wants to establish a
tone and mood for the station's on-air style, to give it a cleaner,
more cerebral look and approach. He's stressing the kind of
enterprise stories that come from basic, hit-the-pavement
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give people good newscasts that are well paced and
have substance to them,'' he said. ``That alone changes the mood of
the broadcast. If people today tell us they're fed up with
sensationalism in broadcast news, and they trust us as journalists
less each day, then it behooves us to listen to them and put on a
product that is responsive. There's nothing fancy here. No
gimmicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowlett said he's not overly dismayed at where KTVT currently
sits in the market. ``I've been here long enough that I can see the
potential. I feel we can be competitive, and to be competitive, I
don't mean that Channel 11 has to march up to No. 1 in the next
year or so. I don't think that's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can't sit back forever and say, `Isn't it great we're
out there trying?' We'll have to have some success. And we will.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
