<HEADER>
A0463 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SLEEPING-WITH-BABY-TW     11-15 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPING-WITH-BABY-TWOTAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPING WITH THE BABY IS A HOT BED OF DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a simple question: When it's time each night for new
parents to get some much-needed shut-eye, is it OK to bring baby
into the bed?
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a simple answer. The family bed is, in fact, a
hotbed of discussion among health and mental-health experts,
government officials and parents.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the debate are pediatricians and child
psychologists who argue that co-sleeping, as the practice is
called, is a bad idea, fostering a range of emotional problems and
physical risks for children. The most recent and serious criticism
of the family bed came in late September when the federal Consumer
Product Safety Commission issued a warning to parents not to allow
children under age 2 to sleep in their beds. Co-sleeping, the
commission said, increased the risk of infant death.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the issue are, again, more pediatricians
and child psychologists _ and parents _ who won't roll over and
accept the commission's statement. These experts argue that the
family bed is not only safe but also helps babies develop a sense
of trust, intimacy and self-assuredness. Foremost among these
family bed proponents is University of Notre Dame anthropologist
James McKenna, who this week will discuss his 18 years of research
on mother/baby sleep patterns at the annual meeting of the American
Anthropological Association in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is often theoretical, sometimes statistical and at
times overly personal. But it's a discussion with practical
implications for every new parent who simply wants to do what's
best for baby. Whatever that may be.
</P>
<P>
   BAN THE BABY
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission's September statement
reignited family bed debate because of the link it proclaimed
between co-sleeping and infant deaths. The commission based its
findings on a study of infant deaths from 1990 to 1997. During that
time, 515 children died while sleeping in their parents' beds. In
121 of those deaths, a parent _ or another child in the bed _
accidentally smothered the child. The other 394 deaths occurred
when the children became trapped in the bed structure or were
suffocated by bedding.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Melissa Garretson, a pediatrician with the Fort Worth-based
Cook Children's Medical Center network, agrees with the
commission's warning. She says she urges all new parents to
establish separate sleeping areas for their baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have them in a separate bed for risk of
suffocation,'' Garretson says.
</P>
<P>
   Besides obstruction of air passages, Garretson says, it's
possible for babies to rebreathe their own air and be unable to
lift their heads on a soft mattress designed for adults.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to physical risks, those who oppose the family bed
point to developmental problems, such as separation anxiety and
lifelong dependence, that can result in children who are raised
sharing a bed with their parents. Garretson also says that parents
invite bad habits in a shared bed by waking up and responding to
everything the baby does, and offers this argument: If every time
you made a noise during the night, your favorite person woke up and
held you and comforted you, ``why would you sleep through the
night?''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bed, Garretson says, babies break that habit of
waking up. ``Usually you have a baby who learns how to self-calm
and learns to sleep all night, and everybody gets a good night's
sleep,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   BRING THE BABY IN
</P>
<P>
   Jenny and John McAllister of Arlington, Texas, are the parents
of two children: Matt is 2 years old and Jake is about 3 months
old. The McAllisters didn't intend to have a family bed, but when
their first child was born, it just happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a few nights of trying to do the crib thing, we decided
this was easier,'' Jenny said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband were concerned about the possible problems
associated with co-sleeping, ``but for us it was more comforting to
have (Matt) close at hand,'' she says. ``We were able to get him
back to sleep quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   The safety commission's September warning didn't worry her,
McAllister said; it just made her look again to be sure they were
taking all the necessary precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common sense is the biggest key to making co-sleeping work,''
McAllister said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she feels her child is safe in the family bed, and she
and her husband are making an informed decision, knowing the risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (co-sleeping) is wonderful,'' she said. ``We did what
felt the most natural and the most right and what seemed to work
for our son the best.''
</P>
<P>
   For many families, the family bed does seem to work best. One
1988 study of sleep habits in New York and Cleveland showed that 19
percent of Anglo families, 59 percent of black families and 26
percent of Hispanic families practiced co-sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the United States, the family bed is even more common.
In Japan and other Eastern countries, co-sleeping is the norm _ in
fact, according to the Couple to Couple League, a Catholic group
that studies family planning and fertility, children sleep with
their mothers in 90 percent of cultures around the world.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna, the Notre Dame anthropologist, is one of co-sleeping's
most vocal proponents. His studies of mother/baby sleep patterns
show that co-sleeping babies cry less, sleep more and are often
placed in safer positions when they sleep.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna has spoken out against the warnings issued against
bed-sharing, saying they're not based on science and make parents
who want to sleep with their children feel guilty unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Another group supports co-sleeping for quite different reasons.
Mary Kouba and her husband are coordinators of the North Texas
chapter of the Couple to Couple league.
</P>
<P>
   Unrestricted nursing suppresses ovulation and delays the return
of fertility after birth, which aids in family planning. The Couple
to Couple League encourages this unrestricted nursing. Co-sleeping
makes nursing easier during the night, so it happens more often,
Kouba says _ which makes it a good tool for delaying fertility.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Koubas' four children started out sleeping in their
parents' bed, Kouba said. They stayed there until they were 18
months to 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience was that having the babies in bed with us made
our nighttimes less stressful,'' Kouba said. (MORE)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
