<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0466 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SLEEPING-WITH-BABY(2n     11-15 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPING-WITH-BABY(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: xxx Kouba said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOTHING TO LOSE SLEEP OVER
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the decision about co-sleeping, like most parenting
choices, is up to each family.
</P>
<P>
   And that decision may be based on personal experiences of what
works _ and sentiments about what feels right.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while the Koubas find co-sleeping relaxing,
Garretson points out that having a baby in bed can put a dent in
sleep quality for new parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about the adjustment time it takes to get used to
sleeping with your spouse,'' Garretson says. ``It takes just as
long to get used to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Babies will make noise, or parents will move and wake the babies
up _ ``It's kind of that vicious cycle of everybody waking
everybody up,'' Garretson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Omar Gomez, a pediatrician at an office of Cook Children's
Physicians' Network, said probably half of his patients practice
co-sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people don't really think about all the risks, so
you have to bring it up,'' he sais. ``It does go on, so parents
have to make an informed decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez said most families' habits won't change. For those who do
want to practice co-sleeping, he just urges common sense and says
it doesn't hurt to take precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to do what they're going to do,'' he said.
``So we should do what we can to make it a little safer.'' ___
</P>
<P>
   Safety steps if you choose the family bed:
</P>
<P>
   --Use a firm mattress, and make sure the child is sleeping on
her back or side. It's easier for children to rebreathe air if they
can't lift up their heads, sais pediatrician Melissa Garretson. A
firm surface limits that risk. Babies and young children should
never sleep on waterbeds.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't use big pillows or heavy blankets. And never put your
baby on a pillow _ he could roll off or suffocate.
</P>
<P>
   --Never put a baby in bed with another young child. The bed
becomes more crowded, and toddlers move and squirm more during
sleep. A toddler also doesn't understand that babies can't defend
themselves against suffocation or overlying, so they don't have a
natural need to protect the baby.
</P>
<P>
   --Never allow a baby to share a bed with an adult who is under
the influence of alcohol or medication. These substances increase
the risk of rolling onto the baby and make it harder for the adult
to wake up at the baby's distress. ___
</P>
<P>
   Tips for transitioning out of the family bed:
</P>
<P>
   --Try a ``co-sleeper'' bassinet that attaches to the adult bed;
the baby is still near the parents, but in a protected, separate
area.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't feel guilty. Don't think of it as ignoring the baby's
needs during the night; think of it as helping her learn how to
sleep through the night. In a separate bed, ``as children learn how
to sleep, they learn how to self-calm, and then learn how to put
themselves to sleep,'' pediatrician Melissa Garretson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once (children) are really verbalizing, you can talk to them a
little bit,'' Gomez said. Instead of reassuring them physically by
inviting them into your bed, ``you can reassure them with words
that you're going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   --Gomez suggests developing a routine before bedtime by the time
children are 18 months to 2 years old. Read them a book, tell them
a story _ do something to make going to sleep alone a little
easier.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
