<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Nov. 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Blustery conditions will persist Tuesday across the northeastern
states and into New England as a strong area of low pressure over
the Canadian Maritimes continues to draw cold air to the south.
Snow showers will develop in the northern mountains of New England
where moisture from the Atlantic is drawn inland and is forced to
rise over the hilly terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, isolated snow showers will also develop downwind
of Lakes Erie and Ontario on Tuesday, but there will be little, if
any accumulation. Winds will remain over 30 mph along the northeast
seaboard, which will make it feel more like December than November.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, cool breezes from the north will continue in the
Southeast. High pressure will promote abundant sunshine, which will
offset some of the cooling resulting from the winds. Farther west,
much of Texas will remain unseasonably warm with afternoon readings
reaching the 70s and even the low 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Spotty clouds will develop across the Dakotas and into the
western Great Lakes ahead of a weak front. It will remain rather
cool in this region. Temperatures will rise once again to
exceptionally warm levels for this time of year across the central
Plains under ample amounts of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will accompany an area of low pressure and move into
northern California on Tuesday. Farther north, showers are likely
in coastal sections of Washington and Oregon, while snow showers
develop in the northern Cascades. Meanwhile, southern California
and the deserts of the Southwest will remain warm and dry.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Late Hurricane
</P>
<P>
   While cold air swept across the Northeast on Monday, a late
blooming hurricane named Lenny with central winds near 100 mph
churned eastward through the Caribbean Sea about 200 miles south of
Jamaica. November hurricanes are not rare in the tropical Atlantic
Ocean. Since official records began in 1886, at least one hurricane
has been observed on each day of the month. Only four November
hurricanes have crossed the coast of the United States during the
last century. The most recent was in 1985 when Hurricane Kate made
landfall on the Florida panhandle on Nov. 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
