Enterprises discusses its long-term strategy in a special
conference call with analysts. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DEKOR _ ATLANTA _ Former Home Depot executives Jim Inglis and
Herb Biggers, who founded an Atlanta-based company called Dekor,
told National Home Center News that they expect to open the first
store in late 2000, to coincide with the launch of a Web site. The
chain will sell ``anything that has to do with color and style in
the home,'' including paint, wallcoverings and countertops. Dekor
will also offer installed sales and other services. Inglis and
Biggers left Home Depot in late 1996. This summer, Home Depot filed
a lawsuit against them and two other former employees, alleging
that Inglis had improperly recruited staff from the Expo Design
Center in Atlanta and stolen confidential information. The lawsuit
was settled in September. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LOWES _ ATLANTA _ Lowe's shares were down as much as 6 percent
after the company announced slightly disappointing sales growth due
to weather and underperforming stores acquired earlier this year.
Earnings growth was strong,though, with a 38 percent increase in
profit. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UPS _ ATLANTA _ UPS buys a logistics unit from Rollins Truck
Leasing Corp. It also sells its UPS Truck Leasing unit and
9,000-vehicle fleet to Rollins and signs a co-marketing deal. Price
wasn't disclosed, and it's unclear if this was in any way
facilitated by the public offering, in which UPS said it wanted
publicly traded stock for acquisitions. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AIRTRAN-UNION _ The Machinists union says it will file a
petition Monday or Tuesday for a representation election at
AirTran. The union wants to represent 1,600 airport and
reservations agents, who it says are low-paid and plagued by
turnover. The small carrier's flight crewd and mechanics already
are unionized. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
