like to do a little goofing off at work. (Staff, Cox News Service.)
Art includes 1-column color photo of color paper clips.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSCENE _ Knowing how to narrow your search is
important when looking for information on the Web. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   GIRL-TECH _ DAYTON, Ohio _ At least in the world of toys, there
are times when boys will be boys, and girls will be girls. Radica
Games Limited, a Dallas-based company best-known for its hand-held
games, has a line of products sold under the name Girl Tech and
designed to meet the unique desires of preteen girls. The products
add technology to such pursuits as keeping a diary, holding on to
keepsakes, hosting pajama parties and paying tribute to whoever is
this week's ``best friend forever.'' (Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WEATHERWEB _ AUSTIN, Texas _ We still can't do anything
about it, but at least we can venture to the following
weather-related Web sites. (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GAMER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Every year, a game comes out and
kicks the incumbents in the teeth. Last year it was Sierra's
Half-Life, and now Sierra has done it again with the release of
Homeworld. (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDGEAR _ AUSTIN, Texas _ How high-tech is Play-Doh? After
all, it's just Play-Doh, right? If you believe this, you haven't
seen the new Play-Doh, the super-duper, high-tech Play-Doh.
(Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: My take on the Microsoft monopoly
decision. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
