<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0472 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COMDEX16-COX     11-15 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMDEX16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT FRIENDS AND FOES GATHER AT COMDEX
 &HT;    Moving in (a) national and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Back in the nation's capital, Microsoft Corp. has
been branded by a federal judge as an abusive monopolist. But here
in this gambling capital, host this week to a huge computer trade
show, Microsoft is widely seen as a high roller that's trying to
beat the odds in the courts and in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are like everybody else in this cut-throat industry,''
said Alan Jones, president of SCM Microsystems, a Silicon Valley
firm that sells ``smartcard'' security devices. ``Microsoft is
seeking every advantage they can get. The difference is that they
are so big that they can't help but run afoul of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   As the world's largest software company, Microsoft is attracting
lots of attention at the 20th fall Comdex, the world's largest
computer show, which formally opened on Monday. Not all of it is
favorable.
</P>
<P>
   A banner the size of a football field, tied to the side of a
parking garage near the Las Vegas Convention Center, where half the
exhibits are housed, reads: ``Scott McNealy Doesn't Want Your
Money.''
</P>
<P>
   McNealy, head of Sun Microsystems Inc., tangled with Microsoft
in the landmark antitrust case over its Java software. McNealy, who
argues that his rival should be barred from acquiring other
high-tech firms for the next five years, recently acquired Star
Office, a full-featured applications suite that competes with
best-selling Microsoft Office. The Sun suite can be downloaded for
free on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   McNealy has been tapped as one of eight industry leaders who are
giving keynote speeches here. But his address on Wednesday is
unlikey to attract the standing-room crowd of 8,000 that came to
hear Microsoft chairman Bill Gates speak and show off his wares for
90 minutes on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``All over America there are entreprenuers working in their
garages and lawyers working in the 20th floor office, both doing
what they do best,'' Gates quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said that since U.S. District Court judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson issued his blistering findings of fact in the antitrust
case, people have told him that what ``Microsoft has done benefits
consumers,'' and ``instead of doing less innovation in Windows, we
should be doing more innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has built one of the largest pavilions at Comdex,
mainly to showcase its Windows 2000 operation system, scheduled to
be released in February. It is far cry from the tiny booth that
Gates staffed in 1979, when 4,000 people came to the first Comdex a
year before Microsoft signed a deal with IBM to provide an
operating system for a new line of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not distracted by the (antitrust) case at all,''
reported Jefferson Brand, a Microsoft engineer demonstrating
Biztalk, software designed to smooth e-commerce. ``We moving
forward on all fronts as fast as we can,'' Brand added, echoing the
company line.
</P>
<P>
   But at the far end of the exhibit hall, Carey Brooks of ATI
Technologies, a Canadian-based video card maker, voiced a more
skeptical view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been concerned over the power of Microsoft,'' he
said, ``We have to jump through hoops to satisfy them. They're
quite controlling in dictating their terms to everyone else in the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Some exhibitors and attendees sought to duck the antitrust
controversy, perhaps in response to Microsoft's power. Others
advanced their views in cautious and nuanced terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in this business is really free of Microsoft,'' said
Brooks McChesney of Bizfinity, a firm that is partnering with
Internet giant Cisco Systems to run business-to-business Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought them to be really tough guys,'' McChesney
added. ``But that's the way the world works. And we don't want the
government telling us what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another frequent theme was sounded by James Kraskowski, a
Sony executive. ``I want to see when Microsoft stock splits
(again),'' he said. ``That's all I'll say about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
