<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SLEEPING-BOOK-REVIEW-     11-15 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPING-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SLEEPING WITH EXTRA-TERRESTRIALS': REASON IN AN AGE OF ANGELS AND
ALIENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 (DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As America slouches toward the year 2000, Wendy Kaminer suggests
in her new book, reason is on the run, and superstition,
pseudoscience and spiritual mumbo jumbo are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just a case of members of the Heaven's Gate cult
committing suicide to join a flying saucer hiding behind the
Hale-Bopp comet. It's not just a case of worshiping at the shrines
of Princess Diana and Elvis, or of Nancy Reagan's consulting
astrologers about her husband's White House schedule. According to
polls cited by Ms. Kaminer, 93 percent of the population believes
in angels, 49 percent believes the government is concealing
information about UFO's, and more than 25 percent believes in
reincarnation and the possibility of communicating with the dead.
Rationality is condemned as left-brain thinking by New Agers,
shrugged off as a male-based trait by vociferous feminists and
dismissed as phony objectivity by radical postmodernists.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaminer has addressed such issues before in ``I'm
Dysfunctional, You're Dysfunctional'' (1992) and ``It's All the
Rage'' (1995), and the debt to those earlier books remains very
much in evidence in ``Sleeping With Extraterrestrials.'' At the
same time ``Sleeping'' reads like a hodgepodge of essays, loosely
cobbled together around the theme of ``irrationalism and the perils
of piety,'' a capacious subject that allows Ms. Kaminer to wander
off on extended (and sometimes only tangentially relevant) riffs
about the drug war, crack babies and therapeutic feminism.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaminer's lame excuse for this incoherence is that she has
tried to adapt to the cyber-age Zeitgeist, which encourages
spontaneous, nonlinear thinking. ``While I continue to compose my
sentences,'' she writes, ``I have changed the way I conceive of my
books. I digress. I imagine each chapter as an autonomous essay,
because I know that people no longer read books about ideas
sequentially.''
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the decline of rationalism, Ms. Kaminer
persuasively makes the point, as she has before, that ``popular
psychologies assume the authenticity of subjective experience'' _
an outlook that discourages the demand for facts and corroborative
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The therapeutic culture shaped by the recovery movement is
profoundly irrational,'' she writes. ``It seeks truth not in debate
but in revelation. It values bolstering people's self-esteem over
challenging their ideas. It assesses proposed truths partly by the
passion with which they are held and partly by their alleged
therapeutic effect. True beliefs are those that help you `heal.'''
</P>
<P>
   Given this mindset, Ms. Kaminer argues, books like ``The
Celestine Prophecy,'' ``Embraced by the Light,'' ``A Book of
Angels'' and ``Conversations With God'' _ which variously depict a
world without tragedy and random accidents, a world in which people
can control their lives and death can be transcended _ are readily
embraced by readers reluctant even to question the basis for such
sentimental optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Celestine Prophecy'' goes so far as to suggest that reason
is an outmoded human tool: it suggests, Ms. Kaminer writes, that
people will one day simply ``intuit'' the answers to global
problems. Other books and inspirational speakers cloak their more
fanciful assertions in the jargon of pseudoscience. Deepak Chopra
buttresses his theories with allusions to physics and biology, and
Marianne Williams cites Einstein, Bohr and Heisenberg in her own
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaminer does a succinct job of situating current New Age
beliefs in context with the American tradition of ``positive
thinking'' (from the ``mind cure'' movements of the 19th century
through Norman Vincent Peale's more recent appeals), and she makes
a compelling argument that the self-absorption embodied by such
beliefs can create a complacent body politic. She contends that
``the habits of unreason'' encouraged by pop spirituality books _
not to mention the ``childlike craving for authority'' nurtured by
many recovery movement gurus _ can lead to passivity and a
reluctance to grapple with the social realities of the world around
us.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Kaminer sees it, the current ``smorgasbord of religions
and newly spiritualized pop psychologies'' are evidence of a 1990s
``religious and spiritual revival'' fueled by widespread,
nonsectarian anxiety about social change and a declining faith in
government. Prayer groups and Bible study groups have proliferated,
she observes, religion-based television shows like ``Touched by an
Angel'' have gained new popularity, and both the religious right
and communitarians on the left have begun to call for a
``remoralization of public policy debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the relationship between religion and public policy
raises important questions _ as the recent vote by the Kansas Board
of Education to discourage the teaching of evolution makes all too
clear _ Ms. Kaminer's discussion of these matters is undermined by
her own willful suspicion of all forms of faith and her beleaguered
conviction that nonbelievers are routinely vilified.
</P>
<P>
   She writes that agnostics and atheists are regarded as ``only a
little more virtuous than many prison inmates'' despite a 1994
survey that showed that 74 percent of Americans agree that someone
who does not believe in God ``can be a good or ethical person.''
While she is happy to brandish other poll results that serve her
purposes, she discounts this particular finding by arguing that
``many people are loath to admit their prejudices to pollsters,
even prejudices that are widely held.''
</P>
<P>
   The passages of this book dealing with politics and religion
tend to be peppered with gross generalizations and debatable
assumptions. In one chapter, for instance, Ms. Kaminer writes that
calls for private school vouchers may be part of an effort ``to
censor secular humanist materials in public schools and
re-establish official school prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is an accurate description of the voucher movement,''
she argues, ``it could fairly be said to promise the elevation of
faith over reason in the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, such speculative statements, as bereft of the sort
of supporting evidence she accuses New Age gurus of eschewing,
diminish the credibility of Ms. Kaminer's more rigorously argued
observations.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SLEEPING WITH EXTRA-TERRESTRIALS'
</P>
<P>
   The Rise of Irrationalism and Perils of Piety.
</P>
<P>
   By Wendy Kaminer
</P>
<P>
   278 pages. Pantheon Books. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
