<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Depot's competition Dekor to sell online
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two former Home Depot executives plan to launch their
rival concept late next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Inglis and Herb Biggers, co-founders of a year-old company
called Dekor, recently told a trade publication they would start
selling products through stores and a Web site within 12 months. On
Monday, Biggers declined to discuss details of the home improvement
business, citing the competition with their former employer.
</P>
<P>
   According to National Home Center News, Dekor will sell paint,
wallcoverings, countertops and other remodeling products. The
stores will also offer installation and design services, according
to the article.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis and Biggers left Atlanta-based Home Depot in 1996. Home
Depot filed a lawsuit against them and two other former employees
this summer, alleging that Inglis was cherry-picking experts from
Expo Design Center in Atlanta to launch a copycat chain. The
lawsuit was settled in September.
</P>
<P>
   At Home Depot, Inglis was a board member and executive vice
president. He is now chairman and chief executive officer of
Marietta-based Dekor, which is located off of Powers Ferry Road.
Biggers is president of Dekor.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
