<HEADER>
A0479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FORSYTH-PHANTOM-NYT &LR;      11-15 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORSYTH-PHANTOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE JACKAL'S DAY LONG GONE, FORSYTH TAILS THE PHANTOM OF THE
OPERA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For a writer who has donned the cloaks and wielded the
daggers of assassins and spies, mercenaries and hoodlums for some
30 years, Frederick Forsyth seems almost to be running scared.
</P>
<P>
   That is not altogether surprising. Forsyth, now 61, is about to
publish his newest book. In it _ possibly to the consternation of
some of the 50 million fans who bought his thrillers from ``Day of
the Jackal'' in 1971 to ``Icon'' in 1995 _ Forsyth has found love.
Not physical love, but a palette of far more tender emotion to
which he was drawn, most surprising of all, by Andrew Lloyd Webber,
the high priest of sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a dinner conversation with that British composer,
Forsyth has written a sequel to the musical ``Phantom of the
Opera'' based on the single tantalizing question: What happened to
the Phantom after the curtain went down?
</P>
<P>
   In the musical _ based on a novel written in 1911 by Gaston
Leroux, a little-known French author _ the monstrous Phantom simply
disappears into the labyrinthine bowels of the Paris Opera.
Forsyth's new book, ``The Phantom of Manhattan'' (Thomas Dunne
Books, St. Martin's Press), to be published next week in the United
States and Britain, pursues the idea that the character somehow
escaped to New York to begin a new, hidden life.
</P>
<P>
   That alone should be enough to distinguish this slender 177-page
volume from Forsyth's earlier work. But as the story unfolds, the
reader rapidly sees many other differences. Strikingly, the single
anonymous narrative voice familiar to Forsyth's fans is replaced by
a variety of narrators, from a dying mistress of the ballet to a
cocky, young New York reporter and from the Phantom himself to a
hashish-smoking, thoroughly evil aide.
</P>
<P>
   In another departure, Forsyth includes an imagined conversation
between a priest and his God: a foray into theology that he fears
may give offense to some readers. (He describes himself as a
``lapsed Protestant'' with a belief in a deity but no conviction
about church ritual.)
</P>
<P>
   In creating what he called in an interview a ``romantic
novella,'' he said he was ``extremely apprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a part of old Fred that hasn't been shown yet,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of this hidden Forsyth, masked in the past as
effectively as the Phantom, has been just as difficult to reveal:
his agent and publishers, he said, had ``deep misgivings'' about
the new book, and its creation was more troublesome than his
thrillers had ever been. The book went to six partial revisions,
compared with Forsyth's usual practice of revising his original
manuscript only once before publication.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, he said, he is concerned that readers who want more
of his hallmark derring-do will be disappointed, while others
looking for romantic themes will not be drawn to a name associated
with anything but the subtleties of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be jeered at, or it could be accepted,'' he said,
adding that readers might ask, ``Where's the spy?''
</P>
<P>
   The new book is ``set in 1906 on the streets of New York,'' he
said. ``There are no silenced automatics. So they may think they
have picked up the wrong book. I think everybody accepts that this
is a question mark. So will it just die within a week?
</P>
<P>
   ``Four publishers turned down `Day of the Jackal,' so who knows?
The arbiter is Joe Public. You can hype just so much. But if it's
worthless, it'll die.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he plans to go back to thrillers. Of the two projects
he is currently considering, he said somewhat enigmatically, one is
a work of fiction about a love affair set partly in the late 18th
century and partly in the late 20th. The other is a collection of
moments and memories _ not an autobiography or formal memoirs, he
insisted _ from four decades of his life ``in some weird places,''
from Biafra during the Nigerian civil war to East Berlin at the
height of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth chose to be interviewed in the coffee shop of an upscale
West London hotel where, like the best of his undercover agents, he
drew no second glances as he strode briskly through the lobby. Even
his drink order seemed incongruously remote from his sinewy heroes
and millionaire-author public image: ``A pot of tea, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth gave up thriller writing after the publication of
``Icon,'' set largely in Russia after the Cold War. Of course, the
world's momentous shift away from ideological division has stripped
many a writer of a stock in trade, and in Forsyth's case there was
a feeling that he had gone as far as he could with a genre that had
had its day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting jaded,'' he said. The themes were becoming ``a
bit samey,'' and he fell prey to existential thoughts. He
celebrated his 61st birthday a few weeks ago, and, he said, the
questions pushed in again: ``What are you going to do? You're
three-quarters of the way through life with a quarter to go. Do you
really want to go on doing this?
</P>
<P>
   ``And I really would like to try something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, he said, returning to the theme, the end of the
Cold War removed the Soviet Union as a prime ingredient of the
espionage thriller, and he is not sure the literary world has
discovered a convincing replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem is: find a good villain,'' he said.
``Villains are harder to invent. Heroes are two a penny.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth estimated that some 60 million people have paid to see
Lloyd Webber's ``Phantom of the Opera,'' and so it must have been
quite a delicious encounter when the writer with 50 million in
sales _ and no great fascination with musicals _ and the composer
with even more in audience numbers chatted over dinner some two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why, but the conversation strayed to `The Phantom
of the Opera,' and he said the question that had always intrigued
him is what happened to them afterward,'' Forsyth said, referring
to the Phantom and his operatic love. After thinking about the idea
for a while, ``I said I would do it as a novella.''
</P>
<P>
   After some background research in New York, Forsyth worked on
the book in the winter of 1998. Although the novella marked a
change of style and substance, one constant remained: his favorite,
much-used typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm computer-illiterate,'' he said, ``I write on a typewriter
with two forefingers. I don't see any reason to abandon the winning
system. If it ain't broke, don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   The question that lingers is whether his followers will think
the same when they measure the new Frederick Forsyth against the
old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
