<HEADER>
A0480 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-ECUADOR-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      11-15 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUST IN ECUADOR LEADER FADES OVER SECRET FUNDS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By JOHN OTIS  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ President Jamil Mahuad has come under criticism
for accepting secret campaign contributions from a now-jailed
Ecuadorean businessman whose bank received vast sums of emergency
aid from Mahuad's government.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal is the latest twist in a financial-sector meltdown
that has hurt hundreds of thousands of depositors and sent the
economy into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   It has also convinced many Ecuadorean voters that their
political leaders are beholden to wealthy donors. Some people are
demanding major reforms to Ecuador's loose campaign finance and
banking laws. Others are calling for Mahuad to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mahuad put the decisions of his government up for sale,''
wrote Cesar Montufar, a columnist in the Quito daily El Comercio.
``He mortgaged the nation and flouted the idea that government
should be independent from private business interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The key figure in the scandal is Fernando Aspiazu, the top
executive and main shareholder of Banco del Progreso, Ecuador's
second-largest private bank until it closed in March.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiazu, who was arrested last month on charges of tax evasion,
announced from his jail cell that he gave $3.1 million to Mahuad's
1998 campaign war chest. That amount is nearly one-third of the $10
million Mahuad is believed to have spent to get elected in this
small Andean nation of 12.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Besides raising ethical questions about relying so heavily on a
single donor, the contribution was never registered with electoral
officials even though disclosure is required by law.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised speech this month, Mahuad acknowledged that he
accepted donations from Aspiazu but said the banker received no
special favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never made any promises to (Aspiazu) or to any other
campaign contributor,'' Mahaud said. ``If he thought that because
he made a donation to the campaign that he could make certain
demands in the running of the government, he was totally
mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts insist that Mahuad's handling of the banking
crisis clearly helped Aspiazu and other powerful bankers at the
public's expense.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles took hold shortly after Mahuad took office in
August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Falling prices for oil, Ecuador's leading export, and a 1995
border war with Peru created a huge fiscal deficit and slowed
growth. The Asian economic crisis spread to Latin America and
spurred capital flight. And flooding from the 1997-98 El Nio
weather pattern ruined hundreds of businesses, which defaulted on
bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts also blame poor government supervision of the
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
   For example, until recently, bankers could channel up to 60
percent of loan portfolios to ventures they controlled. Many gave
themselves credits and wrote them off as bank losses, according to
Wilma Salgado, an economist and U.N. consultant in Quito, the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Several major banks collapsed, and others were set to go under.
But instead of allowing weak banks to fail, as some economists
recommended, the government tried to save them by extending huge
sums in emergency credits.
</P>
<P>
   The government has not revealed how much Aspiazu's Banco del
Progreso received, but banking experts believe it was a
multimillion-dollar sum.
</P>
<P>
   For a handful of banks, the cash injections were not enough, and
the state took over their operations altogether. Today, 65 percent
of the Ecuadorean banking system is run by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The government's most drastic action was to declare a weeklong
bank holiday in March and to order the partial freezing of
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The profession is totally disgraced. It's better not to admit
that you are a banker,'' said Santiago Bayas, a vice president at
Banco del Pichincha in Quito.
</P>
<P>
   Another controversial move was the creation of the Deposit
Guarantee Agency to vouch for 100 percent of deposits. In effect,
the government agency lets the owners of failed banks off the hook
and makes taxpayers pick up the entire tab for reimbursing
depositors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state is assuming all of these costs, and that means the
Ecuadorean people,'' Salgado said. ``No one asks what the bankers
did with the money or why their banks failed.''
</P>
<P>
   It now appears that Banco del Progreso was rife with
irregularities. One foreign economist described the bank as ``a den
of massive corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   In his TV speech, Mahuad said that $550 million of the bank's
$800 million in credits were funneled to businesses and phantom
corporations controlled by Aspiazu. In one case, the sister of
Aspiazu's chauffeur was listed as the recipient of a huge loan. But
when reporters tracked her down, she turned out to be a seamstress
who knew nothing about the money.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing criminal charges, several bankers fled the country.
Aspiazu was finally jailed last month on accusations that he
withheld about $13 million in taxes from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Until the jailed banker revealed his $3.1 million donation to
the Mahuad campaign, many Ecuadoreans could not fathom why the
government waited so long to move against Aspiazu.
</P>
<P>
   According to political scientist Fernando Bustamante, Mahuad
needed the money from Aspiazu to compete with Alvaro Noboa, his
opponent in last year's election and one of Ecuador's richest men.
Noboa is also believed to have spent about $10 million in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Once in office, Mahuad named a handful of bank executives to top
posts in his administration, making it more difficult to adopt
tough measures when the crisis unfolded, according to Juana
Ordonez, assistant editor of Gestion business magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mahuad's first superintendent of banks, the
government's financial sector watchdog, was a former lawyer for
Aspiazu.
</P>
<P>
   All told, rescuing the banking sector may end up costing $2
billion, a figure that outstrips the country's annual tax revenue,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the policy has helped to paralyze Ecuador's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ecuador's deep troubles, Mahuad had been considered an
honest, well-meaning public servant and seemingly a sharp contrast
from the nation's two previous presidents who were enmeshed in
corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Mahuad's job-approval rating has slipped to 14 percent.
There have been rumors of a military coup, while a number of
politicians have suggested that Mahuad step down.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez of Gestion described the campaign finance scandal as
``the beginning of the end of Mahuad's credibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
