<SLUG> BC-LOWES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lowe's disappoints some on Wall Street with latest earnings news
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of Lowe's Cos. took a hit Monday after the
retailer released a mildly disappointing earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street focused on a slip in sales at some stores, even
though Lowe's beat expectations with a 38 percent increase in
fiscal third-quarter profit. The stock dropped as much as 9 percent
before recovering to close at $54.93 3/4, down $2.93 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's, the second-largest home improvement retailer, was
impacted by underperforming stores and extra costs related to an
acquisition in the spring. Analysts said those factors should not
impact Home Depot's third-quarter earnings, which are expected to
be released today.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's posted a profit of $168.7 million, or 44 cents a share,
up from $121.9 million, or 33 cents a share, a year earlier. Lowe's
was expected to earn 42 cents in its fiscal third quarter,
according to a survey of analysts by First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Results in the year-ago quarter were restated to include the
purchase of Eagle Hardware &AMP; Garden in April.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's said earnings would have been higher, but the company
incurred $8 million in costs to accelerate the integration of the
Eagle chain. That reduced earnings about a penny a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 19 percent to $3.91 billion. Sales growth was hurt by
weather in the Southeast and sluggish Eagle stores in the West.
Lowe's noted that sales were helped by expanding installation
services and special orders.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the stock tumbled because investors were
preoccupied with sales at stores open at least one year, which rose
6.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street was expecting better `same-store' sales,'' said
analyst Dan Wewer of Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown. Investors are
closely watching the Eagle stores, which dragged down overall sales
growth, because Lowe's is using them to gain a foothold in the
western United States.
</P>
<P>
   New stores opened by Home Depot and HomeBase in the West are
taking market share from Eagle, analysts said. But Lowe's said in a
conference call Monday that it expects those stores to recoup sales
in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Lowe's continues to improve operations. Significant
gross-margin improvement compensated for the sales disappointment,
analysts noted. And expansion plans call for more stores in Home
Depot markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compare Lowe's to Home Depot, typically Lowe's is not
as productive but they are getting better and better,'' Wewer said.
``Lowe's is getting as good as it can be at No. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
