<HEADER>
A0490 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-15 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAY FOR SUPREME COURT WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If students lead prayers over a loudspeaker to a
captive audience at a public high school football game, are they
exercising the First Amendment right of freedom of religion or are
they violating the constitutional barrier that separates church and
state?
</P>
<P>
   How could officials assure the prayers are non-sectarian and
avoid the imposition of religious conformity upon a secular event,
without unacceptable government intervention? Students are likely
to reflect their own specific church-going background, not some
vague notion of generic piety.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, of course, may be that student-led prayer is simply
a sneaky way around the high court's 1992 ban forbidding school
officials to deliver such messages themselves. Protecting the great
principles of the Constitution against selfish special interests
requires constant vigilance.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court had little practical choice but to agree to
hear the case at hand, which is an appeal from a lower court ruling
that the policy of the Santa Fe Independent School District in
Galveston, Texas, encouraging student-led group prayers at football
games was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   School prayer, in one form or other, has been a raging political
question since the high bench ruled in 1962 against permitting
organized prayer in public schools. The court declared that the
official teacher-led school prayers that used to be commonplace
were too intimidating and coercive, particularly for impressionable
young minds.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the courts have tried to differentiate between prayer
that is acceptable and prayer that is not, with only limited
success. The First Amendment protects the free exercise of
religion; what it does not allow is the ``establishment'' of one
religion. The freedom is for all religions, not just for one faith
that dominates another.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of the religious right on conservative politics
has kept this argument high on the national agenda. On Nov. 7, the
House of Representatives passed a resolution calling on the Supreme
Court to approve voluntary prayer at high school sporting events, a
direct attempt to pressure the justices to overturn the lower court
decision in the Galveston case.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the latest political effort to make a religious
end-run around the court and the Constitution. Ronald Reagan
supported a constitutional amendment to return organized prayer to
the public schools, which is still alive in a congressional
committee somewhere. The House has been flirting with a
constitutional amendment to allow the posting of the Ten
Commandments in public classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court never acknowledges political influence upon
its deliberations, but it has clearly been affected by the
appointment of conservative justices the past 20 years who believe
organized religion can help to combat moral decline.
</P>
<P>
   In their efforts to fine-tune this complicated constitutional
issue, the lower courts have made a muddle of it, ruling this way
and that way although generally limiting the role of religion in
public activities.
</P>
<P>
   Bibles have been banned from offices and schools, for instance,
but the teaching of creationism goes on.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the Supreme Court agreed only to review the
constitutionality of launching school football games with
ostentatious, inescapable prayer messages, leaving other issues
such as student prayer at graduation ceremonies for another day.
The court may find football games an easier place to draw the line
than formal, non-sporting ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The players are thinking about how to beat their opponents, and
so is the watching crowd. If God consistently plays favorites in
such moments, nobody has ever established it. The coach usually
gets the credit, or the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully the Supreme Court will reiterate its holding that
organized prayer does not belong in schools at all but in houses of
worship, in homes, in silent meditation, in solemn moments before
great occasions. A high school football stadium packed with people
of diverse backgrounds who came to watch athletes perform seems
more like an opportunity to proselytize an audience of trapped
folks than an occasion for meaningful prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals decision the high bench will
review declared that football is ``hardly the sober type of annual
event that can be appropriately solemnized with prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decision will come down before the end of the
court term in mid-summer, meaning that it will be a hot topic at
both the Republican and Democratic conventions and during the 2000
presidential election. Republican candidates have tended generally
to support school prayer; Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a Republican
presidential hopeful, joined in the Galveston appeal. Democratic
candidates, including Vice President Al Gore, have sided with the
constitutional tradition of separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Religion is not endangered in this country; it is alive and
well. We are inundated with church symbols from every direction.
That's OK; we can ignore them if we wish. This is after all
supposed to be a very private matter.
</P>
<P>
   What we cannot tolerate in a democracy is organized religion
demanding that the rest of us take public part in a group
endorsement of views with which we might not agree. Can't we just
mind our own business and cheer on the home team?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
