<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0491 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GRAVITY-WAVES-ART     11-15 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GRAVITY-WAVES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPPING INTO THE VIBRATIONS OF THE COSMOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: La., Wash., Mass., Calif., Ill., Md., N.J., Puerto Rico) (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON, La. _ Sprawling across snake-infested Louisiana
woodlands, a gigantic gravity wave detector that builders hope will
open a new window on the universe was inaugurated last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On hand for the ceremony were Dr. Rita R. Colwell, director of
the National Science Foundation, and many leading theorists in
astrophysics, relativity theory and related sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The L-shaped detector here and its recently completed twin in
Hanford, Wash., are called called LIGO (pronounced LIE-go), for
Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory. Having cost
$296 million so far, it is the largest enterprise ever financed by
the National Science Foundation _ and one of the riskiest.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1970s, when it was first proposed, LIGO has met with
the skepticism of many astronomers and assaults from would-be
budget cutters in Congress and elsewhere. The signals of gravity
waves reaching Earth from the merger of black holes and other
cosmic catastrophes are expected to be so faint that LIGO may
detect nothing at all, at least in its first version.
</P>
<P>
   But the possibility of deciphering gravitational radiation as a
means of penetrating secrets of the birth of the universe and the
evolution of black holes, galaxies and other mysteries carried the
day, and LIGO was completed, with enough money to pay for its
operation through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kip S. Thorne of Caltech, the leading theorist on the LIGO
team, predicted that gravity waves, if and when they are detected,
would offer an entirely new way to study the 90 percent of the
universe that is hidden from observation with conventional
instruments that are sensitive to light waves, radio, X-rays or
gamma rays. He urged cooperation between gravity-wave specialists
and other astrophysicists in identifying the sources of gravity
waves, which still hold many mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   The two LIGO detectors, separated by about 2,000 miles, were
built by the California Institute of Technology and the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Leading scientists from both
universities, including Dr. David Baltimore, president of Caltech,
were among the speakers at the inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   LIGO thus became the first large detector in what scientists
hope will be an international network of similar instruments on the
ground and eventually in space. Within two years, the Virgo gravity
detector, about the same size as LIGO, will be completed by an
Italian-French collaboration near Pisa, and smaller detectors are
being built in Japan and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   If both LIGO and Virgo work as hoped, they can operate in
concert, viewing the Northern Hemisphere sky from three separate
points. This would allow scientists to calculate the direction from
which a gravitational signal reached Earth, and to determine
whether the wave coincided with some other kind of signal _ a
gamma-ray pulse, a flash of light or some other kind of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   One such signal might come from a pulse of neutrinos coinciding
with a gravity wave, said Dr. John Bahcall, a leading
astrophysicist at the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton,
N.J. In his talk, Bahcall described gravity waves, like neutrinos,
as ``new messengers for astronomy,'' capable of probing vast and
hitherto unfathomed parts of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   A far more ambitious project than LIGO, the space-based Laser
Interferometer Space Antenna, or LISA, is planned by the European
Space Agency for launching a decade from now. NASA is considering
joining a partnership with the European agency to support the
project, which is expected to cost $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   LISA would consist of three satellites arrayed at the corners of
an equilateral triangle, each separated from the other two by 5
million kilometers (3.1 million miles). The entire assemblage would
be launched into an orbit around the Sun, trailing Earth by about
20 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, scientists hope, gravity-wave ``telescopes'' will
detect the collisions of black holes and neutron stars, the
explosions of certain types of supernovas, the behavior of
supermassive black holes at the hearts of most (or perhaps all)
galaxies, and even the relic gravitational ripples left from the
Big Bang, the huge explosion theorized to have resulted in the
birth of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Turner, an astrophysicist from the University of
Chicago, described the search for gravity waves as vital to the
detection of ``cold dark matter,'' invisible matter believed to
make up most of the mass of the universe. Turner described this
search as ``the greatest challenge of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The quest for gravity waves goes back many years. The General
Theory of Relativity published by Albert Einstein in 1915 predicted
that disturbances in large gravitational fields should propagate at
the speed of light as ripples in spacetime. Theory predicted that a
gravity ripple passing through a detector should alternately
lengthen and shorten spacetime within the detector, and that
supposition was the basis of several experiments.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, Dr. Joseph Weber of the University of
Maryland based one of the first detectors on a huge aluminum bar
that was supposed to ring like a bell when penetrated by a gravity
wave of the right frequency. Experimenters in Australia and
elsewhere still experiment with resonant bar gravity wave
detectors, but with no luck so far.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of gravity waves remained hypothetical until 1974,
when two Princeton University physicists, Dr. Joseph H. Taylor and
his student Dr. Russel A. Hulse detected them indirectly.
</P>
<P>
   Using the huge radio telescope at Arecibo, Puerto Rico, the two
scientists discovered two pulsating neutron stars in orbit around
one another. After making a series of precise measurements of radio
pulses from the two stars, the physicists found that their orbital
spin rate was speeding up, showing that they were losing orbital
energy. The rate of this loss turned out to be just what would be
expected of massive stars shedding orbital energy in the form of
gravity waves.
</P>
<P>
   For their discovery, Taylor and Hulse were awarded the 1993
Nobel Prize in physics.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Physicists expect to spend about two years fine-tuning LIGO
before the system will be ready to begin a formal search for
gravity waves, but there is always the chance that one may turn up
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a good chance that LIGO, at its present level of
technology, will discover nothing at all. Fearing that the initial
search for gravity waves will turn up nothing, project leaders are
already working on an upgrade of LIGO to incorporate future
technical improvements.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement about the project, the National Science
Foundation acknowledged that ``LIGO aims to take risks,'' adding
that ``as science reaches the brink of what is considered nearly
impossible measurement, it requires technological innovations that
were barely conceived of even a few decades ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Colwell quoted the late Edwin Land, inventor of Polaroid film,
in describing the worthiness of such risky projects as LIGO. ``His
requirement,'' Colwell said, ``was for a venture to be manifestly
important and nearly impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In principle, LIGO is quite simple, although the simplicity of
its gray arms, which extend from horizon to horizon through a
wilderness domain of alligators and deadly snakes, belies its
underlying complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Each detector consists of two steel pipes 4 feet in diameter and
2 and a half miles long, at right angles to each other. Inside each
pipe is a pair of mirrors, facing each other and suspended from
flexible wires. The apparatus also contains an infrared laser, beam
splitters, and many feedback control loops.
</P>
<P>
   By adjusting the positions of the mirrors and a beam-splitter
(which reflects half the light striking it and transmits the other
half), the lengths of the laser light paths in the two pipes are
adjusted to be precisely equal.
</P>
<P>
   Normally when a beam of laser light is split and then recombined
in the two arms of the L, the perfectly matched beams interfere
with each other, preventing any light from reaching a detector. But
when a gravity wave passes through the apparatus, physicists
expect, the spacetime in one arm will be stretched while the other
is squeezed, and the differing lengths will momentarily destroy the
lasers' interference pattern, allowing light to shine on the
detector.
</P>
<P>
   LIGO has been designed to detect a difference in the lengths of
the light paths in the two arms of as little as one-tenth the
diameter of a proton.
</P>
<P>
   But such high sensitivity is bound to produce many false alarms.
Dr. Barry C. Barish of Caltech, LIGO's director, expects lots of
terrestrial ``noise'' to impinge on both the Hanford and Livingston
sites, but if the same signal is simultaneously detected at both
places, it is less likely to be noise. Only signals that arrive
simultaneously at Hanford and Livingston will be considered as
gravity wave candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The principle behind LIGO is much the same as the one used by
two American scientists, Albert A. Michelson and Edward W. Morley,
who in 1887 built a device based on their expectation that pairs of
light beams interfering with each other would reveal the passage of
Earth through a hypothetical ``ether''_ an all-pervasive substance
providing a medium for light waves to propagate. The experiment
failed to find evidence of ether (the absence of which was later
explained by relativity theory), but interferometry has found many
other scientific applications.
</P>
<P>
   Among the young scientists inspired by Weber's gravity wave
experiments was Thorne of Caltech, who played a major role in the
development of LIGO and is now one of its chief leaders. (Thorne
has also speculated on the possibility of time travel through
``worm holes'' connecting distant points in the universe, and is
the author of ``Black Holes and Time Warps: Einstein's Outrageous
Legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists who made major contributions to the gravity
wave quest were Dr. Rainer Weiss at MIT and Dr. Ron Drever of
Caltech. These and other LIGO scientists recently acknowledged that
they never expected that it would take so long to build a gravity
wave detector with a reasonable chance of success.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When financing of the LIGO project came before Congress in 1993,
it attracted the strong support of Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La.,
among others, who helped to win it congressional support. But many
scientists opposed it on the grounds that the money could be better
spent on other things, particularly since LIGO's chances of finding
anything seemed so uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Dr. J. Anthony Tyson, an astrophysicist at Bell
Laboratories, polled 70 astronomers and astrophysicists and found
them overwhelmingly opposed to LIGO.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about the project today, Tyson replied: ``My
personal attitude as an experimental physicist is, look, the
money's been spent, right? Don't haggle over it, just go and give
it your best shot. Put the best equipment you can into it, the
cleanest laser, the cleanest mirrors, the best vacuum, and run for
a while and see if there's anything out there. I think that's
Barish's plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who proved the existence of gravity waves in 1974, hopes
for great discoveries from LIGO, but expects them to take years.
Asked in an interview whether he was confident of early success for
the costly project, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I would say that in the first go, with the initial
detectors, nobody's very confident. If nature is really kind to us,
LIGO might see something in the near future, but I think it's
unlikely. But I'm optimistic that with the next generation of
interferometers installed in LIGO, maybe five years down the road,
we'll see something.''
</P>
<P>
   The event most likely to be detected in the next five years,
Taylor said, is the collision of two black holes. More subtle
effects might be detected from the violent, asymmetric collapse of
a Type II supernova up to 50 million light-years away, a spinning
neutron star that wobbles, or perhaps a very faint gravitational
echo of the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary stakes are high in the hunt for gravity waves, but
``for all of us, the completion of LIGO is the realization of a
dream,'' Barish said. ``We're not at the end yet, but the odds look
better than ever of opening a new window on the universe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
