<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-ECUADOR-CURRENCY-HNS &LR;      11-15 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-CURRENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLING CURRENCY, BANKING CRISIS HAVE ECUADOREANS TOTING BAGS OF
CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By JOHN OTIS  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ In Ecuador, it requires just $60 to become a
millionaire. That amount buys an inch-thick wad of bills totalling
1 million sucres.
</P>
<P>
   The country's currency, the sucre, has plummeted in the past
year from 6,400 to the U.S. dollar to nearly 17,000 per dollar,
because of a banking crisis and the worst recession since the Great
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   The largest denomination bill is the 50,000 sucre note, which is
worth less than $4.
</P>
<P>
   To cut deals, business people tote around briefcases or garbage
bags stuffed with cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may look like you have a lot of money, but it now costs 5
million sucres for a refrigerator,'' said Marcelo Almeida, manager
of Credicentro appliance store in Quito.
</P>
<P>
   Lida Quiroz, a money-changer in Quito, recalled that after a
recent day of trading, her pile of sucres was so heavy that she
enlisted her sister to help haul away the money in a duffel bag.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the inconvenience, cash remains the most popular form of
payment because of a deep distrust in banks.
</P>
<P>
   But to prevent a run on deposits, the government temporarily
froze all accounts in March and imposed a 1 percent tax on bank
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Many Ecuadoreans stopped writing checks, closed their accounts
and hid their money at home, a practice nicknamed ``the mattress
bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional financial institutions ``no longer have any
prestige,'' said Marco Bedoya, who runs the Tienda Latino Americana
souvenir store in Quito.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now, Ecuador has avoided a return to the
out-of-control hyperinflation that bedeviled much of Latin America
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   During the waning years of the Sandinista revolution in
Nicaragua, for example, $1 bought 6 million Nicaraguan cordobas.
Lacking the paper to print new bills to keep up with the
devaluations, the Sandinistas simply stamped extra zeros in black
ink on old bills.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuadoreans suggest that doing business would be easier with a
higher denomination sucre note, but a Central Bank spokesman said
there are no immediate plans to print new bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should make a 1 million sucre bill,'' said Quiroz, the
money changer. ``That would be excellent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
