<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0495 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-PALESTINIAN-REFUGEES-     11-15 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-REFUGEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME IN JORDAN: PALESTINIANS RELUCTANT TO RELOCATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By DEBORAH HORAN  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Khalil Attieh is a member of Jordan's
Parliament, an accomplished civil engineer and one of Amman's
wealthiest construction contractors. He builds bridges, drives a
sleek beige Mercedes-Benz and lives in a three-story mansion.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a Palestinian refugee.
</P>
<P>
   When Israelis and Palestinians began to discuss the fate of
refugees last week in negotiations aimed at reaching a final peace
treaty, they were not talking just about people in impoverished
camps.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of Jordan's 4 million citizens are of Palestinian
origin.
</P>
<P>
   They are the engine of Jordan's thriving merchant class. With
money made from businesses here or brought with them from the Arab
Gulf, they built some of Amman's swankiest neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean they plan to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be a Palestinian success story, but I cannot forget my
Palestinian roots,'' said Attieh, a stocky, rotund man who grew up
in the Hussein refugee camp, a few miles away from his mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing would prevent me from having two houses, one here and
one in Palestine,'' Attieh said.
</P>
<P>
   Except maybe the Israelis. They want to limit the number of
refugees allowed to return to the country of 5.6 million. Bringing
back hundreds of thousands of refugees to Israel, they argue, would
threaten its Jewish identity. Letting them move to the West Bank
and Gaza would be too big a burden on the Palestinian
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the possibility for half a million (refugees) to
show up on the doorstep of the Palestinian Authority,'' said Reuven
Hazan, a political analyst at Jerusalem's Hebrew University.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, however, want nothing short of the right to decide
for themselves whether to return or remain in their host countries,
even if most of them never make the move to the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't force a solution,'' said Sari Nasir, a Palestinian
sociologist at the University of Jordan. ``It has to come
naturally. To stay here or settle somewhere else has to be their
decision, individually.''
</P>
<P>
   Many may decide to stay put. A few miles away from Attieh's
villa, Yousef Awwad, who used to live in the Wahdat refugee camp,
has moved in to a government-subsidized home in a working-class
development neighborhood called Manara.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with 3,500 single-family homes built along spacious
streets, Manara stands in stark contrast to the miserable
conditions in Awwad's camp. A house with a mortgage has given him a
sense of permanence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my final destination,'' Awwad said. A photograph from
his younger days showed him dressed in a Palestine Liberation Army
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Funded in part by the Jordanian government and the United States
Agency for International Development and aimed at low-income
Jordanians, developments like Manara have quietly helped to house
thousands of Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of settling refugees here, however, remains a very
sensitive topic. Last month, Jordan's energetic young king,
Abdullah II, visited Baqa'a, the country's largest camp, and told a
cheering crowd of refugees that they were an ``integral part'' of
Jordanian society.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, a government official emphasized that the
king's words were not meant to undermine the refugees' demands to
return to Palestine or to receive financial compensation for
property lost there.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the king may have been responding to the
hard truth that most refugees are not likely to go back to the
farms and orchards they left in what is now Israel. And while they
are living in Jordan, they have a very real need to have the same
rights as any other citizen for as long as they remain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Jordan granted citizenship to Palestinians living here.
They can vote, run for Parliament and hold top government
positions. In 1991, Taher al-Masri, Jordan's 77th prime minister,
was a Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinians also complain of being excluded from the
country's traditional bases of power. They are discouraged from
joining the army and the police. They are under-represented in
government ministries. And when it comes to getting into state-run
universities, Jordanian applicants have a better chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the law, I am Jordanian,'' said Palestinian
Hamadeh Farouneh, considered by some a firebrand in Jordan's
Parliament and who has called for assimilation of refugees into
Jordanian society.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here there are discriminatory practices and tribal values
which prevent Jordanians with Palestinian roots from occupying
leadership positions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, King Abdullah has taken pains to make
Palestinians feel at home. He earmarked $140,000 to build sports
clubs in refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   He allotted $50 million to pave roads and lay sewer pipes there.
</P>
<P>
   And last month, the king reserved 100 places at the country's
state universities for the sons and daughters of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But these moves have left some Jordanians with a sense of
insecurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Settling Palestinians in Jordan was a mistake from the very
beginning,'' said Ahmad Abbady, a Jordanian member of Parliament
who believes Palestinians should not hold Jordanian citizenship or
be allowed to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a country of very limited resources,'' he said.
``Sharing everything _ every piece of bread, every tank of water _
it means we (Jordanians) will suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinians insist that efforts to turn them into
Jordanians will not succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attempts in the past to erase their identity and make them
into something else have failed,'' said Nasir, the Palestinian
sociologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say, `I'll give you money, you sit here and become
Jordanian, forget Palestine.' This will never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In Awwad's living room an embroidered Palestinian flag hangs on
the wall. He can recount stories that his father used to tell about
his family's life in Kufr Anna, their village near Tel Aviv. But he
doesn't think he'll ever return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more Jordanian than Palestinian,'' he said, slowly
choosing his words. ``Since I enjoy all the benefits of a Jordanian
_ a passport, a right to speak _ yes, I am a Jordanian. I was
forced to make this choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
