<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TURKEY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON GENTLY CHIDES TURKEY ON HUMAN RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey _ President Clinton praised Turkey's democratic
progress in a speech to its Grand National Assembly on Monday even
as he gently nudged the country to strengthen its adherence to
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   On his first day of a state visit here, Clinton was clearly
trying not to offend his hosts. Even as he raised the delicate
issue of human rights violations, Clinton reassured Turkish
lawmakers that he was doing so as a friend and that the United
States has grappled with such problems itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind, I come from a nation that was founded on the
creed that all are created equal,'' Clinton said. ``And yet when we
were founded, we had slavery, women could not vote, even men could
not vote unless they owned property.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``I know something about the imperfect realization
of a country's ideas. We have had a long journey in America, from
our founding to where we are. But the journey has been worth
making.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke about the need for greater tolerance of free
expression, police were arresting scores of people staging an
unapproved protest of his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who won applause for his restrained remarks, made no
mention of a State Department report released this year that
complains of ``serious human rights abuses'' in Turkey, including
killings and torture by Turkish police and security officials.
</P>
<P>
   President Suleyman Demirel said Monday, speaking to reporters:
``It is impossible to say that there is no torture in Turkey. There
is torture. But torture is not state policy. Torture is a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with the country's leaders, Clinton highlighted
Turkey's strategic importance because it straddles both Europe and
Asia. Turkey is ringed, he noted, by neighbors such as Iran, Saddam
Hussein's Iraq and Yugoslavia _ countries that are ``either
actively hostile to democracy and peace, or struggling against
great obstacles to embrace democracy and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes Turkey's role in ensuring regional peace all the more
important, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pessimist might foresee a dark future,'' Clinton said. ``A
Middle East with the peace process shattered. Saddam's aggression
unchecked. Democracy collapsed in the Caucasus in Central Asia.
Extremism and terror spreading across the region. More violence in
the Balkans. Military coups. Unstoppable nuclear tensions in
Pakistan and India.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said there is another more optimistic vision _ ``one
that requires a strong Turkey playing its rightful role at the
crossroads of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also strongly backed Turkey's effort to join the
European Union, and commiserated with Turks about the deadly
earthquakes that have struck the country in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the Cold War ended, we have learned something quite
wonderful,'' Clinton said, speaking of the American ties with
Turkey. ``We have learned that our friendship does not depend upon
a common concern with the Soviet Union, and that in fact, in the
post-Cold War era, our partnership has become even more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   With a light rain falling, Clinton led a wreath-laying ceremony
Monday morning at the mausoleum for Mustafa Kemal Ataturk, the
revered founder of the modern Turkish state. And Clinton was
honored at a state dinner at the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dear friend, President Clinton, I see you as someone who
has contributed greatly to world peace,'' Demirel said in
presenting a state award to the American president. ``You have also
contributed to ensuring closer ties between Turkish and American
peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Relieving long-standing tensions between Turkey and Greece is
one of the prime goals of Clinton's trip. After attending a
security conference in Istanbul on Wednesday and Thursday, Clinton
will visit Athens to urge the Greeks to set age-old animosities
aside.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He told Turkish leaders: ``Believe me, I appreciate how much
history lies behind this troubled relationship. But people are
beginning to see the possibilities that can be created by a new and
better history.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed plans by the two factions in Cyprus to begin
talks in New York next month. ``I believe a negotiated settlement
is the best way to meet the fundamental interests of all the
parties, including real security for all Cypriots and an end to the
island's division,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With historical artifacts all around him in this ancient land,
Clinton urged Turks to continue their struggle for reform or risk
following the fate of failed civilizations past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must never forget that Turkey is built on the ruins of many
ancient civilizations that once were every bit as optimistic as we
are today,'' Clinton said. ``To avoid their fate, we must back up
our words and our hopes with deeds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
