<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0505 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS &LR;      11-15 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICAN OFFICIAL SAYS CLINTON OKS VOTE ON VIEQUES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Puerto Rican official said Monday that President
Clinton has agreed to submit to the voters of Vieques a proposed
compromise designed to end a seven-month standoff between the Navy
and Puerto Rico over future bombing on the island's target range.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Aguilar, press secretary for Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro
Rossello, said the governor and the president agreed during weekend
telephone negotiations to put the issue to a vote by the 9,300
residents of Vieques, probably in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If the voters on Vieques approved a resumption of target
practice on the firing range, the Navy would be able to keep its
timetable of using Vieques in early December for final combat
training by a Navy-Marine battle group led by the aircraft carrier
USS Dwight D. Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   The battle group is scheduled to sail for the Persian Gulf on
Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar, speaking in a telephone interview from San Juan, said
the referendum will probably be conducted on the island of Vieques
after Thanksgiving and within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will be asked to endorse one of at least two proposals.
None of the ballot propositions has been drafted yet.
</P>
<P>
   But Aguilar said the options would include proposed resumption
of routine Navy bombardment on the 899-acre live fire target range
that has been used to train Atlantic-based forces since 1941 and a
yet-to-be drafted White House proposal to reduce live fire
training, provide multimillion dollar economic assistance and have
the Navy withdraw within three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still in discussions with the president to determine
what alternative will be presented to the people of Vieques,''
Aguilar said. ``We are in the process of dialogue _ not of
negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   James Fallin, spokesman for the White House's National Security,
declined immediate comment on Aguilar's statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dialogue continues,'' Fallin said.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Pentagon official said the Clinton administration,
with the support of the Navy, has been weighing a proposal to
submit a proposed compromise to the voters of Vieques for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Clinton
administration officials are hopeful that substantial economic
development assistance, land turnovers, phased Navy withdrawal and
promised clean up of hazardous sites would be enough to rally ``a
silent majority'' of residents of Vieques to support limited
resumption of training by Navy-Marine Corps battle groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been giving thought for some time to the idea that
residents of Vieques should be given a voice in their future,'' the
official said, adding: ``We believe there is a good deal of wisdom
in that approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said that Clinton administration officials believe
that ordinary residents of Vieques would support a proposal for
continued Navy operations that included such incentives.
</P>
<P>
   A Navy proposal floated on Capitol Hill in October called for
$55 million in economic assistance over three years, a sum that
would work out to almost $6,000 in assistance for every man, woman
and child living on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello and other Puerto Rican political leaders have opposed
any resumption of Navy and Marine Corps bombing on Vieques in the
aftermath of an April 19 mishap. A Marine pilot mistakenly targeted
a range observation post with two 500 pound bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The accident killed Navy contract security guard David Sanes
Rodriguez, 35, and injured four other civilian employees on the
range.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the range has been closed. Dozens of protesters have
camped on the site to prevent any resumption of target practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor believes we have reached a critical point where
we should have civic consultation with the U.S. citizens on Vieques
who will be affected by any decision,'' Aguilar said. ``The
president agreed with this approach completely; he also believes it
is an important step in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar said that the governor came away from two lengthy
weekend telephone calls with the president convinced that Clinton
will not order resumption of live fire training on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello has threatened to seek a federal court injunction if
the White House orders _ or the Navy resumes _ live fire training
on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials also declined to discuss published reports
that Clinton would propose substituting inert bombs and shells for
the explosive ordnance that has alarmed local residents because of
the noise and fears that the chemicals in the high explosives may
be contributing to a higher rate of cancer on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Pentagon officials, led by Defense Secretary William
Cohen, urged Clinton at a White House meeting last Thursday to
immediately reopen the target range on Vieques to enable final
combat training by the Eisenhower battle group. Clinton, who left
Sunday for a 10-day trip to Turkey, Bulgaria, Kosovo, Italy and
Greece, returns to the nation's capital on Nov. 24 just in time for
the Thanksgiving weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is scheduled to return from a trip to South America on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy owns 22,000 acres of the 33,000 acres on the
picturesque Caribbean island located eight miles east of the main
island of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   More than 9,300 civilian residents live on a swathe of land
located about 10 miles from the beach-front target range where Navy
and Marine aviators based aboard aircraft carriers rehearse bombing
operations before deployment overseas
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Power can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
