<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-IRAN-FILM-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      11-15 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-FILM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN DARES TO FILM ISLAM'S STORY IN IRAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAFGH, Iran _ As an Emmy-winning documentary film director, Rob
Gardner has called ``Cut!'' in many far-flung locations, from Egypt
to Antarctica. But none of his previous ventures have called for
quite the tact and daring required for his current project, as the
first American filmmaker to be allowed to work in Iran since the
Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where Islamic hard-liners still gather to shout
``Death to America!'' on major anniversaries of the revolution,
Gardner has chosen the one topic that oddsmakers in Iran and
elsewhere might think most likely to detonate in an American
filmmaker's hands: the history of Islam as a faith, a culture and a
civilization, with pivotal sequences in the story re-enacted by a
cast of 150 Iranian actors and extras.
</P>
<P>
   In this desert town 350 miles southeast of Tehran, Gardner, 53,
has gone a step farther. For a three-part series titled ``Islam:
Empire of Faith'' that is on the PBS schedule for next fall, he has
been filming sequences that involve the life and death of Muhammad,
the Muslim prophet, a subject so sensitive that the merest hint of
a slight, however unintentional, could sink the project in a
moment.
</P>
<P>
   In Bafgh, as in five other Iranian towns where Gardner has
filmed, power still resides with the mullahs, or Muslim clerics,
men with a network of eyes and ears to scan for any hint of
apostasy. Although much in Iran is changing under a reform movement
headed by Muhummad Khatami, a Muslim cleric who was elected
president in 1997 on a pledge to curb the clergy's powers, almost
every day brings word of some new miscreant's arrest on allegations
of ``insulting Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   If this suggests that Gardner and his American crew have to
operate in a climate of rigid conformity, the reality is otherwise.
About the only stifling thing on the set in Bafgh has been the
heat, which was pushing toward 100 degrees on a recent morning as
the Iranian cast recreated the scenes in AD 632, when word of the
prophet's death in Mecca reached his distraught followers in
Medina, a Muslim holy city in what is now Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   In Medina, Muhammad raised the army that conquered Mecca,
setting the stage for the rapid sweep by Arab armies that
eventually carried Islam across Arabia, westward through North
Africa, Sicily and Spain, and north and east as far as modern
Turkey, Iran and Central Asia. The PBS series will begin with the
life of Muhammad and end with the reign of Suleiman the
Magnificent, the 16th-century Ottoman emperor whose era many
historians regard as one of the most glorious in the Islamic story.
</P>
<P>
   For hours, Gardner, shielded from heat and dust by a flowing
turban, shot and reshot the mourning scenes in an old caravanserai,
a mud-walled structure once used as a staging post by camel trains
crossing the desert. With women in flowing robes and face masks
wailing in a recess, a small army of ferocious-looking men, in
white robes and turbans, each with a luxuriant beard and mustache,
waved curved swords in the air in a trance-like dance of grief.
</P>
<P>
   During breaks, Americans and Iranians alike relaxed and chatted
over glasses of sugary tea and Coca-Cola, still available here
after 20 years of American economic boycotts. With the atmosphere
more like that of a party than a film set, Gardner chuckled at a
visitor's suggestion that the project, involving more than 40 days
of filming in Iran, was the filmmaker's equivalent of a high-wire
act _ exhilarating, but poised at the brink of disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 30 years of filming, I've never experienced the same degree
of simpatico,'' said Gardner, who is based in Baltimore. ``The more
connected we've become with the people here, the higher the comfort
level has become. We haven't had a single problem with the mullahs;
in fact, they've leant over backward to help us out. I think
they've concluded that we can help carry the message of Islam to
the world, and as long as we are doing it in a way that's sensitive
to their beliefs, they're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If that seems strange to Americans, I guess it's
because, psychologically, we are forever referencing the hostage
crisis of 1979,'' the seizure of the United States Embassy in
Tehran in the early months of the revolution, and the 444 days of
captivity for American diplomats that ensued. ``In the American
consciousness, it was the worst thing the Iranians could have done.
But to make this project work, all of us on this project have had
to get past it, and we have.''
</P>
<P>
   When they came to Iran last fall to scout locations, Gardner and
his wife, Char, 53, an assistant producer on the $1.5 million
project, were struck by the fact that filming costs in Iran,
lowered by the Iranian rial's steep devaluation against the dollar
since 1979, were lower than in Morocco, Tunisia, Egypt, Israel and
Turkey, other countries they considered. The abundance of
eye-catching Iranian locations _ desert sand dunes blue-tiled
mosques _ was another attraction.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple were also impressed by the talent in the Iranian
film industry, which, like other creative endeavors, has had
greater latitude _ not yet free of Islamic strictures, but far more
so than before _ since President Khatami's election. American
moviegoers have had a taste of the new Iranian cinema from feature
films like ``The Children of Heaven,'' Majid Majidi's story of a
brother and a sister struggling to survive poverty, which was among
the nominees for best foreign film at this year's Oscar
presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Getting approval to film from the Ministry of Islamic Guidance
and Culture _ despite its forbidding name, a stronghold of
Khatami's reformers _ was simple. Morteza Shayesteh, the project's
Iranian co-producer, said officials had issued a permit without
seeing a script.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked my opinion, I told them it would offer a positive
view of Islam, and they took my word,'' he said. ``These days,
there aren't official prescriptions for filmmakers anymore. It's up
to us _ we have to decide what we can do, and also what we can't
do.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But the Gardners faced more serious obstacles in Washington.
Under American sanctions, imposed at the time of the embassy
seizure and reinforced later to punish Iran for its alleged support
of international terrorism, the filmmakers needed a Treasury
Department exemption to bring computerized American filmmaking
equipment to Iran and to pay Iranian costs. The exemption was
granted only after after Gardner enlisted the support of Sen.
Barbara A. Mikulski, the Maryland Democrat. ``The initial reaction
was, `Hey, Iran's a terrorist state, you can't film there,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Iranians working with the Americans, there is delight at
what they see as a major breach in what Khatami has called ``the
wall of mistrust'' between the two countries. Majid Mir-Fakhraei,
48, the art director, has been crucial to the project's success,
finding remote locations, designing a credible seventh-century
wardrobe for the actors, recruiting stuntmen to ride horses and
camels in battle scenes and hiring 40 Bedouin men and women from
Iran's only Arab-majority province, Khuzhestan.
</P>
<P>
   But Mir-Fakhraei said Iran was the real winner. ``We have been
waiting a very long time for this,'' he said, looking like an
American filmmaker in jeans, sleeveless jerkin and baseball cap.
``It's very important for us to work with Americans, because in my
thinking the cinema belongs to them. We are learning so much _
about their new camera systems, their techniques, their working
attitudes _ that will make our cinema so much stronger in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most joyous endorsements came from extras and stuntmen
who enveloped a visitor during a filming break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very good, very good,'' a beaming Zabihpour Zabiholam, who
specializes in camel riding, said in English. Switching to Persian,
he said that Iranians longed for what Khatami calls ``a dialogue''
with America. ``A dialogue is what we want,'' Zabiholam said, ``and
inshallah'' _ an Arabic word meaning ``with God's grace'' _ ``we
will have it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
