<HEADLINE>
`KING ARTHUR' AND `LE BOURGEOIS GENTILHOMME': SEMISTAGED, FULLY
REALIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How many semistaged performances of semi-operas does
it take to add up to a satisfying whole? In the case of the
presentation of Purcell's ``King Arthur'' by William Christie and
Les Arts Florissants on Friday evening at Alice Tully Hall, one was
sufficient. And although the same cannot be said of Lully's
``Bourgeois Gentilhomme,'' which was added on Saturday evening,
that production made for a pleasant bonus.
</P>
<P>
   To identify these works simply by composers distorts their
nature if not the musically oriented productions here. For these
are rich, barely classifiable mixtures of ``straight'' theater,
dance and song. Each boasts a dramatic text by an illustrious
author: Dryden in ``King Arthur,'' Moliere in ``Le Bourgeois
Gentilhomme.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result they are difficult and expensive to produce, and
although Christie has staged ``King Arthur'' complete in London and
Paris, here, as in 1995 at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, he
offered a spare but elegant semistaging. In an informative
preconcert lecture on Friday he called these productions buskers'
versions. ``They're done on a shoestring,'' he said, ``and I'm
unabashed about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As well he might be. In ``King Arthur,'' in particular, with
direction and choreography by Ana Yepes and a condensation of the
text by Jeremy Sams, this semistaging in civilian dress held the
eye better and conveyed the spirit of the work more than many an
overblown production at the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Christie led a band of 16 from the harpsichord. Nine singers
took the solo parts and made up the chorus, and two actors, Satara
Lester and Patrick Cremin, metamorphosed into a variety of
characters. It all worked well here, since Dryden's players are
relatively few, and the text and music unfold in a steady balance,
so that compressing the text leaves a more or less continuous flow
of music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Le Bourgeois Gentilhomme'' was a different story, since
Moliere spins out a variety of characters, central and peripheral,
in this comedie-ballet, and the music is concentrated in the dance
finale, the ``Ballet des Nations.'' With few tunes in the first act
(actually, the first three acts, quickly skimmed here before
intermission), Sams' text resorts to joking about the lack of
music, promising more later.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lester and Cremin were valiant in trying to convey all the
characters, often in quicksilver succession, and Cremin was
delightfully obtuse as the doltish title figure. But the attempt to
mark characters by sharp accents rendered much of the text
incomprehensible, and to any music lover who knew the qualities of
the musicians onstage, all this compromised theatricality could
only prove frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   The music making was everywhere superb, as is to be expected
from Christie and his French forces.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although ``King Arthur'' can be heard in all its glory in an
Erato recording by Les Arts Florissants, the smaller-scale
performance here in no way disappointed. (And to have repeated the
stagy touches of the sneezes and the wind machine in the Chorus of
the Cold People might have been too predictable, in itself enough
to steer Christie away.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the singers, who, shamefully, were not individually
identified in the program, Gaelle Mechaly stood out charmingly in
several roles in ``King Arthur,'' including an irresistible
Philidel and Cupid. Francois Fauche (not even mentioned in the
programs) was as moving as the Cold Genius in ``King Arthur'' as he
was entertaining as the Mufti in ``Le Bourgeois Gentilhomme,''
ultimately losing control of a recalcitrant fake mustache.
</P>
<P>
   And Iain Paton, with his pliant tenor voice, sang lovely solos
by Lully and anchored the chorus on both nights.
</P>
<P>
   The little dance troupe _ with Ms. Yepes joined by Georges
Keraghel and, in ``Le Bourgeois Gentilhomme,'' Nick Nguyen _
overachieved, and the actions of the physically deft and game
singers fed nicely into a persuasive whole.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday especially, a viewer was left wondering what could be
better than a Christie semistaging. Only one thing sure: a Christie
staging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
