<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-HONORED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE KAYE SAYS HIGH COURT HOLDS NO APPEAL
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chief Judge Judith Kaye of the New York Court of
Appeals said on Monday that even if a U.S. Supreme Court vacancy
surfaces in the 14 remaining months of the Clinton administration,
``nothing could budge me'' away from her job as New York state's
top judge.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington to accept the prestigious William H. Rehnquist
Award for Judicial Excellence, Kaye suggested the question is moot
regardless of her personal wishes because there is no immediate
prospect of a vacancy among the nine U.S. Supreme Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in the running,'' she told a news conference. ``There
is no `running.'''
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation in September that Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg might leave the court after she underwent surgery Sept. 17
for colon cancer. But Ginsburg had recuperated sufficiently to take
her seat Oct. 4 on the high court's traditional opening day. Since
then, Ginsburg has not missed a day of oral arguments at the court.
</P>
<P>
   As chief judge, Kaye, 61, wears two hats. She is chief judge of
the New York Court of Appeals, the state's highest court. And she
presides over the New York State Unified Court System, with 363
courthouses, 1,200 paid judges and four million new cases a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could budge me out of the two seats I now occupy,''
Kaye said. She recalled that in 1993, there was media speculation
that she was on President Clinton's short list to fill the vacancy
of departing Justice Byron White.
</P>
<P>
   She had just come into her position in what she described as a
period of ``tumult'' in New York's legal system. She was referring
to the 1992 arrest of her predecessor Sol Wachtler after a bizarre
episode in which he assumed an alternate identity and threatened a
woman with whom he had carried on an affair.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said she let it be known that she was not interested in
going to Washington at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would betray a lack of character to be a
candidate for another office,'' she said. Clinton ultimately gave
the nod to Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored annually by the National Center for State Courts, the
Rehnquist award is bestowed annually on a jurist who displays
excellence in integrity, ethics, creativity, decisiveness, sound
judgment and other qualities. Kaye received the award Monday night
at a banquet at the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Warren, president of the Williamsburg, Va.-based center,
praised Kaye as a ``judicial innovator.'' He cited her work in
widening juror pools by abolishing many exemptions to service,
upgrading court facilities to make jury service more appealing and
establishing childcare centers at courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has in so many different ways re-engineered court
processes, not only to make them more efficient but more
effective,'' Warren said. Kaye has helped to ease the system's
staggering case burden by establishing special drug-treatment
courts that help addicts ``find some way out of the revolving
door'' of the criminal justice system, and domestic violence courts
to address spousal and child abuse, Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye told reporters the courts must do more to earn the respect
of average people who pass through them, especially the 600,000
state residents who are called for jury duty. ``Frankly, we've been
lazy,'' she said. Efforts to ``spiff ourselves up'' by, for
instance, fixing up court restrooms or emphasizing courtesy among
court personnel are only a beginning, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
