A0537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      11-15 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release TUESDAY AMs, November 16, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-DEAL (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Breaking a
self-imposed silence, negotiator George Mitchell says he is
``increasingly confident'' of a new deal on IRA arms. By Kevin
Cullen. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   US-CHINA (Ankara, Turkey) _ President Clinton announces a major
trade deal with China meant to reduce commercial barriers and
advance China's hoped-for entrance into the World Trade
Organization. By Susan Milligan. 1200 words. (i and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BUSINESS (Washington) _ The US-China trade agreement will
change life for a Chinese housewife who has never put her money in
a bank before, and for American businesses trying to peddle
telephones. By John Donnelly. 900 words. (i and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   UN-BOSNIA (New York) _ In a candid report, the UN blames itself
for failing to prevent the massacre of thousands of Bosnian Muslims
at Srebrenica, saying the campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' needed
to be met by more decisive policy. By Joe Lauria Jr. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-RECORDER (Newport, R.I.) _ Investigators, aided by Arabic
translators, scan the cockpit voice recording of doomed EgyptAir
Flight 990, trying to determine whether a criminal act caused the
plane to crash two weeks ago, killing all 217 on board. By Matthew
Brelis and Ann Scales. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHRITIS-THERAPY (Boston) _ A nutritional supplement called
glucosamine, already widely used by arthritis patients, retards the
joint deterioration of osteoarthritis, the most common form of the
crippling disease. By Richard A. Knox. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-ELECTIONS (Boston) _ Rhetoric rises over the Bay State's
clean elections law approved by voters, mangled by the Legislature,
and now sitting on Gov. Cellucci's desk. The law offers lofty aims,
many flaws, and the possibility that it will make it harder -- not
easier -- for challengers to defeat incumbents. By Michael
Rezendes. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-LOBBYIST (Boston) _ Federal judge wipes out the conviction of
former John Hancock lobbyist William Sawyer, citing a recent US
Supreme Court ruling which requires that prosecutors prove that any
gratuities given to legislators were tied to specific legislative
acts. By Shelley Murphy. 500 words. (a and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GILLETTE-DEGRAAN (Boston) _ Gillette appoints Edward F. DeGraan
to a new post, making him the apparent front-runner to eventually
succeed Michael Hawley, Gillette's new chairman and chief
executive. By Chris Reidy. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-ECONOMY (Boston) _ Report on Massachusetts' ``innovation
economy'' shows many good signs -- venture capital pouring in, lots
of new patents, lots of growth. But companies are struggling to get
qualified workers, suggesting Massachusetts may be a better place
to start a small business than to grow it into a big one. By Peter
Howe. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS-PATRIOTS (Foxborough, Mass.) -- By Nick Cafardo.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT (Foxborough, Mass.) -- By Ron Borges.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN (Foxborough, Mass.) _ By Will McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
