<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-US-CHINA-BOS &LR;      11-15 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US-CHINA TRADE DEAL EXPECTED TO OPEN DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey _ The United States and China have agreed on a
major trade deal meant to lower commercial barriers between the two
nations and advance China's hoped-for admission into the World
Trade Organization, President Clinton announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a relationship-building trip to Turkey, the president also
expressed enthusiastic support for Turkey's entry into the European
Union, a move he said would bring Islamic Turkey more fully into
the family of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Both China and Turkey have come under severe criticism for human
rights abuses. Turkey's rejection by the EU so far has been based
in part on its failure to stop the use of torture and protect
freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has made economic engagement a key part of his
foreign policy, suggested in a series of remarks Monday that
bringing the two nations closer to the West commercially would
ultimately encourage reform in human rights and other areas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with China ``is a profoundly important step in the
relationship between the United States and China,'' the president
said in comments to US Embassy employees in Ankara. ``The trade
agreement is part of a broader agreement, designed to bring China
into global systems on issues from nonproliferation to regional
security to environmental protection to human rights,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Turkish Grand National Assembly, Clinton tweaked
Turkey on its record on human rights and freedom of expression, but
he encouraged them with an acknowledgement that the United States,
too, has had a spotty history on personal freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind, I come from a nation that was founded on the
creed that all are created equal. And yet, when we were founded, we
had slavery, women could not vote, even men could not vote unless
they owned property,'' Clinton told the generally receptive group
of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know something about the imperfect realization of a
country's ideas. We have had a long journey in America, from our
founding to where we are,'' Clinton added. ``But the journey has
been worth making.''
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening trade ties with China is opposed by an unlikely
coalition of human rights activists, isolationists, and trade
protectionists. Turkey is also a favorite target of human rights
organizations and the Council of Europe for alleged use of torture,
extrajudicial executions, and repression of both the Kurdish
minority and those critical of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to say there is no torture in Turkey. There
is torture,'' Turkish President Suleyman Demirel bluntly admitted
to reporters. ``But torture is not state policy,'' he said, and
those who torture are ``penalized accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was much gentler, saying that while ``there is still far
more to be done'' before Turkey meets the standards set by the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights, Turkey is making progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that there has been a renewed and clear
determination of the Turkish government to take a stand against
torture and to generally increase protection of human rights,''
Clinton said at a joint news conference with Demirel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has no say over whether Turkey gets into the EU, but the
high-profile endorsement was important to the Turks from a public
relations perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials were crowing Monday about what
they presented as five important foreign policy advances in the
past few days: the trade agreement with China; progress in
negotiations over Nothern Ireland and the divided island of Cyprus;
a tentative deal to pay some $1 billion in back dues to the United
Nations; and solidifying American-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has truly been an important day for American foreign
policy,'' said National Security Adviser Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
   But the trade agreement with China, which, among other things,
lowers tariffs and gives American business more access to the
world's single biggest market, is sure to be met with objections in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers oppose giving China permanent Most Favored Nation
status on human rights grounds, and there has been more recent
irritation with China over a spy scandal involving nuclear weapons
secrets. In 1992, Clinton himself criticized former President
George Bush for bestowing the trade benefit on China, but he
reversed himself soon after he was elected president. Most Favored
Nation status lowers all tariffs on imports to the lowest rate
given any nation.
</P>
<P>
   The trade pact cannot go into effect without congressional
approval of a permanent, normal trading relationship with China.
The status has been granted on a year-to-year basis.
</P>
<P>
   Berger declined to predict whether Congress would give it
approval, or to say whether a ``no'' vote would kill the package.
``I hope it will have broad support,'' he told reporters in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would eliminate China's subsidies of its exports,
cut duties on imported goods from an overall average of 22.1
percent to 17 percent, allow American companies to provide consumer
financing for auto purchases, and expand importation of foreign
films to China.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Berger would characterize which nation made
greater concessions to arrive at a deal. It would be politically
troublesome at home for the Chinese to appear to cave into the
United States on trade after the US bombing of the Chinese Embassy
in Belgrade during the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The pact does not automatically bring China into the WTO, a
membership China dearly wants, but it does bring the Asian nation
one step closer to joining the trade club.
</P>
<P>
   China is expected to attend an upcoming session of the trade
organization in Seattle as an observer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
