<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SPACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida policymakers to go over Cape's commercial possibilities
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Florida's Space Coast was born from the
1950s Cold War race to reach orbit. During the heady days of Apollo
in the 1960s, the east coast of the Sunshine State became the
world's launch capital.
</P>
<P>
   Not so today.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the world of wireless electronics _ cell phones,
television, the Internet and more _ demands more satellites. To
send their hardware to space, companies now find cheaper contracts
for launches around the globe, including French Guiana in South
America and an oil rig in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials from all levels of government and economic
development are trying to protect their $4 billion space industry.
One key is to shifting Air Force-run Cape Canaveral from a
government bureaucracy to a commercial friendly enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept focusing on government rockets, and we did
commercial as we could. We probably rested on our laurels,'' said
Greg Moore, former director for legislative affairs for NASA at the
Kennedy Space Center. ``We were fat, dumb and happy for a long
time,''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, now senior director of space programs for Enterprise
Florida, which helped replace the state's commerce department, will
be among the industry representatives and policymakers gathered
today in Melbourne for the Florida Space Launch Symposium. The
topic is how the Cape can keep its share of the growing commercial
space market.
</P>
<P>
   Through 2009, nearly 1,500 satellites will be launched. Teal
Group Corp., a defense and aerospace market analysis company in
Virginia, estimated it would take more than 850 launches over the
next decade to propel more than $100 billion of satellites into
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the U.S. will not be able to meet the
demand for launches within the next 10 years,'' said Marcos
Caceres, Teal Group space analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of every 10 satellites are made in the United States. But
even with commercial launches comprising a majority of the Cape's
schedule, less than one-third of the world's commercial launches
take place in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're no longer alone in this business, '' said Adrian
Laffitte, director of the Atlas rocket program. ``We have to thrive
to be competitive. If we don't, we might have to go outside the
Cape. I don't think they want us to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Until four years ago, when commercial customers began finding
alternate liftoff sites, Florida held an unchallenged grip on
sending up expendable launch vehicles (ELV) like the Atlas rocket.
</P>
<P>
   But cheaper and more efficient sites, primarily the European-run
Arianespace near the equator in South America, have cut domestic
business. On top of that, government payloads at the Cape take
priority because tracking and telemetry for the launch range is
operated by Patrick Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to Arianespace, they take one customer at a time,''
said Rick Blucker, chief of plans and programs for the 45th Space
Wing. ``If you come here, you have to wait in line.''
</P>
<P>
   With the bureaucracy comes antiquation, another problem space
advocates are trying to fix.
</P>
<P>
   Budget cuts have left engineers with old equipment. Firing a
rocket one day then the Space Shuttle another means pulling cords
from a box much like a telephone operator from Mayberry would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the vacuum tube era,'' Blucker said.
</P>
<P>
   A $1 billion upgrade is under way, but some users complain it's
taking too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're headed toward working like an airport,'' said
Laffitte, the rocket manager and one of today's panelists. ``But
it's not fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The big market looming in the future is the reusable launch
vehicle (RLV). In theory, it could use a spaceport the same way an
airline uses Hartsfield. That's why groups in Texas, Oklahoma, New
Mexico, Idaho and other states are salivating at the prospect of
creating launch pads and landing strips for spaceplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Several RLVs are being developed. One of the potential prizes is
Lockheed Martin's VentureStar, a rocket that launches vertically
and lands like an airplane. The prototype, the X-33, is undergoing
testing with suborbital flights scheduled for next summer. However,
damage to a liquid hydrogen tank was discovered last week during
tests at NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed projects VentureStar will be operational by 2004,
though others are more pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe that any of the proposed RLVs will be
competitive within the next five years,'' declared a Teal Group
report from June. Teal projects it will be 5 to 10 years before
reusable rockets start impacting the marking and ``at least another
10 years before RLVs will be able to consistently offer the type of
prices necessary to begin to seriously expand the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, a satellite costs about $10,000 a pound to be launched
into orbit aboard an ELV _ costly especially if the launch fails.
On Monday, Japanese space officials destroyed an H-2 rocket loaded
with a satellite that would have been used for weather forecasting
and air traffic control. The launch and payload cost $229 million.
</P>
<P>
   But a spaceplane that could take-off and land once or twice a
week might create a demand volume that would cut cost by 90
percent. One day, such a plane might take tourists into space.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get launches affordable,'' Moore said, ``who knows what
people will launch.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
