<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0544 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-ART-795     11-15 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-ART-795&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT WILL HEAR A SCHOOL-PRAYER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ind., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The decades-old debate over school prayer finally
cycled back to the Supreme Court on Monday in the form of a
singularly American question, one that has as much to do with
culture as with either religion or law: Does it violate the
Constitution for one student to lead others in prayer before a
public high school football game?
</P>
<P>
   The court announced Monday that it would hear a small Texas
school district's appeal from a federal appeals court's ruling that
barred the highly popular and deeply entrenched practice of pregame
invocations. Despite the 1998 ruling, the student-led prayers have
continued in the Santa Fe Independent School District, near
Galveston, under the authority of a defiant federal district judge.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Texas, along with eight other states, filed a brief
urging the justices to hear the district's appeal; Gov. George W.
Bush was the only governor who signed the brief, with the other
states being represented only by their attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe district, which has about 4,000 students, had also
sought review of another portion of the appeals court's decision,
dealing with student-led prayers at graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which is based in New
Orleans, ruled that students could offer prayers at graduation as
long as the prayers were nonsectarian and nonproselytizing. The
school district complained that this limitation would require
school administrators ``to engage in official discrimination based
on religious viewpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices did not accept that portion of the appeal, although
if they decide that students can pray at football games, they may
be hard pressed to avoid entirely the question of what the students
can be permitted to say.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has never addressed the question of
student-led prayers at graduation, a practice that has grown up in
the aftermath of a 1992 Supreme Court decision, Lee vs. Weisman,
which held that public schools could not invite members of the
clergy to lead prayers at graduation.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe district's prayer policy was ``deliberately
designed to circumvent Lee through the use of student surrogates to
deliver prayers before a captive audience that school officials can
no longer deliver themselves,'' the lawyer for the two families who
had challenged the district's prayer practices told the justices in
the case on Monday, Santa Fe Independent School District vs. Doe,
No. 99-62. One family is Mormon and the other is Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Supreme Court has decided to look only at football
games, and not at commencements, the question is what relevant
differences, if any, the justices might find in the two settings.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer at graduations, at least clergy-led prayer, violates the
constitutional separation between church and state, because
students have little choice but to attend their graduation and
should not be made to feel like outsiders there by a religious
observance that is not their own, Justice Anthony Kennedy wrote for
the 5-4 majority in the 1992 case.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates of prayer at football games argue that an
after-school athletic event, where attendance is purely voluntary,
is not nearly as weighty as a high school graduation and that the
analysis of the 1992 decision is inapplicable.
</P>
<P>
   But in barring the football-game prayers, the 5th Circuit saw a
different polarity. While student-led commencement prayers were
justified by ``the singular context and singularly serious nature
of a graduation ceremony,'' the appeals court said, football games
did not merit such solemnizing treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very fact that football is so important in Texas ought to
be a reason for saying that prayer sanctioned by the government is
not appropriate,'' the Rev. Barry Lynn, a lawyer who is executive
director of Americans United for Separation of Church and State,
said in an interview Monday. On the other hand, he continued, ``the
court might see it as `just' a football game, and this might be a
school-prayer case they can give away by resolving narrowly.''
</P>
<P>
   The court has accepted this case at a time of heightened ferment
over religion in the public schools across a range of issues, from
the question of publicly financed computers in parochial schools _
a case the court will hear next month _ to the issue of ``school
choice'' and vouchers for parochial school tuition, which many
people think the justices will need to address in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Religion in the schools has also become a presidential campaign
topic, with Steve Forbes, a candidate for the Republican
nomination, calling for the posting of the Ten Commandments in
every classroom. The Supreme Court declared that practice
unconstitutional in a 1980 decision.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There were these other developments at the court Monday:
</P>
<P>
   Federalism
</P>
<P>
   Adding another important federalism case to a growing list, the
justices agreed to decide whether Congress had the constitutional
authority to make arson of a private residence a federal crime.
</P>
<P>
   A 1970 law prohibits the malicious damage or destruction by fire
of ``any building'' or other property ``used in interstate or
foreign commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The law's application to private homes has been in doubt for
years, particularly since a 1995 Supreme Court decision, United
States vs. Lopez, made it clear that Congress could not exercise
its authority to regulate interstate commerce over activity that
did not have a substantial connection to commerce _ in that case,
carrying a gun near a school.
</P>
<P>
   In the case on Monday, Jones vs. United States, No. 99-5739, a
man who was convicted under the federal arson law of throwing a
Molotov cocktail into a cousin's house in Fort Wayne, Ind.,
challenged the constitutionality of applying the law to those
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Chicago, found that
there was sufficient connection with interstate commerce because
the house was connected to an interstate gas line, carried a
mortgage from an out-of-state lender, and was insured by an
out-of-state insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   If the justices find those connections too insubstantial, they
may avoid striking the law down by finding that, as a matter of
statutory construction, Congress did not mean the law to apply to
private homes.
</P>
<P>
   Religious Meetings
</P>
<P>
   The court let stand a ruling by the federal appeals court in New
York that a self-described atheist could not be required, as a
condition of probation following a drunk-driving conviction, to
participate in Alcoholics Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's philosophy, involving acknowledgment of a
``power greater than ourselves,'' makes the meetings ``intensely
religious events,'' the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said in
ruling that required participation violated the separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County Department of Probation appealed the ruling,
which awarded $1 in damages to Robert Warner, the man who brought
the challenge. The case was Orange County vs. Warner, No. 99-24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
