<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-DEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL SIGNALS SETTLEMENT NEAR IN IRA ARMS SQUABBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Giving the clearest signal yet that
he has fashioned a compromise to break the deadlock over IRA
weapons that has stalled the peace process in Northern Ireland,
former US Senator George Mitchell indicated Monday he would wrap up
his diplomatic rescue mission here this week.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the 10-week effort to save the Good Friday
Agreement he brokered in April 1998 said Mitchell would not have
given such an upbeat public assessment unless he had been assured
that Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble was prepared to take the
compromise to his party council for approval.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise calls for the Ulster Unionists to drop their
longstanding refusal to form a local government that would include
two cabinet members from Sinn Fein, the political allies of the
Irish Republican Army. The unionists had been demanding that the
IRA first begin turning in weapons or declare unequivocally that
its war to force a British withdrawal from Northern Ireland is
over.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Trimble is prepared to risk his leadership of the biggest
party in Northern Ireland on assurances from both Sinn Fein and the
IRA that arms ``decommissioning'' will begin within weeks of the
local government being formed. Sinn Fein and the IRA are expected
to make conciliatory statements over the next two days to
strengthen Trimble's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the parties now understand each other's
concerns and requirements far better than before, and are committed
to resolving the current impasse. I am increasingly confident that
a way will be found to do so,'' Mitchell said, emerging from Castle
Buildings at Stormont to make a rare public statement during a
process he has insisted remain low key.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who two weeks ago was prepared to leave here without
having convinced British unionists and Irish republicans to cut a
deal, was smiling broadly Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there is an unforeseen hitch in a carefully orchestrated
series of confidence-building statements this week, Mitchell will
probably issue a final report Thursday and return to the United
States, where he is anxious to get back to his family and
Washington law practice.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell has been extremely cautious, and his remarks were being
widely interpreted as a signal that he has concluded that the
impasse has been broken. Mitchell made his remarks after meeting
Monday with Trimble, then with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams and its
chief negotiator, Martin McGuinness.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, a car arrived at Mitchell's offices carrying
the Roman Catholic leader in Ireland, Archbishop Sean Brady, and
two Belfast priests who have acted as go-betweens with the IRA, the
Rev. Alec Reid and the Rev. Gerry Reynolds. Reid arranged the 1988
meeting between Adams and moderate nationalist leader John Hume
that is considered the beginning of the current peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists' statements remained guarded. Trimble said
only that Monday marked ``the beginning of the process.'' Ken
Maginnis, the Unionists' security spokesman, was more upbeat,
saying, ``We're moving, hopefully, toward a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reg Empey, the Ulster Unionists' chief negotiator, stressed
that any deal was a two-way street.
</P>
<P>
   ``If unionism is to deliver an exclusive executive,
republicanism must deliver decommissioning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who canceled a visit to Boston this week because the
talks had dragged on so long, said he was encouraged by Mitchell's
assessment. He said disarming could happen only if the agreement is
fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``This review and the Good Friday Agreement are about making
politics work,'' said Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Sources predicted that events would unfold this way:
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein is expected to make a statement deploring violence,
and the IRA is expected to follow with its own statement. The two
statements are aimed at giving Trimble the political cover he needs
to convince his skeptical and divided party that it should take its
historical enemies in the republican movement at their word.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 27, Trimble is expected to seek the endorsement of the
approximately 800-member party council for his decision to
compromise on the party's ``no guns, no government'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-line unionists were already attacking Trimble, accusing him
of selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Trimble has given in on every issue,'' said Peter
Robinson, deputy leader of the Democratic Unionists, who oppose the
political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mandelson, the newly-appointed British secretary of state
for Northern Ireland, has been urging the Ulster Unionists to test
the republicans at their word, saying they can walk away later if
the republicans break their promises.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the parties that support the Good Friday Agreement
and the British and Irish governments agree that the formation of
the local government and the creation of cross-border authorities
representing mutual interests on the island ``should be established
at the earliest possible date.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is also common ground that decommissioning should occur as
quickly as possible,'' Mitchell said, and it should be overseen by
a commission led by retired Canadian General John de Chastelain. At
Mitchell's request, de Chastelain later called on loyalist and
republican paramilitary groups to designate representatives to work
out the logistics of disarming with his commission. The IRA is
expected to address that issue this week.
</P>
<P>
   De Chastelain said that if progress is made quickly, the
decommissioning of weapons could be completed by the target date of
next May.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent John O'Farrell contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
