<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LOWES-ARREST-COX     11-15 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOWES-ARREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lowe's bombing suspect faces federal charges
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _A 51-year-old Greensboro man, allegedly trying
to extort $250,000 from Lowe's Companies Inc., has been charged
with bombing two of the chain's stores and trying to bomb a third.
</P>
<P>
   George Rocha is also charged with mailing threatening letters
and interfering with interstate commerce, according to the arrest
warrant released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Identified as a former electronics store technician, Rocha made
his first court appearance in Greensboro Monday before a U.S.
magistrate. A preliminary hearing is scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal agents arrested Rocha at his home Friday
without incident.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged in the Sept. 22 bombings at Lowe's home
improvement stores in nearby Asheboro, N.C., and Salisbury, N.C.
The Asheboro blast seriously injured one woman. Six days later, an
unexploded bomb was found at a Lowe's store in Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   All three devices were ``fairly sophisticated,'' potentially
lethal pipe bombs, said Richard Fox, special agent in charge with
the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Fox added that investigators believe Rocha acted on his own and
that no further arrests are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents said that, on Sept. 22, Rocha wrote Lowe's
corporate headquarters in North Wilkesboro, N.C., threatening to
``keep bombing your 500 stores until you pay $250,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's received two identical letters Sept. 23, a day after the
two bombs went off. The letters said the bombings were in
retribution for a May 1 accident at Lowe's Motor Speedway in
Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's is a corporate sponsor at the track, where the May
accident killed three spectators and injured eight others.
Investigators concluded, however, that the bombings were not
connected to the speedway accident. In fact, Rocha was motivated by
his arrest in July 1998 at a Greensboro Lowe's for allegedly
producing price labels and affixing them to merchandise, the
warrant said.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged then with obtaining property under false
pretense. He pleaded guilty and was sentenced to 20 days in jail
and 12 months' probation and fined $100.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents credited Internet investigators for helping bring
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving another two threatening letters last week,
Lowe's wired $250,000 to an account in the Baltic state of Latvia.
The company acted out of concern for the safety of employees and
customers and to aid authorities in tracking down the suspect,
Lowe's spokesman Brian Peace said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the bank account was opened over the Internet,
using a fictitious name and driver's license. The address listed on
the account was for a Dunkin Donuts in Winston-Salem, N.C.
Investigators obtained an e-mail message that it said Rocha sent to
Paritate Bank, which identified itself as a European bank with
on-line banking services. Working with telephone company officials,
investigators traced the e-mail to Rocha's phone number in
Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
