<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0548 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE16-COX     11-15 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CCE announces strategy to fend off losses
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coke isn't a bargain-basement soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   And if it's sold that way, it will hurt the long-term financial
performance of Coca-Cola Co. and its bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   That message came through loud and clear Monday from Coca-Cola
Enterprises, the system's largest bottler. Atlanta-based CCE held a
conference call with industry analysts and large investors to
explain its strategy in the wake of recent price increases and a
pummeling on Wall Street, where its stock has fallen 38 percent so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, CCE is shifting its strategy from one based on
boosting case sales to one that relies more heavily on selling
higher priced products to increase profits. Some of the revenue
from the higher prices will then be used to support more intense
marketing and brand-building efforts to try to differentiate its
products from the competition, the company told analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This better be very effective marketing because it has to
overcome a natural tendency on the part of consumers to resist
purchasing more soft drinks when the price goes up,'' said Marc
Cohen, an analyst with Goldman Sachs. ``If they are effective, both
Coke and the bottler should be able to obtain their financial
objectives. If there is any hitch in the marketing execution, then
they may be finding themselves scrambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. already has announced plans to launch a new
marketing campaign for its flagship Coke Classic brand early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   CCE has raised North American supermarket prices by more than 4
percent this year, with further increases expected next year, even
though they will cut into the growth of case sales.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, starting in the fourth quarter, analysts said,
Coca-Cola Co. will be charging CCE about 5 percent to 7 percent
more for concentrate, which the bottler uses to make and distribute
soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   But profits will rise substantially during the next two years,
CCE executives told analysts, for two reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ When the supermarket price increase works its way down to
CCE's bottom line, it will more than offset the effect on case
sales, which will grow at a slower rate.
</P>
<P>
   _ The company will be focusing more of its efforts on the higher
priced beverages sold in vending machines and coolers that yield
greater profit margins than supermarkets do.
</P>
<P>
   The overall strategy will boost earnings per share by about 50
percent next year and another 50 percent in 2001, CCE officials
told analysts. For 1999, the company expects to earn 25 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, earnings per share will rise substantially even though
CCE predicted that North American case sales will increase
considerably less than what the company had predicted previously.
CCE now expects North American case sales to rise 3 percent to 4
percent next year, instead of 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There is a silver lining in the drop in case sales because CCE
can reduce its capital expenditures, such as those for trucks and
additional production lines. It can then redirect some of that
money into repurchasing its shares for what it believes to be a
bargain price now, as well as reducing its debt.
</P>
<P>
   But the moderation in case-sales growth for CCE could postpone
the day when Coca-Cola Co. reaches its long-term goal of 7 percent
to 8 percent annual growth in worldwide case sales, some analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Caroline Levy of Schroder &AMP; Co. said she expects it to
be 2001 before Coca-Cola Co. produces worldwide volume growth of 7
percent to 8 percent. Some other analysts think the company may
start hitting that target in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Volume growth is key to stock price appreciation, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts feel CCE stock is undervalued right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the conference call will mute investor
skepticism ... but the stock price should definitely go up,'' said
Marty Romm, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston. ``I don't
see any reason why the stock is down where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   CCE rose 25 cents Monday to close at $22.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. rose 75 cents to close at $58.25.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
