<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rollins, UPS team up
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service and Rollins Truck Leasing Corp.
have agreed to swap two business units.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based UPS said Monday it is buying Rollins Logistics and
will fold it into the fast-growing UPS Logistics Group, which
manages shipping, warehousing and inventory management for business
clients.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the delivery giant is selling its UPS Truck
Leasing unit and a 9,000-vehicle fleet to Rollins, based in
Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, the two companies also signed a
co-marketing agreement in which each will be the preferred provider
of services to the other.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes just days after UPS completed the biggest initial
public stock offering ever, issuing 109.4 million Class B shares at
$50 each, for a total value of $5.47 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the offering was aimed at creating a class of
public shares that could be used as currency in future
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   But UPS spokesman Norman Black said the Rollins deal doesn't
involve stock and didn't depend on the public offering to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something that had been in the works for quite a
while and just happens to be the first deal to occur after the
offering,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Black said UPS had decided last summer to put the truck leasing
unit up for sale. The decision to buy Rollins' logistics unit arose
during negotiations, he added.
</P>
<P>
   UPS didn't disclose how much it's paying for the Rollins
logistics unit, which has about 100 clients, or how much it's
getting for the truck leasing unit.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
