<HEADER>
A0555 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-TEX     11-15 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT AGREES TO HEAR SCHOOL-PRAYER CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court agreed on Monday to hear a case involving
what has emerged as one of Texas' most emotionally charged issues
this fall _ prayer and Friday night football.
</P>
<P>
   Whether organized, student-led prayer before high school
kickoffs can co-exist with the Constitution may finally be settled
in June, when the nine justices are expected to make a decision on
a four-year-old lawsuit out of Galveston County. It will be the
first major school prayer-related decision by the court in eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled they're going to hear it,'' said Richard Ownby,
superintendent of the Santa Fe school district, where the lawsuit
began in 1995. ``We hope that they find that our policy allowing an
invocation at a football game is legal.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of a U.S. 5th Circuit Court of Appeals decision early
this year declaring student-led prayers at football games
unconstitutional, the otherwise humdrum opening ceremonies at many
games took on far more meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Student rebellions, outraged small towns, clandestine prayers
and the opinions of Gov. George W. Bush and Congress all surfaced
during the latest battle between supporters of prayer at school and
defenders of the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``High school football is not a trivial matter in Texas to begin
with,'' said Frank Colosi, a Fort Worth attorney active with the
American Civil Liberties Union, which filed the lawsuit. ``There is
also the tendency to use schools as a testing ground to push
certain political issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU filed suit against the Santa Fe district on behalf of
two families, one Mormon and one Catholic, who objected to a litany
of practices in their public schools, including prayer before
football games. The families have remained anonymous, citing a fear
of community reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The initial U.S. district court ruling allowed organized prayer
at football games as long as it was ``nonsectarian and
non-proselytizing.'' The students and the school district appealed
to the 5th Circuit Court, which covers Texas, Louisiana and
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling announced in February, a panel of justices from the
5th Circuit Court declared any kind of organized prayer at public
school football games unconstitutional. Unorganized prayers in
places such as the locker room or field are constitutional,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe school board's current policy is to allow a
student, elected by other students, to speak before a football game
with whatever religious or secular message they choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school district has attempted to stake out a position of
neutrality with respect to matters of religion,'' said Lisa A.
Brown, a Houston lawyer who represents the district. ``The school
district is treating religious and non-religious speech in the same
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the policy contend that student-led or not, the
prayer is still sanctioned by the school district and has the
effect of excluding minority faiths, who may not have the same
opportunities to pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you start allowing prayer at school events, it
becomes a very slippery slope,'' said Anthony Griffin, the
Galveston attorney representing the parents. ``That opens up the
schools to prayer at every event, over the loudspeakers every
morning. I'm not sure the Court wants to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative groups advocating prayer in schools agree.
Kelly Shackelford, chief counsel for the Liberty Legal Institute in
Dallas, said he is a tad worried how the Supreme Court might rule
on the issue and considers Justices Anthony M. Kennedy and Sandra
Day O'Connor the critical votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not very good odds,'' Shackelford said. ``It's a
significant issue. There has never been a case of whether the
government is supposed to ban religious expression by a private
citizen. It's a dangerous step and I hope they don't start down
that road.''
</P>
<P>
   Most urban districts in Texas haven't had prayer at football
games in several years, but it remains a thorny issue in many other
districts. A number of suburban and small districts have skated
around the appeals court ruling, but many canceled all prayer until
the legal issue is settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am relieved that the Supreme Court'' is going to look at the
case, said Debbie Thomas, president of the Northwest school
district board. ``I hope that they will overturn the decision and I
hope they will allow prayer at football games. If they do not, and
it remains the law, we will continue to obey the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is further complicated by a ruling this year by the
11th Circuit Court of Appeals that said student-led prayers at
school functions in Georgia are constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did feel that given the conflict on this issue, that at some
point, they were going to need to take a case and address
student-initiated speech,'' Brown said. ``We hope at the end of the
day that we have a ruling that provides guidance to school
administrators and school board members.''
|Chris Vaughn, (817) 390-7547| |cvaughn\Nstar-telegram.com|
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
