<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-BEIJING-NY     11-15 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-BEIJING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BEIJING, TRADE PACT ELICITS JOY, CAUTION, INDIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHINA-U.S.-TRADE and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Many Chinese were pinching themselves Monday
afternoon, filled with disbelief that, after more than a decade of
false starts, China had actually taken the plunge into the
international economy, signing a landmark trade agreement with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   On a chilly gray afternoon in Beijing, many people were
ebullient when they first heard the news. For most people, it
raised the prospect of new opportunities to make money as well as
new chances to consume. The agreement drops many current
restrictions on trade and investment and reduces import taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's signed?'' said Li Dayong, 29, who works for an American
pharmaceutical firm. ``That's great! I'm thrilled! We've been
wanting this for so many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some took a macro view, welcoming the treaty as a sign of bigger
things: China's new economic muscle, an immutable commitment to
further economic reform and a renewal of relations with the United
States, which had been ravaged by the bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, in May.
</P>
<P>
   But Beijingers also seemed keenly aware that there will be
individual winners and losers along China's new path. Most are
paying careful attention to the micro view, calculating what the
trade agreement _ which is widely expected to lead to World Trade
Organization membership _ means for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news. I had planned to change my Daewoo for a
better car soon and now I'll buy an imported American one,'' said
Xu Yiang, a stock investor, referring to the Korean car he now
owns.
</P>
<P>
   Xu said he also plans to change his investment strategy, buying
telecommunications stocks that he deems likely to attract foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
   But Luan Wenqiang, a worker at Beijing Light Truck Co.,
predicted that the agreement would drive him out of his already
tenuous job. ``Our factory is already in bad shape,'' he said.
``Most workers are on leave and are called back only when there is
work to do. This will open China to better and cheaper U.S. trucks.
I don't believe we will survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, duties on imported vehicles will drop
dramatically, from the current rate of more than 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the hundreds of millions of Chinese who farm the land or
work as low-wage laborers in small cities and towns, Monday's
triumphant treaty was a big bang in another universe _ although
many will probably feel its effects.
</P>
<P>
   Half a dozen migrant workers interviewed in Beijing said they
had never heard of the trade organization, which has had only
fleeting recent mention in the press despite the frantic
negotiations here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with my life,'' said a middle-aged man, a
worker in a small machine factory, strapping a huge box of cabbage
to the back of an ancient bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   The new treaty will certainly bring both new investment and
intense competition to China and the outcome will vary from
industry to industry. But many corporate leaders seemed to relish
the challenge of being able to compete in the world arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely happy to hear about this,'' said Duan Yongji,
the chairman of China's giant Stone Group, a computer company.
``Everyone knows that entry will make the country more open and
that will bring more competitive pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we shouldn't need a greenhouse to protect us. And we also
hope that entry will open more opportunities for collaboration and
cooperation between Chinese and foreign companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Duan added that, at a personal level, he was relieved to hear
the government renew its vows, so to speak, to principles like
economic overhaul and engagement with the West. The Chinese
government has often appeared lukewarm on such concepts.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing's business districts, many owners of small businesses
likewise focused more on the opportunities of Monday's deal than
its risks.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign companies have opened offices here in the last five
years _ even though their activities were extremely circumscribed
by Chinese law _ gambling that this huge economy would one day
open. On Monday, people dared to imagine the payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Li Dayong, an American drug company employee, said that until
now his company had not been able to import many of its medicines
to China. ``Now I think it should become easier to bring foreign
medical products in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dai Liming, 35, well dressed in a sweater vest and suit, saw
only possibilities when he heard the news. Dai, who works as a
representative for a domestic trading company, predicted that ``the
deal will bring my company new opportunities for foreign trade.''
</P>
<P>
   But others offered more sober assessments, noting that many of
China's service industries _ from insurance to the Internet to
personal banking _ are young and ill prepared to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are already facing fierce competition from foreign
companies in some areas and if further concessions are made in the
insurance sector we'll be facing a grimmer future,'' said Lu
Youquan, manager of Antai Life Insurance Co. in Shanghai. ``Their
management is more efficient and their marketing skills more
aggressive. Nineteen ninety-nine has already been a bad year for us
_ we're losing clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lu said that he holds out hope that membership in the
World Trade Organization might give the economy a boost, and that
his company's business might improve despite the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this makes the cake larger,'' he said. ``If it does,
then everyone _including us _ can have a larger share.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
