A0557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-SLAVE-LABOR-N     11-15 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-SLAVE-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS REVIVED ON NAZI-ERA SLAVE-LABOR COMPENSATION  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ An improved offer from the German government and the
agreement of new companies to make payments have revived talks on
compensating Nazi-era slave laborers, opening the way for a round
of potentially decisive negotiations in Bonn that begin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   German officials said this month that the talks had been
postponed because leading companies and the government were not
ready to raise a proposal to pay $3.3 billion made last month in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief German mediator, Otto Lambsdorff, said on Monday
that the government had increased its offer by $555 million,
putting the total at $3.85 billion. He added that it was now up to
the corporations involved to raise their sums by similar amounts or
more.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a large engineering and automotive company,
Robert Bosch, said it would join the approximately 50 corporations
that have agreed to make payments toward compensating people forced
to work by the Nazis. Of the companies, most have declined to be
named, presumably because they would rather not be associated with
the use of slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 17 blue-chip companies, including Allianz, Bayer, BMW,
Commerzbank, DaimlerChrysler and Siemens, have stated a willingness
to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on both sides said there were signs that if the
government and businesses were able to raise the total to close to
$5.55 billion, or 10 billion marks, a settlement might be possible
at the Bonn meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a renewed determination to try and resolve this on
both sides,'' said Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat of
the United States. But he added that a further meeting after Bonn
would probably be needed to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   German corporations, concerned about their image in the United
States, are eager to find a reasonable settlement soon, and the
government wants to enter a new century with what is almost
certainly the last major Holocaust-related negotiation behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very good about Robert Bosch's coming in, and we sense
that an offer of 10 billion marks might bring an agreement,'' a
spokesman for the corporations, Wolfgang Gibowski, said. ``But
right now, I do not see that the companies I represent are able or
willing to go higher.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies are taking a guarded approach, in part apparently
because they feel they made a mistake at the last round of talks in
Washington by immediately putting their best offer on the table.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said the corporations had been encouraged to
push hard for a settlement by improved assurances from Washington
that an accord would provide them with protection from further
suits. At the same time, about 15 additional companies have come
forward since the Washington talks, meaning that the financial
burden fund would be spread wider.
</P>
<P>
   Since World War II, the German government has paid $80 billion
in war reparations, mostly to Jews who survived concentration camps
or fled. But German companies have never previously pooled their
resources to offer significant compensation to forced laborers,
generally non-Jews deported to Germany from Central and Eastern
European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have payments been made to a far smaller group of slave
laborers who were put to work in concentration camps and were
mainly Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer from New York who is representing people who have sued
German companies for compensation, Edward Fagan, said here on
Monday that he was dropping an earlier proposal for $12.5 billion
in favor of a much higher amount. ``This case won't be settled for
$10 billion or 10 billion marks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Jewish Claims Conference, an umbrella
organization that represents several Jewish groups, said an offer
of 10 billion marks could lead to a settlement. The advanced ages
of the surviving laborers and the strong desire of the German and
American governments to avert a protracted clash, the officials
said, have contributed to pressure for an accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
