A0561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIRTRAN-UNION-COX     11-15 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-UNION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Union asks for election, hopes to secure AirTran agent
representation
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The International Association of Machinists said it
will seek an election to represent airport and reservations agents
at AirTran Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The giant union filed a petition Monday with the National
Mediation Board, asking it to conduct an election, said Tony
Klinakis, international representative in the Machinists'
Riverdale, Ga., office.
</P>
<P>
   The union wants to represent some 1,600 AirTran agents, about
800 of them working at Hartsfield International Airport and the
carrier's nearby reservations center, Klinakis said.
</P>
<P>
   Another 350 work at a reservations center in Savannah, Ga., he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are low pay, but even more so the way people are
treated,'' he said. ``Working conditions need to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   AirTran spokeswoman Cara Maruskin said the carrier was aware of
the Machinists' organizing efforts but had no immediate comment on
the plan to seek an election. The Machinists union would not be the
first at AirTran, which is based in Orlando, Fla., but has its
flight hub at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots, flight attendants and mechanics already are represented
by unions.
</P>
<P>
   The agents, however, would become the biggest employee group
represented if the Machinists' effort is successful.
</P>
<P>
   Klinakis said the union had been organizing ``off and on'' ever
since AirTran's beginnings as ValuJet. ``Turnover has been so high
it's always been difficult,'' he said. To get an election, a union
must present the mediation board with signed election authorization
cards from at least 35 percent of the workers to be represented.
</P>
<P>
   Klinakis declined to say how many cards the union has collected.
But he said it never seeks an election without cards from at least
65 percent of its members, so as to assure a good chance of winning
an election if one is called.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
