A0563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HIAASEN-COLUMNS-NYTR     11-15 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIAASEN-COLUMNS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIAASEN'S `KICK ASS' IS A COLLECTION OF COLUMNS WITH THAT EXTRA
PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GARY KIRKLAND   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Carl Hiaasen the term ``kick ass'' is a job description for
a metro columnist. In that case, he's got some mighty sore feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kick Ass'' is also the title of his new book from the
University of Florida Press, a collection of his syndicated columns
published since 1985. All of his royalties from the book are going
to the University of Florida College of Journalism and
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   While Hiaasen's novels, such as ``Stormy Weather,'' ``Tourist
Season'' and ``Strip Tease,'' have been best sellers, this is the
first time he's offered up a selection of his nonfiction columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone in Des Moines, Iowa, who picks up this book, for them
it's not going to be that big of a jump from my fiction to my
nonfiction, because there's a lot of echoes and similarities you
can see in the columns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His co-worker at The Miami Herald, Dave Barry, described
Hiaasen's fiction as the ``Bunch of South Florida Wackos genre,''
which also accurately describes the real life people Hiaasen writes
about in his columns. South Florida facts are stranger than
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Like the crooked city commissioner, whose wife had an affair
with his defense lawyer during the trial, who then filed an appeal,
based on the affair _ or as summed up by Hiaasen, ``His wife was
doing with his lawyers what he was doing to the city of Miami all
these years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that edge, his sarcastic wise guy take on events, that puts
the spice in a Hiaasen column.
</P>
<P>
   Just as a boxer gives a twist of the wrist to add snap to a
punch, Hiaasen's power comes from powerful combinations of words,
like describing former Reform Party presidential candidate Ross
Perot as ``looking like a wall-eyed prairie dog on crystal meth.''
</P>
<P>
   And of state Sen. Alberto Gutman, who was under indictment when
he was re-elected, Hiaasen concluded, ``thanks for sending another
thief back to Tallahassee'' and suggested Gutman could be replaced
by ``any pimp off the street.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't write with such venom just to be mean. Hiaasen has
this strange idea that public officials should be honest, even
though he's made a career writing about those who aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to stay mad, to stay outraged. Even though it's
the umpteenth time you've seen one of your elected officials led
off in handcuffs it should be just as shocking, it should be just
as appalling as it was the first time,'' he said. ``There's no
excuse for the betrayal of the public trust.''
</P>
<P>
   And giving up isn't an option, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't walk away from it. If everybody who felt this way just
walked away, then you're turning it over to the heathens, turning
it over to the people who don't care about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman, for example, was supposed to be a public watchdog of the
health-care industry and was convicted of Medicare fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``How else do you treat someone who steals, someone who reaches
into your grandmother's pocketbook and steals money? He's no better
than a purse snatcher, except he's got a nice suit and an office in
Tallahassee,'' Hiaasen said.
</P>
<P>
   As Hiaasen talks, it's quickly apparent that writing isn't a job
but his passion. His goal in pointing out the politicians on the
take, the land rapers and corrupt building inspectors is to grab
people's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absolute worst sin you can commit as a writer is to be
boring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting their attention is the first step to getting them to
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get enough people reading, though, you will get them
thinking. You will maybe make them sit down and write that one
letter to a congressman or to the county commission or to the
mayor. That's not changing the world, but that's how you start,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Kick Ass'' readers will find little evidence of Hiaasen
committing that worst of journalistic sins. Editor Diane Stevenson
sorted through more than 1,300 columns to find those that stand up
over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stuff brings back funny memories, in the dark
sense of funny,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In looking over the work, did Hiaasen think he'd changed as a
writer?
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't think I've mellowed ... when I start to
mellow, I'm bailing out,'' he said. ``I'm not doing the readers any
favors by turning into some wise old sage.''
</P>
<P>
   If feasting on a collection of columns makes readers hungry for
a little fictional dessert, ``Sick Puppy'' is coming in January _
the villain is a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a complete whore, of course, he'll lobby for anybody.
He's not a one-industry lobbyist, he's an equal opportunity
whore,'' Hiaasen said. ``He's right out of how many columns I've
written? That guy, I didn't have to go very far to find him.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
