<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-WTO-1116-COX     11-15 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WTO-1116-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON HAILS CHINA WTO DEAL AS BOON FOR U.S. CONSUMERS,
INVESTORS
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey _ President Clinton hailed the landmark trade
accord U.S. negotiators struck Monday with China as a boon for
American workers and investors, saying the deal would boost the
American economy and generate new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's agreement, one of the most sweeping in U.S. trade
history, set the stage for China to join the 135-nation World Trade
Organization (WTO), which sets the rules of the road for the global
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement capped 13 years of intensive negotiations that
weathered some of the darkest moments in modern Sino-American
relations and the bump-and-grind of China's particularly rocky
journey away from the failings of decades of state-run industry.
</P>
<P>
   It was also seen as concrete evidence that U.S.-China relations
are at least partly back on track after a series of setbacks _
including allegations of nuclear spying by Beijing and the
inadvertent U.S. bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the pact, though, Clinton said, lies an epic
battle to broaden U.S. companies' access to China, home to
one-fifth of the world's people and one of the fastest-developing
economies in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today China embraces principles of economic openness,
innovation and competition that will bolster China's economic
reforms and advance the rule of law,'' said Clinton, who is here on
the first leg of a 10-day swing through southeastern Europe. ``The
agreement will create unprecedented opportunities for American
farmers, workers and companies to compete successfully in China's
market, while bringing increased prosperity to the people of
China.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said, though, that the accord would treat various
sectors of the economy very differently.
</P>
<P>
   It would help out highly educated workers in such service
industries as telecommunications and banking, these experts said,
while pushing out textile workers and others in lower-end
manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest gains are going to be in the service areas . . .
where the restrictions (on sales to China) have been extreme,''
said Nicholas Lardy, senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, a
Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also opens vast new opportunities for U.S.
investment in providing Internet services to China, said Lardy.
Internet business is an area expected to mushroom in the coming
decade as more and more of China's burgeoning middle class goes
on-line.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. cattle raisers and soybean farmers should benefit from
China's promise to widen its market to American foodstuffs. And
U.S. cotton and rice producers should be aided by China's promise
to end export subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said, though, that the agreement gives U.S.
manufacturers a green light to expand operations in China's
low-wage market and export the output back to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That, said trade expert Alan Tonelson, could cost thousands of
Americans their jobs over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts American workers in basically every core
manufacturing industry that you can think of _ electronics,
computers, increasingly aerospace, machine tools, those very
industries that make up the backbone of a modern manufacturing
economy and that create the best jobs,'' said Tonelson, research
fellow with the U.S. Business and Industry Council.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based association represents companies threatened
by increasing imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement is not about opening the Chinese market to
U.S.-based businesses,'' Tonelson said. ``The agreement is about
keeping the U.S. market open to the exports of Chinese factories
owned by the Fortune 500.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to concerns by organized labor, U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshevsky insisted on a number of
safeguards. A so-called ``import surge mechanism,'' for example,
allows for a 12-year adjustment period during which the White House
may limit the flow of Chinese goods when spikes in U.S. imports
threaten large numbers of American workers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's accord cleared away the last major impediment to
China's entry into the WTO. It must still settle outstanding issues
with the European Union and a host of developing countries, but
White House officials expect that will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Striking a WTO deal with China has been a major goal for
Clinton, who journeys to Seattle Nov. 30 to open a new round of WTO
negotiations. Expected to center on expanding market access for
agricultural goods and such services as finance, telecommunications
and technology, the Seattle trade negotiations are expected to last
for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rhongi were near
agreement over China's admission into the WTO last April. During a
visit to the White House by Zhu, however, Clinton confided that
Congress was too irritated over Beijing's alleged spying to support
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over China's entry into the WTO also reflects
the wider national debate over how closely to wed the U.S. economy
with those of developing nations around the world. In these
nations, wages are a fraction of U.S. levels and enforcement of
labor laws and environmental regulations tends to be lax.
</P>
<P>
   China has an added dimension. It's harsh record of stifling
political dissent _ etched in the Western mind by the bloody 1989
crackdown on student demonstrators in Beijing's Tiananmen Square _
and muzzling the press has prompted human rights groups to call for
economic sanctions against China, not increased trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself criticized U.S. engagement with China when he
first ran for president in 1992. He reversed himself his first year
in office, however, and has since become an aggressive proponent of
strengthening economic, political and even military ties with
China.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by international laws of supply and demand as much, if
not more, than by policy decisions, China's trade with the United
States has been booming since Beijing's late paramount leader Deng
Xiaoping set the country on a path of global trade and market
reforms in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   This year the United States is on track to import more than $70
billion worth of telephones, computers, toys, shoes, clothing and
other merchandise from China, which will buy less than $15 billion
worth of U.S.-made goods.
</P>
<P>
   That makes China roughly 5 percent of total U.S. two-way trade,
expected to top a record $2.1 trillion this year, based on Commerce
Department figures through July.
</P>
<P>
   That would amount to a $100-billion increase over last year's
level, almost all attributable to growing imports to feed a hungry
U.S. consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   While critics say the rising imports from China and other
nations is undercutting American workers, the White House argues
the opposite, contending that U.S. exports have fueled as much as
half of the overall growth that has powered the American economy
through the longest expansion in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the White House claims, growth in exports of U.S.
goods and services has created 1.3 million new jobs for Americans,
as unemployment has fallen from 6.9 percent to 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
