<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: 49ERS HIT BOTTOM
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BOB PADECKY   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif. 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Sunday it became official. The 49ers finally hit
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you may have thought the 49ers hit bottom last week when
they lost to the Steelers. Nah. That was Trump Tower compared to
this. The 49ers lost to the Saints on Sunday. Oops, check that.
They got smoked by the Saints. They were taunted by the Saints.
They were beaten the way your momma beats the rug on a clothesline
by the Saints. They suffered every humiliation except maybe trying
to run after the Saints tied their shoelaces together. And we're
still not sure of the shoelaces until we see the films.
</P>
<P>
   All ridicule is now possible. All ridicule is now permissible.
No word is too tasteless, no opinion too absurd, no scenario too
foolish. That's because nothing can be as obscene as the following
sentence: The Saints beat the 49ers by three, count 'em, three
touchdowns! Nothing you can say or do will ever make the hair on
the back of your neck stand up any straighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to wait until I gathered my thoughts,'' said coach
Steve Mariucci, ``I wouldn't be saying anything to anyone today.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mariucci had to be thinking the unthinkable. After what
happened Sunday, the 49ers might finish 3-13 this season. Who can
they beat? Everyone on their schedule has to look like a monster
truck to them right now. Even pathetic Cincinnati on Dec. 5th?
Sure, why not? If Billy Joe Tolliver can play like a Hall of Fame
quarterback Sunday, then so can Cincy's Jeff Blake in December. And
that game is in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers made Billy Joe Tolliver look like Billy Joe Montana.
Tolliver is the NFL poster boy for the nameless, faceless, totally
forgettable quarterback. He couldn't be more anonymous if he was Al
Gore's speechwriter. Yet he went 12 of 15 for 242 yards Sunday. He
ran for two touchdowns, which matched his total in the 75 previous
games he had played in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci probably wishes he had Tolliver. That would mean, of
course, a quarterback upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints beat the 49ers by three touchdowns! Even Eddie
DeBartolo Jr. wouldn't make that bet. Nor would anyone else. In the
15 times the Saints have beaten the 49ers over their 32-year
``rivalry'', New Orleans has never won by such a large margin.
Never. Just getting beat by the Saints is a news bulletin to a team
tethered to five Super Bowl trophies. But by 18 points, when the
Saints were on a seven-game losing streak, when they had lost 17 of
their last 21, well, this is throwing kitty litter on those five
trophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to get on a team early and dominate them or we'd hang
in there and find a way to win it at the end of the game,'' said
linebacker Ken Norton Jr. ``Now, it's like we are out of it in the
first quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Saints! That just can't be repeated enough. Through
the years, no matter how iffy the season was for the 49ers, there
always was the Saints. You always felt good about coming here, both
on Bourbon Street and inside the Superdome. New Orleans always was
a mood enhancer.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that the 49ers lost badly only to good teams. Now
they lose badly to bad teams. It's enough to make you run and hide.
The 49ers have. They played most of the game as if they were scared
of their own shadow. ``Who are these guys?'' Saints fans had to be
asking themselves. They were no streaks or post patterns. Steve
Stenstrom's longest pass was 18 yards. The 49ers ran Charlie Garner
and they ran Charlie Garner and they were hoping maybe the Saints
would get bored to death and Garner could break one. Hardly the
stuff acceptable to Super Bowl legends. Ah, then again, that wasn't
the worst of it, as dreary as that sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints were rubbing it in on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't you do it a little bit after everything you have been
through?'' asked 49ers safety Tim McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   As the outcome became more and more certain, by the second
quarter actually, as the 49ers offense was reduced to field goal
attempts, the Saints players began to let it out. All those years,
all that frustration, recent as well as past, surfaced. It was like
a blood-letting to relieve spiritual toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had beaten this team quite a few times,'' McDonald said,
``and now they had us down and they were letting us know it. I
can't tell you the number of times I was kicked, grabbed, poked
with some words being offered.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints were beating on a lame dog and they saw no reason to
apologize. The 49ers will have to get used to that. A lot of teams
are looking forward to payback. The 49ers are bottom feeders now,
that's how far they have fallen, and bottom feeders always get the
worst of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have seven games left,'' McDonald said. ``This could
get embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   It already is embarrassing. Sunday saw to that. The 49ers are
waaaaaay past embarrassing. They now have entered the funky realm
known as Groundhog Day for Losers, in which every game seems like
the last one played. Each Sunday teams treat the 49ers the same way
and it doesn't matter anymore even if one of those teams is New
Orleans, the team that has played so poorly over the years its fans
were the first to put a paper bag over their heads to hide their
shame. It is wearing apparel, one might think, that just might
catch on quite soon in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
