<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-INTERNET-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS WILL LEAVE INTERNET WINE SALES FOR ANOTHER YEAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress will apparently adjourn for the year
without advancing a crackdown on Internet alcohol sales, leaving
the issue on the shelf until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But both the wine industry and liquor wholesalers, while
disagreeing on what they want in a final measure, agree
congressional action is likely next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel like we are losing any momentum here,'' said
David Dickerson, spokesman for the Wine and Spirits Wholesalers of
America, a main advocate of clamping down on direct-to-consumer
sales. ``We feel like the congressional support is very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The wholesalers won an initial victory last May when the Senate
overwhelmingly adopted a provision that would allow states to use
federal courts to pursue out-of-state shippers who illegally send
alcohol into a state. Wholesalers argued the boom in Internet
shopping had spurred a rash of illegal shipments straight to
minors.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate proposal, offered by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.V., was
added to a contentious juvenile justice measure. That bill got
bogged down in disputes over gun control, preventing the Senate
liquor sales bill from being reconciled with a House version more
acceptable to the wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, thoroughly aired both in committee and on the
floor, grants federal court jurisdiction but prevents the law from
being used in the interest of ``mere economic protectionism.'' The
wine industry believes that language could help them in future
court fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a bill we can live with,'' said Simon Siegl, head of
the American Vinters Association.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesalers lobby is opposed to the interstate commerce
language. Siegl and others representing the wine industry believe
they are in a better position to prevail if the Senate takes up the
House bill or holds a Judiciary Committee ``markup'' on separate
legislation, particularly since Silicon Valley has weighed in
behind the House version.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House bill is not too bad,'' said Bobby Koch, chief
lobbyist for the Wine Institute. ``Further improvements can be made
on the Senate side.''
</P>
<P>
   Vintners believes the Internet presents a future growth
opportunity for them, particularly for smaller wineries which don't
have sufficient production to interest large wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   When the juvenile justice measure stalled, legislative allies of
the wine industry took precautions to prevent the Byrd provision
from being quietly tacked on to any of the remaining spending
measures moving through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This provision is extremely harmful to our nation's family
wineries as well as to consumers who are unable to purchase wine
through the wholesale-distributor network,'' wrote Rep. Mike
Thompson, D-Calif., in a letter urging President Clinton to veto
any measure containing the Byrd bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``More important, it is inextricably linked to larger issues
related to e-commerce and requires a context other than the
Juvenile Justice or an Appropriations bill,'' said Thompson, who
represents a prime grape-growing region.
</P>
<P>
   The wine industry believes its hand is strengthened as the fight
is prolonged and lawmakers learn more about the Prohibition-era
liquor distribution system that remains in existence .
</P>
<P>
   ``As each month clicks off and this issue remains unresolved, if
you are the wholesalers, you probably begin to wonder if this is a
smart effort,'' said Koch.
</P>
<P>
   But the wholesalers remain secure of their strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just like the old adage, we didn't lose the game, we
just ran out of time,'' said Dickerson. ``Luckily, we are going to
have another inning.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
