<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-FIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia firefighters get help for 'man-caused' blazes
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Major wildfires that have burned more than 1,400 acres
in northeast Georgia's ruggedly beautiful Blood Mountain Wilderness
Area were ``man-caused,'' an official with the U. S. Forest Service
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether the fires were set accidentally or
deliberately,'' said Dennis Daniel, district ranger with the Forest
Service in Blairsville, Ga. ``It could have been somebody smoking
out game or campers careless with fires or cigarettes. But there
has been no lightning that could have caused them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten more 20-person firefighting teams from as far away as Puerto
Rico and California, including two specially-trained ``Hot Shot''
crews, began arriving Monday to assist the 40 firefighters who
battled the blaze over the weekend, Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Three fires started at about the same time Saturday afternoon in
the 7,800-acre Wilderness Area, which sprawls across Georgia's
Lumpkin-Union county line. Two fires, which have since merged,
started within half a mile of each other and a third started about
a mile away, Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, fire engulfed a stretch of one of the state's
most popular hiking areas on Blood Mountain, which, at 4,450 feet,
is Georgia's highest point on the Appalachian Trail. The fires
forced officials to close a stretch of the trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so beautiful up there and now all of that's burning,''
said George Case, who owns Blood Mountain Cabins and Country Store
on Georgia Highway 19-129 between the small mountain communities of
Turner's Corner and Choestoe. Case said his property and five homes
across the highway were in no immediate danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can see the smoke and the fire's moving this way,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Foresters with the state Department of Natural Resources, the
Georgia Forestry Service and county firefighters were stationed
near private properties closest to the fires, including the
Walasi-Yi Center, a backpacking store and hiker hostel where the
Appalachian Trail crosses Georgia 19-129, Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to box up our stock,'' said Dorothy Hansen,
co-owner of the center. ``The fire has crested Blood Mountain and
is coming toward us. The firefighters tell us they're trying to
stop it before it gets to the highway, which is really their last
line of defense.''
</P>
<P>
   One fire burned to within half a mile of about 40
privately-owned homes in the Wilderness Area near Lake Winfield
Scott and heavy smoke was affecting residents of Turner's Gap
farther south, Daniel said. Homes in the Miller's Gap community
could be at risk if the fire changes course or spreads, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the fires are in federally-designated wilderness, strict
regulations ban the use of motorized firefighting equipment such as
bulldozers or backhoes. The Forest Service received permission to
use leaf blowers to keep burning leaves under control and chain
saws to protect private property. Helicopters are dumping water on
the blaze and dropping supplies to firefighters who must walk,
carrying their equipment, to remote areas where the fire is
burning.
</P>
<P>
   Strong northwest winds and dry forest conditions are hindering
firefighting efforts, Daniel said. Although drought conditions in
the area are not severe, northeast Georgia's rainfall total for the
year is more than 2 inches below normal.
</P>
<P>
   The ruggedness of the Wilderness Area also makes firefighting
difficult, Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all steep, rocky and bluffy out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jingle Davis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
