<HEADER>
A0580 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-CY-BOS &LR;      11-15 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
23-4 MARTINEZ EXPECTED TO REAP SECOND CY YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Only a handful of pitchers in baseball history have won
the Cy Young and Most Valuable Player awards in the same season,
and the last starting pitcher to do so was Boston's Roger Clemens
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   It could very well happen to another Red Sox starting pitcher
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez, who won the National League Cy Young award in
1997, will add the AL bookend Tuesday when the announcement is made
by the Baseball Writers Association of America. He will be the
third man to win Cy Youngs in both leagues; Gaylord Perry was the
first, and Randy Johnson became the second Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who went 23-4 in 29 starts, is a shoo-in for the
pitching honor; the suspense will come in two days, when the AL MVP
is announced.
</P>
<P>
   Young, the man for whom the award is named, had only two
200-strikeouts seasons in his glorious career (200 exactly in 1904
and 210 in 1905). Martinez is working on four straight _ 222, 305,
251, and 313.
</P>
<P>
   In leading the Sox to the playoffs in back-to-back seasons for
the first time since 1915-16, Martinez has won acclaim for bringing
back the electricity to Fenway Park. Clemens was worth the price of
admission every time he pitched in his '80s heyday. Likewise, all
eyes are on Martinez, sometimes even if he's just sitting in the
dugout. His excellence under immense pressure is much appreciated
by the Fenway Faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Martinez is personally responsible for a large
rise in attendance among Hispanic fans, who haven't come to Fenway
in such numbers since the days of Luis Tiant.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams, himself an award winner as the AL Manager of the
Year, saw NL Cy Young winners Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine, and John
Smoltz up close in his days as a coach with the Braves. Williams
said of Martinez, ``I've never seen a ballpark come to life like it
does when this kid pitches. It's so good to see. Just the
excitement and electricity he creates.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is a team man, and Williams appreciates that more than
anyone. During the season, the manager scratched Martinez from a
start because he arrived late to the park. Some feel that was the
turning point of the season for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship is one of respect,'' said Williams. ``He's a
very intelligent young man. He loves to play the game. He's a
tremendous asset to our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leadership is exemplified when he takes the ball. And we
learned to build on that. Maybe the individual who pitches the day
before him or the one who pitched the day after benefits. He has
been so successful for our team that it makes our pitching staff
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's the best? Clemens, Martinez, or Maddux?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't compare pitchers,'' said Williams. ``But considering
the innings, strikeouts, and magnitude of the games, I don't think
I saw a pitcher have a year like Pedro Martinez did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1904EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
