<HEADER>
A0581 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS &LR;      11-15 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS HUGE UNDECIDED VOTE IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown, viewed as a competent leader
who can keep the economy humming, leads challenger Tom Ammiano,
seen as a champion of the little guy who understands voters'
everyday concerns, according to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
   The poll by the San Francisco Examiner and KTVU-Channel 2 found
that 43 percent of those surveyed would vote for Brown and 33
percent would back Ammiano if the election were held now.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates, both Democrats, face a Dec. 14 run-off election.
They were the top vote-getters in the Nov. 2 general election.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that 24 percent of the voters surveyed had not
made up their minds with a month left before the Dec. 14 election.
</P>
<P>
   While Brown had an edge in the poll, more people have a positive
impression of Ammiano, a two-term member of the governing Board of
Supervisors who now serves as its president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they personally like Tom Ammiano more than Mayor Brown,
but they don't necessarily like him more than Brown to be mayor,''
said pollster Del Ali, who heads Research 2000 of Rockville, Md.,
and conducted the poll for the Examiner and KTVU-TV.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three percent of those surveyed rated Ammiano favorably
compared with 30 percent who gave him an unfavorable rating. As for
Brown, he was viewed favorably by 36 percent of those polled and
unfavorably by 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ali said in the issues that usually decide elections _
leadership, the economy and jobs _ ``Brown comes out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that people think Ammiano is honest and will
fight hard for the disadvantaged, but they are most concerned that
he would not accomplish things if he is elected mayor and that he
would have a hard time working with others at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ali predicted a vigorous campaign ahead that could be won
by Ammiano, whose unprecedented, last-minute write-in campaign
landed him in second place in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The random telephone poll, conducted this past Nov. 9-11,
surveyed 627 registered voters in San Francisco. It has a margin
for error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The poll painted a revealing portrait of how voters see the two
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the poll found, is most capable of encouraging economic
development in the city, and far outshines Ammiano in protecting
and creating jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano got high marks when voters were asked who best
understands the issues affecting the city's neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Brown largely has the support of corporate San Francisco in his
re-election bid, has been a pro-development mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy has pumped millions of extra dollars into the
city's budget. That has allowed Brown to provide pay increases to
city workers and expand services _ more money for parks, bus
service, child care, street cleaning _ all without raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   However, the growth in San Francisco has resulted in more
traffic congestion and skyrocketing housing prices. Brown has vowed
to tackle both problems if he is re-elected to another four-year
term.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano has been criticized by big business in San Francisco for
his suggestions to impose a city income tax on the rich, a tax on
stock transfers and to make businesses pay more for public transit
operations.
</P>
<P>
   He also has pushed hard for a minimum wage law in San Francisco
that would boost salaries to $11 an hour plus benefits for
thousands of low-paid workers whose employers hold contracts with
the city or lease city-owned property.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano contends that higher wages and better benefits would
generate more spending power and also ease the burden on social
services and health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also supports a living wage law, but said Ammiano's plan
goes too far and could bankrupt the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, who is seen as even more liberal than Brown, hopes to
court the conservative vote by focusing on his good-government and
anti-corruption positions.
</P>
<P>
   Voters view Brown as far more moderate than Ammiano, according
to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that 53 percent of the people thought Ammiano
would do a better job of instilling honesty and integrity at City
Hall. Just 33 percent believe Brown would do that.
</P>
</TEXT>
