<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ITALY-BIRTHRATE-ART-N     11-15 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-BIRTHRATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPERILED BY POPULATION LOSS, ITALIAN VILLAGE CONSIDERS A TAX ON
SINGLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Greece, Germany, France)  (ART ADV: Photos, NYT21 and NYT22, and a map are being sent.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VASTOGIRARDI, Italy _ At the Bar Sport, the cafe that serves as
this village's bachelor clubhouse, a government notice promising
financial aid to families with children is posted on the wall _
more as an inside joke than as a community news bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Di Benedetto, 40, the unmarried cafe owner, nudged Orazio
Izzi, 46, a regular, and said: ``What about him? He's been engaged
to the same woman for 22 years.'' Both men are confirmed bachelors,
and they are targets of the new mayor's war on singles.
</P>
<P>
   Aghast by the number of adult men and women who show no desire
to marry or have children _ 50 men and 20 women in a village of 823
people _ Mayor Vincenzo Venditti has threatened to levy a tax on
unmarried people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real problem, a serious problem,'' he said earnestly
as a group of single men grinned sheepishly behind him. ``We risk
losing everything, our culture, our traditions, our schools. It is
useless to ask for economic investment if we cannot keep our
village alive to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vastogirardi, a small village in the hills of Molise, a region
in southern Italy, is in many ways typical of rural areas
throughout Europe, where migration from small towns and falling
birthrates are producing a devastating demographic shift. The
population of Vastogirardi, known for its delicate hand-made
cheeses, has shrunk by two-thirds in the last 30 years as younger
people defected to better jobs and bigger towns. The only bank
closed down years ago, there is no movie theater, two of four
churches have closed, and the local priest commutes from a town 12
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far this year I have performed only two weddings, and six
funerals,'' said the priest, Father Erasmo. ``Nobody seems to
idealize the family anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only one baby was born in Vastogirardi.
</P>
<P>
   Birthrates are low all over Western Europe, but Italy and Spain,
Roman Catholic countries, have the lowest of all: an average of 1.2
children per woman, slightly lower than in Greece and considerably
lower than the rate of 2.1. in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There are objective reasons why Italy's birthrate is so low:
State aid to families with children is lower in Italy than in
France or Germany. There are also cultural differences; studies
show that in Italy women who work outside the home still bear the
brunt of domestic chores.
</P>
<P>
   Marzio Barbagli, a sociologist at the University of Bologna,
explained that Italian men had not yet adjusted their expectations
to accommodate working wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If women work at the office and also do everything in the
home, something has to give, and that tends to be a second child,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But sociologists are puzzled by a phenomenon that in Italy seems
to unite two clashing impulses: a new generation's yearning for
sexual freedom, and financial independence, mixed with an atavistic
reliance on parents for housing, food and doting companionship.
Scholars have written entire books on ``mammoni,'' Italian sons who
are so dependent on their mothers for care and pampering that they
never leave home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it is my fault,'' Ada Marracino, 70, said as she readied
lunch for her husband and two children, a son and daughter who are
both in their mid-40s, unmarried and living at home. ``These
children just don't count the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Alfredo, smiled sadly. ``It used to be the kids who
would look after the old people,'' he said. ``Around here, it is
the reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter, Vincenza, 43, is the village pharmacist. She
studied in Rome, then decided to return to her village 16 years
ago, where the family lives in a narrow apartment inside a
crumbling 1,000-year-old fortified stone hamlet above the village.
Now, only one other family lives there year-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I resented the way big cities eat up your time,'' she
explained. ``Here, I have time even to be bored.'' She said she
felt no social or family pressure to wed. ``I don't feel I have to
get married, just to be married,'' she said firmly, adding,
``Though lately, I have been thinking more about having children
someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes in social mores throughout the West are felt even in
remote Vastogirardi. There is little stigma left to premarital sex,
or spinsterhood, though divorce is still considered mildly
scandalous. The mayor would be delighted if some women chose single
motherhood, but few have.
</P>
<P>
   The disproportion between single men and single women, moreover,
is attributed to the environment. Numbingly boring for many women,
Vastogirardi is in many ways a bachelor's paradise: it offers
hunting, fishing, a soccer field, wine-making and a clubby local
cafe. Some of the same married men who lecture their single friends
on the need to settle down, at times sound ready to trade places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be free to stay out late, play music with my
friends and go hunting,'' Filippo D'Aloiso, a city council member,
said wistfully as he sat in the dining room of Izzi's camping
ground, sampling the home-made pasta, made by the mother of another
local bachelor. ``But I have a child. I have to make sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   Venditti figures that unless something dramatic is done to
increase birthrates quickly, the village nursery school will have
to close down. To give locals work, he wants to start a cooperative
dairy and export local cheeses. ``The town can provide the cows and
the fields,'' he said, ``but I cannot produce the babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Already there are not enough children to fill the elementary
school: first and third grades are taught together, as are fourth
and fifth graders.
</P>
<P>
   There is no middle or high school. Venditti, who actually lives
in Isernia, a town 21 miles away, so his teen-age children will not
have to take a bus to school, concedes that his tax on singles will
probably be ruled unconstitutional, but he said he had to serve
notice to the town, and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are 20 years too late,'' Stella Scocchera, scolded him
furiously. Mrs. Scocchera, who has taught kindergarten since 1976,
is convinced that she will be out of a job within two years. She
blames local residents who have taken the easy route and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are looking at the last kindergarten class of
Vastogirardi,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if some of these oafs do get married,'' she added,
pulling at Izzi's sleeve. ``They will never have enough children to
make up a real kindergarten. You can't do a ring-around-the-roses
with only two kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
