<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0587 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GILLETTE-DEGRAAN-BOS &LR;      11-15 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-DEGRAAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEGRAAN AN EXECUTIVE VP, HEIGHTENING GILLETTE SUCCESSON RUMORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Edward F. DeGraan has been appointed to a new post at
Gillette Co., its board of directors confirmed Monday, a move that
makes him the apparent front-runner in the race to eventually
succeed Michael C. Hawley, 61, Gillette's chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston razor giant declined to comment on the issue of
succession, and the 56-year-old DeGraan, who joined Gillette in
1968, will continue as executive vice president, one of four men
who hold that title.
</P>
<P>
   But in today's global business environment, the issue of
succession has become more crucial than ever. While Gillette has
often looked inside to promote executives, an ever-changing
marketplace and higher turnover at the top make it important for
corporations to have succession plans in place.
</P>
<P>
   The new duties that DeGraan is set to assume Jan. 1 could
seemingly make him the second most powerful individual in the
company after Hawley, who rose to the top jobs seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed that when Gillette's board eventually
decides on Hawley's successor, it will likely choose from among the
company's four executive vice presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gillette has a world-class management team,'' said company
spokesman Eric A. Kraus Monday. ``The board of directors is
continuously evaluating management succession, and there are a
number of internal candidates with outstanding qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new job, DeGraan will be responsible for managing all of
Gillette's product lines and all new product development.
</P>
<P>
   ``By placing management of all the company's product lines under
a single reporting structure, we can take even greater advantage of
the synergies inherent in the development, manufacture, and
strategic development of our products,'' Hawley said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, DeGraan supervises Gillette's grooming and
Duracell battery lines, which accounted for about two-thirds of
Gillette's overall 1998 sales of $10.06 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Executive vice president Archie Livis, who now manages Braun,
Oral-B, and stationery products lines, is also set to take on a new
assignment Jan. 1, developing strategic growth initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   At the Harvard Business School, associate professor Michael
Watkins studies succession at large companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making sure you're grooming multiple candidates and keeping
some ambiguity until very late in the game'' are often the keys to
making the right choice for a chief executive, said Watkins, a
co-author of a recent Harvard Business Review article titled ``The
Successor's Dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambiguity is needed so potential candidates can be tested and
groomed almost until the last minute, Watkins said. Ensuring that
succession works may be one of the most important jobs a board of
directors and chief executive must face, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, when Livis' current duties will be added to
DeGraan's, one of the strategic initiatives Livis may pursue is
what Gillette should do with some of its underperforming Braun and
stationery divisions, which are made up of such brands as Paper
Mate, Parker, and Waterman pens.
</P>
<P>
   For the most of the 1990s, Gillette turned in robust sales and
profit gains. But in the last two years, Gillette has faced two
issues: economic and currency problems in some of its overseas
markets, and the drag that the Braun and stationery divisions has
placed on its strong razor, grooming, oral care, and Duracell
battery businesses.
</P>
<P>
   As Gillette has grappled with these problems, the value of its
stock has plummeted. On the New York Stock Exchange Monday,
Gillette shares fell 3/8 to close at 35 1/16, far below a 52-week
high of 64 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Gillette's core products for hair removal, oral
care, and portable power represent nearly 90 percent of company
profits, Hawley suggested recently that Gillette will consider
selling or discontinuing any lagging category or product line.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it likely Gillette could exit the stationery business
and some Braun household appliance lines, such as coffee makers and
toasters.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for Braun's electric shavers and toothbrushes have been
much stronger, and Gillette would likely hang on to those lines.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to move to the next level and put problems behind it,
Gillette announced a sweeping reorganization 14 months ago. Part of
that plan included cutting Gillette's work force by 11 percent over
a 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gillette's management team was realigned into two
distinct functions: global business management and commercial
operations. Each of those functions was headed by two executive
vice presidents.
</P>
<P>
   DeGraan and Livis were put in charge of manufacturing and
product development. On the commercial operations side, Robert G.
King, 54, was given responsibilities for the Western Hemishpere and
Jorgen Wedel, 51, for the Eastern Hemisphere. Neither King's nor
Wedel's duties are expected to change as a result of DeGraan's and
Livis' new assignments.
</P>
<P>
   While Gillette declined to comment about succession, having a
designated successor can be vital for a company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Gillette chairman and chief executive Colman M. Mockler
died suddenly at 61, only weeks after Alfred M. Zeien had been
chosen as president. Gillette's board appointed Zeien to the top
job a short time later, and Zeien held the titles of chairman and
chief executive until he retired this past spring.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Hawley was appointed president.
</P>
<P>
   The president's title has remained vacant since Hawley assumed
the top jobs in April, and spokesman Kraus said Gillette has ``no
plan at this time to name a president.'' In the last decade, the
title of president has been occupied only about half the time,
Kraus added.
</P>
<P>
   At 61, Hawley would seemingly be in no hurry to retire. That
would give him and the board some time to deal with succession.
</P>
<P>
   And it is possible that Hawley could stay on after his 65th
birthday, as Zeien did.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's board approved several incentive packages to induce
Zeien to delay his retirment. Zeien was 69 when he retired earlier
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
