<SLUG> BC-ARTHRITIES-THERAPY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS BENEFIT OF SUPPLEMENT TO ARTHRITIS SUFFERERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A dietary supplement made from crab, lobster, and
shrimp shells protects arthritic joints against deterioration,
according to a three-year European study discussed Monday at a
major rheumatology meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The study marks one of the first times that a large, rigorous
human study has verified the effectiveness of an ``alternative''
therapy that has developed a wide following through nonscientific,
word-of-mouth recommendations. Health food stores and drug stores
sell the supplement, glucosamine sulfate, for 80 cents to $1.30 per
1,500 &UR;  &LR; milligram dose.
</P>
<P>
   The finding also provides one of the first hints that any
treatment can alter the inexorable course of osteoarthritis. The
joint-destroying malady afflicts at least 21 million Americans and
causes more disability than any disorder except heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Before-and-after X-ray pictures of 212 osteoarthritis patients
showed that 22 percent of those taking a daily 1,500 &UR;  &LR; milligram
glucosamine pill had deterioration in their knee joints, compared
to 38 percent of patients who unknowingly took a placebo, or dummy
pill.
</P>
<P>
   Pain, stiffness, and physical function improved somewhat in the
glucosamine patients over three years, while they worsened in the
placebo group, said Dr. Jean-Yves Reginster of the University of
Liege in Belgium. He will formally present the results Wednesday at
a session of the American College of Rheumatology.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how glucosamine sulfate might prevent the cartilage
that lines and cushions joints from wearing away. One US study
presented Monday suggests one form of glucosamine may block nitrous
oxide, a chemical that breaks down cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   The European study was funded by a manufacturer of glucosamine
sulfate, an Italian firm called Rotta Research Laboratory. But
arthritis experts said its findings were nonetheless credible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study meets the test that alternative-therapy studies
need to meet in order to merit attention,'' said Dr. William J.
Arnold, a Chicago rheumatologist.
</P>
<P>
   The Arthritis Foundation, a nonprofit research and service
group, said the study suggests that glucosamine sulfate ``relieves
symptoms and helps to prevent damage to joint cartilage'' in
osteoarthritis patients. The supplement ``can be considered a
viable option'' along with traditional treatments such as pain
medicines, anti-inflammatory drugs, and exercise, the foundation
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of glucosamine's emerging respectability is that
the National Institutes of Health is about to launch a $6.6 million
arthritis study of glucosamine sulfate and another widely used
dietary supplement, chondroitin sulfate.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of osteoarthritis patients are already taking
glucosamine supplements every day, leading arthritis specialists
say. Some doctors are even taking it themselves to prevent
arthritis, although experts said there is no evidence at all to
suggest that glucosamine can prevent the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence does not indicate that glucosamine is a cure
for arthritis, despite a popular recent book, ``The Arthritis
Cure,'' whose title made that claim.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc C. Hochberg of the University of Maryland said about
half his osteoarthritis patients take glucosamine supplements
because they believe it helps them ``modestly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If patients want to take glucosamine, I say fine,'' Hochberg
said in an interview. ``If they see no effect in 12 weeks, I
recommend they discontinue it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Felson of Boston University Medical School, who also
suggests glucosamine to some osteoarthritis patients, called the
results noteworthy. ``There have been smaller, more obscure studies
on glucosamine that have suggested the same thing, but they have
not been as well-done,'' Felson said.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with glucosamine in this country, specialists said,
is that the substance is considered a nutritional supplement and
not a drug. Thus, the US Food and Drug Administration does not
regulate what is actually in commercial preparations, which may
contain widely varying doses of glucosamine or even none at all, as
well as other adulterants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HOMESTEAD16-COX     11-15 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESTEAD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLORIDA, TEXAS PROTECTION FOR DEBTORS IN JEOPARDY AFTER SENATE
VOTE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Florida and Texas would lose their status as havens
for rich debtors, if a new provision for the nation's bankruptcy
laws prevails.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate voted overwhelmingly last week to set a limit of
$100,000 for home equity that would be shielded from creditors in
bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, the measure would override the Florida and Texas
state constitutions. Both have given their residents unlimited
exemptions for their homes for more than a century. Such protection
has given the states a reputation as sanctuaries for wealthy
deadbeats.
</P>
<P>
   In one famous cases, an Ohio businessman, Marvin Warner, spent
28 months in prison for his dealings in the collapse of an Ohio
savings and loan. Yet he was able to settle on a $2.2 million horse
farm near Ocala, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Burt Reynolds was allowed to keep his $1.17 million home
in Hobe
</P>
<P>
   Sound after claiming $10 million in debts in his 1996
bankruptcy. Former baseball commissioner Bowie Kuhn retired to a
multi-million-dollar home near Jacksonville despite owing millions
when his New York law firm went belly up.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth, Texas, millionaire T. Cullen Davis, once a defendant
in two murders at his mansion, was able to avoid paying alimony to
his ex-wife by claiming the homestead exemption in bankruptcy
court.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bad publicity of such cases, the unlimited
protection for homes has long been considered sacrosanct by its
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the side that (debtors) shouldn't be allowed to delay,
defraud or hinder creditors'' by moving to Florida, Daniel Bakst, a
West Palm Beach, Fla., bankruptcy attorney, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he opposed changing the state laws for
residents who have bought homes with the understanding that they
would have unlimited protection. The exemption extends to a
half-acre in a city or 160 acres in rural area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the state make those changes,'' he said. Federal courts
could help by tightening rulings on debt avoidance, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lowering the limits would affect only a few homeowners, however.
A U.S. General Accounting Office study of bankruptcies in Florida
and Texas found that 1 percent or less involved equity of $100,000
or more.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, the revision still faces major obstacles, including
the opposition of a political odd couple.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Republican, has teamed with
Florida Sen. Bob Graham, a Democrat, to reverse the vote by their
colleagues. Together they have argued that states, not the federal
government, should set bankruptcy rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``These laws reflect the core values and traditions of our
states,'' said a letter circulated last summer by Hutchison,
Graham, and Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, Iowa and South Dakota are the other three states with
unlimited bankruptcy protection for home equity. Other states vary
from offering no exemption to more modest ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``A one-size-fits-all order from Washington is not the right
answer,'' said Hutchison in a column released Monday for Texas
papers.
</P>
<P>
   An aide said that Hutchison would ``do whatever it takes,''
including leading a filibuster, to stop the $100,000 limit if it is
included in the final bill. The measure is part of a major
bankruptcy reform bill that has passed the House, whose version
would allow states to opt out of the homestead limit.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was expected to attempt to complete its version on
Wednesday. A final House-Senate compromise would then have to be
forged, probably next year.
</P>
<P>
   (trim line)
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to change the law in the Florida state legislature have
consistently failed, despite support from two strong lobbies, the
banks and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a proposal to cap the homestead exemption at $250,000
was
</P>
<P>
   defeated. And two years ago, the Constitution Revision
Commission
</P>
<P>
   considered a $500,000 cap before scrapping the idea altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Florida House voted to allow creditors to collect
when
</P>
<P>
   someone has ``fraudulently'' put money into his or her home
right before
</P>
<P>
   filing for bankruptcy. But the Senate did not take up the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be thrilled to see something happen at the
congressional
</P>
<P>
   level,'' said Deborah Lawson, a lobbyist for a coalition of
businesses
</P>
<P>
   who support curbing the exemption. ``It would prohibit these
people who,
</P>
<P>
   in our opinion, thumb their nose at people they owe money to.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes to the homestead exemption have been opposed by Florida
</P>
<P>
   doctors' groups, among others. Rep. Johnnie Byrd, R-Plant City,
the
</P>
<P>
   majority whip in the Florida House of Representatives, said the
</P>
<P>
   unlimited cap should be maintained to protect Florida's large
population
</P>
<P>
   of retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd objects to a cap because it must be constantly adjusted,
forcing
</P>
<P>
   Congress to decide the reasonable value for a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I do not like is the federal government doing a one
size
</P>
<P>
   fits all approach to things,'' Byrd said. ``There's certainly
abuses of
</P>
<P>
   anything. Does that mean we want to create more bureaucracy?''
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate bill passes, it would affect Florida homeowners
</P>
<P>
   involved in only bankruptcy. The exemption would still protect
all homes from
</P>
<P>
   other court orders, such as judgments in lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post reporter Scott Hiaasen contributed to this
report
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
