<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0597 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-LOBBYIST-BOS &LR;      11-15 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-LOBBYIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE VOIDS HANCOCK LOBBYIST'S CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three years after former Beacon Hill lobbyist F.
William Sawyer was convicted of mail fraud for treating state
legislators to rounds of golf, a federal judge Monday tossed out
the conviction, calling it ``a legal error of fundamental
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing a recent US Supreme Court ruling that clarified the
federal gratuities law, US District Judge Edward F. Harrington
concluded that it wasn't illegal for Sawyer to send a $183 check to
a Cape Cod golf club for a game with legislators while he was
working as a lobbyist for the John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said Sawyer's guilty plea to federal mail fraud in
November 1996 was invalid because prosecutors failed to prove that
legislators performed any official act because Sawyer picked up
their golf tabs and it was entirely possible that he was merely
acting out of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer spent one year on probation and was fined $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a person to be branded a felon for an act which is not
criminal corrupts the very heart of due process,'' wrote
Harrington, who expunged the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's ruling is also at the heart of a related case
involving former state Rep. Francis Woodward, who chaired the
Insurance Committee and was convicted of fraud and bribery in 1996
for accepting about $7,400 in free meals, golf games and a trip to
the Super Bowl from Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Douglas P. Woodlock held a hearing in July and
has yet to rule on Woodward's request to vacate his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Thomas R. Kiley, who represents Sawyer, said, ``Bill
has been fighting for his name for a long time. For Bill Sawyer and
Frank Woodward, who are really salt of the earth people, to be
poster boys for the notion of corruption is just so hellacious that
the real fight has been to vindicate their names.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled unanimously last April that jurors
couldn't convict Sun-Diamond Growers of California of giving $5,900
in illegal gratuities to former Secretary of Agriculture Mike Espy
because there was no evidence that the gifts were linked to any
official act.
</P>
<P>
   The court concluded that it isn't enough for prosecutors to show
that gift-givers wanted to curry favor with officials in a position
to help them.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the court said, prosecutors have to tie the gift-giving
to an official act performed or about to be performed.
</P>
<P>
   In Sawyer's case, he wasn't charged under the federal gratuities
law. But Harrington concluded that the Supreme Court ruling still
applies.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer was convicted in 1995 of conspiracy, bribery and fraud,
but the case was overturned by a federal appeals court that said
jurors should have been instructed that, to find Sawyer guilty,
they had to find he intended to corrupt legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The case was resolved without a second trial when Sawyer pleaded
guilty to a one-count information charging him with mail fraud. The
underlying charge was that he used the mails to violate the
Massachusetts conflict-of-interest law, which prohibits giving
gratuities to influence officials.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington concluded that the state gratuities law was modeled
after the federal law and therefore the recent Supreme Court ruling
applies.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant US Attorney John M. Griffin declined to comment on
Harrington's ruling or on whether prosecutors will appeal the
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1916EST &QL; 
