<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE ECONOMY BOOMING, REPORT SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Venture capital money is pouring in to Massachusetts
Internet-oriented companies and their employment rosters are
exploding, but the state seems to face a mounting problem of
keeping small startups here to grow, according to a new state
report.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest yearly report on what it calls the ``innovation
economy,'' the Massachusetts Technology Collaborative indicates the
Bay State is a better place to start a small company than to grow
it into a big one, in large part because of the difficulty finding
enough well-trained workers.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts ``e-commerce'' companies that make software and
equipment for companies to do business over the Internet attracted
$514 million in venture capital last year, or 15 percent of all US
venture investment, putting the Bay State second only to
California. In the first half of this year, that level of
Massachusetts-commerce investment soared to $819 million, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   However, because the state is doing so well, reaching virtually
full employment, job growth in nine key innovation-oriented sectors
slowed to 2.7 percent last year from 3.5 percent in 1997. Nearly 1
in 11 positions for skilled production workers are going begging
because new hires are so hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to see a human-resources constraint on our
ability to expand and grow,'' said Joseph D. Alviani, executive
director of the collaborative, a quasi-public state agency that
promotes high-tech growth. ``I don't know how this economy could
support growing big, big companies, because I don't know where they
would get the people to staff them.''
</P>
<P>
   The report found that Massachusetts faces ``near-zero work force
growth,'' particularly in increasing the pool of people with
college degrees or specialized training to do high-tech
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than one-sixth of the state's colleges, for example, now
offer ``e-commerce'' courses, a sector that ``is becoming
increasingly important to the Massachusetts economy,'' said
Patricia M. Flynn, dean of Bentley College's graduate programs and
chairwoman of a 25-person study advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   While the report's focus is more descriptive than prescriptive,
officials said it serves as another reminder the state needs to do
a better job improving education at all levels, from kindergarten
to graduate school, and make housing more available and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Just over one-third of Massachusetts adults have a college
degree, or 33.5 percent, compared to a US average of 23.9 percent.
The percentage of Bay State adults who have graduated college has
nearly tripled since 1970, while the US percentage has roughly
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most glaring weaknesses of the state's economy, the
report indicates, is an inadequate number of ``technically skilled
workers'' to fill jobs being created by rapidly growing high-tech
companies that may have to look west or south to expand.
</P>
<P>
   The report focuses on nine sectors of the economy that account
for 24 percent of non-government jobs in Massachusetts and 35
percent of total private-sector payroll: Software and
communications services; computer and communications hardware;
post-secondary education; health care technology; textiles and
apparel; defense contracting; financial services; ``innovation
services'' such as engineering and consulting; and ``diversified
industrial support,'' including high-tech machines and plastics.
</P>
<P>
   It also compares Massachusetts to five other ``leading
technology states,'' including California, Colorado, Minnesota, New
York, New Jersey, and Texas, finding Massachusetts is doing well
above average in attracting federal research funds and winning
patents, and enjoys higher pay for most jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   --As of late 1998, Massachusetts counts at least 490 e-commerce
companies employing more than 18,500 people, numbers that almost
certainly have increased since then.
</P>
<P>
   --Massachusetts led the five other technology-rich states in
patents, with 56 issued per 100,000 people in 1998, up from 42 a
year earlier. Health care technology accounts for 28 percent of all
Massachusetts patents, followed by industrial equipment and
machinery, computers, semiconductors and components, and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   --A total of 110 ``gazelle'' companies _ publicly traded firms
whose sales have grown an annual average compound rate of 20
percent for four years _ are based in Massachusetts, up from 80 in
1995 and 51 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   --At $171 per capita, 1997 federal health research expenditures
in Massachusetts were three times as high as New York, four times
as high as California, and 13 times as high as New Jersey. Overall
federal research and development spending at Massachusetts
universities and teaching hospitals reached $1.7 billion in 1997,
but other states are showing signs of catching up.
</P>
<P>
   --Boston ranks number 5 among the 50 ``most wired'' US cities,
according to a Yahoo! index that includes Internet users and hosts
per capita and on-line business registrations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
