<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-CANDIDATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE PACT REVEALS RIFT AMONG GOP CANDIDATES ON CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration's agreement to support
China's membership in the World Trade Organization on Monday laid
bare the deep divisions among Republican candidates for president
on the nature of relations between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of Arizona
gave qualified endorsements of the trade deal, saying that bringing
China into the global trading scheme would help moderate its
economic and political behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But the more conservative candidates for the Republican
presidential nomination condemned it, accusing the administration
of ignoring gross human rights violations in its eagerness to
expand commerce with China.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democratic candidates, Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley, applauded the trade agreement, although aides
said that Bradley would reserve final judgment until he had had a
chance to study its terms. Both candidates are seeking a way to
embrace free trade with China while not alienating important
Democratic constituencies _ including organized labor and some
human rights advocates _ who oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction signals that the coming political battles
on China and trade will take place largely within the major
political parties, rather than between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more heated debate will be within the Republican Party,''
said Gary Bauer, a Republican presidential candidate and vehement
opponent of the trade deal. ``There will be a Reagan wing making my
argument, and the trade wing _ the Bush wing _ unfortunately siding
with Clinton and Gore on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said in a statement that he has consistently supported
membership of China in the world trading organization, a position
also advocated by his father, former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome news of an agreement that will open China's markets
to American products and help introduce American values into
China,'' the governor said. ``The agreement should give American
farmers, ranchers and businesses access to China's growing market,
and help introduce American values along with American products. An
agreement with China should also open the door for Taiwan's
admission to the WTO, which is long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer's view, which is largely shared by fellow conservative
candidates Steve Forbes and Alan Keyes, is that China's record on
trade, human rights, weapons proliferation and threats to Taiwan
has worsened over the past several years. He said that the
administration should have sought significant changes in the way
Beijing does business before agreeing to sponsor its membership in
the world trade body.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, a millionaire magazine publisher who is largely
financing his own campaign, said last week in a speech on China
policy that he strongly opposes allowing China to join the global
trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear,'' Forbes said in an address at the Nixon
Library in Yorba Linda, Calif., ``Yes to Taiwan in the WTO. No to
China. Beijing hasn't earned it and we shouldn't give it. Period.
It is time for our government to reward freedom and democracy _ not
force and demagoguery _ and let us never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not directly address the China trade pact Monday.
But an aide said that Bradley supports China's membership in the
WTO as long as it has to meet the same legal and economic
requirements as any other nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley believes it is better to have China inside WTO
subject to universal rules rather than outside cutting unilateral
deals,'' said Kristin Ludecke, a Bradley spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, of course, supports the administration's position on trade
with China. But he is also trying to finesse the issue because of
the fervent opposition of the AFL-CIO, which has endorsed his
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO president John Sweeney blasted the agreement as a
``grave mistake'' and accused the administration of being
``disgustingly hypocritical'' in claiming that trade deals help to
moderate Chinese behavior.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore spokesman, Christopher Lehane, said in response to
Sweeney's criticism, ``Al Gore has made absolutely clear _ as he
did at the AFL-CIO convention last month _ that all future trade
agreements he would negotiate as president would include labor,
environmental and human rights agreements as part, and they would
be enforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, who is seeking the Reform Party's presidential
nomination, has long opposed what he considers one-sided trade
deals that hurt American workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the latest administration capitulation to Beijing at
the expense of working American families and for the benefit of
transnational corporations,'' Buchanan said in a statement. ``It is
a cave-in, pure and simple, to a regime that even today persecutes
religious minorities and aims nuclear rockets at the United States
of America. I will fight it with everything I have right through to
November 2000.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
