<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the trade accord reached Monday between the U.S. and
China.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Beijing) _ Ledeall: American and Chinese
negotiators reached a landmark agreement Monday to open China's
economy to foreign competitors and in return to make the world's
most populous nation a full partner in international commerce. By
Erik Eckholm with David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, a PM version of this story has moved.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: In the end,
this was the deal Bill Clinton had to sign, both to jump-start U.S.
relations with China and to save whatever claim he has left as the
president who made trade and commercial diplomacy the centerpiece
of American foreign policy. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-IMPACT (Shanghai) _ A news analysis: Although the
immediate effects of China's landmark trade agreement with the
United States may be mixed, the deal is a major victory for Prime
Minister Zhu Rongji, an advocate of reform who has been under
fierce fire from conservative opponents in recent months. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
and business groups prepared an intense campaign Monday to win
approval in Congress for China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, facing opposition from conservatives who object to
almost any dealings with China and liberals who say the trade pact
would be bad for workers. Members of both parties said the deal
would most likely be approved in the key battleground, the House,
based on the solid bipartisan majority that granted China a
one-year extension of favorable trading terms earlier this year. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-CANDIDATES (Washington) _ The Clinton
administration's agreement to support China's membership in the WTO
laid bare the deep divisions among Republican candidates for
president on the nature of relations between the United States and
China. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of Arizona
gave qualified endorsements of the trade deal, saying that bringing
China into the global trading scheme would help moderate its
economic and political behavior. But the more conservative
candidates for the Republican presidential nomination condemned the
deal, accusing the administration of ignoring gross human rights
violations in its eagerness to expand commerce with the world's
most populous nation. The two Democratic candidates, Vice President
Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, applauded the trade
agreement, although aides said that Bradley would reserve final
judgment until he had had a chance to study its terms. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-BEIJING (Beijing) _ Many Chinese were pinching
themselves Monday afternoon, filled with disbelief that, after more
than a decade of false starts, China had actually taken the plunge
into the international economy, signing a landmark trade agreement
with the United States. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-BARSHEFSKY (Washington) _ A woman-in-the-news profile
of the U.S. trade representative. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-WINNERS (Undated) _ Corporate America, with only a
few exceptions, hailed the agreement reached Monday between China
and the United States as a wonderful opportunity to expand rapidly
into the giant Chinese market. Looking at what U.S. industries
stand to gain and who stands to lose. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-STOCKS (Hong Kong) _ Shares of Chinese and
China-related companies surged here Monday as investors concluded
that a landmark trade agreement between the United States and China
_ and the competition it promises _ would help Chinese companies
more than hurt them. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-MOORE (Geneva, Switzerland) _ While hailing the
accord clearing the way for China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, Mike Moore, the trade regulator's chief, also
cautioned that several steps remained before the country could
become a full-fledged member. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
