<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-SANOFI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUCCI PURCHASES CONTROL OF YVES SAINT LAURENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the latest step in the mounting consolidation of the
European fashion and luxury-goods industries, the Gucci Group NV
said Monday that it would buy Sanofi Beaute from the French
billionaire Francois Pinault for about $1 billion to gain control
of Yves Saint Laurent.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci's share price rose by more than 4 percent after the
company said it had reached a deal that would give it control of
Saint Laurent's cosmetics, perfume and ready-to-wear garment
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci said only the haute couture line of Yves Saint Laurent,
which accounts for about $5 million of Sanofi's $696 million of
annual sales, would remain with Artemis SA, a holding company
controlled by Pinault, where it will continue to be run by Yves
Saint Laurent and his longtime associate, Pierre Berge.
</P>
<P>
   The deal represents the first major step by Gucci's chief
executive, Domenico De Sole, to fulfill his ambition of creating a
powerful luxury group of many brands that is large enough to
challenge the industry leader, LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton.
</P>
<P>
   To advance that plan, De Sole agreed earlier this year to
acquire Yves Saint Laurent from Pinault, who had bought it for
about $1 billion. That agreement came after Gucci stopped LVMH's
hostile-takeover attempt. To thwart the bid by LVMH and its
acquisitive chairman, Bernard Arnault, De Sole had earlier agreed
to sell a large stake in Gucci to Pinault and to incorporate Yves
Saint Laurent into the Gucci Group.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuvering by Gucci and LVMH has at times come down to
something of a personal feud between Arnault and Pinault, and
Monday LVMH announced a new round of acquisitions to broaden its
portfolio, saying it had reached agreement to buy Phillips, a
British art auction house, and Zenith, a Swiss luxury watchmaker.
Earlier this year, Pinault, an enthusiastic art collector, bought
Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deal appeared to represent a compromise with Berge, the
38-year partner of Yves Saint Laurent, who had blocked the deal,
originally expected in late July, by insisting that he maintain
control of Yves Saint Laurent's haute couture and ready-to-wear
fashions.
</P>
<P>
   But under Monday's terms, De Sole said that Gucci takes ``full
control of the trademark, the name and operation of the company,''
including the Rive Gauche ready-to-wear collection as well as
perfume licenses for brands like Van Cleef &AMP; Arpels, Oscar de la
Renta and Krizia.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole said it was a ``significant milestone for Gucci in
establishing itself as a leading luxury-goods group.''
</P>
<P>
   Berge, in a telephone conversation, said he was ``very
content,'' with the agreement. ``For one thing, haute couture will
stay in France,'' he said. He added that he was confident of
Gucci's ability to further develop Yves Saint Laurent's product
lines.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole said Gucci would run Yves Saint Laurent as a wholly
owned subsidiary, appointing as managing director Mark Lee, an
American manager who has been responsible for Gucci's worldwide
ready-to-wear merchandising. It was in part Gucci's timely move
from accessories into ready-to-wear garments, notably in key
markets like the United States, that cushioned the group from the
Asian economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci, in a statement, said it would apply the formulas at Yves
Saint Laurent that De Sole used to reinvigorate Gucci itself, such
as a ``major store rollout program'' in key luxury-goods markets
and a shift from licensing arrangements to in-house development of
shoes, leather accessories and ready-to-wear garments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
