<HEADER>
A0613 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-BOOK-TEX     11-15 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ALLOWS A FEW PERSONAL GLIMPSES IN AUTOBIORGAPHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Pleas for mercy trickled in from around the
globe as Gov. George W. Bush pondered whether to use his powers to
temporarily halt the execution of Houston pickax murderer Karla
Faye Tucker. Two days before her date with the death chamber, even
one of Bush's own daughters weighed in.
</P>
<P>
   She announced that she was against the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner-table declaration made Bush's heart ``a little
heavier,'' but he didn't change his mind. Tucker was executed. As
for his daughter, Bush told her she ``had a right and a
responsibility to make her own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   The anecdote, a rare peek into Bush's private home life, is
contained in his autobiography, ``A Charge to Keep.'' It is one of
only a handful of passages in the 253-page book that offer new
insights into a politician whose life has already been written
about extensively. But even at that, Bush did not identify which of
his twin teen-age daughters made the remark.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to unveil the book on Wednesday and has said
that he will give his share of the proceeds to charity. It is being
published by William Morrow &AMP; Co. and will retail for $23.
</P>
<P>
   The book is billed as a look at the experiences that led Bush
into the 2000 presidential race. It combines a series of
well-rehearsed campaign speeches with observations about his
governing approach, his opponents, his famous parents and even his
pets, which include a six-toed cat named Ernie.
</P>
<P>
   Understating an obvious difference between the style of his
reticent father and his own more open approach, Bush writes: ``I
respect his humility and try to emulate it in my private life. In
the public arena, though, if you don't define and promote yourself,
someone else will define you.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most poignant moment in the book is Bush's
recollection of his sister, Robin, who died of leukemia just before
her fourth birthday. Bush, then 7, recalls being at Sam Houston
Elementary School in Midland and seeing his parents drive up. He
was sure he saw his sister in the car too, ``her small head rising
barely above the backseat of my parents' green Oldsmobile.''
</P>
<P>
   He learned otherwise as he greeted his parents. Robin had died,
they told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-six years later, those minutes remain the starkest
memory of my childhood, a sharp pain in the midst of an otherwise
happy blur,'' Bush writes.
</P>
<P>
   The book, written with longtime press secretary and adviser
Karen Hughes, does not contain any bold new pronouncements or deep
insights into what makes the governor tick. It mentions the hot
topic of abortion just once, and quotes Bush giving his standard
line: ``I hope someday unborn children will be protected by law and
welcomed in life.''
</P>
<P>
   He also avoids a detailed discussion on guns. ``Guns are an
issue in Texas, as they are in America,'' he writes. ``I believe
law-abiding citizens should be allowed to own guns to hunt and to
protect themselves and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 53, acknowledges in the book that he needed to quit
drinking, which he did at age 40. He said alcohol ``magnified
aspects of my personality that probably didn't need to be larger
than they already were.'' But the governor expresses disdain for
journalists who want to pry too far into mistakes he made as a
young man.
</P>
<P>
   Many, he writes, ``worship at the altar of public confession,
demanding that candidates tell all. They want to conduct a public
strip search, throwing out a question here and a rumor there,
hoping it will bare another layer.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Bush portrays his tenure as governor so far as
successful, though he acknowledges that the failure of his 1997 tax
overhaul package was a setback. He recalls a ``most dramatic and
most disappointing'' moment when state senators ``one by one'' told
him they couldn't vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   Another dramatic moment came as he waited for Tucker to die
after he declined to grant her a temporary reprieve. It was ``the
longest 20 minutes of my tenure as governor,'' Bush writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Charge to Keep,'' a title inspired by a Methodist hymn, does
not hold itself out as an exhaustive or even objective look at
Bush's record, background and outlook. Mindful of the lesson not to
let others define him, Bush writes that he decided to write the
tome after discovering that other people were doing their own
biographies of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to tell my story from my own perspective,'' he
writes in the book's forward. ``Plus, in our family, even the dog
has written a book.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
