<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE END, IT'LL STILL BE BUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These people who have no use for George W. Bush and are beside
themselves over his early success in the 2000 presidential race
must be absolutely furious: Every time it looks as though Bush
might have made a ruinous misstep in his campaign, he steadies
himself and continues his inexorable march toward the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-bashers first figured that the media's persistent
questions about rumors of past drug use would derail the Texas
governor's campaign. After that storm blew over with no apparent
damage, the anti-Bush crowd pinned its hopes on the so-called pop
quiz that was sprung on Bush by a Boston TV reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dodged that bullet, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Republican front-runner's detractors are touting a poll
suggesting that Arizona Sen. John McCain has erased Bush's
once-sizable lead in New Hampshire. According to the poll, the Bush
lead over McCain has shrunk to a percentage that falls within the
poll's margin of error _ which means that the race is a statistical
dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   This development, some Bush-bashers are saying, represents a
serious threat to the aura of inevitability that has been the
hallmark of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Bush's opponents _ and some of the allegedly neutral
pundits _ are saying. Here's what I say: Baloney.
</P>
<P>
   The poll may or may not reflect reality, but all it means in any
case is that New Hampshire voters are taking a close look at McCain
_ as well they should, considering that he's been spending darn
near enough time in the Granite State to run for governor there if
his presidential bid falls through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on the other hand, has not made campaigning in New
Hampshire a top priority as yet. It stands to reason that his
comparative inactivity in the state would translate to lower poll
numbers. Voters in the New Hampshire primary _ traditionally the
nation's first each campaign season _ expect to be courted, coddled
and cajoled by would-be presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Once Bush starts paying more attention to this demanding segment
of the electorate, his poll numbers are certain to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of argument, though, let's assume that Bush doesn't
bounce back in New Hampshire. Let's assume that McCain is on a
roll, that the former prisoner of war has made such a favorable
impression on the people of New Hampshire that he will surge to
victory in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Good for McCain. Such a scenario would be nice for him; it would
make a terrific anecdote for his next book. But it wouldn't change
the inevitable outcome of the GOP presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will not be the Republican nominee for president in 2000.
That honor will go to Bush, without or without the media's
preoccupation with innuendo and trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. John McCain is a great American, an
excellent senator and a perfectly respectable candidate for
president of the United States. But he does not have the widespread
appeal or the resources to defeat Bush.
</P>
<P>
   There is no downplaying McCain's integrity, courage and
sincerity. But as a presidential candidate, he's a Johnny-one-note.
To hear him tell it, campaign finance reform is the answer to every
question, the solution to every problem.
</P>
<P>
   McCain may well believe that, but he is hanging his hopes of
becoming president on an issue that has never captured the
imagination of the public _ and never will.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, is not merely the presidential money-raising
champion of all time; he's the candidate who is most in touch with
the interests and concerns of most Americans. As the campaign
progresses, voters will see that Bush's vision for the future of
the greatest nation on earth is both compelling and well-defined.
</P>
<P>
   The next big hope for the Bush-bashers, of course, is the
expectation that he will self-destruct in the upcoming debates with
McCain and other Republican candidates. Here's a word to the wise:
Don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   And if he should happen to stumble, Bush will do what he always
does: He'll steady himself and keep on going.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
