r k BC-MAN-OF-THE-CENTURY-HN     11-15 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAN-OF-THE-CENTURY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCHILL: GREAT DISAPPOINTMENT OF THE CENTURY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM M. BURKE   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The world waits for Time magazine to anoint the
``Man of the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Realists might suggest Hitler, Stalin or Mao, the three monsters
who together made the 20th century the bloodiest era of human
history.
</P>
<P>
   Others might suggest a real hero like Franklin D. Roosevelt, the
man who, according to his supporters, saved American capitalism
during the 1930s and then saved Western civilization during the
1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers, especially conservatives, would instead choose
Winston Churchill as the true savior of Western civilization.
</P>
<P>
   But the case for Churchill is not straightforward. Indeed,
contemporaries regarded Churchill as the Patrick Buchanan of his
day _ renowned as a writer and orator but reviled as a blundering
egotist and political turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   A Conservative by birth and tradition, Churchill switched to the
rising Liberal Party in 1903 and was rewarded accordingly. At the
Board of Trade, he pushed social programs and cuts in defense
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Promoted to the Home Office, he became a law-and-order man,
personally supervising (with photographer in tow) the harsh police
repression of striking miners, anarchists and militant
suffragettes.
</P>
<P>
   Next, at the Admiralty, Churchill repudiated his earlier views
and boosted defense spending almost 60 percent between 1910 and
1914. Thus he soon possessed an imposing array of battleships,
which throughout World War I remained safely in port _ except for
the inconclusive Battle of Jutland _ while the flower of British
manhood perished in France.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anxious as ever for action, Churchill persuaded the
Cabinet to accept his plan for the Gallipoli campaign, which turned
out to be one of the worst defeats in British military history. His
idea was to send a fleet through the Dardanelles straits, capture
Constantinople and thus remove Turkey, Germany's ally, from the
war.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was typically Churchillian, with grandiose planning
and sloppy execution, so that more than half of the 489,000 men
committed to the operation were killed or wounded before the final
withdrawal in late 1915.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill paid a political price, but after a spell in uniform
in France he returned to the Cabinet before war's end.
</P>
<P>
   There he argued, unsuccessfully, for a full-scale British attack
on the new Bolshevik regime in Russia. He argued, successfully, for
fighting Irish rebels with government hit squads (the infamous
Black and Tans).
</P>
<P>
   After the collapse of wartime coalition politics and the return
of the Conservatives to power, Churchill switched parties again and
was rewarded with the Exchequer. There he supervised the return of
the pound to the gold standard at its prewar valuation, which
turned out to be one of the worst economic defeats in British
history. The export trade collapsed, and the British economy sank
into a decade-long depression, with considerable labor unrest.
</P>
<P>
   During the General Strike of 1926, Churchill loudly advocated
repression. The working class never forgave him.
</P>
<P>
   Out of office but not out of parliamentary politics during the
1930s, Churchill made more enemies with his loud preaching against
``appeasement'' _ especially appeasement of the nationalist
movement in India. (He was outraged when the governor general
released Mahatma Gandhi from jail.) Viewing the Nazi threat,
Churchill demanded a major arms buildup. But his program would have
left Britain with a glut of obsolete arms at the onset of war.
</P>
<P>
   The program actually implemented by Prime Minister Neville
Chamberlain, with its emphasis on sophisticated radar and
state-of-the-art fighter planes, won the Battle of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chamberlain had to pay the political price after Hitler
reneged on his promises and took over both Czechoslovakia and
Poland. Ironically, his fall came on account of Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the Admiralty at the onset of hostilities,
Churchill staged a disastrous attack on Norway _ a minor Gallipoli.
</P>
<P>
   The war-coalition parties, not knowing where else to turn, chose
the belligerent Churchill as prime minister. For the next two
years, he kept the nation's spirits alive with his magnificent
oratory while the Germans rampaged throughout Europe and the
Japanese ran roughshod over Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Britain was saved when the Japanese stupidly bombed Pearl Harbor
and their German allies stupidly declared war on the United States.
Thereafter, the British were a distant third in Big Three
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   At war's end, Poland, the country for whose independence Britain
had gone to war, lay under the Soviet heel. After Yalta, Churchill
found himself making the same defensive statements that Chamberlain
had made after Munich.
</P>
<P>
   British voters decided in 1945 that they didn't want Churchill's
tattered dreams of imperial glory but instead wanted to march to
the Labor Party's ``New Jerusalem'' under the Beveridge Plan of
cradle-to-grave security. In late 1942, Churchill declared, ``I
have not become the king's First Minister in order to preside over
the liquidation of the British Empire.''
</P>
<P>
   By that standard, his life could be considered a total failure.
He avoided becoming a vassal of the Nazi empire only to become a
vassal of the American empire, while the once-mighty British empire
lay in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William M. Burke is a retired Federal Reserve Bank economist in
San Francisco and a Navy veteran of World War II.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
