<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     11-15 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDO TO LET: CHECKING IT OUT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sally Sweet, who owns Wise Vacation Rentals in Killington, Vt.,
cleanly identifies the core of the issue. ``When 14 people rent a
vacation condo,'' Ms. Sweet said, ``they pick one person to do the
work, and that person wants to be a hero when they all arrive.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to help that point person be a hero, not a goat,''
she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweet, as luck would have it, was talking to a sometime
hero, sometime goat, the point person for a floating group of 10 to
12 picky reporters and editors who rent a house for a week in
September before a journalism conference in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone still talks about the dinner party for 24 we staged in
1998 in a vast house at Jackson Hole. Everyone also talks about the
house we took two months ago in Sundance, Utah, but for different
reasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On my desk are stacks of colorful brochures from resort areas
and states; they are dense with grids of agents' names, telephone
numbers, price ranges and seasons. I also have a raft of brochures
sent by organizations like Home From Home and Hideaways
International. There are more resources than one could possibly
master, and still more on the Web.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it's what the brochures don't tell you that can be crucial
when choosing a rental. What insights keep one from selecting a
condo that has no salt in the salt-shakers and no soap in the guest
bathroom?
</P>
<P>
   How does a nonsmoker gain confidence that a place will not have
upholstery and curtains heavy with the smoke of those who have just
rented it? Although agents know that places with spiral stairways
or cliffs next door should not be rented to families with small
children, there are other sorts of hazards: the Dumpster that is
emptied by a screeching truck at 5 a.m. and a wheezing
air-conditioner in the tropics are assassins of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   My task was to learn what can be done to improve the averages
for picking out a well-furnished, bright, clean, sweet-smelling
house from the vast number of possibilities for the ski season or
in the Caribbean, when one-week or four-day rentals are common. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A friend's experience shows what can go wrong. In ski season one
year, she borrowed a Colorado condominium belonging to a family
member. It was just what she and her husband wanted, and they had a
good time. In a later ski season, she asked the agent for a rental
unit in the same complex. It was like night and day, she said. The
second place needed painting, had soiled carpets, sad beds and the
bare minimum kitchen, resulting in a disappointing stay.
</P>
<P>
   One way of preventing this problem is the route Samuel I. and
Mabelle Adele Thompson of Martha's Vineyard take when they rent in
Barbados: they always rent direct from the owners, getting
photographs inside and out, and they ask friends who live on the
island to keep an eye out. After three winter rentals in other
houses, the Thompsons picked a new one this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked our friends to take a look,'' Thompson said, ``and
they reported, `Invite us over when you get here.' So we knew we
had a good place.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adden B. Chrystie, an associate agent at Valerie Wilson Travel
in New York, believes that you should start the pursuit in company
with someone you trust. Ms. Chrystie, who specializes in vacation
rentals, said that just as one was confident of what sort of place
relatives would maintain, people in her sector of the travel
business have evaluated real-estate managing agents' standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example,'' Ms. Chrystie said, ``it makes a difference
whether the management company does cleaning and maintenance or
whether the owners do. If the owners do, and they don't enjoy
cooking, they may consider it adequate if the kitchen has four
mismatched glasses and a few dishes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said, as did Ms. Sweet, that people should learn when the
house was last redecorated and re-outfitted. ``Things get pinched
from kitchens,'' she continued. ``Finally there will be only one
frying pan, and it's scratched. Who replaces it, and how long will
it take?'' The nub of it is talking to someone who has been through
the house and its cupboards, not someone working from a description
or a diagram. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When our horde of reporters was going to Jackson Hole in 1998,
Andrew Hibbard, the agent at Alpine Vacation Rentals we talked to,
volunteered in June that Morley Manor, a new property with the
company, was in the process of being redecorated. In September it
was pretty much spanking new, with place settings for 24, three
full sets of glasses, an outdoor grille and two dishwashers to
handle the loads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year, when we were confronted with an inadequately equipped
kitchen in a house we rented through the Sundance resort in Utah,
it dawned on me that the redecoration schedule contained a distant
early warning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other subtleties that Ms. Chrystie said were important were
these: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ As to a ski house, what does ``ski in, ski out'' really mean?
``This phrase can be used very loosely,'' she said. ``Is it over
the river and through the woods, or right there?'' The same applies
to beach areas: how much of a walk is it to the beach, across the
street or across several streets, and are there high-rise hotels in
the front rank? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Houses and condos can be linked to resorts with names famous
for luxury, but like hotels bearing such names, she said, they can
be tired behind their titles. Candid information is needed about
the condition of such places from someone who has looked into the
closets and tested the lights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Who will be available in emergencies? Anyone making a cold
call should be sure help is available 24 hours a day if the
electricity goes off, the hot tub does not work or another problem
unfolds. The most common problem the two experts reported was lack
of hot water, which invariably turned out to be a result of
successive hot showers after skiing or swimming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
