<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0619 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FUTURE-TECHNOLOGY-PRO     11-15 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-TECHNOLOGY-PRODUCTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST TECHNOLOGY PRODUCTS TAKE CUE FROM THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by  LANG Group )  
 
 
By DAVID BLOOM, Staff Writer 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As your cook rustles up breakfast, you bring in the groceries
delivered to your door, skim the paper and other publications, then
read a ream of letters from far-flung friends and associates. Your
dog's eyes light up when it sees you.
</P>
<P>
   Your commute to work is only a few feet. Servants take care of
your shopping, while the pharmacist and stores you visit regularly
know your name and what you tend to like or need.
</P>
<P>
   Now this is living the way it used to be, back in the good old
days.
</P>
<P>
   Technological changes are letting us go back to revisit patterns
of living that were typical 20, 40, even a few hundred years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The morning's milk and groceries, for instance, could be
delivered through an Internet service such as Peapod or WebVan,
after your smart refrigerator's computer sensors automatically
notified the online grocer that you were out of milk and bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're changing the way we do so many things, some
mildly, some quite radically, we almost instinctively reach back to
older models to organize it and understand it,'' said Erik Davis,
author of ``TechGnosis,'' a 1998 book about the ways our oldest
practices, spiritual and otherwise, are creeping into our newest
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's happening in a big way and I think it will happen
more,'' Davis said. ``We now have the technology where we can
easily imagine leaving behind much of what we think of as human
life. But at same time, we're realizing we have ways of relating in
our past that have actually been some really good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Expect your entire house to be wired and smart, something that's
being vigorously promoted by sages such as Michael Dertouzos, the
head of the Laboratory for Computer Science at the Massachussetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Besides your refrigerator, you can hook up your security system,
heating controls, entertainment system and more to your computer
and let them do the grunt work for you. Speaking of smart, that dog
of yours will literally have its eyes light up, if it's like the
AIBO robot dogs Sony has been selling recently (at an eye-popping
rate, despite a $2,500 price tag).
</P>
<P>
   In the next decade, Dertouzos said, half a billion
human-operated machines and countless computers in appliances,
sensors, controllers and the like will be interconnected. The
result will be some very smart trash cans, toilets and
refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   Computers have already begun to make our shopping life easier,
however haphazardly. Sometimes those intelligent agents are little
pieces of software that you commission to go out on the Internet
and find good deals for you.
</P>
<P>
   Several agents, for instance, will compare prices for, say, a
DVD player sold at various online sites, then tell you which site
has the best price. Entire volumes, such as ``The Bot Book,''
detail the hundreds of shopping and other agents you already use.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``suggestion software'' at shopping sites such
as Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Once you buy something from Amazon, the software will compare
your purchase history with those of other people who bought the
same books or music or videos. The next time you visit there, the
software will suggest you try other books or music or videos bought
by those people who share your purchase history.
</P>
<P>
   Something of the same nature happens with some online and
telephone-based pharmacy companies, which use sophisticated
software to note your medical history and drug requirements.
</P>
<P>
   When you dial in, the software automatically pulls up your
account, showing the person handling your order your medical and
purchasing history, status of prescriptions and other information.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes, moving forward and back simultaneously, are also
afoot. That morning newspaper you read (maybe even this one) won't
come on newsprint someday.
</P>
<P>
   Already, this paper and others are available on the Internet
(www.dailynews.com) and an increasing number of people say they
prefer to get their news through that medium, despite the current
annoyances of reading online on poor-resolution monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Just wait. Soon enough, you'll have more portable and powerful
alternatives, some of which are already hitting the market, such as
the electronic devices now being sold by Rocket Books and its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility being readied for market is electronic
``paper.'' The paper uses electric current to flip tiny half-black,
half-white balls of ``digital ink'' embedded in the page. The ink
creates a very high-resolution page that can be endlessly updated
and changed. No more stacks of newsprint waiting for recycling.
</P>
<P>
   Reading, in general, has made a comeback, thanks to the Net,
though researchers at Sun Microsystems and elsewhere have found
that we read in very different ways, hopscotching through
information from link to link.
</P>
<P>
   Reading shorter bites of information, with bullet items, many
crosslinks and other organizing options, makes for a much more
intensely read Web page compared to one written in the style we're
used to seeing on the printed page, the researchers have found.
</P>
<P>
   Back, too, is writing, thanks to e-mail. In the past year, for
the first time, we sent more e-mail than snail mail, as techsters
refer to sending a note through the U.S. Postal Service. That trend
will only increase in geometric proportions as the network of
people who have access to e-mail expands.
</P>
<P>
   It's already happening. Most wired people likely would say they
send more notes to friends, lovers, family and others with e-mail
than they ever used to when their main option was taking pen to
paper, then finding envelope, stamp and mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writing of e-mail is a healthy thing,'' said Bart Kosko,
author of the just-released ``Fuzzy Future.'' ``People do
communicate with more people than they ever did before. You can hit
so many more people with e-mail.'' But this welcome renaissance for
reading and writing may be short-lived, and Kosko blames, yes,
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the e-mail revolution will last,'' said Kosko,
an information scientist at the University of Southern California.
``There will be (voice-activated controls) in and out, and then
you'll see the end of writing again, especially when there are
(computerized intelligent) agents to clean it up. It creates what I
call a moral hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosko isn't the only one issuing a cautionary note about our
technological future. As attractive as the past is to some people,
the reality is that it it was fraught with its own problems _
disease, war, famine. Despite rosy scenarios, future technology is
as likely to create as many problems as it solves.
</P>
<P>
   We are already yearning for things we have lost. Davis points to
the cultural scavenging of current youth culture, which ransacks
everything from medieval vampire/Gothic culture to the polyester
hippies of the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of focusing our creative energy rather than
spiralling into a dystopian future,'' Davis said. ``We're at a
point where people are starting to realize some of the things we've
lost in our rush for this new technology. I do sense a return
toward the re-embedding of technology in the body of the world and
of nature.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is truly back to the future. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0620 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2N     11-15 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2NDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: or swimming.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ The configuration of the beds is a basic, and should be dealt
with on the first discussion by examination of a floor plan
supplied by the agent. If a house has all twin beds, it will not
work for some groups, and the same goes for the reverse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Almost all rental houses clean out the leftover food, except
possibly salt and pepper, Ms. Sweet said, because no one should
have to worry about the safety of edibles. But renters need to know
what basic supplies are provided on arrival: filters that fit the
coffee pot, dish detergent, paper towels, toilet paper and trash
bags, for example.
</P>
<P>
   These things are hard to find on a late arrival. If they are not
provided, the agent should be asked what it would cost to get them
in. Most agents are also able, for a price, to deliver the edible
items on a shopping list, against the moment of arrival. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Placement of the bathrooms: bathrooms off bedrooms are not
accessible to everyone at crucial times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ How often is housekeeping service provided and how extensive
is it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael F. Thiel, owner of Hideaways International in
Portsmouth, N.H., has put together a good set of starting questions
for prospective renters in a booklet, ``Villa Vacations Made
Easy.'' It focuses on renting in the Caribbean, although Hideaways,
a membership group, has properties elsewhere, including links to
many European companies. It contains both a self-evaluation form _
what are our priorities? _ and a sample lease.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet was last revised in 1996, but Thiel says that the
price ranges quoted are still valid. A Montego Bay house with a
pool, a sea view, four bedrooms and a staff is quoted at $1,800 a
week for eight people. He puts a Colorado ski house two miles from
the slopes with an outdoor hot tub, sleeping eight, at $350 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet is available for $5 from Hideaways International,
767 Islington Street, Portsmouth, N.H. 03801, or with a credit card
by telephone to (800) 843-4433. The Web site is www.hideaways.com;
membership, which costs $79 a year, is required for Web browsers to
learn the owners' names.
</P>
<P>
   The lightning-swift change in electronic communication has
sharply affected house rentals. Whereas most hotels that deal with
business travelers have hurried to install modem outlets separate
from the room telephone line, frequently in the bases of desk
lamps, some houses have not thought of this as a needed amenity.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweet said that families' need to keep up with e-mail on
monthlong summer vacations meant that data ports were in demand for
long stays. Cable television has been available in the Vermont
properties for 10 years, she said, and this sort of thing is now
comprehended in the ``basics'' of a rental house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chrystie said: ``What the families expect now is what they
have at home, and they don't want to have a vacation spoiled
because the kids can't watch their favorite videos.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting ready to pick a place at Sundance, the reporters and
editors kept asking about a data port and whether the phone would
accommodate it. On arrival we found there was not a phone in every
bedroom, as described, but that an inexpensive new phone had been
hung on a kitchen wall against a molding so a modem line could not
be inserted.
</P>
<P>
   We shifted to the outlet in the closet, using our longest
extension cords. This was not a major item, but it matched the
opinion Ms. Chrystie later voiced, ``If the resort answers, `Oh
yes, sure,' it's time to worry.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In summary, try to rent a house the same way you pick a doctor:
get hold of someone you know and get a report that satisfies your
questions. This is not like renting a hotel room, where you can
shift to another room if you find the view is over the parking lot.
This is someone's house. Be sure it does what you want. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about the people and organizations consulted
for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Wise Vacation Rentals, 405 Killington Road, Killington, Vt.
05751; (800) 642-1147 or (802) 773-4202; www.wisevacations.com.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Winter Guide has a free brochure with a list of agents:
Vermont Chamber of Commerce, Post Office Box 37, Montpelier, Vt.
05601; (802) 223-3443; www.vtguides.com.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Wilson Travel, Adden Chrystie, 475 Park Avenue South,
New York, N.Y. 10016; (212) 532-3400 or (212) 592-1307.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Hole Resort Lodging (Alpine Vacation Rentals has merged
with this company), 3200 West McCollister Drive, Teton Village,
Wyo. 83025; (307) 733-3990; www .jhresortlodging.com.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Hole Central Reservations has a free brochure with a
list of agencies: Post Office Box 2618, 140 East Broadway, Jackson
Hole, Wyo. 83001; (800) 443-6931; www .jhsnow.com.
</P>
