<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Nov. 21) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colorado Canyon Area Is Newest National Park
</P>
<P>
   The United States' 55th national park was created last month
when President Clinton signed legislation creating Black Canyon of
the Gunnison National Park in southwest Colorado, about 250 miles
from Denver. It is the first new national park since Death Valley
and Joshua Tree were established in 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the new park is the dramatic Black Canyon,
whose dark-gray walls of schist and gneiss were carved over a
period of two million years by the Gunnison River. The canyon
plunges as much as 2,660 feet, with one sheer drop measuring 2,200
feet. The narrowest point at the bottom is only 40 feet wide. Both
the canyon and its rims are home to a variety of wildlife,
including black bears, golden eagles and the endangered peregrine
falcon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Black Canyon was established as a national monument in 1933, and
with its elevation to national park status, it acquires 10,000 more
acres. Still, at 30,300 total acres, it is the fourth smallest
national park, exceeding only the Hot Springs (Arkansas), Wind Cave
(South Dakota) and Virgin Islands National Parks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Black Canyon gets 230,000 visitors a year, most of them during
the summer. Many come for trout fishing on the Gunnison, but there
is also hiking, Nordic skiing, camping (115 sites) and rock
climbing. Facilities include a South Rim visitor center, which is
open year round and offers food and ranger programs, and a North
Rim ranger station, which is open during the summer only. Among the
hiking trails are seven primitive routes down to the river.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The park's South Rim is 15 miles east of Montrose, and the North
Rim 11 miles south of Crawford. The entrance fee is $7 a vehicle a
week. Information: (970) 641-2337; www.nps.gov/blca/.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak and Hertz Expand Rental Sites
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak and the Hertz Corp. are expanding efforts to help
railroad passengers rent cars on arrival, just as air passengers
can at the airport. Since May, Hertz has established a presence in
18 railroad stations, mostly in the West, though sometimes it is
only a dedicated wall phone. At the end of October, the two
organizations announced that they would put rail-drive links into
20 more depots.
</P>
<P>
   One will be Pennsylvania Station in New York, where starting in
December, there will be a wall phone; from there, passengers will
walk about a block to 250 West 34th St. to pick up cars.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 18 Amtrak stations with Hertz connections so far, only
those in Whitefish, Mont., near Glacier National Park, and
Wilmington, Del., have counters with staff. Six of the 20 new
cities will be staffed. In other places, Hertz provides pickup and
delivery on phone request _ Anaheim, Calif., is in this category _
or reimburses the traveler for taxi fare to a downtown rental
office, as in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   A major part of the tie-in comes when the train reservation is
made; the Amtrak agent can transfer the call immediately to Hertz.
A Hertz spokeswoman, Lauren Garvey, said that even travelers with
no reservation can use the station phone to seek a car, and be
picked up or get reimbursement for a cab ride to get it.
</P>
<P>
   For Amtrak reservations, call (800) 872-7245.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Show Features Recent Finds by Heade
</P>
<P>
   Martin Johnson Heade, regarded as one of America's greatest
19th-century landscape and still-life painters, was considered a
minor artist in his day and was all but forgotten after his death
in 1904. He was rediscovered in the 1940s, but many of his works
are still untraced, and it is not uncommon for one to turn up
seemingly out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston brings
together more than 90 of his works in his first retrospective in 30
years, including 32 of the more than 200 Heade paintings that have
been discovered since.
</P>
<P>
   Heade was born in Bucks County, Pa., in 1819, and studied with
his neighbor Edward Hicks, the folk artist of ``Peaceable Kingdom''
fame. Before Heade turned 20, he moved to Manhattan, where he met
leading Hudson River School artists like Frederic Edwin Church. His
art changed radically, and he soon became an inventive painter
specializing in landscapes and still lifes.
</P>
<P>
   Heade painted marshes, seascapes and inland views, concentrating
on precise rendering of light and atmosphere, and he traveled
widely, especially to South America. In Brazil, he devoted himself
to painting exotic and colorful hummingbirds in a series of gemlike
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Johnson Heade'' remains on view in Boston until Jan.
17. It will be at the National Gallery of Art in Washington Feb. 13
to May 7, and at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, May 28 to
Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts, 465 Huntington Ave., is open daily.
Admission is $12. Information: (617) 267-9300 or at www.mfa.org.
</P>
<P>
   A Brittany Jewel Regains Its 17th-Century Luster
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Rennes in western France can now tour the grand
halls of that city's newly restored 17th-century Parliament of
Britanny building, which has functioned as a courthouse since the
French Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the building and much of the art inside were ravaged
by a fire five years ago did these treasures and the building
itself attract the attention of the Culture Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Helped along by a renaissance of interest in Breton culture, the
restoration of the Parliament became the symbol for a reinvestment
in regional pride, and a far cry from the dusty court of appeals
it &QL; 
had been.
</P>
<P>
   The $60 million restoration has reclaimed 80 percent of the
damaged art. The work has revealed a sparkling limestone and
granite facade and a wealth of decorative work completed by the
legion of royal painters, sculptors and carpenters from the court
of Louis XIV, who descended upon the Parliament after its
completion in 1655.
</P>
<P>
   Of note are the ceiling paintings that adorn la Grand Chambre
and its annex: the allegorical ``Justice Extending Her Hand to
Innocence'' by Charles Errard and Noel Coypel, and Jean-Baptiste
Jouvenet's ``Triumph of Justice.'' Other works that have undergone
major restorations are Louis Ferdinand Elle's large-scale ``Justice
Imploring Religion'' in the Seconde Chambre and the sculptured wood
ceiling of the Jobbe Duval room.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the Grand Chambre and its annex will not be complete
until 2001, but other attractions, including a small chapel with
17th-century woodwork and the gilded detailing in the Salle des
Assises, are accessible. A series of Gobelin tapestries depicting
key moments in Brittany's history, which were hung in the Grand
Chambre early this century, survived the blaze, though half were
destroyed in another fire where they were being restored.
</P>
<P>
   The court of appeals moved back in on Oct. 4 and tours from
Culture Ministry guides, in English on request, began Nov. 1. They
cost $5.50, at 6.3 francs to the dollar. Information: (33-2)
99.67.11.11.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
