<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-VISITATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING EXPANDS ROLE OF NONTRADITIONAL FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Letting stand a groundbreaking ruling that expands
parental rights for gays and lesbians in Massachusetts, the US
Supreme Court Monday refused to review a decision by the state's
highest court that granted visitation rights to the former partner
of a lesbian mother.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the justices declined to hear a challenge to
the precedent-setting ruling, which was widely viewed as expanding
the legal notion of parenting and acknowledging the place of
nontraditional families in modern life.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the state Supreme Judicial Court in June said that
a lesbian who helped raise her partner's biological son had been a
``de facto'' parent, entitling her to visitation rights after the
couple split up.
</P>
<P>
   Had the US Supreme Court chosen to review the case, its ruling
could have affected a host of family privacy matters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, by declining to take the Massachusetts case, the
SJC decision remains intact here but establishes no legal precedent
outside of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In challenging the SJC's ruling, attorneys for the biological
mother, referred to in court documents only as ``L.M.,'' had asked
the Supreme Court to rule not on the merits of the case, but on
whether the SJC had the legal authority to issue such a decree.
L.M.'s lawyers argued that the high court had no such authority,
and criticized the ruling as an example of judicial law-making.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bonauto, an attorney for the Boston-based Gay and Lesbian
Advocates and Defenders, called Monday's development ``extremely
positive.'' ``What is now clear is that the legal issue of whether
the SJC could declare de facto parenthood has been settled,'' said
Bonauto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the judges and parties will now do what they have
to do, which is the best thing for the child,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The case will now return to Dukes County Probate and Family
Court, where a judge will determine custody, visitation, and
child-support arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a lawyer for L.M. called the Supreme Court's refusal
to review the decision puzzling, particularly since the court
agreed last month to examine whether grandparents are entitled to
visitation rights over the objections of the parents.
</P>
<P>
   Boston lawyer Gary Owen Todd, also noted that high courts in
several states have issued disparate rulings on the issue of de
facto parenthood, raising the expectation that the Supreme Court
would step in and resolve the differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to have the Supreme Court deal with
this issue and bring all states under a unified ruling,'' said
Todd. ``This issue is ripe for determination.''
</P>
<P>
   The case that prompted Monday's ruling involves a lesbian couple
from Martha's Vineyard who lived together for 13 years and decided
to have a child through artificial insemination.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, while the couple was living in Maryland, one of the two
women became pregnant. When the child, a son, was born in February
1995, the woman's partner acted as her birthing coach and cut the
child's umbilical cord.
</P>
<P>
   The couple sent out birth announcements naming both as parents,
and the child's last name consisted of both women's last names. The
boy tells people he has two mothers, one he calls ``Mommy'' and one
he calls ``Mama.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the child was born, and again afterward, the two women
signed a ``co-parenting agreement'' that expressed their intent to
raise the boy together. The agreement also stated that, should the
women separate, both would retain parental status.
</P>
<P>
   After the couple broke up in May 1998, eight months after moving
to Massachusetts, the boy's biological mother denied her former
partner access to the child. The partner then filed a complaint
seeking visitation rights, as well as the right to adopt the child
and assume joint custody.
</P>
<P>
   After a hearing, a Dukes County Probate and Family Court judge
ordered temporary visitation, pending trial, between the plaintiff
and the boy, citing the ``best interest of the child'' standard.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's biological mother appealed the probate court's
decision to the SJC, which backed the lower court's ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1950EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
