<SLUG> BC-HMO-LOSSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGEST BAY STATE HMO LOSES $26.5 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Harvard Pilgrim Health Care lost $26.5 million in the
third quarter, on track with expectations that the financially
ailing health maintenance organization would lose $100 million by
the end of the year, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While the health plan's losses are mounting, the HMO sought to
allay recent fears that Harvard Pilgrim is on the verge of
insolvency, saying it has enough cash on hand to meet its financial
obligations and that it's assets exceed liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers are completely consistent with what we have been
expecting and projecting since July,'' said chief executive Charles
Baker, who joined Harvard Pilgrim earlier this year to stop
financial hemorrhaging and put together a turnaround plan to break
even by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the third-quarter losses, ``we're still going to end the
year in pretty decent financial shape,'' he said. ``We can afford
the losses we're projecting. But of course we absolutely have to
make things turn around in 2000, and we're going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of the year, Harvard Pilgrim said its
losses totaled $75.4 million _ a loss that would have risen to
$96.3 million had it not been for $20.9 million in investment
income.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim's financial condition has been hurt by its
operations in Rhode Island, where state regulators last month put
the health plan's Ocean State assets in receivership. As of Sept.
30, losses in Rhode Island accounted for $33.8 million of the
health plan's overall losses in 1999, the company said. Regulators
expect to transfer Harvard Pilgrim's Rhode Island members to other
health plans before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim's unpaid claims, a measure of the money still
owed to hospitals and physicians, totaled $407 million in the third
quarter, down from $451 million in the second quarter. Meanwhile,
the health plan said it had $319 million in cash and securities
available to meet emergency demands.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim said it is ``on schedule'' with its effort to
cut costs and expects to have finished a key piece of its
reorganization plan _ negotiating simpler and cheaper contracts
with physicians _ by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tufts Health Plan also reported red ink, largely
because of huge losses in Maine. Tufts said it lost $9.4 million in
the third quarter and $26.3 million for the year so far. A full $21
million of those losses came in Maine, where Tufts has lost so much
money from spiraling health costs that it recently announced it
would withdraw from the state by April of next year.
</P>
<P>
   The third-quarter losses are slightly larger than anticipated,
leading health plan officials to say the company will likely exceed
its projected $30 million yearend loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's likely to be a little bit more than that,'' said chief
financial officer Rich Hallworth.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with mounting losses, he said Tufts is planning premium
increases of 10 percent to 15 percent beginning this fall and
continuing through the first part of next year. It is also
renegotiating contracts with member physicians and cutting $21
million in administrative costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts reported
third-quarter profits of $16.3 million for a total gain of $36
million for the full first nine months of the year. Those figures
for the insurer include a $500,000 third-quarter loss at the
company's HMO Blue unit, which reported a total net profit of $4.3
million for the year as of Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Blue Cross and Blue Shield members increased by
35,000, helping it to an operating gain of $9.3 million during the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Having earlier gone through an internal shakeup to cut costs,
Blue Cross and Blue Shield said administrative costs were $7
million lower in the third quarter than they were in the same
period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, concerned about recent financial troubles at HMOs,
the Massachusetts Senate Monday unanimously passed an HMO
insolvency bill that would provide protections for consumers and
HMOs themselves in the event of a health plan's failure. The House
passed a similar bill earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Given the ``ominous'' condition of the state's health plans, the
bill is ``desperately needed,'' said state Senator Bruce E. Tarr, a
Gloucester Republican.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
