<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Nov. 21) 
(jt) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bird-Watching in Rio
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there places in or near Rio de Janeiro where I can do
some bird-watching? I would go with a tour company that organizes
excursions of a few days or even for an afternoon, but am also
willing to venture into a parklike setting by myself. _ David T.
Lane, Norfolk, Va. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Perhaps the most convenient place for bird-watching in Rio de
Janeiro _ and one that you can easily explore by yourself _ is the
339-acre Botanical Gardens. Some 5,000 varieties of tropical plants
and trees attract more than 100 species of birds, including
flycatchers, cotingas and macaws. The gardens, on the Rua Jardim
Botanico, are about a 10-minute drive from Ipanema. They are open
daily from 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission is $2. Information:
(55-21) 294-6012. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few miles to the north, the 8,154-acre Tijuca National Park
and Forest is home to toucans, parakeets, hummingbirds and other
species. For serious exploration, it's best to take a tour _ people
have been known to get lost in the woods, and muggings are not
uncommon. Jeep Tours, (55-21) 522-1620, can organize one-day
bird-watching excursions. The cost is $35 a person with a minimum
of six people. The Tijuca National Park and Forest is open daily, 7
a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission is free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Rio, there are numerous areas for bird-watching. For
instance, the forests of the 27,181-acre Serra dos Orgaos Park in
Teresopolis, a mountain resort 50 miles north of the city, is home
to toucans, parrots, hummingbirds, gray-wing cotingas and kinglet
kalypturas, among other species. Ricardo Parrini, an ornithologist
and guide charges $100 a day per person for a full-day trek through
the park. Information: (55-21) 570-3155; e-mail:
rparrini(AT)hotmail.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One hundred miles north of Rio, is the Itatiaia National Park,
which has one of the densest bird populations in South America,
with some 400 species living in its 74,131 rugged acres. Focus
Tours, based in Santa Fe, N.M., offers a three-day nature tour from
Rio for a minimum of six participants, costing $799 a person,
including transportation, meals, guide and hotel. Information:
(505) 466-4688, fax (505) 466-4689.
</P>
<P>
   France's Picasso Museums
</P>
<P>
   Q. Of the two Picasso museums in France, does the one in Paris
have the more extensive collection? _ Martha P. Atkins, Providence,
R.I.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are actually three Picasso museums in France, and yes,
the one in Paris has, by far, the largest collection. But the two
others _ in Antibes on the Cote d'Azur and in nearby Vallauris _
are well worth visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso, who was born in Spain, spent much of the first half of
the 20th century working in Paris. In lieu of paying estate taxes
after his death in 1973, his heirs turned over hundreds of Picasso
works to the French government. They may be viewed at the Picasso
Museum in Paris, which houses more than 250 Picasso paintings,
1,500 sketches, some 150 sculptures, as well as collages and
ceramics.
</P>
<P>
   Among the works you'll find are ``Portrait of Olga in an
Armchair'' (1917) and ``Pan's Flute'' (1923). An exhibition of
recently acquired works _ ``From Celestine to Dora Maar, 10 Years
of Enrichment at the Picasso Museum''_ runs through Jan. 3. The
museum, at 5, rue de Thorigny in the Marais district, is housed in
an ornate 17th-century mansion known as the Hotel Sale. Admission
is $4.75, $3 for visitors between the ages of 18 and 25, free for
those under 18, $3 for everyone on Sunday. Hours are 9:30 a.m. to 6
p.m.; until 8 p.m. on Thursday; closed Tuesdays. Information:
(33-1) 42.71.25.21. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Picasso spent several months working in the Chateau
Grimaldi in Antibes. The chateau is now the Picasso Museum in
Antibes, which has about 300 Picasso works, including ``La Joie de
Vivre'' (1946), and a fine ceramics display. A temporary exhibition
of works by the modern French artist Roger Bissiere, will run
through January. The museum is open Tuesday through Sunday from 10
a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission is $4.75. Information: (33-4) 92.90.54.20.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller Musee National Picasso La Guerre et la Paix and the
adjoining Musee Magnelli, are in Vallauris, about 10 miles east of
Antibes. Picasso retreated to Antibes between 1948 and 1955 with
Francoise Gilot, his companion at the time. In 1952, the artist
painted a monumental fresco called ``La Guerre et la Paix'' on the
walls and ceilings of the town's 16th-century chapel (now the
museum). The Magnelli displays a collection of Picasso ceramics and
Picasso's 1972 painting ``Hidalgo au Colombe,'' as well as works by
the abstract Italian painter Alberto Magnelli. The museum, on the
Place de la Liberation, is open daily from 10 a.m. to noon and from
2 p.m. to 6 p.m. (until 6:30 during the summer). Admission to both
is $2.50. Information: (33-4) 93.64.16.05.
</P>
<P>
   Sicily-Malta Ferries
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have information on ferryboat travel to and from
Malta, starting in Sicily? Is advance booking necessary? _ Ellen K.
Parrella, Newtown, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. Island Seaway and Virtu are among the companies with the most
frequent year-round sailings. Reservations are necessary only
during the summer, when calling two weeks ahead is suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Island Seaway, a Maltese company, operates from Catania and
Reggio di Calabria in Sicily. Ferries leave Catania at 7 p.m. on
Tuesday and Thursday and arrive in Valletta on Malta at 7 a.m. the
next day. A round-trip ticket costs $107. Children between 4 and 12
pay half the fare (free for those under 4). Cars cost an additional
$150. The return ferry from Valletta departs on Monday and
Wednesday at 8 p.m.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ferries from Reggio di Calabria leave on Sunday, at 1:30 p.m.
and arrive in Malta at 5:30 a.m. Round-trip fare is $134; cars cost
an additional $163. Information: (39-095) 325081, fax (39-095)
7159385.
</P>
<P>
   Virtu Ferries, another Maltese company, operates faster
hydrofoil boats between the southern Sicilian port of Pozzallo and
Valletta. From Nov. 1 to March 14, the hydrofoils leave Pozzallo on
Thursday at 6:30 p.m., arriving in Valletta at 8 p.m.; on Saturday,
they leave at 8:30 p.m. arriving at 10 p.m. A connecting bus for
the Saturday hydrofoil leaves Catania at 6 p.m. From Valletta there
are hydrofoils on Thursday at 7 a.m. and Saturday at 5 a.m. There
are more frequent runs during the summer. Round-trip fare is $67.
Children between 4 and 12 pay half-price. Information: (39-06)
4817807.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
