<HEADER>
A0652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-POINTS-COX     11-15 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POINTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMS the site for Irvan tributeBy Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan is one of NASCAR's 50 all-time greatest drivers. But
Irvan never got a farewell tour or retirement party, after
suffering career-ending injuries during a practice session wreck at
Michigan Speedway three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta Motor Speedway will pay a final tribute to Irvan on
Sunday, just before the start of the NAPA 500. Irvan and his wife,
Kim, will circle the track for a farewell lap in a specially
designed M&AMP;M's ``Millennium'' Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be one of the more emotional moments of the Winston
Cup season, considering what Ernie has done for this sport and what
he has been through,'' said Tom Beard, co-owner of the No. 36 team
that employed Irvan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a pretty neat deal,'' Irvan said. ``I think I've
meant a lot to this sport. And able to do a lap, even though it's
just a show car, is something I owe to all the fans who have
supported me through the years. I know it's going to an emotional
moment for my family and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan, 40, was forced into retirement after 313 races and 15
victories at stock-car racing's highest level. He posted one win at
AMS, the fall race in March 1994. All former AMS champions,
including Irvan, will be honored in a separate ceremony on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of good times racing at Atlanta, and I'm sure I'll
be thinking about some of those moments during the lap,'' Irvan
said. ``Plus (AMS) is owned by Bruton Smith, who also owns the
Charlotte track, where I used to work (as a welder). So, there are
a lot of tie-ins.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan's racing career ended abruptly after he wrecked during
Busch practice Aug. 20. Irvan, who had to be cut out of his car by
safety workers, was diagnosed later with a bruised lung and mild
head injury. He still is recovering from the concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real frustrating, because I'm so lost for a lot of
words,'' Irvan said. ``I can't even bowl, because I don't have all
of my hand-eye coordination back. Just walking up the steps is a
concern. I have got to be real careful: You don't know to pick your
foot up and not to put your foot up. It's something that no one who
hasn't been through something like this would understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the continuing health problems, Irvan said it was
undecided whether he or his wife will drive the car for Sunday's
farewell lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the brain, and not a broken arm or wrist, which you can
visibly see the healing,'' Irvan said. ``Today, 99 percent of the
people that see me don't realize I've ever had a concussion, unless
they know. And if they know, they'll tell me I'm 100 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not 100 percent,'' he said. ``The doctors anticipate a
full recovery for me, but they really don't know when. My thought
process is coming back, but it is just real slow and going to take
some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Irvan's most recent wreck happened five years ago to
the day that he was critically injured in a Winston Cup practice
session at the same Michigan track. Irvan was given a 10 percent
chance to live after the 1994 accident, but he staged an miraculous
recovery and returned to the circuit to win three more races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had any withdrawals about retiring, because today
I'm not capable of driving a race car,'' Irvan said. ``But I'll
probably feel like that at (February's) Daytona 500, because I feel
like I am going to be capable of driving by that time, if I elected
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, I don't have any second thoughts about retiring. I've
got a lot better chances of watching my two kids(, Jordan, 6, and
Jared, 2,) grow up than if I raced again,'' Irvan said. ``Family is
a more important thing to me than Winston Cup racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan said he hopes his decision will be an inspiration to other
athletes. He said he has been monitoring, among others, the
situation of San Francisco quarterback Steve Young, who has been
sidelined with a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, reality has been starting to set in with a lot of
football players,'' Irvan said. ``You see guys like (Young) who
should think about retirement, but they haven't done it yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think God has worked with me for this purpose. He said, `OK,
we saved your life one time, and now you can be an inspiration to
other athletes.' There is so much more to life than just sports.''
</P>
<P>
   While Irvan won't be behind the wheel, he hasn't left racing. He
and Mark Simo own a Winston Cup team that has attempted to make the
field for several races this season. Irvan plans to turn it into a
full-time team by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
