<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS-2TA     11-15 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CLINTON BETS THAT OPENING CHINA'S MARKETS WILL OPEN
SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: 2nd take expected to move by 8:45 p.m.) 
 (With CHINA-U.S.-TRADE and related stories) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the end, the deal struck Monday between the
United States and China was one that President Clinton had little
choice but to seal.
</P>
<P>
   For a president who talks constantly these days about harnessing
the forces of economic globalization, the agreement to integrate
China into the global trading system marked the culmination of
Clinton's single biggest imprint on American foreign policy: the
use of American economic power for strategic ends. That is what
this agreement is all about, locking in China's commitment to
economic reforms and with it, he is betting, a further opening of
Chinese society.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton came to that strategy in the most roundabout of
ways. He began from the other side of the China debate, denouncing
President Bush for economic engagement with a nation that had just
killed hundreds at Tiananmen Square. Soon he came to the conclusion
that every president has reached since Richard Nixon: There is
little realistic choice other than engagement.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half into his presidency, Clinton had already
reversed course, saying he would no longer link human rights or
missile proliferation or other issues to his annual renewal of
China's trading rights with the United States. Ever since, he has
been a passionate advocate of the long-term benefits of opening up
China's politics by opening up its markets _ stringing
American-built cell-phone networks from Shanghai to Tibet, letting
a hundred Internet sites bloom, insisting that if China applies the
the rule of law for Boeing, it eventually will have to apply it to
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   He has, in short, pressed the economic engagement argument to an
extreme no other president, Bush included, has ever taken. Along
the way he has learned a hard lesson: His early hopes that economic
change and political change would quickly come hand-in-hand in
China were a fantasy. In the end, he concluded that if the business
of America is business, so was much of its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, China's leaders thought nothing of
simultaneously negotiating with Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade
representative, over subjecting China to the WTO's commercial laws
while sentencing four members of the Falun Gong, the religious
group whose silent meditations have struck fear into the heart of
the Communist Party, to prison sentences of up to 12 years. The
first was good business, a way of promoting more foreign investment
into a country that needs the world's cash and technology more than
ever. The second was, in the view of China's leaders, a question of
political control. Clinton has now molded American policy to
reflect that reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be realistic about the prospects for change in
China because there are elements of the country that will never
change,'' Ms. Barshefsky said Monday. ``But what's the alternative?
Let's punish China by not gaining access to its market? Who does
that punish? I am cautious in making claims that a market-opening
agreement leads to anything other than opening the market. It may _
it could have a spillover effect _ but it may not. And we've got to
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it reflects a maturing of the China debate in the United
States that just as Clinton has come to understand the limits of
trade agreements, some of his critics have come to appreciate their
possibilities. Human Rights Watch, one of the many organizations
constantly monitoring the country, embraced the accord Monday,
sounding a note of cautious hope that Clinton's long-term bet could
pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's membership in the WTO could increase pressure for
greater openness, more press freedom, enhanced rights for workers
and an independent judiciary,'' Human Rights Watch said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHINA-BUSINESS-BOS &LR;      11-15 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BUSINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISK FOR BOTH SIDES SEEN IN US-CHINA TRADE ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One-fifth of the world Monday bet on the free
market system.
</P>
<P>
   The US-China agreement for China's accession to the World Trade
Organization, announced Monday in Beijing, came after six days of
intense bargaining that yielded a bottom line allowing the global
economy to plow into China.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, say analysts, is risky _ for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   For President Clinton and the United States, the agreement
lowers the trade gate into China another substantial notch, opening
up the world's second largest economy to multinational companies
peddling financial services, telecommunications, computers,
insurance and agriculture. But it also means the United States
loses key leverage on China to curb human rights abuses, and some
critics say the United States could lose jobs, especially in
textile industries.
</P>
<P>
   For China and its 1.3 billion people, the change further exposes
the country's schism between a hunger for a free economy and a
political system that craves control. The deal calls for ripping
off the economic shackles of state-run companies, exposing its
shrouded banking system to accountants of the outside world and
shutting down pirates who steal ideas and trademarks of the West,
from copies of ``Star Wars'' DVDs to fur coats cut in the shape of
Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is betting on China.com instead of China.communism,''
said Todd Buchholz, president of the Victoria Capital investment
firm in Washington and author of ``Market Shock,'' a recent book on
global economics. ``They are saying economic growth and open
markets are more important to the future of China than maintaining
the chokehold of the Communist Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the key details remain hidden. But broad parts of the
agreement, including allowing foreign firms to immediately buy up
to 49 percent of China's telecommunications firms and as much as 50
percent in two years, paint a future that would allow US firms to
make deep inroads into what most international economists believe
will be the world's biggest market in 20 or 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now China must begin negotiations with other WTO countries, but
the US-China deal was the key roadblock. US Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky, who is a political celebrity in Asia after
appearing on the front pages of major newspapers there for the past
six days, predicted Monday that China would likely join the WTO
early next year after wrapping up talks with other member nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva-based WTO operates like this: All member states must
give the same trade deal to each other, effectively giving all
parties ``most favored nation'' basis. Now, China's most favored
nation basis in the United States is reviewed every year by
Congress, which gives lawmakers an opportunity to press China on
prickly issues such as human rights.
</P>
<P>
   But once in the WTO, that annual review would cease. The United
States hopes that the vast influences of the global economy will
have a profound ripple effect in China, encouraging greater
openness in all aspects of Chinese life, including human rights and
military sales. This school of thought embraces the old axiom that
nations that trade don't go to war.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a political gamble for the Clinton administration,
coming at a time when China has been arresting many members of the
Falun Gong spiritual movement and when the Justice Department and
Congress are investigating whether China stole nuclear secrets from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   China has been gradually relaxing trade barriers for a
generation, a process that has sped up in the last three years
under the leadership of Zhu Rongji and President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO agreement, which China has negotiated for 13 years, is
another step along that continuim, but it's a historic step, say
many economists and political analysts such as Buchholz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win for economic reform, and ultimately it leads to
more democracy,'' Buchholz said Monday. ``What this tells me is
that Zhu Rongji is winning the game again within China, where he's
been under tremendous pressure from the front-biting and
back-biting. . . . I predict now the fall of the Communist Party
eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel P. Trachtman, professor of international law and academic
dean at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts
University, wasn't so bold, but he said China will be hard-pressed
now to back away from the free market system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big commitment to liberalization,'' Trachtman said.
``It gets them on a kind of train that will be hard to get off
of.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical benefits to many Chinese are plain. As long as the
Chinese leadership stays in the WTO and agrees to its laws, Chinese
workers, known for their amazingly high rates of savings, would be
able to invest their money with US banks, not just state banks that
give meager interest rates. Computer software engineers might land
jobs with US high tech firms. Internet access could explode as the
prices dip.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO arrangement might seem like just another impact of the
information revolution and the global economy _ except that China
with its hundreds of new skyscrapers and tens of new airports and
its cellular telephone network multiplying at dizzying rates isn't
just another nation, but one-fifth of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
