<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.BARSHEFSKY-     11-15 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLENE BARSHEFSKY, THE WOMAN WHO BROUGHT CHINA INTO GLOBAL
TRADING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 BARSHEFSKY-NYT  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first time Charlene Barshefsky found herself
sitting in the waiting room outside the office of China's
president, Jiang Zemin, her mind was suddenly flooded by an image
from a different time and a different place: Chicago in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girl who lived down the street used to come over so we
could play `Digging to China,''' recalled Barshefsky, the slight,
intense woman who has been at the center of American trade policy
since 1993. ``And I kept wondering, how did I get from digging with
my mother's kitchen spoons in the backyard to negotiating with
Jiang?''
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, Barshefsky completed her dig.
</P>
<P>
   At once jubilant and exhausted, she announced that the
13-year-long quest for an accord that would usher China into the
global trading system was over. For the 49-year-old former trade
lawyer, it is the capstone deal of her tenure in a once-backwater
cabinet post _ a post that, a decade after the Cold War's end, has
made its occupant a central player in American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as Barshefsky regularly reminds both Congress and her
White House colleagues, these days trade accords are ``the new
organizing devices for our international relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a perfect example,'' Barshefsky said Monday in a
conversation from Hong Kong, where she was changing planes on the
way home. ``Since 1979, when we recognized China, there has been no
agreement to anchor the Chinese-American relationship in any
concrete way. I'm not sure this is an anchor, but it's a start.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Clinton administration has discovered time and again,
China defies diplomatic organizing devices of all sorts. Some of
Barshefsky's battles to get to this deal were not fought across the
negotiating table, but in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In April, she engaged in an embarrassing public disagreement
with her boss, the president _ who rejected her advice to take
China's trade offer in April, a decision Clinton immediately
regretted. She seethed with frustration for months as the
administration tried repeatedly to rebuild relations with Beijing,
which went into the deep freeze during the war in Kosovo. She told
Congress the other day that what set the negotiations off track
was, ``Men never ask for directions, and we mistakenly bombed the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.'' Not for the first time, her White
House colleagues winced.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the end-game began in last week _ days and
nights of caffeine-driven talks about the intricacies of American
investment in Chinese telecommunications companies and the need for
American auto companies to set up financing subsidiaries so that
ordinary Chinese can afford cars _ Barshefsky was in her element.
</P>
<P>
   Moving between the Palace Hotel in Beijing and the trade
ministry, she conducted the three-dimensional chess of modern trade
negotiations: There were the arcane rules of ``accession'' to the
World Trade Organization. Then there were the political realities
of the concessions China needed to make to get the deal through
Congress. There were also the concessions that the Chinese leaders
feared they could not make without destablizing their own economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there was the difficult problem of making sure that
Clinton got the credit for an agreement very much like the one he
walked away from.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a one-woman phenomenon,'' her predecessor, Mickey
Kantor, said recently about the woman he first hired as deputy and
then helped promote after he became secretary of commerce. ``I've
never seen anyone who can operate better on no sleep, still talk in
perfect paragraphs, and just grind down the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Barshefsky found during the prolonged negotiations, in
the end the deal hinged on relationships _ relationships with
Clinton and with Prime Minister Zhu Rongji of China.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese knew that Barshefsky has never had the kind of close
relationship or long history with Clinton that Kantor enjoyed. They
knew she was overruled in April. They had reason to question her
authority to negotiate one of the biggest trade deals in history.
She resolved that by bringing along as he co-negotiator Gene
Sperling, the president's top economic adviser and a man they knew
had urged Clinton to walk away from the first deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed the mix,'' she said, ``and it sent a message. And
in a negotiation, every message you send counts.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a lesson Barshefsky learned as the daughter of Russian and
Polish immigrants who arrived in the northwest side of Chicago with
little English, but a passion for education. They were not thrilled
when she got a law degree _ ``it wasn't intellectual enough for
them,'' she once said _ but quickly she had a job at the Washington
law firm of Steptoe and Johnson that paid half a million dollars a
year running the firm's international division.
</P>
<P>
   She tossed away the cash for the chance to be Kantor's deputy,
constantly juggling trips to Japan _ where she became as popular as
a case of the plague _ with shuttling around her two daughters,
Mari, now 16, and Devra, now 11. When abroad, she would review
their homework with them nightly by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   She is married to Ed Cohen, the droll deputy counsel at the
Department of the Interior, who will not be seeing much of her
anytime soon: She heads from the China negotiation into the global
trade talks that start in Seattle in two weeks, an attempt to start
a ``Millennium Round'' of trade barrier reductions.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday morning, going to see Jiang on her way out of
Beijing, Barshefsky said her mind once again drifted away from the
talks and back to her childhood excavations. ``I'm sure the only
thing I knew about China then was that it was halfway around the
world and that it was important,'' she said. ``It was a start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
