u a BC-GA-EDUCATION-COX     11-15 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-EDUCATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAT won't be litmus test if Georgia commission has way
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ High school students would have to take tests at the
end academic courses and the results could help determine admission
to state colleges and universities, according to a scenario that
received support Monday from the Governor's education reform
commission.
</P>
<P>
   End-of-course testing could have a wide-ranging effect on high
school life, but the idea of linking it to college admission is one
that the University System of Georgia is already exploring in a
pilot project.
</P>
<P>
   The project is developing end-of-course tests to use in an
alternative admission policy at 10 colleges and universities and
seven technical schools for students at 11 high schools. Assistant
Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs Jan Kettlewell, who is running
this $1-million privately-funded experiment, said students would be
able to gain admission in 2001 using course-based test scores.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the pilot project is to attempt to bring high school
and college standards and expectations into closer harmony,
Kettlewell said.
</P>
<P>
   In its discussion of end-of course tests, members of the reform
commission expressed enthusiasm for using results in admissions
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would give less emphasis to the SAT,'' Gov. Roy Barnes
said, citing complaints made about this influential
college-entrance exam that tests reasoning skills, not the content
learned in high school courses.
</P>
<P>
   It would take years before such a practice is universal. Such
tests, as the governor's education reform commission discussed them
Monday, would be given in grades 9 through 12 at the end of every
course in language arts, math, science and social studies. Passing
the tests would be required to pass each course as well as to
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Commission members said end-of-course tests would be more
rigorous than the current high school graduation exam because each
test would be given in the year in which the student learned the
subject, rather than waiting until the 11th grade. Also, the tests
could assess high-level subjects such as geometry and chemistry,
which are not on the graduation exam.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cumming writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
