u i BC-UN-BOSNIA-BOS &LR;      11-15 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-BOSNIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN SHOULDERS BLAME FOR MASSACRE OF BOSNIAN MUSLIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United Nations, in an unusually blunt
report, blamed itself Monday for failing to stop the 1995 Serb
massacre of thousands of Muslim civilians in the Bosnian town of
Srebrenica, saying it was wrong to rule out the use of force to
stop the Serbs and wrong to deny Muslims the ability to defend
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Outrage over the slaughter at Srebrenica, which had been
designated a UN ``safe area,'' heightened US and European resolve
to act and helped lead to NATO's military intervention, which led
ultimately to the end of the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through error, misjudgment and an inability to recognize the
scope of the evil confronting us, we failed to do our part to help
save the people of Srebrenica from the Serb campaign of mass
murder,'' the report by Secretary General Kofi Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report makes clear the inadequacy of the entire approach
of the United Nations to the Serb campaign of `ethnic cleansing,'
'' a senior UN official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the July 1995 massacre, NATO launched air raids on
Bosnian Serb targets. The war was over by November.
</P>
<P>
   ``That extraordinary, galvanizing event, which is one of the
great tragedies in Europe in the past half century, was also part
of the reason why the US got fully engaged,'' said Richard
Holbrooke, the US ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   While 2,200 bodies from Srebrenica were recovered, the Red Cross
says that about 7,300 inhabitants are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's 155-page report, requested a year ago by the General
Assembly, dissects in detail the failed UN policy throughout the 3
1/2-year Bosnian war. It concludes that the Bosnian Muslims should
have had access to arms despite an embargo and that airstrikes and
a fighting force, rather than peacekeepers, should have been
deployed early in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said 150 Dutch peacekeepers charged with protecting
Srebrenica cannot be blamed since their repeated requests for NATO
airstrikes on the advancing Serb forces, which Annan Monday called
``clearly warranted,'' were denied by UN military commanders and
headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who headed UN peacekeeping at the time, said he was
included in the decision to deny the air support. He said it was
made to avoid an appearance the United Nations had entered the war
against Serbia, to prevent an escalation of the conflict, to
preserve the UN's humanitarian mission and to prevent peacekeepers
from being taken hostage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were, with hindsight, wrong to declare repeatedly and
publicly that we did not want to use air power against the Serbs
except as a last resort, and to accept the shelling of the safe
areas as a daily occurrence,'' Annan wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Without air cover, the Dutch troops, which have been sharply
criticized ever since, withdrew from observation posts under direct
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Annan says the United Nations had no warning that 20,000 Serb
troops massed near Srebrenica would attack. The Dutch troops are
blamed for not fully reporting the situation, but Annan admits the
United Nations generally failed to understand the Serbs' war aims.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said another failed policy was keeping the Muslims under
the arms embargo, which handed the Serbs an overwhelming advantage.
He said treating all sides equally amounted to ``appeasement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The community of nations decided to respond to the war in
Bosnia and Herzegovina with an arms embargo, with humanitarian aid
and with the deployment of a peacekeeping force,'' the report says.
``These measures were poor substitutes for more decisive . . .
action to prevent the unfolding horror.''
</P>
<P>
   The UN must learn several lessons from the fall of Srebrenica
``if we are to expect the peoples of the world to place their faith
in the United Nations,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   Among these lessons are that peacekeepers must never again be
deployed without a cease-fire or peace agreement and UN-protected
areas must be fully defended by a ``credible military deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Having served as undersecretary general for peacekeeping
operations during much of the period under review,'' Annan said,
``I am fully cognizant of the mandate entrusted to the United
Nations and only too painfully aware of the organization's failures
in implementing that mandate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
