<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0667 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-CONGRESS-8     11-15 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-CONGRESS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION FACES OPPOSITION ON CHINA PACT FROM LIBERALS AND
CONSERVATIVES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)   (With CHINA-U.S.-TRADE and related stories) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration and business groups
prepared an intense campaign on Monday to win approval in Congress
for China's entry into the World Trade Organization, facing
opposition from conservatives who object to almost any dealings
with China and liberals who say the trade pact would be bad for
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties said the deal would most likely be
approved in the House, the more difficult of the two congressional
battlegrounds, based on the solid bipartisan majority that granted
China a one-year extension of favorable trading terms earlier this
year. Victory in the Senate, while far from assured, is more
likely, senators said, because the Republican leadership is likely
to support it.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the supporters nor the opponents were taking the
outcome for granted, given the volatility of the relationship
between the United States and China and the political sensitivity
of trade issues heading into an election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take an awful lot of work,'' said Rep. David
Dreier, R-Calif., who is chairman of the House Rules Committee and
a leading advocate of bringing China into the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Congress would not vote on the agreement itself, but on whether
the United States should permanently grant China normal trading
privileges, which is effectively a condition of the deal. Since
1974, Congress has had to vote annually on whether to retain a
normal trading relationship with China, a process that critics of
China have used to express their displeasure with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to win greater access to the huge market in China _ and
stung by criticism that they had been ineffectual in rallying
support for past trade votes _ business groups promised an all-out
campaign to get the deal enacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were asked by the administration if we could deliver the
votes,'' said L. Craig Johnstone, senior vice president for
international economic and national security affairs at the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce. ``We said we could and we will.''
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications and financial services industries are
expected to be big beneficiaries of the trade agreement as are
American auto makers.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have been generally supportive of a deal with
China, but were cautious in their reaction on Monday. Sen. Trent
Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, said there were still
``significant questions'' about the deal's effects on human rights,
religious freedom and the economic relationship between the two
countries, and that he was reserving judgment until he could study
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Even if, as expected, the Republican leadership ultimately joins
the White House in pushing for the agreement, the proposal is still
sure to set off a bitter debate uniting some of the most
conservative Republicans and the most liberal Democrats against
centrists in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Citing what they said were human rights abuses, the spread of
nuclear and conventional arms, a lack of concern for environmental
issues and the prospect that increased trade would result in some
American workers losing their jobs, a spectrum of groups said they
would try to block or modify the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, called the deal ``a
grave mistake,'' and said that it was ``disgustingly hypocritical''
of the administration to claim to be keeping the interests of
working people in mind even as it negotiated with a regime that
routinely violates human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the trade deal by human rights advocates could
also give an opportunity to conservative Republican presidential
candidates like Steve Forbes and Gary Bauer to win support from the
right wing of their party, whose leading candidate, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, supports the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., said the agreement was a ``raw
deal'' for workers and consumers because it would institutionalize
tariff advantages enjoyed by China.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of that, we'd be putting our stamp of approval on
having a gangster regime coming into yet another international body
and thinking that in some way that body is going to civilize the
regime,'' Rohrabacher said, ``when in fact it's more likely that
the organization itself will be corrupted by having the world's
worst human rights violator in its midst.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they would press hard to get the
deal approved, probably in the first few months of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that when Congress has an opportunity to study the
terms of this, recognize the tremendous benefits to American
industry and American workers around the country, and the
protections that we obtain for import-sensitive industries in this
agreement, that there will be broad support for it,'' Sandy Berger,
the national security adviser, told reporters in Turkey, where
President Clinton was traveling on Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The administration won support on Monday from Human Rights
Watch, an advocacy group that said China's entry into the trade
organization ``could increase pressure for greater openness, more
press freedom, enhanced rights for workers and an independent
judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House is primarily counting on business groups.
Administration officials have consulted closely with business
lobbyists to gauge support for a deal on Capitol Hill and to plan
strategy for winning approval.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Roundtable, which represents the nation's largest
corporations, has readied a plan to tout the benefits of the deal
in 71 key congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, for example, the business group has hired a political
organizer, Bill Menner, to get local businesses and interest groups
working on behalf of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Menner said he plans to turn to influential groups like the Iowa
Farm Bureau Federation and to other employers in the state, like
Diamond V Mills, a soybean processor in Cedar Rapids, and the
corporate headquarters of Roto-Rooter in West Des Moines, to make a
public case for the deal and call their members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The roundtable also plans to run newspaper advertising in Iowa
emphasizing the economic benefits the deal would bring to farmers
and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that when push comes to shove,'' Menner said, ``the
case we can make about the benefits of trade with China will carry
the day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
