<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-CONFERENCE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADER OF CATHOLIC BISHOPS GIVES STATE-OF-THE-CHURCH ADDRESS 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The human rights focus of America's Catholic
bishops feeds into a historical stream of church-initiated social
action still needed by the world, Bishop Joseph A. Fiorenza of
Houston told his brother bishops Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few past centuries have witnessed the display of sin and grace
as starkly as the one now ending,'' said Fiorenza, president of the
American bishops' conference and leader of 900,000 Catholics in the
Diocese of Galveston-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In a state-of-the-church address, Fiorenza decried abortion,
sweatshop labor, weapons of mass destruction, capital punishment
and other social ills.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he led the conference in calling for an end to economic
sanctions against Iraq and questioning the ``moral justification''
of American airstrikes. With Pope John Paul II, the bishops have
opposed the sanctions since the end of the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political and military sanctions remain acceptable;
comprehensive economic sanctions are not,'' says the statement,
urging the United States and the United Nations Security Council to
end the economic embargo. The sanctions have harmed innocent
civilians by halting the flow of essential medicine and food,
Fiorenza said.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, he said retaining the ``Catholic identity'' of
church-affiliated universities is as central to those institutions
today as it was to Catholic schools 125 years ago when the church
established America's parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, ``there was a great effort to preserve the Catholic
mission of our schools,'' Fiorenza said in an interview. ``Those
issues are still involved in the discussion on higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   That discussion tops the bishops' agenda this week as they vote
on a proposal that will determine how much control the church will
exercise over America's 235 Catholics colleges and universities,
including seven in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The prelates are at the center of a divide between Vatican
demands and American traditions of academic freedom. They are to
vote on the matter Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would require that Catholic theologians must obtain
a mandate from the local bishop in their region in order to teach
and that a majority of board members and faculty at such schools be
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics disagree over how stringently the rules would have to
be enforced, but many Catholic academics fear the proposal would
undermine academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop John Leibrecht of Springfield, Mo., said the bishops want
their institutions ``to have autonomy,'' but also want to keep such
schools in the Catholic fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we want our Catholic schools to be uniquely
Catholic in their mission, their identity and the messages they
impart to students,'' Fiorenza said.
</P>
<P>
   If two-thirds of the bishops approve the text of the proposal,
it will go to Rome for approval.
</P>
<P>
   The issue dates to the pope's 1990 decree, ``Ex Corde
Ecclesiae,'' in which the pontiff sought to strengthen the Catholic
identity of church-affiliated schools serving his worldwide flock.
The autonomy and academic freedom of colleges are recognized, but
only ``within the confines of truth and common good.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the papal decree, the Vatican instructed each nations'
bishops to apply the new rules within their countries. In 1996, the
U.S. bishops overwhelmingly endorsed a less-stringent policy widely
supported. But the Vatican rejected that policy, insisting it
should be stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Many bishops could have problems with this draft, predicted the
Rev. Thomas J. Reese of New York, who has authored several books on
the bishops. He said the current proposal could make it more
difficult for Catholic bishops and academicians to keep talking
about what it means to be a Catholic institution. ``The word
Catholic will become identified with mandate and control by the
bishops,'' Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Michael Miller, president of Houston's University
of St. Thomas, supports it. The norms to be approved by the bishops
``will inspire us to take our responsibility with the utmost
seriousness of putting into practice what we claim we are,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
