<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-DO-PART-TWOTAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING SHATTERS KSU COACH'S LIFE 
(ATTN: KAN) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: STORY IS BEING FILED IN ``A'' AND ``S''
CATEGORIES)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. _ Phil Bennett might never have married Nancy
Harris if he hadn't been afraid of losing her.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy was an emergency room nurse at John Peter Smith Hospital
in Fort Worth, Texas. Phil was an assistant football coach at Texas
Christian University. They had dated for a year, and Nancy wanted
to know whether they had a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready,'' Phil repeatedly told her.
</P>
<P>
   Phil was sharing an apartment with Dave McGinnis _ now the
defensive coordinator for the NFL Arizona Cardinals _ and enjoying
life as a 26-year-old bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   Then the young doctors at the hospital began taking an interest
in Nancy. Soon, over enchiladas and chalupas at the Original
Mexican Eats Cafe in west Fort Worth, Phil popped the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go look at a ring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he bought that ring in 1982, he never imagined that ``Till
death do us part'' would come so soon. How do you live without your
wife of 15 years? How do you raise your two children without their
mother? How do you continue the transient life of a football coach
without the one who kept you together?
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Bennett, 41, died Aug. 28, 17 days after being struck by
lightning while jogging in a subdivision under development near the
family home in Manhattan, where Phil is now an assistant at Kansas
State University. Three months later, the homes in the middle-class
neighborhood are all complete. But how do you build a new life?
</P>
<P>
   The worst times are at night. Sleep doesn't come easily or stay
long. Exhausted, Phil forces himself to bed at 1 a.m. but wakes
within three hours.
</P>
<P>
   When he rolls over, she's not there.
</P>
<P>
   His sentences are frequently left unfinished. He still uses the
present tense when talking about her. His tears won't stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like you keep saying: `Is this a dream? Am I going
to wake up? Is someone going to tell me this isn't happening?' ''
he said. ``I miss her. I'm lonely for her. I don't know how you
describe it. Maybe the word is `void.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His last memory of his wife is of her kissing him on her way out
the door. ``I love you. I'll see you tonight,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   How could he have known there wouldn't be a tonight? ___
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Bennett played the same lottery numbers every week. They
included the jersey numbers of her favorite players, among them the
No. 9 of linebacker Dat Nguyen, formerly of Texas A&AMP;M University
and now with the Dallas Cowboys; the No. 48 of former Aggie safety
Rich Coady; and the No. 12 of onetime Louisiana State University
safety Anthony Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Her chances of winning a $1 million lottery _ 2 million to 1 _
were about the same as those of being killed by lightning. From
1959 to 1998, Kansas had 59 lightning fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy jogged every morning before getting the children off to
school. She ran and walked a four-mile course that her husband had
helped her lay out.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:45 a.m. on Aug. 11, Phil woke her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nance, are you going to jog?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she replied. ``I've got to.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil was getting out of the shower when he heard a loud noise.
Unsure whether it was thunder or a military exercise at nearby Fort
Riley, he looked out the window. It was raining.
</P>
<P>
   He left his son, Sam, 11, and daughter, Maddie, 8, sleeping
downstairs and jumped in his car to look for Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   It started raining harder as he slowly traced her route. He
passed a police cruiser with its lights flashing but didn't think
anything of it. He was sure that Nancy had taken cover in one of
the newly framed houses on Meadowood Drive.
</P>
<P>
   With no sign of Nancy, Phil turned back. He drove up to the
policeman and rolled down his window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officer, have you seen a good-looking blonde jogging?''
</P>
<P>
   The policeman's answer was in his pause _ and in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, do you know that woman?''
</P>
<P>
   ``At that instant, I thought: `What you've always been afraid of
has happened. My life has changed forever,' '' Phil said. ``It was
the most helpless feeling I've ever experienced in my life.'' ___
</P>
<P>
   Nancy's address book was as thick as Phil's playbook. She never
met a stranger. Iva Houchin, a waitress at the Original Mexican
Eats Cafe, and Earl Pearson, the manager of an Albertson's grocery
in Baton Rouge, La., were among those she kept in contact with even
as Phil's job took them to TCU, Iowa State, Purdue, LSU, Texas A&AMP;M,
Oklahoma and Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was because she was such a good talker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if she was gone two or three weeks, a month _
when she came back in, it was like it was yesterday,'' Houchin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nancy rarely complained, she never grew comfortable
with their migrant lifestyle. In his 20-year career, Phil has
worked at one high school and seven colleges, never staying
anywhere longer than five years.
</P>
<P>
   The move from Fort Worth took the biggest emotional toll. After
15 years away from her family, Nancy had come home again in 1997
when Phil signed on as TCU's defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   But when head coach Pat Sullivan was fired after the disastrous
1-10 season of 1997, Phil was on the move to the University of
Oklahoma. Only this time, Nancy stayed behind. With Sooners head
coach John Blake on the hot seat, Phil figured that his tenure
there as defensive backs coach was a whistle-stop. He rented an
apartment in Norman, Okla.; Nancy and the children remained in Fort
Worth. They made the three-hour drive every Friday and returned
home Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I sort of kick myself,'' Phil said. ``You only have so
much time, and being away from Nancy and the kids was hard on both
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Phil took an assistant's job at Kansas State, which
was 41-8 for the previous four seasons; he was promoted to
defensive coordinator the next month. Although Nancy was excited
about the opportunity to reunite their family in Manhattan, she was
sad about leaving her parents, Dr. O.T. and Mildred Harris, her two
sisters and her two brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The last time any of them saw Nancy, she and Phil had just
returned from an Alaskan cruise with the other K-State coaches and
their wives. On the cruise, Phil and Nancy were inseparable,
watching the whales, walking hand in hand on the ship's deck and
planning their future in Manhattan. &QL; 
(MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
