<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0671 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HAEART-TERMS16-COX     11-15 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAEART-TERMS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A glossary of heart disease
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEART DISEASE AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   A glossary
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atherosclerosis: A condition also known as hardening of the
arteries. It's caused by thick, hard deposits of plaque that
gradually narrow artery walls. Plaque forms when too much
cholesterol, or fatty substances, circulates in the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cholesterol: A soft, fatlike substance in cells that helps
form cell membranes, hormones and tissues. Cholesterol is made in
the body, mostly in the liver, or absorbed from animal products we
eat: meat, poultry, dairy products or eggs. When cholesterol levels
in the bloodstream build up, plaque begins to form and to narrow
blood vessels. Generally, an overall cholesterol reading below 200
is desirable. People with moderately high readings, of 200 to 239,
have twice the risk of a heart attack as those with readings below
200.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High-density lipoproteins (HDL): Scientists think that this
``good'' cholesterol carries excess cholesterol away from the
arteries and back to the liver, where it is passed from the body. A
high HDL level seems to lower the risk of a heart attack, while a
low HDL seems to raise it. Generally, desirable HDL readings range
from 40 to 50 for men and 50 to 60 for women; a reading below 35 is
low.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Low-density lipoproteins (LDL): When high levels of this
``bad'' cholesterol circulate in the blood, it can slowly build up
on the walls of the arteries to the heart and brain. With other
substances, it forms plaque, which can block blood flow and cause a
heart attack or stroke. An LDL reading below 130 is desirable, 130
to 159 is borderline high, and 160 or above is high.
</P>
<P>
   Risk factors
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Age _ for men, 45 or older; for women, 55 or older.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Race. African-Americans have moderate high blood pressure
twice as often as whites, and severe high blood pressure three
times as often.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A family history of heart disease. If two ``first-degree''
relatives _ mother, father, brother or sister _ have had heart
disease before age 55, your risk rises by 53 percent; one
first-degree relative with heart disease raises your risk by 36
percent. If a first-degree relative suffered cardiovascular disease
at any age, there's an added risk of 6 percent to 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Obesity.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Smoking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Physical inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Elevated LDL (``bad'') cholesterol; low HDL (``good'')
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Heart programs
</P>
<P>
   in metro Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Emory Clinic HeartWise Risk Reduction Program: For heart
patients and those at risk. 404-778-2850.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Northside Hospital Cardiovascular Services: Numerous cardiac
risk reduction classes and programs; public can enroll; various
fees charged. 404-851-6373.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Piedmont Hospital Fuqua Heart Center: For heart patients and
those at risk; fitness center, pool open to public: $45 monthly.
404-605-1834.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Joseph's Hospital Specialty Center for Heart &AMP; Vascular
Care: Provides outreach community and corporate education for free;
free monthly blood pressure screening. 404-851-5112.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Joseph's Heart School: Free monthly class on heart-healthy
living. 404-851-7025.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Joseph's Wellness &AMP; Rehabilitation Center: For heart
patients and those at risk; fitness center, pool open to public;
$40-$50 monthly. 770-730-0010.
</P>
<P>
   Source: American Heart Association
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
