<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0673 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-DEATH-DO-PART(2ndTake     11-15 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-DO-PART(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
 
xxx In Manhattan. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``They had flown back in to Dallas, but Phil had to go on to
Manhattan because of a meeting, so Nancy came by the house about
6:30 one morning,'' said Phil's brother, Jim, head football coach
at Irving High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called us on her cell phone outside our door. She was so
excited. We went downstairs and fixed coffee. She came in, and she
said: `I've only got 15 minutes. I've got to go get the kids at my
parents' in Alvarado.' About three hours later, she left. It was
nonstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy was used to saying goodbye, but this time was the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were standing on the doorstep and hugging and crying like
we were never going to see each other again,'' said Tory Dickey,
the wife of University of North Texas coach Darrell Dickey and one
of Nancy's best friends. ``But it just would never cross your mind
in a million years that you wouldn't.'' ___
</P>
<P>
   Phil and Nancy met on a blind date in 1981. Jim met Nancy's
sister, Suzan, when both were coaching at Alvarado. Jim told Nancy
about his brother, Phil, and she mentioned that she might like to
meet him. Jim wrote Phil's number on a piece of paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't call guys,'' Nancy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if you want to meet him you will,'' Jim said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy, who had recently graduated from Texas A&AMP;M, called Phil,
who had become an A&AMP;M coach after he finished playing there in
1978. Nancy told him that she was visiting College Station for a
friend's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother doesn't make dates for me,'' Phil told her,
agreeing to meet her Friday night to decide whether they should go
out Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   When Nancy opened the door, Phil was struck by her eyes and her
smile. ``Man,'' he said to himself, ``this could be a good blind
date.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy's version of the story, according to Phil, is that he
greeted her with, ``Hi, I'm Phil Bennett, and I'm never getting
married.'' Phil now thinks that could be true.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy moved in with Phil shortly after their engagement in 1982.
By the time they married on June 16, 1984, Phil knew that this was
the woman he couldn't live without.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil was a product of East Texas,'' said R.C. Slocum, who was
Phil's position coach at A&AMP;M. ``Guys back in that generation were
taught to be tough guys. His dad was a pipeline worker _ a strong,
tough kind of a guy. Then Phil had older brothers, so he had to be
tough to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy was from a different background. It was a good blend.
She was really very open and gregarious. I thought she added a lot
to Phil. Where Phil had a quick temper, she was just so smooth with
everything.'' ___
</P>
<P>
   The most painful decision of his life, Phil had to make alone.
</P>
<P>
   When he burst past the security guard into the emergency room at
Mercy Health Center of Manhattan, Phil found a team of doctors and
nurses working to resuscitate his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The lightning had entered at the base of her skull and exited
through her feet. Ron and Laura Thornton, who witnessed the strike
from their home on Meadowood, saw it blow off her jogging shoes and
knock her 6 feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy was burned. Her flesh was smoking. Her forehead was badly
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Phil collapsed, crying, ``Nancy, please.''
</P>
<P>
   In a phone call to longtime friend Joanne Roberts, a former
neighbor in Baton Rouge, Phil sobbed, ``I just don't know how I'm
going to live without her.''
</P>
<P>
   Alone with Nancy later, Phil kissed her.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. She was brain dead.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to give her two weeks to show signs of life. He
consulted specialists from around the country, found by KSU head
football coach Bill Snyder and professional golfer Jim Colbert, a
K-State graduate. Nancy once opened her eyes and her hands
flinched, but doctors said the movement was involuntary. She was
suffering trauma, electrical shock and a lack of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 24, 13 days into the vigil, Phil had life support
terminated. Four days later, Nancy died in his arms.
</P>
<P>
   It's now life after death for Phil, Sam and Maddie, who turned 9
the week after Nancy's funeral. Phil hired Naomi Beck, a Manhattan
Christian College student, as a full-time nanny, and the family has
gone into therapy.
</P>
<P>
   They are coping.
</P>
<P>
   One night, Sam said: ``Dad, every time I hear a siren and you're
at work, I get scared. You're all I have left.''
</P>
<P>
   They miss Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Phil received a certified letter from his mortgage
company threatening foreclosure. He had mistakenly assumed that
their house payments were automatically deducted from their
checking account.
</P>
<P>
   Sam has needed Nancy to fix his skates, and Maddie needed her on
picture day at school, when she went through nine outfits, trying
to find the right one to wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things a mother does that you just can't replace,''
Phil said. ``You just find a way to do them. You find a way to go
on.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first football game, Sam intercepted a pass. That night,
as Phil put him to bed, Sam burst into tears. ``I wish Mom could
have been here to see me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Phil still picks up the telephone to call Nancy before realizing
that she's not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things I just don't know if I can do,'' said Phil,
who has kept Nancy's closet untouched. `I've run a bunch of
marathons, but I have not worked out since Aug. 11. I just can't
bring myself to do it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Every night, the family prays the same prayer: ``God, please
keep us together as a family, draw us closer and watch over Mom.''
It used to be Nancy Bennett who kept watch over her family. Maybe
she still does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel her every day,'' Phil said. ``You just wonder: Where
does it go from here? We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
