<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CONSUMER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Workplace a prime spot for injuries to teenagers
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About once a week, Dr. Anitha Leonard, an urgent-care physician,
treats a teenager who's been injured on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The most common problems: burns caused by steamers and fryers,
cuts caused by slicers or knives, and sprains caused by slick
floors and heavy boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Although summer is the peak season for such accidents, fall is a
good time for parents to evaluate their teenagers' working
conditions. More than 80 percent of high school students work at
some point during the school year, according to a 1998 National
Academies report on child labor. And in the fall, students are more
likely to be fatigued, as a result of being overloaded from school
and extracurricular activities, as well as struggling with cold and
flu season.
</P>
<P>
   Add a job and you have potential for trouble, doctors and safety
experts say. That's particularly true in agriculture, where
children are more likely to be helping with the harvest, according
to the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.
</P>
<P>
   A NIOSH study that examined injuries between 1980 and 1989 found
that 44 percent of job-related deaths of children occurred during
the summer. But almost 25 percent took place in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 children die at work every year, many in motor vehicle,
agricultural and construction accidents. But many more _ around
200,000 annually _ are injured in more commonplace settings, such
as restaurants, grocery stores and stop-and-go markets.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Leonard treated a teenager whose forearm had been
severely burned by a steamer, a scalding that required a trip to
the burn center and follow-up physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people understand how serious these injuries can
be,'' said Leonard, who rotates between Grady Memorial Hospital and
Children's Health Care of Atlanta at Egleston. ``And, often, I
don't think parents have any idea about the conditions their
children are working in.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Castillo of NIOSH agrees. She cited an ``incredibly sad''
case in which a teenager suffocated after a trench collapsed on
him. His father, familiar with construction, had no idea his son
was working in the trench _ ``and said, if he had known, there
would have been no way he would have let him do such a dangerous
job,'' Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
   So what should parents and their children look for in a
workplace?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  First, parents should discuss the kind of work and how many
hours the youngster should be working. Federal law dictates, for
example, that 14- and 15-year-olds may not work more than 18 hours
a week when school is in session, and not more than three hours a
night on school nights.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parents and their children should examine the workplace for
any obvious dangers. Does equipment have safety features? Is the
floor wet and slippery? How many other workers have been injured on
the job? Also, when they're hired, teenagers should be told the
specific jobs they should not be performing because of their age,
in accordance with state and federal laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Young workers should receive proper training in doing the job
correctly and safely. And they should be supervised _ even if they
don't like it _ to make sure they've mastered safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The employer should make the worker aware of the proper
reporting and filing procedure should the worker be injured on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   The State Board of Workers' Compensation provides information
and answers questions about workers' compensation benefits. For an
informational pamphlet or to ask a question, call 404-656-3818 in
the Atlanta area or 1-800-533-0682 elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   There are jobs that the federal government says teenagers should
not be doing, period. They include driving a car or operating a
forklift; operating a circular saw, box crusher, meat slicer or
bakery machine; working in wrecking, demolition, excavation or
roofing; working in mining, logging or a sawmill; working in meat
packing or slaughtering; working where there is exposure to
radiation; and working where explosives are manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   And if your child is 14 or 15 years old, he or she may not bake
or cook on the job (except at a serving counter); operate
power-driven machinery; work on a ladder or scaffold; work in a
warehouse; work in construction; or load or unload a truck,
railroad car or conveyor.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call NIOSH at 1-800-356-4674 or visit its
Web site at www.cdc.gov/niosh/homepage.html.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
