<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-CASE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For mom, daughter, heart disease is family affair
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patty Patterson is one bad-hearted woman. Not because of a mean
streak, but a gene streak.
</P>
<P>
   Like her grandfathers and father before her, she suffered a
heart attack. Hers came at age 37, four years ago. Her father's
heart attack killed him at age 53, her father's father's heart got
him at 65, and her mother's father died at age 51.
</P>
<P>
   And her mother had surgery at age 60 for five blocked arteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reckon I got all the bad genes,'' says Patterson, who lives
in Dalton and works in the shipping department of Oriental Weavers.
``But I had no idea heart disease was hereditary. If I had even a
clue about it, I would have taken better care of myself. At a young
age is when people need to know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson's mother, Betty McPherson, never smoked and thought
she wasn't at risk. ``Then I went in for a routine checkup and
ended up getting checked into the hospital,'' says McPherson, now
69. ``My arteries are still clear. I'm trying to exercise and eat
the right things, but it is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has undergone one heart bypass surgery and three
cardiac angioplasties, including one that left a tiny wire tube,
called a stent, to help keep her blocked artery open.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Patterson has been dealt a bad hand of genetic cards.
But what about those eight cigarettes she lights every day and the
40 pounds she needs to lose?
</P>
<P>
   ``After my first heart attack I did lose a bunch of weight, but
then I gained it back,'' she says. ``And I have cut down on
smoking. Actually, I feel better now than I have in a long time.
... I do play golf and walk on my treadmill three times a week, and
I do lots of yardwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm just a time bomb and if I don't take hold, I won't
even see 50. I know that. But you just can't think about it all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
