r l BC-HESAID-SHESAID16-COX     11-15 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HESAID-SHESAID16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Middle school years are now a pressure cooker
 &HT;    By Maureen Downey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Modern middle school is a mystery to me. I attended first
through eighth grades at St. Catherine's in Elizabeth, N.J. The
melodramatics of adolescence were kept to a minimum by a staff of
all-seeing nuns. The only rap music we heard was the sound of
rulers on knuckles when we misbehaved.
</P>
<P>
   We were indoctrinated. Instead of waiting for phone calls from
boys, we awaited our calling from The Big Guy. Today's
sixth-graders yearn to be Britney Spears. We wanted to be St.
Bernadette.
</P>
<P>
   When I see the social pressures at my 11-year-old daughter's
middle school, I think there were advantages to the school-as-jail
concept. With less leeway, we also had less stress.
</P>
<P>
   There were no status-symbol clothes from the Limited Too and the
Gap to separate the cool from the uncool. We were all sentenced to
dismal earth-green jumpers, geeky knee socks and saddle shoes.
There was no jockeying for the power table in the lunchroom: We ate
at our desks.
</P>
<P>
   A certain esprit de corps ensued; we were unified in our
oppression. Ultimately it may have been a kinder, more democratic
system.
</P>
<P>
   But democracy is easier in a small, homogenous world. My school
graduated only 38 eighth-graders. With so few kids, there was no A
and B list.
</P>
<P>
   I know that dealing with social pressure is part of life. I just
wish that lesson didn't have to come so early.
</P>
<P>
   Kids will survive trials, tribulations of social world
</P>
<P>
   By Bo Emersonc. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Middle school is a roller coaster, a time of high passion,
explosive tempers and wild mood swings. But I hope that as she
becomes accustomed to the environment, Maureen will adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's Maureen who is freaking out. Our daughter Molly
seems to approach the pitfalls of middle school with more
equanimity than her mom.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen's haloed adolescence was a rarity. My public school
experience was closer to the norm, I think. There were hundreds in
my class, a bewildering flow chart of jocks, wonks, freaks,
greasers, techies, stoners, etc.
</P>
<P>
   You swam or you sank. Your social success or failure occurred
totally out of the view of your parents. I can't recall a single
conversation with my folks about the betrayals and back-stabbings
of daily life. I had troubles, but so did everyone, and there
wasn't much an adult could do about it.
</P>
<P>
   This is good to remember, when, as an adult, I'm tempted to fix
the world for my children. You can't create a utopia of equality
among burgeoning teens. You can't insist that no one be excluded
from the cool table at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Even, I imagine, in single-sex parochial schools, young folks
will run the gantlet of social exclusion and/or acceptance. Most
will discover that popularity is a fleeting thing.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen has, more than once, suggested that we intervene, speak
to the parents of another girl or a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   I've persuaded her to refrain. Let's work out those
misunderstandings in the Balkans first. Then we can progress to the
more complicated issues, such as who's going with whom to the
football game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
