<SLUG> BC-PANDAS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More TV for outdoor pandas
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You arrive in this country on all fours, don't speak a
lick of English, and what happens?
</P>
<P>
   You become a cultural phenomenon and a TV star.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo Atlanta pandas Yang Yang and Lun Lun went out in the sun for
the first time Monday, and into the glare of ABC's ``Good Morning
America,'' and NBC's ``Later Today.'' They're scheduled for ``CBS
This Morning'' on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was the first time Zoo Atlanta officials opened the
gates to the bear pair's outdoor habitat, the pandas spent a great
deal of time doing what things on all fours tend to do: sniff
around.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials have been trying their best, despite intense media
interest, to ease the bears' burden of celebrity since they arrived
from China 11 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very active,'' said Zoo marketing director Gail Eaton.
``They played to the cameras. Yang Yang has been initiating lots of
play, and seems to love it outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, both pandas spent lots of time climbing on
outdoor sculptures made of logs. And there were hopeful signs that
our new royal couple would do what is expected of them, one day
start a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing things that indicate a very positive
relationship,'' Eaton said. ``It's very cute.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
