<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0679 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WIT-PLAYWRIGHT16-COX     11-15 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIT-PLAYWRIGHT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fame fails to penetrate the soul behind `Wit'
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Sunday, as workmen hoisted live Christmas trees
onto the awning of Macy's on Herald Square, a shy Atlanta
kindergarten teacher was flying into Manhattan for a quick weekend.
She was here to see a play and visit friends. By today, she planned
to be back in her classroom at John Hope Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing very unusual about that. Except that this teacher wrote
the play. And the play, her first, won the 1999 Pulitzer Prize. And
now the teacher, 38-year-old Margaret Edson _ a sort of modern-day
Emily Dickinson in a denim jacket _ is living half in the world of
phonics and penmanship, and half in the world of the famous writer.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Edson was onstage Sunday night with a New York
Times reporter and baldheaded actress Judith Light (formerly of
television's ``Who's the Boss''), who plays a brainy John Donne
scholar dying with ovarian cancer in the drama ``Wit.'' While the
conversation at this post-performance Q&AMP;A sallies back and forth
between questions of craft and technique, death and metaphysics,
Edson is telling a giggling audience how she's teaching her flock
of 5-year-old charges back home how to make the
</P>
<P>
   letter ``M.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she's been telling them this: ``I don't like just the
two bumps. I like a straight stroke down and then a bump and then a
bump.''
</P>
<P>
   She sketches the letter in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I like the two bumps to be the same size.'' Her jaw drops
open and her tongue curls up in the disbelief of an overwhelmed
child. ``And I said, `Now call me particular, but I like them (the
two bumps) to be touching.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then one of my students said: `Particulaaaaar!'''
</P>
<P>
   So now they call her Miss Particular. And Edson _ an intense,
intellectually rigorous woman who seems to hide behind her wit and
her chosen vocation _ is that. Like Vivian Bearing, her college
professor-protagonist who must submit to the pokes and probes of
her insensitive doctors, Edson has become an unwilling victim to an
inquisitive world that wants to hear all about her accidental brush
with fame.
</P>
<P>
   She's not at wit's end. But she's not exactly loving it either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to have a very hard time getting a story out of
me,'' she tells a reporter over a cup of black coffee in
Virginia-Highland on Saturday, before departing for New York. ``I'm
boring. I am!''
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe that. Hers is one of the better literary tales of
our time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a play that was turned down by nearly every theater in
America,'' says Times culture reporter Dinitia Smith, marveling
about the work that Edson wrote in 1991while employed at a bicycle
shop in her hometown of Washington. This was before Edson got her
master's degree in literature at George Washington University,
before she became a teacher and moved to Atlanta with her partner
Linda Merrill, curator of American art at the High Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Now with talk of a movie deal in the air, with a five-city
national tour kicking off Feb. 1 in Boston (starring Light), an
original-cast production, with actress Kathleen Chalfant, early
next year in Los Angeles, and a London show scheduled for spring,
you'll be reading more about Edson and her exquisitely wrought,
emotionally exhausting drama. ``Wit'' also will be seen in Atlanta
in April, in the intimate atmosphere of the Alliance Theatre
Company's Studio space.
</P>
<P>
   ``That final moment,'' says Smith, referring to the image of
Bearing exposed in the white-hot light of death, ``beats anything I
have seen in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Her personal life is off-limits
</P>
<P>
   Edson, whose 6-foot frame lopes onto the stage in a brown velvet
skirt and jacket and cream colored blouse, has the slouchy posture
of an adolescent girl. But her dark brown eyes are that of a wise
old soul, prescient beyond her years. Like Bearing, she learned
about language beside her elderly father. By the time his middle
child was born, Peter Edson, a well-known Washington syndicated
columnist in the 1950s and '60s, was retired and living at home.
``There's a strain of writing in my family, but I wasn't aware of
it when I was growing up because nobody was doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an interior world here that keeps a discreet address.
When a reporter calls for an interview, Edson says she can't do it
on short notice, then gives in and agrees to meet for coffee.
Arriving, she smiles and apologizes for ``giving you a hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   She responds to questions about her personal life with silence,
penetrating stares, blank looks. Ask the teacher if she wants to
have children of her own, and she snaps, ``That's too personal.''
</P>
<P>
   And so she makes jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Edson says her class followed the Atlanta Braves' World Series
recently by keeping score and cutting out pictures from the
newspaper. ``That gave us good opportunities to explore feelings
and thoughts that adults cope with: disappointment, pain,
resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, so newspapers really are being used in education?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the pictures,'' she quips.
</P>
<P>
   Brevity is the soul of wit.
</P>
<P>
   About the Times-sponsored talk, which has been advertised as a
forum on the impact of ``Wit'' _ ``on writing, medicine and society
at large'' _ she says, ``This is advertising copy. If the ad said,
`An obscure little play about an incomprehensible topic,' people
would not come.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the 499-seat theater is sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer hasn't changed priorities
</P>
<P>
   Edson seems to have her priorities straight. ``When The New York
Times called the company manager and said, `We'd like her to do
this thing,' he said, `It has to be on a weekend, she can't miss
school.' So The New York Times is having to work around the
classroom. It was a nice feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Edson's story is that her play _ which was drawn from
her observations as a clerk in a hospital where early AZT tests
were conducted on AIDS patients _ may be her only one, a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not writing a new play,'' Edson
</P>
<P>
   says, ``I'm not sniffing around for a new
</P>
<P>
   topic either.''
</P>
<P>
   So how has her life changed since she won the Pulitzer? She
can't think of anything. No new swimming pool. No trips to Paris.
``I do have my costumes,'' she jokes about the fancy dresses she
wears to public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she has just returned from a dance class. She and Merrill
have been planting daffodil bulbs in the garden of their new
Midtown home. ``The previous owners ... were wonderful gardeners,
so we're struggling to keep up.'' After this interview, she's going
to lie on her sunny porch and take a nap. It's where she would
prefer to be _ always.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, she's been too much on airplanes. ``I have had maybe 20
speaking engagements this year. ... I'm flying a lot, so I've been
reading Shelby Foote's history of the Civil War. I'm halfway
through volume three. ... I'm looking wistfully toward the end.''
On a recent weekend, she and Merrill visited Chickamauga
battlefield near Chattanooga.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the theater, the evening is winding to a close. A
90-year-old woman stands up to salute Edson and says they have
something in common. ``I'm Smith '31, and you are Smith '83,'' she
tells Edson, a reference to Smith College, where Edson got her
undergraduate degree in history. In a shaking voice she tells the
playwright that she admires the play, but that she is most touched
by the fact that Edson continues to teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't we all wish we had a teacher like this?'' adds the
moderator.
</P>
<P>
   ``WIT'' ONSTAGE
</P>
<P>
   Open-ended run.
</P>
<P>
   $35-$49.50. Union Square Theatre, 100 E. 17th St., New York.
</P>
<P>
   212-307-4100.
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   March 25-April 30. $21 and $27. Alliance Theatre Company's
Studio Theatre, Woodruff Arts Center, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E.
404-733-5000.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
