<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GLENN-BOOK-COX     11-15 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-BOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn's musings compiled in book
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Glenn had just finished nearly nine days in
orbit, his first space flight since becoming the first American to
orbit the earth more than 36 years earlier. The space shuttle
Discovery had sailed spectacularly out of the sunny Florida sky,
landing with pinpoint precision on its 15,000-foot-long landing
strip at Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   The crew transport vehicle, a bus-shaped truck with enormous
hydraulic legs, had pulled up to Discovery and raised its cabin
until it could nuzzle up against the orbiter's hatch. Now everybody
waited ... and waited.
</P>
<P>
   And everybody had one question: Was Glenn OK?
</P>
<P>
   At 77, Glenn was the oldest person to fly in space. Nobody was
sure how his body would hold up under earth's gravity after having
adapted to weightlessness. Could his heart take it? Could his
stomach?
</P>
<P>
   He had done well in space, happy as a puppy. ``Zero G and I feel
fine,'' he had crowed soon after entering orbit on Oct. 29, 1998,
reprising a line from his 1962 Mercury flight. He had used the line
again in a brief radio message after landing: ``One G and I feel
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   So where was he? Reporters wondered as the delay stretched to
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``John Glenn: A Memoir'' (Bantam, $27) Glenn
answers the question and confirms reporters' suspicions: He was
barfing his guts out.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts who spend several days in space lose fluids as their
bodies adapt to weightlessness. When they return to earth, the lack
of fluids can make them sick. So they gulp down pints of salty
fluids just before re-entry. The salt is supposed to help the body
retain the fluids.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn downed five 8-ounce pouches of a lemon-lime concoction he
thought he could tolerate. He was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it from the orbiter to the crew transport vehicle with
the rest of the crew, got unsuited, and then the stuff all came
up,'' he wrote with Nick Taylor, a New York writer.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly dehydrated, ``I was dizzy and shaky,'' he wrote. ``But
I knew one thing. I was going to walk out of there onto the runway
if it killed me.'' Eventually, Glenn climbed out and walked
unsteadily around Discovery with his crewmates.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's post-flight puke is perhaps the only event in the book
that hasn't been widely reported at one time or another. As a war
hero, test pilot, astronaut and politician, Glenn has lived a
highly publicized life.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn didn't write the book to bare his soul or correct the
public record, he said Monday from New York, where he was on a
national book tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing started about six years ago,'' he said, when
his two grandsons, Zachary and Daniel, were getting old enough to
be curious about their grandparents' youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started asking Annie and me questions about what it was
like in the Great Depression and World War II and Korea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn started carrying a tape recorder in his car, dictating any
thoughts about his past that might interest them. His musings
produced a pile of transcripts that added to bales of information
his family had collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the interest in the flight last year, as that was
building up, we decided maybe (writing a book) would be a good
thing to do,'' Glenn said. In addition to leaving a family history
for his grandchildren, he said, he thought the book might encourage
others to think about careers in public service.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn and his wife, Annie (the former Annie Castor), grew up in
New Concord, Ohio, just east of Columbus. He describes his
childhood as idyllic, with firm but doting parents and friends who
liked to roam the fields and woods. ``I never doubted even once
that I was loved,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   His father gave him his first taste of aviation when he bought
them both a ride in a WACO biplane, which was built in Troy, Ohio.
Glenn dreamed of a career in the clouds and earned his pilot's
license, but World War II set him on a path to the stars.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Navy, transferred to the Marine Corps and worked
his way into a fighter unit. He bonded with his Marine buddies, but
war was not idyllic. In his book, Glenn describes his reaction
after his first combat mission, which took his closest buddy's
life: ``I had never felt so helpless. The pent-up feelings of the
last few hours let loose, and I stood there and sobbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn survived World War II and Korea, and his later work as a
test pilot set the stage for his space career. His three-orbit
mission put Americans in orbit and laid the groundwork for future
space flights. He continued his government career with four terms
as a U.S. senator, and capped it last year with his return to
space.
</P>
<P>
   As much as flying has been a lifelong passion for Glenn _ he
still flies his own twin-engine airplane _ so has Annie. The
closest thing to a lovers' quarrel he relates in the book is her
response to his idea about flying in the space shuttle: ``What she
said, the first time I mentioned wanting to go, was `Over my dead
body.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio. E-mail: timothygaffney(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
