<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pokemon phenomenon gets explained in Time
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you've been out of touch with civilization for a few
months, Time ($3.50) offers a handy guide to bring you up to speed
on Pokemon, the hottest craze since Beanie Babies. Pokemania, with
cards, video games, toys and a new blockbuster movie, has become an
addiction for some kids.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools have banned the cards, but creator Satoshi Tajiri
tells Time that Pokemon is simply everything he did as a kid rolled
into one. As a boy, he left no stone unturned in his quest for
beetles. ``Every new insect was a wonderful mystery.'' Pokemon is a
way for children to collect insects and other creatures the way he
did, Tajiri says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Overheard: Talk ($3.50) has an intriguing article on ``10
Conversations That Changed the World'' and a few other meaty
features interspersed among the movie ads and accompanying story on
the upcoming Miramax film ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.'' Editor Tina
Brown probably would call the shameless promotion of the film
cross-pollination; others may describe it as the blurring of ads
and editorial.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations include Harry Truman encouraging Dean Acheson to
make a speech about the plight of Europe after World War II, a talk
that led to the Marshall Plan; John F. Kennedy's call to Coretta
Scott King offering his help after her husband was sent to jail;
and Alexander Sachs' chat with Franklin D. Roosevelt about a letter
from Albert Einstein warning of the possibility of nuclear chain
reactions using uranium that could create a powerful bomb.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The private Ryan: Vanity Fair ($3.95) is as solid as ever this
month, despite a fluffy cover story on actress Meg Ryan. (She may
appear to be the happy-go-lucky girl in ``Sleepless in Seattle''
and ``You've Got Mail,'' but she really wants to do grittier
roles.) David Margolick reports on the feud between New York Times
men Max Frankel and Abe Rosenthal, and Bryan Burrough spins an
intriguing tale about Miranda Grosvenor, a mysterious woman who
made famous men from Quincy Jones to Bob Dylan fall in love with
her after a few flirtatious telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reconsidering Rockwell: Everyone, it seems, is jumping on the
Norman Rockwell bandwagon after decades of scorn from some art
critics. The latest is New Yorker ($3) critic Peter Schjeldahl, who
reviews the exhibit at Atlanta's High Museum and proclaims Rockwell
``a visual storyteller of genius. More than that, he was a
story-maker, a bard. He didn't illustrate Middle America. He
invented Middle America.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
