<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL EXPRESSES OPTIMISM THAT ULSTER DEAL IS CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ George Mitchell's mission to rescue
the Northern Ireland peace settlement, staggered last week by the
refusal of the province's largest party to endorse a blueprint
hammered out over 10 weeks of grinding talks, recovered significant
forward motion Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, the former U.S. senator turned Ulster mediator, made
his first public comment since the extended effort began, saying,
``I believe that the parties now understand each other's concerns
and requirements far better than before and are committed to
resolving the current impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am increasingly confident that a way will be found to do
so,'' he added, indicating that he expected his review to end in
success this week.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of various parties, in a demonstration staged to
restore the lapsed momentum, followed Mitchell to the podium
outside the Stormont Castle buildings, scene of the talks, to voice
positive attitudes and a desire for accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the political ally of the
Irish Republican Army, said of Mitchell's statement: ``We share his
increasing confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, head of the Social Democratic and Labor Party, said,
``His confidence that we can find a way forward, to resolve this
impasse, is significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Reg Empey, a senior negotiator for the Ulster Unionists,
whose rejection of an emerging deal last week had plunged the
mission into crisis, said his party ``recognizes as the events over
the weekend have illustrated, the challenges and difficulties faced
by the leadership of Sinn Fein-IRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell had called a temporary halt to discussions on Friday
morning and asked the parties to devote the weekend to reflecting
on the consequences of failure. In fact, the weekend was devoted
almost entirely to bringing pressure on the Ulster Unionists and
their embattled leader, David Trimble, to obtain party backing for
the deal brokered between them and Sinn Fein by Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   When Trimble presented the outlines of that deal to Ulster
Unionist legislators Thursday night, not enough of them supported
it to enable him to take it to the full party for the needed
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse that has held up progress in putting the April 1998
peace accord in place centers on the Ulster Unionists' refusal to
allow members of Sinn Fein into the leadership of the new Northern
Ireland Assembly unless the IRA begins disarming. The '98 agreement
only obligated the parties to try to persuade affiliated
paramilitary groups to disarm by May 2000, and Sinn Fein has
contended that the Ulster Unionist demand amounts to adding a new
condition to an agreed-upon treaty.
</P>
<P>
   As the parties praised Mitchell Monday, they in turn were
followed by John de Chastelain, the retired Canadian general in
charge of the independent commission on guerrilla disarmament,
issued his own promising assessment of the possibilities for
achieving the dismantling of arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the Mitchell review, it has produced an
atmosphere for such a dialogue. That was unthinkable until now in
the polarized politics of Northern Ireland, where sectarian
violence has claimed more than 3,300 lives in the past three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The deal that has emerged from the Mitchell talks includes plans
for the naming of an IRA go-between to the de Chastelain commission
and the establishment of a verifiable disarmament timetable that
would begin at the end of January and conclude by the May deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of achieving a breakthrough in the deadlock over
disarmament that eluded negotiators in a series of marathon
sessions in the spring and summer has been replaced now by a lower
key arrangement to get to the same objective through a series of
interlocking reciprocal steps.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Mitchell laid out a choreographed sequence Monday,
with de Chastelain calling Monday afternoon on paramilitary groups
to appoint representatives to his commission and the parties
scheduled to make statements on Tuesday pledging to work together
to put the peace agreement into practice.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Wednesday, the IRA is to issue a public statement about
its commitment to the peace agreement, and on Thursday, Mitchell
will make his conclusions known, file his final report and return
to the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
