<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIEQUES (Washington) _ A Puerto Rican official says
President Clinton has agreed to submit to the voters of the island
of Vieques a proposed compromise designed to end a seven-month
standoff between the Navy and Puerto Rico over future bombing on
the island's military target range. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRAYER (Washington) _ In a case pitting Texans' love of
God and gridiron against the Constitution, the Supreme Court agrees
to decide if public-school students can conduct prayers before
football games without violating the constitutional separation of
church and state. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN-BLASTING (Washington) _ When a federal court ruled last
month that blasting off the tops of mountains to mine coal violated
the Clean Water Act, environmentalists thought they had triumphed.
But the West Virginia delegation in Congress is threatening to hold
up appropriations bills with provisions that would rewrite the law
to get around the court's ruling. By ANDREW BROMAN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS (Washington, D.C.) _ Bishop Joseph Fiorenza, president
of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, gives an address on
issues of concern to nation's Catholics. The approximately 300
bishops also debate a document introduced by Fiorenza opposing the
continuing sanctions against Iraq. By CECILE HOLMES.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE-HONORED (Washington) _ The National Center for State
Courts confers its annual award for excellence on Judith S. Kaye,
chief judge of the New York Court of Appeals and a name mentioned
occasionally as a possible U.S. Supreme Court nominee. The justice
says she has no interest in a seat on the nation's high court. By
DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ The girlfriend of defendant Shawn
Berry says in statements submitted as evidence in his murder trial
that her boyfriend had bouts of violence months before the slaying
of James Byrd Jr. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   BRACERO-CONTROVERSY (Undated) _ The federal initiative to stop
the abuses of the old ``bracero'' program that supplied cheap
immigrant labor for U.S. farms has largely failed. Debate has
flared over how to resolve problems with the program. By KIM COBB.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TURKEY(Ankara, Turkey)_ President Clinton savors a
series of foreign policy victories as he also presses Turkish
leaders on human rights and reconciliation with Greece. By NANCY
MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-REFUGEES (Amman, Jordan) _ While Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators open talks on a final peace accord, some
refugees from the former Palestine are quite happy in their new
homeland and do not plan to return, no matter what the accord would
eventually promise. By DEBORAH HORAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-SCANDAL (Quito, Ecuador) _ A multimillion-dollar
political-contribution scandal that has splashed into President
Jamal Mahaud's office has left many Ecuadorians, already buffeted
by the country's worst recession since the Great Depression,
wondering whether their chief executive is now capable of
governing. A look at how the unfolding scandal is worsening the
country's turmoil. By JOHN OTIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   With: ECUADOR-CURRENCY
</P>
