<HEADLINE>
WOOD RELIC FROM HARBOR COULD BE FROM `TEA PARTY' CHEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Plucked from the thick mud of Fort Point Channel in
October, an 18-inch-long piece of wood decorated with gold leaf and
painted with lacquer now rests in water in a Provincetown
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Treasure hunter Barry Clifford, who discovered the pirate ship
Whydah in 1983, believes this small artifact now in his possession
might be yet another startling find: The first relic retrieved in
more than two centuries from one of the 342 chests heaved overboard
during the Boston Tea Party. The defiant event occurred Dec. 16,
1773.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from the site where the Tea Party ships were tied up,''
Clifford said, referring to a long-gone wharf just north of today's
Moakley Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the object ``exactly'' resembles the
description of a chest retrieved from the Tea Party ships that is
in the possession of the Daughters of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   If tests support the object's link to Boston's landmark act of
colonial defiance, Tea Party Museum general manager Don Knuuttila
said the discovery would be enormously significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a wonderful find. Certainly the possibility
exists,'' Knuuttila said. ``Things in salt water and mud can be
preserved for very, very long periods of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Berkland, the Boston city archeologist, said the discovery
is interesting, but that Clifford must share the find with
professional archeologists to determine if the artifact is
connected to the Tea Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obligated to share the information and to get expert
advice on it _ whether it is contacting a conservator from the
Museum of Fine Arts to do wood analysis or to do an identification
of a Revolutionary piece,'' Berkland said.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford, whose 1989 request to excavate the channel was
rejected by the state as too broad, said he would present the
artifact to government archeologists for study.
</P>
<P>
   State Archeologist Brona Simon said the exact location of the
discovery, made by two divers last month, will be critical to
determining whether the object is from the Tea Party. And the
waters just off 470 Atlantic Ave., where Clifford said the find
occurred, have been dredged several times since the Revolutionary
War.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Griffin's Wharf _ where two of the three Tea Party ships
were tied up _ is now buried beneath tons of landfill under
Atlantic Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just so many considerations regarding the
possibility this is one of the tea chests _ tides, dredging of the
harbor, the reconditioning of the wharf area,'' Birkland said. ``It
depends on the context, the environment that the artifact was found
in. If it was undisturbed for a couple of hundred years in dense
silt and clay, then preservation could be quite, quite good.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifford has clashed with archeologists before. His excavation
of the Whydah off Wellfleet, which sank in 1717 and has yielded
more than 200,000 artifacts, has been criticized as being motivated
more by profit than history.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford, however, has countered that his private venture
brought to light the remnants of a misty past that otherwise would
have gone unnoticed if left to public archeology.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the expectation of renewed attacks, Clifford said
he is excited about the possibility of a Tea Party find. The
discovery, he added, reinforces his decade-old push to excavate
parts of Fort Point Channel and other sections of Boston Harbor,
which he describes as a ``treasure trove'' of cultural and historic
artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery was made last month, Clifford said, by two diving
acquaintances who worked by themselves but used information that
the treasure hunter gleaned during a sonar profile of the channel's
bottom in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The divers found the wood protruding from mud near a stone
foundation in 15-foot-deep water, Clifford said. ``The guys were
very excited,'' added Clifford, who is storing the artifact in cool
water in his observation lab in Provincetown.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-inch-long piece tapers from 4 inches to 1 inch wide, he
said. Hand-painted gold leaf adorns the beveled, top edge of the
wood, Clifford added. A dark lacquer covers the outside.
</P>
<P>
   These characteristics match the description of a tea chest held
by the DAR at its Washington headquarters, Clifford said. That
chest reportedly washed ashore in Dorchester after the Tea Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``These weren't cranberry crates. They were highly decorated.
They were painted in gold leaf, and they were lined with either tin
or lead. What's going to happen? They're going to sink,'' Clifford
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in deep mud, they'd stay perfectly preserved. And
that's what Fort Point Channel is _ deep mud. They may have floated
into the mud and eventually been covered up in silt.''
</P>
<P>
   Knuuttila, of the Tea Party Museum, said that 18-inch-long
gilded chests were stored under the captains' quarters of the Tea
Party ships. Historians do not believe the rebellious Bostonians,
disguised as Indians and brandishing ``tomahawks,'' reached that
elite-bound cargo but settled instead for hacking nondescript
crates in the main hold.
</P>
<P>
   However, Knuuttila would not rule out the chance that the
decorative chests also were dispatched to the shallow bottom and
mud flats of then-South Cove during low tide on the night of Dec.
16, 1773.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a great find,'' Knuuttila said. ``This was the
first act of true defiance that the colonists got involved in. They
all could have been shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
