<SLUG> BC-NURSING-SENTENCING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-NURSE SENTENCED TO 360 YEARS IN PRISON FOR HOSPITAL DEATHS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Orville Lynn Majors will spend the rest of his life in
prison for the murders of six patients at a rural hospital in
Indiana where he had been a licensed practical nurse. Majors,
suspected of killing as many as 100 patients by lethal injection,
was sentenced Monday to six terms of 60 years each. He will not be
eligible for parole for at least 180 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At long last, may the souls of Mary Ann Alderson, Dorothea
Dixon, Luella Hopkins, Margaret Hornick, Freddie Dale Wilson, Derek
Maxwell and Cecil Smith rest in peace,'' said Judge Ernest E.
Yelton, naming the seven patients for whose deaths Majors was
prosecuted. The jury was unable to decide whether Majors was guilty
of killing Smith, but convicted him on Oct. 17 of killing the other
six.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual string of deaths was noticed in 1993, soon after
Majors was hired as a nurse at Vermillion County Hospital in
Clinton, 90 miles west of Indianapolis. Majors was fired in 1995,
but not charged until 1997. Investigators who reviewed patient
records said that as many as 100 patients had died suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   In more than five weeks of testimony, prosecutors presented
little direct evidence that Majors killed the patients, only vials
of potassium chloride and syringes found at a house where he once
lived. Prosecutors, who relied on testimony that Majors was often
alone with the patients soon before they died, said that the deaths
were consistent with potassium injections, which stop the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were not allowed to present testimony about the
larger number of deaths, because Yelton said it would confuse the
jury and prolong the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not seek the death penalty because of the higher
cost of prosecuting a death penalty case.
</P>
<P>
   After neither the prosecutors nor defense attorneys made a
sentencing recommendation, the judge lectured Majors, calling his
crimes ``a paragon of evil at its most wicked.''
</P>
<P>
   Majors, 38, of Linton, Ind., did not react to the verdicts, but
looked down. His family has said that he was made a scapegoat for
shoddy medical practices at the hospital, and was demonized because
he is bisexual.
</P>
<P>
   Families of the victims testified Monday to their loss, and then
cried as the judge sentenced Majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Majors, if you don't want the fruit of sin, then stay out
of the devil's orchard,'' said Derek Maxwell's wife, Kathryn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
