<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0692 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-`DUTCH'-REAGAN-TEX     11-15 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`DUTCH'-REAGAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FACE BEHIND THE FICTION IN `DUTCH'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ As ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' makes clear,
this man is an enigma.
</P>
<P>
   He's smart, but a bit shifty; quick-witted, but perhaps not as
intellectually deep as he'd like you to believe. Certainly an
actor, someone who measures each word for effect as well as
meaning. And when the going gets tough and the questions get
tougher, he's a master at answers that sound good but say little.
</P>
<P>
   No, we're not describing Ronald Reagan, but Edmund Morris, the
author of ``Dutch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected controversy,'' the 59-year-old Morris said in his
room in Dallas' tony Adolphus Hotel, in the middle of a monthlong
national promotional tour. ``I expected the method by which I wrote
this book to create heated discussion. But I offer no apology.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those, especially critics, who say Morris owes an
apology. Fourteen years after he accepted a $3 million advance from
Random House to write a definitive Reagan biography, and after the
president allowed him unprecedented access to the White House
during the final years of his administration, Morris shocked the
literary world in October by turning out a 750-page tome in which
he inserted himself as a fictional character. Make-believe has
never been considered an element in political biographies,
especially from an author who won the Pulitzer Prize in 1980 for
his study of the early career of Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Reagan was so complex, so baffling. I thought it was
impossible he could be so simple in one sense, and yet also one of
the most important presidents in recent memory,'' Morris said. ``I
could not achieve any writing rhythm, any sense of who he was
besides the obvious, until I tried this different technique.''
</P>
<P>
   The nattily dressed, bearded native of Kenya who speaks with an
ingrained British accent exhibits a Reagan-like ability to tidy up
past unpleasantness when he discusses ``the epiphany'' that led him
to the unexpected format for ``Dutch'' _ named after Reagan's
college nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened on the campus of Eureka College'' in Illinois,
Morris said, carefully considering each word. ``Like many
biographers trying to get at their subjects, I went back to
(Reagan's) origins. This was in the fall of '92, and I wanted to be
where he had gone to college. I stepped on an acorn. In the moment
of crunching that acorn beneath my shoe, I suddenly felt an empathy
with the young Dutch, who must have stepped on acorns in the same
place at an earlier time.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris then decided to insert himself in Reagan's life as a
fictional college classmate named Edmund Morris, who was once saved
from drowning by lifeguard Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   His new approach, Morris said, put him in a writing groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``What came out of my pen after that was real prose, rather than
the sterile stuff I'd been writing for more than two years
before,'' he said. ``I felt liberated by my new writing device.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics and readers have carped about not being certain what in
``Dutch'' is real and what isn't. Morris suggests paying attention
to footnotes, although he admits that he isn't disappointed if some
people never figure out that narrator Edmund Morris is fictional.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I had the hopeful, romantic notion readers would
really believe they had a biography of Reagan written by an
87-year-old contemporary,'' Morris said. ``I believe the fuss comes
from critics who had rigid expectations. Real readers, the ones who
bought and actually read the book, are overwhelmingly supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of ``Dutch'' seem to validate the approach. The book
debuted on every bestseller list and has remained in the top 10 of
most of them for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But reviews have been caustic. Several critics have suggested
Morris' ego is to blame, that, after winning a Pulitzer and being
acclaimed for earlier work, he wanted to be as much a celebrity as
the former president.
</P>
<P>
   Morris seems almost Reagan-like in his denial. He remains
good-natured and does not accuse anyone of malice.
</P>
<P>
   ``All writing is difficult,'' Morris said, leaning back in his
chair and smiling. ``I had the pressure any writer feels _ how to
write this book, from what POV (point of view), how to begin, how
to end. So the book is, really, a plain narrative, not a political
study, per se, but a life story.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is eager to explain how much time he spent with President
Reagan. In addition to regular half-hour Oval Office interviews,
author and subject even convened for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man had dinner at my home,'' Morris said. ``The next day,
I met him in the Oval Office, and it was obvious our dinner
together the night before had completely disappeared from his
memory. It wasn't Alzheimer's. It was the way he really was at
center. He never, ever, lived in the past, even though he often
invoked the past in his stories and speeches. What interested
Ronald Reagan was always the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The anecdote was meant to illustrate just how difficult it was
for Morris to capture the essence of Reagan, especially in
comparison to Theodore Roosevelt, his next project. It is a second
biography, this covering TR's life from 1901 through 1908. As a
subject, Morris said, Roosevelt won't require the tricks he used in
``Dutch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``TR is a biographer's dream,'' he said. ``He doesn't need a
fictional narrator, since there was so much of him. Reagan, the
actor, constantly needed an audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Morris said he has treated Reagan fairly. Reagan ``was a
huge, dominant figure,'' he said. ``I believe I have done him full
justice for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris said that acclaimed fellow writers such as David
McCullough and Bill Styron have been supportive. He has heard,
however, that Nancy Reagan was ``devastated'' by the book, which
includes fanciful projections of Reagan's love affairs, limited
parenting skills and intense interest in cultivating wealthy
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me. You can't write a biography if you're
worried about hurting people,'' Morris said in one of his few
direct answers.
</P>
<P>
   But what of the former president himself? If Ronald Reagan could
miraculously emerge from the fog of Alzheimer's, how would he react
to ``Dutch?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would not have been interested in the book, no matter what
I wrote in it,'' Morris said. ``Reagan was not really interested in
himself. The only things he liked to look at were political
cartoons of himself. He lacked that kind of vanity. He'd flip
through ``Dutch'' for a moment and put it aside, forgetting
instantly he had looked at it at all.'' .MDUL/.MDNM/ (Jeff Guinn is
books editor of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0693 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-`DOGMA'-COMMENTARY-TE     11-15 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`DOGMA'-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOGMA' PRAISED, REVILED _ HERE'S A CATHOLIC REVIEWER'S TAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, I attended Sunday Mass at a Catholic
Church other than the one I've been attending for the past 10
years. I've always considered my parish kind of mellow, with a
strong music ministry and affable priests who emphasize the
positive messages in the Gospel. But as soon as I walked into the
new church, I knew it would be even more contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   The church was set up in the round, rows of chairs with no
kneelers, with the altar at the center. The choir, which was part
of the circle, seemed to include whatever instruments the singers
could bring to the party: the requisite piano and guitars, but also
various horns and a cello. Most telling, though, was the Mass
itself: Two key prayers were omitted, and one of the two pre-Gospel
readings was dropped. Some of this was no doubt due to the time of
the Mass _ 6:30 p.m. _ but it was still, to me, unusually
user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered what Father Tom would have thought of this. Father
Tom was the pastor at the El Paso, Texas, parish where I grew up;
he was an old-school Irish priest who resisted the modernizing of
the Mass. Father Tom did not believe that lay people should serve
Communion, did not practice the sign of peace _ the pre-Communion
ritual in which Catholics turn to their neighbors, shake hands and
say ``Peace be with you'' _ and did not believe that music should
be part of the Mass, because he considered it a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Father Tom would not have liked Dogma, Kevin Smith's new movie
that's both a satire of the Roman Catholic Church and a plea for a
return to simple faith. Some groups call the movie blasphemous and
anti-Catholic, but its bigger sin is that it's a bit lazy _ Smith,
a gifted and funny writer, is capable of examining the movie's
themes without taking so many cheap shots. But Dogma's foes are a
little lazy, too, in not taking note of its positive elements; his
movie doesn't take a casual approach to faith.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, those interested in how theology is filtered through
pop culture should be putting their energy into promoting films
that are pro-faith without being controversial. Admittedly, though,
there are too few of these in our pop life; too often, any TV show
or film that ``explores'' Catholicism does so by lampooning or
stereotyping Catholic characters _ something we SHOULD get worked
up about. ___
</P>
<P>
   Smith's movie is creating quite an uproar, and it gives me an
odd sense of nostalgia, because every few years while I was growing
up, we would be told at Mass not to see a movie _ Jesus Christ
Superstar, Godspell, The Exorcist, The Life of Brian, The Last
Temptation of Christ _ because of its questionable religious
stance.
</P>
<P>
   Dogma, no doubt, would have received similar condemnation. The
movie has many blasphemous moments; the one that sticks out most in
my mind is when a cardinal played by George Carlin uses a Communion
chalice for putting practice. Because of moments such as this, the
movie has stirred the wrath of activist groups, who contend that
the movie is anti-Catholic. But although I think the movie is
flawed, I believe that Smith meant well; the movie's end message,
however muddled, is pro-faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make a devout flick, you know?'' Smith told The
Philadelphia Inquirer recently. ``I never thought it was
controversial. I just thought it was ... two hours of preachy Jesus
(stuff). Christ knew the value of telling a good story to get his
points across. This film is not blasphemy. We treat God very
devoutly. I believe in God. I don't want to (tick) him off.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell if Smith is being naive or shrewd, but my
money's on naive: The movie was a controversy waiting to happen.
Its most vocal foe has been The Catholic League for Religious and
Civil Rights, which speaks out against defamation of Catholicism.
The league based its opposition to the movie on an early draft of
the script; although Smith points out that league members haven't
seen the movie, many of the gags they objected to made it to the
screen intact. And league officials, while acknowledging that they
haven't seen the film, defend their position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in this particular case, their main characters are
apparent, their roles are apparent and most of the dialogue is
apparent,'' Patrick Scully, director of communications for the
Catholic League, told the San Jose Mercury News. ``You don't have
to see the movie to get that. We saw the script.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Smith's movie _ and the other aforementioned
films, as well as 1994's Priest and the short-lived 1997-98 TV
series Nothing Sacred _ at least makes you think about faith.
Rather than reject these films, I find that they speak to my
Catholicism, because they present Catholics who are much like me _
human, flawed, even troubled. They may go to extremes in doing so,
but they do it in the spirit of challenge _ and faith that can't
withstand challenge is diluted faith. ___
</P>
<P>
   I started thinking this way around the first time I saw Jesus
Christ Superstar. A good Catholic boy (better than I am now,
anyway) when I was in junior high, I avoided seeing the movie for
years because my parish told me not to go. It wasn't till about
three years after its release when, under the influence of an
effusively persuasive friend, I caught it at a midnight movie (on
Good Friday, no less). I was surprised at how moved I was _
remember, I was a teen-ager _ and how much the movie helped me get
a grasp on the story of the Lord's passion. It wasn't till I was an
adult that I realized why the movie upset church groups; among
other things, it portrays Christ as a didactic, self-pitying
whiner. No wonder a teen-age boy could relate.
</P>
<P>
   Often, though, an outcry against a movie like Dogma will
backfire, arousing curiosity in audiences who would otherwise be
disinterested. The best example of this is 1988's The Last
Temptation of Christ, which was lambasted for its infamous
depiction of a crucified Christ imagining what domestic life with
Mary Magdalene would be like. The movie is actually thoughtful _ to
the point of ponderousness _ in the way it addresses Christ's
humanity, and it unfolds in a self-serious 2 3/4 hours; if its foes
didn't want it seen, they should have ignored it _ or handed out
leaflets saying ``Warning: This is really slow.'' (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 2035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0694 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-`DOGMA'-COMMENTARY(2n     11-15 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`DOGMA'-COMMENTARY(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
 
``xxx really slow.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Dogma, Last Temptation was made by a Catholic-raised
director _ Martin Scorsese, whose very Catholic obsessions with sin
and redemption have fueled virtually all of his films. Scorsese has
always been better addressing these topics in a secular way (Taxi
Driver, Raging Bull) than in a spiritual one (Kundun); he's
actually at his most sacred when he's profane. But at least
Scorsese, and Smith, come by their Catholic obsessions honestly.
They're trying to deal with their own doubts and fears, not just
using Catholicism as an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   And cinematically, we are easy targets; the Catholic Church,
with its belief in resurrection, miracles, saints, rituals and
mystery, is ready-made for drama. Our struggles to attain
spirituality in a material world, and our renowned guilt when we
fail to attain that spirituality, are perfect fodder for conflict.
(Believe me, as a church-going Catholic who writes about movies for
a living, and who enjoys many despite their moral shortcomings, I'm
conflicted quite often). We're not unique in this _ people of all
faiths, and nonbelievers as well, have their inner dramas _ but the
combination of mysticism and frailty, coupled with many filmmakers'
own Catholic backgrounds, makes us popular movie subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, we're often subject to carelessness and
cavalier attitudes in how we're portrayed, often in ways that would
inspire outrage if they were aimed at other religious groups.
Imagine what would happen if another denomination was accused of
murder or conspiratorial cover-ups, as the Catholic Church was in
the anachronism-laced Godfather Part III and in this year's
Stigmata (the Catholic League also condemned Stigmata, but not as
vocally as it has Dogma). ___
</P>
<P>
   What's truly offensive, though, isn't movies like Dogma; it's
movies that employ Catholic characters simply for convenience's
sake, without any clue as to what we're all about. The most recent
example of this is The Bachelor, in which James Cromwell plays a
Catholic priest who blithely follows Chris O'Donnell's character,
Jimmie, around San Francisco as Jimmie proposes to more than a
half-dozen women because he stands to win $100 million if he gets
married within 27 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that this marriage is more likely a job for a justice
of the peace; Cromwell is here to act Irish and talk about true
love (he's a widower who turned to the priesthood after his wife's
death). For all his wisdom about true love, he doesn't appear to
have an inkling that Jimmie's marriage plans are a mockery of a
sacrament _ not only does Jimmie jump from woman to woman, he's
also planning to stay married only 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bachelor is merely misguided, as is the just-released The
Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc, which portrays the
15th-century warrior saint as a histrionic, conflicted diva
(several scenes depict Joan wrestling with her ``Conscience,''
portrayed by Dustin Hoffman as a grim hooded figure, although The
Catholic Encyclopedia says that the saint never displayed such
self-doubt). On a purely secular level, both movies are pretty
awful, but they don't sink to the anti-Catholic depths of an
equally awful film, the summer comedy Detroit Rock City.
</P>
<P>
   DRC disappeared from theaters so quickly, it's almost not worth
criticizing, but it may be the most anti-Catholic movie of the past
couple of years. The movie, set in 1978, is about four Cleveland
teens who'll do anything to get tickets to a Kiss concert in
Detroit. Lin Shayes (There's Something About Mary) plays the mother
of one of the teens, an alcoholic harridan who's rabidly against
Kiss' ``devil music'' (funny, I don't remember being told not to
listen to Kiss in '78, but then the group didn't interest me much
at the time). Sam Huntington plays her son, whose rebellion against
his protesting mom includes having sex _ in a confessional. Now
there's a desecration of something sacred to Catholics, and all for
a cheap, unfunny gag that has nothing to do with provoking thought.
___
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Dogma is benign; its most offensive element, to me,
is the suggestion that Catholics have become a bunch of bored
automatons who show up at church every Sunday because they have to.
``It's called the Celebration of the Mass,'' Smith said during an
interview with the ZUG comedy Web site, ``but it's no party. No
one's having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is exaggerating the point, but although a Catholic study
released last week reported that many young-adult Catholics are
slipping away from the church, Smith ignores the church's increased
emphasis on compassion and activism. And the size of the crowds I
encounter every Sunday at my church, a large Fort Worth parish with
several weekend Masses, indicates that many Catholics of all ages
are still very involved in the Mass and the church. Maybe he's
going to the wrong Masses at the wrong church.
</P>
<P>
   Why this boredom has led Smith to include Saturday Night
Live-level blasphemous gags to address crises of faith could be
considered a mystery, but then so could the Catholic League's
comparative silence on movies that are clearly pro-faith, without
the sophomoric sacrilege. In the two years and change that I've
been reviewing movies, we've had Contact, in which Jodie Foster's
lack of faith is shaken by a message from space; Ponette and Wide
Awake, about children praying passionately to God for reassurance
about dead relatives; and The Apostle, with Robert Duvall as a
fallen preacher who finds his way back into the fold. You might
know about the controversy over Dogma, but are you aware that it
opened on the same weekend that NBC showed a TV movie called Mary,
Mother of Jesus? It received much less publicity, despite advance
reports that it was a reverent portrayal.
</P>
<P>
   The struggles over faith have enough drama; it's not necessary
to tart them up with easy gags. But perhaps Smith is trying to get
the young audience he earned with the superior but secular (and
more vulgar) Clerks and Chasing Amy to examine their own beliefs.
If that's the case, he should be commended, not condemned. But I
can't escape the sense that more people are going to enjoy Dogma
for its secular humor and its cheap shots than for anything Smith
really has to say about religion. Whether he's trying to bring
Catholics back to the fold or trying to draw them out of the flock,
it's doubtful he'll succeed in either case. His movie will probably
be a success, but he'll still be preaching to the converted.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot reviews movies for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
