<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: GERMANY, FRANCE, RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (xx) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: U.N. MISSION ON WAY
</P>
<P>
   A stalled human rights mission to East Timor, created to assess
the abuses committed in September by pro-Indonesian militias, was
finally approved by the United Nations and sent on its way by the
Economic and Social Council. Rights groups and diplomats have
criticized the two-month delay, saying evidence will have
disappeared. Eleven countries, mostly from the Middle East and
Asia, voted against sending an investigating team. Russia also
voted no.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: 4 EX-AIDES ON TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   As hundreds of paramilitary troops guarded the building, four
senior officials from the deposed government of Nawaz Sharif
appeared in a Karachi anti-terrorism court accused of kidnapping,
conspiracy to murder and attempted hijacking. The accused, Shahid
Khaqan Abbasi, Ghaus Ali Shah, Rana Maqbool and Aminullah Chaudhry,
said they were not guilty of a plot against Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf,
who took over in a coup.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH KOREA, U.S.: BERLIN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   North Korean and American officials met in Berlin to resume a
new round of talks on relations. The talks follow an announcement
by Washington that it was easing longstanding economic sanctions in
exchange for North Korea's pledge to freeze long-range missile
tests.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: BISHOPS' PINOCHET PLEA
</P>
<P>
   In their first public pronouncement since Gen. Augusto Pinochet
was arrested in London last year, the bishops of the Chilean
Catholic Church called on Britain to release the former dictator on
humanitarian grounds. Pinochet, who is fighting extradition to
Spain on torture and other rights charges, has suffered minor
strokes in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: PLUTONIUM PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   In face of protests from Mohawk Indians and mayors of Canadian
border cities, the U.S. Department of Energy has decided to back
away from shipping to Canada as much as 33 tons of plutonium from
old nuclear weapons for use in commercial reactors to produce
electricity. The project had been seen as a contribution to
disarmament by Prime Minister Jean Chretien. After opposition grew,
U.S. officials decided to destroy the plutonium at home.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MAYORAL CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, from the state of Tabasco, won
overwhelmingly in primary elections to pick the candidate for mayor
of Mexico City from the left-of-center Party of the Democratic
Revolution, which has governed the city since 1997. But Lopez
Obrador faces questions over legal residency requirements.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: U.N. REPORT ON AID
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the Security Council, Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said 12 million tons of food had been imported by Iraq in
three years under the program that allows monitored oil sales to
pay for urgent civilian needs. Annan also said he would like to see
the government of Saddam Hussein do more to improve basic health
care with the money now available.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: BELARUS PACT NEAR
</P>
<P>
   Russia and Belarus will sign a treaty of union, combining some
political and economic functions, at a Nov. 26 ceremony, the
foreign ministry said. The treaty is part of long-running
discussions over merging the two nations into a single state, a
goal believed to be years away.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: DEBT RELIEF SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Russia wants the London Club of creditors to write off $12
billion of the $32 billion in Soviet-era debt still owed to foreign
commercial banks, Finance Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said. He said
creditors want the remaining debt converted into Eurobonds or
another secure instrument, a demand Russia may grant if other
issues are resolved at talks beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: BEEF SUIT STARTED
</P>
<P>
   Britain formally asked Brussels to begin legal action against
France, which has defied the European Union and refused to end its
ban on British beef over fears that it is tainted with mad cow
disease. But Prime Minister Tony Blair said he did not want to
embark on a ``ludicrous sort of tit-for-tat trade war'' with
France.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: TOLL RISES
</P>
<P>
   The death toll from weekend floods in southwest France has
reached 27, and rescuers said people were still missing. Most
affected by the overflowing rivers were small towns and villages in
the valley around Carcassonne.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: SCIENTOLOGISTS ON TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   Five French members of the Church of Scientology, denounced in
France as an unwelcome sect, were found guilty in Marseille of
fraud and attempted fraud, with one sentenced to six months in jail
and a $16,000 fine. The court accused them of extortion for
``purification treatments'' and vitamin cures.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: CRAXI CAN RETURN
</P>
<P>
   A judge ruled that former Prime Minister Bettino Craxi, a
fugitive in Tunisia after being convicted in two corruption cases,
could be put under ``hospital arrest'' in Milan. Friends of the
former Socialist leader, 65, who suffers from heart trouble, want
him to have treatment in Italy, but the question of whether he
would have to serve his sentences has not been resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
