<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWTH-TECH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA ENGINEERS EVOLVE WITH HIGH-TECH INDUSTRIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Gone are the days when the United States had a
clearly defined enemy, and as a result, jobs for aerospace
engineers are no longer as plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Cold War brought with it an unprecedented scaling
back of the military-industrial complex, and no region of the
nation felt its effects more than Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   But the disappearance of aerospace jobs in the suburban San
Fernando Valley and Ventura County areas around Los Angeles, rather
than destroying the economy, has effected a transition in the focus
of the region's employment base.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers who once designed launch vehicles and guidance systems
now are creating telecommunications switches and fiber optic
routers. So while the '80s and '90s saw the development of the
Silicon Valley in Northern California's Santa Clara County, it also
saw the parallel development of a technological hardware industry
in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Noam Lotan, chief executive officer of Chatsworth's MRV
Communications, said his industry especially has benefited from the
services of people once employed in defense and aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've used subcontractors that have in the past been doing
lots of work for the aerospace industry,'' Lotan said. ``The
mechanical tolerances are very, very small. It was very useful to
have this kind of infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Also important, especially to companies in the communications
equipment industry, was the presence of businesses experienced in
working with the military and defense contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of military-related technology has to do with
communications in general and wireless communications in
particular, Lotan said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los Angeles Economic
Development Corp., said military contractors have translated their
expertise into the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of military stuff would involve communication and
networking,'' Kyser said. ``Any time you're talking about
communication and networking (now), that would probably be
something that grew out of a military application.''
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace industry, closely connected to defense
contracting, also contributed to the region's technical base.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had some very definite centers of advanced research _ at
Lockheed, especially Skunk Works, Hughes Missile, Rocketdyne,''
Kyser said. ``As the downsizing occurred, I think a lot of the
people who maybe didn't want to move had some better ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 and 1994, Hughes Missile Systems laid off thousands of
workers and transferred thousands of others to Tucson, Ariz. Those
who opted to stay in California were left with few employment
options at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing a brain drain, state and local officials launched
efforts to encourage institutions such as the California Institute
of Technology and the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, both in Pasadena,
to increase their research.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurship was encouraged through economic development
efforts in a further attempt to prevent the loss of professional
people and to smooth the transition to a more consumer-focused
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the industry has begun to swing away from its military
focus, the technology sector has begun to grow into a major force
in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all came out of aerospace, but the idea is that you have
other applications for that technology,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of entrepreneurs who come to the area to study
at Southern California universities and an available pool of
engineers and skilled workers contributes to the industry's
strength, Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the new crops of educated techies generated by local
schools, and you've got prospects for further growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry clusters tend to develop where the talent congregates.
In the case of the technology industry, the engineers already were
in Thousand Oaks, Westlake Village, Chatsworth, Calabasas and
Camarillo. The budding technology companies simply followed.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
