<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL NOTEBOOK: Niners planning to release Phillips
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco 49ers coach Steve Mariucci said Monday that the
team will release troubled running back Lawrence Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who signed with San Francisco after being waived in
St. Louis and Miami because of off-the-field problems, was
suspended indefinitely from the team. Mariucci said the 49ers were
clarifying contractual issues with the NFL's Management Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we have not waived him yet is because of
contractual reasons,'' Mariucci said. ``There are some salary-cap
ramifications. We want to fully understand those.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who seemed to resurrect his career in NFL Europe this
spring, has been bothered by a sore hamstring this season. He lost
a starting job to former Eagles running back Charlie Garner.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Phillips missed playing time when he was hurt,
Mariucci said the team wouldn't negotiate an injury settlement
because the former Nebraska star practiced as late as Friday.
Mariucci also said Phillips skipped two days of medical treatment
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawrence had every intention of being the featured back
here,'' Mariucci said. ``But he was injured and fell behind the
others. I think right from the get-go that started to gnaw at
Lawrence. He was a spot player with us, but he became very
frustrated with his role on the team. I think he became very
disinterested and shut it down both mentally and physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips didn't travel with the team to New Orleans, where the
49ers lost to the Saints 24-6 Sunday. Mariucci said Phillips
participated in special-teams practice Friday, but refused to
participate in drills with the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Running backs coach Tom Rathman) asked him to take some reps
and Lawrence told him, `You don't put me in games anyway, so why
should I practice?''' Mariucci said. ``That's conduct detrimental
(to the team). I've never seen that before.''
</P>
<P>
   By cutting Phillips now, the Niners would take a $212,000 hit on
their salary cap. The team can suspend Phillips for four games _
the maximum allowed under the collective bargaining agreement _ and
then take less of a salary-cap blow.
</P>
<P>
   Smith `ready to go'
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys lost All-Pro offensive guard Larry Allen for at
least two weeks because of a sprained knee, but running back Emmitt
Smith might return for this week's game at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Smith broke his right hand in a loss at Minnesota two weekends
ago. In Sunday's 27-13 win over Green Bay, the Cowboys played
without Smith, quarterback Troy Aikman and receiver Michael Irvin
for the first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas rushed for 149 yards against the Packers, but substitute
Chris Warren lost two fumbles in 19 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try some different padding on (Smith's) hand,''
Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``It's his right hand and he
carries the ball with his left. If things go well in practice,
he'll probably play. He's feeling better and he's ready to go.
Whenever he can get out there, we want him in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Aikman, who suffered a concussion against the
Vikings and didn't play last week, is doubtful for Sunday's game.
Aikman underwent more medical tests Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds against him playing are very high,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ESPN reported that Irvin, who suffered a neck injury
Oct. 10, will announce his retirement later this week.
</P>
<P>
   49ers looking at `Hoss'
</P>
<P>
   With quarterbacks Jeff Garcia and Steve Stenstrom struggling,
the 49ers will try out Super Bowl XXV hero Jeff Hostetler. Mariucci
said he contacted Hostetler last week, and the former New York
Giants starter is expected to arrive in San Francisco today.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler, 38, hasn't played since 1997, though he was on the
Redskins' roster last year. He sat out this season after his
8-year-old son, Tyler, was partially paralyzed after an all-terrain
vehicle accident in the yard of the family's West Virginia home.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler was the Raiders' starter from 1993 until the team
signed free agent Jeff George after the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Stenstrom, making his first start after replacing former
Canadian League star Garcia, completed 18 of 32 passes for 157
yards with one interception against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stenstrom probably did as well as Hoss would do when you think
about it,'' 49ers general manager Bill Walsh said. ``He had some
dropped balls. He was chased around a little bit. He threw some
good balls. He handled himself pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers haven't scored an offensive touchdown since Oct. 17, a
streak that was prolonged when Stenstrom threw an interception on
the 49ers' final drive.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor hurting again
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville running back Fred Taylor is questionable for
Sunday's game against the Saints after aggravating a hamstring
injury in a 6-3 victory over the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Without Taylor in the backfield, the Jaguars had only 132 yards
total offense and managed just nine first downs _ both franchise
lows. Taylor, a former first-rounder from Florida, has finished
only three games this year. In those games, the team averaged 37
points. In the others, they've averaged only 16.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor originally strained his left hamstring in the second week
against Carolina, forcing him to miss the third game against the
Titans. He returned the following week against Pittsburgh and
aggravated the hamstring again, forcing him to miss games against
the Jets and Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
