<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS-2ND     11-15 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: a statement. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are elements of Monday's agreement that could do just that
_ if one is willing to wait long enough.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Barshefsky's negotiating team spent a considerable
amount of time defanging China's insistence over the summer that
foreigners could never invest in Chinese Internet service
providers. The United States insisted that the Internet had to be
dealt with like the rest of the telecommunications market _ open to
foreigners and Chinese alike. That is a remarkable concession in a
country that only a few years ago strictly controlled who could own
radios and that put speakers in every village, to blare propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an increasingly information-based economy it is difficult
to tell people to be economically creative and politically
suppressed,'' the national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said
Monday from Turkey, where he is traveling with Clinton. ``But it's
a long-term hypothesis.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as importantly, the Chinese gave away their ability to be
the sole judge of what foreign investors can do and what they
cannot. Once China is a member of the WTO, it must submit to the
group's dispute-settlement system. That means cases of Chinese
trade barriers will be sent to three-judge panels in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects that the Chinese leadership will roll over and do
whatever the courts command. But then again, neither do the
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there is hope but no assurance that trade
liberalization can lock in political liberalization. But there is a
far better bet that it may be able to lock in China's economic
liberalizations.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years the accord will throw open to
foreigners _ at least on paper _ markets that have long been out of
reach. Life insurance companies will have the right to sell their
policies anywhere in the country. Grain producers and computer
makers can distribute their goods themselves, without going through
state-owned firms. Five years from now foreign banks will be able
to open branches, doing business with ordinary Chinese in the
national currency, the yuan.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these businesses have long been protected by the Chinese
government. By throwing open the doors, after five years of
preparations, China's leaders are clearly betting that the arrival
of the foreigners will spur both efficiency and growth. It
demonstrates, experts say, that China has learned a lesson from the
experiences of Japan and South Korea: Over-protection of domestic
industries breeds fat, smug companies that are ripe for disaster
when hard times strike.
</P>
<P>
   It is a risky strategy for the Chinese, of course. Competition
can breed unemployment _ already a growing problem in China _ and
unemployment can breed political activism.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a risk for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a backlash against too much trade liberalization
too fast,'' said Jeffrey Garten, the former undersecretary of
commerce and one of the architects of Clinton's early forays into
commercial diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a backlash already in full swing in Europe, and parts of
Asia. If it hits particularly hard in China, Washington may be
reassessing the political benefits of Clinton's strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KILLER-LAWYER-COX     11-15 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-LAWYER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murderer joins bar as lawyer
 &HT;    By Wes Hills and Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Fury and sadness swept over Dayton a quarter
century ago when Derek Anthony Farmer, then 16, was arrested in the
murders of a long-time civil rights activist and a widely respected
police sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer was convicted of those murders and served 18 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Farmer, now 42, earned the opportunity to serve the
law rather be punished by it. He became the first convicted
murderer in Ohio history to be sworn in as a lawyer. He's expected
to practice law in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . I can never pay back, but I can pay forward and I can
make a contribution,'' Farmer said at a hearing that helped
determine whether he could practice law. It took support from
prominent area judges, particularly Chief U.S. District Judge
Walter Rice, for Farmer to become a lawyer after his convictions in
the March 1974 murders of Dayton civil rights activist W.S.
McIntosh and Dayton Police Sgt. William K. Mortimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``So confident am I of his character, ethics and sense of
responsibility, that I would truly trust him with my life and the
lives of my family members,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer's sister, Betty Blankenship, kept any judgment of
Farmer to herself Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've discussed this as a family and just decided that we're
going to have no comment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone believes Farmer deserves this chance. One of
those against it is Dayton Police Chief Ronald Lowe Sr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, it's a slap in the face to me personally, to
every law enforcement officer that's been shot in the line of
duty,'' Lowe said. ``I'm totally for rehabilitation, but there has
to be boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Another one against Farmer is Lee C. Falke, Montgomery County
prosecutor at the time of the murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's lowering the standards for the people we want in
the practice of law,'' Falke said. ``Attorneys already suffer an
image problem and certainly it adds to the problem. . . . I really
don't understand how it's possible that he got a license.''
</P>
<P>
   Falke said he ``knew Sumpter McIntosh and Sgt. Mortimer and I
could never quite forgive or forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer and his nephew, Calvin Jerome Farmer, then 18, held up
the Harry Potasky jewelry store on March 4, 1974, in downtown
Dayton and pistol whipped Harry Potasky, 81.
</P>
<P>
   When they ran from the store into the outstretched arms of
McIntosh, Derek Farmer complied with McIntosh's command to stop.
Calvin Farmer gunned him down.
</P>
<P>
   That same morning, Derek Farmer surrendered seconds before his
nephew fatally shot Mortimer, 43, as police closed in on a housing
project on the city's West side.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 18, 1975, Farmer was then convicted of aggravated murder
in McIntosh's slaying and of purposeful murder in the slaying of
Mortimer.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Farmer was convicted of a single count of murder and
sentenced to life in prison _ but served the then eight-year
minimum sentence before he was paroled in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County Common Pleas Judge Rodney M. Love, now
deceased, declined to send Derek Farmer to the electric chair and
sentenced him to life.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Farmer would spend nearly a decade longer behind bars than
the triggerman. While at the Southern Ohio Correctional Facility in
Lucasville, he earned his high school and college diplomas before
his release on Oct. 29, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 23, 1997, letter to the Tuscarawas County Bar
Association, Professor J. Dean Carro of the University of Akron
School of Law urged that Farmer be permitted to take the Ohio Bar
exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since Derek has been in law school, I have entrusted to
him the care of the most important people in my life _ my two
boys,'' Carro wrote. ``Derek routinely baby-sits for my children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the race of life, sometimes we judge people by where they
finish,'' Carro continued. ``Sometimes we should measure people
from where they started and where they finish. On that basis Derek
has achieved more than any person I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice continues to be one of Farmer's strongest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   After exchanging letters with Farmer for several years, Rice
recalled meeting him upon his release from prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed at the time with the fervor of his
determination to pay back our community for what had transpired,''
Rice wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer worked in Rice's court as an intern in the summers of
1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia J. Mengel, clerk for the Ohio Supreme Court and secretary
for its board of commissioners on character and fitness, said a
felony conviction is no automatic barrier to becoming an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Mengel said the board, as well as the Tuscarawas County Bar
Association, thoroughly reviewed Farmer's past as well as ``lots
and lots of evidence that demonstrate his positive social
contributions'' before recommending that he be permitted to take
the bar exam.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony before the Ohio Supreme Court's board of
commissioners on character and fitness, Farmer said he initially
thought of himself as the victim. But while incarcerated, he said,
he realized that the victims' families experienced the real agony.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer said he has turned down interviews with the media because
they would have incensed the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the hearing, Farmer said he could only hope that
he would be judged on his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I can never pay back but I can pay forward and I can
make a contribution and I hope (the victims' families) would judge
me by that, if they judge me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0706 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ATM-FEES-ART-NYT &LR;      11-15 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATM-FEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE INTENSIFIES OVER ATM SURCHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., N.Y., Iowa, Vt., Wyo., Ark., Miss.)  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:15 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA _ Lashawanda McCullom, a 30-year-old nurse, put her
credit union's cash card into a Bank of America automated teller
machine here, punched in her secret code and requested a
withdrawal. The machine spit out her card and flashed a message:
``Due to a recent vote by the Santa Monica City Council, the
convenience of this ATM is now available to Bank of America
cardholders only.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCullom, who expressed mild frustration at being denied her
cash, was caught in the cross-fire of a skirmish over ATM
surcharges that now seems to be breaking into a full-fledged war.
Suddenly, the fact that it costs an extra $1.50 or so to get money
out of a cash machine seems to have tapped into some deep well of
public resentment _ or at least politicians believe it has.
</P>
<P>
   This oceanside suburb of Los Angeles last month passed the
nation's first local ordinance banning banks from charging
noncustomers for using their ATMs, and Bank of America retaliated
by denying noncustomers use of its machines. San Francisco voters
approved a similar measure earlier this month, and now, legislators
in other cities and states are said to be looking at similar
ordinances. The New York City Council speaker, Peter Vallone, said
Monday that he planned to propose such a law, and the Los Angeles
City Council has instructed the city attorney to study the city's
authority to enact a ban.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Defense has also proposed a ban on such
surcharges on all military bases. Connecticut and Iowa already ban
such surcharges under pre-existing laws, and three other states _
Wyoming, Arkansas and Mississippi _ have price caps on the
surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers just find the surcharge sort of the fee that broke
the consumer's back, so to speak,'' said Richard Blumenthal, the
attorney general of Connecticut, which is now battling the banking
industry in court. ``Consumers see no reason for it. They regard it
almost as a personal insult. It has evoked an emotion that is quite
astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The banking industry, saying it has the right to charge for a
service, is fighting to squelch the uprising before it gathers more
steam. California's leading banks argued Monday in U.S. District
Court for an injunction preventing the Santa Monica and San
Francisco ordinances from being enforced.
</P>
<P>
   And on the day Santa Monica's ordinance took effect _ last
Thursday _ Bank of America and Wells Fargo Bank, the state's two
largest banks by far, began prohibiting noncustomers from using
ATMs, which is why Ms. McCullom could not get her money on Friday.
The banks say they will do the same in San Francisco when that
ordinance takes effect, probably next month.
</P>
<P>
   How widespread the bans will become remains to be seen. Santa
Monica and San Francisco are both unusually liberal cities.
Consumer groups have failed to get any state legislature to enact
such a ban, and Alfonse D'Amato, when he was a U.S. senator from
New York, never got very far with his attempt to legislate a
nationwide prohibition. Rep. Bernard Sanders, an independent from
Vermont, this month re-introduced legislation banning surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say it is unreasonable to charge consumers for access to
their own money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks are basically holding our money hostage,'' said Jon
Golinger of the California Public Interest Group. The U.S. Public
Interest Research Group found that 93 percent of banks surveyed
impose such a surcharge, up from 71 percent in 1998 and 15 percent
in 1996. Nationally, such surcharges appear to generate about $2
billion to $3 billion a year or more for operators of the ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say that in many cases consumers are being charged
twice for each withdrawal. If a Wells Fargo customer, for instance,
takes money out of a Bank of America machine, Wells Fargo charges
that customer $2 for using a ``foreign'' ATM, about 50 cents of
which goes to reimburse Bank of America. But Bank of America itself
charges $1.50 for use of its machine by a noncustomer, bringing the
total fee for retrieving as little as $20 of one's own money to
$3.50.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Monica and San Francisco ordinances, as well as the
regulation in Connecticut, bar only the $1.50 surcharge levied by
the ATM owner, not the fees imposed by a bank on its own customers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the frustration over the surcharges stems from what is a
general proliferation in banking fees in an era of deregulation,
and the fact that ATM use was once free. ``People see the way banks
are trying to charge for everything under the sun,'' said Walter
McCaffrey, a New York City councilman from Queens who is helping
draft the proposed legislation there. ``The original position was
that ATMs were not a profit center.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks say it is their right to charge for services. If consumers
don't want to pay they can use their own bank's ATMs. Without
surcharges, they said, there would be fewer ATMs and less
convenience for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to find too many people who are willing to
give the service for free,'' said Terry Zink, senior vice president
in charge of ATMs for Wells Fargo. ``The biggest issue is whether
or not consumers have the right to pay for services they want.''
</P>
<P>
   What is perhaps most unusual about this battle is that only a
few years ago, the forces were on the opposite sides. The banks
themselves, through two major networks that link ATM machines,
prohibited the surcharges. And legislators in 15 states enacted
laws overriding the prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Banks initially shunned fees to encourage people to use the
machines. They viewed ATMs not as money makers but as cost-savers,
a way to cut down on the number of tellers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
