<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR NOTEBOOK: Grandstand tickets remain for NAPA 500
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOMESTEAD, Fla. _ Atlanta Motor Speedway officials said Monday
that about 14,500 reserved grandstand tickets are available for
Sunday's NAPA 500.
</P>
<P>
   With a weekend forecast of partly sunny skies and temperatures
in the mid-60's, AMS president Ed Clark said he expects a flurry of
last-minute ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the NAPA 500 has been a sellout, and we expect a
tremendous demand for tickets this week due to the very favorable
event-week forecast,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   For tickets, call AMS at 770-946-4211 or Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering Allison
</P>
<P>
   The memory of Davey Allison, the Winston Cup driver who was
killed in a 1993 helicopter crash, played a prominent role in both
victory celebrations following Sunday's Pennzoil 400.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie sensation Tony Stewart took the checkered flag for his
third victory of the year, breaking Allison's 1987 record for
victories in a season by first-year drivers, with two.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett also wrapped up the Winston Cup championship, the
first one for team owner Robert Yates. Yates started his team in
'87 with Allison as the driver. Allison fell just short of winning
a championship for Yates in '92 and was a top contender for the
following season's title before perishing in the July crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that Davey Allison is a huge part of this,''
Jarrett said. ``He's the one that sat with Robert and started this
whole thing back in 1987. That is when Robert decided to buy the
team. The success that they have had, the organization that they
built from the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this would have ever happened if it wasn't for Davey,
and it's unfortunate that he was taken, not only from our sport,
but a lot of people's lives because of the person he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that he's had a huge hand in
this, along with Ernie Irvan (another former Yates driver) and what
he was able to do and accomplish and keep things going at Robert
Yates Racing. Davey Allison was a very special person, and we know
that's someone we've had on our side this whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates, who maintained his composure throughout the post-race
celebration, finally broke down when asked about Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you're going to make me cry,'' Yates said softly. ``We
knew Davey was watching over us.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Allison parallel: Jarrett, 42, is the second-oldest
Winston Cup champion. Bobby Allison, Davey's father, was 45 when he
won the title. The engine builder on Allison's trophy-winning team
was none other than Robert Yates.
</P>
<P>
   Extra laps
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nemechek and three members of his family were involved in a
single-car crash Sunday evening after arriving at Concord (N.C.)
Regional Airport. The only injured passenger was Nemechek's wife,
Andrea, who is expected to be released from the hospital today....
Nine Winston Cup drivers, including Jeff Gordon and Dale Earnhardt,
tested the 2000 Monte Carlo on Monday at Homestead-Miami Speedway.
``I think the car has got a lot of potential,'' Mike Skinner said.
``We're overdue for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
