<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0711 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BONDS-COLUMN-TWOTAKES     11-15 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONDS-COLUMN-TWOTAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS ADVOCATE GUN CONTROL IN MEMORY OF SON'S SUICIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a glorious Saturday morning in June of 1993, John Cleveland
Stevens got up early, showered and shaved, and then told his
parents that he was going to the guitar store. He walked out the
door carrying his guitar case, but he would never return. Later
that day, John drove to a nearby Park, just down the road from his
Fort Worth, Texas, home. It was around 4 p.m. when he put a
short-barreled shotgun in his mouth and committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   John Stevens was only 19.
</P>
<P>
   There was no news account of his death. A newspaper obituary a
few days later didn't mention how he died.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, Kenneth and Nancy Stevens, are sharing his story
six years later because they believe that their son would be alive
today if Texas had a waiting period to purchase firearms. They also
believe that Texas should not allow minors to purchase guns.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics released recently by the U.S. government show that
the rate of violent crime is dropping nationwide. But it is
difficult to celebrate such news after reading about the recent
deadly shootings in Honolulu and Seattle, which continue a pattern
of mass murders that have occurred in places such as Pearl, Miss.;
Paducah, Ky.; Springfield, Ore.; Littleton, Colo.; Atlanta; and
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Gun crimes, in fact, seem to be getting more commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   While America becomes a killing field, a circular debate about
gun control continues. The Brady Bill that imposed a national
waiting period expired in 1998, replaced by a system of instant
background checks that critics say is flawed because of
inconsistencies in reporting information in each state.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner for the
Republican presidential nomination, advocates enforcement of gun
laws already on the books, but does not believe there is a need for
new legislation. In 1995, he signed a bill allowing people to carry
concealed weapons with the provision that they first apply for a
permit.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation that might address the issue has either died or is
going nowhere on a state and national level. The larger question
now is whether society is willing to protect its citizens,
especially its children.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy and Kenneth always believed more needed to be done to
regulate the proliferation of firearms. But like most of us, every
time they read the headlines, they just shook their heads and
turned the page. Their son's death changed that. ___
</P>
<P>
   It is early October, shortly after 8:30 a.m., a warm day like
the Saturday John Stevens died, six years ago. Nancy Stevens sits
on a chair. Her husband, Kenneth, is on the living room sofa.
</P>
<P>
   They remember that when John headed to the guitar store, the
rest of the family _ including his brother and sister _ was
watching the movie ``American Graffiti.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a difficult time for John. He had just completed his
freshman year at Earlham College in Richmond, Va., but when he
returned home he was depressed. His relationship with the girl that
he hoped one day to marry was ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could tell he wasn't doing well,'' his mother said. ``He
wasn't eating.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was a freshman in high school, John began having mood
swings that were diagnosed as clinical depression. He also suffered
from attention deficit disorder. A psychologist prescribed Prozac,
which managed to keep John's condition under control.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he was depressed again. John stayed up late one night
writing a letter to his girlfriend. On the night before he died, he
began sorting through his possessions, keeping some, discarding
others.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his parents had no way of knowing how distraught he was
or what thoughts might be running through his head.
</P>
<P>
   When he didn't return from the guitar store by noon, however,
Nancy Stevens became uneasy. John's bass guitar was standing in a
corner of his bedroom against the wall, but she distinctly
remembered him taking the guitar case.
</P>
<P>
   She canvassed the neighborhood, looking for the family's
bright-blue minivan that her son was driving. When she didn't find
it, she decided to run a few errands and return home.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:30 p.m., the worried mom got into her husband's car and
drove to the park, just a quarter-mile away. That's where she saw
the minivan and instinctively knew that something was wrong. But
she was afraid to see for herself and quickly drove home to find
her husband.
</P>
<P>
   They returned to the park _ where a Texas Christian University
student had hanged himself a year earlier _ and headed for the
minivan.
</P>
<P>
   In a clearing, they saw John's guitar case and their hearts
began to race. They were running now, sensing that something
terrible had happened. Kenneth got to John first. He turned and
urged his wife to stay back.
</P>
<P>
   That was all that Nancy Stevens needed to know. ``I just started
crying,'' she said, tears spilling from her eyes now as they did
then. ``Oh, no. Oh, no,'' she said, sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   Her son was dead. ___
</P>
<P>
   John was an intense, blue-eyed boy who adored his brother,
James, and his little sister, Sara. He loved Russian literature and
played in the high school band and on the football team.
</P>
<P>
   He volunteered at the Fort Worth Museum of Science and History
and the Presbyterian Night Shelter. He was a member of the
Religious Society of Friends.
</P>
<P>
   No one except his immediate family knew that John suffered from
clinical depression. He did not have to provide this information
when he bought the shotgun. Even now, instant background checks are
often incomplete and fail to disclose data about mental
instability.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy and Kenneth know that some people will say that John
would've killed himself regardless of whether he had a gun. But
they believe the lack of stricter gun laws made it too easy for him
to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``For young people, in particular, who have a very impulsive
element to their suicide, having access to a means of suicide that
is quick and irrevocable, like a gun, is an unnecessary risk,''
said Dr. Kay Redfield Jamison, a professor of psychiatry at John
Hopkins School of Medicine in Baltimore, Md., and author of a book
detailing her own struggle with manic depression and suicide
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Vital Statistics Report, guns were
used in 17,566 suicides in 1997, the last year for which statistics
are available, compared with 13,522 homicides.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when John Stevens took his own life, six of his
schoolmates also died. Three were slain; three committed suicide.
All the incidents involved guns.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that these statistics show a decrease from the
beginning of the decade. Nonetheless, what Nancy and Kenneth find
distressing is that their 19-year-old son could not purchase
alcohol legally, but could walk in off the street and buy a gun.
(MORE)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
