r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN(2ndTak     11-15 0285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: xxx buy a gun. 
___
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six months after their son's death, Nancy and Kenneth learned
who had put the shotgun in his hands. In December 1993, a Christmas
catalog addressed to John Cleveland came in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   It was from Firearms Unlimited in southwest Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the guy up and told him to take John off his mailing
list,'' Kenneth said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stevenses believe that within 24 hours before his death,
their son withdrew $500 from his savings account, and spent about
$200 of it to purchase a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon of the day that their son shot himself, a store
manager from Bookstop, his favorite bookstore, called to offer John
the job he had applied for the day before.
</P>
<P>
   His parents believe the job offer would've been enough to give
him renewed hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much good stuff ahead for him,'' Nancy said,
``had he just been able to get through one afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   By sharing their story, Nancy and Kenneth Stevens hope to help
parents prevent similar tragedies. They want to stop the
manufacture and sale of automatic weapons. They want guns
registered, the way cars are. They want to keep guns out of the
hands of young people.
</P>
<P>
   They speak before groups such as the League of Women Voters and
they belong to Texans Against Gun Violence.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Stevens teaches constitutional history. He knows the
right to bear arms is guaranteed by the Second Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no freedom is absolute,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can reach her at gstaples(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
