<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONT-ROW-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOPRANOS' STAR WORKS ON IMAGE ; MIZRAHI'S ASSOCIATES FIND NEW
PROJECTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When some aspiring actresses envision their own
stardom, they think of time spent writing gushy notes to their good
friend Tom Ford, thanking him for all those feathered jeans and
python stilettos he keeps sending over, no bill enclosed.
</P>
<P>
   During the decade-plus she struggled to make it in show
business, Edie Falco was never one to harbor those fantasies.
Fashion simply wasn't something Ms. Falco, now the star of ``The
Sopranos,'' the HBO series, thought much about. For years she
happily made do with unfeathered jeans and discarded clothes from
the movies on which a friend, Eric Mendelsohn, assisted the costume
designers. Once, Mendelsohn recalled, he gave Ms. Falco items from
a film in which the lead character, named Dottie, just wore things
with dots. ``For a long time, Edie only wore dots,'' Mendelsohn
said. Now a director, he cast Ms. Falco in the title role of his
first feature, ``Judy Berlin,'' to be released in February.
</P>
<P>
   But this kind of ad hoc approach to dressing doesn't work once
you are finally famous, as Ms. Falco is learning. Shortly after a
television show declared her one of the worst-dressed guests at the
Emmys in September _ an event in which she won the best-actress
award for her portrayal of Carmela Soprano, the mob wife with
social aspirations _ HBO provided Ms. Falco with the services of a
stylist, Toni Fusco, and a $20,000 budget to help the actress
refurbish her image.
</P>
<P>
   From her apartment in Manhattan last week, Ms. Falco said she
was humiliated when she discovered from friends that panelists on
Melissa and Joan Rivers' post-Emmy show had found her seemingly
innocuous Pamela Dennis skirt and halter top so offensive. ``It's
actually a big deal for me to get dressed like a grown-up,'' she
explained. ``I thought I looked good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was embarrassed at how embarrassed I was,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Falco dealt with her shame by joking to all her ``Sopranos''
colleagues about her worst-dressed status, hoping she'd be the
first to tell them. (Everyone, as it turns out, already knew.) Ms.
Falco began asking a ``Sopranos'' costume designer for fashion
advice, and soon enough Ms. Fusco was called by the network's
talent-relations office to help the ``Sopranos'' star do some
shopping. (A spokeswoman for HBO said she couldn't comment on the
matter.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she looked beautiful at the Emmys,'' Ms. Fusco said.
``I felt so bad for her.''
</P>
<P>
   On their major shopping outing, Ms. Fusco took the actress to
DKNY (Ms. Falco's suggestion), Barneys New York, Bergdorf Goodman
and Manolo Blahnik (the stylist's choices). Ms. Falco bought a
pantsuit, a handkerchief skirt, some cashmere sweaters and a few
pairs of pumps. But bleeding HBO dry she is not. The actress' total
purchases came to about $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE AFTER MIZRAHI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Eisner, a former fashion editor, muse and stylist, has
strayed far from the world of dressing celebrities. Having worked
for Isaac Mizrahi overseeing ad campaigns, Ms. Eisner began
rethinking the merits of a career based on the vagaries of the
runway when the designer closed his business last year. ``I felt
that I was at a point where I was over the whole fashion world,''
Ms. Eisner said from her home in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   With the encouragement of her friend Bruce Weber, the
photographer, Ms. Eisner teamed up with a former Mizrahi colleague,
Roman Alonso, and a graphic designer, Lorraine Wild, to open an
art-book publishing house named Greybull Press in Los Angeles.
Forthcoming books include ``Height of Fashion,'' with images of
people at moments when they feel they've looked their best, as well
as a book on all things custom-made, photographed by Dewey Nicks.
</P>
<P>
   Greybull's first book, though, due in February, comes from Ms.
Eisner herself. Titled ``Rodeo Girl,'' it features pictures taken
from the world of rodeo queen pageants, an obsession of Ms.
Eisner's, who grew up in Cheyenne, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodeo Girl'' also attracted another member of the Mizrahi
circle, Douglas Keeve. Keeve, who directed the documentary
``Unzipped,'' about Mizrahi, was so intrigued by the subject of the
book that he's going to begin shooting a new documentary (with Ms.
Eisner) on rodeo pageants in Las Vegas later this month. The film
will be financed in part by Polo Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   Keeve, who has moved back to New York from Los Angeles, said he
was offered a chance to direct studio films after the success of
``Unzipped'' in 1995, but nothing panned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stuff I'd been dreaming about my whole life,'' he said.
``Rodeo Girl,'' though, is a project he's looking forward to. ``I
didn't make `Unzipped' for my fashion friends,'' he said. ``This is
similar. People will hear about this film and say `Who cares?' And
they'll see this film and say, `I care.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0717 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ATM-FEES-ART-2NDTAKE-     11-15 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATM-FEES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SANTA MONICA, Calif.: of tellers.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   But then some banks as well as some nonfinancial companies began
realizing that charging customers would make it economical to put
ATMs in remote locations and away from banks themselves. Moreover,
the prohibition on surcharges raised antitrust issues because it
made it difficult for nonbanks to be in the ATM business because
there would be no way to recover their costs. This led to the state
laws allowing the fees and to the decision in 1996 by two major
national ATM networks _ Visa's Plus and Mastercard International's
Cirrus _ to lift the prohibition on surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the number of ATMs has nearly doubled to 227,000 from
123,000 in 1997, according to the American Bankers Association.
Most of the new machines are not at banks and thrifts but at
supermarkets, malls, airports, amusement parks and other so-called
off-premise locations. Indeed, slightly more than half of all ATMs
are now off premise, according to Bank Network News, a
Chicago-based newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, about half of all new ATMs _ including most of the
off-premise ones _ are owned by companies other than banks, thrifts
or credit unions, according to Speer &AMP; Associates, an Atlanta
consulting firm. These companies include Electronic Data Systems,
the big computer services company, the Publix Supermarkets chain
and many smaller companies that have gone into business just to
provide ATMs. Many retailers own their own ATMs, but some merely
collect some fee from the ATMs that are stationed in their stores
but are owned by others.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco and Santa Monica laws allow these nonfinancial
institutions to levy the surcharges, under the theory that they do
not gain savings from having fewer tellers. The Connecticut rule,
however, bars surcharges on all machines. The New York ordinance
has not been drafted yet but could be similar to the California
ones.
</P>
<P>
   While consumer groups say that bank fees are well in excess of
what it costs for an ATM transaction, some bankers say they are
losing money on ATMs even with the surcharges. And they say
prohibiting surcharges will force closure of many ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the surcharge, there's no way a lot of off-premise
ATMs can be profitable,'' said Robert Litan, director of economic
studies at the Brookings Institution, who studied the matter for
the American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence on this question is mixed. Connecticut has only about
two-thirds of the number of ATMs per million people as the nation
as a whole, according to Bank Network News. But Iowa has almost as
many machines per capita as the nation as a whole and more than
some states that allow the surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   In their court case in San Francisco, Bank of America, Wells
Fargo and the California Bankers Association argue that local
ordinances are pre-empted by federal banking regulation. The Office
of the Comptroller of the Currency, a federal regulator, has
intervened in the case on the side of the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Banks have won decisions on these grounds in Iowa and
Connecticut, but the ban on surcharges in those states remains
while the decisions are being appealed. But a 1990 decision by the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which covers California and
other Western states, found that a federal law does allow some room
for states to regulate ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the surcharges say they favor the big banks under the
theory that consumers, to avoid the fees, will put their accounts
in banks that have the most machines. ``When a business can gain
customers by raising prices, that's not what competition is all
about,'' said Adam Radinsky, deputy city attorney for Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Some smaller banks and credit unions have pushed for free ATM
use or have banded together to offer free use to one another's
customers, to better compete with bigger banks. Still, many smaller
banks impose the surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Santa Monica, some people think the whole controversy is
overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Santa Monica is overstepping its rights trying to
impose business practices on the banks, and I think the banks are
being vindictive and hasty in trying to make a statement back to
the city of Santa Monica,'' said Katrina Osio, a 33-year-old
marketing director of an Internet company. ``I just think it's
childish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
