<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINA TO OPEN ITS ECONOMY UNDER LANDMARK TRADE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   United States and Chinese negotiators agreed to open China's
economy to foreign competitors and make the world's most populous
nation a full partner in international commerce. Under the deal,
Beijing would reduce tariffs on industrial and agricultural
products and lift many of the barriers in the way of American
companies. In exchange, the United States agreed to support China
for membership in the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Moore, the head of the World Trade Organization, cautioned
that several steps remained before China could become a
full-fledged member.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Chinese and China-related companies surged as
investors concluded that the trade agreement would help Chinese
companies more than hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   UPRISING WIDENS OVER ATM FEES
</P>
<P>
   After two California cities banned banks from charging
non-customers for using their automated teller machines, many other
cities are said to be considering similar bans. And the banking
industry is fighting to squelch the uprising before it gathers more
steam.
</P>
<P>
   TOYS `R' US PROFIT INCREASES 55 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us posted a 55 percent jump in third-quarter earnings
on strong sales of video games, Pokemon cards and other products,
easily beating Wall Street expectations. The company benefited from
popular products like the Sega Dreamcast computer system and from
the introduction of Pokemon game leagues in all of its stores.
Shares of Toys ``R'' Us rose $1.4375, to $17.9375.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DIP AHEAD OF FED DECISION
</P>
<P>
   Stocks closed little changed as investors waited for today's
Federal Reserve decision on interest rates. The Dow Jones
industrial average dropped 8.57 points, to 10,760.75. The Nasdaq
composite index declined 1.61 points, to 3,219.54. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell 1.67 points, to 1,394.39.
</P>
<P>
   COKE BOTTLER REASSURES INVESTORS
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises, Coca-Cola's largest bottler, told
investors and money managers in a rare conference call that its
decision to raise retail prices earlier this year should improve
the company's cash flow and profitability despite a drop in volume.
</P>
<P>
   GATES SAYS HE BACKS CONSUMERS
</P>
<P>
   At the Comdex technology conference, William H. Gates tried to
portray Microsoft as a company that wants to give consumers choices
in how they use computers and get on line. But most attendees were
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore told hundreds of Microsoft employees that
competition is fundamentally a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   RITE AID NAMES NEW CHAIRMAN
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid said that it had named Leonard Green its chairman in
hopes he could revive the company, which also said that KPMG
International had resigned as its auditor. Rite Aid is restating
results of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI GROUP TO BUY SANOFI BEAUTE
</P>
<P>
   In the latest step in the growing consolidation of the European
fashion and luxury-goods industries, Gucci Group said that it would
buy Sanofi Beaute for about $700 million in cash to gain control of
Yves Saint Laurent. The deal represents the first major step by
Gucci's chief executive, Domenico De Sole, to fulfill his ambition
of creating a luxury group of many brands that is large enough to
challenge the industry leader, LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS NAMES CHIEF EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Borders went outside the book industry for a chief executive,
appointing Greg Josefowicz, a food and drugstore executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
