<HEADLINE>
HOSTESSES RELY ON FAMILY HEIRLOOMS TO SERVE UP MEMORIES AT
THANKSGIVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Setting the holiday table is the best reason to take on the
chore of hosting the family's holiday feast.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing the stage is an exhilarating ritual, one that many
hostesses are loath to share. They think of it as an intimate act
of self-expression _ the gift of the meal surrounded by the setting
that says this moment is special.
</P>
<P>
   There are family members who have never been a part of this
ritual. They don't know where the tablecloths are stored, and
they've never seen the felt-lined chest that holds the family
silver. They will never experience the familial connection of
pulling Grandmother's gravy boat from the back of the cupboard and
washing the dust off by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers jealously guard their position as sole table designer,
and only when their daughters reach a double-digit age are they
allowed to help. Direction and vision belong to the hostess; girls
are allowed to assist, but their contributions are not sought. Sons
are rarely inducted into the silver-setting, centerpiece-arranging
routine, and that is a shame.
</P>
<P>
   There is a wonderful sense of continuity that comes from
preparing the same meal that Mother and Grandmother made. No matter
how antiquated the menu _ starch-heavy and bereft of fresh produce
_ there is a sense of history in using the same recipes and serving
the food in some of their hand-me-down dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Most members of the family think the holiday table appears as if
by magic.
</P>
<P>
   The process begins in the early hours when the house is quiet,
long before the guests arrive and when the children are still
asleep. For a moment, the cold turkey and empty pie pans are
abandoned in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The dining-room table is cleared of homework, bills and shopping
bags. It is wrenched apart with a terrible sticky, creaky-wood
groan. The leaves are wrestled into place, and the table is pushed
back together. At either end, the wood is dull and scratched,
showing the wear of family dinners. The center leaves have few
stories to tell; they are still shiny and slick. This visual tale
of old and of special occasion is the tableau, the stage, ready to
be dressed. ___
</P>
<P>
   When Renie Steves opens her cabinets to take out her holiday
table settings, she has multiple choices. The professional cooking
instructor has a weakness for stoneware and china, and her
cupboards are stacked with scores of patterns. But since this is
Thanksgiving she reaches for the 100-year-old cut glass. It
belonged to her father, a collection he compiled over many decades.
</P>
<P>
   Steves believes Thanksgiving is the perfect time to bring
memories and mementos to the table. She unpacks boxes and boxes of
the beautiful faceted glass. She has more-expensive crystal, she
has more-elaborate china, but the cut-glass pieces make her feel
connected. She begins to tell stories about her father and his
quest for yet another piece of glass.
</P>
<P>
   Glass becomes Steves' motif. She uses glass grapes to hold place
cards, and Baccarat crystal bone plates. She takes liberties with
her stemware. She can _ she is a wine writer, and she is not
intimidated at all about using small etched-glass tumblers for her
white wine and hollow-stem wine glasses for champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mixing casual with elegant is the best trick around,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Layers of cut-glass plates are piled on top of Royal Worcester
Livinia pattern china that rest on Fitz &AMP; Floyd green chargers. The
same green chargers are used at Christmas for another elaborate
table.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece, designed by Jill Ross, owner of French Meadows,
is filled with fresh produce. Ross said she was inspired by Flemish
still-life paintings of abundant flowers and fruit. So Ross did the
same, filling the table with seasonal fruits, vegetables and
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farmers market is wide open, and I try and use things that
will last awhile,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   She places decorative kale along the center line as a base on
which she piles pine cones, asparagus, cinnamon sticks, sunflowers,
cranberries, coffee beans, roses, hydrangeas, raspberries, Indian
corn, sheaves of wheat, artichokes, apples, and seed pods from
poppies. There are probably more things in the Ross mix; the sheer
variety is overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to reflect the bounty of Thanksgiving as it flows
into Christmas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bounty is the key word in decorating holiday tables. Take a look
around the specialty stores and friends' homes. Notice how the pros
set the table. They use an abundance of stuff _ plates, glasses,
ornaments, flowers, silver. An overloaded table is the hallmark of
the holidays. There is no hint of a microwaved dinner when the
Spode Christmas pattern is towering over the buffet table.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you don't need a special set of china for holiday
dining. At Fort Worth's Dishes From the Past, mismatched patterns
are encouraged. Granny's Wedgwood can be paired with the Royal
Doulton, and a bit of Noritake can slide into the mix too.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are buying patterned salad plates to go with a
plain set of china,'' said store owner Jennifer Marcell. She's
finding brides are now registering for entire sets of mismatched
patterns. It's quite the trendy thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
