<HEADLINE>
150,000 FEWER SMOKERS IN SIX YEARS, BAY STATE TO REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Touting its aggressive antitobacco program, the state
Department of Public Health today is releasing statistics that show
Massachusetts with at least 150,000 fewer smokers than six years
ago, and a slightly declining teen smoking rate that is bucking a
national trend.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which will be presented at the monthly Public Health
Council meeting, will also show that 75,000 fewer people died from
tobacco-related illnesses since the state's tobacco control program
began in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials Monday refused to divulge the survey
numbers, but Cellucci administration sources have described the
latest findings as ``incredible'' and that it demonstrates that the
Massachusetts antismoking program ``leads the country (if not the
world)'' in efforts to curb tobacco use.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most encouraging facts to emerge is that there are
signs that Massachusetts teens _ the hardest age group to convince
to stay away from cigarettes and other tobacco products _ are
smoking less at a time when the trend nationally indicates
teenagers are smoking more.
</P>
<P>
   According to one source, youth smoking fell to 19 percent from
25 percent, a 20 percent drop. The change is within the 8 percent
margin of error of the poll, but officials are still expected to
point to the drop as a trend, particularly at a time when national
figures show teen smoking rising.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Adult Tobacco Survey, which is taken from time
to time for the department's Tobacco Control Program, was carried
out by the Center for Survey Research at the University of
Massachusets/Boston and was completed early in the summer. It is
taken by random phone surveys.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts antismoking campaign, which spends $13 million
on advertising, has often been held up as national model. Since it
began in 1993, various studies have shown there have been steep
drops in Massachusetts adult smoking.
</P>
<P>
   An Abt Associates study last year found consumption of
cigarettes dropped by 31 percent in six years to a rate that ranked
Massachusetts as the third lowest in the nation. The survey being
released measures the smoking rate, or the percentage of people who
say they smoke on a regular basis, as compared to consumption,
which is measured by sales.
</P>
<P>
   The survey results are being released at the same time the
American Cancer Society _ the prime sponsor of the 1992 ballot
question that raised the cigarette tax by 25 cents per pack and
created the nationally acclaimed antismoking advertising program _
promotes its Great American Smokeout on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Fresina, the society's director of government affairs, said
she did not know the exact results of the survey but had heard they
are ``very very encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``But despite all this good news, there is still a need to
redouble our efforts,'' Fresina said. ``Twenty-eight people a day
die in Massachusetts and we have not won the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature has agreed to use $22.8 million that the state
is receiving from the national tobacco settlement and add it to the
$31.2 million current annual funding for the Department of Public
Health's antismoking program, an increase in the department's
budget of 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The additional funding is part of the $20.87 billion budget plan
lawmakers put on Governor Paul Cellucci's desk last week. The
governor, who is expected to announce his vetoes Tuesday, will
leave the funding intact, administration sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Cellucci has sharply questioned the large amounts
of expenditures for tobacco control. In his budget plan released in
January, the governor suggested spending $500,000 to evaluate the
program. He also wanted to divert $4 million to a firefighters
education program for school children that allowed firemen to earn
overtime. Public health critics said the program was not effective
in preventing smoking and was a boondoggle for a firefighters union
that endorsed the governor's election.
</P>
<P>
   The $22.8 million will be used for four different areas: $7
million will be directed to local communities to enforce local
ordinances and by-laws; $6.7 million for tobacco cessation
programs; $2.5 million for research and evaluations; and $6.6
million to media campaigns targeting minority areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
