<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT WORKERS QUESTION GORE AND DON'T LIKE HIS ANSWERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Vice President Al Gore stepped into the lion's
den Monday, facing down hundreds of Microsoft employees smarting
from the judicial finding that their company had bullied its rivals
and stifled competition. He told them just what they did not want
to hear _ that competition is fundamentally a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   With 300 people packing an auditorium on the computer giant's
campus, the vice president talked about ``unfair use of market
dominance in one sector to stifle innovation in another sector.''
He added: ``If competition is valuable, which I think it is, then
antitrust laws have a place in embodying the values of our
country.'' At another point: ``The values that are inherent in the
antitrust laws are ones that are sound, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was virtually echoing the heart of the federal government's
case against Microsoft, and the atmosphere here in the company
auditorium went icy at his words.
</P>
<P>
   Gore trooped out to Microsoft, Washington state's largest
employer, as just another candidate for president. He was following
in the footsteps of several of his rivals, including former Sen.
Bill Bradley of New Jersey, his sole Democratic challenger, and a
number of Republicans, including Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and
Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore had the added burden of representing an administration
that has ferociously pummeled Microsoft in court. Complicating his
task as a candidate is the fact that, as one questioner pointed
out, Gore is probably the most ``technologically savvy'' candidate
ever to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   He also had the misfortune to have had an earlier meeting here
rescheduled so that Monday's visit came just 10 days after Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson of U.S. District Court found in a
devastating assessment that the company has monopoly control over
PC operating systems and that it wields that power in ways that are
hurt American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, wearing a sweater and slacks, the casual attire that
Microsoft allows its employees, tried at first to avoid commenting
on the case. But the audience relentlessly questioned him about his
views. Isn't government interference more of a threat to consumers
than Microsoft? he was asked. Isn't it a dangerous invasion of
privacy when the government can cull and regurgitate someone's
e-mails to use against them in court?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most pointedly, one employee told Gore that he shared
his Democratic social values and wanted to vote for him but felt
deeply conflicted because of the administration's ``favorable
reaction to a ruling that says we're harming consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   William Kovacic, a law professor specializing in anti-trust
cases at George Washington University, said afterward that Gore had
put himself in ``an extraordinarily difficult position,'' but, he
said, ``the issues the case raises are so fundamental to the future
of the company and of innovation that it's perfectly reasonable for
people to ask what his views are.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a precedent for commenting on such cases. When Boeing
acquired McDonnell-Douglas in 1997, Gore came to the home of Boeing
in Seattle and said the United States would fight attempts by
Europe to block the merger. Kovacic said that Gore's advocacy in
favor of Boeing's monopoly, and in favor of the American company's
pre-eminence in the aircraft sector of the economy, stood in stark
contrast to the administration's opposition in the case of
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has a lot of domestic enemies, and a lot of them are
in Silicon Valley, and they have thrown a lot of cash at both
parties, but in particular to the Democrats,'' Kovacic said.
``Microsoft has a legion of enemies who hold it in contempt. And
that's a tricky issue for the White House. Do you attack the
pre-eminent symbol of American information technology success or
safeguard the interests of their Silicon Valley opponents? It's a
tough call.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore turned the conversation to one of values, mentioning
support for research and development, dealing with inequality and
then said: ``And yet another value that I think is important in our
country is competition. And competition can be stifled both by
unwise and unhealthy government action and also by private action
on the part of companies that want to unfairly use market dominance
in one sector to stifle innovation in another sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this grim judgment, Gore has tried to portray himself as
a friend of the high-tech industry, going so far earlier this year
to proclaim himself as the father of the Internet. He has promoted
tax credits for research and development, and Monday he threw
around notions like and quantum computing and Moore's Law with
abandon. He also noted that one of his daughters, Karenna, had
worked briefly at Slate, Microsoft's online magazine. One of his
former employees, Ginny Terzano, once Gore's press secretary, has
just been hired by Microsoft to head its lobbying office in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear what kind of affinity Bill Gates, the
Microsoft chairman, may have for Gore. Gates was not on hand for
Monday's visit, having a prior commitment at a conference. There
has been considerable debate over Gates' political leanings and
speculation that he wants to drag out the lawsuit until a new
president takes office and appoints a new chief of the Justice
Department's anti-trust division.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft gave $1.3 million last year to candidates in both
parties. Microsoft employees have been more generous to Republicans
this year than to Democrats, giving $29,000 to Bush and $13,000 to
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Several employees who attended Monday's session with Gore
reflected the computer industry's stance that elected politics has
little to do with their success. A cluster of employees, who
declined to give their names, said they were more interested in
Gore's views on education and health care than on the anti-trust
case because, as one put it, ``the administration doesn't have much
say in the overall economic growth of the last 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's comments did not appear to win him many friends. ``I
appreciate him being honest,'' said one employee. ``But I'm not
encouraged. He was on the side of the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
