<HEADLINE>
TRADE MISSION COST TAXPAYERS $142,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It will go down as one of the most expensive trade
missions Massachusetts has ever organized.
</P>
<P>
   A one-week trip to France and Ireland in June cost taxpayers
$142,000 _ an average of nearly $16,000 for each of the nine people
in the official Massachusetts delegation, according to expense
accounts released Monday to the Boston Globe under the Freedom of
Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   The tally included:
</P>
<P>
   --$42,872 for individual hotel and food costs and another
$13,000 in airfare.
</P>
<P>
   --$10,000 for cars and vans in Paris, and $10,500 for the same
in Dublin and Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   --$8,869 for 16 rental cell phones, with extra charges for a
lost leather pouch and battery charger. Kathleen Molony, head of
the Massachusetts Trade Office, said the delegation knew the phones
would be expensive, but felt it was important to stay in constant
contact with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it (nearly) $9,000?'' said Jason Kauppi, a spokesman for
Governor Paul Cellucci. ``Well, when you're overseas selling
yourself, you need to look like you're a world class operation.''
</P>
<P>
   --$6,800 for meeting room rental charges in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   --A $2,400 Parisian breakfast for 50 at an average cost of $48
per head.
</P>
<P>
   --Nearly $2,000 for dozens of trinkets _ letter openers,
coasters, glassware, and frames _ from Boston jeweler Shreve, Crump
&AMP; Low that the governor handed out to dignitaries. Another $140 was
spent on gifts for officials in Ireland. ``We do take gifts as a
matter of protocol,'' Molony said.
</P>
<P>
   --About $2,000 for a tour of Paris and help with protocol for
Cellucci's three days in France. That included some translation
services for courtesy calls with French ministers.
</P>
<P>
   --$150 for luggage pickup at a Paris hotel.
</P>
<P>
   An internal post-trip report written by the state director of
economic development Carolyn Boviard shows that IBM, Custom
Extrusion, and Cerulean Technology Inc. had possible business leads
from the trade mission, but that there was little else to show for
the costly excursion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That report was done immediately following the mission,'' said
Candace Perodeau, a spokeswoman for Boviard. ``Those were just
initial reactions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Molony conceded that, nearly five months after the trade
mission, there is still no tangible commerce as a result of the
trip. ``It sometimes takes a bit longer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken White, executive director of Common Cause Massachusetts, was
shocked to hear the litany of expenses. ``It would be interesting
to hear those who flew on this trade mission explain how the
investment and trinkets from Shreve, Crump &AMP; Low produce benefits
for the taxpayers of Massachusetts,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One has to ask, `What sort of return do we get in exchange for
this kind of outlay?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some on the trip did pay their own way, including House Speaker
Thomas M. Finneran, who used campaign funds to cover expenses.
Boston College and Northeastern University paid their own way, as
did local companies.
</P>
<P>
   IBM attended six meetings. ``Among the successes noted that came
from the trip was the opportunity the trade mission offered to
`introduce Investment Belfast to Lotus,' '' stated the economic
development report, which was also released to the Globe. ``The
company (IBM/Lotus) speculates that it may earn as much as $5
million from having participated in the trade mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerulean Technology ``had meaningful follow-up with seven
different firms,'' and Custom Extrusion ``was able to survey the
markets and to see how the Economic Union is changing the manner in
which business transactions occur,'' the report said. The company
told the state it had found a ``strong contact in France with whom
they plan on doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boston College said it found a potential pool of
technical workers in Ireland. Northeastern said the trip was
``useful in talking about the French education system.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Cellucci took office as lieutenant governor in 1991, there
have been 25 state trade missions, according to Molony. She said
the only one in recent memory that cost more was a trip to South
America that spanned four countries. However, she said she did not
know the bottom-line expense of that mission.
</P>
<P>
   Kauppi, Cellucci's spokesman, defended the trip, saying France
imported $700 million in goods and services from Massachusetts,
making the country the sixth-leading export for the state. And
Ireland, with its booming economy, has tremendous trade growth
potential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
