<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO HEAR TEXAS SCHOOL PRAYER CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case that combines the Constitution, God and
the Texas gridiron, the Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide if
public school students can conduct prayers before football games
without violating the constitutional separation of church and
state.
</P>
<P>
   When the court hears arguments in the case this winter or
spring, the Santa Fe Independent School District in Galveston
County will press the justices to rule that pre-game prayers do not
violate the Constitution's prohibition on governmental endorsement
of religion. In successfully urging the high court to hear the
case, Santa Fe said the prayers are the legitimate free expression
of students who publicly seek God's assistance in maintaining
sportsmanship during the games.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Santa Fe Independent School District vs. Doe, marks
the Supreme Court's first major foray since 1992 into the thorny
First Amendment issue of governmental endorsement of religion at
public schools. The justices, in several decisions since 1962, have
ruled that the Constitution generally prohibits school-district
involvement in sectarian activities, saying that such participation
alienates students of minority religions.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals cited the Supreme Court's
line of religion cases in ruling in February that Santa Fe, by
permitting students to recite prayers before football games,
endorsed faith in violation of the Constitution. The First
Amendment prevents public schools from compelling students to
listen to expressions of religions they do not accept, the court
said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Leon Frels, representing the school board,
assailed that ruling and said the Constitution does not apply
because the students, not the school, are initiating and leading
the pre-game prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logic and reasoning of the 5th Circuit's decision will
require that school officials prevent any speaker, including
speakers as diverse as athletes, politicians, academics,
entertainers, maybe even judges, from discussing a religious topic
or invoking the Lord's name, to ensure that no audience member
perceives that the school is endorsing the speaker's religious
message,'' Frels argued in a legal brief to the justices.
</P>
<P>
   But parents of some Santa Fe students, who have so far
successfully challenged the pre-game activity, countered that that
prayers violate the Constitution by subjecting players and
spectators to religious expressions with which they might disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that ... prayer before football games is led by
students does not diminish the pressure to religious conformity, if
anything, it may increase it,'' wrote the parents' attorney,
Anthony Griffin of Galveston, in a brief to the high court. ``And
the fact that a prayer is overtly sectarian only magnifies the
message that there is one (true) faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Santa Fe and the parents cited the Supreme Court's 1992
decision striking down as unconstitutional a planned invocation by
a rabbi at a high school graduation in Rhode Island. The justices
in Lee vs. Weisman held 5-4 that schools may not direct a religious
exercise at graduation ceremonies, noting that students at such
events have no real alternative but to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe argued that the Lee case does not apply to football
games because the students themselves, without the school's
direction or assistance, are conducting the prayers.
</P>
<P>
   But the parents challenging the school district countered that
football games are no different than graduation ceremonies insofar
as the students in attendance must either listen or leave.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe case has become a rallying cry for Texas political
leaders and lawmakers who regard God and the gridiron as virtually
inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Attorney General John Cornyn have
submitted a brief to the justices, urging them to rule the pre-game
prayers constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the leading Republican contender for president, hopes the
court will overturn the 5th Circuit decision because ``he believes
it is a First Amendment right for students to participate in the
free exercise of religion, and he believes government should not
dictate or censor the content of voluntary student-led prayer,''
said the governor's spokeswoman, Linda Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most members of the Texas congressional delegation
this month spearheaded passage of a House resolution calling on the
Supreme Court to rule pre-game prayers constitutional. The
resolution, which does not have the force of law, was intended to
express the ``sense of the House'' that the Constitution permits
students to publicly seek divine guidance for sportsmanship and
fairness before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   During the football season, Santa Fe High School senior Marian
Ward delivered prayers at home games. She and her family filed a
separate lawsuit in September challenging the ruling by the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals that even nonsectarian,
nonproselytizing prayers were inappropriate at football games.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the nation's highest court would review the case
spread quickly through Santa Fe and Galveston County on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're elated, but I don't think we should be surprised,'' said
school board president John Couch. ``We've stood on principle for
the last six years, saying we believe our students have the First
Amendment right to their message.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
