<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-DUES-CONGRESS-REACT-N     11-15 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUES-CONGRESS-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IF DUES PAYMENT IS MADE, U.S. MIGHT STILL LOSE GENERAL
ASSEMBLY VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With DUES-CONGRESS) 
(HLW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Appropriating nearly $1 billion in back dues
and assessments to the United Nations may not be enough to prevent
the United States from losing its vote in the General Assembly next
year, U.N. officials say.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.N. official estimated that the United States must
come up with at least $350 million by the end of December to avoid
forfeiting its vote. But legislation worked out by Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., and Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., would
initially pay only $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility is real because the U.N. charter says that any
country falling two years behind in its dues will be stripped of
its right to vote in the assembly. A few other countries have lost
their votes for this reason, such as Bengladesh and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official expressed confidence that the
gap could be covered by pooling the first payment with other funds
being appropriated in a separate bill for the Departments of State,
Commerce and Justice. Another official described this as ``creative
accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Helms-Biden legislation authorized $926 million in payment
over three years. But it also attached the following conditions,
which other countries are likely to challenge:
</P>
<P>
   --The other 187 member countries must accept the $926 million as
Washington's payment in full and agree not to keep billing for the
remaining arrears. The United Nation says that Washington owes
nearly $1.6 billion, using different calculations and counting
expenses that the United States has refused to pay for political
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   --The United States' share of the U.N. budget must be trimmed to
22 percent from 25 percent, which Washington has been paying for
years.
</P>
<P>
   --The United States' share of peacekeeping costs must be cut to
25 percent from 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   --The U.N. budget cannot include any growth in spending, even
allowing for inflation. The budget has not risen in dollar terms
since since 1994, said Catherine O'Neill, the director of the U.N.
office in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Another condition, that the United States be reinstated on a key
budget committee, was met after Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright told foreign ministers attending the General Assembly in
September that without the committee seat, the administration would
find it impossible to get Congress to allocate money.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is the biggest contributor to the United
Nations, but also its biggest debtor, accounting for more than 60
percent of the total owed by member countries.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the General Assembly vote for nonpayment would not affect
the United States' seat and vote in the Security Council, or its
veto power as one of the council's five permanent members. But the
loss of the assembly vote would be a setback to the nation's
prestige and influence in the organization, which has been
declining as the arrears piled up.
</P>
<P>
   The debt was on the minds of a group of lawmakers who visited
U.N. headquarters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is tragic that we will have not paid our dues up to
this point,'' Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said. ``I'm very
embarrassed about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Boxer told a cluster of reporters, many of whom
represent foreign news organizations, that the administration had
done the best it could in working out a compromise. But she added,
``We have some very radical members controlling Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our national security in paying our dues is of utmost
importance,'' Senator Boxer said. ``The fact that our national
security is being held hostage by these radical elements in
Congress is shocking to me, and I think it is shocking to the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., said the effect of the new
legislation could not be seen until it was in draft language. ``My
understanding from conversations with folks in Washington is that
we will be able to fulfill our obligations,'' Gejdenson said. ``It
would be truly outrageous that after all this time we still don't
pay our bills.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior administration official said that some of the reforms
contained in the Helms-Biden legislation, like reducing the United
States' share of the United Nations' cost, might become possible
once Washington offered the money. ``If we have a check in hand,
the climate for reforms will be greatly improved,'' the senior
official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
