<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991115.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0746 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HOSPITAL-INTERNS-III-     11-15 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-INTERNS-III-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: of preaching.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food, Glorious Food
</P>
<P>
   The Gin Mill bar on 83rd Street and Amsterdam Avenue was a hive
of activity, especially in the rackety back area where the interns
congregated. It was Residents' Happy Hour, courtesy of Pfizer.
Almost every Wednesday one of the drug houses sponsored a Happy
Hour, when the interns could drink and attack a buffet table.
</P>
<P>
   A young, primly dressed Pfizer representative stamped Dr. James'
hand, to show she was entitled to free drinks, and gave her a
brochure on Norvasc, a hypertension drug. Dr. James deposited it in
her pocket. She was here to socialize.
</P>
<P>
   She scooted to the bar and mingled with the other interns. There
was plenty of gossip to absorb _ could you believe that resident
who was hitting on two interns? There were pictures to study _ one
intern had just married in Japan and had brought his album.
</P>
<P>
   They lined up for food.
</P>
<P>
   Interns were obsessed with food. Since they never had time to
eat, they thought about it constantly. One of two things generally
happened during internship: You gained weight because all you ate
was junk food, or you lost weight because you skipped so many
meals.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it was a well-known fact that the best way to fill a room
with residents was to bait the room with food. Planning a lecture
on bladder catheterization? Order pizza and make sure there are
plenty of seats.
</P>
<P>
   One particular species willing to provide consumables was the
pharmaceutical salesman. Eager to impress on the doctors the
illimitable virtues of their drugs, they appeared almost daily at
lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   In the late morning, when hunger was gnawing at the interns, the
magic words would reverberate over the public address system:
``Lunch for the house staff will be served in conference room B at
noon.'' The meaning was clear. A drug rep was here. Free food!
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the interns dictated the menu. On Fridays, for
instance, they usually insisted on Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The interns felt they were crossing no ethical lines. They had
essentially no say in which drugs were put on the hospital's
approved list. ``I come to see the other interns and to eat,'' Dr.
James said.
</P>
<P>
   The drug reps were not the only visitors. One day, John Hancock
came peddling insurance and mutual funds to an audience commonly
boasting negative net worths. Still, the room was full. The company
had brought Indian food.
</P>
<P>
   `A Little Gastric Upset'
</P>
<P>
   At the monthly meeting for the medicine residents, there were
the same nagging issues. The residents were admonished about the
need to discharge patients in a timely manner. The all-important
length of stay (LOS) averages had been creeping up, particularly
among Medicare patients. In 1992, the hospital's LOS was 14 days,
and it was now a little over six, but that was still above the
national average. Keep someone too long and the hospital ate the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in an unsubtle way of shaming the laggards, St. Luke's
had resumed sending LOS report cards to the attendings, as the
senior staff doctors are known. The residents received their own
promptings: ``Anyone who discharges someone today gets a second
free sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was hard to make the residents care too deeply about
medicine's new economics, about managed care's protocols. Their
income remained at the same low level no matter how many patients
they treated or how fast they treated them.
</P>
<P>
   They were still full of medical-school idealism. To a certain
extent, they felt shielded from reality, being taught by doctors
who were unsure how to teach for the new medical world.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Lesch, the chairman of the department of medicine,
struggled in his own mind about how much to adapt. He labored at
getting his department's LOS in line. (As he put it, ``This is no
longer a hotel.'') But when he got deep into a discussion of
managed care, he would get riled and say: ``I teach them medicine.
Managed care is not medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   There was actually something of a generation gap among the
attending physicians. Some younger ones did not quite share the
older doctors' virulent feelings about the new age. Even so, the
interns heard almost nothing but grumbling from attendings, even
young ones, about the changed ways, and often Dr. James said to
herself, ``Enough already.''
</P>
<P>
   One day an attending cornered her in the hallway and began
moaning about how he was making so much less money and how horrible
his life had become. ``What am I supposed to do,'' Dr. James
thought, ``not become a doctor?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, from their own rush of experiences, the interns had begun
to adopt their own biases about managed care. In tallying the risk
factors of a new patient, Dr. James and her friends joked that if
the person was covered by a certain managed-care company, they
would consider that a risk factor like smoking or obesity.
</P>
<P>
   All manner of mixed signals filtered down to the impressionable
interns. One morning, after an intern informed her attending doctor
that her patient was ready to leave, the attending said he wanted
her to stay another day. He wanted to take a picture of the woman's
exotic, looping toenails but had forgotten his camera.
</P>
<P>
   The intern was astonished that someone was being kept in the
hospital for a snapshot of her toenails. To Dr. James, this one set
of toenails seemed to reflect the growing disharmony of the times.
On one rotation, Dr. James reported to a third-year resident, who
repeatedly told her: ``This is a teaching hospital. If you're just
curious, order the test.''
</P>
<P>
   With staffing tight, the attending doctors were stretched as
thin as the residents, and it was an issue trying to get them to
teach enough hours. Private attendings rarely taught anymore, as
they once voluntarily did. And many staff attendings would spend an
hour on rounds and then be swallowed up by an increasing weight of
responsibilities _ private patients, paperwork, research.
</P>
<P>
   They would write a progress note only when a patient was
admitted. Lesch asked them to write daily notes, as the interns
did; the hospital could bill for them. Eyes lifted. Medicaid would
pay $7 a note. Eyes lowered. Lesch wondered how some attendings
even knew the patients. How could they teach the interns how to
interact with patients when the attendings themselves didn't
interact with them?
</P>
<P>
   He recognized that what the interns saw and heard was often
contradictory. But he did not have the answers. ``They have to find
their own values,'' he said. ``They have to find how far they will
go before they compromise. I hope I at least give them a little
gastric upset.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
