programs for children are nothing new. But the New Jersey pheasant
shoot was an example of a newer and growing phenomenon of state
wildlife agencies and private groups working hand in hand to
promote hunting among children. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CHESTER, N.J. -- Nov. 15, 1999 -- YOUNG-HUNTERS, 11-15 --
Mary Konboz, 11, and her father Anthony, hunting pheasant earlier
this month as part of Take a Kid Pheasant Hunting Day, an event run
since 1996, sponsored in part by the New Jersey Division of Fish,
Game and Wildlife, and the National Rifle Association Foundation,
an arm of the gun lobby. Shooting programs for children are nothing
new. But the New Jersey pheasant shoot was an example of a newer
and growing phenomenon of state wildlife agencies and private
groups working hand in hand to promote hunting among children.
(Dith Pran/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Nov. 15, 1999 -- SCI-ORPHAN-DISEASES, 11-15 --
Jessica and David Godek, with their son, Eric, at 6 months.
Rejected for a clinical drug trial, Eric died a few days later from
a rare muscle disorder known as Pompe disease. (Steve Kagan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LIVINGSTON, La. -- Nov. 15, 1999 -- SCI-GRAVITY-WAVES-2,
11-15 --From the Louisiana woodlands, a gravity wave detector peers
at the distant universe. The l-shaped detector here and its
recently completed twin in Hanford, Wash., are called LIGO
(pronounced LIE-go), for Laser Interferometer Gravitational-wave
Observatory. At $296 million so far, it is the largest enterprise
ever financed by the National Science Foundation. (California
