<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0748 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HOSPITAL-INTERNS-III-     11-15 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-INTERNS-III-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: gastric upset.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internship: The Bottom Line
</P>
<P>
   One of his clinic patients paid in cash _ $67.50. Seeing actual
money change hands, Holland felt good. ``I'm bringing in money for
the hospital,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Given their low pay and handyman job description, the interns
assumed they were big moneymakers for St. Luke's. And compared with
attending doctors, they were so much of a bargain that more of them
were graduating than society could absorb.
</P>
<P>
   Nodding to concerns about a glut of doctors, New York was in the
midst of a federal experiment in which the government was paying
the state's teaching hospitals to reduce their number of residents
by a fourth. Yet more than half of the enlisted hospitals had
withdrawn, unable to make the economics work.
</P>
<P>
   After scaling back the number of its interns, St. Luke's was
going to raise the number next year. Even so, the hospital was
having an increasingly hard time breaking even on its residents.
</P>
<P>
   The algorithm computed by the financial staff went like this: It
cost about $184,165 a year to train an intern. There was the modest
salary of $39,270, the proportionate expense of an attending
doctor, malpractice premiums and various other expenses like the
high technology and the inevitable excess of tests and longer
patient stays.
</P>
<P>
   Some 80 percent of the cost was covered by Medicaid and
Medicare, and the rest by private insurers, through a special state
tax. In this stubborn new environment, though, they were reducing
the level of payment.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, St. Luke's calculated that it actually lost about
$1,500 per intern. It tried to economize. The rule of thumb used to
be that residents ordered every test known to man times two. While
attendings no longer allowed so many tests, studies suggested that
residents still ordered about 20 percent more than doctors at
nonteaching hospitals did.
</P>
<P>
   With further funding cuts looming, there was not much more the
interns could be asked to do other than swab the floors.
</P>
<P>
   `Another Medical Triumph'
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon, Dr. James joined the others for Intern Report, in
which an intern presented one of her cases. Dr. Gregory Steinberg,
associate director of medicine, moderated.
</P>
<P>
   The intern recited the bare facts: a 39-year-old man whose chief
complaint was that he felt sick for five days and was getting
worse. He had no significant medical history. He had a throbbing
headache, chest pain, shortness of breath and abdominal pain. He
smoked crack and marijuana and occasionally slept on the street,
where he was exposed to pigeons and rats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do pigeons do for you?'' Steinberg said. ``What do rats
do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plague,'' someone suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not too much plague in New York,'' Steinberg pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
   What sort of people were exposed to rat urine?
</P>
<P>
   One intern said, ``Swimmers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Swimmers?'' Steinberg said. ``Where do you do your swimming?''
</P>
<P>
   The correct answer was sanitation workers and those who work in
sewers.
</P>
<P>
   The man was administered antibiotics, though his diagnosis
remained unclear. Tests were done. Day by day, he began feeling
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we treating?'' Steinberg asked. ``At God knows what
cost per day? We're treating us. We're feeling better because he's
feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurers were howling to get patients discharged swiftly, but
the house staff wanted to learn. When oddities arose _ curious
tangents not always clinically relevant _ the interns investigated
at their leisure, sometimes forgetting about the patient, never
thinking about dollars and cents.
</P>
<P>
   By day 12, this patient was feeling so much better that he was
discharged. The assumption was that he had leptospirosis, an
infection that rats can transmit.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we did nothing for him but gave him antibiotics, and he
probably would have gotten better without them,'' Steinberg said.
``Another medical triumph. We did nothing. The patient got
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Children, Checks and Balances
</P>
<P>
   He had been drinking. The police found him passed out on the
subway and brought him in. His blood-alcohol level was twice the
legal limit for an adult. He was 12.
</P>
<P>
   Holland visited him in his room and tried to discover the
precipitating events. It was a fragile moment. ``Kids start with
one thing and then move on to drugs and who knows what,'' he said.
``You want to stop it right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy insisted that he was just experimenting. He was getting
good grades in school. Holland learned from the parents that they
were having marital problems. That might be part of it. The boy
squirmed and smiled weakly as Holland spoke indignantly of the
evils of alcohol. Truth was, social work was part of being a
doctor, too.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the room, Holland was quiet. ``I think he'll be OK,'' he
said. ``He's clearly smart and well-mannered. He said he was never
doing this again. I think he'll be too scared to.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after a shift in the clinic, Holland and the other
doctors clattered into a small back office for a soda. With the
inevitability of gravity, the conversation turned to the problems
of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The attending on duty, a young woman from India, mentioned how
she recently did a blood screening for a child and the insurer
wouldn't pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ```Not indicated,' they said,'' she complained. ``And it was
absolutely needed. It's really bad out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland gave a wry smile: ``Down with the insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The attending went on: ``It's good that something came along,
because we needed checks and balances. There was a lot of waste in
the system. But they've gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Her own son had been hospitalized for pneumonia while visiting
India and her insurer had refused to cover it. ``I fought for a
year and two months to be paid,'' she said. ``I nagged them every
week. Then I threatened to report them to the attorney general. I
got a check in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning,'' Holland said. ``Threaten, threaten.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what they get away with,'' the attending said.
``Most people don't have the knowledge to fight. I'm in the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an exaggerated silence. After a while, the attending
said: ``The administration calls here all the time and they want
numbers. They want patients every 20 minutes. They're constantly
looking for numbers. Some socially deprived children need 45
minutes or an hour. I'm supposed to teach the interns, and I'm
supposed to turn out numbers. They're contradictory issues.
Something has to give.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``They're always pulling the interns out of the
clinic to cover something on the floor. When these interns go out
into practice, they almost feel like admitting everybody, because
all they know is in-patient care. They haven't developed clinical
judgment. Someone has pneumonia. Admit him. But wait, this kid
doesn't have respiratory distress. I'll send him home and follow up
tomorrow. Clinical judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland said: ``I've noticed different types of attendings. Some
have no clinical judgment. They order every test because they're
insecure. Others know right away what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to develop a feel for who you listen to and who you
don't,'' the attending said. ``When you're finished here, you'll
know what each attending doesn't know. Not what they know, but what
they don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
