<TEXT>
<P>
   Conundrums of Intensive Care
</P>
<P>
   The big-bellied man would never wake up. His was a life now
unsalvageably distant. His diseased heart had sent him into cardiac
arrest. He had lost his pulse entirely. By the time doctors had
resuscitated him, he appeared to be brain dead.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the doctors could shut off the ventilator and that would
be that, just another of those quotidian horrors of internship.
Tests detected no brain waves. He was removed from the ventilator.
Under the hospital's protocol, he had to fail for two and a half
minutes to take a breath. A few seconds shy of the deadline, he
gave a single gasp.
</P>
<P>
   That gasp was enough that now only his son, who lived in Puerto
Rico, could end what pretense of life the machinery continued to
give his father.
</P>
<P>
   When Dr. James called him, she explained that, barring
unexpected divine intervention, there was no chance his father
would recover. She explained that the motionless man lying in
intensive care was little more than flesh attached to machines. The
son said: ``What does it hurt? Let's keep him alive.'' At a cost of
$3,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   She shivered in anger: ``I thought the son was being selfish and
stupid. It sounded like he didn't want to think that he was turning
off the ventilator and killing his father. But what about how it
was inhuman to keep his father alive? How we would have to keep
doing tests on him. Maybe add a feeding tube. Maybe end up cracking
his ribs if he coded _ for someone who was no longer a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, the father did ``code'' _ his heart stopped _
and this time the doctors could not revive him.
</P>
<P>
   The intensive-care unit was the grimmest destination in the
hospital. Here Dr. James often saw the final gasps of someone's
life, and it was never pretty. It was here that she experienced the
frustration of having to do too much, to treat patients in the
throes of incurable, lingering disease, whose lungs were run by
respirators, whose stomachs were fed by tubes, who were more like
lab experiments than human beings.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James kept hearing that time and money were precious, and
yet so much of both was expended on patients locked in an
unstoppable dance with death. ``Why do another X-ray, another blood
culture?'' she said. ``It's not making them better. If anything,
it's making them worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Often the only sounds in the unit were the hum and buzz of
machines and the occasional television _ talk shows, soaps. And so
many sad stories.
</P>
<P>
   She looked in on a patient on a ventilator who was unable to
speak. The patient was 89, with respiratory pneumonia. Dr. James
had taken care of her for two weeks, without exchanging a word.
``It's weird,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The managed-care doctor had stopped by and urged that her course
of antibiotics be finished so she could return to her nursing home.
``But the nursing home doesn't take `vents,''' Dr. James said. ``I
don't know if I can wean her off it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And for what life? The woman had dementia. She had not spoken in
a long time. She had no family, only a legal guardian. Guardians
are usually reluctant to halt care, because of fear of
repercussions. The attending looked in: ``I have the feeling that
if that woman were awake, she would say, `Please stop _ don't do
this to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   A pulmonary fellow in the unit said: ``Doctors are uncomfortable
talking to people about health-care proxies when they're well, and
we pay the price. When I have a practice, I'll have it right on the
chart as the first thing to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   She was silent a moment. Then she added: ``But it's not easy.
Like, I don't have one. It's hard to know, who do I entrust my life
to?''
</P>
<P>
   So many of these patients posed ethical conundrums for the
interns. Do this. Don't do this. Sometimes Dr. James felt bitter.
Why should she have to work so hard in here, often for no gain?
There were consequences for the soul. The family of one comatose
woman had decorated her room with pictures of her dog and cat, and
that made Dr. James think of her as truly alive. But she would
never open an eye again.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they would joke about someone: ``Oh, the guy's shot.
Let's just let him die.'' It muted the sorrow, but it also
expressed what they felt.
</P>
<P>
   So many cases were hopeless that the interns were taken aback
when they encountered an ICU patient back on the wards, nearly well
again. Dr. James had a man with sickle-cell anemia who reached the
brink of death only to reject it. Soon he was released. She thought
of him as Lazarus.
</P>
<P>
   Over the loudspeaker now came word of a drug-company lunch, and
the interns' spirits abruptly lifted. Escape from this sorrowful
shift. By the time Dr. James wrapped up her paperwork and got
there, however, the turnout was so huge that all the plates had
been claimed. Disappointed, she backtracked to the cafeteria with a
fellow intern and had to pay for ravioli.
</P>
<P>
   In an uninflected tone, her friend told her about a dreadful
case. The interns were urged always to ask about DNR (do not
resuscitate) orders, but it was complicated. The friend said she
had just lost a patient, a 53-year-old woman with emphysema. She
was intubated and then, as she improved, extubated. She got worse
again and refused another intubation. She had signed a DNR order.
Helpless to do anything for a woman she felt could recover
completely, the intern watched her die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I just got the funniest news from Ohio,'' Dr. James said.
``Someone I know who's doing her internship in Dayton just had her
first death _ this after eight months of internship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding,'' her friend said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I had one the first month,'' Dr. James said. ``I'm
sure glad I'm not doing my residency in Ohio. What would I learn?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
