<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0751 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HOSPITAL-INTERNS-III-     11-15 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-INTERNS-III-ART-5THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: I learn?''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Postmortem Blues
</P>
<P>
   There was a pep talk on autopsies. For years, it had been
getting harder to obtain permission for them, and the number of
autopsies had dwindled steadily. Enhanced technology had greatly
improved doctors' ability to diagnose illness and families felt
there was nothing more to discover.
</P>
<P>
   Patients' relatives were more reluctant to expose them _
particularly those who were very old _ to what they saw as an
indignity, when no known medical procedure could do them any good.
Religious factors were involved, too.
</P>
<P>
   Still, autopsies did turn up surprises and were important
teaching aides. Federal rules decreed that teaching hospitals
should perform autopsies for at least 15 percent of deaths, but
since few hospitals could meet the threshold, it was rarely
enforced. St. Luke's had an 11 percent average.
</P>
<P>
   Interns were understandably squeamish even at broaching the
issue with patients' families. So the medicine department had
devised a macabre contest of sorts, with a prize to the intern who
rounded up the most autopsies.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, interns had received medical textbooks or Barnes
&AMP; Noble gift certificates for each autopsy they achieved. These
were apparently inadequate stimuli, so this year the incentive was
sweetened, to a grand prize of $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the interns found this particularly ghoulish. Some
actually felt no longer inclined to pursue autopsies. In any event,
there was a catch. The prize was awarded only if the department
recorded at least 100 autopsies for the year, and it was woefully
shy of that target.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James had zero autopsies. Personally, she felt them
inappropriate, unless there was some mystery about the death. She
almost had one. But the hospital was unable to get it done before
the family insisted on burial. Overnight, she went from plus 1 back
to 0.
</P>
<P>
   Salving Loneliness, Saving a Life
</P>
<P>
   Lathan felt gloomy. ``When you're counting the hours and waiting
for the shift to end, you know it's not good,'' he said over lunch.
His best friend, an intern at another hospital, told him that one
of the surgery interns there had hanged himself in his room. There
were money issues. Love issues. Protracted depression.
</P>
<P>
   Lathan was not so much depressed as aggravated by his ascetic
life. He didn't even date; he had no time for a relationship.
``You're spending like 80 percent of your life in this place,
working six days straight,'' he said. ``It's like being in a prison
camp. I find myself less tolerant. Now it's a case of if it's not
about my education, I don't want to do it, and I resent it. I don't
want to be used as a slave just because of lack of manpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement and thrill is not there. It's a shame, too,
because medicine really is a joy. It's a shame that they have a
system that actually makes you hate medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Into the ER the patients still came. The man said he felt a
weakness in his side. He said he could not walk steadily: ``I walk
like a zombie. I walk like a robot.'' He had to go to the bathroom.
Lathan watched him walk. He walked like a person. What he was was
depressed. Lathan discharged him and suggested a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wasting my time,'' Lathan said. ``I don't like people
who waste my time.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw an 85-year-old woman complaining of diarrhea, vomiting,
chills. Her home-care aide told Lathan: ``I think her biggest
problem is loneliness. She says when she's home she feels sad. When
she got here, she said she felt alive.''
</P>
<P>
   He nodded. He understood.
</P>
<P>
   Lathan was summoned to another room. A woman, 41, desolate for
reasons best known to her, had swallowed 28 tablets of Doxepin, a
depressant, saying she wanted to die. ``She just wanted to kill
herself in front of the triage nurse,'' a nurse said.
</P>
<P>
   Lathan and several residents channeled their energy into
reversing her actions. He put in a breathing tube. She was
connected to an EKG machine. ``Hello, hello,'' Lathan said.
</P>
<P>
   They began pumping her stomach. While Lathan worked on her, the
chief resident dispassionately lectured him on how much fluid to
add, why this, why that. The woman was a life hanging by a thread,
but also a vehicle for teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The contents of her stomach were placed in a pink plastic bin.
``It's how you take gasoline out of a tank, water out of a swimming
pool,'' someone said.
</P>
<P>
   The floor was a mess of discarded packaging from the cavalcade
of medical supplies. Soon the woman was ready for a chest X-ray,
and then she would go to intensive care. The chief resident said,
``All right, we're cool.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing more to say. Lathan had a pilot with abdominal
pain who was supposed to be flying to Spain. The shift had hours to
go. Something special had happened. A woman would live who had
tried not to.
</P>
<P>
   Managed Care 101
</P>
<P>
   Late in the internship year, in a rare attempt at formally
addressing the mechanics of managed care with the house staff, the
hospital arranged for a pair of seminars. They were described in
leaflets sent to all the residents as ``important seminars that can
assist you in practicing medicine in this ever-expanding era of
managed care.''
</P>
<P>
   The sessions were staged in a large conference room at Roosevelt
and beamed by closed-circuit television to St. Luke's. They
attached an accept-it-it's-not-going-away sensibility to the topic.
Reprints of studies and charts were stacked on a table for
attendees to take with them.
</P>
<P>
   There was not much need. Only a handful of people showed up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
