<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0762 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ATM-FEES-1STLD-WRITET     11-15 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATM-FEES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE INTENSIFIES OVER ATM SURCHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., N.Y., Iowa, Vt., Wyo., Ark., Miss.)  (Subs to correct dateline) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ Lashawanda McCullom, a 30-year-old nurse,
put her credit union's cash card into a Bank of America automated
teller machine here, punched in her secret code and requested a
withdrawal. The machine spit out her card and flashed a message:
``Due to a recent vote by the Santa Monica City Council, the
convenience of this ATM is now available to Bank of America
cardholders only.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCullom, who expressed mild frustration at being denied her
cash, was caught in the cross-fire of a skirmish over ATM
surcharges that now seems to be breaking into a full-fledged war.
Suddenly, the fact that it costs an extra $1.50 or so to get money
out of a cash machine seems to have tapped into some deep well of
public resentment _ or at least politicians believe it has.
</P>
<P>
   This oceanside suburb of Los Angeles last month passed the
nation's first local ordinance banning banks from charging
noncustomers for using their ATMs, and Bank of America retaliated
by denying noncustomers use of its machines. San Francisco voters
approved a similar measure earlier this month, and now, legislators
in other cities and states are said to be looking at similar
ordinances. The New York City Council speaker, Peter Vallone, said
Monday that he planned to propose such a law, and the Los Angeles
City Council has instructed the city attorney to study the city's
authority to enact a ban.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Defense has also proposed a ban on such
surcharges on all military bases. Connecticut and Iowa already ban
such surcharges under pre-existing laws, and three other states _
Wyoming, Arkansas and Mississippi _ have price caps on the
surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers just find the surcharge sort of the fee that broke
the consumer's back, so to speak,'' said Richard Blumenthal, the
attorney general of Connecticut, which is now battling the banking
industry in court. ``Consumers see no reason for it. They regard it
almost as a personal insult. It has evoked an emotion that is quite
astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The banking industry, saying it has the right to charge for a
service, is fighting to squelch the uprising before it gathers more
steam. California's leading banks argued Monday in U.S. District
Court for an injunction preventing the Santa Monica and San
Francisco ordinances from being enforced.
</P>
<P>
   And on the day Santa Monica's ordinance took effect _ last
Thursday _ Bank of America and Wells Fargo Bank, the state's two
largest banks by far, began prohibiting noncustomers from using
ATMs, which is why Ms. McCullom could not get her money on Friday.
The banks say they will do the same in San Francisco when that
ordinance takes effect, probably next month.
</P>
<P>
   How widespread the bans will become remains to be seen. Santa
Monica and San Francisco are both unusually liberal cities.
Consumer groups have failed to get any state legislature to enact
such a ban, and Alfonse D'Amato, when he was a U.S. senator from
New York, never got very far with his attempt to legislate a
nationwide prohibition. Rep. Bernard Sanders, an independent from
Vermont, this month re-introduced legislation banning surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say it is unreasonable to charge consumers for access to
their own money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks are basically holding our money hostage,'' said Jon
Golinger of the California Public Interest Group. The U.S. Public
Interest Research Group found that 93 percent of banks surveyed
impose such a surcharge, up from 71 percent in 1998 and 15 percent
in 1996. Nationally, such surcharges appear to generate about $2
billion to $3 billion a year or more for operators of the ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say that in many cases consumers are being charged
twice for each withdrawal. If a Wells Fargo customer, for instance,
takes money out of a Bank of America machine, Wells Fargo charges
that customer $2 for using a ``foreign'' ATM, about 50 cents of
which goes to reimburse Bank of America. But Bank of America itself
charges $1.50 for use of its machine by a noncustomer, bringing the
total fee for retrieving as little as $20 of one's own money to
$3.50.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Monica and San Francisco ordinances, as well as the
regulation in Connecticut, bar only the $1.50 surcharge levied by
the ATM owner, not the fees imposed by a bank on its own customers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the frustration over the surcharges stems from what is a
general proliferation in banking fees in an era of deregulation,
and the fact that ATM use was once free. ``People see the way banks
are trying to charge for everything under the sun,'' said Walter
McCaffrey, a New York City councilman from Queens who is helping
draft the proposed legislation there. ``The original position was
that ATMs were not a profit center.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks say it is their right to charge for services. If consumers
don't want to pay they can use their own bank's ATMs. Without
surcharges, they said, there would be fewer ATMs and less
convenience for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to find too many people who are willing to
give the service for free,'' said Terry Zink, senior vice president
in charge of ATMs for Wells Fargo. ``The biggest issue is whether
or not consumers have the right to pay for services they want.''
</P>
<P>
   What is perhaps most unusual about this battle is that only a
few years ago, the forces were on the opposite sides. The banks
themselves, through two major networks that link ATM machines,
prohibited the surcharges. And legislators in 15 states enacted
laws overriding the prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Banks initially shunned fees to encourage people to use the
machines. They viewed ATMs not as money makers but as cost-savers,
a way to cut down on the number of tellers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But then some banks as well as some nonfinancial companies began
realizing that charging customers would make it economical to put
ATMs in remote locations and away from banks themselves. Moreover,
the prohibition on surcharges raised antitrust issues because it
made it difficult for nonbanks to be in the ATM business because
there would be no way to recover their costs. This led to the state
laws allowing the fees and to the decision in 1996 by two major
national ATM networks _ Visa's Plus and Mastercard International's
Cirrus _ to lift the prohibition on surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the number of ATMs has nearly doubled to 227,000 from
123,000 in 1997, according to the American Bankers Association.
Most of the new machines are not at banks and thrifts but at
supermarkets, malls, airports, amusement parks and other so-called
off-premise locations. Indeed, slightly more than half of all ATMs
are now off premise, according to Bank Network News, a
Chicago-based newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, about half of all new ATMs _ including most of the
off-premise ones _ are owned by companies other than banks, thrifts
or credit unions, according to Speer &AMP; Associates, an Atlanta
consulting firm. These companies include Electronic Data Systems,
the big computer services company, the Publix Supermarkets chain
and many smaller companies that have gone into business just to
provide ATMs. Many retailers own their own ATMs, but some merely
collect some fee from the ATMs that are stationed in their stores
but are owned by others.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco and Santa Monica laws allow these nonfinancial
institutions to levy the surcharges, under the theory that they do
not gain savings from having fewer tellers. The Connecticut rule,
however, bars surcharges on all machines. The New York ordinance
has not been drafted yet but could be similar to the California
ones.
</P>
<P>
   While consumer groups say that bank fees are well in excess of
what it costs for an ATM transaction, some bankers say they are
losing money on ATMs even with the surcharges. And they say
prohibiting surcharges will force closure of many ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the surcharge, there's no way a lot of off-premise
ATMs can be profitable,'' said Robert Litan, director of economic
studies at the Brookings Institution, who studied the matter for
the American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence on this question is mixed. Connecticut has only about
two-thirds of the number of ATMs per million people as the nation
as a whole, according to Bank Network News. But Iowa has almost as
many machines per capita as the nation as a whole and more than
some states that allow the surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   In their court case in San Francisco, Bank of America, Wells
Fargo and the California Bankers Association argue that local
ordinances are pre-empted by federal banking regulation. The Office
of the Comptroller of the Currency, a federal regulator, has
intervened in the case on the side of the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Banks have won decisions on these grounds in Iowa and
Connecticut, but the ban on surcharges in those states remains
while the decisions are being appealed. But a 1990 decision by the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which covers California and
other Western states, found that a federal law does allow some room
for states to regulate ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the surcharges say they favor the big banks under the
theory that consumers, to avoid the fees, will put their accounts
in banks that have the most machines. ``When a business can gain
customers by raising prices, that's not what competition is all
about,'' said Adam Radinsky, deputy city attorney for Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Some smaller banks and credit unions have pushed for free ATM
use or have banded together to offer free use to one another's
customers, to better compete with bigger banks. Still, many smaller
banks impose the surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Santa Monica, some people think the whole controversy is
overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Santa Monica is overstepping its rights trying to
impose business practices on the banks, and I think the banks are
being vindictive and hasty in trying to make a statement back to
the city of Santa Monica,'' said Katrina Osio, a 33-year-old
marketing director of an Internet company. ``I just think it's
childish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
