u i BC-CLINTON-TURKEY-HNS &LR;      11-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TURKEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRESSES TURKISH LEADERS ON HUMAN RIGHTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey _ President Clinton, savoring a series of foreign
policy victories Monday, pressed Turkish leaders on human rights
and reconciliation with Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The president began a five-day visit to this important
crossroads as diplomatic breakthroughs occurred on China trade
talks, Northern Ireland peace, payment of United Nations arrears
and new efforts to resolve the status of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   The White House moved quickly to claim the achievements for
Clinton, who hopes to craft a significant foreign policy legacy
during the final year of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've had a very good day in foreign policy,'' said
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The achievements come just a month after Clinton suffered his
biggest foreign policy defeat, the rejection by Senate Republicans
of the nuclear weapons test ban treaty. The embarrassing defeat
raised questions about Clinton's ability to conduct foreign policy
as a lame duck.
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide said one of the developments would have been a
victory but to have all four occur within 24 hours ``is
overwhelming.'' He suggested Clinton's critics should ``give him a
nod'' for those victories, contending those achievements dispute
the notion that the president is a powerless lame duck.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had announced new talks Dec. 3 between Turkish and Greek
Cypriots over the status of the Mediterranean island, long a source
of tensions been the two nations. After some confusions, those
talks will take place in New York under the auspices of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's foreign policy skills are being tested anew on
this trip to Turkey, part of a 10-day tour of southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   This republic, founded from the ashes of the Ottoman Empire
after World War I, lies at a geographic, religious and cultural
crossroads between Europe and Asia. The troubled nations of the
Balkans and the Middle East all sprang from the collapse of the
600-year-old Islamic empire, and the ancient conflicts are still
alive today.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Grand National Assembly, Clinton gently urged
the 550-member legislative chamber to do more on human rights,
citing the United States' own historic struggle with slavery and
race as part of a ``long journey'' worth making for a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When peaceful outlets exist to express normal human
differences, the peace is preserved, not shattered,'' Clinton said,
quoting Mustafa Kemal Ataturk, the founder of modern Turkey.
``Sovereignty should not be built on fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups criticize Turkey's record on torture and
beatings of dissidents and minorities such as the Kurds. President
Suleyman Demirel conceded torture exists but said it is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is torture,'' Demirel said during a news conference with
Clinton. ``But torture is not a state policy. Torture is a crime. I
can say that we are doing everything we can to make sure that there
is not torture.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also urged the assembly to reduce tensions in the Aegean
by reconciling with rival Greece. ``Believe me, I appreciate how
much history lies behind this troubled relationship. But people are
beginning to see the possibilities that can be created by a new and
better history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Clinton repeatedly took note of the
assistance Greece provided Turkey after a devastating Aug. 17
earthquake killed 17,000 people, and urged it to be used as an
opportunity to improve relations.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, a longtime Cold War ally of the United States because of
its proximity to the Soviet Union, awarded Clinton with its highest
state honor. Clinton also was the first foreigner to speak before
its National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an irony of history that we are on the edge of a new
millennium which will be shaped by unbelievable advances in
technology. But the biggest problem the world has is that
everywhere people are too much in the grip of the oldest difficulty
of human societies: We still are prone to fear people who are
different than ourselves,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will tour earthquake-damaged areas Tuesday and go
sightseeing Wednesday. On Thursday, a session opens in Istanbul for
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe. Clinton
also will visit Greece, Italy, Bulgaria, Macedonia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
