<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     11-15 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE ADULTS ARE MISSING FROM TENNIS TEEN WORLD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No more Steffi. No Monica this week, either. Just
when women's tennis was getting great, absent from its year-end
championships are the only players who have ever been great.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about sustained greatness, not the kind instantly
attached in our over-infomercialized, dot com world. Lindsay
Davenport and Martina Hingis and the Williams sisters are all
superb players, worthy successors. But without Steffi Graf and
Monica Seles on the Madison Square Garden carpet, the women's game
will not be nearly the showcase the promoters and the critics have
cranked it up to be.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so much the Graf-Seles rivalry, irreversibly altered by
a madman's knife, that the sport suddenly lacks. It's the contrast
of generations, the chronological tension. Graf took most of it
with her when she retired last summer. Seles, out of this
tournament with a stress fracture in her foot, just seems to be
doing a gradual fade, as opposed to taking a dramatic walk.
</P>
<P>
   When they played a riveting three-set match won by Graf here
last November, I remember thinking that she would never allow
herself to do as Seles has. Graf would never languish as a
professional quarterfinalist, unwilling to step out or do what it
takes to move up. After teaching Hingis to respect her elders
during their I-Want-Mommy French Open final, after falling a
victory short of the perfect ending at Wimbledon, Graf intuitively
knew she had done all she could with her eroding, 30-year-old body.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have no idea how much she was hurting the last couple
of years, how many trips to the hospital she made,'' said Jim Fuhse
of the Women's Tennis Association.
</P>
<P>
   Graf at least got all she could out of her game. In a sport
plagued by victimization, Seles has been the ultimate casualty. I
have rooted for her harder than I do for any other professional
athlete, yet by last September, by the time 17-year-old Serena
Williams was finished thrashing Hingis in the Arthur Ashe Stadium,
it was apparent that, in tennis years, the 25-year-old Seles was as
30-ish as Graf.
</P>
<P>
   Graf rounded 30 and headed home, without so much as a wave to
her beloved Wimbledon Center Court, without taking a farewell
stroke in New York City. Not one given to sentimental displays, she
was talked into a retirement ceremony at Bill Bradley's favorite
arena Tuesday night. All the players, I'm told, will be in on it.
Why not? The Garden may not be Center Court, but it is the center
of the city Graf once used as a safe haven from German fame.
</P>
<P>
   Jana Novotna will be here for the weekend, and I hope they'll
spare a few minutes for her as well. Novotna, who at 31 retired
with her one Wimbledon title, never did live up to her
serve-and-volley potential, but, as Fuhse said, ``Without Jana,
there are no more serve-and-volleyers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, as she survived her good cry on the
shoulder of the Duchess of Kent's shoulder after blowing a
Wimbledon final to Graf, Novotna had her own quiet charisma, a good
story to tell that began behind the Iron Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis needs people with personal tales that don't have to be
sanctioned by mom and dad. Teenagers may buy jeans pitched by Anna
Kournikova, who has won far more endorsements (the most of any
women's player) than tournaments (none). Adults still buy tickets
to tennis matches. Most adults probably aren't moved by the
hold-the-presses developments in tennis teen world, such as last
night's scoop that Hingis has dumped the service-challenged
Kournikova as her doubles partner.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it surprising that Graf and Novotna quit, while Seles
seems merely interested in giving herself something to do as she
decides where to go with her life. It's one thing to seize the
opportunity to school Hingis on a sunny June day in Paris. It's
another thing to engage a pack of mouthy teenagers week after
monotonous week.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe tennis could somehow do a better job making both its tours
more adult-friendly. That is not easily achieved for those who
begin training for their careers by first grade and, if eminently
successful, earn a fortune before their first date. It's a wonder
how Graf, who started on tour at 13, even mustered the tolerance to
sit through a few recent matches featuring Agassi, her new
post-tennis companion.
</P>
<P>
   She has left the tour in more capable and gifted hands than have
ever carried it before. Who knows where the family Williams can
take women's tennis in the coming years? Venus and Serena are just
kids, though, all fire and forehands. It's going to be a while
before a great mature player again defends the honor of being 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
