<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-FLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUMP IN MIAMI WITH MODEL AND PORTFOLIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ With a Slovenian supermodel on his arm, and claiming
that he could outspend anyone, including George W. Bush, in a
three-way race for the presidency, Donald Trump visited Miami on
Monday and reached out to the common man.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that because he has made billions of dollars from hard
work and smart investing he is more qualified to be president than
the sons of wealthy men who have never proven anything, Trump
stopped short of saying he planned to seek the Reform Party
nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   But if he does run, and if he wins that nomination, Trump said
he would have more to offer the American people than Bush or Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Although some commentators labeled Trump's visit here as his
first campaign trip, Trump said it was not a political event but
instead was a show of support for the United States' embargo of
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Trump, accompanied by his girlfriend, Melania Knauss, a
model who said he would make a fine president, sounded and looked
like a candidate as he made speeches and even, despite his
well-known aversion, shook hands around Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viva la libertad! Viva Donald Trump!'' chanted veterans of the
failed Bay of Pigs invasion of 1961, during Trump's visit to Little
Havana earlier in the day. Some of them pumped his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not something I'm in love with,'' he said later, ``but I do
it, and I'm satisfied with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a news conference near the airport, he sounded even
more like a candidate, as he compared his skills with those of Bush
and Gore, whom he described as ``annointed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched the misstatements and I've watched the
incompetence,'' he said at a news conference that, in typical Miami
flavor, switched from English to Spanish and back again.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in particular, he said, is merely riding the name and
connections of his father, former President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that makes them a better candidate than me,''
said Trump, a real estate and casino millionaire who is the son of
a successful businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they make billions in a short period of time? I don't think
so,'' he said. ``It's success,'' he said, when asked about his
credentials. ``Some people have a way of getting things done.''
</P>
<P>
   When Trump was asked if he could match the money being raised by
Bush, he said he could do better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need campaign contributions,'' Trump said, though he
said it was hard to turn down offers of honest contributions. And
if he does run, he said, ``I would spend whatever is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump, with his business connections and massive casino mailing
lists that could translate into Reform Party votes, is threatening
to shove aside Pat Buchanan as the Reform Party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wanted the Reform Party nomination, I think I'd get it,''
said Trump, who has referred to Buchanan as a ``Hitler lover.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump, a best-selling author, was asked if his threatened run
for the presidency was a ploy to sell real estate and books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need this to sell condos,'' he said. He also said he
did not need a political platform to sell books, then proceeded to
name the three books, by title, that he has written.
</P>
<P>
   Trump was also asked about his stand on abortion _ he finds it
personally distasteful but supports a woman's right to choose.
</P>
<P>
   But in Miami, there is only one issue that matters to many
people here _ at least politically: Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   On that issue, Trump made new friends. In his visit on Monday to
the Bay of Pigs Museum in Little Havana, Trump told about 30
veterans of that failed invasion that he supported the U.S. embargo
as a way to squeeze out Fidel Castro's dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   He was accompanied on his visit to the museum by Rep. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen, a Republican whose district includes Little Havana.
And while she welcomed Trump's strong stand on the embargo, Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen said she was supporting Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
