<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0773 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-REENACTMENT-COX     11-15 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-REENACTMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge says OK to reenactment of Branch Davidian siege
 &HT;    By Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ In what plaintiffs' attorneys in the Branch
Davidian civil lawsuit are calling a major victory, a federal judge
in Waco has ordered a demonstration designed to show whether
government agents fired into Mount Carmel on the final day of the
51-day siege with David Koresh and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. on Monday approved a
request from Special Counsel John Danforth for neutral experts to
conduct a simulation that would recreate government aerial infrared
surveillance tapes from April 19, 1993, to determine if bursts of
light on FBI videotapes are gunfire from federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Branch Davidian survivors, who challenged the
government to just such a demonstration last month, have alleged in
a wrongful-death lawsuit that government agents fired into the
compound during the inferno that claimed Koresh and 75 of his
followers.
</P>
<P>
   The government long has denied the accusations and would not
agree to participate in the testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be an overstatement in the least to say that the
plaintiffs have won a major victory today,'' said Mike Caddell, who
represents the majority of the Branch Davidian survivors. ``This is
something that we have been pressing for for weeks. We think this
is perhaps the major issue in the case because it touches on so
many other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In his three-page order, the judge gave attorneys on both sides
of the case 10 days to submit nominations for a neutral expert, who
will be chosen and retained by the court to conduct the experiment.
The judge also gave the parties a week to forward any objections or
suggestions to the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is basically a wholesale endorsement of essentially
our proposal, with Danforth's modifications to it,'' Caddell said.
``I think it is a very positive step. If you are interested in
getting at the truth, I don't know why you wouldn't embrace this
order by Judge Smith with open arms. And since the Department of
Justice is so interested in getting at the truth, I am sure they
will welcome his order.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said Monday that his
office still is reviewing the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have been invited by the court to respond,'' Marlin
said. ``All I can say is that we are still reviewing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he is absolutely convinced that government agents
fired into the compound on the final day because of studies by
plaintiffs' experts, some who are former government employees, who
reviewed the FBI's tapes from its Forward Looking Infrared (FLIR)
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Smith noted that his office has received a letter from
Danforth's office that indicates the FBI is willing to conduct a
re-creation of the FLIR activity for the office of special counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Deputy Special Counsel Edward L. Dowd Jr. notes, this could
result in two separate but simultaneous re-creations _ a nonpublic
one which the FBI authorizes and a public one which DOL
challenges,'' Smith wrote. ``The court is persuaded that one FLIR
test should be conducted, with participation and observation by the
parties and the OSC.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith ordered that the parties, including Danforth's office,
agree upon a written protocol that would best approximate the
conditions of April 19, 1993, including the make and model of the
FLIR equipment, the type of aircraft, altitude, weather conditions,
angle of the sun, types of weapons and rate of firing.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth was appointed by Attorney General Janet Reno in
September to investigate recent revelations in the Branch Davidian
controversy. He has said that the issue of government gunfire will
be among the ``dark questions'' his inquiry will seek to answer.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI contends that the flashes on the infrared tapes recorded
by its airplane were glints of sunlight on puddles of water, metal
or other debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this order further increases the chances that there
will never be a demonstration,'' Caddell said, ``because the truth
is everybody who is involved in this knows how that demonstration
is going to turn out. It increases the likelihood that wiser heads
at the FBI will prevail and say, 'OK, we admit that it is gunfire.'
If Reno and (FBI Director Louis) Freeh are going to have any
vestiges of credibility or authority or leadership left, they need
to admit that it was gunfire now instead of being forced to do so
by the court in this public demonstration.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlin said he would not comment on Caddell's accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Witherspoon writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
