<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: DRUG MAKER DISCLOSES DATA ABOUT PACT WITH PFIZER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In what is becoming one of the drug industry's
nastiest takeover battles, Warner-Lambert released some
confidential details on Monday of its agreement with Pfizer to
co-promote Lipitor, a successful cholesterol-lowering drug.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies had agreed in 1996 to co-promote Lipitor, a
drug that analysts predict could have worldwide sales of about $5
billion next year. The details of the Lipitor agreement between
Pfizer and Warner-Lambert had long intrigued analysts, because it
was unclear how much profit Pfizer was receiving from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   While the earnings split regarding Lipitor was not disclosed
Monday, the sales grid that Warner-Lambert released made it clear
how valuable Lipitor was to Pfizer's future performance.
</P>
<P>
   During the first five years of the agreement, Pfizer could
receive up to 48 percent of Lipitor's net sales in the United
States beyond a set amount. Analysts noted Monday that the totals
were relatively low during these years _ ranging from $208 million
in the contract's first year to $584 million in the fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert had announced a $72 billion merger with American
Home Products two weeks ago. That same day, Pfizer made an $80
billion takeover bid for Warner-Lambert. Since then, Warner-Lambert
and Pfizer have made much of their correspondence public, in part
to stir investor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   That trend continued Monday, when Lodewijk de Vink,
Warner-Lambert's chairman, sent a letter to William Steere Jr., the
chairman of Pfizer, noting that the details of their Lipitor
arrangement should be made public, including the gain to
Warner-Lambert and the loss to Pfizer should the agreement be
terminated.
</P>
<P>
   In another statement, Warner-Lambert reiterated that it was
considering canceling its co-promotional agreement with Pfizer
altogether, or at best, discontinuing it in 2002, after it came up
for review in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have now is a bare-knuckles fight,'' said Viren Mehta,
an analyst at Mehta Partners. ``Civility is a matter of the past.
What is clear from the Pfizer side is how they can get all of
Lipitor. The company will proceed with their hostile bid.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have questioned whether Pfizer miscalculated in
its attempt to take over Warner-Lambert, especially if the company
risks losing its take of the Lipitor revenue. Analysts appeared
confident Monday that Pfizer stood little chance of losing its
Lipitor revenue immediately. Pfizer has expressed even more
confidence in that respect.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer disputed Warner-Lambert's threat to cancel the agreement
over Lipitor immediately, noting that the only way that could
happen was for the company to break its original agreement on
Lipitor. Pfizer also said that it expected Warner-Lambert to renew
the agreement on Lipitor in 2002 because no other company has the
same marketing savvy or history with Lipitor as Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Monday that the public spats between Pfizer and
Warner-Lambert had just begun. One theory among analysts was that
Warner-Lambert released Lipitor's sales grid on Monday to show how
much was at risk for Pfizer if Warner-Lambert canceled their
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer had offered 2.5 of its shares for every Warner-Lambert
share. By contrast, American Home Products had offered 1.49 of its
shares. By the company's closing prices on Monday, Pfizer's offer
was worth $87 a share, compared with American Home Product's bid of
$83.25 a share.
</P>
<P>
   In order for Pfizer's takeover bid for Warner-Lambert to
succeed, analysts contend that it would have to increase its bid.
That would be difficult for Pfizer if the company's stock dropped
in the wake of negative news about Lipitor.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, investors are betting that the offers from
Pfizer and American Home Products are both too low.
Warner-Lambert's shares closed Monday at $92.75, down 87.5 cents.
The company's stock has increased 10.6 percent since it announced
its merger with American Home Products and Pfizer made a hostile
bid.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown between Pfizer and Warner-Lambert should continue
to heat up this week. Pfizer is holding a meeting with analysts on
Tuesday to review drugs it is working on. The company has been
criticized by some analysts as trailing many of its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The company may also put its spin on the Lipitor agreement. One
spokesman from Pfizer said Monday that the two companies' Lipitor
agreement had been so successful that there was no reason for
Warner-Lambert to end it out of spite.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Monday that they did not expect the public spats
between Pfizer and Warner-Lambert to harm the prices of drug
stocks. Pfizer's shares dropped 12.5 cents Monday, to close at $35
a share. Shares of American Home Products dipped 6 cents, to close
at $55.875.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember that this merger battle is like a
baseball game,'' said Neil Sweig, a pharmaceutical analyst with
Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. ``We're only in the early innings, but there's
plenty more to go. And it's already a donnybrook.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
