<HEADLINE>
SANCHEZ-VICARIO LOSES FAST TO AUSTRIA'S SCHETT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Austria, Spain)   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The legs do not churn and chug the way they used to,
a costly decline for a woman who made a reputation as her sport's
ultimate retriever and captured four Grand Slam titles and nearly
$15 million in prize money. Monday night at the Chase Championships
at Madison Square Garden, an event Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario has
appeared in 11 consecutive years yet barely squeaked into this
season, her stay was cut short by a Chase newcomer, Barbara Schett
of Austria.
</P>
<P>
   But the 16th-seeded Sanchez-Vicario, who had not anticipated
qualifying for singles and had not played a match in a month, did
not seem disheartened by her opening-round loss.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-seeded Schett, playing from the baseline and the net
with obvious ease while Sanchez-Vicario scrambled in the backcourt,
made a convincing Chase debut, winning by 6-1, 6-4 in just 61
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arantxa is not playing very powerful,'' Schett said about
Sanchez-Vicario, who held just four of her eight service games,
broke Schett only once and made 21 unforced errors, most of them on
her forehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I was not at my best, at all,'' Sanchez-Vicario
said. ``She's a talented player, and she did play much better than
me. I was missing a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sanchez-Vicario, rumors of her impending retirement
are premature. She hopes to survive the selection process a fourth
time and represent Spain in the Olympics next year.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a year ago that Sanchez-Vicario, whose
counterpunching had wavered before an onslaught of teenage power
players, made a surprise resurgence at the French Open, ending a
four-year Grand Slam title drought. But a left wrist injury kept
her out of action from mid-January to mid-March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
