<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Nov. 21) 
(jt) 
 By L.R. SHANNON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEALTH CARE ON THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   www.highwaytohealth.com
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that you are visiting a foreign country when a pain in
the back doesn't respond to aspirin, or your child shows signs of
an ear infection, or your spouse develops a fever. You don't speak
the language and you don't know the name of a doctor (or medecin or
medico).
</P>
<P>
   HighwaytoHealth, a Web service based in Radnor, Pa., is designed
to help you find, get and pay for medical care while traveling. For
an annual membership fee of $19, a traveler is covered around the
world for any number of trips. The service says more than 18,000
physicians in 80 some countries _ I didn't count them _ belong to
the network.
</P>
<P>
   Although you can explore the Web site, you can't see the names
and locations of the doctors or make an appointment until you
subscribe and select a user name and password.
</P>
<P>
   First, I tried Paris. After selecting ``medical doctor'' (you
can also choose dentist, physical therapist or sports medicine)
within five miles of where I was, I was presented with a map of
Paris. Next came a list of 10 doctors there whom I could see.
Wandering around, I found seven doctors in New Delhi, two in Buenos
Aires and one in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   You submit a request for a medical appointment to
HighwaytoHealth by e-mail or telephone. When one or more physicians
respond, the subscriber is sent the list to review and select the
best offer. The physicians have signed contracts with the service
agreeing to see subscribers if their schedule permits. The HTH call
center monitors the appointment requests, the company says, to make
sure they are answered, and will even try to schedule an
appointment with an independent doctor if there is none under
contract in your area.
</P>
<P>
   The site also offers City Health Profiles, health care
information for some 350 popular travel destinations and, for extra
cost, insurance meant to supplement your regular health plan when
traveling. Two insurance plans, offered through Worldwide Insurance
Services, are TravelGap Vacationer, insurance for one trip at $4.50
a day, and TravelGap Gold, a full year of coverage for $199. Of
course, the value of that insurance depends on the details of your
regular coverage, the procedure required and the country you are
visiting.
</P>
<P>
   HELP FOR NONMEMBERS
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to subscribe to HighwaytoHealth to use its City
Health Profiles. The information for each city covered is divided
into two parts. The first lists such things as emergency telephone
numbers, hospitals, clinics and pharmacies, health care at airports
and other general information. The second is detailed information
about things in the first.
</P>
<P>
   For Paris, there were emergency telephone numbers for ambulance,
police (you dial 17, not 911) and fire help, and for the American
Hospital of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   There were also numbers for the International Society of Travel
Medicine, and a link to its Web site, www.istm.org. It provides
news from the World Health Organization and the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-15-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
