<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0782 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-HONGKONG-$ADV2     11-15 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HONGKONG-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG IS HOPING DISNEY MAGIC RUBS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Nov. 21) 
(jt) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Ever since it was handed back to China in July 1997,
this former British colony has worried obsessively about what it
was going to become. Now, it has an answer: Hong Kong will be the
next outpost in the Disney empire.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Walt Disney Co. announced plans to build a theme
park here, its third outside the United States and second in Asia,
after Tokyo Disneyland. While it would be cynical to say that this
metropolis of 6.8 million will be defined by Mickey Mouse, it is
hard to overstate the impact that officials here believe a
Disneyland will have on Hong Kong's image and its tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of faded out of the spotlight after 1997, and
everybody wrote us off,'' said Mike Rowse, Hong Kong's tourism
commissioner. ``This project tells the world that we are alive and
kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   As the man who negotiated the $3.6 billion deal to bring Disney
to Hong Kong, Rowse is understandably keen to prove its worth. He
contends that Hong Kong Disneyland, which is to open in 2005, will
pump $19 billion into the economy over four decades, much of it
through a revived tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   Rowse said that the theme park would attract 1.4 million
additional visitors to Hong Kong in its first year, and 2.9 million
more annually by the time it is fully developed in 2020. If these
projections are accurate _ and the 17.5 million people a year who
visit Tokyo Disneyland suggest they might be _ the park would
reverse a steady erosion in tourist arrivals since the handover.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hong Kong drew 9.5 million visitors, an 8 percent
decline from 1997. Much of that can be attributed to the regional
economic crisis. But even before that, Hong Kong was becoming less
popular. In 1996, nearly 12 million people visited Hong Kong. Many
were eager for a last look at a British colonial outpost. Once the
Union Jack came down, the crowds went elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here note that the number of arrivals has rebounded 11
percent so far this year. But nobody disputes that Hong Kong needed
a jolt _ something to remind tourists that it is still probably the
most cosmopolitan city in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives said Hong Kong's international character was a
key reason they chose it over Shanghai and other mainland cities
that were lobbying to be the site of the first Chinese Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an incredibly exciting city,'' said Judson C. Green,
chairman of Disney's theme-park division. ``It always has been,
irrespective of the financial crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said Disney was also attracted by Hong Kong's
infrastructure. With a spectacular year-old airport and a gleaming
network of roads, railways, tunnels and bridges, Hong Kong is one
of Asia's easiest cities to get to and get around in. The site for
the proposed Disneyland is in a quiet bay on Lantau Island,
conveniently midway between central Hong Kong and the airport and
not far from a high-speed train that connects the two.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Magic Kingdoms, the park will have shops, restaurants
and theaters _ some with an Asian flavor. It will also have three
or four hotels, with a total of 2,100 rooms. Although the hotels
could compete with those in Kowloon or central Hong Kong, few
hoteliers seem worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a boon for all the hotels, because it will put Hong
Kong back on the map,'' said Robert Hutchinson, former group
director of marketing at Shangri-La Hotels and Resorts, a leading
Asian chain.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said that business people traveling to Hong Kong
would have an incentive to bring their families; they could stay in
the city for a week, then tack on an extra couple of days at a
Disney hotel.
</P>
<P>
   To be successful, Hong Kong's Disneyland will also have to
attract millions of visitors from mainland China. Officials here
said that they planned to work with Beijing to streamline the visa
procedures. With opening day five years away, officials are
confident of reaching an accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Disneyland is poised to draw more Chinese visitors to
Hong Kong, some people here fret that it will rob the city of its
Chinese character. Disney's goal in Hong Kong _ as in Paris and
Tokyo _ is to create an idealized version of America that pays
little heed to the folkways of the host country.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, what makes a city great is its ethnic
identity,'' said David Tang, the founder of Shanghai Tang, a
boutique that sells pricey clothing with a retro-Mao flavor, mostly
to tourists. ``This is a Chinese city. We have to cultivate these
Chinese elements.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tang is a lonely dissenter. After years of worrying about
its future _ fears that were compounded by the Asian crisis _ Hong
Kong seems willing to bear the cultural baggage of Disney so long
as it brings the crowds back. Besides, people here are used to
foreign powers with global ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
