NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 16
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Nov. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Nov. 9,
about an American who faces 10 years in prison for a car accident
in the former Soviet republic of Georgia, in which his interpreter
died, misstated the position of the State Department. The
department says it has never maintained that the jailing of the
American, Loren Wille, was a retaliation for that of a Georgian
diplomat, Gueorgui Makharadze, who killed a teenager in Washington
in 1997 in a drunken-driving accident.
</P>
<P>
   The report also misstated the circumstances surrounding the loss
of Mr. Makharadze's diplomatic immunity. It was lifted by the
Georgian Embassy so that he could face criminal charges arising
from the accident; it was not waived after his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BUSH-AUTOBIOGRAPHY (moved on Sunday, Nov. 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Nov. 14,
about ``A Charge to Keep,'' an autobiography by George W. Bush,
misidentified the owner of its publisher, William Morrow &AMP; Company.
Morrow is an imprint of HarperCollins, not part of the Hearst
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Nov. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Nov.
10, about the i-Opener computer, misstated the manufacturer's name,
as did a correction of the Web address, in this space on Friday.
The company is Netpliance Inc., not -NetPliance.com; its Web site
is www.netpliance.net/, not www.netpliance.com.
</P>
