<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE BEGINS CASE FOR THIRD SUSPECT IN DRAGGING DEATH 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The last of three white men to be tried in last
year's dragging death of James Byrd Jr. could have gotten the black
man's blood on his clothing the day after the killing while
watching someone else clean a bloody chain at the local car wash, a
defense expert testified Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Paulette Sutton, a forensic serologist at the University of
Tennessee in Memphis, told jurors in Shawn Berry's capital murder
trial that specks of Byrd's blood found on the defendant's jeans,
shirt and boots were not consistent with a beating, but could be
explained by an experiment she conducted at a carwash.
</P>
<P>
   First she stuffed a pair of used jeans with rolls of paper
towels to simulate a person's legs and hung them with bungee cords
at a car wash. Sutton then sprayed water on a 12-foot length of
chain that she had painted the night before with two teaspoons of
human blood.
</P>
<P>
   The faint stains she created as the blood-tinted water
ricocheted off the chain and onto the bluejeans matched a
photograph of the stains on Berry's jeans, she said. Sutton also
said she was wearing a pair of boots at the car wash and got water
spray on her boots consistent with stains on Berry's boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blood was splashing onto an observing individual,'' Sutton
testified, adding that she had been told that Berry had accompanied
co-defendant Bill King to a Jasper carwash and was standing nearby
as King washed off a 24-foot logging chain that had been used to
drag Byrd to his death early on June 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray, who contends
that Berry actively participated in chaining Byrd to the back of
his pickup and was driving the truck that dragged Byrd more than
three miles, challenged the validity of Sutton's experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Besides questioning the methodology, the prosecutor forced her
to concede that she used a different brand of jeans than Berry was
wearing the night of the killing, a different chain and a different
car wash.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the victim's sisters _ one a science teacher and the
other a lab technician _ weren't buying the testimony either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her experiments so far are not scientifically sound, and
anyone in the scientific community will tell you,'' Clara Taylor
said outside the courthouse. ``You have to have a controlled
experiment and all the conditions have to be exactly the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton was one of 20 witnesses to take the stand Monday as
Berry's lawyer, Joseph C. ``Lum'' Hawthorn, began his defense.
Sixteen of those witnesses, including two black people and one of
mixed race, testified that Berry was not a racist, that he had
several African-American friends and that he had cried at the
funeral of a black man he had worked with at a local tire shop.
</P>
<P>
   Berry is expected to testify today. If convicted by the
all-white jury, Berry would face either life in prison or join his
two co-defendants, white supremacists Russell Brewer Jr., 32, and
King, 25, on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Berry's girlfriend, Christy Marcontell, took the
stand to explain her tumultuous relationship with the defendant and
to say that she had lied or exaggerated when she signed two police
statements in October 1997 and in May 1998 complaining that Berry
had assaulted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Shawn enjoyed fighting,'' she testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn Berry has never punched me. He has never done anything
like that or I wouldn't be sitting there by his side,'' added
Marcontell, who has been sitting at the defense table throughout
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Assistant U.S. Attorney Brit Featherston,
who is assisting with the prosecution, asked Marcontell which of
her stories the jury should believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lied to police two times, but I'm up here under oath and I'm
not going to lie,'' she said. ``This police report right here is
not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, outside the courthouse, Marcontell told reporters she was
embarrassed that she had to air the couple's dirty laundry on the
witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had absolutely nothing to do with this,'' she said. ``What
is relevant to this case is what happened out on Huff Creek Road.''
</P>
<P>
   It was on Huff Creek Road that police found Byrd's decapitated
body, outside a rural black cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Beaumont, Texas, psychiatrist Edward Gripon
also downplayed the couple's problems, dismissing Marcontell's
complaints as minor incidents of domestic violence that did not
result in serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   Gripon admitted under cross-examination that Berry would have
been aware that King and Brewer were violent racists because they
talked constantly about starting a race war and because their arms
had been blackened with racist tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   He described Berry's decision to offer a ride to a black man in
the middle of the night with two Klansmen in the truck and then
drive him to a remote wooded area ``relatively poor judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Relatively poor judgment, doctor?'' Gray repeated
sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   And Gray challenged Gripon's contention that Berry had been
paralyzed in fear at the crime scene and when he lied in his first
statement to police because he was worried about retaliation from
King and Brewer. In that statement, Gray pointed out, Berry had
pointed the finger at the other two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't he drop them in the grease in the first statement?''
the prosecutor asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gripon conceded that Berry may have lied ``in an attempt at
self-preservation and damage control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
