<HEADER>
A0794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FOX-APPOINT-ART-600&AMP;A     11-15 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOX-APPOINT-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF FOX TV STUDIO GETS NEW NETWORK POST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox Inc. named Sandy Grushow, already president of its
television production studio, to the newly created position of
chairman of Fox Television Entertainment Group on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The move puts Grushow in charge of both the prime-time schedule
on the Fox network and many of the most important shows on the
schedules of competing networks.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment added a further entanglement to what is becoming
a complex series of interlocking business interests within the
television industry. Most of the networks are now part of much
larger entertainment entities and all are seeking to combat rising
program costs and declining revenue by taking advantage of the
opportunities created by holding complementing assets. Studios like
Walt Disney and Fox are increasingly producing shows for their own
networks.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox's production arm, 20th Television, is the largest
supplier of programs in the television business, with 20 series
spread out across five networks. In addition to eight shows on the
Fox network, the Fox studio produces such hits as ``The Practice''
and ``Dharma and Greg'' for ABC, ``Judging Amy'' and ``Chicago
Hope'' for CBS, ``Stark Raving Mad'' for NBC and ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' for WB.
</P>
<P>
   While Grushow said he would keep the interests of the studio and
the interests of the network ``operating totally independently,''
some industry executives suggested that his promotion could
complicate his relationships with competing networks.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had already stirred some confusion and resistance in the
network television industry with its decision last summer to
combine the operations of its studio and the network entertainment
division under two executives, Lloyd Braun and Stu Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   Grushow said Monday that ``This is not the ABC model.'' He said
that instead of combining operations, Fox intended to keep the
studio and network decision-making separate, even though both
divisions will report directly to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe for a second that there is going to be any
reason for anyone to worry about divided loyalties,'' Grushow said.
``That's the easy and obvious argument, but I just don't believe
there's any justification for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in contrast to ABC's stated chief intention for
combining the studio and network operations _ to ensure that more
ABC-owned shows get onto the network's schedule _ Fox had no plan
to change its strategy for its studio, which involves producing the
most shows possible for as many networks as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to do anything to put a multibillion-dollar
business at risk,'' Grushow said. ``If one of our writers comes to
us with an idea that is best suited to a network other than Fox,
that show will be going to that network.''
</P>
<P>
   But the double responsibilities of studio and network do create
potentially unusual situations for Grushow. For example, last
spring he pushed hard at NBC for a new comedy, ``Stark Raving
Mad,'' to win that network's most coveted time slot, Thursday at
9:30 p.m. _ which it did. Now he will be in the position of trying
to find the right show on the Fox network to compete with ``Stark
Raving Mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Grushow said he would step back a bit from leading the effort to
place Fox studio shows at other networks by naming a new president
of the studio. ``I expect that person will come from inside the
studio,'' he said. ``And he will be the principal salesman for the
shows. But I expect I'll get on the phone a lot to endeavor to get
our shows placed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Grushow's arrival at the network also complicates the role of
Doug Herzog, the president of Fox Entertainment, who joined Fox
only a year ago after leaving his position as president of the
Comedy Central cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about Herzog's future have run through Hollywood this
fall. Fox got off to a woeful start this television season, with
virtually all its new shows failing and its slow introduction of
original episodes of series questioned throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Grushow said Monday that Herzog would stay on and would remain
in charge of the day-to-day operations of the network's
entertainment division. He said Herzog had been in the job only 10
months and had been ``unfairly ridiculed for what's gone on at Fox
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation at the network, Grushow said, is bad enough that
he expects initially it will demand more of his time than his work
at the studio.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog said he was comfortable with Grushow's appointment,
saying, ``Look, we can use the help.'' He added, ``Things move fast
at Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   Herzog had reported to Peter Chernin, the president of News
Corp., parent of Fox. Chernin said Monday that he made the decision
to place Herzog under Grushow essentially to help out Herzog.
</P>
<P>
   ``This did not have anything to do with lack of support for
Doug,'' Chernin said. ``I think he's done a pretty good job.'' But
he acknowledged that adding the network to Grushow's
responsibilities had little to do with needs at the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume it will be good for the studio, but to be blunt, that
was not the issue here,'' Chernin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
