<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; TRADE _  &LR;  With a handshake and a clink of champagne glasses, U.S.
and Chinese negotiators finally came to terms yesterday on a
breakthrough agreement that paves the way for China to enter the
World Trade Organization. Under the accord, reached after six days
of marathon talks in Beijing, China has agreed to cut tariffs on
agricultural and industrial goods and allow easier market access
for U.S. financial institutions, insurers and telecommunications
firms. By David Lazarus
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MICROSOFT &LR;  _ So, what are you going to do about your Microsoft
stock?
</P>
<P>
   The software colossus seems highly vulnerable in the wake of the
withering denunciation by federal Judge Thomas P. Jackson of its
``monopolistic'' business practices. However, its fate remains
uncertain, pending Jackson's final verdict in the federal
government's antitrust case. Barring an out-of-court settlement
between Microsoft and the government, Jackson is expected to render
a verdict in favor of the government early next year and to mete
out stiff penalties. He may order the company broken up into three
or more pieces. Or, he may leave the company intact but impose
draconian restrictions on its business practices that will
drastically slow its tremendous growth. Microsoft's fate is
important not only to people who own the stock directly, but also
to millions of mutual fund investors and pension-plan beneficiaries
who own it indirectly. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MONEYBAG  &LR; _ Income rules for switching to Roth IRA. By Arthur M.
Louis
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CYGNUS _ &LR;  After striking it rich with a multibillion-dollar IPO
this summer, Red Hat Inc. is now using its highly valued stock to
acquire other companies. By Tom Stein
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SCHWAB _  &LR;  Three of the nation's largest online stock brokers and
three well-known Menlo Park venture capital firms are forming an
investment bank that will specialize in funneling new high-tech
stocks to online investors. The new firm, which has yet to be
named, will be based in Silicon Valley and plans to start
underwriting and distributing shares of information technology and
Internet companies early next year. Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. of San
Francisco, TD Waterhouse Group of New York and Ameritrade Holding
Corp. of Omaha are investing in the enterprise and will be
exclusive sellers of all equity securities underwritten by the new
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CHRONICLE _  &LR;  Nion McEvoy, the great-grandson of San Francisco
Chronicle founder M.H. de Young, yesterday bought specialty
publisher Chronicle Books from his fellow family members for an
undisclosed sum. McEvoy, 47, already the editor in chief and a
13-year employee of Chronicle Books, said he was pleased to keep
the San Francisco company in the family as other assets of
Chronicle Publishing are sold to outside corporations. By Dan Fost
</P>
