<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-CHRONICLE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Chronicle Books Remains All In the Family  &HT;     By Dan Fost  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Nion McEvoy, the great-grandson of San Francisco Chronicle founder
M.H. de Young, yesterday bought specialty publisher Chronicle Books
from his fellow family members for an undisclosed sum.
<P>
   McEvoy, 47, already the editor in chief and a 13-year employee
of Chronicle Books, said he was pleased to keep the San Francisco
company in the family as other assets of Chronicle Publishing are
sold to outside corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it became clear to me that the family was planning to
sell all the assets of the publishing company, I felt very strongly
about wanting to continue my involvement with this one,'' McEvoy
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Chronicle Publishing said it sold television
station KRON, but it did not identify the buyer. The station, San
Francisco's NBC affiliate, was the subject of intense interest from
NBC's parent, General Electric, as well as from News Corp., Gannett
Co., Young Broadcasting and several other media companies.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Books employs about 130 people and publishes more than
300 books per year, in addition to maintaining an extensive
backlist of more than 1,000 books. It has three divisions _ adult,
children and gift _ and publishes books in such subjects as food,
photography, art, architecture, interior design, gardening, pop
culture and fiction.
</P>
<P>
   In buying Chronicle Books, McEvoy said he was happy to keep the
small press independent in the face of publishing industry
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it great is its independent spirit,'' McEvoy said.
If a large New York publishing conglomerate had bought the company,
``it would have been the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other publicly announced bidder for the firm was Leo J.
Hindery, who had recently left his post as head of AT&AMP;T Corp.'s
broadcast and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery's entry presented an intriguing twist: Hindery, the
former chief financial officer of Chronicle Publishing, was bidding
against McEvoy, who sits on the board of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McEvoy recused himself from all deliberations relating to
Chronicle Books and had to out-bid Hindery for the property. ``Nion
was put through the hoops like he was any other bidder,'' said John
B. Sias, chairman and chief executive of Chronicle Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Books had an estimated value of about $40 million. The
sales price was not disclosed, but the deal was at least $15
million, as it is subject to federal Department of Justice
antitrust review, Sias said.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery, 51, of Hillsborough was traveling and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy said, ironically enough, Hindery had encouraged him to
join Chronicle Books 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy does not plan any major changes in the company. ``Right
at the moment, it ain't broke,'' McEvoy said. ``I want to keep it
the dynamic and innovative company that it is today and explore all
the opportunities that our independence affords us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said company President Jack Jensen will would  &LR; remain in that
position.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy recalled joining Chronicle Books ``in 1986, when there
were only 15 of us and we were only doing 25 books a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded in 1968 by former Chronicle executive
Phelps Dewey, and although it was one of the smaller units of
Chronicle Publishing, it was a moneymaker money-maker  &LR; and a source
of pride.
</P>
<P>
   The de Young descendants voted earlier this year to sell all
assets of Chronicle Publishing, starting with the 134-year-old
flagship, The San Francisco Chronicle, which was sold to Hearst
Corp. That sale is pending federal review.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy, a former attorney with the William Morris Agency, noted
that his own publishing history extends not only to his de Young
roots, but also on his paternal side: His father, Dennis McEvoy,
who died in 1982, was an executive with Readers Digest magazine,
launching the Japanese and Spanish editions of the magazine and
working with such writers as James A. Michener. In addition, his
grandfather, J.P. McEvoy, was a playwright who also worked for the
Ziegfield Follies and wrote dialogue for W.C. Fields and Shirley
Temple movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
