<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SCGWAB </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Brokers, VC Firms Team Up  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Three of the nation's largest online stock brokers and three
well-known Menlo Park venture capital firms are forming an
investment bank that will specialize in funneling new high-tech
stocks to online investors.
<P>
   The new firm, which has yet to be named, will be based in
Silicon Valley and plans to start underwriting and distributing
shares of information technology and Internet companies early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. of San Francisco, TD Waterhouse Group of
New York and Ameritrade Holding Corp. of Omaha are investing in the
enterprise and will be exclusive sellers of all equity securities
underwritten by the new investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The other financial partners _ Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers,
Trident Capital and Benchmark Capital _ will help steer startups to
the new underwriting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ryles, who resigned as head of technology investment
banking for Merrill Lynch two weeks ago, will serve as chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new firm will be designed to respond to online investor
demand for new issues, which to date has not been fully satisfied
by the traditional offering process,'' said Ryles. Most traditional
equity underwriters allocate scarce shares of hot IPOs to large
institutional clients like mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Although many customers of online brokerages own shares in
high-tech companies, Ryles noted they ``generally have not been
able to participate fully in the initial public offering process.''
Instead, they buy shares, often at inflated prices, once trading
begins.
</P>
<P>
   The average gain for 438 IPOs that have gone public this year is
a whopping 125 percent, according to IPO Monitor. And the biggest
gains often occur on the first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer demand is just huge,'' said Schwab Chief Strategy
Officer Dan Leemon. Schwab has distributed about 10 million shares
in 73 IPOs this year, and Leemon said it could easily have sold
several times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab began exploring the creation of an investment bank in the
summer and decided it would have more clout working with other
underwriters if it teamed up with other large online brokers.
Schwab recruited TD Waterhouse and Ameritrade, which together serve
4.5 million active online investor accounts (more than 50 percent
of the total) with nearly $750 billion in combined customer assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know our customers, and the investment managers we serve
want a bigger share of the IPO pie,'' said Schwab President David
Pottruck. TD Waterhouse President Frank Petrilli added, ``We are
excited to be part of a venture that fundamentally changes the IPO
process and recognizes individual investors as the powerful force
that they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides offering shares in IPOs, the new investment bank plans
to provide research to individual and institutional investors and
eventually sell them late-stage investments in private companies.
</P>
<P>
   The new investment bank is not alone in going after the online
market. Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette distributes some IPO shares
through its DLJDirect unit, and online broker E-Trade Group of
Menlo Park has invested in an online investment bank called
EOffering.
</P>
<P>
   Ryles said one of the goals of both the brokerage and venture
capital backers of the new investment bank is to allocate shares to
customers who plan to hold on to the stock rather than ``flip'' it
for a quick profit.
</P>
<P>
   By better assessing online demand for new shares, the investment
bank and issuers should also be able to to do a better job pricing
new shares.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
