<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYGNUS-CYGNUS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Red Hat Juggles Executives While Picking Up Cygnus  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
After striking it rich with a multibillion-dollar IPO this summer,
Red Hat Inc. is now using its highly valued stock to acquire other
companies.
<P>
   Red Hat, the leading distributor of Linux software, said
yesterday that it will buy privately held Cygnus Solutions of
Sunnyvale for about $697.6 million in stock. Cygnus makes tools
used by computer programmers to create software applications for
the Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement yesterday, Red Hat said chief
executive Bob Young is stepping aside and will be replaced by the
company's current chief operating officer, Matthew Szulik. Young
will stay on as chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat of Durham, N.C., became an instant Wall Street darling
when it went public in August. The stock price shot up from $14, to
as high as $135, in its first few weeks of trading before leveling
off at about $100. Red Hat shares climbed $3.56, to $105.38, in
trading yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat now has a market capitalization of $7.3 billion. Not bad
for a company that has yet to make a profit and that had revenue of
just $10.8 million for the fiscal year ended February 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Linux operating system is widely perceived as a possible
threat to Microsoft's Windows software, which today runs the vast
majority of desktop computers. Unlike Windows, Linux is an
open-source software program that is available free to users.
However, Linux currently is suitable only for users with
considerable technical know-how, while Windows is marketed for
average PC owners. Red Hat, and a handful of other companies, make
money by providing support and services to businesses using Linux.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition of Cygnus, Red Hat picks up valuable
engineering talent and a workforce of 181 employees. Red Hat
anticipates no layoffs and expects to have a total head count of
more than 400 workers once the deal closes.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Cygnus is subject to regulatory approval and is
expected to close on January Jan.  &LR; 27.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also gives Red Hat a strategic toehold toe-hold  &LR; in the
so-called post-PC world. That's because Cygnus software is used in
such products as wireless phones, handheld computers and other
Internet devices.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, shipments of these appliances are expected to outstrip
shipments of personal computers, according to International Data
Corp. Unlike the Windows advantage monopoly &LR;   &LR; in personal
computers, there is no dominant operating system for these new
devices.
</P>
<P>
   George Weiss, an analyst with the Gartner Group, thinks the deal
makes a lot of sense but worries that Red Hat may be positioned to
grow big and mean at the expense of such Linux competitors as
Caldera Systems, Suse and Turbo Linux.
</P>
<P>
   ``The open-source movement is based on the principles of sharing
and giving back to the community,'' he said. ``But Red Hat needs to
make more acquisitions and get larger to justify its high
valuation.'' He believes the company may run into trouble _ and
incur the disdain of developers _ as it tries to reconcile these
opposing forces.
</P>
<P>
   As for Red Hat's management shuffle, the official line is that
Bob  &LR; Young will remain deeply involved in the company and will
continue to play an important role in promoting Red Hat and the
entire Linux movement.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said Young does not have the full confidence of
Wall Street and lacks key leadership qualities. By contrast, new
CEO Matthew  &LR; Szulik has a proven track record, having held
executive positions at five software companies. ``Red Hat needs
more seasoned, professional leadership as it moves from a startup
to a financially viable organization,'' said Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
