<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Income Rules For Switch To Roth 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: My wife is approaching age 701/2, when she must begin taking
distributions from her traditional individual retirement account.
The IRA contains almost $24,500, all of it taxable. Rather than
take distributions, she would like to convert the account to a Roth
IRA, which would mean declaring the $24,500 as income (and paying
the tax). However, this looks like a Catch-22 situation. We have a
substantial income already, and the additional $24,500 would push
us above $100,000, which is the highest permissible amount for
people making IRA conversions. Do they make an exception in cases
like ours to let us do a rollover anyway?
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   The amount you want to roll over to a Roth IRA is excluded from
your income from salary, interest and dividends, capital gains,
pensions and the like in calculating whether you are eligible for a
rollover, says Bob Meyer, assistant technical coordinator with the
Internal Revenue Service's Northern California district. ``You
could even roll over a million dollars or more,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   However, if your wife doesn't act soon and is forced to take
distributions before she rolls over her IRA, the distributions must
be figured in with the rest of your income. If a distribution
pushes you above $100,000, you won't be eligible to do a rollover
that year.
</P>
<P>
   The Roth's creator, U.S. Sen. Senator  &LR; William V. Roth Jr.,
R-Del., wanted distributions excluded from the income calculation.
He hoped to give a break to IRA holders who _ through no fault of
their own _ already had reached age 701/2. But he had to back off
because the federal bean counters said such an exemption in the
early years of the Roth program would cause a significant budget
squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has decreed that distributions no longer will affect
your eligibility for a rollover starting Jan. 1, 2005.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
When Not to Pay Taxes
</P>
<P>
   Q: My income is primarily from Social Security disability
insurance and a private disability insurance policy. Neither is
taxable. However, I own shares of a mutual fund that pays out
capital gains from time to time. Also, I recently sold $2,000 worth
of shares at a capital gain to have more cash on hand. My question:
Do I have to pay taxes on my capital gains?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: That depends on the size of your gains, your age, your
marital status and whether you are filing a separate or joint
return.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to pay taxes if your income, apart from the
nontaxable disability payments, is greater than the sum of your
exemptions plus either the standard deduction or your total
itemized deductions _ whichever is greater.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, you won't even have to file a return if your
income is less than the exemption plus the standard deduction. For
single people under age 65, the income cutoff for filing a return
next April is $7,050; for those 65 and older, the cutoff is $8,100.
</P>
<P>
   For married couples filing jointly, the cutoffs are: $12,700
with both spouses under 65; $13,550 with one spouse under 65;
$14,400 with both spouses 65 or older.
</P>
<P>
   You are correct in stating that your Social Security disability
payments are tax-free. However, if your private policy was provided
by your employer, the benefits are not exempt from taxes. But if
you bought the policy yourself, then the benefits cannot be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Tardiness Costing Money
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been investing in my company's 401(k) plan for the
past two years. We have a choice of funds through the T. Rowe Price
mutual-fund group. I am paid biweekly, and my 401(k) payment is
automatically deducted. Since the beginning of the year, I have
been checking my balance every day, and I have noticed that my
contributions were showing up in my account at irregular intervals
_ sometimes as early as the day I am paid, other times as much as
four business days later. According to my calculations, I have lost
money this way because the fund prices have tended to rise during
the periods when my contributions were delayed. What can I do about
this?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: T. Rowe Price spokesman Todd Remert says the fund group
``makes every attempt to get 401(k) contributions invested on the
day we receive the money.'' Generally speaking, that will be the
same day you are paid because standard procedure is for employers
to wire the money to Price.
</P>
<P>
   If there have been delays, Remert says, it might be that your
employer caused them.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility, he says, is that your plan has ``unique
procedures'' that make occasional delays inevitable. For example:
``An employer might be processing payrolls from multiple locations
across the country, and it may have asked us to wait to invest
until we've received all the money.''
</P>
<P>
   You should ask your employer if it can explain the delays. You
also should call T. Rowe Price at (800) 638-5660. Give them the
name of your employer, and discuss your plight. Remert promises
that Price will check it out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
