<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0803 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT_S     11-15 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Legal Limbo Mires Microsoft Stock  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
So, what are you going to do about your Microsoft stock?
<P>
   The software colossus seems highly vulnerable in the wake of the
withering denunciation by federal Judge Thomas P. Jackson of its
``monopolistic'' business practices.
</P>
<P>
   However, its fate remains uncertain, pending Jackson's final
verdict in the federal government's antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an out-of-court settlement between Microsoft and the
government, Jackson is expected to render a verdict in favor of the
government early next year and to mete out stiff penalties.
</P>
<P>
   He may order the company broken up into three or more pieces.
Or, he may leave the company intact but impose draconian
restrictions on its business practices that will drastically slow
its tremendous growth.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's fate is important not only to people who own the
stock directly, but also to millions of mutual fund investors and
pension-plan beneficiaries who own it indirectly.
</P>
<P>
   The stock is nearly ubiquitous in professionally managed
portfolios. It is owned by more than 2,000 institutions, which
among them hold nearly close to  &LR; 2 billion of its 5 billion shares
_ about $175 billion worth.
</P>
<P>
   Only this month, Microsoft became one of the 30 stocks in the
widely watched Dow Jones industrial average. That means a weak
performance by Microsoft will drag on the indicator that many
people consider ``the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Microsoft's stock has been a tepid performer
since the judge issued his ``findings of fact'' after the stock
market closed on November 5.
</P>
<P>
   While most technology stocks have been on a tear _ the
tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index has risen 3.8 percent in that
brief span _ Microsoft is down 5 percent, closing yesterday at $87.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of the software giant's principal business
adversaries have been particularly strong since November 5.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems, Apple Computer, International Business
Machines and Red Hat _ all of which produce computer operating
systems that compete, or try to compete, with Microsoft _ have
enjoyed nice run-ups.
</P>
<P>
   So have Oracle, second to Microsoft in applications software,
and America Online, owner of Netscape, which produces the
second-most-popular Internet browser, after Microsoft's Internet
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   If you had put equal amounts of money into each of those six
stocks on November 5, you would be sporting a handsome 8 percent
gain as of yesterday's market close.
</P>
<P>
   If you own Microsoft and the company's plight worries you _ but
you want to remain invested in high technology _ you might consider
selling at least part of your holdings. You could then invest the
proceeds in other strong, prominent technology companies with
clearer prospects _ particularly competitors that stand to benefit
most if Microsoft bogs down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's management is going to have to alter their
decision process,'' predicts Stewart J. Pillette of Pillette
Investment Management in San Francisco. However the legal chips may
fall, he says, it seems likely that Microsoft will be less able to
``bulldoze'' the competition in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't own Microsoft stock, it might be advisable to avoid
it for a while, because uncertainty usually puts a damper on a
stock's performance. At some point, the company's legal problems
may drive the stock so low that it becomes a screaming buy _ but
that doesn't seem to have happened yet.
</P>
<P>
   Another choice would be to hedge your bet by investing in a
predominantly high-tech index, such as the Nasdaq 100, which
includes Microsoft and many of its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   There are several mutual funds that track this index _ or, you
can buy shares in the Nasdaq-100 Trust, which trades as a stock on
the American Stock Exchange under the symbol QQQ. The trust's
shares closed yesterday at $144.09 _ up 5.7 percent since November
5.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's moderately weak stock-market performance in recent
days reflects the consensus evaluation of the perils the company
faces. What the consensus seems to say is that the future looks
unpleasant for Microsoft, but not necessarily disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Market experts interviewed by The Chronicle stress that
Microsoft is one of the great corporate juggernauts in business
history, full of talented people on both the technology and
financial sides. Even broken into pieces, they say, it will remain
a great and profitable force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can just say that Microsoft is done for,''
says Scott Marcouiller, a vice president and analyst with A.G.
Edwards &AMP; Son in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Acuff, market strategist with Salomon Smith Barney in
New York, says Microsoft's outlook is ``fundamentally quite good.''
He says the Windows 2000 launch, scheduled for February, ``probably
will be one of the most successful product launches in the history
of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also will be buoyed by continuing, strong technology
trends, Acuff believes. ``The Internet is probably going to expand
substantially in the next few years, and certainly Microsoft will
be one of the beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that Microsoft's fate could remain uncertain for
years. Whatever the judge may finally rule, the company is likely
to appeal, and the appeals process could last two years or more.
</P>
<P>
   However, some experts think Microsoft will negotiate a
settlement, rather than submit further to Judge  &LR; Jackson's tender
mercies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge's statement was so severe, there's just no question
that Microsoft is highly motivated to come to a settlement,'' says
Gail Seneca of GMG Seneca Capital Management in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts disagree, feeling that Microsoft's notoriously
combative management will never voluntarily agree to restrictions
on its strategies and tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see a settlement myself,'' says Peter Ausnit, an
analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan in San Francisco. ``The judge seems
to want to stop them from adding significant features and functions
to their operating system. They fundamentally believe that if they
don't innovate, they will be left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects Microsoft to grit its teeth until the judge hands
down the verdict and sentence, then fight tooth and nail in the
appeals courts.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the most radical punishment the judge is likely to
impose would be to break up Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, one likely scenario would be to split it into
three companies, centered around Microsoft's operating systems,
applications (such as Microsoft Office) and consumer products/Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Any such ruling would rank right up there with the most
momentous antitrust breakups of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup of Standard Oil produced several large, independent
oil companies, among them San Francisco's San &LR;  Francisco-based
 &LR; Chevron. The breakup of American Telephone and Telegraph gave
birth to the so-called Baby Bells.
</P>
<P>
   Breakups, as those examples suggest, aren't necessarily bad.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Standard Oil and AT&AMP;T, they turned out to be
hugely profitable for shareholders. Free to innovate and flourish
on their own, the liberated parts of those monopolies collectively
became worth more than the whole.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a breakup, the most valuable pieces of Microsoft would
still be around, with a potential to continue earning humongous
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of how a breakup might occur,'' says Seneca,
``there is no question that the real moneymaker for Microsoft has
been its software products, primarily its Windows operating system.
The operating system would continue to operate, no matter where.''
</P>
<P>
   The greater danger for Microsoft, most experts say, would be for
it to remain in one piece, but hog-tied competitively by harsh,
court-imposed restrictions on how it can develop and market
products.
</P>
<P>
   However, not all experts consider a breakup desirable. In an
interview with Barron's this week, David Readerman of Thomas Weisel
Partners in San Francisco, estimates the company's breakup value at
a mere $65 per share _ $22 below yesterday's close. Readerman
suggests that Microsoft is overvalued now, and that this is likely
to become more obvious in a breakup, when investors assign rational
values to each of the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
