<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0806 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TRADE-TRADE_SFCHRON &LR;      11-15 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-TRADE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 U.S., China Sign Landmark WTO Accord  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
With a handshake and a clink of champagne glasses, U.S. and Chinese
negotiators finally came to terms yesterday on a breakthrough
agreement that paves the way for China to enter the World Trade
Organization.
<P>
   Under the accord, reached after six days of marathon talks in
Beijing, China has agreed to cut tariffs on agricultural and
industrial goods and allow easier market access for U.S. financial
institutions, insurers and telecommunications firms.
</P>
<P>
   In return, China takes a big step closer to fulfilling its
long-held ambition of joining the WTO, which calls the shots for
global commerce and mediates disputes among member countries.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a 50 percent cap on U.S. investment in mainland
telecommunications businesses, it looks as if the American side
managed to fulfill most of its wish list, though the precise
details of the accord won't be clear for another few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement is a major step forward in bringing China into
the WTO and a profoundly important step in the relationship between
the United States and China,'' President Clinton said yesterday
during a visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   He said the accord is ``good for the United States, good for
China and good for the world economy.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; 11th-Hour Agreement
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative who hammered
out the 11th-hour agreement, said, ``This is a profound and
historic moment in U.S.-China relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Her counterpart in the negotiations, Chinese Foreign Trade
Minister Shi Guangsheng, told reporters in Beijing that the talks
were held amid a ``win-win spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The conclusion of this agreement serves the interests of both
China and the United States and is conducive to the development of
Sino-U.S. relations, to China becoming a WTO member as soon as
possible and to the development of the world economy and trade,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may be too late for China to become a full member of
the WTO by the start of the organization's November 30 summit in
Seattle, it almost certainly would receive more deference than
generally given an ``observer'' nation.
</P>
<P>
   Before gaining full WTO membership, China would have to receive
``normal trade relations'' recognition from the U.S. Congress,
which, with an election on the horizon, won't come easily.
</P>
<P>
   China's human rights record angers politicians from both the
left and right, and just about every special interest group _ from
farmers to textile and apparel makers _ will want to weigh in with
criticisms before giving a green light to China's WTO accession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a tough fight,'' said Dave McCurdy, president of
the Electronics Industry Alliance, a confederation of tech and
telecom trade groups. ``But at the end of the day, I think Congress
will approve it.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-China trade accord obligates Beijing to slash tariffs
by an average 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But China backpedaled from an earlier agreement to allow U.S.
companies to hold 51 percent stakes in mainland telecommunication
ventures. Instead, Beijing drew the line at 50 percent ownership,
thus preventing foreign companies from holding a majority position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big 1 percent,'' acknowledged McCurdy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. telecom companies racked up more than $2 billion in sales
to China last year, and investment of as much as $200 billion is
foreseen in the near future as the country rapidly erects its
infrastructure for digital communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most dynamic sector out there,'' McCurdy said. ``They
want to keep a piece of the action.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord also:
</P>
<P>
   _Allows for foreign investment in Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   _Doubles the number of foreign films allowed into Chinese
theaters from the current annual total of 10.
</P>
<P>
   _Allows overseas manufacturers to import and distribute their
own products rather than go through state-run enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   _Permits foreign banks to offer services in local currency to
mainland companies within two years of joining the WTO, and to
individual Chinese within five years.
</P>
<P>
   _Allows foreign auto companies full distribution and trading
rights. By 2006, China will reduce tariffs on automobiles to 25
percent from the current 80 to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _Cuts tariffs on agricultural products to 14.5 percent from the
present 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said much of the discussion over the weekend centered
on ``import surges'' and illegal ``dumping'' of products. The U.S.
steel industry, in particular, has been calling for more-stringent
measures to prevent Chinese manufacturers from undercutting
domestic companies with bargain-basement exports.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides ultimately agreed to maintain trade limitations
for 12 years and to uphold current anti-dumping restrictions for 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Textiles also figured prominently in the final negotiations. The
United States has agreed to end its import quotas after five years
but to implement ``anti-surge'' safeguards for four years
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Waiting for Fine Print
</P>
<P>
   While all observers are still waiting to see the fine print on
the accord, initial reactions were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know so far is excellent,'' said Anne Craib, director
of international trade for the Semiconductor Industry Association.
``We think we got everything that was in the April agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   That presumably would include China signing the Information
Technology Agreement, a separate treaty that calls for most tariffs
on tech products to be eliminated by 2000. It affects $500 billion
in global technology trade, including $100 billion in U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
   While Zhu had agreed in April to sign the treaty prior to China
joining the WTO, it's not yet known whether that pledge remained in
effect for yesterday's deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was a sticking point, so I assume it's in
there,'' said Jennifer Guhl, director of international trade policy
for the American Electronics Association, which represents about
3,000 high-tech heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just have to see when the full agreement is released,''
she said. ``The devil truly is in the details.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the AFL-CIO said U.S. workers should be concerned
about increased competition from low-paid Chinese factory
employees.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; `A Grave Mistake'
</P>
<P>
   ``The fevered rush to admit China to the WTO is a grave
mistake,'' AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said in an angry &LR; 
statement. ``The agreement reached this weekend would deal away our
democratic principles and most cherished values, and we will fight
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Pulaski, secretary-treasurer of the California Labor
Federation, said his group would follow the AFL-CIO's lead in
opposing China joining the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has a bad habit of engaging in prison labor,'' he said.
``That's not what positive economic relations should be about.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar dissent is likely from European labor leaders, but most
observers expect China's pending talks with the EU to proceed
smoothly. They note that many of the EU's concerns overlap with
those of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else, the agreement marks China's coming of economic
age following 13 years of failed negotiations to join the
135-member WTO. Beijing still must cut separate deals with the
European Union, Canada and other nations, but the U.S. negotiations
were the main stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations hit a brick wall in April when the Clinton
administration gave a cold shoulder to a series of far-reaching
concessions offered by Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the president's advisers felt that the political
climate wasn't right for a trade deal with China, which was facing
accusations of having made off with American nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while a red-faced Zhu was still trying to explain the
situation to more-conservative elements of his government, NATO
warplanes accidentally bombed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Beijing and Washington went from chilly to
downright frigid, and China took a number of its earlier
concessions off the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   By all reports, Clinton later kicked himself for not having
accepted Zhu's original terms and subsequently became more
personally involved in reopening trade talks with the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   After several go-nowhere meetings between the two sides in
recent months, Barshefsky and her team were dispatched to Beijing
for what most observers believed was a last-ditch effort to get the
negotiations back on track before the WTO summit in Seattle later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
