<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0808 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-CHINA-CALIFORNIA-LADN     11-15 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CALIFORNIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA, U.S. SIGN TRADE PACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Southern California's economy will see
significant long-term gains from Monday's breakthrough U.S.-China
trade agreement, trade experts said, but they cautioned that
improvements will be gradual.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Beijing to slash tariffs and other trade
barriers that now keep U.S. products away from China's 1.3 billion
consumers. In exchange, the United States will support China's
membership in the World Trade Organization, the 135-member
Geneva-based organization that sets the rules for global trade.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups such as the U.S. Chamber of Commerce applauded
the deal; labor unions and industries that will have to compete
against inexpensive Chinese imports denounced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to say that this agreement is a step in the right
direction, but it's also just a start,'' said Jack Kyser, economist
with the Los Angeles Economic Development Corp. ``We'll have to see
how it works in reality because China is not your typical
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, for one, achieved a notable victory as the number of
American films allowed into China _ legally _ will double annually
to 20.
</P>
<P>
   Economists were quick to note that the deal does not
specifically address China's widespread intellectual piracy, which
results in hundreds of American films flooding the market each year
via pirated videotapes. ``That's a very important issue to the
motion picture and computer businesses,'' said California
Department of Finance economist Ted Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, even though Chinese consumers have shown an appetite
for U.S. films, the market remains undeveloped, with modest numbers
of movie houses and taxes of more than 50 percent. Additionally,
authorities have barred American movies for parts of this year
during the 50th anniversary celebration of the founding of
communist China and during the aftermath of the U.S. bombing of the
Chinese embassy in May during the military campaign against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment industry's lobbying arm, the Motion Picture
Association, has estimated that pirated videos, videodiscs and TV
programs in China generated an estimated $120 million in losses for
U.S. studios last year. But MPA chief Jack Valenti issued a
positively worded statement Monday that called the agreement
heartening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are joyful that our friends in China have recognized the
worth of American films in their country,'' Valenti said. ``We are
looking forward to working with China Films so that the American
films that enter are given the widest distribution. This bodes well
for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Burbank-based Walt Disney Co., which has made the most
aggressive move into China with its recent deal to build a theme
park in Hong Kong, also endorsed the deal. ``We think it's great
that we will have more opportunities to exhibit our films in
China,'' said spokeswoman Christine Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser said Southern California companies that could see
long-term gains from the pact include those in entertainment,
financial services, money management, health services, biomedical
and professional services such as engineering and aerospace. ``I'd
say the agreement is being greeted with relief and some
skepticism,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached after 13 years of talks, requires China
to cut tariffs an average of 23 percent and promises greater access
to U.S. banks, insurers and telecommunications firms. The pact will
not take effect until China gains entry to the WTO, and most of it
will be phased in over five years or longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will probably see increases in port traffic across the
board as trade restrictions are lifted,'' said Gordon Palmer,
manager of master planning for the port of Long Beach. ``It means
that West Coast ports are probably going to continue to be busy.''
</P>
<P>
   China already generates the largest cargo volume of any nation
at Long Beach, with $12 billion in imports and exports during the
first half of this year, up 14 percent over the same period last
year. The largest components are electrical machinery at $1.9
billion, footwear at $1.7 billion and other machinery at $1.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, noting that economists expect China's cargo volume to
grow by 6 percent annually, also said the deal is likely to spur
further development of new Chinese ports beyond the mainstay
locations at Hong Kong and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   The trade agreement was announced two weeks after Disney sealed
its deal with Hong Kong for a theme park that will open in 2005.
Entertainment analyst Linda Bannister of Edward Jones &AMP; Co. said
Monday the new pact could help keep the Disney deal on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kind of improvement in the U.S.-China relationship would
only act to improve the relationship between U.S companies and
China,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bannister also said the agreement will add to the likelihood of
Universal going forward with rumored plans to open a theme park in
China.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
