<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-NEWMEX-LADN-(SLAN     11-15 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEWMEX-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPATRIATE GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Quick, name the Division I university outside of
Los Angeles with the most L.A.-area football players. If you're
stumped, don't take it too hard because Justin Mobley, Joe Manning,
Tyler Fenwick and Jake Farrell _ who all guessed Arizona _ were
wrong, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a Pac-10 school. Nor is it an independent or a member
of the Big Ten, SEC, ACC, Big East or Big West.
</P>
<P>
   It's the school the four former area standouts attend, the
University of New Mexico, which plays in the Mountain West
Conference, in Albuquerque. Heading into Saturday's game at
Wyoming, New Mexico is 3-6, 2-3 in the conference. A three-game
losing streak has ended any chance at a winning record and bowl
bid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seven area players, head coach Rocky Long was at
UCLA and assistant coach Jim Fenwick _ who recruited most of the
seven _ coached at Valley College and Cal State Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Albuquerque isn't the first place you'd consider looking for
numerous transplanted Angelenos. It's biggest claim to fame might
be Bugs Bunny's punch line: ``I knew I should have made that left
turn at Albuquerque.''
</P>
<P>
   The area players _ Mobley (Antelope Valley Christian), Manning
(AV), Fenwick (Chaminade), Farrell (Newbury Park), Ted Iacenda
(Hart) James Pritchett (Hart) and Quincy Wright (El Camino Real) _
agree life is different in the nation's 36th largest city.
</P>
<P>
   For one, it takes just 20 minutes to drive out of town, and a
traffic jam that lasts 10 minutes is considered major. Also, there
aren't as many malls, clubs, restaurants, movie theaters or other
diversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even compare it,'' Wright said. ``L.A. is upbeat, up
to date. Albuquerque is slow, dry. I'm used to action and it's dead
out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the players enjoy the clean air, the changing seasons, the
new football complex and playing in front of 33,000 fans. Also, the
players agree, having so many Angelenos helps cut down on
homesickness.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Lobos' impressive sports amenities don't hurt
either. The complex includes a 10,000-square-foot weight room,
which Farrell said is nicer than UCLA's.
</P>
<P>
   The training facilities have 30 tables and 60 trainers, plus a
full-time doctor. Every position has its own meeting room _ ``That
blows me away,'' Farrell said _ and there are larger rooms for the
offense, defense and entire team.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a player's lounge, complete with leather sofas,
big-screen TVs and soda machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Facilitiesare a big part of where you want to go,'' Farrell
said. ``That's a big seller for me. It's clean. That's where you
spend all your time.''
</P>
<P>
   The complex was one reason Jim Fenwick was able to recruit so
many area players. Even without the help, though, Fenwick's role
can't be understated. With his Southern California roots, it's no
surprise he has assembled a corps of skill players from the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of me knowing the area and feeling comfortable
with it,'' Fenwick said. ``It's good football or we wouldn't
recruit it. I'll always be in Southern California. I know the high
schools and junior colleges and can feel and know when they're up
and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he gets a recruit, Fenwick shows him the city, points out
how the Lobos are the only game in town, mentions how the climate
isn't much different than back home (except for the snow), and
walks them through the complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids come here and feel like they're in a special program,''
Fenwick said.
</P>
<P>
   The players enjoyed widespread media attention in high school,
but it's an even bigger deal here. Newspaper and television
reporters are at every practice. Tyler Fenwick says fans write
letters suggesting plays. Mobley told of a time someone called into
Long's radio show and announced Mobley had been sleeping in a
two-hour lecture class.
</P>
<P>
   The players are often asked to make appearances at charities and
schools. Once, Farrell had lunchwith the best students at an
elementary school, where he was considered a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's also a down side. The media played up an
incident last summer, when a walk-on from Albuquerque was arrested
for making fake IDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all over the TV. It was all over the newspapers,''
Farrell said. ``They arrested him when he was working out in the
locker room. A TV crew followed the police in. . . . If we do
anything wrong, it's splashed all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question, why would someone like Iacenda want to
move into this fishbowl? Because he could get a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   After being arrested and later cleared of sexual assault while
at USC, Iacenda wanted out, but the Trojans were slow in granting
him a waiver to transfer. Fenwick waited it out and got Iacenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so grateful,'' Iacenda said. ``He's the man. I owe
everything to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The media also has been positive, portraying Iacenda as a man
wronged by a woman's false claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're nice people,'' Iacenda said. ``There's so much support
for the New Mexico program. They die Lobo red.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NEW MEXICO SEVEN &QL; 
A look at L.A.-area football players at New Mexico: &QL; 
__ Jake Farrell: WR _ 8 games, 3 catches, 54 yards, 1 TD &QL; 
Has seen between 12-15 plays each game. Likes the Native
American/Southwestern styles but finds the campus too homogeneous.
Dismisses the Albuquerque Dukes baseball team, saying,``No one goes
to Dukes games. The stadium _ it's so old and desolate. The Dukes,
it's pretty depressing. They lose all the time.'' &QL; 
__ Tyler Fenwick: WR _ 9 games, 2 catches, 8 yards &QL; 
Plays as much as 25 downs a game. Really misses the various
fast-food hamburger restaurants that L.A. has, especially Carl's
Jr. ``That hurts. When we played San Diego State, all the
California guys say we've got to go to Carl's Jr.'' &QL; 
__ Ted Iacenda: RB/WR _ 9 games, 20 catches, 199 yards, 1 TD. Also
18 rushes for 78 yards. &QL; 
Has started twice. His only complaint about Albuquerque? The cold
winters. ``They're brutal.'' Says the adjustment wasn't difficult
because he considers his hometown of Santa Clarita to be a smaller
version of Albuquerque. &QL; 
__ Joe Manning: WR _ 7 games, 11 catches, 98 yards. Also 17 punt
returns for 87 yards and 2 kickoff returns for 54 yards. &QL; 
Coaches didn't know what to do with him after a horrible spring.
But he worked hard in the offseason and convinced the coaching
staff to play him. Has seen as many as 40 downs a game. &QL; 
__ Justin Mobley: QB _ 7 games, 9 of 23 passing, 88 yards, 1 TD, 3
INTs. Also 19 rushes for 89 yards and plays on special teams. &QL; 
Went to New Mexico because coaches promised him a chance to throw
the ball (other schools wanted him to play defense). His one
touchdown was to Farrell, but he hasn't played quarterback in the
last five games. &QL; 
__ James Pritchett: WR _ Redshirting. &QL; 
Is Iacenda's roommate. He hurt his chances when he pulled a quad
muscle during rookie camp. ``It set me back really far. I'll have
to wait 'till spring.'' &QL; 
__ Quincy Wright: RB _ 9 games, 5 rushes, 96 yards. &QL; 
Primarily plays on special teams. Since he's from South Central
L.A., he often gets asked if he was there during the riots and if
he was scared (he was and he was). Suffered homesickness the first
month, but placing pictures around his room made him feel better. &QL;
</P>
