<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-DIVORCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Answer wife, judge tells Gingrich
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Cobb County judge tersely ordered Newt Gingrich
Monday to answer all of his estranged wife's questions about his
money and extramarital love life, or else.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Dorothy Robinson gave the former U.S. House
speaker 20 days, or until Dec. 6, to ``fully and completely''
answer 32 questions, some of them potentially embarrassing, that
his wife has asked in their divorce. The questions include one that
asks Gingrich to name any lovers he's taken during his 18-year
marriage to his wife, Marianne, 48.
</P>
<P>
   In her short, two-page ruling, Robinson said she will wait to
see if Gingrich, 56, complies with her 20-day deadline before
deciding whether to sanction him for not answering the questions,
which his wife posed three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to answer them all,'' said Gingrich's attorney,
Randy Evans, following the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson rejected Gingrich's argument that the multiple-part
questions actually amounted to more than the 50 allowed by state
law.
</P>
<P>
   While Robinson agreed that many of the interrogatories
represented two or more questions, she still counted a total of
just 49.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also must answer this question that Evans previously
has called silly: ``Do you believe that that you have conducted
your private life in this marriage in accordance with the concept
of `family values' you have espoused politically and
professionally?''
</P>
<P>
   John Mayoue, attorney for Marianne Gingrich, said he was
``enormously pleased'' with the ruling. ``It's disturbing that it
takes a court order to require Mr. Gingrich to fully and completely
answer questions under oath,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich's attorney said he and his client had to take the
issue to the judge. ``If you don't do that, then you've waived the
rule and they just keep asking more and more and that defeats the
purpose of the rule,'' Evans said. He pointed out that Marianne
Gingrich now has just one question left.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's ruling Monday ended one of several bitter disputes
that have marked the case since Gingrich filed for divorce in July.
A second order she issued Monday may end another.
</P>
<P>
   The judge gave the Gingriches until Nov. 29 to comply with a
temporary agreement they voluntarily drafted in September. The
agreement requires the couple to put all of their assets into a
joint account until their divorce is final.
</P>
<P>
   The Gingriches have been fighting over whether Marianne Gingrich
has placed all the money she controls into the account. Both sides
asked the judge to step in.
</P>
<P>
   And a third dispute should be put to rest next week when a
Washington judge decides when Callista Bisek, the congressional
aide Gingrich admits to having an affair with, will have to answer
questions under oath about the relationship. Bisek, 33, has asked
the judge to toss out Marianne Gingrich's subpoena requiring Bisek
to show for a deposition and bring documents proving the affair.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing is set for next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Duane D. Stanford writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
