<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-UGA-WOMEN-COX     11-15 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-WOMEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Dogs dodge upset bid by UAB
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Being near the top of the national rankings is no
good place to be at the start of the season, as the Georgia women
found out Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 3-ranked Lady Bulldogs looked sloppy but hung on against
a gritty Alabama-Birmingham team for a 76-75 win in the first round
of the Women's Preseason NIT at Stegeman Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, which moved up two spots in the polls before ever
playing a game because of losses by Tennessee and Rutgers on
Sunday, almost fell into their company.
</P>
<P>
   Junior guard Kelly Miller was shut out most of the first half
but led Georgia in scoring with 22 points. Coco Miller scored 17
and Tawana McDonald 11 for the Lady Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   For Alabama-Birmingham, forward Deanna Jackson led the way with
28 points and Mia Thrash had 14.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Georgia plays at No. 17 Virginia Tech, a 60-45
winner over Liberty, in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   In a ragged display, as season openers tend to be, the Blazers
were not daunted by facing the highest-ranked team in the 16-team
NIT field.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 35 minutes, UAB dictated the tempo, while Georgia
was erratic defensively and couldn't get into the running game it
likes.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had an answer every time Georgia came close. The
Lady Dogs took their first lead of the second half with 7:57 to
play when Kelly Miller stole the ball from Sally Jeter while
applying pressure on an inbounds play and put in a layup for a
59-58 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until the final minutes that Georgia was able to
add to its lead. The Millers hit consecutive jumpers from the
perimeter for a 71-67 lead at the 2:34 mark, but Thrash halved the
gap with two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Then UAB's Holly Holland shot an air ball, and Georgia's Deana
Nolan was fouled on the rebound. She made one of two shots, and
Kelly Miller made two more from the line for a 74-69 edge.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson came back and hit two 3-point baskets in the final
seconds, including the last points of the game, but Georgia made
five of six free throws.
</P>
<P>
   From the earliest moments of the game, Georgia had trouble
solving Alabama-Birmingham's matchup zone or countering the
transition game, and trailed 35-33 at the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Miller scored her first four points of the game on buckets
in the final 1:21, but Thrash sank a trey at the buzzer for the
Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
