<SLUG> BC-GORE-MICROSOFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GETS A WORKOUT AT MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The managers of Microsoft Monday greeted Vice President Al Gore
with a mental workout that was the equal in intensity to the
physical exertions he underwent while climbing Mount Rainier last
July.
</P>
<P>
   Angry that their company would be accused of harming American
consumers, employees in Redmond told Gore the software industry is
intensely competitive, and voiced offense at the Justice
Department's celebration of a federal judge's anti-trust ruling 10
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gore refused to talk about specifics of the Justice Department's
case against Microsoft. But he delivered a plainspoken defense of
anti-trust laws, underscoring many of the underlying arguments that
the administration used against the Redmond-based company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If competition is valuable, which I think it is, then
anti-trust laws have a place in embodying the values of our
country,'' said Gore, the Clinton administration's self-described
point man on technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to another question, Gore added: ``Competition can be
stifled both by unwise and unhealthy government action, but also by
companies that want to use innovation in one sector to stifle
competition in another.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has looked out at friendly faces and heard only the
occasional heckler during 11 previous previous visits to the Puget
Sound area since the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he drew big crowds _ 300 packed into an auditorium at
Microsoft's campus and 500 people at the Northshore Senior Center _
but faced tough, knowledgeable questions on anti-trust, abortion
and trade.
</P>
<P>
   He heard genuine anguish at Microsoft. One questioner, who began
working for the software company when he was 14, said he was a
Democrat because of the party's stands on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is I want to vote for you ...'' the questioner
told Gore, but the vice president is number two man in an
administration ``that accuses us of harming the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I respect your feeling and thank you for the underlying
values that motivate it,'' replied Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Again straying close to a comment on the Microsoft case, the
vice president added: ``The values that are inherent in our
anti-trust laws are ones that are sound, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore received a warm greeting at the senior center, and a few
hot questions. A woman named Toni Potter voiced fears of the World
Trade Organization that the new world economic order might bring
about disappearance of the world's forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe we must integrate labor and environmental
concerns into trade negotiations,'' said Gore, echoing a position
he unveiled during a July speech in Seattle. The vice president
challenged Potter on how she would change trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should be done in public,'' Potter replied.
</P>
<P>
   Gore started to put down his questioner, citing the fact that
juries work in private. He pulled up, however, and said: ``I think
it should be a little more open.''
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers have vowed they will put 50,000 demonstrators
on the streets of Seattle for an anti-World Trade Organization
protest on Nov. 30, as trade ministers from around the world
convene in Seattle. Monday, however, they mustered only nine
protestors outside the Northshore Senior Center.
</P>
<P>
   At Microsoft, the vice president reveled in the Clinton
administration's successful conclusion of a trade agreement that,
he said, ``virtually assures'' that China will join the World Trade
Organization. The vice president predicted the accord will ``open
up Chinese markets to a lot of our goods and services.'' But Gore
appeared to deliberately distance himself from a deal struck over
the weekend between the White House and House Republicans. In
exchange for money that will cover the United States' back dues to
the United Nation, the administration agreed to a ban on U.S. money
going to international organizations that support abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was asked about the deal during his appearance before
Microsoft employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not favor bargaining away any critical policy aspect of a
woman's right to choose,'' he replied. Afterward, the vice
president made clear that he was not part of negotiating the deal,
and said he has not talked to President Clinton about it.
</P>
<P>
   As he runs for president, Gore _ who was hit by a thunderstorm
on Mount Rainier in July _ has become a lightning rod on such
global issues as the World Trade Organization and
Northwest-oriented issues like prevention of oil spills in the
Strait of Juan de Fuca.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has been an occasional bearer of popular
news, announcing Friday that a Navy rescue tug will be put at Neah
Bay starting in mid-December, providing immediate response to
marine mishaps during the darkest, stormiest months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Monday how long the tug will be stationed at the mouth of
the Strait, Gore replied: ``As long as it's needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was also serving as a financial drawing card Monday. He
adjourned to Newcastle Country Club last night, dining with about
20 big donors at a fundraiser that took in an estimated $225,000
for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president seemed charged up by his session at
Microsoft, which came just 10 days after U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson found that the company has stifled competition to
the detriment of American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won a healthy round of applause by asking if he could come
back. He was the sixth presidential candidate to visit the
Microsoft campus, which has also hosted GOP frontrunners, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain, as well as former
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's fast-rising competitor for the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Microsoft severed relations with Gore. The software
giant has just hired the vice president's former press secretary
and longtime Democratic spokespersonm, Ginny Terzano, to head its
Washington, D.C., lobbying operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
