A0843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEONID-SHOWER-COX     11-15 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEONID-SHOWER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leonid meteors: A sprinkle, shower or storm?
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Constellation Leo will roar in the
pre-dawn hours Thursday, shooting a blizzard of white-hot meteors
across the eastern sky.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe the much-awaited Leonid meteor storm will happen
Wednesday morning. Or later Thursday when we'll miss most of the
celestial fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it won't be a storm of meteors at all, merely a drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom among astronomers is that the best space
show this side of Hollywood will debut early Thursday when between
200 to 5,000 meteors per hour will streak above the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for precision? These are the same folks who touted
such notorious astronomical fizzles as comets Kohoutek in 1973-74,
Halley in 1986 and Hyakutake (gesundheit!) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Many predicted a storm last year. Although some spectacular
fireballs were seen (18 hours ahead of schedule), the peak was only
250 meteors per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meteor showers are like blind dates,'' said Jack Horkheimer,
director of the Miami Space Transit Planetarium. ``You never know
what you're going to get until you meet face to face.''
</P>
<P>
   The Leonid shower, so called because the meteors seem to flare
from the sickle-shaped constellation of Leo, is an annual event.
Mark your calendar today through Thursday when the Earth moves
through the debris trail of Comet Tempel-Tuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Microscopic specks of dust, chunks of ice and extraterrestrial
rock slice through the atmosphere. They appear as shooting stars as
they burn into nothingness at 43 miles per second.
</P>
<P>
   A typical year boasts 10 to 20 meteors per hour. But every 33
years the fresh ribbon of debris makes for spectacular celestial
fireworks. The 1966 peak was 2,400 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Local sky-watchers counted 50 per hour at the peak last year
when clouds obscured most of the sky. Globally, the top number was
250 per hour over Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year it could be a shower, a storm or a sprinkle,'' said
Charlie Fredrickson, president of the Astronomical Society of the
Palm Beaches. His group will gather in the pre-dawn darkness near
20-Mile Bend where urban lights will not obscure the flashes of
meteors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect more meteors but dimmer,'' Fredrickson said.
</P>
<P>
   The darker the sky, the easier to spot the meteors. If the
darkness of the wilderness west of Loxahatchee is too scary, try a
beach or a pier jutting into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try to get far enough away to see the Milky Way,'' Horkheimer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The best viewing for the east coast is expected to be between 3
and 6 a.m. Thursday, after the moon has set and Leo has risen in
the east, said Erich Landstrom, astronomy director at the South
Florida Science Museum in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Grab a lounge chair, a thermos of coffee and plenty of patience.
No binoculars or telescopes are needed. In fact, they only narrow
the view. Scan the sky rather than looking at Leo. Better yet,
divide the sky into quarters and each observer take a quadrant.
</P>
<P>
   Meteors often come in spurts so there could be many minutes
between sightings.
</P>
<P>
   Horkheimer is taking no chances. He's going out before dawn
Wednesday and then before midnight the next night. ``I missed the
storm in '66 by one hour,'' he said. ``I went to bed. I'm not going
to miss it this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Meilia writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: timomeilia(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
