<SLUG> BC-BBN-CY-YOUNG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDY JOHNSON GETS NATIONAL LEAGUE CY YOUNG AWARD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a year in which one pitcher won 22 games, it took
an extraordinary season for another pitcher to win the Cy Young
award.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Arizona's Randy Johnson, who finished with a 17-9 record
but had 364 strikeouts in 2712/3 innings, beat out Houston's Mike
Hampton _ who went 22-4 _ for the National League Cy Young award.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who won the 1995 award while with Seattle, became just
the second pitcher to win in both leagues. (Gaylord Perry was the
first.) A third pitcher, Boston's Pedro Martinez, is expected to
become the third pitcher to join that group, because he is almost a
lock to win the American League Cy Young award Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson lost nine games in the regular season and
struggled in the postseason, he used his flaming fastball to have a
dominant year, leading the league in earned run average (2.48) and
complete games (12).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also led the majors in strikeouts. He was only 19
strikeouts short of the season record held by Nolan Ryan, and
Johnson now has the fourth-highest, single-season total. Johnson
struck out 10 or more batters 23 times, matching Ryan's record set
in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson received 20 of the first-place votes cast by members of
the Baseball Writers' Association of America. Hampton led the
league in victories and received 11 first-place votes. Atlanta's
Kevin Millwood was third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think this award isn't solely based on wins and
losses,'' Johnson said. ``There was a lot more to the season I had
than wins and losses. Quite honestly, I feel, still, this is the
best year I had in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, the most feared hurler among hitters in the
National League because of his long-limbed, left-handed release,
was also a hard-luck pitcher. In seven of his losses, Arizona
scored two or fewer runs, including a stretch in which the
Diamondbacks were shut out in four straight Johnson starts. In
those games, Johnson had an e.r.a. of 1.41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't dwell on it,'' Johnson said about the lack of
support. ``There were a few players that came up and said I handled
it really well and that meant more than any win I got this year. It
was frustrating. I continued to work hard and I was able to put up
some numbers I felt at the end of the year I could be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Johnson struggled in his only postseason appearance this
year when the New York Mets overcame 11 strikeouts to score seven
runs and hand him a loss. In postseason play, Johnson has lost
seven consecutive decisions over nine games that began after he
beat the Yankees twice in the 1995 playoffs while pitching for
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, when Tom Glavine won the award, the National League
Cy Young award has been dominated by Greg Maddux, John Smoltz and
Glavine, the heart of the Braves' rotation. From then until now,
the only other pitcher to break their string was Martinez, who won
while with Montreal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
