<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-REICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WINS ENDORSEMENT OF A CLINTON LABOR SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Robert Reich, the former secretary of labor
in the Clinton administration, broke ranks with his old boss Monday
and endorsed former Sen. Bill Bradley over Vice President Al Gore
in their race for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully choosing his words during a joint appearance with
Bradley at St. Anselm's College, Reich called his decision ``very
difficult,'' saying he had ``great respect and admiration'' for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Reich, who served as labor secretary in Clinton's first
term, said he thought Bradley had laid out stronger proposals for
confronting what he called ``the nation's great unfinished
agenda,'' ending child poverty, extending health care to all
Americans and improving schools. Reich, who teaches social and
economic policy at Brandeis University, has been informally
advising Bradley on social policy for several months, Bradley's
aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The times call for bold solutions,'' Reich told 250 students
at the college. ``Bill Bradley will provide them.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he considered Gore unelectable _ as Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., asserted when he endorsed Bradley in September _
Reich replied, ``I won't say anything negative about the vice
president.'' He added that he had broken the news to Gore in a
telephone call Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign responded to the news by releasing documents
purporting to show clear differences in Reich's positions on health
care policy and Bradley's proposal to make health insurance
available to almost all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley plan calls for replacing Medicaid, the government
health care program for he poor, with a system of private
insurance. Gore asserts the plan would hurt poor black and Hispanic
people. And Monday, it produced quotes from Reich criticizing past
efforts to overhaul Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   But Reich told reporters Monday that he could see the logic of
Bradley's plan, saying many poor people go on and off Medicaid and
therefore might be better served by a system of private insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
