<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNESMANN IN SURPRISE SUIT TO STOP HOSTILE BID BY VODAFONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to insert new 5th graf noting further Mannesmann-Vodafone
entanglement.) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A day after rejecting a $106-billion takeover from
Vodafone Airtouch PLC, Mannesmann AG of Germany moved Monday to
thwart the British company's hostile bid by suing to remove its
corporate adviser, Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., accusing the Wall Street
investment bank of a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann played its surprise card Monday afternoon when its
lawyers filed a request for an injunction with Britain's High
Court, seeking to prevent Goldman from advising Vodafone, the
world's biggest wireless operator. It argued that Goldman's
previous work for Mannesmann had given it access to confidential
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that Goldman, Sachs has explicitly promised us
not to advise Vodafone or anybody else on an unsolicited bid, and
then did the contrary,'' Klaus Esser, Mannesmann's chief executive,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers depicted the maneuver as potentially a
landmark event in corporate takeovers, one that might change
deal-making by turning advisers into litigation targets alongside
the corporations in play. A boom in European mergers has left many
investment banks in the position of working for competing
companies, creating the same potential conflicts as those alleged
in the Mannesmann-Vodafone brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, two of Mannesmann's current advisers in its
efforts to repulse Vodafone also worked for Vodafone's allies in
other deals in the last year. Merrill Lynch advised Bell Atlantic
and Morgan Stanley advised Airtouch Communications when it was
acquired by Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, the top corporate adviser in Europe, said it would
temporarily stop advising Vodafone until the case is heard
Thursday, thereby suspending its involvement at the height of an
intensifying takeover drama that had been billed as likely to
produce history's biggest-ever hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone said it was reviewing Mannesmann's court maneuver.
Goldman said in a statement that it ``has acted properly and has
pressed for an early hearing so it can challenge this action
vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
   Only hours earlier, executives close to the takeover discussions
had said that Vodafone was leaning toward a bid for Mannesmann
early Tuesday. But the pending court action injected new
uncertainty, representing a clear escalation of the battle between
Vodafone and Mannesmann, which began three weeks ago when the
German company announced its $33 billion acquisition of Orange PLC.
That purchase of Britain's No. 3 mobile phone operator turned
Mannesmann from a Vodafone partner elsewhere in Europe to a rival
on Vodafone's home turf.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is dominance in Europe's mushrooming wireless market as
the Continent gears up not only for a boom in the number of mobile
phone users, particularly among the European Union's 350 million
people, but also for a surge in wireless Internet use propelled by
technological advances.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman had managed the international portion of a $1.6 billion
sale of new Mannesmann stock and was an adviser to Hutchison
Whampoah, a Hong Kong-based group that owns 44 percent of Orange's
stock and was a key participant in Mannesmann's $33-billion deal to
buy Orange. Vodafone's advisers on the Mannesmann takeover effort
are Goldman and Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday, Mannesmann, a fast-growing German
telecommunications giant that has emerged from what was once a
staid engineering concern, rejected a $106.4 billion overture from
Vodafone's chief executive, Christopher Gent, who had flown to
Duesseldorf, Germany, to present his offer only to be told by
Mannesmann's Esser that it was ``wholly inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann's rejection of Vodafone's all-stock bid _ which
valued the German company at 203 euros, or $209.50 a share _ sent
Vodafone's stock down by 3.75 pence (six cents) to close at 292.5
pence ($4.73) on Monday. Mannesmann's shares rose 9.5 percent to
17.68 euros ($18.21) to a record 202.98 euros ($209). Mannesmann's
stock has risen by 31 percent in the past two weeks of fevered
takeover speculation that has driven up telecommunications stocks
in general.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications PLC, for instance, closed up 46.5
pence (70.68 cents) at 1,286 pence ($20.83). But the move in share
prices did not shake the widespread belief among analysts that
Vodafone has little option but to pursue a hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the stakes are as high as they are, they need to show
an aggressiveness and forcefulness,'' said John Jensen, a
telecommunications analyst at Salomon Smith Barney. ``And it's not
like they are starved for cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Jensen and several other analysts said Vodafone would need to
bid upwards of 220 euros ($226) and possibly up to 250 euros
($257.50) to persuade Mannesmann's shareholders _ none of whom hold
a controlling bloc of shares _ to support such a deal. The upper
limit of Vodafone's bid will be dictated partly by the level at
which the offers would dilute the earnings of the combined
companies, a figure that some analysts placed at between 230 euros
($236.9) and 240 euros ($247.20).
</P>
<P>
   That means that the bid could be valued at around 127 billion
euros, or $130.8 billion _ compared with the previous European
record for an unsolicited bid of $64 billion, by Olivetti SpA for
Telecom Italia SpA earlier this year. The bid would also far exceed
the current record, a $115 billion takeover deal by MCI Worldcom
for Sprint announced last month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vodafone is set to announce first-half earnings Tuesday, and
analysts are anticipating a 70 percent gain in earnings to 810
million pounds ($1.31 billion) as a result of its acquisition last
January of Airtouch, a U.S. telecommunications concern.
</P>
<P>
   Any deal for Mannesmann would be far more complex than the
trans-Atlantic negotiations that fused Vodafone and Airtouch.
</P>
<P>
   Successful hostile takeovers are virtually unknown in Germany
and Mannesmann has expressed its desire to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   Esser, the Mannesmann chief, sought to reinforce that impression
Monday, telling CNN: ``There is always a price for everything but I
am 100 percent convinced that there will not be a price which is
good enough, which is fair enough to Mannesmann shareholders, which
is at all affordable to Vodafone shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Esser's view reflects his his belief that Mannesmann's strategy
is ``diametrically opposed'' to his suitors', according to an
executive close to Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   The German giant has decided its future growth is based on a
combination of communication methods, including land-line networks,
data networks and wireless networks. Conversely, Vodafone has
successfully built its business strictly on a wireless strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
