<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-HOSPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF FUNDS ENDANGERING CARE IN SOUTH AFRICA'S HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The public hospital system in South
Africa is so short of cash that it lacks enough workers, medical
equipment, ambulances, linens and medicine to provide proper care
to the poor, a government commission has found.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors cancel surgical procedures because they lack sterile
towels and sheets, the commission said. Nursing departments are so
shorthanded that immobilized patients must often be bathed and fed
by relatives. Outdated medicine routinely appears in wards. And at
two hospitals, several patients died because the equipment they
needed was broken or unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear that the budget is insufficient for current
services,'' the commission wrote in its study, which was issued in
October. ``It is clear to the commission that health care is
compromised if much needed personnel cannot be appointed and
equipment cannot be acquired in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   The report focused on five hospitals in Soweto, Pretoria,
Midrand, East Rand and Vereeniging and emphasized that many
doctors, nurses and pharmacists still provide good care. But
government officials say the findings are particularly worrisome
because they reflect problems common in public hospitals across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of apartheid, the government has greatly expanded
access to health care for blacks and people of mixed race, who were
once relegated to substandard facilities in urban areas and often
went with little or no care in rural areas. Today the country
spends more than $3 billion a year on health care and offers free
primary care to pregnant mothers, children under 6 and poor people
without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But the policy on primary care has left public hospitals
straining to care for surging numbers of women, children and people
with AIDS, the commission found. Many of those patients should be
treated in the developing network of public clinics but end up in
hospitals because the clinic system suffers from even greater
shortages of workers and medicines.
</P>
<P>
   The health minister, Manto Tshabalala-Msimang, recently vowed to
improve the quality of care, expand primary clinics and revitalize
public hospitals. Local officials in Gauteng, the province that
encompasses the five troubled hospitals, have promised to spend an
additional $4 million on those hospitals and to seek donations of
medical equipment from international agencies and private business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that the issue of the budget is the biggest
challenge we're facing,'' said Gwen Malegwale Ramokgopa, the
provincial health minister.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first improvements is to allow some hospitals to fill
positions that had been frozen. The good news came to Soweto last
month when hospital administrators learned they would be allowed to
fill 104 of 140 vacant doctors' posts. But the administrators said
shortages of nurses and pharmacists still exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved,'' said John Pettifor, who heads the pediatrics
department at Chris Hani-Baragwanath Hospital in Soweto. ``But we
still don't have enough nurses to manage the patients we're
admitting. And equipment is not being replaced as fast as it
becomes obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital wards and bathrooms are so dirty that ``hospital
hygiene does not meet clinically required standards,'' the
commission found. And some hospital pharmacies turn away 300 to 500
patients daily because they lack enough workers to distribute
medication.
</P>
<P>
   Other hospitals lack wheelchairs and gurneys. Faulty and
outdated devices give incorrect readings or break down. And because
of an ambulance shortage, it can take 46 minutes or more to
transport patients to the hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
