<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-15 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0991 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     11-15 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV05-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., DEC. 5, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am building some floor-to-ceiling wood shelves on one wall
in my family room and want to make sure that the vertical sides
will be absolutely plumb and vertical.
</P>
<P>
   Because the walls, as well as the floors and high ceilings in
this old house, are not really level I cannot simply measure in
from a corner of the room to draw a truly vertical line on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   How can I plumb the vertical ends of my built-in bookcase
without having to go out and buy an expensive long spirit level of
some kind?
</P>
<P>
   A: The simplest way to draw a vertical line that is absolutely
plumb is to snap a chalk line on the wall by using a plumb bob and
length of chalked line as shown here.
</P>
<P>
   The line should be coated with chalk powder by rubbing it over a
piece of chalk or by passing it through powdered chalk (sold in
hardware stores).
</P>
<P>
   Tie a plumb bob to the bottom end of this line and tie the top
end to a nail driven into the wall up near the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Allow the line to hang free until the weighted plumb bob down
near the floor stops swinging, then pull the string tight while
holding the plumb bob steady at the bottom with one hand.
</P>
<P>
   With the other hand pull the center of the string out an inch or
two from the wall, then allow it to snap back against the wall.
This will create a chalked line on the wall that will be exactly
plumb.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The exhaust fan in our bathroom rattles when it is running.
Can you tell me if this rattle can be corrected, and if the fan
really should exhaust bathroom odors?
</P>
<P>
   A: The rattle is probably due to one of two things: the fan
blade could be loose on its shaft, or the blade could be hitting
something inside the housing when it is spinning.
</P>
<P>
   This can be determined by pulling off the housing or grill that
covers the fan, then turning off the power and rotating the fan
blade by hand while observing what happens as the blade spins.
</P>
<P>
   As for the fan's use _ most home bathroom fans in general are
intended to exhaust moisture when bathing. They do help to exhaust
odors, but most are not really large enough to do a thorough job of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The aluminum siding on my house was originally brown, but now
the color is dull and faded.
</P>
<P>
   When I accidentally spilled some linseed oil in one area near
the garage, I noticed that the oil made the color look darker and
more like its original color.
</P>
<P>
   Since I like the appearance, and since this was accomplished
without painting, I wonder if it would be possible to do this on
all the siding on that side of the house?
</P>
<P>
   A: The trouble with linseed oil is that it is very susceptible
to mildew _ it will usually turn dark and blotchy looking in time.
Most oils will have this same affect on dark colors, but the color
will not last as long as paint.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you want try this, then don't use linseed oil.
Instead, use a product like Penetrol, or one of the clear
penetrating wood sealers that are sold in all paint stores.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our family room and kitchen windows get lots of afternoon
sun, which makes these rooms uncomfortably warm during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   I have installed window shades, but these tend to darken the
rooms and kill our outside view.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a special glass or some kind of clear film we can
install that will help solve this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are transparent window films that can be applied to
window glass to greatly cut down on the amount of heat that will
come through that glass. Some are clear but the most efficient ones
are slightly tinted (usually an amber cast).
</P>
<P>
   Most create a ``mirror'' effect on the outside during daylight
hours (you can see out, but outsiders can't see in). At night the
effect is the opposite: if interior lights are on, you cannot see
out, but those outside can see in.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``PLUMB LINE'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Chalked plumb line will mark vertical line on wall when
snapped lightly after pulling plumb line tight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
