<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-1STL     11-15 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA AND U.S. REACH LANDMARK AGREEMENT ON TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to change 134 to 135 in 4th graf. In 6th graf of 2nd take,
defines illegal `dumping.') 
(ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM with DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ American and Chinese negotiators reached a landmark
agreement on Monday to open China's economy to foreign competitors
and in return to make the world's most populous nation a full
partner in international commerce.
</P>
<P>
   After six days of arduous negotiations, the U.S. trade
representative, Charlene Barshefsky, and China's trade minister,
Shi Guangsheng, signed the papers at 3:50 p.m. on Monday, shook
hands and raised a champagne toast to an agreement that capped 13
years of on-and-off negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal signed on Monday, Beijing would reduce tariffs on
various industrial and agricultural products and lift many of the
barriers in the way of American banks, insurance and telephone
companies to operate here.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the United States agreed to support China for
membership in the World Trade Organization, the 135-member
organization that sets the rules for global trade. China must still
complete side agreements with the European Union, Canada and some
developing countries, including Brazil, before its application can
be taken up by the body's 135 member states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just say that this is a profound and historic moment in
U.S.-China relations,'' said a clearly exultant Barshefsky, adding
that the agreement would not only aid the economies of both
countries, but also serve as an anchor in the tumultuous political
relationship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The last six days of day-and-night negotiations were conducted
in a ``win-win spirit,'' Shi said at the ceremony, ``and finally we
reached an agreement that serves the interests of both China and
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the rejoicing, the agreement still faces tough
resistance in the United States, where it is opposed by labor
unions and some critics of China. The U.S. Congress must vote to
put an end to the annual review of Chinese trade and to establish
permanent normal trading relations with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   For China, membership in the trade body will mean a long-sought
acceptance into the ``club'' of world powers. The WTO's elaborate
rules will help protect China from discriminatory policies abroad,
but will also force the discipline of globally agreed rules on
China's own fitful progress toward a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   The accord goes to the heart of China's transition to an open,
market economy. It would put Beijing, for the first time, under the
jurisdiction of the rules set by the World Trade Organization,
which are enforced by a trade court.
</P>
<P>
   Full WTO membership will be a victory for President Jiang Zemin,
who sees achieving China's economic modernization as his legacy
even as he tries to insure continuation of Communist Party rule. At
the same time it will cheer the more liberal, reform-oriented
factions led by Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, since it locks China
onto the path of economic opening and the global competition they
hope will force China's own state-owned industries to become
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   The step is a politically risky one for Jiang and Zhu at a
moment when those state-run companies are already shedding millions
of workers. For President Clinton, Monday's agreement provides a
badly needed centerpiece to his fraying policy of engagement with
China, offering the prospect of tangible gains to many companies
and to consumers. It is also a stunning recovery from what his own
top aides describe as a huge mistake: his decision to walk away
from the surprisingly sweeping deal, similar to Monday's, offered
in April by Zhu.
</P>
<P>
   After the signing, Barshefsky and Gene Sperling, the White House
chief of economic policy who attended the talks as a symbol of
Clinton's personal commitment, were driven to the secluded
leadership compound for a brief meeting with Jiang, who had twice
in the past month conducted telephone talks with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in the talks was far more than how deeply American
insurance and telephone companies could invest in China, or how
freely American oranges could be exported there - among the many
issues that both sides have argued about for years. The accord goes
to the heart of China's transition to an open, market economy and
for the first time it puts Beijing under the jurisdiction of the
rules of international trade set by the World Trade Organization,
enforced by a trade court.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Turkey on Monday, Clinton said: ``I think this is a
good agreement for China, for America and for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's struggle to make this accord a central foreign
policy achievement is far from over. Congress will review the
accord when it takes up the biggest single American concession:
Granting permanent trading rights to China rather than reviewing
those rights annually, a Capitol Hill ritual that has turned into
an annual debate about human rights and arms proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has spoken often of ``integrating China into the world
economy'' and gradually getting the country to embrace ``the rule
of law,'' starting with commercial law. But without closing a WTO
agreement, his aides said, he would have little progress to point
to.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement may also help to repair the damage done from
charges of Chinese spying in the United States, the accidental
American bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade last May and
China's continuing suspicion that the United States is attempting
to ``contain'' its military and economic power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Successful completion of WTO will go a long way to smooth out
some of the extreme oscillation that we have seen in Sino-American
relations in recent years,'' said Joseph Fewsmith, a China expert
at Boston University. `'I think it gives us a chance to build some
substance into a relationship that has been badly damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   The WTO sets rules for global commerce, adjudicates disputes
and, with global trading accords, presses for ever-freer markets.
Monday's agreement is a huge step toward membership for China. It
is probably already too late, experts said, for China to be fully
admitted before Nov. 30, when a new round of global trade
negotiations will begin in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's accord means that China will take a larger role in
setting the agenda at Seattle, and the talks are expected to go on
for years.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the American goal was to press China not
only for large reductions in tariffs on imported farm products and
industrial goods such as automobiles. In measures that may
ultimately have a far more profound impact, China had to commit
itself to allowing foreign companies to take majority investments
in many industrial and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
   The final six days of negotiations went through several rough
spots. Several times Barshefsky and Sperling suggested they were
packing up to leave, threats Barshefsky said in an interview on
Monday that were ``largely tactical, to force the Chinese to make
some progress.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
