u a BC-COSBY-EXTORTION-NYT     11-15 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-EXTORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGES REINSTATE CONVICTION IN EXTORTION OF BILL COSBY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a highly unusual move, the federal appeals panel
that overturned the conviction of a woman accused of trying to
extort $40 million from Bill Cosby reversed itself Monday and
reinstated the guilty verdict against her.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Autumn Jackson, who had claimed to be Cosby's
out-of-wedlock daughter, and two others were convicted in 1997 of
conspiring in a threat to sell her story to a supermarket tabloid
unless the actor paid her the money. But a three-judge panel of the
2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the judge in the trial
had improperly instructed the jury and overturned the convictions.
Ms. Jackson was released from prison after serving only 14 months
of her 26-month sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, that same panel reversed itself and reinstated all
three convictions, citing a Supreme Court decision on jury
instructions that came down just one day after its ruling last
June. As a result, Ms. Jackson will probably have to return to
prison, said her lawyer, Robert Baum, who delivered the news to her
by phone late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was devastated,'' said Baum. ``She asked me a few
questions, and then she just broke down and started crying and
couldn't talk to me any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Baum said Ms. Jackson, 25, who gave birth to twin boys in jail,
had been living with her husband and sons, who are about a year and
a half old, and her mother outside Los Angles.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson had been serving her sentence at the federal
Correctional Institution at Dublin, in northern California, when
her conviction was overturned last spring. Baum said Ms. Jackson
would surrender to prison authorities, but he added that he would
then seek her release on bail. He said he was considering seeking a
review by the full federal appeals court or the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Cosby, Andrew D. Schau, said Monday: ``The decision
confirms that the defendants' conduct was wrong, and that the jury
that convicted them got it right the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney
in Manhattan, who prosecuted the case, had no comment Monday on the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The original trial of Ms. Jackson and her two co-defendants
attracted widespread attention because of Cosby's role as the
victim. Testimony in the case showed that on Jan. 16, 1997, the
same day that Ms. Jackson made her demand of $40 million, Cosby's
son, Ennis, was killed in California. There was no connection
between the two incidents.
</P>
<P>
   When Judge Amalya L. Kearse, writing for the panel, ordered the
convictions overturned June 9, she said the jury should have been
allowed to consider whether Ms. Jackson believed she had a rightful
claim to the money in light of her contention that Cosby was her
father. The trial judge had told the jury that Ms. Jackson's belief
was irrelevant to whether she was guilty of extortion.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, Kearse said that under a new Supreme Court decision
handed down on June 10, the judge's failure to instruct the jury on
the issue was ``harmless error,'' and the convictions could be
affirmed. The Supreme Court had ruled that errors in a judge's jury
instructions are harmless when they could not have affected the
jury's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The defense in the trial had argued that Ms. Jackson's conduct
was not illegal because she honestly believed that she was Cosby's
daughter and had a claim against him. Cosby has denied that he is
Ms. Jackson's father, although he did admit having an affair with
her mother in the 1970s
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The government, in seeking to have the convictions reinstated,
told the panel that no matter what the jury was told by the trial
judge about Ms. Jackson's feeling of entitlement, no rational juror
could have agreed with her belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any asserted belief that Jackson was entitled to $40 million
from Cosby would have been preposterous on the facts of this
case,'' Ms. White said in papers submitted to the appeals panel.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, who was joined in her opinion by Chief Judge Ralph K.
Winter and Judge Ellsworth A. Van Graafeiland, agreed that there
was ``no evidence on which a rational juror'' could find ``that
Jackson had a plausible claim of right to the $40 million she
demanded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
