<HEADER>
A1001 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-15 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARPED VALUES A LAUGH A MINUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Ken Griffey Jr., who casts as large a shadow over
Seattle as the Space Needle, demands to be traded so he can be
closer to his wife and kids. If we could speak over the trumpets'
blaring of Junior's old-fashioned family values, we'd ask him: If
it's all about kin, why not just sell the house in Orlando and take
up permanent residence in Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   There's a name for political candidates in these times who are
as disingenuous as Griffey, who is catering to his kids only if
they are fraternal twins named Greed and Glory:
</P>
<P>
   Also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   Just as there's a word to describe workers in other fields who
reject a substantial raise and call in sick 100 consecutive days in
protest, as did Seattle Seahawks receiver Joey Galloway:
</P>
<P>
   Unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with putting athletes on a pedestal is they tend to
look their best when contributing the least to society's upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   They don't interact with our children eight hours a day like
teachers or day-care workers; they don't counsel battered women or
create jobs for the needy or feed the homeless or patrol our
streets at night.
</P>
<P>
   They entertain us for a few hours and help us forget our
troubles and for that they are treated like royalty.
   We watch Shaquille O'Neal shrug off a $10,000 fine for
instigating a fight with Charles Barkley as the cost of being a big
man in a hacker's league.
</P>
<P>
   We watch Lawrence Phillips blow off practices and Ryan Leaf blow
off steam at his general manager and it dawns on us: Somewhere
along the way, the court jesters began ruling the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   This occurred to the creators of ``Cosby,'' too. Executive
producer Tom Straw and writers Nick LeRose and Tom Reeder cleverly
address the absurdity of society's values in this week's episode of
the CBS sitcom, which airs Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Straw, LeRose and Reeder conjured up a world in which teachers
get money for nothing and computers for free; a society in which
educators make more in five minutes than entertainers do in a year;
an environment that leads disgruntled basketball star Patrick Ewing
to opine, in a wickedly wonderful cameo, ``I blame the media. They
treat these teachers like Gods.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode _ extended a half hour to 60 minutes because the
well of satirical material to draw from was so deep _ revolves
around Doug E. Doug's character, Griffin Vesey, a science teacher
at Ralph Bunche Middle High in Astoria, N.Y., who is barely making
ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Vesey fantasizes about what it would be like if teachers enjoyed
the same kind of attention and adulation as today's superstar
athletes. What if he were a free agent being courted by a rival
school district with very deep pockets?
</P>
<P>
   What if he had an agent (played by Bill Cosby) to do his
negotiating and the ensuing bidding war played out on television
and in the tabloids?
</P>
<P>
   Vesey could be Keyshawn Johnson impersonating Barkley playing
Doug Jeter imitating Ricky Williams. The professional sports scene,
with its sycophants and stratospheric salaries and insatiable egos,
is a landscape ripe for ridicule and the ``Cosby'' writers manage
to pluck it clean.
</P>
<P>
   The message that gives the lines their punch is that society has
it all backward. We empower and enrich and elevate people whose
unique skills make today a little brighter but don't do a whole lot
toward lighting tomorrow's path.
</P>
<P>
   We pay athletes hundreds of millions of dollars to jump high,
shoot low, run fast or age slow. Then we pay them millions of
dollars more to endorse sneakers while teachers on shoestring
budgets buy construction paper and crayons and books out of their
own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Our children grow up wanting to emulate their favorite sports
stars and make millions, not be like their favorite instructors and
make a difference. Society lets them know in myriad ways which one
is more valued.
</P>
<P>
   Straw grew up in the San Fernando Valley. Some years later, he
can remember the names of the teachers at Birmingham High in Van
Nuys who positively influenced him. The idea of teachers as
celebrities he got from author Frank McCourt, who recently was
quoted in The New York Times magazine lamenting education's low
placement on society's ladder of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the idea of doing a sports parody, ``there were so
many things that connected so quickly,'' Straw said Monday from New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, Jerry Rice and Doug Flutie _ good sports that they are _
made cameo appearances, playing themselves in Vesey's fantasy as
dedicated athletes who are underappreciated and overworked.
</P>
<P>
   They delivered the message, loud and clear. We trust somebody
will explain to Phillips, Leaf, Galloway, Griffey et al., why the
episode is so funny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
