<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIMS SCORES FALL SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 and JENNIFER BARRETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 9 of 10 Arizona high school sophomores failed to meet
minimum mathematics requirements last year on the AIMS test.
</P>
<P>
   On the reading portion of the statewide exam, whose results were
released Monday, 61 percent of students hit or exceeded the
necessary standard. On the writing section, 30 percent did.
</P>
<P>
   State Superintendent of Public Instruction Lisa Graham Keegan
called the results ``unsettling'' Monday, but not surprising. This
was the first year the test was given, Keegan said, and some
portions were designed for juniors and seniors.
</P>
<P>
   But she also said Arizona's teachers must continue to bring
their lessons into alignment with the academic standards reflected
on the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the students, it's the way we're teaching them,''
Keegan said. ``The schools and teachers out there need our support.
They're our front line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get behind them and give them what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Keegan said her department plans to lobby the Legislature to
extend the school year a week and add 24 hours for teacher
training.
</P>
<P>
   She also wants the state to require three years of math in high
school instead of the current two, and to fund after-school and
summer remedial programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't change a direction without a map,'' Keegan said.
``This is a map.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials statewide cautioned that many sophomores had
not yet taken the math classes they needed to pass the test.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Russell was one. She had already had algebra and was
taking geometry, but Russell, a junior with a 4.0 average at Cactus
High School in Glendale, said Monday she had never seen some of the
math problems before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, `OK, what is this?' I left some of it blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of her classmates felt the same, Russell said. Although
Cactus students scored well in the reading and writing sections,
only 13 percent of students met math standards. Russell should get
her score late this week. &QL; 
45,000 TAKE TEST &QL; 
About 45,000 district and charter school students took AIMS _
Arizona's Instrument to Measure Standards _ last April in reading,
writing and mathematics. For them, the scores will not count toward
a diploma, though the results will be noted on their transcripts.
They also can retake the test until they get a satisfactory score.
</P>
<P>
   This year's sophomores, who will take the AIMS test in the
spring, will be the first class who must pass it to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Scores fall into four categories: exceeds the standards, meets
the standards, approaches the standards and falls far short of the
standards. In order to ``meet standards'' in each of the three
subject areas, students had to score at least 500 out of a possible
800.
</P>
<P>
   Though students and parents will know what category they fall
into, the general public may not. Due to privacy laws, the
``approaches'' and ``falls far short'' groups will be lumped into
one on the school and district levels.
</P>
<P>
   Individual scores will be sent to parents over the next week by
mail or via their children. &QL; 
`WE HAVE CLEAR PICTURE' &QL; 
Teachers, administrators and state officials said the scores may
not be stellar, but they do provide a bench mark for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just really happy to finally have some information,''
said Linda Bromert, an assistant administrator in Peoria Unified
School District. ``Now we have a clear picture of what we have to
do to ensure the success of all our students.''
</P>
<P>
   Median test scores in the Peoria district exceeded state
averages. Still, Bromert said the district hopes to offer
additional help to students who are having a hard time passing the
test.
</P>
<P>
   But critics still expressed reservations about AIMS, which they
say may be too difficult and may have been launched too quickly.
They also contend that it puts non-English speaking and
special-needs students at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   John Wright, a teacher in the Window Rock Unified School
District and vice president of the state's largest teaching union,
said the test should have been given to younger grades first so
they know what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, third-, fifth- and eighth-graders will take
versions of the AIMS test geared to their grade levels. &QL; 
GOOD PERFORMANCES &QL; 
Despite the generally dismal results, many of last year's
sophomores turned in performances worthy of mention.
</P>
<P>
   At Chaparral High School in the Scottsdale Unified School
District, 91 percent of the approximately 450 test-takers met or
exceed the standards in reading. At Tempe Preparatory Academy, a
Tempe charter school, 100 percent of the 30 pupils earned that
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Arizona, 63 percent of test-takers met or exceeded
the reading standards at Patagonia Union High School.
</P>
<P>
   Still, academic advisor Heidi Imhof stressed that AIMS is just
one way of measuring academic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a test score. What's important is what kids can
actually do,'' Imhof said.
</P>
<P>
   In writing, Desert Vista High School in the Tempe Union High
School District had 54 percent of its test-takers over the passing
mark; 52 percent did so at Scottsdale's Desert Mountain High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that not all sophomores were going to meet the state
standards,'' Myron Marsh of the Scottsdale district said. &UR; ``But our
results indicate we've had a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one school in Arizona _ University High School in Tucson,
which caters to gifted students _ had a majority of students that
met or exceeded the standards in math. Most schools had 10 percent
or less scoring that high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad,'' said Bob Koch, Dysart Unified School District
board president. &QL; 
POOR MATH RESULTS &QL; 
Approximately 99 percent of 124 Dysart High students failed the
math portion, but Koch said the poor scoring extended beyond his
district's boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that all over this country, children are not
learning as much as they used to to become successful members of
society,'' Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain View High School in Mesa was one of the top schools in
math scores; one-third of its students met or exceeded the
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the district said it will need the scores earlier in the
school year if the test is going to help students learn from their
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is you're supposed to remediate between tests,'' Joe
O'Reilly of Mesa Unified School District said.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan also applauded Prescott and Colorado City high schools as
well as Foothills Academy, a charter school in Cave Creek, for
their math scores.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the AIMS scores were supposed to be made public on
Wednesday. But state educators moved up the release after they were
told that a local television station planned to air the scores
later in the day. &QL; 
Republic writers Lori Baker, Hernan Rozemberg, Patricia
Biggs-Cornelius, Melissa L. Jones, and Betty Reid contributed to
this article. &QL; 
Kelly Pearce can be reached at (602) 444-7981 or at
kelly.pearce(at)pni.com. &QL; 
Jennifer Barrett can be reached at (602) 444-7113 or at
jennifer.barrett(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
