<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG'S FUTURE BRIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MALIBU, Calif. _ When Lorenzo Romar resigned as the Pepperdine
men's basketball coach in March to take the head job at Saint
Louis, some returning players wondered how their playing time would
be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Armstrong wasn't one of them because he didn't play a
minute for the Waves in 1998-99. One of Romar's top recruits the
year before out of Vallejo High, Armstrong didn't qualify
academically and sat out his freshman season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Armstrong could see a lot of playing time at point guard.
Head coach Jan van Breda Kolff is projecting Armstrong to be a
significant contributor when the season opens Nov. 20 against Long
Beach State at Firestone Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong is a player . . . we're looking at,'' said van Breda
Kolff, who begins his first season at Pepperdine and seventh
overall as a Division I head coach. ``He has the ability to be a
really special player for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, 6-foot-5 and 190 pounds, was recruited by New Mexico,
Oregon, USC and Washington out of high school. Van Breda Kolff said
Armstrong seems to be fitting into the Waves' motion offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves return point guards Tezale Archie and Robert Fomby,
who both saw considerable playing time at the end of last season
when All-West Coast Conference performer Jelani Gardner slumped.
</P>
<P>
   __ World traveler: Gardner reported to the Ft. Wayne Fury of the
Continental Basketball Association, where he's going to try and
impress NBA teams that passed on him in the June draft.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was playing for a pro team in Israel in September before
he came back to Los Angeles, where he lives with his girlfriend and
young daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, who averaged a team-leading 13.8 points per game as a
senior and helped lead the Waves to a 19-13 record and their first
postseason appearance in five years, said he was frustrated with
not getting picked in the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is a business once you get out of college,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
