<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBF WILL GIVE TITLE BELT TO LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lawyers for Lennox Lewis and the International Boxing
Federation worked out an agreement Monday that would allow Lewis to
keep the organization's heavyweight world championship belt and
maintain a unified title.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who held the World Boxing Council title, defeated Evander
Holyfield on a 12-round unanimous decision on Saturday night in Las
Vegas to win the World Boxing Association and IBF championships.
But the IBF withheld its belt because Lewis' promoters refused to
pay a $300,000 sanctioning fee directly to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' promoters agreed to pay the sanctioning fee Monday and
mailed the check. The IBF gave Lewis the belt and now recognizes
him as its champion, according to Milton Chwasky, Lewis' New
York-based lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Krovatin, a lawyer for the IBF president, Robert Lee Sr.,
said the $300,000 sanctioning fee for Lewis had arrived at the
group's East Orange, N.J., headquarters. ``If the check clears, the
IBF will confer the belt on Lewis,'' Krovatin said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Lewis, 34, has all three major titles, he must defend
them against the No. 1 contenders from the WBC, WBA and IBF in what
the organizations call mandatory defenses. If Lewis refuses to
fight the mandatory bouts, the organizations can strip him of the
titles, declare them vacant and have other boxers fight for the
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Panos Eliades, Lewis' London-based promoter, said that the WBC
considered the fight against Holyfield a mandatory defense. So
Lewis will not have to fight the WBC's No. 1 contender for another
year. Eliades said he thought the IBF and the WBA should have
box-offs to determine who should fight Lewis for their heavyweight
titles. Eliades will pitch his idea to the WBA at its convention in
Panama next week.
</P>
<P>
   The WBA's mandatory challenger for Lewis is Henry Akinwande. Two
years ago Lewis and Akinwande met in a WBC championship fight and
Akinwande was disqualified for excessive holding and refusing to
fight. ``Akinwande is not a good fight,'' Eliades said. ``No one
wants to see that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the fighters who will be lining up for a shot at Lewis in
the next year are David Tua, No. 1 in the IBF; John Ruiz, No. 1 in
the WBC; Michael Grant, No. 2 in the WBC; Vladimir Klitschko, the
World Boxing Organization champion, and Mike Tyson, the No. 1
contender in the WBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Klitschko and he wants to fight Lennox, and Lennox wants
to fight Michael Grant,'' Eliades said. ``We'd love to have those
fights in London. Lennox will fight anybody, but he doesn't want to
fight nobodies. He can't get motivated for those kinds of fights
against guys like Akinwande. But I'll take Grant in London as
Lennox's next fight. I don't think Grant is that good. He's strong,
but he's not very clever.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou DiBella, senior vice president of programming for HBO
Sports, said the cable network was not interested in televising bad
bouts just for the sake of Lewis' keeping the titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lennox would like to give up one or more of the titles,
we'd support him,'' DiBella said. ``With or without the belts we'd
be interested in seeing him fight Tua, Grant, Klitschko or Derrick
Jefferson.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lewis will be in New York on Wednesday and DiBella plans to meet
with him to determine what Lewis wants to do. Eliades said Lewis
wanted to remain busy, fighting once every six months, regardless
of what happened with the mandatory title bouts.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is also expected to attend the bout between Grant and
Andrew Golota on Saturday night in Atlantic City, N.J. If Grant
gets past Golota, that could pave the way for a Lewis-Grant bout
early next year. Lewis has already beaten Golota, knocking him out
in the first round two years ago. Golota admitted taking a shot of
lidocaine in his left knee before fighting Lewis that night.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he would like to fight Tyson, because he represents
one of the best fighters of Lewis' era. But Eliades said he didn't
believe Tyson was ready to fight Lewis right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
